<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
And may the best `Superman' win
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Superman times two.
</P>
<P>
   One with the logo tattooed on his biceps. One with the insignia
ironed on the front of a baggy T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal is the Man of Steel on steroids. Reggie Miller
is Clark Kent with rickets.
</P>
<P>
   It's Lakers vs. Pacers in the NBA Finals and time to see which
one can make his team fly.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what happened in their respective conference finals,
the answer would seem to be Shaq and the Lakers, who were faster
than a speeding bullet in coming from 15 points down in the last
10{ minutes Sunday to knock off Portland in Game 7 of the Western
finals.
</P>
<P>
   But after all those years of coming up short, Miller and the
Pacers finally did leap the tall buildings of New York in a single
bound to win the Eastern title in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks vs. Fix.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Middle America represented by Larry Bird's team from
the heartland, the conspiracy theorists never rest. The Oliver
Stone set points to that fourth-quarter run by LA at Staples Center
as evidence the NBA and its kissin' cousins at the network simply
could not and would not tolerate a small-market Finals matchup of
Indiana-Portland.
</P>
<P>
   They point to a touch foul that sent the Lakers' Kobe Bryant to
the foul line for a three-point play during the decisive 15-0 run.
They point to the Blazers' Steve Smith being virtually hammered
into the floor on his drive to the basket in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Good points. Just bad calls. They happen all the time in the
sport that is the most difficult to officiate.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy-seekers overlook the fact that, with the
exception of Rasheed Wallace, the Blazers played the fourth quarter
like frightened turtles, pulling their heads inside their shells,
afraid to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   They also overlook the fact that a St. Louis-Tennessee matchup
produced the best Super Bowl of all time and TV ratings that also
ranked high.
</P>
<P>
   While it is a pleasant notion to think of NBC Sports chairman
Dick Ebersol perched on a high window sill at Rockefeller Center,
ready to air a steady diet of Suddenly Susan reruns rather than
Pacers-Blazers live to the nation, the truth is the two best teams
with the two best stories are here.
</P>
<P>
   It is a duel of contrasts. Young vs. old. Small town vs.
Tinseltown. Earthbound vs. high-flying.
</P>
<P>
   It is Bird vs. Magic one more time, though with both in vastly
different roles. Maybe it isn't Lakers vs. Celtics. But put the
hawk-nosed Bird anywhere within sniffing distance of Hollywood's
phoniness and you get a real sense of disdain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like 'em,'' Larry Legend says.
</P>
<P>
   This time around Magic is no more than the world's biggest
cheerleader, his seat on the baseline just across from the Lakers'
bench. But he rarely occupies it during the fourth quarter of
games, standing and pacing in the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I'd love to be out there,'' Magic says.
</P>
<P>
   What it might be is the Team of the Past vs. the Team of the
Future.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, previous Pacers teams were better than this one
but never could get over the considerable hump of Michael Jordan or
around the scrappy roadblock of the Knicks. The Indiana team that
lost to O'Neal when he was with Orlando in the 1995 Eastern
Conference finals had more speed to get up and down the floor in
the transition game, not to mention a more mobile Rik Smits in the
middle. The Pacers who were beaten by the Knicks a year ago had
more strength and bulk up front with Antonio Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Lakers, in spite of their 67-15 regular-season
mark, have shown during the playoffs that they are still green and
growing into the team that can live up to all of the hype. These
Lakers allowed Sacramento to get up off the floor to force their
first-round series to the limit and then could not close out a 3-1
lead on Portland until the Blazers took a late-game trip to Choke
City.
</P>
<P>
   In a year or two, perhaps the Lakers will be worthy of having
their own weekly TV series on NBC. But for now, they are a project
that is under construction as a real dynasty, living too much on
the edge of the raw talent of their only two great players, Kobe
and Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   But somebody has to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Superman or Superman. Shaq or Reggie.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the vote for the young Elvis or the old Elvis on the
postage stamp. As pumped up as Roseanne or skinnier than Calista
Flockhart? Bending iron rims with slam dunks or shooting 3-pointers
with X-ray vision?
</P>
<P>
   Bet on a guy with a cape.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
