<SLUG> BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Venus ill-prepared for French assault
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ On a cold day in Paris, one cold enough to pass for
winter in Houston of late, Venus Williams couldn't keep her inner
fires lit Tuesday. She tried to shake off the chill, and the veneer
of rust from her game, but she obviously found herself in the wrong
place at the wrong time, being underprepared and underdressed.
</P>
<P>
   And, hence, grossly over-seeded, considering how scarce she has
made herself in 2000. Venus was way out of her element _ and
elements _ confronting Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario on Roland Garros'
red clay, the gritty surface the gritty Spaniard most loves and has
most frequently conquered. That Arantxa, a three-time French Open
champion who is second only to Chris Evert in career match
victories on clay, could be slotted eighth, four notches below the
enigmatic U.S. teen, seemed preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   And it was, once they started exchanging baseline blows.
Sanchez-Vicario blitzed Venus 6-0 in the first set and 6-2 in the
third, although Williams had enough wherewithal to briefly reverse
her sagging fortunes with a 6-1 blitz of her own in the middle set
when Arantxa briefly let up on the throttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did all I could today,'' Williams said, conceding it wasn't
nearly enough to send her forth into the semifinals of the
tournament that places a premium on strategic planning, mental
toughness and physical preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Venus remains grossly deficient on each count, coming up short
in the latter because she has played just four matches in the last
six months amid speculation, fueled primarily by her own wacky
father, that she was contemplating retirement at the nubile age of
19.
</P>
<P>
   The official reason given for Williams' hiatus was painful
tendinitis in her wrists. Many wondered, nonetheless, if it wasn't
really sister-itis, brought on by Serena Williams' becoming the
first of the heralded siblings to win a major championship at the
U.S. Open last fall. As close as the girls might be, Venus failed
to handle the dramatic usurping by her ``kid'' sister well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help at all,'' she said of the doubles title the
Williamses claimed the next day in New York. ``It never helps. I'll
never forget it. I'm very bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, after subsequently losing to Serena in the Grand Slam
Cup, Venus pretty much disappeared. Richard Williams, who once told
us he intended to buy Rockefeller Center, suggested there was a
better than 50-50 chance Venus would quit tennis to focus on other
interests, not the least of which would be spending the $15 million
she had earned playing the sport as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   But since $15 million doesn't go as far as it used to, Williams
finally resurfaced at the Betty Barclay Cup tournament in Hamburg
the first week of May, where Amanda Coetzer whipped her in the
quarters. Three weeks later, Jana Dokic whacked Venus in the
Italian Open's round of 16. No one had pushed her through the first
three rounds in Paris, but she hadn't played anybody, either.
</P>
<P>
   But, even at 28 and losing some of her once-indefatigable
fetching skills, Sanchez-Vicario is nobody to be trifled with at
Roland Garros, which she first conquered before her 18th birthday
and again just two years ago. Williams might have beaten Arantxa
four times in a row _ twice on clay, too _ but that was before
Venus wandered off to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game,'' Williams said, ``is not anywhere near normal, in my
opinion. I've made a lot of improvement since Hamburg, though. It
wasn't until Rome that I could start practicing my serve.''
</P>
<P>
   She had no 120-mph rockets in reserve for Sanchez-Vicario but
insisted: ``No worries because I'll eventually be there.''
</P>
<P>
   In time for Wimbledon? Perhaps, as long as she can prepare
herself for the lawns by practicing at home in Florida, out of the
rain and cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I can find some grass courts that aren't soaked,'' she
said, getting a dig in at the unseasonably ugly weather Europe has
been experiencing. `` For me it's OK if I go home and just
practice. That's what I need to do anyway. In general, I don't play
so many warm-up tournaments for the Grand Slams. If I'm on my game
and I'm hitting the ball, where's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   But getting on her game and staying there has been a problem.
The widely anticipated dominance of the WTA Tour by the Williams
girls will remain the stuff of conjecture only until they can stay
healthy and maintain a higher level of consistency. Professional
coaching would seem a desirable option, but that never has been
seriously considered with father calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, Venus took on Paris by her lonesome after Serena
pulled out, citing chronic knee pain. The injury has plagued her
since early April and presumably threatens her participation at
Wimbledon, although Venus predicted Serena will play.
</P>
<P>
   But at a title-contending level? We never can be sure with
either of them.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
