<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ELECT-895&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SPENDING $35 MILLION, CORZINE WINS DEMOCRATIC SENATE PRIMARY
IN N.J. 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Will be updated with results of GOP primary.) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Jon Corzine, the Wall Street multimillionaire
whose $35 million spending spree shattered all records for a U.S.
Senate primary, trounced former Gov. Jim Florio on Tuesday to win
the New Jersey Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, a former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. who ran on
a platform of big-spending government programs and unabashedly
liberal positions on social issues, rolled to victory after a
12-week onslaught of television commercials turned him from a
wealthy campaign contributor who was otherwise unknown in his home
state into as much a household name as Florio.
</P>
<P>
   In unofficial returns reported by The Associated Press, with 85
percent of districts reporting, Corzine had 59 percent of the vote
to 41 percent for Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, 53, used his victory speech to lay out his entire
agenda: investing in health care, Medicare, Social Security,
education, the inner cities, the environment and in benefits for
service members and veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' he shouted to a jammed hotel ballroom in
East Brunswick. ``I want to invest in America _ that's what this
campaign will be about.''
</P>
<P>
   Conceding defeat, Florio said he would support his rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with Jon Corzine on a number of issues,'' Florio
said, ``but I agree with him a lot more than I would agree with any
of the Republicans who are running for that office.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio continued: ``I am a Democrat, and I will be working very
hard to elect Democrats for all positions that are open this
November.''
</P>
<P>
   In the four-way Republican primary, Rep. Bob Franks, a four-term
congressman from Union County, was in a tight race with state Sen.
William L. Gormley, a veteran lawmaker from the Atlantic City area
with strong financing from casino interests there.
</P>
<P>
   With 94 percent of districts reporting, Franks had 35 percent of
the vote and Gormley had 34 percent, according to the AP. James
Treffinger, the Essex County executive, had 18 percent, while
Murray Sabrin, a college professor who ran for governor as a
Libertarian in 1997, had 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, Corzine's stated willingness to spend
whatever it took to win now has put a burden on Republicans, who a
year ago, before Gov. Christie Whitman dropped out of the race, had
viewed New Jersey as an easy victory. Republican leaders now will
have to decide whether to commit large resources to try to defeat
Corzine, or focus on other, less costly races.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's entry into the race as a self-financed candidate saved
state Democratic leaders from having to raise as much as $10
million for a less wealthy Senate candidate. Now, his victory in
the primary means they will be able to focus on the real prize of
New Jersey politics: the governor's race in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic outcome had rested on two uncertainties: whether
voters would be persuaded or repulsed by the money Corzine spent on
his campaign, and whether Jim Florio could overcome the lingering
animosity of Democrats still nursing grudges over the $2.8 billion
tax increase he signed as governor in 1990, fueling years of
Republican electoral victories.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine was expected to spend $2 million on Tuesday alone in
get-out-the-vote efforts, from rain gear and rented vans to
payments of $75 or more for his street workers. The previous record
for a U.S. Senate primary was $8.1 million, and Corzine has already
exceeded the nearly $30 million Michael Huffington spent in vain in
his race for the U.S. Senate in California in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Democrats was embodied by one couple at the
public library in Westfield. ``I wasn't going to vote, but I'm
opposed to someone who spends $36 million to buy an election,''
said Mark Rubin, an accountant voting there. ``Florio was an awful
governor, but I voted for him because no one has a right to buy the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bu Rubin's wife, Andi, said she could not bring herself to vote
for Florio. She waited in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The winner in November succeeds Sen. Frank Lautenberg, who
surprised the state's political community in February 1999 when he
announced that he would not seek a fourth term. Lautenberg, himself
a millionaire businessman, said he did not want to spend two years
raising money for re-election. He endorsed Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time as Lautenberg announced his retirement,
Corzine was forced out of his job as co-chairman of Goldman Sachs.
When Goldman Sachs held an initial public stock offering in May
1999, Corzine received 4.4 million shares, and instantly became
worth $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   When Corzine's candidacy emerged several months later, it was
viewed as the answer to a prayer by many Democrats, among them Sen.
Robert Torricelli, who believed the only way to defeat Florio was
with a great deal of money.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, as combative as he was in three races for governor,
relentlessly assailed Corzine as a political neophyte whose naivete
could not compete with his own experience in state government and
as an eight-term congressman. With a meager $2.5 million budget,
Florio ran only attack commercials in the last two weeks of the
race, and had to be pressed at times to articulate his own agenda
were he to win a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Florio did little to deflect Corzine's attacks, which began
on television in mid-April and remained unanswered for a month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nearly as closely watched as the Senate races were the primaries
in both parties to fill Franks' seat in Congress, as well as the
contested Republican primaries for two other House seats. With
three seats potentially in play, New Jersey has become one of a
handful of states that could decide which party controls the House
of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fifth District, Rep. Marge S. Roukema, a 20-year
Republican incumbent, again defeated E. Scott Garrett, a
conservative state assemblyman who nearly unseated her in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12th District, former Republican representative Dick
Zimmer beat another former Republican representative, Mike Pappas,
for the right to challenge the freshman Democrat, Rep. Rush Holt.
While Pappas appealed to hard-line conservatives, Zimmer ran
television commercials reminding voters of Pappas' paean to Kenneth
Starr on the House floor during the impeachment proceedings against
President Clinton, sung to the tune of ``Twinkle, Twinkle, Little
Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt used similar commercials to unseat Pappas two years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
