<SLUG> BC-OLY--LOPEZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Games' golden girl girds for 15th Olympic trip
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The most amazing of Olympic streaks is alive and well.
And as Gertrude Birkman is quick to point out, so is she.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm still kicking,'' Birkman, 87, said. ``You probably
were wondering, `Whatever happened to that old lady?' I'm still in
pretty good shape except for I forget some things sometimes. But
you know, I'll never forget the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   How could she? By any gauge, Birkman, who lives in the Champions
area, is America's greatest Olympic fan. And, yes, she's headed for
Sydney to watch her 15th Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting tickets has been smoother this time,'' Birkman said.
``You know, they charge like the mischief. But I think it's worth
it. I'm thinking this one will be the last one, though.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's what she said in 1996 and here she is again.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall the inspiring story of the quippy, fun-loving
Birkman and the travails she had trying to purchase, ``one measly
ticket in my home country,'' four years ago when the Summer Games
were in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Birkman, who had been to 13 previous Olympics (counting the 1988
Winter Games) since watching Jesse Owens in Berlin in 1936, was
constantly denied when she tried to purchase Olympic tickets
through the confusing Atlanta ticketing system. She put up with
interminable waits on the telephone and filled out three ticket
requests on the day tickets became available, but was shut out.
</P>
<P>
   She even wrote a letter to Atlanta Olympic chief Billy Payne and
sent it via certified mail, looking for answers to her ticketing
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured he was the head fella,'' she said, ``so I thought
maybe he could help. Why would I want to deal with anyone else?''
</P>
<P>
   But Payne didn't. Birkman received a form letter consoling her
for coming up empty. But after Birkman's story came to light,
hundreds of Houstonians stepped up and offered tickets. Her
telephone rang off the wall and TV crews from all over began
knocking on her door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be talking on the phone and someone would be at the front
door and someone else at the back door,'' she said. ``If that
happens again, I'll try to be nice, but you know old women can get
kind of snippy.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations gave her tickets. Strangers called her home and the
Chronicle, offering seats. Even Olympic expert Jack Kelly, who has
since become an adviser for Houston's 2012 campaign, stepped up and
said, ``Tell her she can have tickets for any day that she's
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Birkman indeed made it to Atlanta and enjoyed the Games, but
like many others was less than enthusiastic about Atlanta's effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too hot,'' she said. ``I hope if Houston gets it, it
will be air-conditioned. The arrangements were terrible in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   But now it's on to Sydney for this superfan, who has seen
firsthand the most memorable of Olympic moments.
</P>
<P>
   She laughed out loud like the young lady she was, when Owens
sprinted to gold in Adolf Hitler's Berlin. She marveled at Babe
Didrikson Zaharias redefining women in sports. She was high in the
seats at Mexico's Estadio Azteca when Bob Beamon shattered the long
jump record in 1968. She was courtside in Munich, Germany, when the
1972 Soviet Union basketball team shattered America's basketball
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   She watched Nadia Comaneci in 1976, Mary Lou Retton in 1984 and
Shannon Miller in 1996. She has been to London, Rome, Munich,
Montreal, Seoul and every other Olympic host city since Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse Owens and Babe Zaharias were the ones that really got me
hooked,'' she said. ``It's just a wonderful thing. And I'll never
forget what people did for me four years ago. Dear Lord, the people
of Houston made me humble. My dream came true.''
</P>
<P>
   And the dream is alive and well.
</P>
<P>
   Birkman had triple-bypass surgery in 1995, but has since stayed
relatively healthy. She now walks with a cane and gave up golf
three years ago because of bad knees.
</P>
<P>
   Friends have encouraged her to move to a retirement home, to
which she replies, ``The only way I'm leaving my house is feet
first.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, she fell off the curb in her front yard while
doing yardwork and opened a gash in her head.
</P>
<P>
   But she said of the accident: ``I was just bleeding a lot. The
way people were hysterical when they found me, they were the ones
that should have gone off in an ambulance. I didn't knock my square
head off, just the crown.''
</P>
<P>
   She will be 88 in Sydney. She swears that this time her 15th
Olympic Games really will be her last.
</P>
<P>
   But to that, only four words come to mind: See you in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
