<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY NOW MATTERS TO LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ If championship-round experience counts for anything,
theLakers should have an edge in the NBA Finals that begin tonight.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The franchise hasn't been this far since 1991 and hasn't won a
championship since 1988, but the locker room is replete with rings.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper won three championships with the Chicago Bulls, along
with coach Phil Jackson and his staff, who won six. John Salley won
two rings with the Detroit Pistons and a third with the Bulls.
Robert Horry won two titles with the Houston Rockets. And of
course, A.C. Green, the lone link to those Showtime years, won a
pair of championships with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Brian Shaw haven't won but did play in the
1995 Finals, losing to Horry's Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   But Horry said don't make too much out of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't mean anything. It's all about how the team
is playing and how you have come together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Horry also doesn't see any value in discussing Finals
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has been close to this situation before. They know
what's at stake. There is no need for for anybody to say
anything,'' he said. ``If you don't know what's at stake now, you
need to be checked into a mental hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper did warn his younger teammates about the media crush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing is I told the guys with having all of you
(reporters) here, is take it easy. It's all hype,'' Harper said.
``You're going to see them for the next 8, 10 days. Just come out
and play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Shaw and O'Neal admit they've discussed their '95
experience, mostly because they'd like to redeem themselves. And
Shaw said the Lakers' wealth of Finals appearances is indeed an
asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it's overrated,'' he said. ``As far as all
the extraneous things, off the court, that's seven or eight guys
who have all been through that and know what it's like and have a
better chance of dealing with it. That helps.''
</P>
<P>
   FINAL-LY: No matter how many games the Lakers won or road trips
they swept, Jackson avoided all season any attempts to place
expectations on his team. So when was he finally convinced they
were championship material?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two minutes to go in the last game,'' he said, referring to
Game 7 against Portland. ``It was an ultimate moment for this team
on Sunday, whether they could rally from such a game.''
</P>
<P>
   GUARDED: Jackson hasn't unveiled his defensive strategy, but it
seems likely that while Harper will open against Reggie Miller and
Kobe Bryant on Mark Jackson, the matchups are likely to change
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a plan on how we want to send Reggie and what we
want to do, but this team counters well,'' Jackson said. ``They've
made an art out of what they have been doing. ... We'll definitely
have Kobe on him. We'll have Brian Shaw on him. We'll have plenty
of people that will have to guard Reggie.''
</P>
<P>
   CAN'T TOUCH THIS: Bryant was concise when it came to the Pacers'
defensive challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Can they stop Shaq? ``Who, Indiana? I don't think so, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Can they stop you? ``No, I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL REMINDER: Of the Lakers' many struggles in the postseason,
Jackson listed the two-game letdown in Sacramento as the most
surprising, and said it provided a warning for this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taken out of that road game in Sacramento by crowd
noise and by defensive pressure and by a team that played a
freewheeling offensive system,'' he said. ``Indiana presents that
same kind of problem in their offensive system. A lot of space, a
lot of distance for 3-point shooters. Nobody really hangs around in
the paint where Shaq can hang out and anchor himself around the
lane. So this will be a challenge for our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   OUCH REPORT: The Lakers enter the Finals relatively healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Little-used rookie forward Devean George remains out
indefinitely with a sprained left ankle, but Kobe Bryant's sprained
right foot doesn't appear to be a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foot feels good,'' he said Tuesday. ``I didn't need any
treatment this morning.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
