<HEADLINE>
SUFFOLK SHERIFF PLEADS NOT GUILTY TO CORRUPTION CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ The sheriff of Suffolk County surrendered
himself Tuesday and pleaded not guilty in criminal court to all
charges of corruption and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Patrick Mahoney was indicted by a grand jury that
investigated his office for 15 months, and finally charged with one
felony count of defrauding the government and 54 misdemeanors for
incidents during his 11 years in office here on eastern Long
Island, including charges that he raffled off special deputy
sheriff positions to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also accuse Mahoney of using a full-time county
employee to coordinate his re-election efforts; using county
offices and vehicles for personal business; and of embezzling
$16,000 from the heriff's Benevolent Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney's former undersheriff, Edward J. Morris, was charged
with 28 felony counts and seven misdemeanors, the most serious
charge being bribery. Morris is accused of coercing correction
officers under his command into making campaign donations to the
sheriff in exchange for paid overtime .
</P>
<P>
   According to the grand jury indictment unsealed Tuesday in
Suffolk County Court, Morris solicited and accepted more than
$10,000 from county jail officers during the last 10 years on
Mahoney's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Morris also pleaded not guilty to all charges.
</P>
<P>
   The arraignments came as no surprise: Mahoney said last week
that he expected to be indicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing has the odor of (the) garbage that it is,''
Mahoney said. ``Catterson's gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney said the indictments are the culmination of a
long-running feud between him and Catterson, Suffolk County's two
top elected law enforcement officials. It is a battle between a
Republican district attorney who is not shy about using his
prosecutorial powers, and an independent, hard-charging Republican
sheriff who bucked the party last year and crossed over to the
Democrats to run against the Republican county executive.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 months ago the district attorney impaneled a grand jury
to investigate allegations of corruption in the sheriff's office.
</P>
<P>
   The feud between Mahoney and Catterson goes back at least to
1993, when Catterson reportedly felt that the sheriff had upstaged
him after Katie Beers, a 10-year-old who was kidnapped and held in
a dungeon for 16 days, was found alive. Previously, Mahoney had
endorsed Catterson for district attorney. Now their relationship
has so degenerated that Republicans routinely argue over who has
the unsavory task of standing between the two men during photo
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system works when honest people work the system,'' Mahoney
said in his office at the Suffolk County Jail after his
arraignment. ``When dishonest people like the D.A. use the system
to indict his political enemies, the system fails. Catterson is the
biggest bully in Suffolk County.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Catterson brushed off those remarks as the ramblings of a
desperate man. ``I understand he's under a lot of pressure,''
Catterson said at his Hauppauge office. ``He's been saying these
things for years. This so-called feud is in his mind. This had
nothing to do with personality but everything to do with
misconduct,'' Catterson said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
