A6697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-ELECT-ASSESS-NYT     06-07 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ELECT-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: DESPITE HIGH SPENDING, CORZINE AVOIDED ERROR OF MANY RICH
CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
 (With NJ-ELECT) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ It wasn't just the money. It was also the
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Corzine's record-breaking spending spree on his way to the
Democratic Senate nomination in Tuesday's New Jersey primary made
most of the news during his long and venomous campaign against
former Gov. Jim Florio, just as the advertising it paid for helped
turn him from a nobody into a household name across the state in
only a few months.
</P>
<P>
   But on election day, it was the backing Corzine's millions
cultivated among leaders of New Jersey's Democratic Party
establishment that produced the turnout in key election districts
that finally sank Florio's dogged struggle for a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   In the populous northern urban counties of Bergen, Essex and
Union, Democratic county leaders spent lavishly on Corzine's
get-out-the-vote effort to bus voters to the polls, handing him
top-heavy margins of victories that swamped Florio's strong leads
in his southern base of Camden, Atlantic and Cumberland counties.
</P>
<P>
   Florio can complain that Corzine's $35 million in spending
bought the friends he needed on Election Day, and Corzine's friends
in the party can reply that he was only practicing the kind of
deep-pocket ``party building'' that prosperous Republicans have
been doing for years.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that in tending to the party and not just to the
politics of the campaign, Corzine avoided the mistake of other rich
men who thought, as rich men often seem to do, that their money was
all they needed to get what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many examples can you call up?'' said Stephen A. Salmore,
a Republican campaign consultant. ``Ron Lauder, Al Checchi,
Huffington, Mark Dayton in Minnesota _ the number of wealthy
candidates who have spent their money and gone down in flames is as
great if not greater than the ones who have spent their money and
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Checchi and Michael Huffington lost in Republican races in
California, after spending huge fortunes for elusive votes. Lauder,
the cosmetics heir, scorned the New York City Republican Party when
he ran for mayor in 1989 and was gleefully crushed by them. Dayton,
a department store heir, ran third in his race for governor in
Minnesota two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine had the support of virtually every important Democrat in
the state and outside it, including the chairman of the Senate
Democratic Campaign Committee; both of the state's Democratic
senators, Robert Torricelli and Frank Lautenberg, who is retiring
and whose seat Corzine is seeking; and a roster of county
Democratic chairmen and committee members.
</P>
<P>
   These Democratic leaders were not, as Florio charged, interested
only in Corzine's money, which allowed them to save a bundle for
next year's governor's race, the grand prize in New Jersey
politics. They were also deeply averse to hitching their party's
wagon to Florio's dubious star, which has sputtered more than it
has sparkled in three races for governor, only one victorious. Most
recently, Florio was evicted from the State House by Christie
Whitman in 1993 after forcing a $2.8 billion tax increase through
the Legislature, a tax increase that still resonates in the state,
including in Corzine's attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as Robert C. Janiszewski, the Hudson County
executive, put it on Sunday, the Democrats were not interested in
spending the fall campaign ``defending Jim Florio's tax
increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he lost, Florio still made a strong showing in his
South Jersey stronghold, and among thousands of Democrats around
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the emotional favorite of the rank-and-file Democrats,''
said Roger A. Bodman, a prominent Trenton lobbyist who was a member
of Gov. Thomas H. Kean's Republican administration. ``It goes
beyond his tax increase to 25 years as an assemblyman and a
congressman and as governor, and as a guy who stood up for the
party year in and year out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Florio could not get the traction he needed by making
Corzine's money and his Wall Street career the issue. He accused
Corzine of buying the nomination, he accused the party leaders who
abandoned him for selling out, and he linked Corzine's career as
the head of Goldman Sachs, the investment house, to a range of
evils, including profiting from slavery in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Now the state is poised for an unusual match.
</P>
<P>
   As Bodman put it: ``You can have this curious situation where
the Republican candidate is the middle-class everyday Joe with a
mortgage and a 6-year-old car against the Democrat who is a
millionaire and who out of noblesse oblige decides to go out and
give something back to society.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine may wake up on Wednesday hoping that his victory has at
last put to rest Florio's charge that the $35 million he spent on
the primary represented a poisonous level of spending. After all,
he could maintain, the voters have absolved him.
</P>
<P>
   But Salmore maintained that the Republicans could easily build
on the record of ill will toward Corzine's millions built up by
Florio's relentless attacks, and add to it a favorite Republican
theme, that Democrats cannot be trusted with money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how you say it,'' Salmore said. ```Look how much money
he spent on his campaign, and now guess how much of your money he
is going to spend if he goes to Washington. This man doesn't know
the value of a dollar _ how can you trust him with your taxes?'''
</P>
<P>
   Robert G. Sommer, a Democratic lobbyist and once a member of
Florio's congressional staff, said that Corzine would not
necessarily allow the Republicans to spring their syllogism that
big campaign spending necessarily equals big tax dollar spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end of this campaign, the money issues certainly came
to the fore,'' Sommer said Tuesday. ``But now it's five months to
Election Day, and Jon Corzine can make it a question about him and
his character. He is a man of character, he's worked harder than
his opponent in this race, and now he's the home team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
