<HEADER>
A6699 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-IRL-FISHER-TEX     06-07 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-FISHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHER, 19, HAS GROWN UP FAST IN THE FAST LANES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Teen-ager Sarah Fisher isn't sure what sort of
reception to expect when she returns to Texas Motor Speedway this
week.
</P>
<P>
   But four races and two ``confrontations'' into her Indy Racing
League career, Fisher knows she hardly is the same wide-eyed,
19-year-old who made series history when she qualified for the
Mall.com 500 at TMS in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I tougher? For sure. This is serious,'' said Fisher, who
was 13 days past her 19th birthday when she started 17th and
finished 25th on the 1.5-mile quadoval in Fort Worth last fall. ``I
was a kid before and I always had my dad (Dave) there. Now, I've
got to fight my own battles. I've still got (team owner) Derrick
Walker there to help me, but I've got to be just as tough as
nails.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the profile she has created for Walker Racing and the
star-starved Indy Racing Northern Light Series, the fact remains
that Fisher has crashed out of her past two races. Included was the
well-dissected wheel-banger involving Lyn St. James during the 84th
Indianapolis 500 last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I've got to finish this race. That's it,'' said
Fisher, referring to the 500-kilometer event at TMS on Saturday
night. ``I've got to finish it. I'm not expecting a top-10, because
we've had two races that we haven't finished. We need to finish a
race first.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you just can't jump into this sport and be dominant,
unless you're God's gift to racing. I don't think I have that much
talent, or I'd have won the Indy 500.''
</P>
<P>
   The wreck at Indy involving Fisher, St. James and Jaques Lazier
generated huge interest, as it eliminated the first two women to
ever start an Indy 500. Fisher was driving a solid race when she
attempted to pass St. James in Turn 1. Lazier, however, had slipped
inside of Fisher in the bottom groove to make it three-wide. St.
James, racing on the outside line, clipped Fisher's car in the
side. St. James slid into the concrete wall, while Fisher lost
control of her car and skimmed the wall in the short chute between
Turns 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not haunted by it. But I'm a bit disappointed because we
thought we could have for sure finished,'' Fisher said during an
appearance at SpeedZone on Tuesday. ``We had some fuel pick-up
point problems, and were stalling out of the pits. That would have
caused us problems as well, but at least we would have finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate and wasn't our fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker directed some pointed criticism at St. James, the race's
oldest driver at age 53, immediately after the incident. But Fisher
said she spoke to St. James at the victory dinner a few hours after
the race to square matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her it wasn't me on the inside, that it was Jaques
Lazier and I had to give him some room as well,'' said Fisher, the
third woman to qualify for the Indy 500. ``She admitted that she
hadn't heard that until after she had done her interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make sure she didn't have any hard feelings
about me, because I believe that was her last race. And it's better
to talk about it than to let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, however, has not totally made peace with veteran Eliseo
Salazar. Fisher was running second to Mark Dismore at Las Vegas
Motor Speedway on April 22 when she spun and collected the car
driven by Salazar, knocking both out of the Vegas Indy 300.
Salazar, in his first season of driving for Texan A.J. Foyt, ripped
Fisher on national television for being in over her head.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar, a native of Chile, apologized in a TV interview for
those remarks before the start of qualifying at the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway. But Fisher said Salazar has not spoken to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't realize _ and nobody knows this _ that
after the race, I went and apologized to his crew,'' said Fisher,
who was tutored at Indy by four-time race-winner Al Unser. ``Eliseo
had already left for the day, and apparently they never said
anything to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be polite if he did \Rapologize\S, instead of through
the media. But that's the way it is. You got to look at him as
another competitor on the racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   Same as Texan Greg Ray, the reigning IRL champion who is coming
off an Indy 500 performance in which he crashed in Turn 2 _ twice.
After starting on the pole, Ray finished 33rd and last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg Ray has torn up as many race cars as I have; actually, I
think he's torn up more than me this year,'' said Fisher, driver of
the No. 15 Walker Racing Cummins Special Dallara/Aurora. ``He needs
to do the same _ finish races.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray is aware of that, and said he will have no problem racing
against Fisher through TMS' high-banked, 24-degree turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't lose any sleep over that issue \Rracing Fisher\S, one
way or the other,'' Ray said. ``Sarah Fisher's resume says she's
one helluva race car driver. In the times I've seen her race, I've
seen her make some mistakes. So have I. So have other guys and
girls. She has a lot to learn, and a lot of natural ability.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Walker's determination, too, when he signed Fisher, who
has been racing some type of vehicle since age 5, without so much
as a test in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarah has a lot of potential,'' said Walker, who compared
Fisher's style to that of a young Rick Mears at the start of his
storied career at Team Penske. ``She's at the right age and she's
got a good opportunity in being in the IRL to learn her craft. The
challenge, in part, is hers and ours because no race driver is a
race driver by themselves. They have to have the right mechanism
around them to be able to do what they need to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in this business to have fun. We like to have it
when it comes, but in reality, it's a business and winning is what
it's all about. We're both going to survive on the results that we
create together as a team and a driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her recent sour runs, Fisher believes there is still ``a
ton'' of people cheering for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because we're the underdog,'' Fisher said. ``If you
look at it, I'm just a kid going into this race. But I'm trying to
do something that's pretty neat.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
