<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACTORING COULD HELP HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) The comprehensive exploration of the health care
insurance industry's ``claim game'' by The Star on Sunday implies
what would seem a promising business opportunity for a savvy
financial management enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The problem alleged by many physicians, hospitals and their
patients is one of slow-paying insurers. In some instances,
otherwise reputable businesses face charges of failing their
fiduciary duty in an effort to take advantage of the humongous
``float'' created by health care industry money flows.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common examples of a ``float'' occurs when a
financial intermediary uses money to make money until it settles
with the ultimate payee. When you buy a traveler's check, for
instance, the issuing company can earn interest on your payment
until you cash the check.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurers today stand accused by increasing numbers of
their critics of being inordinately slow to transfer the money they
receive from the insured to the providers of medical services. The
growing suspicion is that because profits are under pressure,
insurers resort to this strategy to fortify the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Motives for slow paying aside, anyone who has dealt with medical
insurers up close and personal can accept at face value any claim
that insurers are too often too slow to honor their obligations.
Not only does this create financial problems for providers, but
also it often puts hapless patients at odds with those they depend
on for their health care.
</P>
<P>
   The solution to the problem thus far has been for providers to
employ a growing army of clerks assigned to do nothing but monitor
the disposition of claims and badger insurers and patients for what
they're owed when reimbursement is deemed too slow.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a particularly effective approach, though, especially
given the apparently growing nature of the problem. A better
approach might be for a provider of factoring services to step into
this void. A factor is used in many business arrangements to buy a
company's receivables at a discount and collect the money owed at
100 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   In the health care industry, it seems, it would make a lot of
sense for providers simply to sell their billings to an enterprise
for something less than face value and let a professional bill
collector handle the often onerous chore of dealing with insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The economic appeal of traditional factoring services is that it
makes money immediately available to plow back into the business,
which is critical for those operating on thin margins. For health
care providers, the added benefit would be not only to reduce
clerical overhead, but also to free up everyone involved to focus
entirely on practice of the healing arts.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when providers could rob Peter to pay Paul when certain
groups became no-pays for whatever reason, be it indigence or
uncooperative insurers.
</P>
<P>
   With everyone responsible for paying the bills playing it so
close to the vest these days, however, cost shifting no longer is
an option. Therefore, with insurers becoming increasingly difficult
to deal with, medical professionals themselves are in need of
professional help with their business operations.
</P>
<P>
   Factoring, anyone?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-FINALS-LAD     06-07 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-FINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS REGROUPED, READY FOR GAME 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Precious little time has passed since Kobe zipped
the lob and Shaq rattled the rim and the Lakers forcefully blasted
their way to a Western Conference title. The celebration ended in
an NBA-record 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers open the NBA Finals tonight for the first time since
1991, and will be battling both the Indiana Pacers and a bit of
vertigo, brought on by their rapid rise from the ashes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling until the 6 p.m. tipoff at Staples Center how
the most grinding, emotionally draining and thrilling victory in
years _ the Game 7 comeback against Portland _ will affect the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   High on momentum? Or drunk on the effects?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just kind of riding it out. We're still up,'' Kobe
Bryant said Tuesday after the Lakers' sole pre-Finals practice,
which followed an off day Monday. ``Our confidence is pretty high.
It should be. And we're excited. We should be. By the same token,
we have a lot of work to do. And we have to be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of steadiness has been a hallmark of this team since
coach Phil Jackson's arrival this season. And it will have to carry
them for one more best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only natural to be worried about the fact that
you expended so much energy and emotion in a series that there
would be a letdown,'' Jackson said. ``But we feel like it might be
a momentum boost for us too. You can't tell. This Laker team is a
very interesting team that way. We're a little skittish, but I
think that we have some momentum going into this thing. ... (The
Pacers) may be more rested and physically in better condition, but
we have the home court, and I think we'll have the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers finished off the New York Knicks two days before the
Lakers closed out Portland, giving them more time to rest, but also
more time to hear the incessant conventional-wisdom chatter: that
the West is supreme, and that either winner would trounce the
East's representative.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise that Reggie Miller and Co. came to town a
little edgy, and looking forward to the idea that the Pacers might
have been overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good,'' Miller said. ``We hope they overlook us. We're
not coming in here to lay down. We're coming in here to shock the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   By its very nature, the Finals will be like nothing the Lakers
have faced this postseason. But hype and distractions aside, it
also could be easier.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in these playoffs, the opponent isn't built
around an elite power forward _ the Lakers' Achilles' heel on
defense. And for the first time in weeks _ or ever since the Lakers
and Trail Blazers' series began _ Shaquille O'Neal should be free
to dominate once more.
</P>
<P>
   That the Lakers needed seven games to advance was a testament to
the Blazers' unique personnel, and the ability of Rasheed Wallace
and Scottie Pippen to roam and crowd O'Neal. Indiana coach Larry
Bird won't use more than a double-team to help spindly center Rik
Smits and certainly won't be able to get away with throwing three
or four bodies at O'Neal, as the Blazers did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'd be as successful at it,'' said Pacers
forward Austin Croshere, ``because I don't think our guards are as
athletic as Scottie Pippen, who's so long that he can guard a point
guard, get down into the paint and get back out to contest shots.
But at the same time, we will definitely have to mix that in. I
don't think that you can allow a team like the Lakers a set
defensive scheme and allow them to kind of pick it apart and take
advantage of it. We'll have to mix things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Pacers were encouraged by what they saw Portland do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Croshere said. ``It just showed that they're not
invincible. That they've lost games at home, that they were taken
to seven games.''
</P>
<P>
   And although O'Neal should easily score more than the 17.5
points a game he settled for in Games 6 and 7, he's bracing for
more abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it won't be easy,'' O'Neal said. ``They're probably
going to pack it in and force our shooters to hit some shots. ...
But I'm just going to play my game and do what I've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for the quick turnaround between the last round and this
one, O'Neal welcomes it. His Orlando Magic team in 1995 had more
than a week off before the Finals and ended up getting swept by the
Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's better (this) way. You really don't have time to
celebrate,'' O'Neal said. ``You get prepared for the other team and
you can keep it going. Last time I went to the Finals, which was in
'95, we had like 10, 11 days off, and we just kind of lost focus,
messing around, joking around. But we had a half a day to
celebrate, now it's back to business and it all starts up
tomorrow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 0032EDT &QL; 
