<P>
   DIM-RESTAURANTS (New York) _ Over recent years more and more
restaurants have veered closer to nightclubs with hidden addresses,
incredible noise levels and lower and lower lighting. Some have
become so dim that you don't know if you're in the theatre or a
mosh pit. Diners can be seen corraling votives to read the menu,
and some restaurants like Blue Hill and Grace have conceded the
difficulty by having waiters at the ready with flashlights and
reading glasses to loan. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-DRINKS (Undated) _ It was a spring evening last March. I
sat in a gravel courtyard outside the Cafe du Lezard in St.
Remy-de-Provence, waiting for a table to clear. I ordered the house
drink from a chalkboard, a rose peche: a glass of rose wine with a
splash of peach liqueur. I took a sip; it was like an interior
sunset. Two ingredients. It couldn't have been simpler. But it had
the big kaboom of science. The next thing I remember I was hungry.
The first asparagus. Young lamb. Early strawberries. The idea of
the rose peche came back with me to New York, like a Provencal
glow. But it was harder to find the same understanding, or
availability, of the house drink. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
