<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6715 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-DODGERS-RANGERS-L     06-07 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-RANGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAGNE GETS FIRST `W' AS DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ARLINGTON, Texas _ Scarborough Green has a big-time name and
big-league swing, but this was Eric Gagne's night. Finally.
</P>
<P>
   The proof during Tuesday's 7-1 Dodgers victory over the Texas
Rangers was Green's fifth-inning blast into the right-field stands
that touched off fireworks at The Ballpark in Arlington and was
announced as his first major-league home run.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson ran out to argue. It was worth
spoiling the party because replays showed the ball landed three
feet foul. But it also was critical because Gagne was making his
eighth start in search of his first victory this season.
</P>
<P>
   Umpires changed their call. Then they had to coax a reluctant
Green out of the Rangers dugout and back to the plate where he
popped to short. And though Gagne pitched one more inning, his long
wait for victory ended right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so great to get that first one out of the way so we can
start working on the second,'' said Gagne, who scattered five hits
in six-plus innings. ``All of this has been an adventure and I've
learned a lot. But there is nothing like coming out on the winning
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Gagne went out for the seventh but left after David Segui opened
with a double and Chad Curtis walked. Terry Adams came on to pitch
out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give Eric a lot of credit because we have had to skip him in
the rotation and that can be tough on a young pitcher,'' Johnson
said. ``It's not something I like to do, but we've wanted to keep
(Kevin Brown) and Carlos (Perez) on a regular schedule. Eric has
done very well with it, which is great because we are going to need
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who were shut down the night before by Ryan Glynn
and John Wetteland, didn't have much success against Texas starter
Mark Clark (3-4) until the fifth, when they scored four times.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hansen capped the inning when he greeted Clark's
replacement Francisco Cordova with a two-run single. Gary Sheffield
had two hits and two sacrifice flies. Rookie shortstop Alex Cora
added two hits, two runs and raised his average to .280.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Dodgers, who had dropped eight of 12, had 14 hits.
Shawn Green, who reached base twice for the 41st time in the team's
55 games, also robbed Rusty Greer of a home run with a leaping
catch at the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers finally scored in the eighth inning when last year's
AL MVP Ivan Rodriguez homered off Adams. Mike Fetters pitched the
ninth for the Dodgers, who end their six-game trip here this
afternoon before returning home Thursday to play Houston in the
makeup of an April 17 rainout.
</P>
<P>
   ``A game like this makes you feel like good things are going to
start happening,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne went 1-1 with a 2.10 in five starts last September when he
made the jump from Double-A San Antonio. But this year had not been
so kind.
</P>
<P>
   He was so bad in four spring-training starts that he opened the
season in Triple-A. He made one start there and pitched six
scoreless innings. Gagne returned to the big leagues and pitched
well in spots, but he did not break through until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Against Cincinnati in mid-April, Gagne left with a lead after
allowing three hits and two runs in five innings, but the Dodgers
bullpen could not hold it.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, against East-leading Atlanta, Gagne allowed four hits
and one run in seven innings but lost 2-1 to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned something from every game I've pitched, the good
ones and the bad ones,'' Gagne said. ``Sometimes you get breaks,
but mostly you have to make your own. You have to make good
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he had a four-run lead, Gagne's pitch to Green in the
fifth could have shaken his confidence. The Dodgers applauded
first-base umpire Gary Cederstrom for asking the other umpires what
they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see that very often, but I know I appreciated it,''
Gagne said. ``The ball was clearly foul, but you have the crowd
cheering and the fireworks going off. What are you going to do? The
umpire made a great call.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
