<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6716 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NJ-ELECT-1STLD-WRITET     06-07 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ELECT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SPENDING $35 MILLION, CORZINE WINS DEMOCRATIC SENATE PRIMARY
IN N.J. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs top of story for updating, rewriting; also subs last 4 grafs
for updating and rewriting)  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Jon Corzine, the Wall Street multimillionaire
whose $35 million spending spree shattered all records for a Senate
race, easily defeated former Gov. Jim Florio on Tuesday in the
Democratic primary for the seat being vacated by Sen. Frank
Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   In the four-way Republican primary, Rep. Robert Franks, a
four-term congressman from Union County, declared victory at 12:20
a.m. on Wednesday over State Sen. William Gormley, a veteran
lawmaker from the Atlantic City area who nonetheless refused to
concede.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' Corzine shouted to the crowd at a hotel
ballroom in East Brunswick. ``I want to invest in America. That's
what this campaign will be about.''
</P>
<P>
   Conceding defeat Tuesday night at 10:35, Florio said he would
support his rival. ``This has been a tough campaign, this has been
a very spirited campaign,'' Florio told dispirited supporters at a
hotel in Cherry Hill. ``I disagree with Jon Corzine on a number of
issues, but I agree with him a lot more than I would agree with any
of the Republicans who are running for that office.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio's aides had hoped that a low turnout caused by heavy
rains Tuesday morning would favor him, but in unofficial returns
reported by The Associated Press, with 98 percent of districts
reporting, Corzine had 245,901 votes, 58 percent, to 178,562, 42
percent, for Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, in his victory speech, likened himself to Gov. Christie
Whitman, former President Ronald Reagan, Gen. Colin Powell and Sen.
John McCain. But he also acknowledged his relatively poor name
recognition and quickly borrowed a line of Florio's to begin his
campaign against Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good evening, New Jersey, I'm Bob Franks, the candidate with
experience that money can't buy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gormley, speaking simultaneously in Egg Harbor, refused to
admit defeat, saying about 100 precincts had yet to report results.
``We're going to look at the numbers and wait until everything
comes in,'' he said. ``It's not my intention to needlessly prolong
this process.''
</P>
<P>
   With 98 percent of districts reporting, Franks had 95,546 votes,
or 35 percent; Gormley had 91,738 votes, or 34 percent; James W.
Treffinger, the Essex County executive, had 47,792, 18 percent; and
Murray Sabrin, who ran for governor as a Libertarian in 1997, had
34,089, 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, Corzine's stated willingness to spend
whatever it took to win now has put a burden on Republicans, who a
year ago, before Governor Whitman dropped out of the race, had
viewed New Jersey as an easy victory. Republican leaders now will
have to decide whether to commit large resources to try to defeat
Corzine, or focus on other, less costly races.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's entry into the race as a self-financed candidate saved
state Democratic leaders from having to raise as much as $10
million for a less wealthy Senate candidate. Now, his victory in
the primary means they will be able to focus on the real prize of
New Jersey politics: the governor's race in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic outcome had rested on two uncertainties: whether
voters would be persuaded or repulsed by the money Corzine spent on
his campaign, and whether Jim Florio could overcome the lingering
animosity of Democrats still nursing grudges over the $2.8 billion
tax increase he signed as governor in 1990, fueling years of
Republican electoral victories.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine was expected to spend $2 million on Tuesday alone in
get-out-the-vote efforts, from rain gear and rented vans to
payments of $75 or more for his street workers. The previous record
for a U.S. Senate primary was $8.1 million, and Corzine has already
exceeded the nearly $30 millon Michael Huffington spent in vain in
his race for the U.S. Senate in California in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Democrats was embodied by one couple at the
public library in Westfield. ``I wasn't going to vote, but I'm
opposed to someone who spends $36 million to buy an election,''
said Mark Rubin, an accountant voting there. ``Florio was an awful
governor, but I voted for him because no one has a right to buy the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bu Rubin's wife, Andi, said she could not bring herself to vote
for Florio. She waited in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The winner in November succeeds Lautenberg, who surprised the
state's political community in February 1999 when he announced that
he would not seek a fourth term. Lautenberg, himself a millionaire
businessman, said he did not want to spend two years raising money
for re-election. He endorsed Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time as Lautenberg announced his retirement,
Corzine was forced out of his job as co-chairman of Goldman Sachs.
When Goldman Sachs held an initial public stock offering in May
1999, Corzine received 4.4 million shares, and instantly became
worth $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   When Corzine's candidacy emerged several months later, it was
viewed as the answer to a prayer by many Democrats, among them Sen.
Robert Torricelli, who believed the only way to defeat Florio was
with a great deal of money.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, as combative as he was in three races for governor,
relentlessly assailed Corzine as a political neophyte whose naivete
could not compete with his own experience in state government and
as an eight-term congressman. With a meager $2.5 million budget,
Florio ran only attack commercials in the last two weeks of the
race, and had to be pressed at times to articulate his own agenda
were he to win a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Florio did little to deflect Corzine's attacks, which began
on television in mid-April and remained unanswered for a month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The New Jersey primary also featured three of the nation's most
competitive congressional races. In the Fifth District, Marge
Roukema, a 20-year incumbent, clung to a narrow lead over E. Scott
Garrett, a state assemblyman. With 99 percent of the vote counted,
Roukema, who beat Garrett by 1,710 votes two years ago, was
maintaining nearly the same margin, 1,571 votes, or 52 percent to
Garrett's 48.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12th District, where two former congressmen fought a
testy campaign for the Republican nomination, Richard Zimmer scored
a convincing victory over Mike Pappas. With 100 percent of
districts reporting, Zimmer had 62 percent of the vote to Pappas'
38 percent. The winner will face a freshman Democrat, Rush Holt,
who two years ago defeated Pappas, who succeeded Zimmer in 1996
when Zimmer vacated his seat to run for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the Seventh District, with a crowded field of four
Republicans and four Democrats, Michael Ferguson, a college
instructor, defeated Thomas Kean Jr., the former governor's son,
and two other candidates. In the Democratic field, Maryanne
Connelly and Michael Lapolla were almost tied at 45 percent each
with 99 percent of the precincts reporting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
