<HEADER>
A6720 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-07 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF A REFORMED REGGIE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A decade and more, we've waited to get Reggie
Miller back in Los Angeles for basketball games that matter. And
this is who shows up?
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen-points-a-game Reggie?
</P>
<P>
   Second-option Reggie?
</P>
<P>
   A (ital) reformed (endital) gunner?
</P>
<P>
   A leader by example?
</P>
<P>
   Say it ain't so, Reg.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the rumor swirling around the Staples Center on the
eve of tonight's NBA Finals opener between Miller's Indiana Pacers
and the Lakers that Reggie Miller, 34 years old and 13 seasons out
of UCLA, has toned down his act, for what is quaintly referred to
as the good of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, he would talk about getting it done. Now, he just gets
it done,'' said John Salley, the Lakers' veteran backup center who
is a long-time Reggie-watcher. ``He's leading more by example. You
see him in his interviews more professional clothes, more
professional manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Clothes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. Some guys get up there and look bummy. He gets up there
and looks professional. That shows how he's matured and realizes
how you present yourself carries over.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Salley said that, Miller climbed onto a
press-conference podium wearing a fishing hat pulled low over dark
shades, and a long-sleeved Pacers T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   There went the fear he's grown up completely.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there were the words of Pacers guard Travis
Best, on Miller's new willingness to (is he kidding?) pass the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought last year, when we played New York (in the Eastern
Conference finals, losing in six games), there were times guys may
have been open but he took the shot because he felt like he had
to,'' Best said. ``He just didn't have the confidence in the other
guys late in the game. Now, he doesn't mind giving the ball up for
the last shot. That's what you have to do to win.''
</P>
<P>
   To which we say: Good for Indiana, but meanwhile, Los Angeles
would like to sell some tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Mellow Reggie isn't going to put fans in the seats. We might as
well pay to see Mark McGwire choke up and hit ground balls to
right, to see Deion Sanders field snaps for the field-goal kicker,
or to see Oscar De La Hoya and Shane Mosley settle it with a game
of backgammon.
</P>
<P>
   When you go to the WWF, you want to see a guy bashed over the
head with a chair. And when you go to see the Pacers, you expect to
see a guy bombing 3-pointers from 30 feet, giving ``choke'' signs
to the opponents' bench, and keeping up the taunts all the way to
the team bus.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to that Reggie?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, thank goodness, is that he's still around here
somewhere, and he's reemerging.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different Miller who led the Pacers during their 56-26
regular-season run to the Central Division title. The difference
being that the 6-foot-7 guard didn't actually lead them.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 11 years, Miller (18.1 points a game)
wasn't the Pacers' top scorer. The improvement of guard Jalen Rose
(18.2) relieved him of that burden.
</P>
<P>
   In place of his old 21-points-a-game air show, Miller displayed
new facets to his game. Inverting the concept of improving your
range, he became more than a pure jump shooter, showing off
mid-range and post-up shots and drives to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can kind of pace himself and let Jalen Rose do his thing
for a little while, Travis Best, other guys,'' said Lakers guard
Brian Shaw, who came into the league a year after Miller. ``But I
think he has more of an all-around game now. He's always been able
to shoot the ball from the perimeter. But he's taking the ball to
the basket and finishing well, (while) getting to the free-throw
line, which he's always done.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of this is entirely new for Miller. Pacers president
Donnie Walsh points out that he drove more early in his career,
before the NBA's cycle of rule changes led to rougher play, making
the paint unsafe for slender young men.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't have made it through a season if he'd kept that
up,'' Walsh said during the Pacers' practice Tuesday at the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, knowing he'll have to adapt to survive as he ages,
Miller added muscle to his frame, his listed weight rising from 185
before the 1998-99 season to 202 on the Indiana playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing better defensively, too,'' Shaw said. ``A lot of
people look at his slender frame and think that he's weak. He's a
wiry-strong kind of guy. His competitive spirit and his will
enables him to compete and get the best of a lot of guys who are
bigger and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   He broadened his repertoire as well as his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Miller played with the Lakers' Kobe Bryant in the offseason and
each picked up something from the other. Miller learned some
one-on-one moves. Bryant learned about using screens and about
Miller's step-back jumper. Oh, and Bryant learned about Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves contact, he draws fouls and gets to the free-throw
line,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Ron Harper _ who was an NBA rookie as Miller was
completing his 2,000-point UCLA career in 1987 _ will be the Lakers
most responsible for guarding Miller in this best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades after another Reggie (Reggie! Reggie!) in pinstripes
tormented Los Angeles, another is poised for the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news for the Lakers is that after Miller let his scoring
average slip to its lowest in 11 years during the regular season,
he has raised it to its highest (23.8) in four years during the
Pacers' playoff victories over Milwaukee, Philadelphia and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   He's looking like the NBA's all-time leader in playoff
3-pointers (185) again.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for all but the most unromantic Lakers fan is that
this means vintage Reggie, one of the great basketball entertainers
of the 1990s, is here in 2000 after all.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire will swing from the heels, Deion will high-step into the
end zone, and Oscar and Sugar Shane will throw leather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team game, of course, but there are guys who lift a
team up, and Reggie is one of those guys,'' Walsh said. ``He has
the ability to make the shots when the game is on the line. And he
visibly wants the ball for the last shot. There aren't many guys
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy who scored 25 points in the first quarter of a 1994
playoff game against New York, and who scored eight in the last 8.9
seconds of a 1995 playoff game against New York, is the one who put
the Pacers in their first NBA Finals by scoring 17 of his 34 points
in the fourth quarter of Friday's Game 6 victory over the same poor
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Riverside product is pumped to be playing his first
championship series in front of family and friends in Los Angeles.
He's also pumped as ever to be considered an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope they overlook us,'' Miller said from beneath that hat
and those shades. ``We're not coming in here to lay down. We're
coming in here to shock the world. ... Great players should step up
when the money is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Did somebody say Reggie has cut out the big talk?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I think he's still talking as much as he ever has,'' Shaw
said, laughing at Salley's assertion. ``That's something that gets
him going. I played with Larry Bird, and I can't remember anyone
who talked more than him, but that's what got him going.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to the guys on our team (is), if he's having a quiet
night, let sleeping dogs lie. Don't start talking and get him hyped
up. We've seen what he can do when that happens.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
