<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON TOWERS OVER SEATTLE SPORTS SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A 30-foot poster of Gary Payton draped over a building
in the heart of downtown goes a little beyond symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the building is NikeTown. And granted, Payton is in
Phil Knight's stable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the message is clear: Seattle is his city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's saying I'm going here or there or whatever. I say
just let me relax a little. Everybody knows I want to stay with
Seattle,'' Payton said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It is not every day you get to replace Ken Griffey Jr., but
Tuesday was that kind of day for Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Where Griffey's face was emblazoned for three years on the front
of Nike's flagship storefront on glittery Sixth Avenue, there is
now a shot of Payton _ which Payton unveiled during a special
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   He is captured from his tough-guy, photo-shoot stare all the way
down to his two-tone, No. 20 `Glove' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look here,'' Payton said, pointing to the feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This photo is from 1996. See those shoes? Those are the first
`Glove' shoes. We're up to the fourth edition by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton also said the bulging biceps and popped veins running
down his forearm were not technically enhanced by some darkroom
geek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, now. That stuff's all natural,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton likes the poster. And the people of Seattle, or whoever
voted in a poll to choose Griffey's replacement, seem happily
married to this guy named Gary _ sometimes wild, sometimes crazy,
sometimes generous, always a character.
</P>
<P>
   It is not Alex Rodriguez who was voted as the new poster boy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is because Rodriguez is widely viewed as on his way
out of town, the caboose in a trainload of exiting talent starting
with Shawn Kemp and continuing with Randy Johnson, Griffey and Joey
Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   But a larger part of how Payton earned his place literally on
the Seattle skyline is because of all the sweating and sneering
he's done over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rumblings to the contrary, fans are starting to see that
Payton could be a lifelong Sonic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees the value to dedicating himself to being a one-team
athlete,'' said Payton's agent, Eric Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   It is this kind of mindset that could lead Payton and the Sonics
to a contract extension. With three years left on his 1996 deal for
$87 million, it is the right time for such a move.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, short of ripping the team apart and rebuilding,
 &UR; gfgrave &LR; a la the Bulls or Magic, would be insane not to lock up
Payton.
</P>
<P>
   For every snarl, for every media blowoff, for every TV remote
control thrown at Vernon Maxwell that seems to underscore Payton's
volatility, Payton has countered with conciliatory gestures, many
of them deeply meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the school kids Payton helps sponsor were brought over
to Planet Hollywood for a nice lunch. The Gary Payton Foundation
got a $5,000 check from Nike, added to the millions Payton has
raised and donated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I got a lot of people looking at me, asking me for
my time, and I try to do everything I can, and I'm going to keep on
trying,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude apparently applies to the Sonics as well.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever roller coaster the Sonics were on for the second half
of the season, Payton said he has no issues with head coach Paul
Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I complain is when it's real bad. Right now I
think things can be fixed,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   Payton has a few suggestions for general manager Wally Walker. A
center would be good, for instance the Wizards' Jahidi White or
Magic's John Amaechi.
</P>
<P>
   As for 2-guard? Maybe Walker should take a seat for this: Isaiah
Rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says he's a problem, but you have to deal with the
problem, because he can score on the floor. He can't ask for too
much, so I say give him a year, take a risk. If I'm with him, I
think I can work with him. Off the court, that's where he has his
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton might also take a trip to visit Rashard Lewis, the
talented 20-year-old who is a restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rashard wants to come back here. Just before the
draft, I'm going to talk with him. He can come play and score 20-30
points a night here, and I think this team is better suited for
him,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own summer plans, Payton is taking the kids to Disney
World, taking his wife to the Bahamas, then heading off to his Las
Vegas home in July to start training with Tim Grgurich for the
Sydney Olympics and next season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a close-up view during playoff work for TNT, Payton said
the Western Conference champion Lakers don't scare him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw us last year. We were in games all the time against
those guys. I think we just need a couple more pieces and we'll be
all right.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Payton's part of the Seattle ``We.'' He's into it.
He's towering over everything now. It suits him.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
