<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMED AND DANGEROUS: BUHNER, JAVIER THROWS HALT ROCKIES RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Pinball Wizards broke loose in the sixth inning at
Safeco Field Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Colorado trying desperately to rally from a 3-1 deficit,
Mariners outfielders Jay Buhner and Stan Javier took turns playing
the Safeco wall to precision.
</P>
<P>
   On consecutive plays in support of reliever Rob Ramsay, Buhner
threw out Todd Helton at second base and Javier threw out Jeffrey
Hammonds trying to reach the same destination, helping preserve the
Mariners' 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very inflating for us, and very deflating for them,''
shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. Rodriguez took Buhner's throw on a
tough in-between hop to put the tag on Helton. ``They're thinking,
`We hit a couple of rocket doubles, and we've got two out and
nobody on.'''
</P>
<P>
   In each case, Helton and Hammonds short-hopped the outfield wall
with balls that probably should have been doubles. But right
fielder Buhner, then left fielder Javier, read the angles of the
wall to perfection. Each was waiting in place for the ball when it
bounded back toward the infield. Each plucked the ball out of the
air, then whipped it toward second base and an eventual out.
</P>
<P>
   A proper pinball machine would have had bells and whistles
shrieking and lights flashing. Buhner and Javier had to settle for
prolonged ovations from the 26,812 in attendance, who saw those
plays help the Mariners turn the corner in a win that gave them
sole possession of first place in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised I threw the ball that well,'' Javier
said. In his youth, Javier had a nice arm, but age and a series of
injuries has sapped some of its suppleness. ``I used to throw the
ball a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be tough for Javier to throw the ball better than he
did, bringing the crowd to its feet.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no pinball machine would be complete without a trap
door. The Rockies found one when Jeff Cirillo hit what he thought
was a three-run homer, only to see it turn into a single,
short-circuiting an inning that had the potential to make the
Mariners go ``tilt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, that's where I had my trouble _ damage control,''
Mariners starter Brett Tomko said. ``When you can get out of an
inning like that giving up just one run, you're in pretty good
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo, batting with two on and none out in the third, crushed
a Tomko serve for what he thought was a three-run homer. But
first-base umpire Eric Cooper, as close to the ball as anyone who
hadn't bought a ticket, ruled _ correctly, replays would show _
that the ball didn't go out. Instead, it hit the top of the fence
and stayed in play.
</P>
<P>
   Although base runners Tom Goodwin and Mike Lansing each advanced
a base and stayed put, Cirillo, who didn't have Cooper's view of
the ball, was caught in a rundown and was tagged out by first
baseman John Olerud. Hammonds would get the Rockies a run with a
sacrifice fly, but Tomko escaped without a major mishap and would
go on to record the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Paniagua pitched 21/3 innings of strong scoreless relief to
reach the ninth inning, where Kazuhiro Sasaki took over and
finished up for his ninth save, his second this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge 21/3 innings Jose gave us,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``He gave it to us when we really needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua took over for Ramsay in the sixth. Ramsay was in
trouble even after the two pinball throws, walking the next two
batters he faced. Paniagua warmed up in a hurry, came in, got a
grounder to Rodriguez to get the third out, then pitched two more
shutout innings, aided by Mark McLemore. The second baseman plucked
a tough but soft short-hop off the bat of Cirillo out of the air
with runners on the corners and turned it into an inning-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of defense going on tonight,'' Javier said.
``The play McLemore made was something else, too. Ever since I've
been here, I've been impressed by the defense we've played.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you don't win (division titles) without defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Punctuating the point, the Mariners took over first place in the
West, with Texas losing to fall a game off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   The game wasn't without some downside for the Mariners. Rickey
Henderson left with what was called a stiff neck, and Tomko took a
line drive off his left foot in the third inning. Henderson was
scheduled to get Wednesday off anyway, and Tomko isn't expected to
miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third inning was kind of a daze to me after that,'' Tomko
said.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, because hitters have been in kind of a daze facing him in
interleague games. After picking up his fourth win in six decisions
overall this year, Tomko improved his career record to 7-0 in
interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' Tomko said, ``but if they want to
play all interleague games, it's fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said his injury was in his shoulder blade more than in
his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me when I run it gets aggravated,'' Henderson said.
``It should be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning has a way of making things all right.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
