<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS FROM MIRACLE GAME 7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers and Reggie Miller will hopefully forgive the
Lakers and their bandwagon if they begin the NBA Finals tonight
still hung over from Sunday's Miracle on 11th St.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the Western Conference Game 7 win over Portland the
biggest win in this generation of Lakers, but it came about 10
minutes away from being the Flop on Figueroa, too. Friends and
colleagues who have replayed tapes of the fourth quarter still have
a hard time accepting the result.
</P>
<P>
   Three themes left over from Game 7 are sure to be continued
during the series:
</P>
<P>
   1. The maturing of Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   When all of the Laker world was about to crumble in the fourth
quarter, it was Kobe who kept his wits about him and made big play
after big play. They weren't all big plays along the lines of a
28-foot jumper or a highlight-worthy drive through the lane,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe made defensive stops, rebounds, blocks and assists in
between his field goals. Jerry West should take immense pride that
Kobe has developed into the kind of dominating, complete player he
envisioned when he dealt for the high school graduate during the
1996 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant took the Portland challenge personally. The Trail Blazers
kept saying they could break Bryant down, but in the end the
opposite was true. In the fourth quarter, Bryant broke down Scottie
Pippen. ``They were saying they wanted to expose me, post me up,
break me down,'' said Kobe. ``It got under my skin. I said I wasn't
going to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he has a chance to win an NBA title in his third pro
season. He's still precocious, but with poise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I've dreamed about,'' Kobe said Sunday,
pausing for effect, ``for all my 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we have to remember is that it's still just
basketball. Have fun and play.''
</P>
<P>
   2. The continuing education of Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   There were times in Game 7 when the NBA camera peered in on the
face of the Lakers' center and showed the nation a young man with
streams of honest sweat rolling past anxious eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when Shaq seems to get caught up in the tension
of the moment, and he becomes so intent on making correct decisions
that he becomes a bit tentative. He all but acknowledged as much
when noting, ``sometimes when we try too hard, we make a lot of
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But considering the onslaught he faced against Portland, this
was understandable. I don't care how big a person is, when a team
decides to aggressively triple-team a player, and when the
officials will allow them any contact short of rape, it is going to
wear him down.
</P>
<P>
   And not enough has been said about the difficulty of playing
Portland's Arvydas Sabonis. The Lithuanian is a 7-foot-3, 300-pound
tree trunk, the only real physical match for O'Neal at least in
terms of size, who also forced O'Neal to move out defensively to
guard his outside shot.
</P>
<P>
   In the two biggest losses in the series for Portland, Sabonis
was absent for key stretches the third quarter of Game 3, when Mike
Dunleavy left him on the bench too long, and the fourth quarter of
Game 7, when Sabonis picked up three fouls in five minutes of play
and fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   He exited with 8:35 left after picking up his fifth, and the
Trail Blazers were outscored, 6-0, before he returned with 4:19
left. He fouled out 95 seconds later, Shaq making two free throws
to tie the game, and the Trail Blazers never led again.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, like most NBA teams, has no answer for Shaq. The NBA
record for highest scoring average in the Finals is Michael
Jordan's 41.0 in 1993 against Phoenix. I'd have to think it's in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   3. The psychology of Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, there have been times when it's been abnormal
psychology. I can't say I was very impressed by the way he tried to
get in the head of Scottie Pippen, even if it ultimately worked.
Pippen took himself out of Game 7 by backing away from the
challenge in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jackson knew he would. But the daily thumping of Pippen's
psyche, including employing Rick Fox like his jailhouse character
in the HBO series ``Oz,'' seemed cheap, like clubbing baby seals.
Reggie Miller isn't likely to go down from these kind of tricks in
the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson seems more interested in playing with the minds of
his own players. He has dangled this team's ``arrival'' all season,
and it still hangs there despite the Portland win.
</P>
<P>
   He'll still push it, too. He'll undoubtedly remind them that
seven of the eight teams in the modern era that finished the
regular season with a winning percentage over .800 the Lakers'
67-15 comes home at .817 went on to win the title, the only
exception being the 1983 Celtics (68-14, .829, East Conference
finals losers to New York). That list includes three of his six
title-winning Bulls teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see if we've learned anything,'' he said after Game 7.
Well, here's a tip to Shaq and the fellas: Phil will always have
you chasing this carrot. After all, he has eight rings.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to have their attention. The Portland series turned out
to be a lot closer than it had to be, just like Sacramento. That
doesn't mean the Lakers won't throw a shoe at least once in the
Finals, just as they have in each series. But there's less chance
it will become a continuing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Especially since Bryant has a chance to do something not even
Jordan did win a title by his fourth season. Especially since Shaq
now has a chance to bury that sweep at the hands of Houston in the
'95 Finals, not to mention the other similar endings since.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Orlando (in 1995), we had a full week off before the
Finals,'' said O'Neal. ``There was a lot of partying. Our focus was
on making the Finals. After we beat the Bulls and Michael (in the
1995 Eastern Conference finals), we felt we had it won.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude this time is that we have four more games to win.
There is still a job to be done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 0317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 03:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6726 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LADN     06-07 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE HOPE FOUND FOR PACERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around the truly important places water coolers, bar stools and
latte lines the NBA Finals 2000 already is considered the biggest
mismatch since Rik Smits' first blind date with black socks.
</P>
<P>
   Smits, who's never been on ``NYPD Blue,'' is employed by the
Indiana Pacers as their starting center. About as nimble as the Tin
Man with ACL issues, this guy.
</P>
<P>
   Having an obligation to explore the bright side, it should be
stated that the 7-foot-4 Smits _ known as the ``Dunkin' Dutchman''
before gravity reduced his feet to aper weights _ can shoot it. And
make it. But his presumed inability to check Shaquille O'Neal _
backed by solid evidence threatens to make Pacers vs. Lakers as
competitive as a surfboard in a tsunami.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any hope for the Indiana Pacers?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not, but in the interest of analytical freewheeling,
let's explore one of the few variables in their favor:
</P>
<P>
   It's known as 2-3-2, which reads as if it could be defined as
the illegal defense Buddy Ryan designed for Portland's Trail
Blazers in their relatively successful skirmish with O'Neal. But
what 2-3-2 really represents is the venue breakdown for the NBA
Finals, a tricky proposition allegedly born of geography.
</P>
<P>
   The first two games are to be contested in the arena of the team
with the home-court advantage (Lakers), followed by three at home
for the underdogs (Pacers), wrapped up _ if necessary _ by two more
at the original site. This is a not exactly slight deviation from
the 2-2-1-1-1 format of the conference quarters and semis. It's
also a warning for the favorite to take care of business in Game 1
and 2.
</P>
<P>
   According to league spotters, this change (which has been used
for a few years now) is to reduce the number of back-and-forth
trips required for teams with vast time-zone differences.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Lakers' erratic behavior in the Portland series,
location may not be anything. But we're struggling to identify a
competitive edge for the Pacers, and this may be the best we can
do.
</P>
<P>
   OK, they seem to have the stronger bench, but the previous
series demonstrated that it's unwise to go cuckoo over that one.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an extremely ambivalent coach in the departing Larry
Bird, Indiana has a pack of accomplished snipers, the ringleader
being former UCLA star Reggie Miller. The Lakers' marvelous Kobe
Bryant figures to have Miller duty during the important stretches
of this series. Miller duty means chasing one of the NBA's ranking
trash talkers through a phalanx of illegitimate screens designed by
savvy assistant coach Rick Carlisle.
</P>
<P>
   Pacer point guard Mark Jackson should be no problem for Laker
Ron Harper, but Jackson's caddy, speedy Travis Best, could be a
nightmare. Best, a headline writer's secret weapon, was
particularly menacing in the Pacers' Jan.14 victory over the Lakers
at Indianapolis. Even with smallish Derek Fisher assigned to
violate his airspace, Best _ with the help of high screens by Smits
_ smoked L.A. in a memorable fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   However, the biggest defensive dilemma the Lakers must address
is posed by small forward Jalen Rose. Rose, voted the NBA's Most
Improved Player, figures to be a tough cover for Glen Rice. This is
where Indiana could do some business.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Lakers may even try to hide Rice on Jackson, leaving
Miller and Rose to Bryan and Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Power forward Dale Davis is the key rebounder for a
poor-rebounding squad, but on a team of offensive rifles, he's
something of a musket.
</P>
<P>
   As a defensive unit, the Pacers are less formidable than the
swarming army from Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is the shotblocker, Smits the lumbering liability and
Jackson, a former Clipper, is slower than Friday afternoon traffic.
Miller and Rose have their moments defensively, but when Bird needs
a few stops, he relies on Best _ one of the few humans who has a
reasonable chance of staying in front of Philly's Allen Iverson _
and reserve forward Derrick McKey. Despite going almost 6-10, McKey
is extremely agile and could be summoned to take on Bryant when
Kobe starts to get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's unofficial defensive coordinator is Dick Harter, the
former University of Oregon coach whose philosophy of stinginess
earned a seat next to Chuck Daly in Detroit and one beside Pat
Riley in New York. Harter's theories include shunning the low-post
double-team, while ganging up when the opponent attempts an
on-the-ball screen.
</P>
<P>
   But the triangle offense directed by Lakers assistant Tex Winter
and promoted by Phil Jackson has little use for on-the-ball
screens. And there will be two reasons for Harter to rethink his
notion about double-teaming the post:
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   He can attempt to handle Bryant on the post with McKey; but the
only answer he has for O'Neal in a one-on-one setting is Smits.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why, despite the 2-3-2 proposition, it looks like
Lakers in five. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
