<P>
   EDITORIAL-UN-WOMEN _ The year 2000 graduates have received their
diplomas and most schools are out for the summer. But 110 million
children never entered school this year_ two thirds of them girls.
That's one reason wny the United Nations meeting on women this
week, a follow- up to the 1995 Beijing conference, is so important.
(The Atlanta Constitution). 9.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-GAMBLING _ Bet you didn't know there are more than 250
online casinos, 64 lotteries, 20 bingo games and 139 sports books
attracting suckers on the Internet. Legislation to ban this
activity passed the Senate in relatively good shape, but the
measure has collected harmful House amendments like a ship acquires
barnacles. House should start all over. (The Atlanta Constitution).
8.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ It's true that Veronica was one of the youngest
and the smallest, and that she had entered the class mid-year. Last
November, I had visited Jeraldyne's _ the teaching school of the
Dayton Contemporary Dance Company _ only days after the death of
founder Jeraldyne Blunden. Inspired by the grace and enthusiasm of
the young dancers, I decided to enroll Veronica, who always seemed
to be dancing to some inner beat.(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ Puzzling is how my private e-mail account also
is filling up with junk mail. I'm not sure how all these people
find their way to my personal e-mail address. I have several e-mail
addresses. I welcome messages from any and all sent to my public
e-mail addresses. But I also have a couple of private e-mail
addresses that I give out only to people I want to contact me.
(NETHAWAY, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ Two weeks ago Michael ``Cowboy'' Toney tried to
sell five seats to his own execution on the Internet auction site
eBay.com. This is false advertising, because there are no seats in
the viewing room at the execution chamber in Huntsville. The
auction was on display only about four hours; eBay shut it down
before anybody bid on the alleged seats. Prison officials say that
even if someone had bought seats, they couldn't get in. (Kelso,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
