<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6848 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN08-COX     06-07 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Capitalizing on capital punishment
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got to hand it to death row inmate Michael ``Cowboy''
Toney for displaying that good old Texas entrepreneurial spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Toney tried to sell five seats to his own
execution on the Internet auction site eBay.com. This is false
advertising, because there are no seats in the viewing room at the
execution chamber in Huntsville, Texas. The auction was on display
only about four hours; eBay shut it down before anybody bid on the
alleged seats. Prison officials say that even if someone had bought
seats, they couldn't get in.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, poo-- . This is Texas, where lethal injections are as common
as honky-tonkin', rodeo and the cow-chip toss. Why is the state
picking on this guy just because he's trying to make a buck off one
of Texas' leading institutions?
</P>
<P>
   Texas may not lead the nation in everything _ it's been a while
since we won a college football championship. But by George, as in
George W. Bush, we are No. 1 in state-sponsored killing: 216 since
1982, and 131 since Bush took office in 1995. Why shouldn't Toney
be allowed to make a fast buck off the phenomenon? Obviously at
these rates, there's a market out there.
</P>
<P>
   If a guy wants to drum up a little extra cash on his way out,
why stop him? Heck, if he wants, he ought to be able to leave a
couple of extra tickets at the -- ill -- all window for Elvis. It
wouldn't take a visionary such as myself to point out that the
state could set up a Death Row Gift Shoppe outside the viewing
room. There could be Big House refrigerator magnets, ``He's Outta
Here'' T-shirts, death row potholders, coffee cups, paperweights,
even ``We're No. 1'' foam hands.
</P>
<P>
   I personally wouldn't want one. But what capital punishment
booster wouldn't want to dangle his car keys off a key chain
decorated with Death Row and the state seal?
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't do my Christmas shopping in a place like that. But
I'll bet plenty of Texans would. And I say guys like Toney ought to
be able to get a piece of the action _ before the state gets a
piece of him. It's only fair.
</P>
<P>
   Executions are supposed to be a deterrent, right? Isn't that the
logic behind the justification? I personally wouldn't want to go to
a show like this. But wouldn't executions be even more of a
deterrent if Texans could buy a ticket to look? Why not increase
capacity for viewing executions at Huntsville from the current 20
or so to something much larger, with theater seating?
</P>
<P>
   May I suggest an Offing in the Round, a dinner theater
arrangement where ticket buyers get to enjoy the same last meal
selected by the victim. I hear cheeseburgers are a big favorite. If
you want something light, you probably should eat before you come.
</P>
<P>
   The state could sell sky boxes. Let's think big here. How about
a football stadium with a retractable roof and making the guy the
halftime show?
</P>
<P>
   It would be just the thing for that depressing lull that sets in
for bored Texas sports fans after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, as execution-happy as we are in this state,
why doesn't somebody come up with a cable channel called the
Execution Channel? ``All gurneys, all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Me? I think I'll stick with Animal Planet.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman. He can be
reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
