<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6850 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX     06-07 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dancer's disdain, delight
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Edgar Degas had seen her, he would immediately have taken up
his paint brush or sculpting clay.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica swung her pink recital dress back and forth like a
wedding bell. With her pageboy cut swept up into an elegant French
twist, she looked the very portrait of the dainty young dancer.
</P>
<P>
   This effect had taken considerable effort _ a trip to the
hairdresser's complete with a public tantrum: ``I want to keep my
pinktails!'' But I knew in my heart it would all be for naught. No
amount of adorableness, I feared, would prevent her from ruining
the dance recital.
</P>
<P>
   I had tried to bail two weeks earlier, when Veronica was showing
no signs of getting with the program, quite literally, in her
creative movement classes at Jeraldyne's School of the Dance. While
all the other 4- and 5-year-olds struggled valiantly to learn their
routines, Veronica stared into space or twirled around,
ragdoll-limbed, in her idiosyncratic interpretive dance.
</P>
<P>
   I felt sorry for her teacher, Monnette Bariel. Here she was, a
world-class dancer with a world-renowned dance company, coping with
a recalcitrant 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think she ought to go through with the recital?'' I
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, she'll be fine,'' Monnette answered stoically. ``She's
coming along.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as I could tell, she was only ``coming along'' when one
of the other little dancers yanked her by the hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Veronica was one of the youngest and the
smallest, and that she had entered the class mid-year. Last
November, I had visited Jeraldyne's _ the teaching school of the
Dayton Contemporary Dance Company _ only days after the death of
founder Jeraldyne Blunden. Inspired by the grace and enthusiasm of
the young dancers, I decided to enroll Veronica, who always seemed
to be dancing to some inner beat.
</P>
<P>
   That, alas, proved to be the problem. When the other little
girls gamely pretended to be butterflies or trees, she pretended to
be a bunny rabbit. Or stared into space.
</P>
<P>
   The creative movement class, the youngest group of dancers, was
scheduled to perform first at Saturday's concert. They must have
been terrified, these pint-sized performers, as they skipped
onstage one at a time. Yet their faces blossomed into smiles, as
naturally as sunflowers to sunlight, when they hit the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   All of them, of course, except Veronica. She waited in the
wings. And waited.
</P>
<P>
   With a performer's true instinct _ or the instinct of a kind
heart _ the next little girl in line grabbed Veronica's hand, and
they skipped onstage hand-in-hand.
</P>
<P>
   The girl continued to mother-hen Veronica, patiently showing her
where to plant her feet. Their pas de deux _ the one dancer all
helpfulness, the other all stubborn cluelessness _ drew delighted
laughter from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never told her to do that,'' Monnette said afterward of the
mission of mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Monnette put Veronica onstage? Maybe it had something to
do with Jeraldyne Blunden _ with her determination and grit and the
freedom she gave her dancers to make choices. Monnette eulogized
Blunden as ``a mother figure to me.'' Other instructors paid
tribute to Blunden with a series of poems and reminiscences during
an annual student concert.
</P>
<P>
   When I picked my daughter up at intermission, Veronica was
oblivious that she had been anything less than the star of the
show. Which, in a sense, she had been. She stared up at me with her
deep brown eyes and pulled a carnation from her pocket. Her face
blossomed into a smile:
</P>
<P>
   ``My teacher gave me a flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX     06-07 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growing privacy concerns sure to make issue a hot one this
election
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only time I fail to find my mailbox stuffed with junk mail
is on postal holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Most of my junk mail is flipped into the trash unopened. Most of
the rest also is junk mail that I open because it looks close
enough to personal mail that it tricks me.
</P>
<P>
   I admit that I must have caused this flood of junk mail by
occasionally buying merchandise out of catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of some kitchen knives several years ago brought
forth catalogs and offers featuring every item remotely associated
with knives or the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   More puzzling is how my private e-mail account also is filling
up with junk mail. I'm not sure how all these people find their way
to my personal e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   I have several e-mail addresses. I welcome messages from any and
all sent to my public e-mail addresses. But I also have a couple of
private e-mail addresses that I give out only to people I want to
contact me.
</P>
<P>
   How do people get their hands on my private e-mail addresses? I
don't know, but it gives me an eerie feeling that I'm being
watched.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of Americans feel the same way. According to a New York
Times article by Richard L. Berke, both presidential political
parties and their candidates believe that privacy will emerge as
one of the big hot-button issues during the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Neil Newhouse said privacy ``tests off the
charts.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's pollster, Mark Penn, said privacy is ``a
pretty powerful groundswell.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush told Business Week, ``I'm a
privacy-rights person. The marketplace can function without
sacrificing the privacy of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's recent speech at New York University
put privacy front and center. He said there is greater protection
for video rental receipts than for most intimate medical
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen cases where people's prescription drug histories are
sold freely to direct mail companies without their permission;
where hundreds of employees at an HMO have access to patients'
records,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, both presidential candidates and their parties are
going to try to claim the high ground when it comes to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   By 47 percent to 41 percent, Americans responding to a March
Gallup Poll believe Bush would do a better job protecting ordinary
citizens from privacy invasions.
</P>
<P>
   More than being upset with junk mail, both real and virtual,
polls show a growing number of Americans don't trust the keepers of
their financial and health records.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation moves more to wireless communications for personal
and business uses, Americans worry that their privacy will be
further eroded.
</P>
<P>
   I once wrote that I bought a frequency scanner for my car before
a long road trip that also picked up cell phone conversations,
which was a complete surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Reader response was swift and outraged, both at me for buying
and reporting on the device, and at the government for allowing the
public to purchase such an evil piece of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, I had no idea that people felt so deeply about
their cell phone privacy, particularly when analog cell phone calls
are transmitted unscrambled and can be received on an inexpensive
frequency scanner easily purchased at electronic stores around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   These privacy anxieties have not escaped the political parties
that intend to promise all manner of government controls over
privacy invasions.
</P>
<P>
   When the candidates make their promises to pass laws to protect
privacy, voters need to make sure that the cure is not worse than
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor at the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
