   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-INJURIES _ The Packard Foundation will release a report
June 8 (embargoed till then) asserting that injury-prevention
campaigns aren't successful in reducing accidental injuries among
children in the US, and only legislation can make a difference.
Prevention of accidental injury is a major CDC concern, so we seek
their reaction to the Packard proposal. (McKenna, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   GECKOS _ WASHINGTON _ High-speed photography has revealed the
secret that allows gecko lizards to scurry up sheer walls or along
the underside of ceilings. Hundreds of millions of microscopic
hairs on the lizards' feet enable them to invoke a form of atomic
energy known as the ``van der Waals force.'' The force causes atoms
to cling to each other and enables geckos to cling to just about
anything. Berkeley University researchers describe their research
in the journal Nature on Thursday. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). 30.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
