<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE08     06-07 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE: News, notes from the wrestling industry
</P>
<P>
   By John Allen
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Last week Multichannel-Online reported that World Championship
Wrestling lost over $60 million last year and is on pace to lose
close to that amount this calendar year. Guess we know why
cost-cutter Bill Busch isn't around anymore. According to the
report, ``there was talk of SFX (Entertainment) wanting to buy a
stake in WCW, but a Time Warner official already went on record by
saying that WCW is not for sale. WCW President Brad Siegel couldn't
be reached for comment. It appears as if the negotiations with SFX
are merely for them to promote live WCW events. This would be WCW's
worst financial year as of yet if the projections hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers will probably hold because top stars such as Ric
Flair, Bret Hart and Hulk Hogan are finishing up guaranteed
contracts and television ratings are still lagging. The World
Wrestling Federation is only seven weeks away from topping WCW's
record of consecutive Monday night ratings' winners. Nitro held a
streak of 83 straight wins over RAW dating from 1996-1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ While WCW maybe losing its shirt, ECW star Sandman is losing
his pants. At last weekend's TNN tapings in Pensacola, Fla.,
Sandman was the last man to enter the ring in an eight-man tag
match (Steve Corino, Jack Victory, Scott Anton and Rhino vs. Raven,
Tommy Dreamer, Tajiri and Sandman). Sandman, whose gimmick involves
chugging and spilling a few beers on the way to the ring, appeared
drunk before he entered the ring, falling down and needing
assistance to get into the ring. The wrestlers in the ring came out
of character and laughed at Sandman. Sandman grabbed the microphone
and promised the crowd he'd flash them and did so a few times.
Raven and Dreamer got Sandman to put his pants back on and got him
out of the ring. As a result, Sandman is expected to be fined and
the Bayfront Auditorium, where the event was held, will not welcome
the return of ECW anytime soon. Of course it will make for
interesting editing for ECW executive producer Paul Heyman.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another wrestling tragedy happened last week. An independent
wrestling group, UWF, had a wrestler die from injuries suffered in
the ring Wednesday. According to The Union Leader of Concord, N.H.,
Mark Mendlan, 20, died as a result of severe neck and head
injuries. Mendlan, who wrestled as Kid Gorgeous, was dropped on his
head by his opponent, Ben Alcorn, who wrestles as the Dudeman.
Mendlan laid motionless in the ring for several minutes after
landing awkwardly from the gorilla press slam. He was rushed to an
area hospital where he was pronounced dead. The match was the first
professional match for Alcorn, who told UWF officials that he had
been involved in backyard matches for years and had trained with
UWF for three weeks. Mendlan started with UWF at 18 and came from
backyard wrestling matches.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you missed it the first time, NBC will re-run the Saturday
Night Live episode that was hosted by The Rock on Aug. 10. The show
was the highest rated SNL: episode of the year.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are in Arizona Saturday, you'll get a chance to see
former WWF star Shawn Michaels at the Diamondbacks' baseball game.
Michaels will be throwing out the first pitch before the game
against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of the Heartbreak Kid, HBK-TWA.com, the official Web
home of Shawn Michaels' Texas Wrestling Alliance, says it will hold
another TWA vs. ECW match featuring their champion against ECW
champ Justin Credible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maybe he's changing his gimmick, but 'Stone Cold' Steve Austin
is scheduled to be on the Oprah Winfrey show on July 16th. The
title of the show is ``Live with the Famous.''
</P>
<P>
   _ She has seen her fame wane, but former WWF valet Rena Mero,
better known as Sable, will have an online chat with the Microsoft
Network on June 13 at 7 p.m. She is scheduled to talk about her
dedication to fitness, her new book and professional wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   _ On DustyRhodes.net, Rhodes says former WCW wrestler and
current Turnbuckle Championship Wrestler Ray Lloyd, a.k.a. Glacier,
will get a tryout with ECW.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spike Dudley says on his Website, SpikeDudley.net, that
reports of a five-year deal between Dudley and ECW's Heyman are
untrue. In fact Dudley, has been out of action for the last two
months with a knee injury and probably won't return until the fall.
He claims to have not talked to Heyman in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rebuilt American Wrestling Association has signed a bit of
their past _ the Road Warriors. The first team to hold the AWA, NWA
and WWF tag team championships, the Road Warriors have been looking
for work since being let go by the WWF last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
