<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-N     06-07 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS FROM THE WORLD OF COMPUTERS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRADE SHOWS SUFFER
</P>
<P>
   The shakeout and consolidation that is sweeping Internet
retailing has reached a related industry: Internet retailing trade
shows.
</P>
<P>
   After a month of layoffs, closings and executive layoffs at
Internet retailers, the publisher and show organizer, Faulkner &AMP;
Gray, has canceled its Internet Retailer World 2000 conference,
which was scheduled later this month in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt T. Peters, a group publisher at Faulkner &AMP; Gray, said that
Web trade shows were under the same pressures as Web retailers.
More narrowly focused shows, like automobile e-commerce
conferences, are now in favor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the normal shakeout and consolidation you see in
any industry,'' Peters said. ``It's just happening faster on the
Internet because everything happens faster on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters said registration was still strong for another show,
Electronic Commerce World 2000, which his firm was planning for
October in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In another bad omen, the Internet Retailer World 2000 show had
also planned to feature some companies that are now in deep trouble
_ or out of business. ToySmart, the defunct Disney-backed toy Web
retailer, had agreed to send its chief e-commerce officer, Mark
Reese, to the show as a speaker. Executives from the struggling
companies CDNow and Skymall.com, were among other officials who had
originally agreed to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as another confirmation that there's a problem in the
e-commerce segment,'' said Richard Smith, an Internet consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Smith knows this first-hand. In February, he agreed to speak at
Internet Retailer World 2000 about balancing marketing needs with
customer privacy. But in mid-May, he received a letter from the
organizers saying the show had been canceled because not enough
people had signed up.
</P>
<P>
   --LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   SALON RELENTS AND REDESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to soothe ruffled readers, the online magazine Salon.com
completed its product recall last week.
</P>
<P>
   Salon pulled back the site redesign, which had elicited an
immediate and hearty chorus of e-mail boos and hisses from readers
after it was introduced on May 22. The disgruntled audience said
the new site included bugs, was hard to navigate and used type that
was too small to read.
</P>
<P>
   Within two days, Salon's editor, David Talbot, posted a note to
readers saying he had heard their wails and was taking the concerns
into consideration. Then, last Thursday, came another note from
Talbot, entitled ``Salon to readers: you win!'' and introducing a
new new design that addressed many of the readers' criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   The new five-column look remains in place, but the third and
fourth columns effectively serve as a single column to showcase a
feature article. Type sizes can be controlled by readers, and
headlines for the main articles once again link directly to the
reports, rather than taking readers through department home pages.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot said the magazine in its latest guise had accomplished
the goals of promoting breaking news from news services while also
featuring more of Salon's own content. But he said the latest
overhaul had also removed the bugs and eliminated some of the
``horizontal sprawl'' that one reader complained about in the May
22 redesign.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot said the ``ear splitting'' response had indicated how
deeply the readership was attached to the magazine. ``We
unwittingly turned our readers into a focus group,'' he said,
noting a lesson for any future redesigns. ``Maybe we'll test it out
a little internally first.''
</P>
<P>
   --MATT RICHTEL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-04-00 1818EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
