<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-HUEY-MAGS-MEDIA-A     06-07 1568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-HUEY-MAGS-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAGAZINE GIANT WEIGHS IN ON INTERNET BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Huey is a magazine editor known for his Southern
charm and pit-bull mentality: when he has an idea between his
teeth, he might be pleasant about it, but he will never let go.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Huey, managing editor of Fortune magazine,
decided that Time Inc. ought to start or purchase a magazine about
Internet business. He flew to San Francisco and met with editors
and publishers at The Industry Standard, Red Herring and Business
2.0, deciding who or what or whether to buy. No luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to see if there was a way that we each could satisfy
the other's goals, and we basically decided we could not,'' Huey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he could not buy 'em, he joined 'em. The result is
E-Company Now, a new monthly magazine from Time Inc. that Huey said
cost less to start ``than it would have ever cost to pay the
Internet multiples everyone was asking for.''
</P>
<P>
   With the first issue, released three weeks ago, Huey and his
editors jumped, some would say belatedly, into a fray of magazines
that besides The Standard and Red Herring includes titles like
Upside, Fast Company and _ take a deep breath _ the newly
rechristened Ziff-Davis Smart Business for the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the dot-com advertising boom to last forever.
What's more, Huey must keep E-Company Now from leeching content
from Fortune, its inspirational parent.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this daunts Huey. ``I'm relatively confident this is
going to work,'' he said in an interview last week from his home in
Atlanta. (Huey prefers to commute to work from Georgia most weeks
than to live in New York City.) ``We figured out about two years
ago that the whole Internet story was moving out of the realm of
being a tech story alone. But we never wanted Fortune to drill down
so deep into the subject that it became a magazine just about the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Company Now may soon have something else going for it that the
other magazines do not, words that would make any Internet-magazine
mogul's heart go pitter-pat: America Online and Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other magazines in the field do not have the benefit
of Time Inc.'s expertise in consumer magazines or the marketing
clout of AOL, which has given the magazine special placement on
choice CompuServe, AOL and Netscape sites. So far, those sites have
generated more than 30,000 subscriptions, said Ned Desmond, editor
in chief of E-Company Now.
</P>
<P>
   Huey said the advantages of Time Inc.'s backing were obvious.
``We are not running around trying to raise a new round of
financing or preparing an IPO,'' he said. ``We're running around
trying to get the best editors and writers we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, most of the magazines about Internet business _ even
those that are still raising financing and preparing initial public
offerings _ are thriving and expanding. Business 2.0, which is
published by Imagine Media in San Francisco, shifted from a monthly
to a twice-a-month publication three issues ago.
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring, published by Red Herring Communications, will do
the same in November; its June issue is 628 pages. Ad pages for The
Industry Standard, the weekly from IDG, are up almost 500 percent
against last year and have almost surpassed those of People
magazine. Its issues often reach 360 pages, including both
advertising and editorial material.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the magazines have been buoyed by the fact that the
market for advertising pages promoting dot-com companies has grown
exponentially the last three years. In 1997, online, Internet and
e-commerce companies spent $113.2 million in advertising in
American magazines, according to Competitive Media Reporting.
Spending climbed to $153.6 million in 1998 and then surged to
$687.3 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide has shifted in recent months, as some of the
speculative excess in technology and Internet stocks has subsided;
many of those advertisers can no longer afford to spend so freely
and no longer need to reach the venture capitalists who thumb
through the Internet magazines. Rich LeFurgy, chairman of the
Internet Advertising Bureau, said the flow of dot-com advertising
would soon abate and probably fall steeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shift is toward more moderated spending and more effective
spending,'' LeFurgy said. ``You were getting to absurd lengths with
some of these magazines as it was. They were getting out of control
in terms of the number of ad pages relative to editorial. That will
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Huey said he had already thought of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not naive about advertising,'' he said. ``We have along
with the dot-com advertising, consumer advertising and business
advertising, liquor, cars, fashion. Yes, we will take every dot-com
ad that can pay for it, but our business plan is not built on
soaking up an ever-growing pool of dot-com advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The real battle among the Internet magazines may play out not in
terms of advertising pages, but in the more mundane sphere of
old-fashioned circulation. While some of the Internet business
magazines have significant circulations, most remain fairly small.
Ziff-Davis Smart Business for the New Economy has a circulation of
1,048,941, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations, but that
was all gained when the magazine was still known as PC Computing.
(Ziff-Davis repositioned the magazine to a business-strategy
magazine with the May issue.) Fast Company's circulation is
402,603, according to the circulation bureau.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the magazines have circulations closer to that
of Model Railroader, and many give away the bulk of their
subscriptions free.
</P>
<P>
   Upside, which is not audited by the Audit Bureau of
Circulations, reports circulation of 257,000, of which 15,000 are
paid. Gini Talmadge, president of Upside Media, said that the
subscriptions were given away to qualified readers, meaning readers
who have filled out a survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``So our subscriber list reads like a Who's Who of the
Internet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Industry Standard, which also is not audited by the Audit
Bureau of Circulations, gives away half of its weekly 150,000
circulation to qualified subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Huey said that competition like The Industry Standard, Business
2.0 or Red Herring was not a threat to his new magazine, which has
guaranteed advertisers a circulation of 200,000 readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Industry Standard says they are a must-read for anybody
doing business on the Internet,'' Huey said. ``If that's true, why
does it have a circulation of 150,000 and half of it they give
away? They are the hot trade book. And that's a very good position
to have. But look at us. We want to be a national business magazine
that is informed by the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Weber, editor in chief of The Industry Standard, does
not dispute the circulation figures. But he said paid circulation
was growing ``at a healthy pace'' and that ``substantial
increases'' would be announced soon. He dismissed Huey's other
criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   There are potential pitfalls for Huey's and Desmond's magazine.
Editors of competing magazines are quick to criticize Time Inc. for
coming late to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are two years late to the party,'' said James Daly,
editor in chief of Business 2.0. ``They have to do something that
other magazines are not doing, and there's not a lot of space
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential problem is that E-Company Now is a monthly
title in a field that is now almost exclusively on weekly or
twice-a-month schedules.. But Huey said the magazine's Web site,
with its daily columnists and a business-to-business component,
would help keep readers plugged in. He suggested that the shift to
twice-a-month publication by Business 2.0 and Red Herring was part
of a strategy to get more advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems pretty obvious to me what that's about,'' he said.
``Our argument is that they are not doing the frequency thing for
the reader.''
</P>
<P>
   About Huey's theory, Ted Gramkow, publisher of Red Herring,
said, ``I don't think so.'' He countered, ``This is John Huey's
way, and Fortune and Time Warner's way, of attracting dollars that
have been beyond their high price in Fortune. This is a pure
advertising play.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it would be hard for any publisher to argue that
readers want even more Internet magazines. But the titles continue
to proliferate. Business 2.0 is introducing an as-yet-unnamed
offshoot in October, a business lifestyle magazine whose editor in
chief is a former editor of Harper's Bazaar and In Style.
</P>
<P>
   The former publisher of Office Products International is
introducing line56, an Internet-business magazine whose title was
inspired by the famous soliloquy in Act III of Shakespeare's
``Hamlet,'' that begins with the words ``To be or not to be.''
</P>
<P>
   IDG, The Industry Standard's parent company, has just introduced
Darwin: Business Evolving in the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to be way too much for me,'' LeFurgy of the
Internet Advertising Bureau said. ``I have total information
anxiety. The magazines just stack up and stack up in my office
now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-04-00 1648EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
