</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-GAMER0606-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Maken X looks great but lacks substance
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Superconsole horsepower pushing superconsole graphics does well
to hide less than super gameplay in Maken X ($40; www.sega.com; for
the Dreamcast). There is probably a reason the first-person
``slasher'' genre is under exploited: A sci-fi sword game offers
close-quarter combat but does not, by nature, offer an appropriate
perspective. Maken is the weapon, with an innate ability to ``brain
jack'' or possess various characters throughout the game. But this
clever approach is befuddled by poor control of the mostly-unseen
Maken wielder. Auto-locking on a given target does afford the gamer
some ability to dodge/thrust/parry without becoming completely
disoriented, but it makes for a shallow combat system just the
same. Add to that a story that is so completely hokey _ (We're
fighting evil. How evil? The Devil!) _ and plodding, poorly
scripted dialogue, and all you end up with is a great-looking,
fast-moving, wannabe anime role-playing sword game that only
exploits fresh gaming style, while the extraordinarily cool gaming
concept is unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   X-COM Collector's Edition ($30; www.hasbro-interactive.com; for
Windows) is a retro buff's dream, harkening back to the days (a
mere half decade ago) when games were perhaps more graphically
simplistic yet characteristically more deep, more absorbing and
simply better _ in this case at least. A collection of the three
X-COM strategy games, UFO Defense, Terror from the Deep and
Apocalypse, Collector's Edition, promises to satiate both the game
addict's hunger for a solid game experience as well as introduce
new or casual gamers to purity of gameplay often lost in late-model
splatter and gore festivals. A set of strategy, micromanagement and
resource hoarding games in essence, the X-COM titles have always
garnered praise for their attention to intangible details and sheer
addictiveness. One more kick at the can seems their due, especially
at a mere $10 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   Need For Speed: Porsche Unleashed from Electronic Arts ($35,
www.needforspeed.com, for Windows PCs) takes a big risk by focusing
its game on a single line of automobiles, and it succeeds wildly.
Driving the venerable ''Need For Speed'' franchise to a new,
faster, more hair-raising place with a long list of innovations,
the focus here is on creating a true simulation, not just a game.
And the genius is in the details, from the glint of sunlight on
chrome to the completely realistic driving physics, fully
functional dashboard, mesmerizing replay mode and long list of
once-and-future Porsches you can customize and drive. Multiple
camera angles capture every twist of dozens of beautifully detailed
tracks, all so easy to customize that you'll never run out of ways
to race. Perhaps the most fun is in the ''evolution'' style of
campaign gameplay in which you work toward faster,
smoother-handling cars. The only drawback is the large amount of
computer muscle needed to run the sim, but you can easily tweak
down the detail level. Electronic Arts promises to have an online
racing site running within a few weeks to make the multiplayer
options easier. This is the best of the series and goes to the top
of the list of ''must-haves'' for road-racing gamers. Vroom.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
