<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS0606-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    'Best encyclopedia' is no idle boast for Microsoft's Encarta
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a ``Letter from the Editor'' on the opening page of
the Microsoft Encarta Encyclopedia Deluxe 2000, Gary Alt calls his
product ``the very best general encyclopedia available in any
medium _ electronic or print.''
</P>
<P>
   He may be right.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of pure information, Britannica has to be considered
king of the encyclopedia hill. However, while I have not seen the
2000 edition, last year's electronic Britannica was just beginning
to test the multimedia waters. Britannica doesn't hurry into
anything.
</P>
<P>
   One can argue that an electronic encyclopedia is more valuable
than a print encyclopedia, because its user can find the
information more readily, and because it can present information
that the print media cannot, most importantly in terms of video and
audio.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Encarta is by far the best of the 2000 electronic
encyclopedias I have seen. The Deluxe version is available in the
Reference Suite _ five CDs or one DVD. I'm looking at the latter.
In addition to the encyclopedia, which can be had separately, the
reference suite includes the World English Dictionary, which
provides synonyms and basic facts and figures in addition to
standard dictionary services, and Microsoft's Interactive World
Atlas as well as a research organizing tool.
</P>
<P>
   Encarta's interface has been revamped again. Gone are the rather
startling (at least initially) snap-down menus, replaced by the
more familiar click-to-scroll kind. Every article is accompanied by
boxes containing links to available multimedia, topic-specific
online sites and an assortment of online search engines.
</P>
<P>
   The most imposing feature of Encarta continues to be its refusal
to shortchange its users through cost-cutting. You won't hear the
segment of Haydn's London Symphony played on some electronic
version of the hurdy-gurdy. You'll hear it played properly by an
orchestra. All the music, and there's a lot of it, is played on the
instruments for which it was written. You don't get this on any
other electronic encyclopedia with which I'm familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Some information _ as with any of the encyclopedias _ is shaky.
The unsigned article on flamenco is still the most accurate and
informative of all, but it persists in referring to Spanish gypsies
as Roma or Romani instead of gitanos, and uses the word ``canto''
instead of the proper ``cante'' for the vocal heart of the art.
</P>
<P>
   A video clip from a film on gypsy life has been added, which is
most welcome. But once again, the information is somewhat wrinkled.
It shows a woman dancing what is purported to be a zambra, ``a type
of flamenco dancing which owes much to Roma culture.'' The zambra
owes much to Moorish culture, not gypsy culture. What little we
hear sounds more like a tango, which indeed owes much to the
gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   Also new is the Archive, a large collection of articles from
Collier's Yearbook taken from the years before Encarta was created.
There doesn't seem to be much point to most of the older stuff
other than curiosity; it's extremely general, stiff and, the
intervening years have shown, wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Encarta continues to do a good job of appealing to all ages. It
is not as erudite as Britannica, which I suppose is a commercial
advantage in this anti-erudite age, nor does it cater obviously to
the elementary school student.
</P>
<P>
   The time line is a wonderful tool. It can be broken into
numerous topics _ art, science and the like _ and into numerous
areas _ Africa, Europe, etc. _ and two of these can be brought
on-screen for direct comparison.
</P>
<P>
   If you can only have one encyclopedia, Encarta is the one you
want.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
