<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, June 7, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS:  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-HOLES (San Francisco) _ They're the vacuum cleaners of the
universe: black holes, those cosmic monsters that devour stars with
nary a burp. They're not rare: A super-size black hole occupies the
centers of each of at least 33 galaxies including ours, the Milky
Way, scientists announced this week. More than six decades after
the first modern speculations about black holes, they have become a
central topic of astronomical study, especially at Stanford and
MIT. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   OTTER-THEFT (San Francisco) _ The folks who stole Harriet the
river otter from the Oakland Zoo in the dead of night this week
will not get the cuddly, playful creature they might have expected,
says assistant zoo director Allison Lindquist. ``She has really
sharp claws and she bites. They don't make good pets,'' Lindquist
adds. The zoo pleads for a safe and speedy return, saying the
animal could die without professional care. By DEMIAN BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   ABALONE-DIVERS (San Francisco) _ The Sonoma and Mendocino coasts
of California have always been a paradise for abalone divers, the
last sanctuary for the beloved red abalone _ where commercial
diving has long been prohibited. But a recent sweep of San
Francisco Bay Area abalone poachers unveiled again how greed and a
lucrative black market have severely threatened a species. By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH (San Francisco) _ He was the second most powerful
politician in America, the combative, high-profile speaker of the
House, whose name was synonymous with militant conservatism, and he
left Congress under a cloud. But Newt Gingrich, his confidence and
ambition unimpaired, is still on a mission, and he's thinking big.
Gingrich, now a scholar at Stanford University's Hoover
Institution, a political analyst for Fox News and founder of the
Committee for New American Leadership, has morphed into a futurist.
By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-CONTRACTING (San Francisco) _ The Rights Commission
should be stripped of its control of San Francisco's troubled
minority contracting program in order to limit political influence
over the awarding of big public works contracts here, a consultant
recommends. Such a move would greatly diminish the influence of
Mayor Willie Brown. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-ARTIFACTS (Watervliet, N.Y.) _ State officials say that
hundreds of valuable military artifacts have disappeared from
armories and small museums in New York following decades of
mismanagement and shoddy bookkeeping at these facilities, which
collectively contain one of the nation's most prestigious wartime
collections. By BRENDAN LYONS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-WEB (Undated) _ The technology industry is touting
wireless Internet access as the next must-have, something
indispensable and vital to consumers. Wireless devices are selling,
but consumers aren't flocking to the service. Instead, consumers
seem to be asking: Is this freedom, or is this nonsense? By ROY
BRAGG.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE (San Francisco) _The traditional, if somewhat shaky,
honor system that dominates online buying and selling was further
transformed this week when Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. and the leading online
auction site eBay Inc. said they are introducing an option to pay
for purchases online with an electronic check. By CHRISTIAN
BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-APPOINTMENT (San Francisco) _ A low-key San Francisco
businessman who has been one of the Democratic Party's biggest
donors in recent years despite past problems with federal
regulators will be named by the White House to an important trade
post involving the Far East. We profile the prospective nominee,
George Chao-Chi Chu - who trades with Europe, China, Taiwan and
Japan from the office here. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MILSAP (San Antonio) _ Ronnie Milsap's decision to forego
law school and stick with music led him to become one of the most
successful artists in country music history. For the first time,
Milsap's colossal collection of chart toppers is now available in
one package, Virgin Records Nashville's ``40 No. 1 Hits.'' By JOHN
GOODSPEED.
</P>
<P>
   CATSKILL-BOOK (Haines Falls, N.Y.) _ Edward Henry is a blend of
scientist, historian and artist. He U.S. Fish &AMP; Wildlife Service
employee also is the author of ``Catskill Trails: A Ranger's Guide
to the High Peaks'' (Black Dome Press, $14.95). The informative
guide is far more than a basic catalog of the various hikes
available in this area. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARAPLEGIC-SWIMMER (San Antonio) _ Jason Pipoly, 29, a
paraplegic since breaking his back in a car accident two years ago,
is determined to swim the English Channel, a feat he first
attempted when he was 11 years old. When he will again try the
grueling swim from England to France is still up in the air. But
the training has begun in earnest on a small, quiet lake northwest
of San Antonio. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
</TEXT>
