<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATSKILL-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EARLY LOVE OF CATSKILLS INSPIRES RANGER'S BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAINES FALLS, N.Y. _ Edward Henry is a hybrid. Part tour guide,
part student, Henry is also a blend of scientist, historian and
artist.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains why hiking with Henry along the eastern
escarpment of the Catskill Mountains is such a unique experience.
The former Eagle Scout studies and explains the cycles of emerging
mountain laurel and wild blueberries, all the while showing his
guest the breathtaking vistas to the south and west that inspired
Thomas Cole and other painters.
</P>
<P>
   Henry is beginning a new project in the mountains that he
considers his second home. He wants to pinpoint the various
locations where Cole and other members of the Hudson River School
painted their famous romantic landscapes. Then he plans to
photograph those views, roughly a century and a half later, to
compare how the ever-evolving Catskills have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone's ever done a real accurate examination
of the landscapes these painters depicted then versus how they look
now,'' Henry said, removing a faded black Baltimore Orioles cap to
wipe his brow. ``I'm thinking this might make a nice
coffee-table-type book.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to another element that is at Henry's core:
author. The 30-year-old public affairs specialist with the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service has in the past few weeks published his
first book, ``Catskill Trails: A Ranger's Guide to the High Peaks''
(Black Dome Press, $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   The informative guide is far more than a basic catalog of the
various hikes available in the region, which receives considerably
less recreational traffic than the Adirondack Mountains. That's
because it reflects Henry's multifaceted fascination with the
Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   He started writing the book a decade ago when he was an
undergraduate at Binghamton University. A native of West Hurley, in
Ulster County, Henry became familiar with the rugged terrain west
of the Hudson River as a youth. But a camping trip during his
sophomore year in college to Woodland Valley, during which he hiked
to Wittenberg and Giant Ledge, changed him forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The views during that camping trip were just incredible,''
Henry recalled. ``We looked down into the Ashokan Reservoir and it
simply sparkled. In the distant horizon we could see Vermont,
Massachusetts and Connecticut. It was awesome, and I was hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next six years, as he completed a master's degree in
forest ecology at Syracuse University, Henry continued to explore
the Catskills' rocky trails, cataloging his observations and
researching the specific history of the various areas.
</P>
<P>
   He was also writing about each adventure and taking photographs,
putting together what he envisioned as a coffee-table book.
</P>
<P>
   However, Debbie Allen and Steve Hoare, the editors at Black Dome
Press in Hensonville, had other ideas. When they read Henry's
manuscript they saw an opportunity to publish a hiker's companion
guide with a fresh perspective, a soft-cover book that belongs in a
backpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catskill Trails'' is the first of two books by Henry that
Black Dome is putting out. Book One, which started appearing in
bookstores in late May, focuses on the northern Catskills, from
Mount Utsayantha to the west to Kaaterskill High Peak just seven
miles from the Hudson River. Book Two, scheduled to be released
next year, is devoted to the southern Catskills, the region that in
the mid-1800s was often referred to as the Shandaken Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Henry no longer lives in New York. For almost three years he and
his wife, Kerry, have lived in Pennsylvania near the Delaware Water
Gap. Henry commutes to Pleasantville, N.J., across the bay from
Atlantic City, where he is stationed with the Fish and Wildlife
Service.
</P>
<P>
   But he regularly returns to his home turf, usually with his
American Eskimo dog, Arctic, in tow. Hiking and bushwhacking _
going off the trail to a particular destination _ are among his
favorite activities, and the Catskills are his favorite
destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most people realize how accessible the Catskills
are,'' Henry said. ``There are a lot of easy hikes that take only a
morning or part of an afternoon. These mountains are as easy or as
hard as you want them to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
