<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-MILSAP-HNS &LR;      06-07 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MILSAP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RONNIE MILSAP RELISHES MUSIC AND HIS MANY HIT SONGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GOODSPEED  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Ronnie Milsap faced a difficult decision in the
mid 1960s _ follow through on a scholarship in Atlanta and become a
lawyer, or play music.
</P>
<P>
   If he hadn't quit college, Milsap said in a telephone interview
from Nashville, Tenn., ``I'd probably be in Atlanta _ and they sure
don't need any more lawyers over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Milsap's choice led him to become one of the most successful
artists in country music history. For the first time, Milsap's
colossal collection of chart toppers is now available in one
package, Virgin Records Nashville's ``40 1 Hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the late Conway Twitty had more country hits, but those
included duets with Loretta Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the secret is, just do your work, man, and things
happen,'' Milsap said. ``You just do what you love to do. Music is
my baseball, my tennis or my golf _ it's an avocation and a
vocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard work, but most of the time it's fun. And I wound up
here at the year 2000 with 40 No. 1 records. I'm just proud to have
been part of something like this for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Milsap's string of No. 1 hits began with a triple in 1974:
``Pure Love,'' ``Please Don't Tell Me How the Story Ends'' and
``(I'd Be) A Legend in My Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some top 10 songs followed in 1975, but he nailed six No. 1s in
a row beginning in late 1976 and stayed in the top 10 for the next
15 years. Through the mid-1980s, such pop crossovers as ``It Was
Almost Like a Song'' and ``Smoky Mountain Rain'' secured his
stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Milsap blurred lines between hard-core country, R&AMP;B, soul, '50s
rock and other forms of pop, causing occasional controversy but
winning six Grammy and eight Country Music Association awards.
</P>
<P>
   Milsap declines to pick a song he likes the most, much like a
good parent won't choose a favorite child.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all been kind of like children in some ways,'' he
said, explaining the long nurturing process _ finding a song,
getting the right people in the studio, fitting it all together
just so and then sending it out to mature on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole thing of making records, it's a bunch of voodoo
anyway,'' Milsap said. ``It's not nearly as planned as you'd
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Milsap's magic resulted in not just one career song, one that
not only defines an artist but raises the bar for his next effort,
but 10.
</P>
<P>
   He considers ``Pure Love,'' his first No. 1, as a career song,
along with several remakes _ Kris Kristofferson's ``Please Don't
Tell Me How the Story Ends,'' Don Gibson's ``(I'd Be) A Legend in
My Time'' and Al Dexter's 1944 ``Too Late to Worry, To Blue to
Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Daydreams About Night Things' is the next big thing that
happened because it was a song that was totally identifiable with
me that nobody else had done before,'' Milsap said.
</P>
<P>
   He was with songwriter John Schweers at Charlie Pride's
publishing company when ``John read that Olivia Newton John had
made a comment in a magazine that she'd been having daydreams about
night things. He jumped up and said, `I'm going to write a song
about that.' It made a lot of noise at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are ``It Was Almost Like a Song,'' pop crossovers ``Smoky
Mountain Rain'' and ``Getting Over Me,'' ``Stranger in My House''
and ``Lost in the Fifties Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Milsap surmounted a number of obstacles to get where he is. Born
blind and in poverty in the Appalachian town of Robbinsville, N.C.,
he was sent to a state school for the blind in Raleigh. His
instructors noticed his musical talents and he mastered the violin,
guitar, woodwinds and his trademark piano.
</P>
<P>
   As a young adult, Milsap didn't rush into country music. He sang
R&AMP;B in Atlanta first and had a hit with ``Never Had It So Good.''
He met his wife of 34 years, Joyce, moved to Memphis and did
session work _ keyboards on Elvis Presley's ``Kentucky Rain'' and
singing harmony on ``Don't Cry Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   When his R&AMP;B career sagged, he moved to Nashville, hooked up
with Charley Pride's manager, Jack Johnson, and signed with RCA, an
association that continued until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Milsap is busy preparing to tour in support of ``40 1 Hits,''
which features two new, uptempo songs with a new sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Producer Scott Hendricks said he was going to drag me into the
new century,'' Milsap said, ``and he did with `Livin' On Love'' and
`Time, Love and Money,''' which will hit the radio on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Milsap also is selecting songs for his next Virgin Nashville
album, which he says will feature more contemporary tunes along
with others reminiscent of his older work.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes his new efforts will add to his list of hits, although
he's happy where he is, working with his son, Todd, as production
manager and lighting director, and being a grandfather of two young
girls with a grandson on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is the business I'm in,'' Milsap said, ``but I'd be
doing this whether I got paid or not.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact John Goodspeed by e-mail at
jgoodspeed(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
