<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMID PEACE TALKS, BARAK FACES CALLS FOR NEW ELECTIONS
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ While negotiators try clear the way for a peace
summit, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's political opponents Wednesday
tied to take his Israeli government to the brink.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's parliament voted 61-48 for preliminary passage of a
bill calling for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The move does not mean the immediate downfall of Barak's
year-old government. The bill would have to pass several more
procedural steps that could take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some of those voting for the measure may have just been
making a symbolic show of dissatisfaction in an attempt to win
leverage over nuts-and-bolts domestic Israeli issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle will likely prove a distraction to Barak as he
moves ahead with peace talks with the Palestinians and attempts to
rekindle stalled talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright returned to Washington on
Wednesday after talking to all sides. U.S. officials are pushing
for progress in the closing seven months of President Clinton's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian talks focus on the Golan Heights, a plateau that
Israel captured in 1967. The talks broke down in January.
</P>
<P>
   Albright met in Cairo Wednesday with Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk Al-Sharaa, but no concrete progress was made toward getting
the two sides back to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of slight progress the night before, U.S. officials in
Jerusalem said that Israeli and Palestinian negotiators would meet
next week in Washington. They are trying to reach an outline for a
permanent peace. American officials want to seal the deal in a
still-unscheduled summit meeting between Barak and Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   But officials from all sides say large gaps remain on most
issues. Especially contentious are the emotional issues of whether
Jerusalem, now controlled by Israel, can be shared, and whether
Palestinian refugees who lost homes in Israel can ever return.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's domestic troubles are largely not about these issues,
but rather grow out of the fractious nature of Israeli politics.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's parliamentary move was lead by the ultra-religious
Shas Party. The party is the second largest member of Barak's
government, but has been complaining that it does not receive
enough government money for its system of religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's minister of education, Yossi Sarid, is from the
stridently secular Meretz Party and has accused Shas's schools of
widespread mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Shas has threatened to bring the government down before, but has
been satisfied at the last minute by concessions from Barak. This
time, Barak has refused to deal. It prompted one Israeli columnist
to liken the former general to movie tough guy Chuck Norris.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has reportedly threatened to fire members of his cabinet,
mainly from Shas, who voted for the new elections bill. But his
allies said Wednesday that they expected no moves immediately.
</P>
<P>
   More deals could still bring Shas into the fold. Also, the prime
minister reportedly is considering rebuilding his ruling coalition
without Shas.
</P>
<P>
   One prevalent theory is that Barak could limp along until he
reaches a deal with the Palestinians, then, with the momentum of
that achievement, call for new elections himself.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Israeli politics: www3.haaretz.co.il/eng
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks: www.washingtoninstitute.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow can be contacted at LarryK(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
