<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE TICKET FOR ROCKER? NO, A PINK SLIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves made the right decision when they shipped
motormouth relief pitcher John Rocker to the minor leagues. But why
won't the team take credit for doing the right thing?
</P>
<P>
   Braves' management insisted that Rocker got the boot because he
wasn't pitching well _ not because he's an insufferable creep who
embarrasses the team, infuriates his teammates and insults the
paying customers. Team honchos said that Rocker's demotion was in
the works long before he berated and threatened a sportswriter
Sunday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The object of Rocker's latest outburst, by the way, was the very
same Sports Illustrated writer whose December story quoted
statements by Rocker that clearly branded the Atlanta pitcher as a
race-baiting, gay-hating, xenophobic nitwit. The fallout for Rocker
included a two-week suspension and a $500 fine, not to mention the
lingering resentment of teammates such as Brian Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted Jordan:
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got one guy being a cancer time and time again.
Eventually, it's going to have an effect on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves obviously decided that the cancer needed to be
excised _ or at least exiled. So they told Rocker to pack his bags
and report to their Triple-A farm club at Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Braves chose to blame Rocker's lousy pitching _ 25
walks in 18 innings _ rather than his lousy personality because
they were afraid of antagonizing Rocker partisans in Atlanta who
routinely jump to their feet and cheer when this moron enters a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they figured that demoting Rocker for failing to
control his fastball would hold up better against a challenge by
the players' union than demoting him for failure to control his
temper. Commissioner Bud Selig, don't forget, wanted to fine Rocker
$20,000 and suspend him for a month after the Sports Illustrated
article was published, but the punishment was reduced by an
arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. The game of baseball is so hopelessly dysfunctional
that even when it does the right thing, it does it for the wrong
reason.
</P>
<P>
   At least one baseball pundit speculated Tuesday that Rocker
would never return to the Braves, and he must know more about it
than those of us who only read about this stuff in the papers. But
as an on-again, off-again _ mostly on-again _ boycotter of
major-league baseball, I'll believe it when I see it.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that Rocker was merely banished in anticipation of a
Braves' trip to New York to play the Mets later this month? New
Yorkers, after all, were the primary targets of Rocker's insulting
comments last December.
</P>
<P>
   If Rocker starts looking like his old self on the pitcher's
mound, on the other hand, couldn't the Braves decide that his
potential ability to mow down Met batters outweighs the furor he
will cause in the Big Apple?
</P>
<P>
   We'll know soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, the Braves ought to give Rocker his walking papers
_ no matter what the cost, no matter what the reaction of some
misguided fans who seem to revere him as an icon of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about free speech, folks. Rocker is certainly
entitled to his opinions, however disgusting they may be, but he is
not entitled to embarrass his employer or malign its customers or
spit in the face of the public that pays his salary. He most
definitely is not entitled to threaten sportswriters simply because
they have the audacity to report his malignant rantings.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that if Rocker can get away with assaulting and/or
threatening reporters, it will be no time at all before he is
assaulting and/or threatening fans. And if one day he leaps into
the stands to beat up a patron who annoys him, what will Braves'
management do about it? Send him back to Richmond?
</P>
<P>
   If the onetime national pastime hopes to regain its
once-cherished place in the hearts of American sports fans, it must
purge the rampant perception that the game is populated by
arrogant, self-indulgent jerks. It could start by purging John
Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
