<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-TRADE-APPOINTMENT-HNS     06-07 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-APPOINTMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSINESSMAN TAPPED FOR U.S. PANEL FACED FEDERAL INQUIRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A San Francisco businessman and big donor to the
Democratic Party will be named by the White House to an important
trade post involving Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Although the nominee, George Chao-Chi Chu, was the focus of
federal investigations into business practices, he has never been
charged with any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced Tuesday that he intended to name
Chu, 43, to the government's Advisory Committee on Trade Policy
Negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Chu's Da Tung Trading Company does business in Europe, China,
Taiwan and Japan. Chu said the company buys expensive cognacs and
liqueurs in France and sells them in China, Taiwan and Japan;
invests in commercial real estate in China, Taiwan and Japan; and
exports American computer and solar equipment to Japan and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working in trade matters for a long time, and I'm
happy to provide my expertise and be able to help our president to
make policy,'' Chu said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he favors free trade with ``any country in the world,''
but thought he could be especially useful as the United States and
China move toward normalized trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-1997, at a time when the party and the Clinton-Gore
re-election campaign were under fire for their fund-raising
practices, Chu had contributed more than $500,000 to the Democrats
and to events specifically benefiting Clinton, according to federal
campaign contribution records.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the money was donated in 1996, the same
year the state of California hit Chu with a $15,700 lien for
personal income taxes dating from 1989. The matter was quickly
settled.
</P>
<P>
   White House and Democratic National Committee (DNC) records also
showed that Chu had donated up to $55,000 through John Huang, the
former Commerce Department official and onetime executive of
Indonesia's Lippo Group. Huang, vice chairman of the DNC's national
finance committee, later was accused of raising more than $1
million in illegal contributions. There was no evidence that Chu's
donations through Huang were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Federal records showed that Chu and five of his brothers and
sisters had been investigated repeatedly between 1985 and 1996 by
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   They were suspected of mislabeling imported alcoholic beverages,
failing to keep proper records and failing to pay back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Chu was never charged and the only member of his family who
faced enforcement action was his older brother, Michael, also a San
Francisco businessman and a Democratic Party donor.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chu was suspended from importing activities for a
minimum of 45 days and ordered to pay $80,000 in back taxes, court
records showed.
</P>
<P>
   George Chu said Tuesday that the problem with the federal
government ``was a kind of misunderstanding that has been
resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he no longer contributes so-called soft money to the
DNC. He said he has made no decision yet about supporting Vice
President Al Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Current campaign finance records show that, subsequent to
mid-1997, Chu made at least eight donations totaling more than
$30,000 to the California Democratic Party; to Sen. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y.; Sen. Tim Johnson, D-S.D.; and the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokeswoman said she could not comment immediately
on the Clinton administration's investigative and decision-making
procedures in selecting members of the advisory panel to which Chu
will be appointed.
</P>
<P>
   Media interest in the Chu family has sparked criticism by some
members of San Francisco's Asian-American community.
</P>
<P>
   Rodel Rodis, a lawyer and friend of Chu's, said Tuesday that he
believes Chu would not be getting ``the same scrutiny if he were
not Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the White House, the advisory committee's task is
to provide ``overall policy advice on matters concerning objectives
and bargaining positions before entering into a trade agreement.''
It works closely with the office of the U.S. Trade Representative.
</P>
<P>
   Chu and his brothers and sisters were the children of a former
Taiwanese government official who came to the United States in the
1970s and did business in California through 1982. George Chu took
over the family business after his father's death in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
