<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GATES SKIPS WASHINGTON SOFTWARE SUMMIT
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT.
 &HT;    Moving the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's top software moguls, including
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates, urged the presumptive Democratic and
Republican presidential candidates Wednesday to regulate the
booming high-tech economy with a light hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next president must commit to a minimalist regulatory
regime based on private sector leadership and responsibility,''
members of the Business Software Alliance said in identical letters
to Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, one of the 13 signers, canceled his scheduled appearance
at a news conference on Capitol Hill. He flew back to Redmond,
Wash., the corporate headquarters, late Tuesday ``in order to be
with his employees'' when the judicial ruling on the Microsoft
antitrust suit came down, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hours in advance of the court decision, other members of the
chief executives' panel were reluctant to comment on Microsoft's
fate. ``It's very early to speculate on what is going to be a long
and drawn-out process,'' said Eric Schmidt, chairman and chief
executive of Novell Inc. Microsoft competes with Novell in the
network server market.
</P>
<P>
   But with government antitrust policy on the front burner,
high-tech executives have become more aggressive in pursuing that
issue as well as other controversial matters of concern, such as
Internet privacy and the industry's strongly felt need to hire more
skilled workers from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened interest in Washington policy issues has come in
tandem with a sharp increase in campaign funds to incumbents of
both parties by top executives at Microsoft and in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter to the forthcoming presidential candidates, the
software chieftains said: ``It is essential that the government not
insert itself as a competitor in private markets providing
technology goods and services, nor seek to excessively regulate
such markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question on the government's proper role in
fostering Internet privacy, Schmidt said:: ``We're concerned that
very, very fast action can have unforeseen consequences. ... We
think now is not the time. Give us some more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, the Federal Trade Commission, by a slim
majority, contended that industry self-regulation of Internet
privacy had failed. They called on Congress to legislate firm
consumer safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Following that agency report, 10 Democratic members of Senate
Commerce Committee announced plans to introduce sweeping privacy
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.bsa.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
