<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INTERNET AUCTION HOUSE PLANS E-CHECK PAYMENT OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. and the leading on-line
auction site eBay Inc. are introducing an option to pay for
purchases over the Internet with an electronic check.
</P>
<P>
   The service could transform the traditional, if somewhat shaky,
honor system that dominates on-line buying and selling.
</P>
<P>
   The method mainly benefits small-time auction site sellers who
do not have merchant accounts to receive payment by credit card,
and who do not want to wait the days or weeks that it can take for
buyers to send checks or money orders by mail.
</P>
<P>
   It will also aid on-line buyers who do not use credit cards or
who are still reluctant to give out credit card numbers over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we've been able to research with eBay, sellers
have to wait for a buyer to write a check or obtain a money order,
and go to the post office,'' said Debra Rossi, Wells Fargo's vice
president of Business Internet Services. ``It could be weeks before
the seller gets their funds. What we're providing is faster receipt
of your funds, the payment is guaranteed, and it's
cost-effective.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, buyers promised to send payments by mail and
sellers promised to ship goods, and reputations of buyers and
sellers were made and lost on auction sites' feedback bulletin
boards. But more recently, entire industries have sprung up around
such transactions to ensure both parties are satisfied, including
escrow firms that act as clearinghouses to make sure customers are
satisfied with goods and sellers receive their funds.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kelley, president of i-Escrow Inc., a company that provides
such services for auctions on eBay, Yahoo and Amazon.com, said
features like electronic check payment may boost the completion
rate of auctions by alleviating wariness of on-line fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's significant because it's another arrow in eBay's
quiver of payment options,'' Kelley said. ``It'll be interesting to
see, with the trust consumers have in a large money center like
Wells, if they can get some traction to overcome this wariness
consumers have to disclose their account routing numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The system will require both buyer and seller to provide their
bank routing and account numbers so the cash transfer can take
place.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi said Wells' research showed that 80 percent of the
transactions from on-line auction sites were completed by mail.
Other industry experts say payment delays _ and, less frequently,
lack of any payment _ are of paramount concern to on-line
auctioneers.
</P>
<P>
   But more secure forms of payment have also sprung up, including
person-to-person on-line credit card transactions like the one
announced in April by Billpoint, a joint venture between eBay and
Wells Fargo. Banks usually take fees of 3 to 5 percent to perform
the credit card transactions, while the on-line check costs 35
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Users can be customers of any bank, not necessarily San
Francisco-based Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want to do is keep the transaction on line, keep the
people on line,'' Rossi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
