r f BC-WIRELESS-WEB-HNS &LR;      06-07 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-WEB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WIRELESS WEB SURFING ISN'T MAKING WAVES WITH CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROY BRAGG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The marshaled forces of high technology are touting wireless
Internet access as the next must-have, something indispensable and
vital to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But a skeptical America looks on indifferently. Wireless devices
are selling, but consumers aren't flocking to the service. Instead,
they are asking: Is this freedom, or is this nonsense?
</P>
<P>
   The corporate excitement over a wireless future is fueled by a
few reports, such as a recent one by wireless research group Ovum
that says 484 million people will make wireless connections by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   But another survey of 800 wireless phone users by The Strategis
Group think tank shows that 66 percent aren't interested in
wireless access to the Internet, and 63 percent don't pine for
wireless e-mail services.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Hswe, a Strategis Group senior analyst, blames that on
the perception that wireless Web service is expensive and phone
displays can't be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Expect that perception to change. Prices are dropping and phone
screens are getting bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely going to take a while to change minds,'' she
said. ``It's not going to happen in two months. These sort of
things take a while'' to gain popularity).
</P>
<P>
   A road test of the latest in Web-enabled phones shows that
they're all pretty much the same, although phone companies will
tell you differently.
</P>
<P>
   Each phone is text-based, requiring specific, specially designed
Web sites. Each operates between 14.4 and 19.2 kps. Each requires
extensive thumb typing to input specific data on the phone keypad,
though each has set-up procedures that will let a user input basic
personal information once.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel Online is one of the newest entries, offering Web access
starting at $14.95. Wireless minutes don't count against air time.
The three Web-enabled phones start at $99.
</P>
<P>
   The opening menu gives users options to shop Amazon.com and
entry to the MSN Mobile Portal, which includes truncated versions
of MSNBC.com news, weather, sports and financial information.
There's Hotmail.com, a free Web-based e-mail service, and
Expedia.com, which lets travelers check itineraries booked on line.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, meanwhile, has been advertising the dickens out of its
PCS Wireless Web phones. The company is offering Wireless Web (or
another option) for free with all of its Free and Clear phone
plans. Seventeen models of phone are Web-enabled, Sprint says,
ranging in price from $30 refurbished models to top-of-the-line
versions at 10 times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the bunch might be the NP 1000 ($300) because of its
huge display window, which shows 11 lines, bigger than most other
phones.
</P>
<P>
   The company also offers other Web-enabled models with smaller
screens and other features.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint also has been at this longer, so there are a lot of
offerings on the phone, such as Yahoo.com, CNN.com, Fidelity.com,
Bloomberg.com, FOX Sports.com, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint phone also comes with software that loads onto your
personal computer, allowing you to synchronize dates, addresses and
memos between the two devices. And with a $100 connection kit, the
phone functions as a modem, providing a 14.4 kps connection. That's
not greased lightning, but it beats tapping out e-mail messages
with your well-worn thumbs on the phone's keypad.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T Digital PocketNet service is the latest incarnation of
a product that's been around for years. Using the faster CDPD
system, it offers three tiers of service _ free, $7 and $15 _ with
different levels of unlimited Web access for each.
</P>
<P>
   PocketNet comes on two phones _ a slim $100 Ericsson, and a $200
Mitsubishi, which has a bigger screen.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is the 500-pound gorilla of telecommunications and the
Digital PocketNet service is yet another example of why.
</P>
<P>
   It offers more choices in terms of news, shopping and other
information.
</P>
<P>
   As for specific products, each has pros and cons.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless phones do provide basic Internet information, but at
the expense of your thumbs and your time.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of years, wireless service will stream at broadband
speed, meaning there will be more stuff available, such as video,
music and serious file-downloading. By then, voice-activated
technology will give your thumbs a break.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, frequent travelers will get the most benefit.
They can confirm reservations, get directions, and check e-mail
while out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders will like these things, since they can get alerts
and consummate stock transactions instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,''' said Strategis' Hwse. ``You go to
Starbucks, order a caffe latte and you're sitting down. Now what do
you do? You read a book. You read the paper. Well, when wireless
Internet becomes more available, it'll replace certain activities
we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of us, a wireless phone's usefulness might be
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Using a wireless phone to speak while driving is dangerous
enough. Imagine trying to tap out the name of the restaurant ``The
Magic Time Machine'' on the ``Find A'' site while driving 70 mph.
To use it safely, a driver would have to pull over.
</P>
<P>
   If you're pulling over, why not just stop at a gas station and
ask for directions? Or dial 411, call the restaurant, and get
directions the old-fashioned way?
</P>
<P>
   Why spend time squinting at news stories on a phone? Turn on the
car radio. Buy a paper.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe wait a few years until the promise of the wireless Web
is realized.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Roy Bragg by e-mail at rbragg(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
