<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S A MAD, MAD, MAD, MAD WORLD: DON'T RUSH INTO MISSILE
DEFENSES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABM-MISSILE-RETHINK-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ When U.S. President Bill Clinton meets with Russian
President Vladimir Putin beginning June 4, he will propose to amend
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty to allow limited
land-based defenses against a limited missile attack, not from
unthreatening Russia, but from hostile regimes, such as North
Korea's. Clinton and Putin should look to their defenses in a
spirit of cooperation, rather than confrontation. It is too big a
decision to be rushed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for June 4 Putin-Clinton summit)
</P>
<P>
   (1,250 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO STOP DIAMONDS FROM FINANCING NASTY AFRICAN WARS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIAMOND-WARMONGERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ De Beer's nightmare has shifted from a flood of
diamonds to blood on diamonds. At least three wars in Africa are
``fuelled'' by diamonds. In two of them, rebel movements control
mines and sell diamonds to buy weapons. The United Nations wants to
cut off their source of cash: so-called `conflict diamonds.' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIJI: STOP MAKING CONCESSIONS TO GEORGE SPEIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIJI-TERRORISM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ George Speight is known as a ``failed businessman.''
But since May 19, when Speight and other rebels took the Fijian
government hostage, he has been proving to be a successful
terrorist. Enough is enough, however; a line must be drawn, and
Speight expelled from Fiji. In the longer term, a solution is
needed for the underlying dispute between Fijians and Indians,
which is over land. Whatever happens, Speight must not be
rewarded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AVENGING DUKAKIS: WHY GORE MIGHT YET TRIUMPH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GORE-DUKAKIS-REVENGE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What can Al Gore do to lift himself out of his
current doldrums? Change from earth tones to black leather, to up
the ante on last October's Alpha-male makeover? Replace Naomi Wolf
with Tina Brown? Appear on Oprah Winfrey? A more modest strategy
would be to sit back and reflect on the campaign of the last
Democrat to lose. Michael Dukakis's 1988 defeat at the hands of
George Bush senior provides a perfect playbook of how to destroy
George junior. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE REMAKING OF A PRESIDENT: GEORGE W. GETS A MAKEOVER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSH-REINVENTED-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The only way that George W. Bush's presidential
campaign could go any better these days would be for Al Gore to
announce that, as well as smoking a little dope as a student, he
also joined the Communist Party. Whatever the outcome of the race,
one of the lasting ironies of the 2000 campaign may prove to be
that the ``lightweight'' Bush grabbed the intellectual edge from
the ``heavyweight'' Gore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 525; 1,600 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREEN PARTY'S RALPH NADER: `WE OWE GORE NOTHING' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RALPHNADER-ROLLS-ON-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A few years ago, Ralph Nader, the Green Party's
probable presidential candidate, seemed something of a relic _ the
man who made cars safer and then seemed to go slightly bonkers
about trade. Now he seems ahead of the curve _ one of the first
people, for instance, to argue that Microsoft was a monopoly and
needed to be broken up; one of the strongest supporters of
wide-scale campaign-finance reform; and from some perspectives, the
godfather of all the nongovernmental organizations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,075 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (375 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALL'S QUIET ON THE LEBANESE FRONT _ FOR NOW, AT LEAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEBANON-LIMBO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KFAR KILA, LEBANON _ As a procession of helicopters swept in to
land, loudspeakers blasted Wagner's ``Ride of the Valkyries'' over
the hillsides southern Lebanon. The U.N. peacekeepers' noisy
display was a deliberate reference to the Vietnam War, as depicted
in the film ``Apocalypse Now.'' Pundits had predicted an apocalypse
in Lebanon if Israel made good its promise to withdraw from the
country's southern fringes even without a peace deal with Syria.
But the Israeli-Lebanese border has remained remarkably quiet since
Israel's army retreated to its side on May 24, ending a 22-year
occupation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA: WHERE ECOLOGIST IS A DIRTY WORD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA-BLUE-`GREENS'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Even in the democratic heyday of post-communism, Russia
was a tough place for greens. Where the right laws existed, they
were hard to enforce. A combination of abundant natural wealth,
plenty of space and careless habits meant that few Russians took
environmental housekeeping seriously. Now, a mix of business
interests, criminal activity and government paranoia threatens to
make matters far worse. On top of all this, the new government of
Vladimir Putin announced ambitious plans on May 25 to build 40 new
fast-breeder nuclear-power station in Russia over the next 30
years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT'S TO BE DONE ABOUT PERU'S SHAM ELECTION? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STINKER-FUJIMORI-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIMA _ ``Democracy is dead,'' declared President Alberto
Fujimori's defeated challenger, Alejandro Toledo, to 50,000
supporters in Lima after the polls had closed in Peru's May 28
presidential run-off. ``Fujimori, murderer,'' chanted the crowd.
Much of Latin America tacitly agreed, So too, loudly, did the
United States. But what were they all to do about the result? And
more importantly, perhaps, how will Fujimori reckon with the new
political activism that his electoral shenanigans have unleashed? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-COMMERCE RESTORES TRUCKING'S GLORY DAYS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CYBER-TRUCKERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RICHMOND, VA. _ Once, America's trucking industry was a cozy,
regulated semi-cartel, with a few big companies dominating most
regions. CB radio and the call of the open road made every boy
dream of one day driving his own 18-wheel rig. But when
deregulation hit in the 1980s, the business quickly lost its charm.
Yet a radical transformation of the trucking industry is now under
way, thanks to e-business. CB radio has given way to e-mail, GPS
tracking and wired hubs. Who knows? As e-commerce restores
trucking's glory days, a new generation of kids might even dream of
being truckers again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Virginia) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,100 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS SOCCER OUT OF SYNC WITH THE AMERICAN SPIRIT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOCCER-STARS'N'STRIPES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ As the Euro 2000 championship looms and the
continent again becomes football-crazy, an old question is being
asked once more: will Americans ever learn to love ``the other''
football _ European football, that is _ or are the rhythms of the
world's most popular game somehow out of sync with the American
spirit? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW SOFTWARE GOT ITS NAME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VICTORIAN-`SOFTWARE'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ An etymology researcher has discovered that the
ubiquitous computer term ``software'' was coined way ahead of its
time _ though in a quite different context. Back in 1850,
``soft-ware'' and ``hard-ware'' were terms used by trash-can
scavengers to distinguish compost from non-biodegradable matter. So
a Victorian would have been baffled by the modern use of the
term.... Garbage in, garbage out, as computer programmers like to
say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
