<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6998 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-ROYALS-BOS &LR;      06-07 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ROYALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES AND CAMILLA REWRITE THE FAIRY TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The tabloids used to call her The Other Woman. Now
they're calling her The Next Queen.
</P>
<P>
   Never has a mistress of an heir to the throne undergone a more
swift and thorough rehabilitation than has Camilla Parker Bowles,
Prince Charles' longtime consort.
</P>
<P>
   When the prince's mother, Queen Elizabeth II, ended her
prolonged snub of Parker Bowles and exchanged pleasantries with her
during a barbecue at the prince's Highgrove estate last Saturday,
the tabloids breathlessly suggested a royal wedding was in the air.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, when it emerged that Parker Bowles has been holding
secret talks with the Archbishop of Canterbury, even the staid BBC
reported that speculation was rife that the Prince of Wales and his
mistress planned to eventually marry. Because the prince is a
divorcee, the Church of England, of which he is titular governor,
would have to approve of his remarrying.
</P>
<P>
   But while the British people seem to have forgiven Parker Bowles
for being the other woman in a love triangle that doomed the
fairytale marriage of Charles and Diana, Princess of Wales, there
are no signs they want her as their queen.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been no reliable polling done, telephone polls
by the tabloids suggest the prince should proceed with caution.
While 68 percent of readers polled by the Mirror said they wanted
the couple to marry, 83 percent said Parker Bowles should never be
queen.
</P>
<P>
   But if Charles decides to marry her, the public won't have a
say. According to David Starkey, the constitutional historian whose
television show on the life of Elizabeth I was a surprise ratings
success in Britain last week, the law is quite clear that whoever
is married to Charles if or when he becomes king will be queen.
Starkey says that if Buckingham Palace doesn't want Camilla to
become queen, the palace will have to petition the government to
change the law.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles and Parker Bowles, who is also divorced, have
insisted all along that they have no intentions of marrying. But
there is a growing belief here that the carefully choreographed
rehabilitation of both their images is aimed at making their
relationship more acceptable to his potential subjects. Bookmakers
here, generally accurate barometers of public opinion, this week
lowered the odds of their marriage from 3-1 to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The prince's aides at St. James's Palace were stunned and elated
16 months ago when the couple's first public appearance together at
the Ritz Hotel was greeted with widespread approval or, at worst,
indifference by most Britons.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, there has been a seemingly calibrated increase in
the couple's public appearances, while the Queen's decision on
Saturday to grant Parker Bowles not only an audience but cordial
conversation was seen as the boldest step to rehabilitate a couple
who only a few years ago were seen by many as cruel adulterers who
drove Diana to a lonely pursuit of affection and, eventually, her
death with a reckless playboy in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   While the tabloids crank out the violin music, not everyone is
cheering for love to prevail. Ros Coward, a writer, is less than
impressed by what she sees as a mundane relationship that is being
milked cynically by both the royal family and the tabloids they
profess to hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This blanket coverage is not just tedious. It's maddening,''
Coward complained in The Guardian. ``Since Princess Diana's death,
royal coverage has been relatively muted. Uncertainty about just
how far public distate distaste for the whole royal family had gone
has kept this stuff off the front page. Now the signs are the press
is heading back _ no holds barred _ to royal fantasyland.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the more serious papers that support the monarchy seem as
accepting of the increasingly public relationship as the tabloids,
which cynically milk the royals for circulation. But while The
Times predicted a marriage within five years, the biggest-selling
conservative papers, The Mail and The Daily Telegraph, urged
caution. The Telegraph urged the prince to consider the
relationship ``not so much a moral matter as one of taste and
tact.''
</P>
<P>
   Coward, ever the cynic, thinks the British people will soon tire
of the hysteria, and a couple she sees as horsey, tweedy, and
boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to imagine Camilla's life ever resonating with
anyone outside the hunting set,'' Coward said. ``Editors might be
rubbing their hands with glee at the prospect of the next episodes
in the royal soap _ family reconciliation, engagement, marriage _
but the tedious saga of this odd couple is more likely to be a
total ratings disaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
