<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS SHOULD DOMINATE AT THE GAMES DOWN UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cargo ships, loaded with tables, chairs, computers, judo
mats, and a volleyball floor, already are headed across the
Pacific. The horses, sailboats, kayaks, and racing shells will
follow later. By mid-August, the 600 athletes will be outfitted and
given physicals at a San Diego naval facility before flying across
the international date line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like going to war,'' said Greg Harney, the US
Olympic Committee's director of international games preparation.
</P>
<P>
   The Games of the XXVIIth Olympiad are still 100 days off, but
the American expeditionary force already is gearing up for its
longest trip since the 1988 Games in Seoul. And though Uncle Sam's
athletes never have performed as well on the road as they have at
home (they haven't topped the medal table at a foreign Olympics
since 1968 in Mexico City), that will change this time.
</P>
<P>
   While the Americans probably will win fewer than 90 medals,
their lightest haul since 1960, they'll still be well ahead of the
rest of the world. The breakup of the Soviet Union into 15 pieces
and the disappearance of East Germany has everything to do with
that.
</P>
<P>
   Had the former USSR competed as one nation in Atlanta, as it did
(as the Unified Team) in Barcelona in 1992, it would have grabbed
123 medals to the Americans' 101. Alone, the Russians won but 63 in
1996. And the combined Germany won barely half as many medals (65)
as the drug-fueled DDR did by itself in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the benefit of home cooking, the Yanks still should
get fat Down Under. The track and field team is still No. 1. The
swimmers should match the Aussies medal for medal in their home
pool. And the basketball squads should sweep again. Some things
about the Games don't change, whatever the latitude.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 15-hour flight from California will be daunting (``I
tell them it's nine hours, 360 minutes _ it sounds better,'' said
Harney), it means that the Americans also will be 15 hours away
from the U-S-A! U-S-A! pressure-cooker they labored in last time.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bela Karolyi, the women's gymnastics team coordinator,
``All the media reminders about medals, the promises of this and
that, the we're-going-to-beat-the world . . . It might be more
favorable for us in Sydney than if the Games were at home.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at the US medal prospects:
</P>
<P>
   ARCHERY: Even with Justin Huish (drug charges) and Shane Parker
(cheating at trials) off the roster, the men still have a shot at a
team medal. But there will be no double gold this time, and the
women are still off-target.
</P>
<P>
   BADMINTON: The Americans are literally a one-man team (Kevin
Han), and he'll be happy to survive the first round.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL: Boggsie wearing the stars and stripes? If a few Hall
of Famers can be coaxed out of recent retirement to play alongside
top minor leaguers, the US could upgrade from bronze to gold. But
the Japanese and Koreans will be using their pros, too.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL: Since the Dream Team showed up at Barcelona, the US
males haven't come close to losing a game. The women have won three
of the last four titles. Double gold _ again.
</P>
<P>
   BOXING: Best team since 1976? Possibly. The US won four world
titles in their home ring last year and three of the victors (light
flyweight Brian Viloria, featherweight Ricardo Juarez, heavyweight
Michael Bennett) made the Olympic team. But matching the five golds
by Sugar Ray &AMP; Co. at Montreal is a pipedream.
</P>
<P>
   CANOE/KAYAK: Where have you gone, Greg Barton? Gold medals are
fantasies for the paddlers these days. But a silver from Scott
Shipley in the kayak slalom is within reach.
</P>
<P>
   CYCLING: Better hope Lance Armstrong stays in the saddle. If he
does, there could be a medal of each color, with Marty Nothstein in
the match sprint and Alison Dunlap in mountain biking.
</P>
<P>
   DIVING: Last time, the Americans were off the gold standard for
the first time since 1912. This time, they could be off the podium
entirely. Somebody had better make sure Mark Ruiz gets his wakeup
calls.
</P>
<P>
   EQUESTRIAN: The US was the only country to make the medal stand
in all three team events in Atlanta. A repeat is possible _ but so
is a handful of fourths.
</P>
<P>
   FENCING: No American has won a medal against a full Olympic
field since Albert Axelrod in 1960, but Iris Zimmermann could do it
in women's foil. A bronze would seem like gold.
</P>
<P>
   FIELD HOCKEY: Neither team qualified.
</P>
<P>
   GYMNASTICS: How can they top Atlanta? The Magnificent Seven
capped the best showing ever (five medals) at a non-boycotted
Games, but the entire program took a tumble at the next world meet.
A gold medal is unlikely _ the US has won only one (Trent Dimas in
1992) at an overseas Games in 76 years. But bronzes from the
women's team and Blaine Wilson in the men's all-around are worth
betting on.
</P>
<P>
   HANDBALL: Neither team qualified.
</P>
<P>
   JUDO: No Yank ever has won Olympic gold in Japan's national
pastime, but Lawrence's Jim Pedro is lightweight world champ. On
his best day, he's the man.
</P>
<P>
   MODERN PENTATHLON: The medals have dried up (none since 1984) as
George Patton's old sport has dropped off the radar screen. But new
face Chad Senior could slip in for a bronze if the planets align
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ROWING: The star-spangled flotilla hasn't won gold against a
full Olympic field since 1964 but the men's eight, three-time world
champs, has the goods. If the women can outpull nemesis Romania,
the daily double is there. Pencil in the lightweight women's double
of Sarah Garner and Worcester's Christine Collins for a silver.
</P>
<P>
   SAILING: After the worst showing in 60 years (two bronzes),
anything has to be an improvement over Atlanta. But the US sailors
won't come anywhere near the nine medals they won eight years ago.
Three _ in Star, Europe, and men's 470 _ is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING: The trapshooters bagged one of each last time behind
deadeye Kim Rhode. Now, things are looking up on the rifle range,
too, with world champ Thomas Tamas. If they keep their powder dry,
the Yanks could fire off half a dozen medals.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER: Last hurrah for the women, who'll need their A game and
then some to hold off the Chinese. The men, loaded with MLS pros,
should make the quarters, but a medal is still a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTBALL: The US women still rule the world but the days of
knockouts and no-hitters are over. The Australians and Chinese can
match them inning for inning now. The price of gold is sharply
higher overseas.
</P>
<P>
   SWIMMING: The wet set hit a gold rush with a stunning 13 in
Atlanta. Matching that against the cranked-up Aussies in their own
chlorine is a tall order, but the Americans could do it. The Jenny
(Thompson) and Lenny (Krayzelburg) Show might be good for four
between them, the relays are worth at least three, and there are
enough soloists like vets Amy Van Dyken and Tom Dolan to pick up
another half-dozen.
</P>
<P>
   SYNCHRONIZED SWIMMING: The days of slam-dunk gold are over. The
Americans now rank behind the Russians and Japanese in the team
event and their best man in the duet (Bill May) is staying home
because he's a man.
</P>
<P>
   TABLE TENNIS: Ping-Pong diplomacy has its limits. The Chinese
yield nothing at this table. The US won't survive the prelims.
</P>
<P>
   TAEKWONDO: It may be a Korean thing, but the Americans may be
able to kick their way to a medal or two. Juan Moreno has the best
shot.
</P>
<P>
   TENNIS: The Americans parlayed the home-court advantage into
three gold medals under Georgia's sizzling sun. Olympus isn't the
Australian Open, but Andre Agassi and Lindsay Davenport could
repeat.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK AND FIELD: Last time, the Yanks won more medals (23) than
the next three countries combined. Even with half a dozen fewer,
they'll still top the table. Maurice Greene, Michael Johnson,
Marion Jones, and Inger Miller are good for five golds in the
sprints, the relays should produce three and there should be four
more in the men's shot (C.J. Hunter) and discus (Anthony
Washington) and the women's hurdles (Gail Devers) and pole vault
(Stacy Dragila).
</P>
<P>
   TRIATHLON: America may have invented the Ironman but the Aussies
are the iron, especially in their shark-flavored waters. A bronze
from Barb Lindquist, though, is reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   VOLLEYBALL: The indoor teams, who crashed in Atlanta, are still
under construction. The medals, again, are on the beach, but there
may only be one this time _ a bronze from the women.
</P>
<P>
   WATER POLO: The men washed out in Atlanta and the women are
making their debut. Both should be respectable, but medals appear
out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHTLIFTING: Cheryl Haworth, the 16-year-old Samsonette,
figures to hoist the first US medal against a full field since
1976. No chance for the men _ unless they pump up on funny
vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING: After grabbing eight medals at each of the last two
Games, the Americans may have to settle for half as many this time.
But three of them (with freestylers Steve Neal, Lincoln McIlravy
and Les Gutches) could be gold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
