<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-RELIGION-YORUBA-BOS &LR;      06-07 1725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-YORUBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS IN US TURN TO ANCIENT AFRICAN RELIGION YORUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some people start their day with a prayer or
meditation. Tony Van Der Meer brings positive spiritual vibes into
his life with the help of a little water. Every morning, he goes to
a religious shrine erected in his home and sprinkles the fluid on
an icon representing esu, a trickster divinity in the Ifa
divination system practiced by the Yoruba people.
</P>
<P>
   Giving esu (EH-shoe) this simple sacrifice, says Van Der Meer,
is how he ``asks for blessings, asks for safety, asks for a good
day, asks to be the best person I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Der Meer is finding spiritual solace in a 5,000-year-old
Nigerian religion, called either Ifa (ee-FAH) or Yoruba, that
wended its way into the culture of the Americas via the slave
trade. Although white masters forced the African newcomers to
abandon their traditional beliefs, aspects of the old ways
survived, melding with Christianity to become the syncretic
religions Candomble, Macumba, Lucumi, and Voodoo.
</P>
<P>
   Now Van Der Meer, 46, is part of a growing number of
African-Americans divesting Yoruba of its Christian trappings. They
are setting up shrines, communing with their ancestors, and
chanting in foreign languages in order to discover the religion of
their African forefathers. The reason they give for this return to
their roots is both spiritual and cultural.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of the religion ``shows that black people in this
country didn't just come out of slavery,'' says Van Der Meer, an
Africana studies professor at the University of Massachusetts at
Boston. ``Our legacy goes deeper than that. We have a way of
thinking, a way of life that has a high cultural aspect to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 100,000 people nationwide practice some form of
Yoruba-based religion, according to Wande Abimbola, a Yoruba
scholar who teaches religion at Boston University. They are a
melting pot of African-Americans, whites, Latinos, and Asians who
are responding to a belief system that counsels respect for the
environment and stresses spiritual self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are disenchanted with the Western way of conquesting
nature,'' says Abimbola. ``They are looking for a more humane and
natural way of life. It leads them to Yoruba.''
</P>
<P>
   While a renaissance of spirituality in the 1990s has popularized
everything from Buddhism to cabala, the practice of Yoruba is still
looked upon skeptically by the general public, say its followers.
Onlookers stereotype them as chicken killers who practice some
strange form of mysticism, they complain.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the religion is slowly becoming demystified as people begin
to publicly practice an ideology that has been kept secretive for
centuries. Consumers now snatch up the best-selling self-help books
of Iyanla Vanzant, a Yoruba priestess. You can step into the
spiritual house Ile Ase Sango Ewelere (ee-LAY ah-SHAY shang-GO
EH-WAY-lay-ray) in Roxbury and take Yoruba 101-style classes (some
taught by Abimbola) that explain Yoruba thought, divination, music,
and chanting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're involved in this process of orisa (divinity) worship
and you feel ashamed of it, how are you going to move forward?''
reasons Elizabeth Coleman, who with Barbara Eaton leads the Ile,
which started in the early 1990s. ``It should be out there, it
should be very much a part of your life and identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a sparsely decorated Boston University office,
Abimbola explains the tenets of the Yoruba religion with quiet
intensity. It's part of his job as awise agbaye (ah-wee-shay
ah-bay-YAY), a religious title that means spokesperson of Yoruba in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The scholar, whom local adherents respectfully call baba (Yoruba
for father), comes from a family that has clung to Ifa even as
other Africans turned to the Christian and Muslim faiths. In
addition to acting as a bridge between Yoruba followers in West
Africa and the Americas, he gives individual consultations and
recently delivered an invocation during the April opening of a
Metropolitan Museum of Art exhibition of objects used in
divinations.
</P>
<P>
   Yoruba devotees believe in one high god, Olodumare
(oh-LOH-dumare), explains Abimbola, but the cosmos is filled with
other entities as well. The good divinities, or orisas, come in the
form of trees, forests, mountains, or metal. The ajogun
(a-joe-gun), or bad spirits, represent death, deceit, imprisonment,
or disease.
</P>
<P>
   The orisa and ajogun ``are eternally set against each other,''
says Abimbola, dressed in a traditional outfit of long embroidered
tunic and pants. ``It's sacrifice that brings balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many who worship Western gods, Yoruba followers don't
attend services once a week. When a practitioner has a problem, he
or she confers with a babalawo (BAH-BAH-LAH-woah), or priest, who
provides counsel, makes sacrifices, creates herbal remedies, or
performs divinations that analyze individual problems.
</P>
<P>
   How does the religion work in daily life? Walter Clark, 45, a
Yoruba devotee, gives an example as he sits in the Ile, located in
a house painted blood red to represent the divinity of thunder,
Shango. About a year ago, Clark started a job working as a welder.
On his second day of work, he got hit by a car and fractured a leg.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's problems _ the car accident, the cracked bone _ were
traced to Ogun, a divinity of iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had to remind me, `Look, you're doing your god's work
and you haven't acknowledged it,' '' says Clark, who then gave an
offering of a yam to Ogun (oh-GOON). ``I went back to work and had
two pay raises.''
</P>
<P>
   That yam offering brings us to Yoruba's bete noire: sacrifice.
In Yoruba, explains Abimbola, ``sacrifice is a code of
communication. We don't think that verbalization is enough. It's
our own myopia and arrogance that makes us think that every
divinity will hear us.''
</P>
<P>
   The perception of followers killing goats and chickens has made
the religion controversial among organizations concerned with
animal protection. What people don't understand, says Abimbola, is
that a sacrifice can consist of liquid, clothes, food (like Clark's
yam), or animals. Of the latter form of sacrifice, Abimbola notes,
``there is not a preponderance of it. And 99.9 percent of the
animals that are sacrificed are eaten by us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   African-American interest in Yoruba can be traced back to at
least 1959, when a man named Walter King traveled to Cuba to be
initiated in a syncretic religion. By 1971, King had changed his
name to Oba Oseijeman Adefumni, had been crowned the Yoruba King of
the Americas in Nigeria, and was reigning over a traditional Yoruba
village in Sheldon, N.C., that has become a popular tourist spot.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, blacks were introduced to Yoruba as an
influx of immigrants arrived from the African diaspora and as
African-Americans traveled to Africa to unearth the roots Alex
Haley wrote about. They were enticed by an ideology that gives them
a stronger spiritual connection than Christianity ever did, say
Yoruba converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came up, I was just empty,'' says Heywood Fennell Sr.,
52, who was a Baptist and Episcopalian before discovering the
Yoruba faith. ``I had tried the churches but I just knew there had
to be something better.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark had that nagging feeling as well. ``I knew,'' he says,
``there was something deeper than Christianity because we didn't
practice Christianity in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Their disaffection with Western religion, says Abimbola, may be
related to the way it's practiced. ``Christianity seems not to be
able to help its devotees beyond prayer,'' Abimbola notes, ``hoping
that when you die, you'll go to heaven and, perhaps, if you pray,
your condition here on earth will be better.'' Yoruba, however,
``is based on the fact that you can help yourself,'' says Abimbola.
</P>
<P>
   As Fennell, a Yoruba priest who was introduced to the religion
in the late 1970s, points out, ``This is living. You don't wait
until you die to get your blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Van Der Meer, ``It teaches you that you can redeem
yourself. That something can happen to you and you don't have to be
completely devastated. You're able to recover from that and move
ahead, but you have learned the lesson that's invovled in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Those teachings weren't always apparent to Van Der Meer when he
began practicing Lucumi in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucumi was very difficult,'' says Van Der Meer, who found that
questions he had about the theory behind the religion were left
unanswered. ``They began to kind of create this type of mystery
about the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yoruba Van Der Meer studies under Abimbola is different, he
says, because it's based on an ancient Yoruba text similar to the
Bible, Koran, and Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something that's secret, you know,'' says Van Der
Meer. ``It's something we should know, should study, and should
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet information about Yoruba remains vague, with various books
and Web pages disseminating conflicting facts. With so much
inaccurate information circulating, the religion continues to be a
target of derision.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a sculptor who incorporates African divinities into his
art, discovered this firsthand while exhibiting his work at a local
library. As Clark explained the African divinities to a curious
onlooker, the man became increasingly agitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like, `No. Uh-uh. Not me. I'll never fall down before
this,' '' recalls Clark. ``It hit me kind of heavy that he would go
off like that. But that is the general feel that I get from a lot
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Those perceptions seem to be slowly changing as experts like
Abimbola explain how the religion is practiced in Africa and Yoruba
devotees gently introduce the religion to family and friends. Take
the example of Van Der Meer, who recently went home to Harlem to
celebrate the 50th birthday of his twin siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Before the festivities started, Van Der Meer convinced his
family to connect with their ancestors by participating in a
Yoruba-style chant. In this instance, there was no drama, just a
spirit of well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt very good about it,'' says Van Der Meer, ``to the
point where they said, `You know, we need to do this more.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
