<HEADLINE>
A STRATEGY FOR THE HEARTS, MINDS AND BEARDS OF THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was all ribbon-cuttings and speeches Monday when
Gillette Co. chairman and chief executive Michael C. Hawley
dedicated a new $40 million razor-blade factory in St. Petersburg,
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   When it was his turn to speak, Hawley noted that during the
early part of the year, ``Russia was our fastest-growing major
market worldwide'' during the first three months of this year, up
40 percent from the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's sales growth in Russia is impressive. A decade ago,
sales were insignificant in a country where
turn-of-the-18th-century czar Peter the Great once deemed the 5
o'clock shadow an uncivilizing influence and levied a tax on
beards. Now Gillette's Russian sales could soon exceed $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing facility in St. Petersburg is more than just a
razor-blade factory; it's also a beachhead, the latest installment
in an ongoing ``foot-on-the-ground'' strategy that aims to secure
Gillette's global razor domination. It's a strategy that Gillette
has used for more than 40 years as it seeks to win over consumers
the world over.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the strategy that can be described as: Infiltrate a
developing country, buy a local razor brand, familiarize the locals
with Gillette products, gain marketing intelligence, then build a
modern factory.
</P>
<P>
   While these are the core principles, the strategy is flexible
enough to be adapted to a wide variety of countries, said Jorgen
Wedel, Gillette's executive vice president of commercial operations
for the Eastern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tailor-make the approach to the individual country and type
of market,'' Wedel said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, most consumers are familiar with
Gillette's product lines. They shave with SensorExcel razors. They
brush their teeth with Oral-B toothbrushes. They percolate their
morning joe with a Braun coffee maker and power their boomboxes and
flashlights with Duracell batteries.
</P>
<P>
   But only about 40 percent of Gillette's $9.9 billion in 1999
sales came from purchases made by US consumers. The rest of
Gillette's revenue comes from overseas sales.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Gillette's exposure to overseas markets has been both
a liability and an asset. After years of strong profit increases,
fluctuations in foreign currency rates have helped to slow
Gillette's momentum and batter its stock price. Gillette stock
closed Tuesday at $34.75 on the New York Stock Exchange, up 12.5
cents for the day but far below its 52-week high of $52.375. On the
upside, foreign markets mean big growth opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   That aside, what many foreign consumers are buying from Gillette
today are not the Mach3, Gillette's latest razor, or the Duracell
Ultra, but the double-edged blades and earlier generation of zinc
batteries that were popular with the grandfathers of today's
American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a simple explanation for this. Many foreign consumers
have less disposable income than their US counterparts. What they
can afford are the product lines that Gillette originally developed
for the US market 20 or 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of shaving, many Russians are at the sixth-grade
level, while Americans are in graduate school,'' said Fredric E.
Russell of Fredric E. Russell Investment Management Co., an
Oklahoma firm that owns a large number of Gillette shares.
</P>
<P>
   It's these older product lines that are often being made in St.
Petersburg and many of the other sites that Gillette operates
manufacturing plants in developing countries. All told, Gillette
has 54 manufacturing facilities in 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette made its move into Russia about the time the Soviet
Union was dissolving and Russian president Vladimir V. Putin, then
a local official, was helping to establish a special economic zone
for multinational companies in the city now known as St.
Petersburg. In 1993, Gillette entered a joint venture with the
Leninets Concern, a local company that made a razor blade known as
the Sputnik.
</P>
<P>
   The mid-1990s might be described as a sort of Russian
reconnaissance mission for Gillette. As it helped Leninets to
continue to make Sputnik razors, Gillette studied Russian consumer
habits and tested marketing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gillette began to import some of its brands into
Russia. As these brands became more popular, the decision was made
to build a state-of-the-art facility in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   This foot-on-the-ground approach offers several advantages. For
openers, it allows Gillette to avoid some of the high tariffs that
many countries slap on imports.
</P>
<P>
   There's a second benefit. Many countries throw all sorts of
bureaucratic hurdles into the path of a multinational company that
wants to build a local factory.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its joint ventures, Gillette can enlist the aid of
its local partner to cut through some of the red tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``They help us with political maneuvering, which is very
important,'' Wedel said of Gillette's local partners.
</P>
<P>
   A variation of this foot-on-the-ground strategy has been used
several times before. In China, Gillette bought a stake in local
razor brand called the Flying Eagle more than 20 years ago. In
India, which Gillette entered in the early 1980s, one of the razor
brands that Gillette markets is called the 7 O'Clock.
</P>
<P>
   Many US consumers are familiar with Gillette's ``trade-up''
philosophy for making money. Every seven years or so, Gillette
introduces a new generation of razor, one it claims represents a
major advance in shaving technology.
</P>
<P>
   The new razor costs more than its predecessor. But if Gillette
can persuade many consumers in developed countries to put down
their SensorExcel razors and ``trade up'' to the more expensive,
next-generation Mach3, it can add millions of dollars to its bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure consumers hear the argument that they should trade
up, Gillette saturates the airwaves with big ad campaigns, spending
$606 million on global advertising last year.
</P>
<P>
   Similar tactics are used in developing countries, though often
with older-generation products. In Russia, for example, one goal is
to get consumers to swap their Sputniks for an Atra razor and maybe
some day a Sensor or a Mach3.
</P>
<P>
   This approach isn't just used for blades and razors. In general,
Gillette has also had success with applying this same formula to
its battery and oral-care product lines.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has worked less well for its stationery products
and household appliances. That may be one reason why Gillette
recently announced that it is negotiating to sell its Parker, Paper
Mate cq, and Waterman pen lines to Newell Rubbermaid Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For much the same reason, Gillette has hinted that it may sell
the household appliance business that it markets under the Braun
brand name.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the product is a razor blade or a toothbrush, and
regardless of whether the consumer lives in Boston, Beijing, or St.
Petersburg, Gillette is always looking to persuade that consumer to
trade up.
</P>
<P>
   The extra cost to a Russian or Chinese consumer who trades up
from a Sputnik or Flying Eagle razor to one of Gillette's snazzier
brands is only a couple of pennies, but multiply those pennies by a
couple of billion times and it might even generate enough money to
get Gillette back into Wall Street's good graces some day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
