<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE RETIRING EARLY, PAY OFF MORTGAGE, DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am married with three children, the youngest of whom are 15
and 17 years old; both of them will probably attend junior college
for two years and then go to local universities. I have worked for
the city of Los Angeles for the past 27 years, and all of my
pension options include a full cost-of-living adjustment with no
cap. Although the pension would increase considerably if I worked
longer, I don't know if I can last three more years. I want to
retire and coach high school baseball and enjoy life. I am
considering selling the condo to pay off some debt. The condo
brings me $1,100 a month rental income, minus $500 for taxes and
fees. It is fully depreciated and is no longer a tax write-off. I
would incur about $20,000 in taxes if I sold. Beyond my mortgage, I
have no debt aside from $5,000 in credit cards. I also owe my
family a nice vacation. How am I positioned for retirement? Should
I work three more years?
</P>
<P>
   B.M., Thousand Oaks, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The more I have been pondering this situation, the tougher it
gets to be satisfied with an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Here is some of my thinking: After deducting your contributions
to the deferred savings plan, you have pretax income of $72,250.
Assuming you used the income from your rental condo to pay the
taxes on your home, you still would be spending $31,200, or 43.2
percent of your pretax take-home pay, on your mortgage. After what
I would guess are substantial state and federal tax liabilities, it
would seem to me you don't have a whole lot to live on.
</P>
<P>
   So I am combining that situation with your remark that you're
not sure you can last three more years at your job to infer that
you are earning a substantial amount of overtime, and that your
$85,000 base salary therefore doesn't reflect your actual income.
For that reason, I have a hard time trying to calculate whether you
could maintain your current standard of living, or even one only
modestly reduced, upon retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But let's start with the easy one. If you would come out with
$145,000 after taxes upon selling your condo, you could calculate
that you are achieving a 4.9 percent return on the value of your
investment. That might be acceptable if you feel there is a
substantial potential for growth in the value of the condo. But if
there's not a big upside potential there, I agree selling the condo
probably would be a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Were you to sell the condo, use $5,000 to pay off the
credit-card debt, apply $125,000 against your home mortgage, and
then devote the remaining $15,000 to that long-overdue vacation,
you then would be in a position where you would need only 25 months
to pay off the rest of the mortgage. Taking that vacation seems to
be a good idea _ and perhaps a vacation you need as much as your
family. Perhaps that refreshment might allow you to face another
two to three years of work _ and the retirement situation would be
brightened dramatically once you get those substantial mortgage
payments off your back.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason you might want to consider delaying retirement a
bit is that you soon will be facing the costs of your children's
college education; even if they choose public schooling and obtain
substantial amounts in student loans and other financial aid, you
doubtlessly will face significant costs associated with their
education. Take it from me; I've been there.
</P>
<P>
   In all of this discussion, I purposely have left your $175,000
accumulation in the deferred compensation plan aside. This is
because whether you retire at age 50, 53, or 55, you should
anticipate many years of retirement, and although your pension will
come with annual cost-of-living adjustments, if I were you I would
feel much more secure if there were some additional savings that
could pull you through in the event those adjustments do not quite
keep pace with changes in your own cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   In summary, I am not saying either yes, retire now, or no, put
it off a couple of years. I suggest you begin the analysis by
calculating how much you are actually spending, and then coming up
with a budget showing how much you would need in retirement. If you
can make the numbers work, go for it. My guess is that it probably
will work fine, but only after you have finally burned that
mortgage note.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have owned 1,000 shares of Reebok International common
stock for the past five years and have lost more than half of what
I paid for the position. I don't want to sell right now because I
would really take a bath. With the stock market turning into a bear
market and Reebok going nowhere, what do I do?
</P>
<P>
   S.W., Worcester, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, most of the past five years have been pretty dismal for
Reebok, but both in terms of its stock price and its earnings
picture things seem to be turning up. And, of course, its
price-to-earnings ratio of 11 is always appealing to an old value
hound such as myself. First-quarter earnings of 56 cents per share
compared nicely to the 32 cents per share of a year ago, and
analyst estimates for the full year range from a low of $1.10 per
share to a high of $1.55. Results for 1999 were 20 cents per share
earned, down from 42 cents per share in 1998 and $2 plus from 1995
to 1997. In short, the fundamentals seem to be on the way back, so
why sell now, particularly since you would be selling into a market
that just hates value stocks, which is what Reebok has become.
</P>
<P>
   The one situation in which I might consider selling, if I were
you, would be if you have a capital gain on another stock that
might be sold, and the capital loss on Reebok could be used to
offset the gain from your other holding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My sister and I are widowed and are looking to invest
$340,000 accumulated from an insurance settlement and an
inheritance. What do you suggest we do? We also plan to sell the
family home and purchase a condo or a smaller house.
</P>
<P>
   M.S., Boston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Normally in a situation such as this I'd suggest a solid GNMA
fund such as Vanguard GNMA. But with five-year CD rates running as
high as 8.01 percent (for a CD of $100,000 or more) why expose
yourself to the potential of further interest rate increases, which
could drive the principal of a bond fund down?
</P>
<P>
   Even though at this point there isn't even a hint of trouble
within the banking system, I suggest you take the cautionary step
of not exceeding the FDIC insurance limits at any single
institution. For example, if $200,000 of the money is owned jointly
by your sister and yourself, you could place $200,000 in a CD at a
single institution and be fully insured, but any amount in excess
of that would not be covered.
</P>
<P>
   If the money is individually owned, I suggest you take the
cautionary step of limiting the amount of a CD at any single
institution to $100,000, the minimum amount that qualifies for the
jumbo rate, which is typically (but not always) slightly higher
than the rate for a smaller CD. Right now, there's not much
variance, with the highest rate for a jumbo CD entering this week
at 8.01 percent, and the highest rate for a CD of less than
$100,000 a flat 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a major variance in the best rates in the nation
and the average for all rates, which was 6.52 percent for a
five-year jumbo entering this week. You can find the institutions
with the best rates at many sites online (the site I have
bookmarked is www.bankrate.com) or in the DataBank page of the
Sunday New York Times. The online site also will let you seek out
the highest rates in your region of the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
