<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REPORT FROM THE TRENCHES OF A NET START-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of us write about the new economy. Some of us participate
in it.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ashbrook does both.
</P>
<P>
   A former reporter and editor at The Boston Globe, Ashbrook left
journalism four years ago to join the Internet revolution. His new
book, ``The Leap,'' chronicles his journey from the old world to
the new. It is also the story of his often painful attempt to build
HomePortfolio Inc., a Newton, Mass. company that serves the home
design business. The company recently received $48 million in
venture financing.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up with Ashbrook the other day to hear what he had to
say about creating a dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Until recently, there's been a sense that the new economy was
a can't-miss proposition. Yet at your company you were always one
step away from running out of money and shutting the door.
</P>
<P>
   A. The impression grew up during last year's Internet mania that
this whole thing was risk-free, that if you put a dot-com on your
name a billion dollars would drop on your head. This was never
risk-free. Many people who joined the fray will not walk away rich.
This new economy is more fluid. It has fewer safe islands. It asks
participants to put their security and the stability of their life
at risk in a way that most Americans are not used to.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You and your partner used credit cards to keep the company
going. How much debt did you amass?
</P>
<P>
   A. More than $250,000, all of it personal. Think about it. That
means that if you are 40 or 45 years old and you have to go back to
a regular job, you are going to have to work for the next 10 years
to pay off the debt acquired pursuing a wild dream that didn't work
out.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But the risk is more than financial, right?
</P>
<P>
   A. That's right. People talk about the burn rate for money but
there is another burn rate _ the burning up of faith and hope, and
intimacy and ultimately the fiber of a relationship. Because I had
to throw everything into getting a new venture off the ground, I
came within a hair's breath of losing my house, my wife, and my
family. You burn up so many hours _ hours that you are not reading
to your kids, hours not talking to your wife. You can't get those
hours back.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The time and energy people put into these start-ups is
amazing. What is the motivation?
</P>
<P>
   A. You don't just do it for the money. If that is all you come
for I don't know how you stick it out. It is too dry. Part of the
answer is the Web itself. It promised a revolution. It was going to
change everything. All that can make you feel like a crusader
marching behind the cross. It brings out a crazed commitment to the
cause. People are willing to make extraordinary sacrifices and
investments in energy and time. No sacrifice is too great when you
are changing the world. As a boomer I was susceptible to that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But that manic energy gives start-ups a real competitive edge
over established companies, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   A. It is a competitive edge. The big companies look around and
say: Who are these flyspecks? They never stop coming. And because
of that energy and technology some of these little flyspecks will
become major global players in a very short time. That is
unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You guys were turned down by a zillion venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   A. We saw at least 100.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Still, I got the sense from your book that even the people
who turned you down forced you to improve your product.
</P>
<P>
   A. We learned something from every single meeting _ even the
ones with guys who had three eyes and nose hair. The Internet
encouraged vast dreaming, titanic ambitions, and we were infected
with that. The VCs helped us to take it one step at a time. They
taught us that if you can't narrow down your plan to actionable
steps, you will never get to the big dream. They were relentlessly
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We've been through a period in which dot-coms could do
nothing wrong and now we are in one in which they can do nothing
right. Where do we go from here?
</P>
<P>
   A. I continue to think the ultimate impact of the Web has been
underestimated. We were in a bubble mentality last year. I am happy
to see some of the crazy extremes disappear. I think this
sobering-up period is a healthy thing. It will weed out some of the
just plain flaky stuff and get people focused on real value. We
welcome that.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a real businessman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
