<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-ART-BOS     06-07 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 LABOR JOINS THE WIRED WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Brent Tocci to realize a four-year
college degree wasn't for him. He enrolled at a community college
``to get my feet wet,'' but had no desire to continue.
</P>
<P>
   But after a friend told him he could make better money splicing,
testing, and maintaining fiber optic cable, the Braintree High
School graduate entered a four-year union-sponsored apprenticeship
program in 1994 and learned the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Today, just two years out of the program, Tocci's total annual
compensation _ including a $10,000 employer pension contribution
and free health and dental benefits _ is about $70,000. Tack on
overtime, and the figure balloons to $90,000, a salary package that
has allowed him to buy a home in Abington.
</P>
<P>
   Former Newbury Street hairstylist Eileen Farr of Quincy doubled
her salary after graduating from a four-year, union-sponsored
apprenticeship program in Dorchester. Now a fully certified
voice-data-video installer, she says the career switch has improved
her quality of life and enabled her family to buy a home and take
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the day I graduated from the training program, I've
never been unemployed,'' said Farr. ``There is always work out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from being locked out of the New Economy, thousands of
blue-collar workers are commanding top salaries by exchanging old
economy skills for technical training in the digital world,
particularly telecommunications. As the Internet revolution moves
at breakneck speed, it is this blue-collar work force that is
laboring behind the scenes installing and trouble-shooting systems
that allow companies to use tools such as video conferencing, the
Internet, and voice recognition systems.
</P>
<P>
   With the right skills, today's blue-collar workers are just as
likely to be members of the up-and-coming e-class as are the recent
graduates with degrees in computer science, programming, or
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Germarshausen, director of systems technology for the
National Electrical Contractors Association, says the
telecommunications industry is exploding.
</P>
<P>
   ``On an annual basis, when you look at growth, the electrical
industry now has a growth rate in the single digit numbers ranging
from 3 to 5 percent,'' says Germarshausen. ``But when you look at
the voice-data-video sector within the telecommunications industry
you are looking at, conservatively, a growth rate of 19 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, industry experts say 55,000 newly trained
voice-data-video installers and technicians are needed annually to
meet what many now see as a critical shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we think about technology, we often think about how it is
applied, but there are people who support it in other ways who are
critically important and are being highly rewarded for what is,
essentially, a demanding job,'' says Fred Breimyer, chief economist
at State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these people have gone through extensive training,
which also focuses attention on the transformation of traditional
union operations that are continuing to adapt and change as these
growth industries adapt and change.''
</P>
<P>
   Farr, 36, of Quincy, was earning between $35,000 to $40,000 a
year as a hairstylist in 1991 when she switched careers and
enrolled in a four-year, apprenticeship training program at the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 103 training
hall in Dorchester. She'd heard about the Internet and what was
then described as the coming explosion in telecommunications, and
she didn't want to be left out. Five years ago, Farr completed the
training; now she wires buildings, providing client companies with
Internet and cable access.
</P>
<P>
   ``My income, when you look at the benefits and the pay, has
doubled,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Farr, whose husband is an electrician, says her new career also
improved her family's lifestyle. ``We purchased a home in Quincy, a
three-bedroom Cape, soon after I got a job. We can afford to send
our son to Boston College High School, which we could not have
afforded in the past. Things have improved. I'm not counting every
penny I spend.''
</P>
<P>
   For Farr the gains are tangible: a new four-door Plymouth Breeze
and yearly trips to her family in Ireland, including an upcoming
trip this summer in which the family ``will see the country like
real tourists instead of just visiting friends.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the training she acquired was demanding, requiring
four years on-the-job apprenticeship as well as regular weekly
coursework at a training site run by the Local. Moreover, the
initial pay is a scant $9 per hour, though each trainee received
full benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice-data-video person is working all the time,'' said
Germarshausen. ``This is the person who programs systems and
trouble-shoots systems that allow companies to use video
conferencing, closed circuit TV, the Internet, security access
programs, and voice systems. Eventually, we are going to see more
techs working than standard electricians. That's because the work
is changing so radically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there is a huge demand for people who are trained
at every level,'' she said, ``apprentices, installers, and
technicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Electricians willing to update their skills are not the only
ones who stand to gain. Steamfitters who used to manipulate pipes
are now being trained to use computer-aided temperature controls,
wiring, and fiber optic cabling.
</P>
<P>
   Annual compensation for these New Economy technicians ranges
from $35,000 for video-data-voice apprentices, to up to $90,000 for
installers and technicians with at least five years' experience.
Project managers, with either college degrees or several years'
experience can earn up to $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing is that the skilled trades are evolving as
a result of the Internet, the new technology, and the deregulation
of the telecommunications industry,'' says Germarshausen, ``and the
demand for people is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh McLaughlin, owner of Sullivan &AMP; McLaughlin Communications
Group in Dorchester, can't hire enough people fast enough. He
currently employs 185 but says he could easily use 25 more. The
problem is finding them.
</P>
<P>
   Says McLaughlin, who last year pulled in $25 million in sales,
``I would never have envisioned having that much in sales five
years ago. Not a chance. But the industry is exploding and it won't
let up. We have work booked for the next three years. Even if the
stock market dropped and the economy bottomed out, it would be
three years before we'd even begin to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many others in the greater Boston area, McLaughlin is
benefitting from the break up of the old Bell Telephone system. His
clients are the new telecommunications companies that have sprung
up to compete for local consumer dollars and are looking for
highly-skilled technicians to service their systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good jobs,'' he says. ``These jobs allow the working
class guy to have a beautiful home and buy a decent car and live
moderately comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, not every new entrant into the New Economy is reaping
big gains. For those without the benefit of union backing, breaking
into the field can be more difficult. Tom Schrafft, 31, of Revere
was making $12 per hour as an administrative assistant last
December when he enrolled in a two-week technical training course
and began volunteering in computer companies' warehouses to get
more hands-on experience maintaining, installing, and repairing
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Schrafft has done some temporary work but has not
had any success finding a permanent position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to succeed in the field,'' he said. ``I figure this is
where the future is. If I'm going to survive in  &UR; today &LR; 's world,
this is where I have to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
