<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GREEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR HISTORIAN JIM GREEN GETS BEHIND THE PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When James Green took the microphone at this year's May
Day rally in the Massachusetts Capitol in support of home-care
workers, he spoke ``not only from my head but also from my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the history and labor studies professor officially came
to spotlight low pay ($8.62 to $9.15 for entry-level positions)
``in the most prosperous era in our state's history,'' he told
legislators, union leaders, and social activists that he was there
not just ``to speak of my findings as a researcher, but of my
feelings as a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Green, born 20 years ago with severe cerebral palsy,
``has been well-served by many home-care workers,'' Green said,
``especially during the past seven years, when she has been a
resident of two group homes for young people.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of the rally may have been particularly
emotional, but Green argues that putting head and heart together is
essential for the health of social movements _ a point he argues in
his new book, ``Taking History to Heart,'' published this spring by
the University of Massachusetts Press.
</P>
<P>
   While a study of social movements, the book is also part
autobiography. As Green says, ``I don't see myself as an activist,
but as a participant.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, 53, teaches at the University of Massachusetts at Boston
and lives in East Somerville with his wife, Janet Grogan, a
community activist herself, and their son, Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   As a graduate student at Yale, he studied under the legendary
Southern historian C. Vann Woodward, who inspired his students to
write what he called ``history with a purpose.'' Green came to
UMass after not only failing to get tenure at Brandeis, but after
realizing that its interest in labor history was so minimal that he
had landed in what he now jokingly calls ``the folding chair of
labor history.''
</P>
<P>
   But at UMass, Green said, ``I'm at a place where the things I
wanted to do have priority. There's no break between what I do here
and what I do outside.''
</P>
<P>
   At the university, Green works out of a windowless office
brightened with posters commemorating such landmarks in labor
history as the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire, the 1912 Lawrence
textile workers strike, and the last big May Day rally in New York
a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his students, said Green, are ``white working-class
people who don't have a sense of being connected with anything
bigger. There's a need to be active, but they aren't finding it in
electoral politics.''
</P>
<P>
   What fills their ``hollowness'' _ or at least what Green offers
as a way to fill it _ is an introduction to social movements,
especially the labor movement where Green's most vivid experience
lies.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the historic photographs in ``Taking History to
Heart'' _ Norman Thomas addressing tenant farmers, Boston
packinghouse workers celebrating a strike victory _ there is an
unexpected one of Green, in sunglasses and a union T-shirt, in the
field with a video camera.
</P>
<P>
   He is standing next to documentary filmmaker Barbara Koppel _
best-known for her Academy Award-winning film ``Harlan County,
USA'' _ as they film an interview with a striking Pittston, West
Va., coal miner in 1990. The interviews _ ``in every kind of coal
field accent,'' Green said _ became ``Out of Darkness: The Mine
Workers' Story''
</P>
<P>
   Green had met United Mine Workers president Richard Trumka when
he spoke at Harvard Trade Union program. Some of his favorite
students there, Green recalled, were ``brilliant miners who had
left the coal fields'' to work for Trumka.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked my approach to UMW history,'' Green said of Trumka,
who invited him to come down to Beckley, West Va., the headquarters
for the Pittston strike, and teach labor history to the strike
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a labor historian,'' Green said, ``this was a terrific
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   And turning that experience to academic use, Green said, ``I get
great response from white trade unionists who want to convert their
unions into social movements.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pittston, ``the moral leader was Jesse Jackson,'' not Lane
Kirkland, the president of the AFL-CIO at the time. ``The miners
picked up the lingo from him and were saying that what they had was
not just a strike, but a people's movement.''
</P>
<P>
   And labor support at the May Day rally for home-care workers is
unlike a traditional union action, Green noted. The Service
Employees International Union ``doesn't represent them, but they're
fighting to get them a pay raise. . . . That's a big shift in how
unions think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
