<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7011 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-BOURDAIN-BOS &LR;      06-07 1837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BOURDAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISHING THE DIRT ON RESTAURANT KITCHENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE YONAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Given Anthony Bourdain's criminal sensibility, his
fascination with the Mafia, and his gritty new tell-all memoir
about the restaurant business, it would be tempting to dismiss him
as a rat in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But the differences between Bourdain and your run-of-the-mill
snitch emerge just as easily as the action unfolds in ``Kitchen
Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly'' (Bloomsbury
USA). Bourdain weaves hilarious tales of the bloody (a line cook
grimaces and curses as he sews up his own knife wound), the profane
(a chef leaves his station to give a sexual ``send-off'' to a bride
in her wedding gown), and the cautionary (Friday's fish turns into
Monday's fish special). And along the way, something else becomes
clear: This man adores the business _ blood, sex, bacteria, and all
_ as no mere rat could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately in the New York press the book's being treated as an
expose, as if I'm trying to settle hash, I'm bitter about the
business, I'm somehow looking to change it,'' he says,
chain-smoking at a window table at Brasserie Les Halles in
Manhattan, where he is executive chef. ``I'm not. I love it. It was
the lifestyle that attracted me to the business in the first
place.''
</P>
<P>
   What a lifestyle. Bourdain writes of his favorite sous-chef and
prankster, Steven, who once bragged of snorting cocaine through
uncooked penne and who ``has a tattoo of a cartoon cat wearing a
chef's toque on his crotch.''
</P>
<P>
   He writes of Adam Real-Last-Name-Unknown, the ``loud, dirty,
unkempt, obnoxious, uncontrollable, megalomaniacal madman'' whose
divine bread has seduced Bourdain into hiring him on countless
occasions, and whose psychopathic behavior has always cost him the
job within months.
</P>
<P>
   He writes of practical jokes, such as food made to look like
grisly dismembered fingers, toes, or sexual organs and left for
waiters to find.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, he writes of restaurants _ good, bad, and in
between, run by control freaks and well-meaning incompetents.
Bourdain has worked at dozens of such places in his 28 years in the
business, and in the past decade has found himself at the helm of
many a sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, what's not to love?
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's the child's dream of running your own pirate
crew,'' says Bourdain, 43, who is shown holding two sabers on his
book cover. ``So I look at it perhaps overromantically.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the restaurants that employed him, ``Kitchen
Confidential'' shows signs of longevity. Before the hardcover was
even in stores, paperback rights were sold, director David Fincher
(``Fight Club'') optioned it for a movie, and Bourdain started
getting national coverage in just about every medium. Sunday, it
will be number 7 on the New York Times bestseller list for
hardcover nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for something that began as a ``much more foul-mouthed
and frank sort of a rant'' in the wake of another restaurant death.
Bourdain happily landed at Brasserie Les Halles, toned down the
essay, and ``on a lark'' sent it to The New Yorker. Within weeks,
editor David Remnick called to snap up the piece, which became the
titillating ``Don't Eat Before Reading This'' in April 1999,
warning restaurant-goers about Monday fish specials, mussels,
Sunday seafood frittatas, dirty bathrooms, and recycled bread and
butter. Bloomsbury USA immediately commissioned the book, and gave
him a mere six months to write it.
</P>
<P>
   Having written the mystery novels ``Bone in the Throat'' and
``Gone Bamboo'' in the 1990s, Bourdain plunged ahead, relieved that
he ``didn't have to worry about plot, for a change, or moving
characters through space, or story arc.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended up doing much of that anyway, creating a cast stranger
than fiction and pulling the reader right into the obscenity-laced
clamor that lurks behind the swinging kitchen door. As for story
arc, he has a knack for pinpointing crucial moments in his life of
food, starting with the boyhood defiance that led him to taste an
oyster on a boat in southwestern France _ the experience he credits
with turning him into ``a thrill-seeking, pleasure-hungry
sensualist.''
</P>
<P>
   Other milestones include a 1970s Provincetown dishwashing job,
where he witnessed the chef having sex with a bride, still in her
gown, in the garbage stockade (``I knew then . . . I wanted to be a
chef''); his training at the hands of ``Bigfoot,'' who turned him
``from a bright but druggie (expletive) into a serious, capable and
responsible chef''; and the steakhouse job he desperately needed,
and missed out on, because he mistakenly heard ``me'' instead of
``meat'' when the owner/interviewer asked, ``What do you know about
meat?'' (His answer: ``Next to nothing!'')
</P>
<P>
   As the latter example would indicate, Bourdain does not exempt
himself from the glare of his spotlight. ``You know, I was someone
you absolutely would not want to have working for you from 1982 to
1987,'' he says. ``Had I tried to portray myself as any different
than I was would have been a bald-faced and provable lie. There are
plenty of people who remember me from back then. I'm not saying
it's a noble instinct on my part; I count myself among the wounded,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the mischief, Bourdain also offers up homages to great
chefs he's known and worked for, and even allows a few tastes of
practicality, from warnings aimed at the restaurant-going public to
advice aimed at aspiring cooks, professional and amateur.
</P>
<P>
   But he clearly had more fun with the stories of tattooed
sous-chef Steven and baker Adam Real-Last-Name-Unknown, who signed
releases allowing him to describe their ``utterly disgusting
personal habits.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite chapter, he says, is ``The Level of Discourse,''
devoted to the bilingual, sex-obsessed language of kitchens. It
recalls comedian George Carlin's litany of obscenities, and as such
is largely unprintable in a family newspaper, but Bourdain does
manage an expletive-free explanation of what such patter says about
the nature of restaurant work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the system seeks, what it requires, is someone, anyone,
who can hold up their station, play the game without getting bent
out of shape and taking things personally,'' he writes. ``If you
are easily offended by direct aspersions on your lineage, the
circumstances of your birth, your sexuality, your appearance, the
mention of your parents possibly commingling with livestock, then
the world of professional cooking is not for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the book's wisecracking tone, its writing was not
without peril, though nothing so concrete as a burned steak or a
jailed line cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I'm doing in the kitchen,'' Bourdain says.
``Anybody who gets in my way I will bully, bludgeon, humiliate, do
anything necessary to move forward, and when I go home at the end
of the night, more often than not, I will know I did about as well
as anyone could do under the circumstances. I have nothing to be
ashamed of. I have a good writing day, on the other hand, and I'm
just racked with self-doubt and terror and uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he's back at his keyboard. His next book projects
are one on Typhoid Mary as a misunderstood cook, and ``The Cook's
Tour,'' in which he'll visit Burma to eat monkey brain, Africa to
eat gigantic beetles, Japan for fugu.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the simple act of eating can be a victory, it's eating at
its best,'' he says. ``You're trying something new, and you pay a
price for getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourdain worries that he may end up paying a price for the
success of ``Kitchen Confidential,'' that it will take him away
from the best job he's ever had. But he still hopes that he has
whipped up something worthwhile on the page.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a dream of mine that in 10 years a line cook who
just started out on the line, the vegetable station, and is having
a hard time of it, is getting his (expletive) kicked by some
maniacal chef . . . stumbles across my book in the library, and it
makes him feel the way I felt when I came across `Down and Out in
Paris and London' for the first time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That my suffering, however temporary, that some of the more
ludicrous aspects of the business, that they weren't just happening
to me. That my experience is part of a continuum going back to 1900
and before, that this is just part of the life that we endure and
learn to love and find funny and ugly and poignant, and that at the
end of the day it's worth doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL; 
A FEW CUTTING REMARKS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Bourdain dishes out his frank judgments as easily in an
interview as he does in ``Kitchen Confidential.'' Here are his
assessments on a variety of culinary topics:
</P>
<P>
   --Organic versus genetically modified food. ``I see a lot of
organic produce, and it's not necessarily great. What does organic
mean, grown in (expletive) by hippies? That doesn't sound like a
good thing. If the genetically modified stuff is good, if it's
crunchy, if it tastes better, if it holds up better in my fridge,
no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   --Vegetarians and vegans. ``You know, people who worship their
body as this hygienic vessel, not to be polluted by the world,
that's just freakish to me. I see the body as an amusement park. I
mean, we live in the world. We leave a wake. We leave marks, and
the world should leave marks on us as well. . . . Obviously, I'm
very pro-carnivore.''
</P>
<P>
   --Julia Child. ``It's so easy to make fun of her, but she's
always been there, a visionary, and just cool. Some people just
are. It's the Orson Welles syndome. The man made `Citizen Kane.' If
he wanted to make (expletive) wine commercials late in his career
or go on Dean Martin roasts, he's still cool for life. It's the
same with Julia.''
</P>
<P>
   --Martha Stewart. ``She stands for everything I distrust in
television entertainment and TV chefs, but if you watch her show,
not only can she cook, but she's got moves. She moves with real
speed and economy back there. She's not clumsy, like some of the TV
chefs, where you throw up your hands like, `Oh my God, look what
they're doing.' I get this terrible sense that if it was Saturday
night at 8 o'clock, and Martha Stewart's in the dining room, and my
saute man just died of a heart attack, I could probably throw her
back there and she could dig us out of the weeds.''
</P>
<P>
   --Emeril Lagasse. ``I don't think I'd want Emeril anywhere near
my restaurant. The catch phrases alone would be painful.''
</P>
<P>
   --Ferran Adria, who has made waves with such extreme food as hot
and cold foams at El Bulli in Spain. ``That's so bogus. That's
novelty food. Others will steal the more useful of his
presentations, and they'll hopefully make more sensible use of it.
You already see that. There are already some foamy sauces now, and
hey, good idea, fine. But I don't want to be the foam guy, all
right? `Let's go to the foam restaurant.' Give me a (expletive)
steak already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
