<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLOT INITIATIVES: GOOD AND BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ To begin with, Hiram Johnson hated his
father. That fact helps explain the growing fondness of Americans
for initiatives, referendums, and other forms of direct democracy.
Johnson was the godfather of the ``progressive'' movement, which
introduced ballot law to California after he was elected governor
90 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   David Broder thinks that initiatives and electronics, ``taken
together, could make our 18th-century Constitution irrelevant.'' In
``Democracy Derailed: Initiative Campaigns and the Power of
Money,'' he asks, ``Do we really wish to keep this a republic? That
question is coming at us with the speed of e-mail.'' Broder trusts
Madison, Hamilton, Franklin, and the other framers over the
consultants, sharpies, and sultans of signature-gathering he
describes in characteristically diligent reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Hiram Johnson was a reluctant candidate in 1910, according to
``Inventing the Dream,'' part of Kevin Starr's masterful
multivolume history of California. ``He hated his hometown of
Sacramento, for one thing _ and for deeply personal reasons. As an
anti-railroad candidate, moreover, he would have to square off
against his own father, Grove Johnson, a prominent pro-railroad
attorney and state legislator with whom son Hiram had never really
gotten along _ whom he had fled Sacramento, in fact, to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Pacific pretty much owned the Legislature then, but
it doesn't now. Scandals are rare here, especially since
initiative-imposed term limits. Most politicians agree that big
money has perverted the ballot process as much as it has corrupted
any other form of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Hiram Johnson offered ``a way for the citizens to get around the
special interests running the Legislature. Now it's a way for the
special interests to get around the Legislature,'' says John L.
Burton, the state senate president pro tem and the Legislature's
top Democrat. Few Republicans would argue. ``The only real people's
initiative that I can recall is the coastal commission back in the
'70s,'' Burton adds. The real estate lobby was heedless of
environmental arguments then and would have erected high-rises
along the shoreline had voters not protected the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Some initiatives are sound, but most are not, depending on
gridlock conditions. ``A split in party control,'' Broder writes,
``results in the increased use of the initiative.'' But even though
Democrats dominate Sacramento, Californians faced 20 ballot
questions in the March presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Miller, assistant secretary of state, offers another
variable. ``After an election with record turnout, the number of
ballot questions usually drops,'' she says, predicting only five
statewide questions for this November's ballot. She also notes that
the number of votes on questions seldom varies with big-bucks
advertising. Unlike the drop-off from governor to legislative
offices, nary-a-nickel Question 19 attracts as many voters as
Question 1, with millions spent on television. Citizens may
actually read the ballot summary the secretary of state's office
mails out in a pamphlet as hefty as the Fresno white pages.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Constitution began with ``We, the people,''
politicians seeking their votes have treated with solemn reverence
the collective judgment of citizens. Broder is too polite to say
so, but ``the people'' can often be foolish, mean, and venal. ``The
people'' are the same folks who make millionaires of Jerry Springer
and the sponsors of televised wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Hiram Johnson was self-righteous, bolting his party to run as a
Bull Moose candidate. He was an isolationist who opposed both world
wars and was overall a dour chap. The next time Dave Broder is
hereabouts, I'll invite him to pour some Pepsi on Johnson's
elaborate grave in Colma. Johnson's ideas have been distorted, and
the initiative process should be curbed, but probably not
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
