<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GEEK-CHIC-ART-BOS &LR;      06-07 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEK-CHIC-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HE'S THE ELITE GEEK _ AND PROUD OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Mass. _ Although he is now known from here to Kuala
Lumpur as ``The Sexiest Geek Alive,'' Tony Northrup has discovered
that some things haven't changed with fame. People make fun of him
behind his back. Women basically ignore him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being in middle school again,'' Northrup sighed over
lunch in a generic suburban restaurant here packed with other
hungry foot soldiers of the technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
   One thing _ and a big thing it is _ has changed, though.
Northrup, 26, is proud to call himself a geek. So are the 16,000
people from around the world who competed against him for the
Sexiest Geek honor, bestowed by the entertainment Web site Geek &AMP;
Guru. So are the many who attended the Geek Pride Festival in
Boston in March, or who patronize such Web sites as Geek.com or
GeekCulture.com.
</P>
<P>
   They are leading the geek backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make geeks proud, and make the jocks jealous. I want
to show the world that even if you can't get a date or throw a
football, you can still be a success,'' Northrup wrote in his
contest application.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask the people at Geek &AMP; Guru, or anyone who admires Bill
Gates, the geek will inherit the earth. Or already has.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the geek has pretty much taken over the country, so we
wanted to celebrate that,'' said Jim ``Roz'' Rosnack, the creative
director of Geek &AMP; Guru, based in Austin, Texas. ``It's those who
were tortured in high school who grew up to pretty much own
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sexiest Geek Alive application was designed to reveal both
intelligence and impressive technical knowledge. After answering
the requisite Star Trek questions, entrants had to explain
Heisenberg's Uncertainty Principle _ anyone who cut and pasted an
encyclopedia answer was disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   The judges were equally unforgiving of contestants who named a
geographical location in answer to this question: ``In what state
is Compaq Computers?'' A first-caliber geek, Rosnack says, knows
the answer should be ``disarray or confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks and charm came into play at the March pageant in Austin,
where 12 finalists met the judges. One performed his signature
geeky dance. One read her speech off her Palm Pilot. Several used
cell phones on stage so friends could coach them through the
proceedings, Rosnack said.
</P>
<P>
   Northrup stood a head above the rest based on his technical
expertise and ``his awkwardness and shyness, and his fashion sense,
or lack thereof,'' Rosnack said. But judges also saw some attitude
in Northrup. They wanted someone with edge, a winner who was ``a
little Gen-X, or a little anti-Gen-X.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest the number of applicants _ 16,000 _ sound unimpressive,
consider that that there was no prize, and finalists had to pay
their own way to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The contest's popularity is a sign that geeks are no longer
content to scurry into dark corners with their graphing
calculators. These days, geeks are sassy and in-your-face. The Geek
Pride Festival, next hitting San Francisco in September, loudly
proclaims ``Be there AND be square!'' Last weekend, the New York
Times Magazine called high school geeks ``a new kind of elite,
bound for real-world fame and fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   The explanations for Geek Chic are obvious at a time when it
seems that everyone works for a start-up, when the dot-com nouveaux
riches are thumbing their noses at everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   But are the geeks really cool? A closer examination of Northrup
reveals that, maybe, just maybe, a geek's idea of sexiness is
getting as close as possible to nongeekiness while still knowing
your way around your operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Northrup, the anointed poster-boy for geeks around the world, is
almost disappointingly normal. Granted, his life revolves around
computers. He does Web hosting (whatever that means) for
Burlington-based Genuity Inc., and on the side writes technical
books that have been published in a half-dozen languages.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a result of standing in the media glare for a while,
but he has polished his social graces _ like holding open a door
for a woman. And he says he'd rather talk about his hobbies _
hiking, rollerblading, photography _ than computers. He likes to
party. He has a girlfriend, who, he stresses, he did not meet
online.
</P>
<P>
   He's good-looking, too, in a nondescript way _ 6-foot-1, medium
build, with pleasing features and a widow's peak. Though his sense
of style is, by his own admission, lacking. He shows up for lunch
with his gray flannel shirt unbuttoned halfway down (with a white
T-shirt underneath).
</P>
<P>
   Queried about his seeming normality, Northrup replied, ``A lot
of geeks wouldn't consider me a geek because I'm not as geeky as
them, but I know people who are just regular people and I am
definitely a geek.''
</P>
<P>
   Although everyone has a general notion of what a geek is, no one
seems confident of an exact definition. To Northrup, it's ``anyone
who is really, really into computers.'' To Merriam Webster's
Collegiate Dictionary, it's ``a person often of an intellectual
bent who is disapproved of.''
</P>
<P>
   Northrup's geek credentials are rooted in childhood. At the age
of 8, he started taking computers apart and putting them together
in his home town of Pflugerville, Texas. He calls himself an ugly
kid (overweight, bad skin) who hung out with the band crowd and
played trombone. ``I guess I couldn't find a more awkward
instrument,'' he said. He remembers suffering his share of minor
indignities at the hands of ``cooler'' kids.
</P>
<P>
   Being Sexiest Geek Alive has attracted him considerable media
attention. The contest has been featured on CNN, ``Good Morning
America,'' ``The Montel Williams Show,'' and in plenty of
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But women, Northrup laments, have been unimpressed. No one has
hit on him. He's gotten only a few e-mails from women he's never
met. ``You're not that bad-looking,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   Men he knows have not always taken his ``sexy'' designation with
good humor. ``Guys in general are completely uncomfortable with
it,'' he said. ``I hear that people at work say things like, `What
makes him such a big shot?' It's clearly a joke!''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Northrup filled out the application just for fun, when
he was bored listening in on a conference call at work one day. It
turns out he doesn't really want revenge on the jocks and
cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   So the question remains, how hip is geekiness really? Rosnack
admits that the contest's creators were interested in a winner who
would be an appealing ambassador to the nongeek world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show the world, hey, geeks can be cool,'' Rosnack
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
