<SLUG> BC-ELDERS-EDUCATE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE RETIREES HEADING BACK TO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Filing into a cramped room for the spring
session's first day of classes, the eager Harvard seniors opened
fresh notebooks, examined crisp sheets of paper listing future
lectures, and anxiously exchanged gossip before the seminar on
human nature began.
</P>
<P>
   Many wore sweaters, though it was a warm day in late May. The
women pulled books from large purses, not knapsacks. And the
juiciest gossip wasn't about sports or keg parties, but about a
classmate's surgery.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't any undergraduate philosophy seminar: These seniors
were real seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all were at least 65 years old, and they weren't
concerned about such things as job offers, high grades, or graduate
diplomas. They had come to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to prevent the dying of my gray matter,'' Gertrude
Kline, 71, of Newton, said before a previous class surveying the
history of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The students at Harvard's Institute of Learning in Retirement
are part of an explosion of the lifelong learning movement, as
college campuses increasingly host educational programs for people
older than 55. Spurred by increasing life spans, and the
realization that graying baby boomers want more from retirement
than bingo, travel and bouncing grandchildren, schools are finding
that many in this college-educated generation are hungry for
intellectual stimulation. And these older students want to learn
about everything from quantum theory to the short stories of Henry
James.
</P>
<P>
   When Harvard started its program in 1977, it was the second of
its kind in the country, following the New School in New York, now
the New School University.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few programs opened in the 1980s, but the trickle led to
a deluge. Today, there are about 350 such accredited programs
around the country, according to the Elderhostel Institute Network,
a Boston-based umbrella organization for institutions of learning
in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, 14 college-sponsored elderly education
programs are affiliated with Elderhostel, and at least two more are
opening in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Harvard, schools with post-retirement classes in
the area include Boston College, Williams College, Middlesex
Community College, Lasell College, and the University of
Massachusetts at Boston and Lowell. In September, Brandeis and
Tufts are starting programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, indeed, an explosion, and it's only continuing,''
said Nancy Merz, director of Elderhostel, which has 72,000 members
and plans to open 52 more institutes soon. ``The only problem is
responding to the demand. We get five to 10 calls a week from
colleges or people who want to open new institutes. The programs
now often have to refuse people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past century, the average life span in the United States
has increased to 77 years from 47. While today about 21 percent of
the population is older than 55, the Census Bureau projects that in
2030 the percentage will jump to about 31 percent, an increase of
48 million people.
</P>
<P>
   At many post-retirement educational programs, that translates
into a competitive admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   With about 500 lifetime students accepted, Harvard can take only
25 new students a year. Soon after announcing its program, Brandeis
officials received about 800 applications for 400 spaces. And
despite more class space and better parking than Harvard, Boston
College has an eight-year-old program that routinely turns away
prospective students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so competitive we find ourselves having to make some
extremely invidious choices,'' said Leonie Gordon, director of
Harvard's program. ``We would love to have more people, but we
don't have the room.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, reasons other than intellectual
stimulation that lure so many older people to college classes.
Chief among them is the chance to get out of the house and
socialize. ``I've made a lot of friends since I've been here,''
Kline said. ``That's an integral part of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Another motive is to spend time on college campuses, which in
addition to nostalgia include the charm of youth, ideas, and
structure.
</P>
<P>
   For retired professors like Marie Callahan, the classes offer a
chance to prevent the atrophying of teaching skills. At most of the
programs, students do the teaching, requiring them to spend time
planning their courses, writing syllabuses, and preparing lectures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program offers a lot of opportunities, but for me, it
really helps keep my academic faculties alive,'' said Callahan, a
retired community college professor of French history who teaches
Kline's class on Irish history at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   The post-retirement education programs serve two main purposes,
Gordon said: preventing the withdrawal of seniors from society and
increasing contacts between the young and the old.
</P>
<P>
   While she doesn't believe every school needs such a program, she
says, people now more than ever should know there's life after
retirement. Gordon conceives of a third level of education, a
system that one day might become as normal as an 18-year-old
graduating from high school and going to college. In the third
level, retirees would have the option of returning to school.
</P>
<P>
   A similar vision spurred Bernard Reisman, 73, to launch such a
program at Brandeis. Before retiring last June from teaching Jewish
studies at Brandeis, Reisman wondered how he might stay involved
with the academic community.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after months of planning, he has 20 classes lined up for
the fall semester with seminars ranging from religion to the
history of science. ``People 55 and over are bountiful and eager
for some sophisticated and stimulating activity,'' he said. ``The
notion of coming to a college for classes really has people getting
in line.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, with canes propped in a corner, balding men craning
to read the blackboard through thick glasses, with an eagerness for
knowledge absent in many college classes, the seniors in the
philosophy seminar titled ``A Glorious Accident'' chatted about eye
surgery and trips to the Orient.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the professor turned out the lights for the main event: a
documentary on free will featuring biochemist Rupert Sheldrake.
After a while, as in other college classes, some students intensely
scribbled notes, others gazed blankly out a window, and a few fell
fast asleep.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, however, made the difference clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this exciting?'' she whispered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
