<SLUG> BC-SCOOTER-FAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUPED-UP SCOOTER COULD DRIVE A TRANSPORTATION REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This season's hot new accessory not only goes
anywhere, it takes you almost anywhere you want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Scooters, those icons of suburban childhood circa 1950, are
suddenly popular with people who were barely old enough to ride a
bicycle back then; or who were not even born yet. Powered by gas,
battery, or old-fashioned foot power, they can be spotted here
wherever an errand is being run or a cup of coffee is being
grabbed, especially in places where parking spots are few and far
between.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Oshirak sometimes totes her scooter on the ferry, then
rides it the rest of the way to work. She takes it to lunch, to
meetings, anywhere she needs to get to fast. The other night she
scooted downtown in just seven minutes, a third of the time it
would have taken by car in rush-hour traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be tooling down the street and the biggest disruption
isn't cars or potholes or pedestrians; it's people asking, `Hey,
where'd you get that?' '' said Oshirak, 31, marketing and events
director at the San Francisco-based Joe Boxer Corp. ``It's perfect
for a city this size. I haven't run out of charge yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The model Oshirak prefers is known as the Zappy, a 37-pound,
$599 electric scooter that got priceless publicity when actor Kevin
Spacey rode his onto the set of David Letterman's late-night talk
show and declared it the only way to get around New York. Sales
were strong before, with more than 20,000 already on the streets in
the United States and other countries. Now there's a backlog of
several thousand for scooters that come in what Ian Olson, manager
of Zapworld.com's local store, dubbed ``electric'' red, blue, and
yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Slower than a bicycle, faster than two feet, Zappies travel
about 13 miles per hour, depending on the weight of the rider and
the hilliness of the terrain. The more oomph the rider puts into
it, the farther the cruise range, which Zapworld officials put at
as much as 8 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are saying, `Why Zappies? Why now?' '' said
Gary Starr, chief executive officer of Zapworld, based in
Sebastopol. ``But we always thought it would take off. It's
efficient . . . and it's a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Farrell, senior vice president of creative services at
Sharper Image, which is based here, said he has no ready
explanation for the sudden demand for the scooter, which has become
the top seller at the retail chain's stores and No. 2 when catalog
sales are included. Named the Razor and manufactered in China, the
$99 nonmotorized scooter first swept Japan, then Australia, Hawaii,
and California. Weekly sales are in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Now its popularity is moving East, Farrell said, with the Razor
already evident in New York and expected in quantity in Boston
sometime this summer. Zapworld, which just shipped $200,000 worth
of Zappies to Norway, recently brought out its own version of the
so-called kick scooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those magical, fad-driven things,'' said
Farrell, whose employer also sells an upscale version of the Razor
that costs about $400 and travels at four times a walking pace.
``Utility is not the whole story. It's just a phenonemon that we
can't explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, part of the explanation is portability. Both types of
scooters fold up easily for carrying. Unlike the also-popular
Go-Peds, powered by 1.2 horsepower engines and able to travel 25
miles on a tank of gas, Zappies and Razors do not require fuel.
That means they are allowed on public trains, buses, and boats, no
small advantage in a city where traffic congestion is among the top
laments of the dot.com employees remaking San Francisco in their
own image.
</P>
<P>
   Parking, or the lack of it, was the reason Douglas Watson cited
for test driving a Zappy the other day. Helmet on, he practiced
kick-starting, picking up speed, slowing down, and stopping behind
the company's San Francisco outlet, where shoppers can also buy
regular bicycles, battery-powered bicycles, and other
energy-efficient means of transportation. Still, Watson was
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's kind of silly looking, but I don't really care,''
said Watson, 24, an audiovisual technician at a hotel. ``It would
be great for covering short distances. And it's getting really,
really hard to find parking.''
</P>
<P>
   The parking problem was what moved the owners of Black Rocket
Marketing to decide that Zappies were just what its 30 or so
employees needed. The firm bought four for itself, and gave another
two away. Now they're used at any hour of the day to courier
packages, run office errands, or go out for a quick lunch.
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Mumford, a 25-year-old production artist who leaves
his Zown appy at Black Rocket for colleagues to use, put it, ``I
unplug it, I run over to the sandwich shop, I take it right in the
store, I put the food in the bag, and I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend has drawn the attention of state lawmakers, who now
require riders to wear helmets, and to stay off sidewalks and roads
where the speed limit exceeds 25 miles per hour. Only riders 16 or
older can use public roadways at all, and then they are forbidden
from pushing their scooters past 15 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the dangers _ in May a San Mateo man was killed when he
drove his electrically powered scooter into traffic, and dozens of
people have been injured on their motorized scooters _ Oshirak said
she is about to start wearing a helmet. What she can't imagine
doing is getting around town any other way than on her Zappy, a
fleet of which Joe Boxer acquired in August 1999 after featuring
them in a fashion show along with models showing the company's
underwear collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing a big grand finale and we wanted to show
underwear in a new way,'' said Oshirak. ``We just thought of
Zappies. . . . It's the way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
