<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS URGE LIFELONG RELIGIOUS EDUCATION FOR CATHOLICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned that many adult Catholics do not know enough about
their own religion, the 29 Catholic bishops of New England have
taken the unusual step of issuing a joint call for intensified
lifelong religious education.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops, from the 11 Roman Catholic and two Eastern Catholic
dioceses in the six New England states, issued a pastoral letter
declaring that ``with ever greater urgency, we are all called in
this new millennium to know our faith and to pass it on in all its
fullness to the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which the bishops plan to distribute through
diocesan newspapers, over the Internet, and in parishes, does not
lay out specific proposals for reforming adult education, but
stated: ``We want all adults to have the opportunity to deepen
their understanding of the Christian message by means of
theological instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bishop Richard J. Malone of Boston said the
region's Catholic leaders are working on ways to improve the
education of adults, but that the hierarchy also expects clergy and
laypeople to come up with ideas for translating the pastoral letter
into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our formal religious education usually stops with
confirmation, and people go through adulthood with what is
sometimes an adolescent understanding of faith,'' said Malone, who
is the top education official for the Archdiocese of Boston.
``We're trying to shift the paradigm from thinking of religious
education as exclusively something for children to a sense that
religious education is a lifelong process.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said surveys have indicated weak understanding of some
tenets of Catholicism among Catholic adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like them to learn more about Catholic doctrine,
liturgy and the sacraments, the Catholic moral life, and prayer,''
Malone said. ``In other words, what we believe, and how we
celebrate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said some parishes are already doing innovative things to
draw adults further into the church, such as appointing mentors for
new parents who arrive at church to baptize a child. But he said
too many churches depend on poorly attended lecture series as their
adult education program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very engaging adult things going on in many
parishes, but in general it can be a lot stronger,'' Malone said.
``We're trying to stretch people creatively beyond the lecture
thing. How can we infuse all the different activities, even social
activities, with a little bit stronger adult education component?
We need to look over the whole of parish life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the bishops' document is titled ``A Pastoral Letter on
Catechetics,'' Malone said forms of instruction should be more
sophisticated than the question-and-answer format historically
associated with the word catechism.
</P>
<P>
   The letter follows more pointed documents issued by Pope John
Paul II and by the National Conference of Catholic Bishops aimed at
rejuvenating Catholic religious education, especially for adults.
According to Thomas Groome, a Boston College theology professor who
specializes in religious education, Catholic Sunday school programs
for children have become increasingly vibrant in recent years, with
increasing enrollments and more effective teaching methods, but
with the new documents church leaders are trying to emphasize the
importance of ongoing faith formation by adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is much empirical evidence of new vitality in the
church's catechetical ministry, and for adults as well as for
children,'' Groome said. ``I am grateful that our New England
bishops celebrate and encourage the success of this all important
ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Other religious denominations are also grappling with adult
education, and some have moved more aggressively than the Catholic
Church to take advantage of a resurgent interest in religion and
spirituality among some Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Malone spoke approvingly of the Me'ah program, a two-year
intensive adult education program launched by the Boston Jewish
community that has been enjoying considerable success.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodist Church has been a leader among Protestant
denominations at offering rigorous religious education for adults.
More than 640,000 Methodists have taken part in a 34-week program
called Disciple Bible Studies, a lay-led weekly Bible study course
for adults conducted in small groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
