<HEADER>
A7046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-9     06-07 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-900(2TAKES)-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK GOVERNMENT THREATENED AFTER PARLIAMENT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government was
thrown into tumult Wednesday when parliament, by a substantial
majority, approved a preliminary bill to disperse and head toward
new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires three more hearings to become law, and it
could end up being derailed by political maneuvering or the basic
desire of members of parliament to cling to their jobs and
perquisites. But it seemed inevitable Wednesday that the vote would
break up the governing coalition and create a chaotic interlude at
a diplomatically inopportune moment.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final peace talks between Israelis and Palestinians
that were supposed to consume Barak's energies this summer.
Instead, he will be forced to devote considerable time to domestic
negotiations _ ``Poker time!'' his Cabinet secretary, Yitzhak
Herzog, said. Barak could face the endgame of the peace effort and
the endgame of his year-old government at almost the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the threshold of a new era, and from here it looks
like it will be a mess,'' said Nahum Barnea, a veteran political
analyst, as he surveyed the frenzied politicking in the bustling
halls of the flat-roofed parliament building Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak did not make any statements directly after the vote, which
was 61-48 with 11 of 120 members absent. But right before the vote,
when the outcome was already clear, he told Israel Radio: ``I have
a positive disposition by nature. This government will continue to
rule.''
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday evening, he addressed the nation with a completely
unruffled manner. Saying that the Cabinet would meet on Sunday and
figure out how to proceed, his advised all Israelis to relax, enjoy
the holiday of Shavuout that begins Thursday, and trust him to
restore calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dust will settle,'' he said confidently. ``There aren't
going to be any elections.''
</P>
<P>
   A former general who was elected by an overwhelming majority
last May, Barak went to great effort to cobble together a broad
coalition of left and right, religious and secular parties in what
he portrayed as an effort to heal the diverse rifts in Israeli
society. He also believed that he needed a broad government to back
his peacemaking plans.
</P>
<P>
   But from the time Barak took office last July, the coalition was
fractious.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday three of the six parties in his 68-member
government voted against him: the National Religious Party, which
was on its way to quitting anyway; the Russian immigrant party,
Yisrael B'Aliyah, led by the interior minister, Natan Sharansky;
and Shas, the ultra-Orthodox movement that is the third-largest
political party in Israel, after the Liberal/One Israel and the
Likud parties.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All three parties voting against Barak served in the right-wing
Cabinet of the former prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu. A former
chief of staff of Netanyahu's, Avigdor Lieberman, who heads a
second Russian immigrant party, introduced the bill. Shas members
encouraged him to do so, and when the vote passed, they surrounded
Lieberman for an extended group hug.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, several feet away, Ophir Pines-Paz, the
chairman of Barak's faction, sat alone, looking shocked and
crestfallen.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, which with 17 members of parliament represents Jews of
North African and Middle Eastern origin, has been the balkiest
party in the coalition, fighting for money and respect from the
first day. The other two parties more specifically opposed Barak's
peace moves, and long felt out of place in a center-left
government, frequently siding with the right-wing opposition that
was weakened without them.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Barak faces several options in the immediate future, as this
bill wends its way through parliament.
</P>
<P>
   He could try once more to save his broad coalition, which
experts considered unlikely. Before the vote, Barak's office put
out a statement suggesting that he would dismiss any ministers who
cast their ballot against the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister has decided to put a stop to a situation in
which ministers warm their Cabinet seat but act as though they're
in the opposition,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   He could reshape the coalition as a narrow minority government
that depends on Arab parties for majority votes on peacemaking
issues, which is the most likely. That would give him a government
that echoed the one led by his mentor, the late Yitzhak Rabin,
which faced a strong right-wing opposition. Barak had aspired not
to copy it because he felt it was divisive and undermined the peace
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Or he could bypass parliament and ask outgoing Israeli President
Ezer Weizman for permission to resign, which would force new
elections in 90 days from the time the request was granted. That
would be much quicker than if the elections came about as a result
of Wednesday's bill, and it would allow Barak to seize the momentum
and profit from his surge in popularity after the Israeli troop
withdrawal from Lebanon last month.
</P>
<P>
   Several ministers of the government wrung their hands Wednesday
and claimed that the politicians who voted to shake things up were
tone-deaf to the public mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote has nothing to do with what people want,'' said Haim
Ramon, a minister charged with Jerusalem affairs. ``Your desire,''
he told the lawmakers, ``is disconnected from reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Melchior, a dovish rabbi in Barak's Cabinet, said the
vote revealed the ``sectorialism'' of parliament and predicted that
it would infuriate the public. ``What? They want a period of
uncertainty?'' he said. ``No one will want this. Everyone outside
this building will hate us.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said they feared that the country's diplomatic efforts
would suffer most. ``This is not just a government crisis,'' said
Naomi Chazan, a leftist lawmaker. ``It's the future of the peace
process, and everyone who voted for this is exercising maximum
irresponsibility.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the right-wing Likud Party did not waste time in
proclaiming Barak's days to be numbered. ``I'm running around
trying to form a new coalition right now,'' said Silvan Shalom, a
young lawmaker who aspires to take over the Likud.
</P>
<P>
   Shalom acknowledged that the peace effort, which is not his
priority, might be hurt. `Obviously the other side will understand
that they are negotiating with a lame duck, and they won't want to
make decisions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Shas party, whose power base is built on a social service
network that includes a large religious school system, has been
battling for money to cover its schools' debts. Shas' leader, Eli
Yishai, has butted heads with the leftist education minister, Yossi
Sarid, on funding, educational reform and power issues. And Shas'
spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, is under police investigation
for inciting violence against Sarid in his sermons.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' vote Wednesday was the culmination of its threats against
the government, which followed Barak's suspension of negotiations
over the problems of its school system earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided on Monday morning to vote in favor of Avigdor
Lieberman's bill,'' said Yitzhak Suderi, the spokesman for Shas.
``When we gave him our word, he decided to introduce his bill. We
warned the prime minister a few weeks ago that Lieberman was
preparing the bill and that we might support it if we were to
continue to be persecuted by Meretz,'' which is Sarid's party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for the prime minister to make a decision,''
Suderi continued. ``Does he want a narrow coalition that will
endure only two or three weeks, or does he want to try to maintain
his broad coalition. He can either show leadership, as we know he
is capable of, given the experience with the withdrawal from
Lebanon, or he can do Yossi Sarid's bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   The liberal, secular members of the Israeli public who voted
Barak into office are hoping that he will finally turn his back on
Shas. Several ministers said they imagined he would.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ramon, long a political ally of Shas, sounded fed up
Wednesday. ``One thing's for sure,'' he said. ``The mess is over.
And the next coalition will be organized so that whoever votes
against us is out the same day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
