   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, June 8:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MICROSOFT &LR;  (``f`` code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories and graphics on
the judge's ruling in the Microsoft antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Ledeall: Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson is scheduled to release his final decision in the
Microsoft antitrust case this afternoon. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ASSESS (Undated) _ A news analysis on the legal
strategies planned by Microsoft during the appeal process. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LAW (Washington) _ Applying the old standards of
antitrust law to the New Economy. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REACT (Washington) _ Looking at the reaction from the
plaintiffs as well as political fallout. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REDMOND (Redmond, Wash.) _ The reaction from Microsoft
headquarters. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   Others as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's government was thrown into tumult Wednesday when
parliament, by a 61-48 vote, approved a preliminary bill to
disperse and head toward new elections. The bill requires three
more hearings to become law and it could become derailed by
political maneuvering. But it seemed inevitable that it would break
up the governing coalition and create a chaotic interlude as the
peace process tries to proceed. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT (Cairo, Egypt) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright met Wednesday with Syria's foreign minister, Faruq al
Sharas, and said the door is still open for Israeli-Syrian talks to
resume. She also bluntly called for Syrian troops to leave Lebanon.
By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-WAR-CRIMES (Prague, Czech Republic) _ In an extensive
report that has infuriated NATO leaders, Amnesty International said
Wednesday that NATO violated international law in its bombing war
over Yugoslavia by hitting targets where civilians were sure to be
killed. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
