<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-MONASTERY-NUNS-2ndTak     06-07 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONASTERY-NUNS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
CHRISTOVAL, Texas: living,'' she said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet, days later, after her family had been called to her
bedside, Buchholz sat up in bed and was quickly able to walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Carmelite nuns had been praying for her. Doctors concluded
that she was suffering from a rare fungal disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm alive because a whole bunch of prayers were said,'' she
insists. ``We came through it. In a strange way, it was a
blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other stories about the power of the nuns' prayers,
Chandler said. Many in the community attest that the sisters'
prayers are ``almighty powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   And the community has shown its gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, the Carmelite sisters have been saving money for a
new monastery. Their hope was simply to expand their old site,
maybe bring in a few more nuns, even recruit more women to their
calling.
</P>
<P>
   They never dreamed of the missionlike compound that is being
built.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a Christoval family offered the nuns a section of
ranch land on which to build their monastery. Pierce Holt, the
landowner, graduated from Angelo State University in 1987 as one of
the university's top football players.
</P>
<P>
   He was a consensus All-American in college and went on to play
in the National Football League, becoming a Pro Bowl lineman with
the San Francisco 49ers and the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``His wife was teaching a catechism class and wanted to bring
her students to our monastery to learn more about it,'' Sister
Marie said. ``While they were here, we told them we planned to
build a new monastery for a jubilee birthday gift for Jesus. They
were excited about that and later came back with her husband and
three children and said they would offer part of their land for the
monastery.''
</P>
<P>
   Then more benefactors arrived. One man put in a road to the
building site; others donated materials. People paid $100 each to
have their names etched on stones for a ``Pathway of Prayer''
outside the nuns' cottages.
</P>
<P>
   And Eva Tucker, a legendary San Angelo native, donated hundreds
of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   At 89, Tucker is active in the Catholic church and has twice had
private audiences with the pope.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in San Angelo in 1911, attended Incarnate Word
Academy in San Antonio, and then became the first Hispanic to
graduate from what then was San Angelo High School. She also
attended San Angelo Business College and San Angelo College.
</P>
<P>
   She taught school in Mertzon and headed a school for Hispanic
students in Ballinger before the system integrated. During World
War II, she served as a translator for the State Department in
Washington, D.C. After the war, she married Art Tucker, a prominent
oil producer who died in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Tucker is a very charitable person,'' Sister Marie said.
</P>
<P>
   As the project progressed, one of the nuns, Sister Annunciata,
studied the building plans and eventually began supervising
construction. Most of the workers came to know her as Sister
Contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to open the monastery this spring, and the sisters
have moved to their new home. But the monastery isn't completed and
won't be for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just rough it,'' Sister Marie said. ``We are about
$200,000 short, and we're still looking for ways to raise the
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Already women are writing to the sisters, inquiring about
joining the monastery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interestingly, in these days when there is a decrease in
vocations like mine, in religious life in general, there is a
surprising new interest in this deeper way of life,'' Bishop
Pfeifer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new hunger for God in people, a new spirituality.
We are in a world of noise, constant activity, people judge by the
dollar sign,'' he said. ``Here are people who commit themselves to
God, give up material things and help us to realize the meaning of
life is found in the soul.'' ``The new monastery's address is
Carmelite Monastery of Our Lady of Grace, 1 Via Maria, Christoval
TX 76935. The phone number is (915) 853-1722.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NUNS TRACE HISTORY TO 13TH CENTURY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carmelites trace their history to a band of Christian soldiers
who settled in the caves ``near the fountain of Elijah'' on Mount
Carmel in Palestine after the Crusades in the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   They sought to live as hermits and to meditate in silence and
solitude. They became a recognized religious order about 1215 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   The first monasteries of nuns were founded in the 15th century.
There are two orders of Carmelite nuns. The original order is
called Carmelites of the Ancient Observance. The Discalced Order
was established in the 16th century. Discalced, which means
``barefoot,'' is the reformed order.
</P>
<P>
   The Carmelite Monastery of Our Lady of Grace near San Angelo is
from the original order.
</P>
<P>
   Their vestment is a large brown scapular, a sleeveless outer
garment worn on the shoulders. The nuns believe it is the same as
the scapular that the Virgin Mary gave to St. Simon Stock in 1247.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Carmelite Monastery of Our Lady of Grace
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
