<P>
   TINY-APARTMENTS (New York) _ In the most ingenious small
Manhattan apartments, designers and their clients become
illusionists. They make beds disappear, tables double in height and
televisions spin between two rooms at once. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT8,9.
</P>
<P>
   SURFER-SHACK (Undated) _ It is a well-known fact that there is a
corollary between the size of a house and the number of headaches
it causes. And in the Hamptons, their severity increase
exponentially as one proceeds east along Route 27 to the windmill
in East Hampton. Cynthia Rowley, the fashion designer, and her
husband, Bill Keenan, a designer and sculptor, shucked the
headaches involved in owning a four-bedroom shingled stunner in the
estate section of East Hampton and moved instead to a surfer's
shack in Montauk. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   TOWER-BY-THE-SEA (Undated) _ In tower building, small is lovely.
It is the tall imagination that counts. A few summers ago in Maine,
I built a tower on a high hill overlooking the sea. My tower is
only 12 by 12 1/2 feet and three stories high, if you generously
include the observation deck. Building up to that deck _ with
simple tools, no electricity and little help _ was a major
satisfaction, indeed a salvation, during a year that saw my
marriage shaken, and my faith often in shambles. By Bill Henderson.
</P>
