<SLUG> BC-MONASTERY-NUNS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARMELITE NUNS TURN TO A NEW TEXAS HOLY LAND FOR SOLITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHRISTOVAL, Texas _ On a hot and gusty West Texas day, Sister
Marie hurries across the chalky construction site with her
traditional brown habit lapping at the top of her blue cowboy
boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have cowboy boots,'' she says of the six cloistered
nuns who have made the new monastery their home. ``They warned us
there were a lot of snakes out here, but they said the snakes
wouldn't strike higher than six inches, and we would be safe as
long as we had our boots on.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Carmelite Monastery of Our Lady of Grace is rising,
stone by stone, above the twisted mesquite and live oak trees. It
is a new Texas holy land on the rocky pastures, a place of prayer
and deep spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   Also a place of goats and cattle and rattlesnakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to learn to live out here,'' the
55-year-old Carmelite nun says with girlish enthusiasm. ``It's like
a different planet.''
</P>
<P>
   She points to what will be the kitchen and then hurries off to
the chapel, talking excitedly and stirring up a whirl of dust with
her unconventional footwear. She warns, ``Watch your step.''
</P>
<P>
   The nuns have become familiar with the serpents. ``One of our
sisters was hanging clothes on a line out here when she saw
something sparkling in the grass,'' Sister Marie recalled. ``She
thought it was rosary beads, but when she looked closer, she saw it
was a snake.''
</P>
<P>
   The snake didn't strike, Sister Marie believes, because it
sensed the ``calmness and serenity'' of the nun. ``Sister had 10
guardian angels on her shoulder that day,'' Sister Marie said.
``She came running in to tell us about the snake, and we all went
out and chopped its head off.''
</P>
<P>
   Life will be different for the nuns on the West Texas pastures.
The rolling hills, harsh and drought-hardened, bristle with cactus.
Rocks litter the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, quiet pervades this 640-acre site. Solitude is
essential to the Carmelite nuns, and they had almost none at their
old home in San Angelo about 25 miles north.
</P>
<P>
   Their small frame monastery at the edge of Goodfellow Air Force
Base in San Angelo had been their home and sanctuary for 11 years,
although its crowded rooms made life difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old neighborhood is pretty peaceful'' except, she said,
for loud rock 'n' roll music on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   But the nuns' little ranch house wasn't conducive to their life
of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be more like the first hermits of Mount Carmel,''
she explained, referring to 13th-century Christian veterans of the
Crusades who sought a contemplative life in the caves on Mount
Carmel in Palestine. ``They had separate caves. They had silence
and solitude and would only come together for prayer and their
meals.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Marie arrived in San Angelo from a monastery in North
Dakota in 1989. Life was different there. The monastery was
established, roomy and set on a lush farm.
</P>
<P>
   She knew life would be different in Texas, she said, but she
welcomed the adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually looked forward to the heat and doing our gardens
all year round,'' she said. ``It was very delightful in more ways
than one, because the people were just as warm as the weather. We
were so amazed. It was unexpected to us: the warmth of the people,
their eagerness to help in every way. It was just one miracle after
another.''
</P>
<P>
   The people of the San Angelo area, Catholic and non-Catholic,
were eager to embrace the nuns. Bishop Michael Pfeifer of the San
Angelo Diocese invited the sisters to establish a monastery in
town, and on their arrival they asked him what he wanted them to
pray for first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain,'' he answered. The night of the monastery dedication,
four inches of rain fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the bishop announced they were coming, there was
jubilation,'' said Tilly Chandler, a member of Holy Angel parish.
``It is such an asset to have them here, knowing what they are and
how they lead their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had to be 1,100-1,500 people for the dedication of the
monastery, and the old chapel only seats 40. Hundreds of people
stood outside in the rain listening to Mass.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said it was comforting to know that San Angelo had a
group of women ``at that height of spirituality whose sole purpose
is to pray for the needs of this community.''
</P>
<P>
   And some in the community insist that the prayers are being
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Buchholz, a 47-year-old San Angelo resident, credits the
nuns with a life-saving ``miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have a paper on my wall that says it was a miracle,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Buchholz became desperately ill and was taken to a San
Antonio hospital. She soon fell into a coma and her organs began to
fail. More than 20 specialists examined her, she said, but no one
offered a diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paper I have on my wall is from my consultation with an
infectious disease specialist who figured my mortality chances at
95 percent. I was given only a 5 percent chance at living,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
