<HEADER>
A7102 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-07 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STATE CRACKDOWN ON POACHERS IS MAKING A DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Sonoma and Mendocino coasts have always been
a paradise for abalone divers, the last sanctuary for the beloved
red abalone.
</P>
<P>
   But last week's highly publicized sweep of Bay Area abalone
poachers unveiled again how greed and a lucrative black market has
severely affected a species.
</P>
<P>
   According to the California Department of Fish and Game, three
sophisticated poaching rings working simultaneously raped that
paradise in the past six years for more than 70,000 abalone worth
$2.5 million. In an arrest sweep, 18 suspects from Bay Area
counties were picked up and booked, many for felony conspiracy.
That brings the number of arrests to 100 in the past two years for
the illegal take, and often sale, of the cherished mollusk.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested include groups of divers, wholesalers, buyers and
delivery transporters, said Fred Cole, a deputy chief of DFG's
Enforcement Branch.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonoma and Mendocino coast is one of the best areas in the
world for sport abalone diving, where divers will free-dive,
holding their breath, often using snorkels. Any kind of air assist,
such as using a scuba tank, is illegal, and so is selling any
abalone taken there. According to biologists, that is why abalone
on the Northern California coast have flourished while being picked
clean in areas where commercial diving has been permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Game wardens working undercover have discovered that abalone
typically sell illegally for $35 each, and occasionally as high as
$80.
</P>
<P>
   That also is why this area has always represented a forbidden
paradise for Bay Area poachers. Four years ago, DFG game warden
Dave Bezzone, often working on his own to track abalone poachers,
uncovered the biggest felony wildlife poaching operation in
California history with links to San Francisco, Los Angeles, San
Diego, Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature then mandated a new Special Operations
Unit for the DFG. In the past two years, this new unit, often
working undercover, has made three major sweep arrests in the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   Each investigation has uncovered similar operations, said state
game warden Mark Lucero, starting with the illegal take of abalone
in large quantities from the Mendocino and Sonoma coast.
</P>
<P>
   The damage to wildlife health can be staggering.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reef where we found them targeting was outside Mote Creek
in Mendocino County,'' Steve Martarano said. ``They had just picked
it clean.''
</P>
<P>
   In such areas, it will take 15 years to undo the damage,
according to Konstatin Karpov, a state marine biologist. He said it
is vital to catch abalone poachers, and that they ``threaten the
sustainability'' of the species in areas where they have been
overfished.
</P>
<P>
   Martarano added that undercover wardens believe the past two
years of ongoing investigations has put a significant dent in the
illegal operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last September's arrests, we noticed a decrease in
activity right away,'' Martarano said. ``Then we noticed that there
were a lot more women involved and arrested last week.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that, he said, is ``because their male partners
had been arrested last year'' and were in jail, so it fell to their
spouses to continue the illegal operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-PARAPLEGIC-SWIMMER-HN     06-07 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARAPLEGIC-SWIMMER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAN SEES PARALYSIS AS NO IMPEDIMENT TO SWIMMING ENGLISH
CHANNEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOERNE, Texas _ The sun was just beginning its daily climb over
Boerne Lake when Jason Pipoly rolled his wheelchair down the
gravel-covered boat ramp and into the cool, green water.
</P>
<P>
   He wheeled himself out about 20 feet, until the thin tires were
imbedded in the lake bottom and his paralyzed legs were half
submerged. Then he pushed his body weight onto his arms, leaned
forward and gently rolled into the water.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Pipoly did this, the police thought they had a
suicide on their hands. Now they know better.
</P>
<P>
   Pipoly makes this trip just about every day, motivated not by
desperation, but by his determination to conquer a physical
handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Pipoly, 29, a paraplegic since breaking his back in a car
accident two years ago, is determined to swim the English Channel,
a feat he first attempted when he was 11 years old, a crossing his
father made 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When he will again try the grueling swim from England to France
is still undetermined. But the training has begun in earnest on
this small, quiet lake northwest of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a journey that I'm so happy I've gone on,'' Pipoly
said before another three-hour swim back and forth across the lake.
``The training has become the best part of my day. It's spiritual.
I feel the presence of God out there.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 swimmers have crossed the English Channel since
British Capt. Matthew Webb made the first recorded crossing in
1875. Hundreds more have failed.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is challenging by any standards. The Channel is 21
miles wide at its narrowest point _ the Strait of Dover _ but
winds, tides and currents can carry swimmers far off that track,
adding miles and hours to the journey. Water temperatures, even in
the summer, are a crisp 60 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, his father, Carl Pipoly, swam the Channel. Jason was 9
at the time, and remembers being more excited over the trip to
Britain than awed by his father's accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, a more grown-up Jason Pipoly tried to
become the youngest Channel swimmer of that time. He lasted eight
hours in the water before adverse weather halted his swim.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the athletic effort made the young swimmer famous enough
for an appearance on Johnny Carson's ``Tonight Show,'' where Pipoly
confidently told the talk-show host that he would return to conquer
the English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Those dreams faded, though. In 1998, Pipoly was living in Aspen,
Colo., and more focused on skiing and a budding career in
photography. His life took an abrupt turn one morning when his car
slid off the road and down an embankment, flipping onto its side
and slamming roof-first into a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately knew I broke my back,'' Pipoly said. ``I
couldn't feel my legs, and I knew something was seriously wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Months of rehab followed, and Pipoly was forced to accept the
realization that he was paralyzed from the middle of his chest
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn how to do everything all over again, even
breathing,'' he said. ``You have to learn how to dress yourself,
how to take care of yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to have this attitude of saying, `This is your new
life.' I knew sulking wasn't going to solve anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He moved to San Antonio in 1999 to live closer to his father,
who is a lawyer in the South Texas city. Months later, while
visiting relatives, an aunt pulled out the old tapes of the
``Tonight Show,'' and replayed the 11-year-old's unfulfilled
promise about returning to conquer the English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just stuck with me,'' Pipoly said. ``I told Johnny I was
going back, and I never went back.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to a pool but could barely stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I could do was pull myself across the pool,'' Pipoly said.
``I told myself, `You're insane. Go home and forget about it.'
Well, I couldn't forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   By early this year, Pipoly was ready to start training in colder
water and more natural conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On his first swim at Boerne Lake, he returned to shore to find a
police officer waiting. Someone had seen Pipoly's empty, partly
submerged wheelchair and reported a possible drowning. The officer
was ready to summon rescue crews to begin dragging the lake for a
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cop just shook his head when I swam up,'' Pipoly said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the solitary morning swim is the best part of his day,
Pipoly said. Alone in the water, he thinks about polar bears
swimming in the freezing arctic waters; he travels to far-off
lands; he prays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come up with wonderful ideas,'' he said. ``It's the clearest
my mind is throughout the day.''
</P>
<P>
   His partner and biggest supporter in the endeavor is his sister,
Gina Safranic of Minneapolis. They are working to raise the
estimated $20,000 to $30,000 he will need to train, travel and
attempt the crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Pipoly said the challenge and the training have brought his
son to a new level of acceptance about the turn of events in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you come through what he's come through,
there is a normal anger there,'' the father said. ``This has
diminished the anger and gotten him to accept the injury. He's
setting goals and moving on with his life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pipoly would not be the first handicapped swimmer to strike out
across the channel. The Channel Swimming Association, which
regulates and authenticates Channel swims, has seen attempts by
amputees and deaf and blind individuals, said Duncan Taylor,
secretary of the association.
</P>
<P>
   The first record of a paraplegic crossing was in 1998, when
Australian John Maclean swam from England to France in just under
13 hours. A year later, a Baltimore Vietnam veteran with missing
legs attempted the crossing but was foiled by mechanical problems
in the boat that must accompany all swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Pipoly admits doubt sometimes creeps into his mind. The
logistics of raising money, setting up the trip and actually
striking out from Dover can overwhelm him. He doesn't doubt his
ability to succeed, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``When stuff enters my mind, the best thing for me to do is to
come out here and swim,'' Pipoly said. ``When I get a good workout,
I start to think the whole thing is possible and I can actually do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Cindy Tumiel by e-mail at ctumiel &LR; express-news.net)
</P>
