<HEADER>
A7127 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BLACK-HOLES-HNS &LR;      06-07 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-HOLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BLACK HOLES A CENTRAL TOPIC FOR ASTRONOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They are the vacuum cleaners of the universe:
black holes, those pitch-black cosmic monsters that devour stars
with nary a burp.
</P>
<P>
   They are not rare: Scientists say a super-size black hole
occupies the centers of each of at least 33 galaxies. One is a
super-massive black hole that squats at the center of Earth's
galaxy, the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 years after the first modern speculations about
black holes, they have become a central topic of astronomical
study. That is clear from the topics at the American Astronomical
Society meeting this week in Rochester, N.Y.:
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at Stanford University are planning a laboratory
simulation of a mysterious process thought to occur in the vicinity
of black holes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology have
used a space-based super-telescope to watch a black hole generate
intense radiation as it disrupts a nearby gas cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Rogue black holes drift through space, threatening whatever
stars or planets they pass. These juvenile delinquents of the
galaxy are omnipresent. An estimated 10 million black holes float
in the plane of our galaxy alone, said John Kormendy, an astronomer
at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not worried that Earth eventually will disappear into
a black hole. The galaxy is so huge, about 100,000 light-years
wide, that it's highly unlikely we will encounter one, he said. (A
light-year is 6 trillion miles, the distance that light travels in
a year.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability that one of those will come near us during our
civilization is an enormous number of times smaller than that some
stupid (asteroid) floating around the solar system will hit us,''
said Kormendy, who spoke at the Rochester conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if one were to wonder which dangers from space we should
worry about, we should worry about rocks from space _ they've hit
us before and they will hit us again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as the 18th century, astronomers speculated that a
star might be so massive that its gravity would trap light, making
the star invisible. But the idea was not taken seriously until the
1930s, when scientists used physicist Albert Einstein's equations
to show that such stars might really exist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the notion remained a backwater of science-fiction
writing until the 1960s and 1970s. That is when astronomers began
discovering extremely violent, star-like objects _ quasars, for
quasi-stellar objects _ on the edge of the known universe.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, quasars are generally thought to represent torrents of
radiation from matter plunging into giant black holes in galactic
cores.
</P>
<P>
   The closest black hole is the Milky Way, shielded from direct
view by immense interstellar clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers know it is there because their dish-shaped radio
telescopes can see through the clouds. They detect intense
radiation coming from the galactic center. The radiation is X-rays
and gamma rays, lethal to matter plunging into the black hole.
</P>
<P>
   About 33 super-massive black holes have been detected by
Kormendy, his colleagues and other scientific teams, he said at the
Rochester conference.
</P>
<P>
   A super-massive black hole is at least 1 million times the mass
of the sun. Ordinary black holes are mere runts, just a few times
as heavy as the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary black holes could be relics of stars that explode with
their residual matter collapsing under gravitational pull.
</P>
<P>
   But super-massive black holes must have formed ``in a completely
different way. How they originally formed, we don't know,''
Kormendy, 52, said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
