<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7135 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CONTACT-YATES-TEX     06-07 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTACT-YATES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS NATIVE A TONY-NOMINATED KNOCKOUT IN `CONTACT'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She doesn't sing. Doesn't utter a word, in fact. Her character
doesn't even have a name.
</P>
<P>
   And she's the biggest thing on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Yates, a Texas native and honors graduate of Southern
Methodist University in Dallas, is the Girl in the Yellow Dress in
``Contact,'' the acclaimed ``dance-play'' that won Best Musical at
the Tony Awards on Sunday. Yates herself was nominated, a fact
she's still coming to terms with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could say it's a dream come true,'' she said. ``But it's not
even that, because I never even allowed myself to dream about
getting a Tony nomination. I already feel like I've won.''
</P>
<P>
   The twentysomething dancer _ ``Dancers never give their age,''
she demurs _ didn't win for Best Featured Actress in a Musical
(co-star Karen Ziemba took home the Tony in the category), but the
show swept most of the top awards, including Best Choreography for
director Susan Stroman and Best Featured Actor in a Musical for
Boyd Gaines, to go along with the Best Musical prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact'' is three stories dealing with relationships, told
through dance, with no dialogue. In the third piece, in which Yates
appears, an advertising executive who seems to have it all wanders
into a swing club, where he sees The Girl in the Yellow Dress on
the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   As men dance with her, the exec decides he must meet her, but
then he discovers there's one thing he doesn't have in his life:
rhythym. ``She represents his salvation,'' Yates says. ``She's the
lioness of the den, she's in control.''
</P>
<P>
   The show has taken the Great White Way by storm, but
traditionalists, as well as the musicians' union, felt ``Contact''
shouldn't have been nominated for Best Musical because the
``dance-play'' has no original music, live orchestra or singing.
The debate about what constitutes a musical has been brewing since
last year, when the dance revue ``Fosse'' took home Best Musical.
There has even been talk of creating a new category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's certainly one solution,'' Yates says. ``But I
think they're perhaps being just a bit rigid about what a musical
actually is. An art form always evolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the experience of `Contact' is very much a musical
theater experience. The three pieces have three distinct
narratives. No, it's not an original score, but the music is
absolutely essential to what is going on. And the dance is, as
well. If you had a show that had all singing and very little
staging or dancing, people would have no qualms calling that a
musical. But when the situation is reversed, and there's not
singing, people won't call it a musical.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether people want to call her show a musical or not, one
thing's for sure: Yates' life has changed dramatically since she
took on the role of The Girl in the Yellow Dress. The nomination,
she says, was just the icing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part of being a nominee is that you meet all the
other nominees, the creme de la creme of Broadway,'' she says
excitedly. I met ``legendary performers: Eartha Kitt, Rosemary
Harris, Gabriel Byrne, Derek Jacobi.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not be long before other young actors are saying the
same about Yates.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Dallas, but her family moved to the small East
Texas town of Jacksonsville, about 30 minutes south of Tyler, when
she was very young. There, she participated in gymnastics and
studied ballet and tap.
</P>
<P>
   Always an excellent scholar (she qualifies for Mensa), she was
an honor student through high school and college, although her
heart was not in the classroom but onstage. Her major at SMU was
radio/TV, but she never let dance out of her sight. After
graduation, she knew what she had to do.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Chicago, but her first regular professional
performing gig wasn't in the Windy City but on the open seas _ as a
dancer on Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines. After six months, she got
herself back on dry land and immediately headed to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Her family ``thought I was a bit nuts at first,'' she says.
``Nobody in my family is in show business and didn't know anything
about it. Now they're very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   With her long legs and indefatigable athleticism, she quickly
landed a high-profile job in the Big Apple, as a Rockette at Radio
City Music Hall. ``It's a privilege to be a part of them,'' she
says of the famous dancing group. ``There's an incredible tradition
to them. Generations have come to see their Christmas
spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   When she wasn't high-kicking at Radio City, she was auditioning
for shows and doing temp work to make ends meet. She appeared in
the short-lived Broadway show ``Dreams'' and in several productions
in the City Center's Encore Series.
</P>
<P>
   In autumn '98 she heard about a new kind of dance show and
secured an audition. She was hired and started workshops in January
'99. By August, ``Contact'' was in full rehearsals, although no one
knew whether anything would come of it. The show opened
off-Broadway in September and quickly garnered rave reviews. In
March, it moved to Broadway, where the raves _ especially for Yates
_ intensified.
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Times review, theater critic Ben Brantley said,
``Ms. Yates has the daunting assignment of incarnating the woman
whom every man wants, and remarkably, that is exactly how she comes
across. She's not only dangerously beautiful, suggesting a
razor-edged Grace Kelly; she also has an exquisite balletic poise
and extensions to die for. She can act, too, projecting the
requisite fire of wistfulness beneath the icy exterior. A pinup
girl for straight men in a New York musical: Who would have thought
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Stroman, for one, says she knew her show was going to make Yates
a Broadway star. Yates has nothing but praise for her
choreographer, comparing her to the theater's dance greats.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the tradition of Jerome Robbins and Bob Fosse,'' Yates says
of Stroman's choreography, ``it is the movement itself that is
telling the story, versus using a song or a scene and then doing a
production number. You don't have to separate the two with her.
It's always completely logical. I think she's very creative. One of
her greatest strengths is that she casts people very well, and
allows them to do what they do. She allows them to bring their
creativity to the role.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lowry reports on cultural affairs for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7747, or e-mail:
markl(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
