<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7144 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MILITARY-ARTIFACTS-HN     06-07 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-ARTIFACTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MISMANAGEMENT BLAMED FOR MISSING WAR RELICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENDAN LYONS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERVLIET, N.Y. _ Hundreds of valuable military artifacts have
disappeared from armories and small museums in New York following
decades of mismanagement and shoddy bookkeeping at these
facilities, which collectively contain one of the nation's most
prestigious wartime collections.
</P>
<P>
   The state Division of Military and Naval Affairs, operating out
of the Watervliet Arsenal, has launched an intensive project to
recover the missing artifacts, which are being meticulously
cataloged and stored in two giant brick warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had ever done anything effective about this,'' said
Col. R.H. von Hasseln, history director for the Division of
Military and Naval Affairs. ``It was not properly inventoried and
not properly protected.''
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts, many of which have real historical significance,
have been targeted by professional thieves or misplaced over
decades, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, collectibles have been tracked to former armory
employees and even the offices of state legislators, investigators
say, though they declined to identify the lawmakers. Often, an item
will mysteriously reappear after investigators begin making
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery effort began five years ago and is relying heavily
on State Police investigators to help track down dozens of stolen
and missing items. Some have been found being offered for sale on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Division of Military and Naval Affairs is
responsible for oversight of the estimated 300,000 pieces of
military memorabilia that are kept primarily at armories statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items date back to the 1600s. The collections
include the uniform of the first soldier killed in the Civil War _
complete with the hole from the bullet that felled him _ to
documents signed by George Washington. There are machine guns,
howitzers, Civil War flags with cannonball holes in them, sterling
silver plaques, swords and thousands of other wartime memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Many items were stolen or misplaced so long ago that police
officers tracing their trail have found themselves interviewing
residents of nursing homes and reading obituaries in search of
leads.
</P>
<P>
   There are 65 state armories. Many of the armories served both as
recruiting offices during wartime and local museums for military
artifacts that were meaningful to their communities, historians
said. Historically, regiments and other units often were raised
locally and came back with war booty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened with the closing down of many of these
facilities is it took an already bad situation and made it worse by
forcing more and more artifacts into the hands of administrators
who had to make a decision about what to do with them,'' said
Assemblyman Jack McEneny, D-Albany, who is the former Albany County
historian.
</P>
<P>
   When the inventory effort began, state historians found
priceless artifacts stuffed in the attics, basements and even
closed-down bathrooms of some armories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in parts of buildings that most people never knew
existed,'' said Michael Aikey, a librarian and archivist for the
New York State Military Museum. ``The first door I walked into was
the Schenectady Armory. By the time I walked out the next day, they
knew (at armories) in Buffalo that something was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikey and others involved in the project say it was not unusual
to find that a former caretaker had given away items, sometimes to
local veterans groups that would hang them in private lodges like
trophies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found one field piece (a Civil War cannon) missing out of
Rochester that was in somebody's garage,'' said State Police Capt.
John Byrne, a Civil War buff who is helping lead the recovery
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The value of memorabilia from that conflict has skyrocketed in
recent years, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such a market in military hardware that people don't
realize how much some of this stuff is worth,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has been arrested in connection with the recovery
of an artifact, primarily because the new owner usually doesn't
know it was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the State Police found a silver plaque offered for
sale on the Internet auction site eBay.
</P>
<P>
   On June 2, 1898, the plaque had been given by the Sons of the
Revolution to an infantry regiment that had fought in the
Spanish-American War. The small sterling silver plaque apparently
had been taken off a memorial flagpole in New York City years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The police did not charge the Long Island man who was willing to
sell it for $275 _ the bid made by undercover investigators. The
man quickly turned it over to investigators when he was informed
that it was state property, Byrne said. The plaque had changed
hands so many times among antiques dealers that investigators gave
up trying to find who stole it.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, State Police have been visiting gun shows
around the state looking for pilfered antique weapons. With the
assistance of military historians, investigators also have entered
the serial numbers of missing guns in a nationwide police computer
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain investigators throughout the state who love
to do this,'' Byrne said. ``They're history buffs, and these cases
are worked on when we can get to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the thefts have been spread over decades, but Byrne said
that as recently as two months ago thieves raided a monument in a
Columbia County cemetery and made off with a pair of World War II
machine guns. They had been welded to the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a subculture. You can't believe the underground in
artifacts,'' Byrne said. ``What's really hot right now is Civil War
items ... and there's a lot of that stuff missing out of the
armories.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of artifacts were discovered missing when the state
inventoried much of the collection in 1959 at the New York State
Military Museum. The work was done as part of the state's effort to
refurbish the museum before it reopened its doors to the public in
the east lobby of the Capitol in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was decimated 25 years ago when professional
burglars pulled off what historians consider the single largest
theft of state war memorabilia in history.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 5, 1975, thieves struck the museum's storage warehouse
and made off with more than 20 ``presentation swords,'' most of
which were captured from Confederate officers during the Civil War.
Even 25 years later, the whereabouts of the swords, each valued at
tens of thousands of dollars, is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (burglary) was investigated when it happened, but we still
go around to these gun shows looking for these swords,'' Byrne
said. ``We believe it was people who knew what they were after and
knew how valuable some of these pieces were. It was a major hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The success stories among the artifacts that have been recovered
so far include the dress uniform of Capt. George W. Yates. The 7th
Calvary officer died June 25, 1876, next to a river in southeast
Montana at the Battle of Little Big Horn _ Custer's Last Stand.
</P>
<P>
   Several decades ago _ no one exactly knows when _ the uniform
was loaned by New York officials to a Civil War museum at Fort
Knox. But there was no written record about the loan, so New York
officials were relieved when the Kentucky museum returned the
uniform, which is valued at $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to make some great recoveries,'' von Hasseln
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
