 CHRON  
 Editors note: Psst! Read the latest? If not, you haven't
read  HotStuff, the San Francisco Chronicle's weekly roundup of
great 
 new home-and-garden items and places to visit.   HOT STUFF: Smiles of Delight  
   
 By Chronicle Staff Writers  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 Tap Into the Fun of Wooden Toys  
   
 SAN RAFAEL, Calif. _  There's something about wooden toys that
sparks the imagination. Solid to the touch, sturdy and bright, they
stand up to boisterous play. Now, a San Rafael company _
 allwoodtoys.com  _ makes it easy to find a variety of high-quality
wooden toys from woodworkers in Vermont, New York, the Bay Area and
elsewhere.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Company owner is Tex Dunlap, dad to 4-year-old Colin. Wooden
toys, Dunlap explains, allow kids to play in a way that today's
video games can't. ``It adds more creative play,'' he says.
``That's what you want, to get the child to interact with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's dollhouse selection includes the pictured
Hollyhock House (above, 22x22x11 inches, $100), made by the Reprint
Mint in Oakland and imprinted with climbing vines and patterned
wallpaper. Make it homelike with wooden furniture sets ($15-$22)
and dolls with solid wood heads, bendable bodies and fabric
clothing ($10 each, $30 for family of four, available in various
ethnicities).
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Blocks abound, like some with colorful Plexiglass insets
(14-piece set, $50); tree-branch-shaped blocks ($40-$45); and
pieces that form skyscrapers, a barnyard setting or a castle.
Wooden trains are ready to roll; wooden puzzles and games await
rainy afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Little hands can grab onto friendly wooden critters or clowns
($14-$22), shake wooden rattles ($6-$8), push a chunky car ($10),
or pull a colorful, stackable Convoy ($34).
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap takes care to select toys from manufacturers who adhere
to child-safe standards, and he's carved out a niche with durable
toys that let kids turn off the TV and really &LR;  play &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best tester, obviously,'' he notes, ``is our son.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; To place an order or request a catalog, visit &LR;  allwoodtoys.com
 &LR; online or call (888) 655-9663. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Beth Bourland, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Gardening Specialty Store Branches Out &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ST. HELENA, Calif. _ &LR;  Given Napa Valley's climate, so conducive to
life outdoors, it's not surprising that the owner of
Berkeley's &UR; Gardenhome  &LR; sensed opportunity in wine country. What
might surprise Charles Cross's Berkeley customers, however, is the
scale of his new venture. Opened in late May on the south end of
St. Helena's busy Main Street, the second Gardenhome is three times
the size of its Fourth Street sister and designed to make a bold
retailing statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the store the whole country is talking about,''
says Cross, whose 10,000-square-foot emporium is merchandised
around the idea of erasing the boundary between house and garden.
In a former prune dehydrating plant, later a Dansk outlet, Cross
and his team have created an inviting series of open rooms
displaying plants, china, glassware, furniture, tabletop
accessories, floating candles, candelabras, soaps, lotions and
vases.
</P>
<P>
   To showcase their outdoor furniture, fountains and pots, they
installed a flagstone courtyard with mature olive trees and locally
made iron gates.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the vast, skylighted building, shoppers can wander from
``room'' to ``room,'' perusing fabric choices for upholstered
furnishings in a design corner, choosing an orchid and having it
potted up into a handsome container (Cross is the former president
of the Rod McClellan Co., a Bay Area-based orchid company) or
sniffing their way through a huge selection of scented soaps.
</P>
<P>
   Buyer Martin Spector, formerly with Gump's, has sought out
dinnerware from France and Italy made exclusively for the store,
painted pine furniture from Belgium and high-quality Indonesian
teak outdoor furniture. Reflecting Cross's roots in northern
England, the store also sells custom British conservatories and has
a fully furnished one on display.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Gardenhome, 801 Main St. (Highway 29), St. Helena; (707) &LR; 
 &LR; 967-4800. Open 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday through Thursday; 10 &LR; 
 &LR; a.m.-7 p.m. Friday and Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Janet Fletcher, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Throw Some Pizzas on the Barbie &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; First came the commercial-style home kitchen. This
summer the patio goes high end with high-quality,
professional-style barbecues.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't your father's cookers. These heavy-duty gas grills
come with brushed stainless steel finishes and promises of adding
panache to picnics.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Jenn-Air Pro-Style &LR;  outdoor grill offers two 25,000 BTU
burners _ enough to heat a house, though not recommended for such
use, parent company Maytag says. The burners, guaranteed to last a
lifetime or until barbecues go out of style, are nestled in a
30-inch-wide cart with 554 square inches of grilling space,
fold-down side trays and a closed storage cabinet underneath.
</P>
<P>
   The grill's suggested price is $1,499, plus a rotisserie
accessory for $199 and an optional grill cover for $99.
</P>
<P>
   Throw a few pizzas and streudels on the grill with &UR; Kenmore's &LR; 
 &UR; Elite  &LR; series _ the three models come with instructions for baking,
deep frying, simmering and stir-frying. Each includes a high lid to
accommodate roasting and baking, and each has a warming rack.
</P>
<P>
   Some specs: Elite 9904 Graphite grill, 555-square-inch cooking
area and four burners, $550; Elite 9904 Stainless Steel grill
(pictured at direction), adds a side burner, $750; Elite 9906
Graphite &AMP; Stainless Steel grill, six burners and 815-square-inch
cooking area, $980.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Jenn-Air Pro-Style grills are available at selected dealers; &LR; 
 &LR; for information, call (800) 536-6247 or visit  &LR; www.jennair.com.
 &LR; Kenmore Elite grills are sold at Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.; find the &LR; 
 &LR; nearest store by calling (888) 536-6673 or visiting &LR; 
www.sears.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Holly Ocasio Rizzo, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
