<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7158 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NYSE-GLOBAL-STREET &LR;      06-07 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYSE-GLOBAL-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYSE IN TALKS TO FORM GLOBAL STOCK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM ARANGO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talks are under way between the New York Stock Exchange and
seven other exchanges in Europe, Asia and the Americas to form a
global stock market that would allow investors to trade around the
clock, officials of the exchanges announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance would involve the Big Board; Euronext, a merger of
exchanges in Paris, Amsterdam and Brussels; the Tokyo Stock
Exchange; the Hong Kong exchange; and exchanges in Australia,
Toronto, Mexico and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The global market would focus on the world's largest companies
and have a stock market capitalization of close to $20 trillion, or
60 percent of the world's total market capitalization, according to
the Toronto Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic trading systems of the partners in the so-called
Global Equity Market would be linked, with the aim of reducing the
costs of cross-border stock trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement will strengthen and globalize our markets within
North America as well as between time zones,'' Richard Grasso,
chairman and chief executive of the New York Stock Exchange, said
in a statement. ``It is an ambitious and exciting challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The details will be worked out in the coming months, after the
officials at the exchanges consult with regulators in their
respective countries. No significant regulatory hurdles are
expected, a representative of the Amsterdam Stock Exchange said,
since the deal is an alliance rather than an outright merger.
</P>
<P>
   Stock exchanges across the globe are seeking out mergers and
alliances to cut costs and survive in the face of an increasingly
borderless world for capital flows. Europe has taken the lead,
driven by its common currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have the same currency, it doesn't make sense to have
fragmented markets,'' said Bruno Rossignol, a spokesman for the
Paris Stock Exchange. ``This is answering the needs of investors.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the exchanges in Paris, Amsterdam and Brussels
announced they would merge to form Euronext to rival a planned
union between the London Stock Exchange and the Frankfurt Stock
Exchange. Meanwhile, the Nasdaq market has formed joint ventures
with London and Frankfurt to trade European and American technology
stocks. And Nasdaq Japan is set to begin later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nasdaq has had an international strategy for a while,''
Rossignol said. The New York Stock Exchange, meanwhile, as the
world's largest exchange, has been reluctant to develop a global
strategy. ``They are the No. 1 exchange in the world, and you're
not necessarily aware that others want to compete and take your
business.''
</P>
<P>
   But as stock trading goes global, ``it is normal for the NYSE to
begin to realize that it isn't just a U.S.-based exchange,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board began bilateral talks earlier this year with
exchanges around the world, but a deal involving seven exchanges
from all corners of the globe marks the most ambitious plan yet,
Rossignol said.
</P>
<P>
   The venture is on the agenda of the European Federation of Stock
Exchanges, which is to begin meeting Wednesday night in Lucerne,
Switzerland. A solid roadmap of how the seven exchanges will
proceed is expected by the fall, but trading is not expected to
begin until next year.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
