<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AIRLINE-MERGER-STREET     06-07 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-MERGER-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIRWAYS, KLM CONFIRM MERGER TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, prices in last graf do not reflect market close)  
 By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consolidation for the airline industry is rife with
possibilities on both sides of the Atlantic, if Wednesday's news is
any indication.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways (BAB:NYSE ADR) and KLM Royal Dutch Airlines
(KLM:NYSE) confirmed Wednesday that they are in merger discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions were first reported in Monday's edition of The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are in a ``preliminary'' stage, with ``no assurance
that they will result in any transaction between the parties,'' the
companies said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the U.S., spurred on by a $4.3 billion agreement
for UAL's (UAL:NYSE) United Airlines, the largest airline in the
world, to buy US Airways Group (U:NYSE) last month, the second- and
third-largest airlines in the U.S. reportedly held talks which may
well lead to a merger
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 American Airlines, owned by AMR (AMR:NYSE), and No. 3
Delta Air Lines (DAL:NYSE) held preliminary talks on industry
consolidation on Monday in New York, according to Wednesday's
edition of The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Together, United and US Airways would control over 27 percent of
the U.S. market. Currently, the three largest airlines -- United,
American and Delta -- hold relatively equal market shares of 17
percent to 20 percent, while No. 4 Northwest Airlines
(NWAC:Nasdaq), No. 5 Continental Airlines (CAL:NYSE) and No. 6 US
Airways collectively control just under 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller airlines such as Southwest Airlines (LUV:NYSE), America
West Holdings' (AWA:NYSE) America West Airlines, Trans World
Airlines (TWA:Amex) and Alaska Air Group's (ALK:NYSE) Alaska
Airlines together have a share just under 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of a combined United/US Airways naturally concerns
United's rivals, like American, based in Fort Worth, Texas, and
Atlanta-based Delta, who are exploring ways to compete more
effectively against a much larger No. 1 airline. One of those ways
could be to merge, though U.S. regulators could well stymie a
second massive consolidation in the airline industry, should they
approve the first between United and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice has been historically tough on the
airline industry. ``In the past the DOJ seems to have seen more
that they dislike about competitive activity (or lack thereof) in
the airline industry than they like,'' wrote Samuel Buttrick, an
analyst at PaineWebber. The DOJ has now been ceded antitrust
authority over airline mergers from the Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the DOJ's objections in the mid-1980s to the mergers of
TWA with Ozark Airlines and Northwest with Republic Airlines. In
the early 1990s, the DOJ also came out against Eastern Airlines'
proposed sale of takeoff/landing slots and gates in Washington,
D.C. to United. More recently, the department has challenged
American on predatory pricing and Northwest on its ownership of a
controlling stake in Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Buttrick also addressed the chances of approval of a United/US
Airways merger, Northwest's stake in Continental and an additional
merger like one between American and Delta. ``Approval of three
mega-mergers without astounding remedies would amount to a total
abrogation of professional responsibilities by the DOJ -- pretty
inconceivable,'' Buttrick wrote. He rates UAL an attractive and US
Airways a neutral and has a buy rating on both AMR and Delta. His
firm has done no recent underwriting for any of these companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are other merger possibilities out there.
Indeed, American is also said to be mulling an acquisition of
Northwest, while Continental could also be a strong partner.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for AMR, Dale Morris, said, ``As a matter of policy,
we do not comment on rumors or speculation.'' A call to Delta for
comment was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMR rose 1/8 to 28 7/16 in Wednesday morning trading,
while shares of Delta were up 1 7/32, or 2 percent, to 52.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of British Airways dropped 15/16 or 2 percent to 58 5/8,
while shares of KLM rose 2 1/2, or 9 percent, to 29.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
