<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MP3COM-WARNER-STREET &LR;      06-07 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3COM-WARNER-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MP3.COM, WARNER MUSIC REPORTEDLY NEAR SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, prices in last two grafs do not reflect market close)  
 By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet music company MP3.com (MPPP:Nasdaq) is said to be close
to settling a copyright infringement suit with Time Warner's
(TWX:NYSE) Warner Music Group.
</P>
<P>
   MP3, which distributes music over the Web through a digital
format, is expected to pay between $15 million and $20 million to
New York-based Warner Music to settle the claims of copyright
infringement, according to Wednesday's edition of The Wall Street
Journal. The terms may be announced as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a plan for San Diego-based MP3 to license music
from Warner Music.
</P>
<P>
   The music industry sued MP3 after the company made computerized
copies of more than 40,000 CDs without permission. MP3 was found
liable for copyright infringement on April 30. On that day, MP3's
stock tumbled 40 percent to 7.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to MP3 and Time Warner for comment were not immediately
returned.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's shares have since rebounded in hopes of a
settlement, closing Tuesday trading at 11 5/8, up 1/16, or 1
percent. Shares of Time Warner closed Tuesday trading at 81 1/8,
down 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MP3 also rose 12 percent, or 1 3/8, to 13 in Wednesday
pre-market trading, according to Island ECN.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
