<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7168 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-HOLOCAUST-PAPERS-TEX     06-07 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-PAPERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHIVES TELL STORY OF GERMAN WHO HID JEW FROM NAZIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Lilli Wolff and Mati Driessen rarely spoke of
their remarkable past. A few close friends and relatives knew; most
others never questioned how the two German women, living in Dallas,
had come to be like sisters. They worked together, lived together
and reared Mati's son, Klaus, together.
</P>
<P>
   It was only in their later years, and then after their deaths,
that Lilli and Mati's story came to the attention of a wider
audience, was recognized for its magnitude and has, more recently,
found its official place in history.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, Arlington educator Klaus Driessen donated 121
original documents, including photographs and letters, to the U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington. The papers once belonged
to Lilli, a German Jew who escaped the Nazi genocide.
</P>
<P>
   She had Mati to thank for her life.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Driessen, 51, has told his mother and Lilli's story many
times in the past decade _ to school groups, at Rotary club
meetings, in synagogues. In 1991, he traveled to Yad Vashem, the
Holocaust memorial in Jerusalem, to see his mother's name unveiled
in the Garden of the Righteous Among Nations. Mati had died a year
earlier, but she is permanently remembered as one of the thousands
of gentiles who saved Jews from Hitler's Final Solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nicest part is that my mother is listed,'' Driessen says.
``It took a lot of courage for her to save just one.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1940 to 1945, Mati hid Lilli in a Vienna apartment, out of
Hitler's murderous reach. At the slightest threat of discovery,
Lilli would take refuge in an armoire with a false lining. To peek
out the window or to leave two dirty dishes in the sink might have
given her away. Mati would certainly have perished at the hands of
the Nazis, too.
</P>
<P>
   The women had met in Cologne before World War II. Both were in a
dressmaking school and opened a business together. They designed
theater costumes and eventually employed 40 women in one of
Cologne's main retail districts. They prospered.
</P>
<P>
   But growing German anti-Semitism would not allow it. During
Kristallnacht, the night in November 1938 when Nazis plundered and
burned Jewish storefronts and synagogues, Lilli and Mati's
employees sat in the staircase that led to the shop and blocked the
Nazis' entry. The women succeeded that evening, but intensifying
restrictions on Jews soon forced them to close the business.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Lilli's parents had been sent to a work camp in
Berlin. The correspondence between Lilli and her father during that
time makes up much of the papers saved by Klaus Driessen and now
archived in Washington. On Nov. 10, 1940, Richard Wolff wrote to
his family, describing life in the Jewish ghetto in Berlin:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our room is small but we at least have heat. There are so many
changes we have no control over, we should be happy to just have a
roof over our heads ...''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Wolff was 70 years old. Soon after he wrote that letter,
he and his wife died of starvation. Only one of Lilli's six
siblings would survive the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, Lilli moved to Vienna and into the city's Jewish
ghetto. Mati followed, setting up a dress shop in her apartment.
``There was no work in Germany for a dress designer who had tried
to protect a Jew,'' Driessen says of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the movement of Jews around the city and the jobs
they could hold were severely limited. Beyond the confines of the
ghetto, Jews had to walk in the gutter. They could not take public
transportation. They were required to wear a Star of David on their
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Mati and Lilli worked out a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving the ghetto each day, Lilli would wear her Jewish
star prominently on her scarf. Several blocks later, she would
subtly button the scarf a different way, so that the star was not
visible. She made her way to Mati's and the two sewed all day.
Lilli would be back in the ghetto by curfew.
</P>
<P>
   But each day when she returned, another block of the ghetto
would be empty, the Jews who had been there that morning gone. To
where exactly, Lilli was unsure, but she knew she did not want to
go there. One night, instead of returning to the ghetto, she stayed
at Mati's. It would be 4 1/2 years before she could walk the
streets freely.
</P>
<P>
   She left the apartment twice. Once, Mati acquired false papers
for Lilli and arranged for her to have stomach surgery at a local
hospital. The doctor and nurses knew Lilli was a Jew. Anyone could
have given her away. They kept silent.
</P>
<P>
   The second time, Lilli wanted only to steal a few moments in the
park on a beautiful spring day. She narrowly escaped an encounter
with a German officer who asked for her identity papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians liberated Vienna in 1945, and two years later Lilli
was in New York City. Her sister Alice, who had fled to the United
States in 1937, had sponsored Lilli's immigration. Ten years later,
Lilli helped bring Mati and her 8-year-old son, Klaus, to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the two women opened a dressmaking business. They
struggled financially although their dresses were popular with the
city's debutantes and society women, such as Mrs. Trammell Crow and
Mrs. H.L. Hunt. But for the longest time, the only furniture the
two women owned were two sofas.
</P>
<P>
   Lilli died in 1983 at age 86; Mati was 80 when she died in 1990.
Since then, Mati's name has been added to the list of Righteous
Among Nations at the Holocaust museums in Dallas and Washington,
D.C. Driessen donated his mother's Yad Vashem medallion to the
Dallas museum and has spoken there to teacher groups and museum
docents.
</P>
<P>
   He is determined to keep his mother's and Lilli's experiences
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remember what happened during World War II and
continue to tell the story of the Holocaust,'' he says. ``The past
... can be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
