u f BC-B2B-STREET &LR;      06-07 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B2B-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM, NORTEL, TOSHIBA, OTHERS TO START TECH B2B MARKETPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUSTIN DINI   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM(IBM:NYSE), Nortel Networks(NT:NYSE), Toshiba and several
other big global technology players said Wednesday that they would
create a business-to-business marketplace for the computer,
electronics and telecommunications businesses, joining a movement
that has already attracted a number of big industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture, dubbed e2open.com, has raised more than $200
million in financing from a group of partners that includes Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter(MWD:NYSE) and the consulting firm McKinsey &AMP;
Co.. Software companies Ariba (ARBA:Nasdaq) and i2 (ITWO:Nasdaq)
are providing technology assistance for the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   The venture will provide an online marketplace for member
companies and their customers to buy and sell components used in
consumer electronics, computers and telecom equipment. The
companies said they expect e2open.com to begin operations by
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   The other partners in the venture are Japan's Matsushita
Electric Industrial Co. and Hitachi Ltd.(HIT:NYSE), South Korea's
LG Electronics Inc., U.S. electronics parts manufacturer Solectron
(SLR:NYSE) and U.S. hard-disc maker Seagate Technology (SEG:NYSE).
</P>
<P>
   The venture expects transactions worth at least $1 billion on
its virtual marketplace during the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement is only the latest in a series of B2B
marketplaces rolled out recently. In February, the Big Three
automakers announced a marketplace for car parts. That same month,
Sears, Roebuck(S:NYSE) and Carrefour of France said they were
working with Oracle(ORCL:Nasdaq) to form an online exchange.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
