<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-SUMMIT-TAX08-COX     06-07 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SUMMIT-TAX08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SECOND TOP TECH EXEC URGES TAXATION OF ONLINE SALES
 &HT;    With TECH-SUMMIT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ High-tech executives and members of Congress who
want to block states from taxing online purchases should end their
``unrealistic'' battle, Carly Fiorina, chief executive of
Hewlett-Packard Co., said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not realistic of our industry to stand and say, 'This
taxation should never be applied to e-commerce,' `` Fiorina said on
the second day of the ``High-Tech Summit'' sponsored by the
congressional Joint Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Fiorina also conceded that the existing sales tax system is
far too complicated to work well on the Internet. Trying to collect
all the taxes now imposed by some 30,000 state and local
jurisdictions would be ``disastrous,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The best course of action is for state and federal lawmakers to
work together to streamline sales taxes, making them uniform enough
to fit ``the borderless nature of the online economy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Congress is considering several bills that would
extend a moratorium on new Internet taxes. Under existing law,
states can require merchants operating within their borders to
collect sales taxes on purchases. But states cannot force retailers
in other states to collect taxes. So an online merchant in one
state can sell goods to residents of the other 49 states without
collecting sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Many state officials fear that as electronic commerce grows,
sales tax losses will grow into the tens of billions of dollars. To
prevent that, the National Governors' Association is coordinating a
drive among states to streamline sales taxes and is asking Congress
to support that approach.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorina applauded such efforts. ``What we are calling for is a
concerted effort to do the heavy lifting and bring our taxation
system into the modern age so that we can tax _ in a fair way _
both online and offline transactions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorina's comments echoed those of Intel Corp. Chairman Andy
Grove, who spoke to the summit Tuesday. Grove said that blocking
states from collecting sales taxes on online purchases would amount
to giving electronic merchants an unfair subsidy. ``As a matter of
public policy, I don't see the justification for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Joint Economic Committee, www.senate.gov/(tilde)jec.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
