<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DOG-TAGS-NYT &LR;      06-07 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DOG-TAGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO-FREQUENCY TAGS COULD PIERCE SOME OF THE FOGS OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANIEL SORID    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The same kinds of tags that let cars move quickly past
tollbooths may soon help the armed forces keep track of their
vehicles, weapons and people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end game of this,'' said Ron Gilbert, a senior scientist
at the Department of Energy's Pacific Northwest National
Laboratory, in Richland, Wash., ``is to tag everybody and
everything and know what it is, what its status is, and know where
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The small rectangular tags respond to radio waves sent by a
special transmitter called an interrogator. This is how it works: A
soldier operating an interrogator sends a radio signal to a tag
placed on an object. A tiny antenna on the tag is stimulated by the
signal and sends information about its identity and location to the
interrogator.
</P>
<P>
   The communicators are called radio-frequency tags, or RF tags.
Bulkier versions have been used for several years to keep track of
tolls or inventory, both by private companies and by the
government. But the new tags are being designed to be as small as a
few inches long and to be capable of handling more information.
</P>
<P>
   The interrogators should be able to find the new tags from as
far away as several hundred feet. From that distance, a helicopter
flying over a storage container could determine exactly what was
inside the unit. The interrogators could also scan several items at
once, allowing them to check an entire case of battlefield
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tags will be able to operate without batteries,
absorbing and recycling energy from an interrogator's signal. These
new tags are expected to have a range of 30 feet, compared with
less than 5 feet for the current tags, Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly larger tags that are equipped with small batteries will
not only have a greater range _ several hundred feet, Gilbert said
_ but will be able to connect to sensors that can monitor
conditions like temperature and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   In one application, the new tags might be programmed to keep an
object like a pair of night vision goggles disabled until they were
scanned. That would deter theft, Gilbert said. ``Unless you're the
right soldier with the right ID code,'' he said, ``we can render
the item useless.''
</P>
<P>
   The new tags are being prepared for field testing by the Navy.
Depending on the outcome of those tests, the tags could be sent
back for changes, approved for use or canceled outright.
</P>
<P>
   Almost any object could be tagged. In a study by the Defense
Department last year, researchers attached tiny tags to honeybees
to determine whether the bees could be tracked. The idea is that
researchers might someday be able to locate things like land mines
by analyzing particles carried back to the hive by each bee and
correlating those particles with where the bee had been that day.
But the tags were too heavy for the bees and are being redesigned.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, radio-frequency tags have been used in
many commercial applications. Railroads, for example, use the tags
to keep track of trains. And on many toll roads and bridges,
vehicles equipped with special radio-frequency tags, like E-ZPass
tags, can move through through tollbooths without stopping. The tag
tells an interrogator at the booth to let the car through without
sounding an alarm.
</P>
<P>
   But as the tags become smaller and able to handle more
information, new uses will be possible. One application being
developed is an radio-frequency dog tag that could replace the
metal identification tags that soldiers wear on chains around their
necks. Medics would be able to read information like the soldier's
name, age, allergies and blood type from the tag. The Department of
Energy laboratory has developed a working prototype and may be
ready to produce the tags for the military within two years,
Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   After treating a wounded soldier on the battlefield, a medic
could send a signal that would inscribe on the dog tag the type of
medical care the soldier has received. When the soldier arrived at
the hospital, Gilbert said, ``they know who he is, what he does,
and what the corpsman did to him in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Navy medics, for example, record information about a
sailor's injury and treatment on a slip of paper, which can be
soiled or misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that many of the interrogator units to be used
with the new tags are the size of toolboxes, Gilbert said. But
Gilbert said his laboratory might try to convert personal digital
assistants for use as radio-frequency interrogators.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert said the laboratory would probably use something like
the Handspring Visor, which has expansion slots that add to the
device's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer First Class Michael Stiney, who is helping to
evaluate the electronic dog tag at the Naval Aerospace Medical
Research Laboratory in Pensacola, Fla., said that a major advantage
of the tag was that information about injuries could be sent from
the medic's interrogator to a central computer, where patterns
could be analyzed. ``If you pick up a certain batch of symptoms in
a certain area of conflict, you could diagnose or predict an
outbreak of a food-borne illness or a chemical attack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
