<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7199 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ASHLEY-GOOSEHEAD-     06-07 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ASHLEY-GOOSEHEAD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND LEMONADE STANDS: A GIRL SEEKS HER FORTUNE ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHEL MARRIOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the small screen _ no, not television's, but the personal
computer's _ Ashley Power is becoming a big star. And yes, that's
her real name.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley, a 15-year-old from Southern California who posts her
experiences, her schoolgirl insights and her Hollywood good looks
on her Web site (www.goosehead.com), is starting to be recognized
these days with a chorus of ``Hey, isn't she that girl on the
Internet?''
</P>
<P>
   She created her site after an especially trying eighth grade,
she said in a recent interview in her Goosehead.com office in
Studio City, Calif., just north of Los Angeles. The site features
message boards oriented toward teen-agers, weekly chats with
Ashley, digital games and music for downloading, free e-mail and a
homework-helper page with links to an online dictionary, a
thesaurus and language translation services.
</P>
<P>
   But the site's breakout hit is ``Whatever,'' an episodic
offering of original comedy, delivered by streaming video with
considerable attitude. Goosehead.com attracts more than 100,000
visitors a day.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about her success, Ashley said: ``This stuff is so amazing
to me. It has so blown my mind that I can't even comprehend it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever'' stars Ashley and is written by her and her
stepfather, Mark Schilder (who is also the director). The
popularity of the 15-minute episodes has attracted the attention of
the actor Richard Dreyfuss, who joined Goosehead.com as a partner
this spring to help create more Web-based shows. (Dreyfuss' brother
is the business partner of Ashley's mother, Michelle Schilder, an
advertising executive.)
</P>
<P>
   Part of what persuaded him to become involved with the site, he
said, was what he described as Ashley's ``purity of vision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are trying to remember their past, or they are
people trying to make money,'' Dreyfuss said in a telephone
interview, talking about some of Goosehead.com's competitors.
``They're certainly not talking to their audience the way Ashley
can connect with hers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley's company is now negotiating with two networks about
spinning off ``Whatever'' into a television show. Without a hint of
self-consciousness, Ashley said she was determined to make
Goosehead.com into a major Web site for teen-agers by emphasizing
``quality over quantity, definitely.'' She also said she had always
wanted to direct.
</P>
<P>
   And while the teen-age Web maven can merrily chat with
laser-sharp clarity about what her site needs to be, Goosehead.com
appears to be the product of two different versions of Ashley
Power. The first is a girl who, like many others, found her voice
online and began sharing it with anyone who would visit her site.
The other is an attractive teen-ager who is the center of a
franchise-in-the-making that is capitalizing on the untested
star-making muscle of the Internet, an electronic emporium where
facts and fantasies are often indistinguishable and sometimes very
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every section of Goosehead.com opens with a page bearing
Ashley's image. One shows a dimple-cheeked girl-next-door, while
another reveals her wearing a tight T-shirt and a pouty expression.
In a soft-focus shot on her Homework page, Ashley is dressed in
what looks like a skirt from a Catholic school with thigh-high
white stockings more reminiscent of Britney Spears than Esther
Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Ashley dealing with her own sexuality, trying to show
another side of herself,'' said her stepfather, who is an artist
and writer who has also shot television commercials. ``We don't
want her to do anything totally funky, but we want her to control
her own image.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley said she didn't understand why anyone would care about
how she looked on her site. Like a typical teen-ager, she said, she
frets about her body _ she wishes that she was thinner, or not so
tall. But even Goosehead.com's new 14-year-old columnist, Stephanie
Joy Pruner, recently wrote about Ashley and the ``sex appeal'' she
displays on the site. ``I'm tired of seeing a million pictures of
Ashley looking like a !(NU)%&AMP;$! supermodel!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley said her site had not started out as a tool to reach the
masses. It was just for herself and her friends, she said, when she
began Goosehead.com in the fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley's mother, Michelle Schilder, said Ashley had always been
independent. Schilder said she was single when she gave birth to
Ashley at the age of 18. She carried her baby daughter from
classroom to classroom as she completed her college education.
Schilder recalled that Ashley would occupy herself in classrooms by
doing creative things with paper and crayons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't really surprise me from a creative point of view
that she would do creative things with her computer,'' said
Schilder, whose company shares office space with Ashley's company.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people her age, Ashley practically grew up with a
mouse in her hand. She has had a succession of Macintosh computers
since she was 8 years old, she said, so she instinctively turned to
the Web as a ready means of expression and communication. At 13 she
began teaching herself from a book how to write HTML files so she
could work on her Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Online, by way of e-mail exchanges, she found fellow computer
geeks, men sometimes three times her age, who eagerly helped her
over snags with getting Goosehead.com off the ground and on the
Web, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today Ashley employs at least a half-dozen of them as partners.
One of them is Pat Galvin, 44, who lives in nearby Valencia, Calif.
``I was just trying to be a nice guy,'' he said, recalling when he
had first begun answering a flood of e-mail questions from Ashley
about building and maintaining Web sites. In the beginning, he
said, he did not realize that Ashley was 14. Nonetheless, he
recognized that she had ``great vision,'' he said. ``She is
extremely sweet,'' he added. ``The smile gets you.''
</P>
<P>
   When her stepfather learned that Ashley had enlisted the help of
men she had met on the Internet, he insisted on finding out who
they were. Ashley said she had given Schilder the men's e-mail
addresses and telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   After talking to each of the men, Schilder said, he was
satisfied that they sincerely wanted to help Ashley, who then had
her site up and was attracting considerable attention among
teen-agers. He organized a meeting last August in Las Vegas, where
all the Webmasters _ some lived as far away as Florida and Ohio,
and each paid his own way _ met to map out a strategy to turn
Goosehead.com into a bona fide online business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you sit down with someone, when you really meet them, you
get a sense of what they are about,'' Schilder said. ``I wanted to
have Ashley talking to everyone in the room. I wanted to see how
they responded to Ashley.''
</P>
<P>
   Goosehead.com was incorporated last November. The site's name
comes from a childhood incident when Ashley accidentally
decapitated a cement goose that decorated the family's front lawn.
Even before Goosehead.com was incorporated, Ashley listed it with
some of the Web's most popular search engines. As a result, it
started getting 40,000 hits a day and tidal waves of e-mail
messages, sometimes thousands in a day.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of months, Ashley's site had propelled her (with the
guidance of her stepfather's business sense) into the hyperspeed
world of the Internet entrepreneur. As the founder and chief
executive of Goosehead.com., she had moved in blazing Internet time
from being a computer geek (with a mother and a stepfather who
quickly recognized the site's enormous potential) to being the soul
of an Internet portal for teen-agers, a business with 31 employees,
22 of them working full time for Goosehead.com.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Along with ``Whatever,'' Goosehead.com's programming includes
installments from Ivan Tell, a roving teen-age reporter who turns
in pithy dispatches as he roams Los Angeles in a 1963 Cadillac
convertible. More shows are in production, Ashley said, like ones
called ``Cornman,'' a mock documentary about a zoologist tracking
down a Bigfoot-like creature, and ``The Janitor,'' which follows a
school custodian who fantasizes about being a superhero.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has really created a clear personality for the site,''
said Jeff Thomas, a marketing team leader at iSyndicate, an online
syndication service based in San Francisco that provides
Goosehead.com with content like its movie page. ``It's really a
kind of unique thing. It feels like there's a real teen-ager in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Production on new episodes of ``Whatever'' began last week. The
mounting workload means that Ashley works on Goosehead.com business
not just because she wants to but also because she has to, she
said. The site generates most of its revenue from corporate
partnerships and advertising, said Schilder, who is co-chairman of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Goosehead.com is also dipping its corporate toe into e-commerce
by selling T-shirts and caps bearing the site's logo, a smiling
cartoon goose face. While the site has yet to make a profit, Ashley
and her family are not discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are spending money faster than we are getting it,''
Schilder said, ``but we are in a position to make money very
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley said her company was securing investment capital, and she
predicted a future for her Web site that would be as bright as a
smog-free California noon.
</P>
<P>
   She knows that much of the responsibility for Goosehead.com's
success rests on her shoulders, she said. As a result, Ashley said,
she occasionally has to miss school to attend an important business
meeting or deliver a speech to an Internet group. Her grades have
suffered, she said, which is something her teachers have prodded
her about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hang in there,'' she said. ``I keep going with what I
feel is right in my heart.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
