<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSPECTING CHIMNEYS, VERY CAREFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring is a good time to inspect your chimney. An early
inspection alerts you to any defects and allows plenty of time to
schedule and perform maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, you will have to climb on the roof to make the
inspection. Climbing onto a high roof can be dangerous, especially
if it has a steep pitch. Wait for a calm, dry day for the
inspection. Wear rubber-soled shoes; do not attempt to climb on a
wet roof. Make sure that you understand, and follow, all ladder
safety rules.
</P>
<P>
   When moving about on the roof, watch for loose or torn shingles,
moss, wet leaves or debris. If you are unsure of yourself on a high
roof, call a professional to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Start at the top of the chimney with the crown. The crown is the
masonry cap that covers and protects the rest of the chimney. If it
is cracked or broken, rainwater will seep into the core holes of
the brick. The thaw-freeze cycle that occurs during the winter
months will cause the water to expand and eventually split the
chimney apart. A professional contractor should replace a cracked
or damaged crown.
</P>
<P>
   Also inspect the gap between the cap and flue. If there is a
wide gap, it should be caulked to prevent water seepage. Use
concrete caulk for this. It is available in cartridges at home
centers.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to apply the caulk; simply insert the cartridge in a
caulking gun and draw a bead around the flue. Smoothing the bead
may be a little difficult because the caulk is very sticky. You can
smooth it by dragging an ice cube across the surface of the bead.
</P>
<P>
   Look carefully at the bricks and mortar in the chimney for
cracks and crumbling brick or mortar. Mortar that is cracked or
deteriorating should be chiseled out and replaced. This repair
technique is called repointing, or tuckpointing.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to repoint, you will need a few tools: a cold
chisel (it should be narrower than the mortar joint), a two-pound
sledgehammer, a mason's trowel (for mixing and holding mortar), a
pointing tool (for pushing the mortar into the joint), a jointing
tool (for shaping the contour of the joint) and a stiff-bristle
brush to remove residual mortar. You'll also need the proper safety
gear: safety goggles for your eyes, heavy-duty gloves for your
hands and work shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'll need new mortar. You can make this by mixing
type N masonry cement and masonry sand (do not use beach sand).
There are different types of masonry cement (designated by the
letters M, S, N and O, indicating the varying proportions of their
ingredients) but type N is a good, all-purpose mix. The sand is an
aggregate that softens the mortar and allows it to expand and
contract with the surrounding bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Start by chiseling out the deteriorated mortar from between the
bricks to a depth of about two and a half times the width of the
joint. Work carefully to remove the old mortar without damaging the
surrounding brick.
</P>
<P>
   After you've chiseled out all the old mortar, wash the joints by
brushing them with the stiff-bristled brush dipped in water. Next,
mix the mortar ingredients with the trowel; it's best to do this on
the ground and carry the mix to the roof in a small bucket. Mix
three parts sand to one part masonry cement and mix only as much as
you can work with in about 30 minutes. Dry-mix these ingredients
first before adding water. Add water slowly until the mix has the
consistency of a stiff paste.
</P>
<P>
   Position a ball of mortar on the bottom of the trowel. Use the
pointing tool to push it from the trowel into the joint. Allow the
mortar to harden slightly, then shape the contour by running the
joint tool along the joint. Shape the vertical joints first, then
the horizontal ones. Use the stiff-bristled brush to remove excess
mortar.
</P>
<P>
   After you have repointed the brick, allow time for the mortar to
dry, then seal the entire chimney by brushing the surfaces with a
sealant.
</P>
<P>
   A good chimney sealant is a water-repellent called siloxane (one
brand is called Sure Klean and is available from building
suppliers); it repels water but allows chimney gases to escape
through the masonry. Siloxane is combustible, so read the package
directions carefully first. Turn off all gas appliances and
extinguish open flames before treating the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   You should also install a chimney cover if your chimney doesn't
have one. Chimney covers keep out water that could rust the damper
and metal flue liner. They also keep birds and small animals from
nesting in your chimney.
</P>
<P>
   To find a dealer, look in the Yellow Pages under ''Chimney
Materials.'' Be sure to measure the furnace flue and flue liner
before ordering the cover.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
