<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OTTER-THEFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ZOO OFFERS REWARD FOR MISSING OTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Whoever stole Harriet the river otter from the
Oakland Zoo in the dead of night will not get the cuddly, playful
creature they might have expected, assistant zoo director Allison
Lindquist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has really sharp claws and she bites. They don't make good
pets,'' Lindquist said of the 15-year-old American River Otter
nabbed from its exhibit early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials said thieves apparently jumped two fences, cut
through a third and broke a lock to grab Harriet and spirit her
away in a tan, kennel-type carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo keepers found the damage while doing 8 a.m. rounds at the
facility, which is home to more than 380 exotic and native animals.
</P>
<P>
   Lindquist pleaded for a safe and speedy return, saying the
animal could die without professional care and precise dieting,
including vitamin supplements required to treat a metabolic
ailment.
</P>
<P>
   The otter's offspring, which remains at the zoo and is not yet 1
year old, is also in danger without the care, instruction and
nursing of its mother, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A $5,000 reward for the return of the otter is being offered.
</P>
<P>
   Harriet came to Oakland from a Minnesota zoo in 1987 and hooked
up in an exhibit with a male otter named Ozzie. Handlers had been
trying to mate the two for almost a decade before finally finding
success last year.
</P>
<P>
   Harriet weighs about 20 pounds and is 2 1/2 feet in length.
American River Otters eat fish, frogs, turtles and rodents, among
other small creatures, and spend about one-third of their time in
water.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact the Oakland Zoo at 510-632-9525.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
