<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7207 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GINGRICH-HNS &LR;      06-07 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GINGRICH HAS A NEW ROLE: FUTURIST
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ He was the second most powerful politician in
America, the combative, high-profile speaker of the House whose
name was synonymous with militant conservatism, and he left
Congress under a cloud. But Newt Gingrich, his confidence and
ambition unimpaired, is still on a mission, and he's thinking big.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is now a scholar at Stanford University's Hoover
Institution, a political analyst for Fox News and founder of the
Committee for New American Leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Author of the watershed ``Contract With America,'' the statement
of principles that House Republicans ran on in 1994, leader of the
104th Congress during the fight for a balanced budget and welfare
overhaul, and Time magazine's man of the year in 1995, Gingrich has
morphed himself into a futurist.
</P>
<P>
   America is caught up in ``a very long wave of change'' fraught
with promise and challenge, which is gaining great speed, he said
in a speech here this week.
</P>
<P>
   Changes based on a combination of biology, information and
nanoscience (the science of objects from one to 400 atoms in size)
figure to be even more transforming than those brought on by the
computer revolution, Gingrich said. ``They will be to the 21st
century more than the computer was to the 20th century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes will be driven to a great degree by a growing
network of venture capitalists who are creating an efficient system
for nurturing entrepreneurs and moving new ideas to the market
rapidly. ``We are creating a culture of entrepreneurship unlike
anything the world has ever seen,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   To sustain the momentum and to obtain the highest rate of
return, ``a dramatic increase in basic science research'' and the
creation of a national science budget are absolute necessities,
Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the federal government has a responsibility to
encourage the former and fund the latter, noting that it was the
Department of Defense that financed ``the entire core of the
computer revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he said, the nation needs an overhaul of the schools'
mathematics and science curriculum, and it should put computers in
the hands of every 4-year-old American child.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds radical now, Gingrich said, ``but in 1800
universal education was a radical idea,'' and free textbooks were
such a novelty that then-Gov. Huey Long became a hero in Louisiana
in 1928 by making them available to public schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich calls his Committee for New American Leadership ``a new
kind of political activism for the 21st century,'' and it has a
pronounced libertarian bent. Its front-burner issues are a ``max
tax,'' or 25 percent cap on all taxation, federal state and local
combined, and ``Social Security Plus'' accounts for workers who
choose to mix entrepreneurship with their pensions. He claimed that
the second proposal _ similar to one offered by George W. Bush, the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee _ would ``save the
Social Security system.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich stepped down as speaker of the House after the
Republicans lost several seats in 1998, a loss that his critics
blamed on his abrasive confrontational tactics.
</P>
<P>
   He had also been hammered politically for ethics violations and
for a messy divorce after he left his then-ailing wife and took up
with a young congressional aide.
</P>
<P>
   Has he given up the quest for elective politics for good? ``I'm
not ruling anything out,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
