<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-TOWER-BY-THE-SEA-2TAK     06-07 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWER-BY-THE-SEA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOWER RISES ABOVE TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This article is adapted from ``Tower: Faith, Vertigo and
Amateur Construction,'' by Bill Henderson (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
2000).) 
 By BILL HENDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDGWICK, Maine _ In tower building, small is lovely. It is the
tall imagination that counts.
</P>
<P>
   A few summers ago in Maine, I built a tower on a high hill
overlooking the sea. My tower is only 12 by 12{ feet and three
stories high, if you generously include the observation deck.
Building up to that deck _ with simple tools, no electricity and
little help _ was a major satisfaction, indeed a salvation, during
a year that saw my marriage shaken and my faith often in shambles.
A plague of cancers had descended on several of my friends, all of
them young women. Their agony was one reason I had to lose myself
in raising the tower. It became a tower of oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   You may wish to go higher than I did, but in many communities
zoning restrictions will hold you below the treetops. You are,
after all, contemplating an impractical, frivolous and
idiosyncratic structure. Also, your next-door neighbor may worry
that you will block the sun. (Try not to.)
</P>
<P>
   And of course, you will have to endure the phallus-substitute
cracks. When this happens, point out that William Butler Yeats also
had to listen to Freudian cheap shots from his friend Ezra Pound,
who called Yeats' Thoor Ballylee ``Ballyphallus.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeats restored his tower, a Norman-era semi-ruin in County
Galway, in 1917, with thick planks and paving stones from an old
mill; it sheltered his family from the Irish Civil War. A winding
staircase became Yeats' symbol for the ``widening gyre'' up the
stairs of consciousness. He recalled his labor in his poem ``To Be
Carved on a Stone at Thoor Ballylee'':
</P>
<P>
   I, the poet William Yeats,
</P>
<P>
   With old mill boards and sea-green slates,
</P>
<P>
   And smithy work from the Gort forge,
</P>
<P>
   Restored this tower for my wife George;
</P>
<P>
   And may these characters remain
</P>
<P>
   When all is ruin once again.
</P>
<P>
   I built my tower near Sedgwick village, overlooking the
Atlantic. Because of its slow and steady pace, many residents of
this peninsula live years longer than people from ``away,'' despite
a climate that can be brutal, especially in winter. The terrific
winds may be why Down East Maine is not known for its towers.
</P>
<P>
   But I had been summering here for many years and had recently
constructed a cottage on nearby Deer Isle. I made up the cottage as
I went along, with good advice from A.J., at the lumberyard. My
tools were a hammer, a handsaw, a tri-square, a tape measure, a
level and a length of Manila rope. I lost 20 unwanted pounds, but
my great joy was in the making of it, an obsession perhaps. I made
a summer home for my little family.
</P>
<P>
   I first heard about Christy Hill from a real estate agent, and
once I saw the lot I wanted to buy it. As my dog, Opie, and I got
out of the car, I looked northeast in the clear cold air to the
crown of Blue Hill, scene of the annual Blue Hill Fair, the
inspiration for E.B. White's tale of Wilbur the pig and Charlotte
the spider. Twenty miles to the east were the mountains of Acadia
National Park on Mount Desert Island, and below me were dozens of
lesser islands and ledges, fringed with ice. Beyond them the open
ocean stirred quietly.
</P>
<P>
   In the distance I imagined I could just make out the top of
Mount Katahdin, Maine's highest peak.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way I could afford it, I thought. What was this
really but a 1.78-acre subdivision in the middle of nowhere? More
important, how could I explain my infatuation to my wife, Annie?
She might remind me that we often couldn't pay our bills,
particularly that fuel bill the previous winter.
</P>
<P>
   I telephoned my friend Doris Grumbach in the little town of
Sargentville, just the other side of the Deer Isle bridge. ``Can I
drive you to church?'' I asked. She said I could, and afterward, I
drove her to the top of the hill and pointed out the distant views
across the fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do here?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' I said. ``Probably leave it as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Doris, who is always careful with her words, said nothing. In
Maine, you are allowed to go as crazy as you wish.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I had my hill, but I couldn't dig my foundation until the
April thaw, giving me most of the winter to dream of what I had
come to think of as my ``tower for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be no neighbors near this tower with their
busynesses, and no busynesses of my own. Just me and the wild
turkeys, coyotes, moose, porcupines, skunks, deer, eagles and black
bears. Uncompromised. At full attention. Lifted up. Nearer to the
eternal spirit. Brother of Thoreau.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe just a middle-aged guy and his version of a boy's
treehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Because I couldn't afford help and my wife wanted nothing to do
with the tower, I was going to be one guy alone with lots of lumber
and concrete to haul into the woods, which as yet had no road, not
even a path. And after I chose my site and assembled my materials,
I would have to raise it all alone, and by hand.
</P>
<P>
   As for electricity, a line through the sweet woods from the
poles at the main road? Never. And no gasoline machinery, either.
No generators, no backhoes, no cranes, I pledged. Bad enough that I
drove that smoking Oldsmobile. Someday it too would go. Then I
would rediscover my feet by hiking up and down this magnificent
hill.
</P>
<P>
   Like Yeats _ and like Thoreau, in building his Walden Pond cabin
_ I saved by shopping for leftovers. Early in March, while
bicycling the dead streets of the town on Long Island where I live,
I came across a Dumpster with sections of a sliding glass door
sticking out. Thermal-pane doors are heavy, but since they often
refuse to slide, they are common in Dumpsters. And they are
terrific fixed windows, if you can haul the panels to your car and
to the site without developing a hernia.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick had granted me the freedom to erect whatever I liked.
Now I had only to seek permission from the wind. If I had been
thinking clearly, my model would have been the Eiffel Tower, that
984-foot marvel of wind resistance. The Leaning Tower of Pisa
provided lessons as well. When I was a Sunday school child, I was
taught that you should begin your life on a firm foundation: on
rock, not sand. Only later did I hear about the citizens of Pisa,
and how a lousy foundation beneath their 180-foot tower made them
rich, if not saintly.
</P>
<P>
   My foundation of choice was concrete posts, a terrific
foundation for the amateur builder. All that is required is a
strong back or a sturdy wheelbarrow, a shovel and buckets.
</P>
<P>
   The builder will also need eight-inch-diameter cardboard forms,
premixed concrete, reinforcing bars and J-bolts.
</P>
<P>
   But the soil, unbuilt upon since perhaps forever, was not
interested in my tower vision. When I started to dig, hammer, ax
and shovel progressed only 2 feet into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The local wisdom at the Sedgwick General Store was that a 4-foot
depth was the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   I called for help.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dave Webb arrived later that afternoon with his huge backhoe. We
talked as we walked through the woods to my problem. ``A tower,''
Dave mused. ``Gets breezy up here.'' He said no more. This was my
project.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 and a half feet, the land started to screech in protest
against the backhoe's metal fangs: bedrock. But after I paid Dave
and he roared off down the hill, I realized the simple solution: If
I couldn't get below 2 and a half feet, I'd pile up the earth 1 and
a half feet around each post and achieve my 4-foot burial. And I
had to pour concrete now so that I could begin placement of the
girders and joists when I returned later in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   With an old saw I cut each 12-foot-long tube into three 4-foot
sections and put the sections in two trenches, three on each side.
I checked for level and added or subtracted soil as necessary. Then
it was time for some heavy lifting: ready-mix Sakrete bags weigh 80
pounds each. Each post required somewhat more than two bags of mix,
or 15 bags total. Since the ground was too rough for a wheelbarrow,
my shoulder had to do for the march to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Each sack was followed by a bucket of water, which I hauled with
my car to the top of the hill. With a garden trowel I blended the
water and mix and poured the soup into the tube. I added the
reinforcing bar, and finally pushed the J-bolt into the wet
concrete, ready to receive the nut and the metal plate that would
fasten to the main girder.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-by-6 floor joists would be nailed to these girders, and
the plywood floor would be attached to the top of the joists. This
would be a terrific foundation, I thought as the March night
closed.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned to the spot in June, the tiny birch and beech
leaves were just out, pale and tender. I was halfway along the path
into the woods when something to the right formed out of the fog.
Something very large _ framed and sheathed, it was a two-story
house-in-progress, just 20 feet from my property line.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have to begin all over again: digging six holes inch by inch
in the rocks and roots, shouldering 15 bags of 80-pound concrete
mix and many buckets of water to a new foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I need to build this tower? What was the point? Food for
mosquitoes, flies and worms, I was. Dejected, I sat on an old stone
wall at the center of the property.
</P>
<P>
   Then I noticed a large patch of moss almost the measurement of
my intended tower. Here, nearly 400 feet above sea level (almost as
high as the Great Pyramid of Cheops at Giza) was the archetypal
foundation, solid Big Bang granite. ``Thank you,'' I muttered to
the moss.
</P>
<P>
   That summer I fell into a consuming maelstrom that centered
around my marriage. I suspected that Annie felt the same. I
imagined she wanted me gone. My foundations of home and faith were
evaporating in a marital fury. My daughter, Holly, then 11,
remained, but I couldn't share any of this with her. I was, in
short, hysterical.
</P>
<P>
   And alone in the Maine woods without power tools.
</P>
<P>
   As Thomas Merton observed, tough common work is a great
purifier. Hand-sawing those studs, slamming in those 16-penny
nails, hefting frames into place on the platform with nobody around
to help me if I lost my footing, concentrated my rage and
dissipated my hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Towers have been built for many reasons. Mine was founded on the
edge of despair and framed in pure frenzy. Later I discovered that
an astonishing series of modern towers had been created by a man
who, in a similar mood, happened to share some of my demons.
</P>
<P>
   The Watts Towers were the creations of Simon Rodia, a
bad-tempered, lyrical little guy with enormous energy. Simon, or
Sam, as he was later known, was born in a village near Naples,
Italy, that annually celebrated a pageant dating from the Middle
Ages featuring great ceremonial towers _ eight of them, six stories
high and three tons each.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rodia left Italy at 15 and wandered here and there until he
was hired in California as a concrete worker. As his third marriage
failed in 1921, he started his first tower, and he didn't quit
until 1955, when he had completed three lacy, intricately decorated
spirals of wire and reinforced concrete in his backyard. Two of
these towers are almost 100 feet tall, the third a mere 55 feet. To
me, his soaring spires, now the center of a state historic park,
are the ultimate in backyard tower construction _ dances of
caprice, anger, joy and nostalgia. They have withstood seven major
earthquakes. They are also the tallest structures ever made by one
man alone.
</P>
<P>
   If you build all day, every day, as I did for many summertime
weeks at age 54, you will emerge a far younger man. I framed out a
rough opening for my handsome red exterior door (found at the East
Hampton dump) and raised a two-by-four stud frame. (Don't try it in
a wind, as I did the first time, unless you have an escape route.)
At the corner of the east and west walls, I tripled the studs and
fitted the north and south walls inside them to support them in a
gale. For the next floor, I decided to use 7-foot wall studs, not
the usual 8-footers _ less height but also less to wobble in the
wind, I guessed. And any tower worth its name should incorporate an
inside stairway, leading to a balcony. (I would let sunlight do my
decorating.)
</P>
<P>
   I guessed that my 10-foot 2-by-6 joists could run across the
girders and stick out at each side. The extra foot at each end
didn't seem like much of an overhang at the time, but it made a
difference in stability that I would profoundly appreciate while
finishing the summit.
</P>
<P>
   As I was ready to nail on the roof sheathing and start with the
tar paper and the rolled roofing, I looked over the edge at the
rocks below.
</P>
<P>
   All sense of balance was gone _ and the tower was definitely
shifting under me. Death was a few feet away, somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In my dreaming, I had ignored a problem: vertigo. As a child, I
could scramble up any tree without a care, but now I couldn't climb
open stairs without clawing for support and inching back down on my
hands and knees. That's one reason the views from the tops of the
great steeples and monuments of Europe and America were unknown to
me.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later I discovered the secret of amateur semi-sloping
roof-building: the crab-scuttle butt-sit. I scuttled about that
roof, growing bolder and bolder until, by sunset, I had nailed down
all the sheathing.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the second day, I had a roof that didn't dare leak
and vertigo that had slunk away, defeated by the same spirit that I
also learned could control the panic. Embrace it. Wait. Be still.
</P>
<P>
   If you are thinking of constructing your own tower, I suggest
that you don't become overly analytical. Resist your shrink's
advice that you devote more time and money to psychological
explanations for your urges; avoid your doctor's offers of Prozac
or Viagra; harden your heart against your spouse's complaint that
what you really need is a used Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   By scrounging and following Thoreau's example, I was able to
build my tower for $2,264.56. Putting together that modest tower
was a priceless rediscovery of my spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else much matters, including all the towers of the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1618EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7215 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     06-07 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT FAILING E-STORES IT'S VULTURE BEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine that some shoppers react sympathetically when a store
goes out of business. My mother, for instance, still feels guilty
about Bonwit Teller and wonders if her decision not to buy a
certain red wool coat there one winter somehow contributed to the
department store's demise. I agree it was a mistake to pass up the
coat, because it looked so good with her hair.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the extent of my remorse. When a store goes out of
business, I drop everything and rush out to the liquidation sale.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine that other people would consider this behavior
unseemly. My mother, for instance, has been heard to refer to the
elbowing shoppers who surround the ``final sale'' pillowcases as
``vultures.'' I prefer the more neutral, and I believe more
accurate, label: foragers.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the recent flurry of high-profile online retailers who
have gone out of business _ like the toy seller Redrocket.com and
the arts and crafts supplier Craftshop.com _ shoppers like me have
a new place to graze.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awful lot of online businesses are going out of business
faster than offline stores,'' said Bill Blundon, executive vice
president of Extraprise, a consulting firm in Boston, ``because
when their initial funding dries up, venture capital firms will not
be as willing to step in to fill the void.''
</P>
<P>
   So after reading about the financial travails that forced the
trendy online apparel company Boo.com into liquidation last month,
I wondered if I might find some online bargains. Last week I went
to visit.
</P>
<P>
   At Boo.com I found all the glitzy trappings that stopped me from
shopping at the site in the first place: the annoying flashing
screens and confusing graphics that made it difficult to shop, a
gimmicky feature that let shoppers ``try on'' items and even the
site's too-perky mascot, Boo, an animated personal shopper.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing was missing: evidence that the site was going out
of business. No sale merchandise. No invitations to the crowds
flying overhead in circles _ I mean, foraging _ for the last
marked-down designer backpack. Instead, the merchandise _ from the
DKNY sweat pants to the Converse sneakers to the Helly Hensen
active wear _ were marked full price, but I was so confused that I
filled a shopping cart anyway. Only when I tried to check out with
a pair of black running shorts that cost $42 and a $20 T-shirt did
I get a clue that things were not right. ``An error has occurred
with your session, please try again,'' the site informed me.
</P>
<P>
   After a few more failures, I realized this was Boo.com's
understated way of saying the store was closed. I called the
liquidators at KPMG in London to find out and learned that Boo.com
had stopped taking orders a week earlier. ``An offline store would
post a sign or something,'' I complained. ``Otherwise, how are
people supposed to know?''
</P>
<P>
   KPMG's Mick McLoughlin said he would be surprised if anyone
didn't know. ``This has probably been the best publicized
insolvency in some time,'' McLoughlin said. In other words, stop
looking at the fashion advertisements and start reading the
financial pages. When traditional stores go out of business, they
have inventory to get rid of before they lock the doors. For online
retailers, who have little or no inventory, the old rules do not
apply. And what if a shopper managed to miss the news that Boo.com
was in trouble and was among the last to place an order?
</P>
<P>
   In troubled stores, online shoppers will face a new risk. ``The
old risk was: If you've never heard of them, how do you know those
guys aren't crooks?'' said Erik Gordon, director of the University
of Florida's Center for Retailing. ``Now the new risk is, I know
they're not crooks, but how do I know they're not going out of
business tomorrow, and if they do, will I get my money back?''
</P>
<P>
   In a real store, the transaction is a simultaneous exchange: you
hand over the payment and immediately receive the merchandise.
``You would feel a little differently if you had to hand over $20
to a store that was going out of business and then come back a week
later for the shirt,'' Gordon said. ``On the Internet, that's what
you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   McLoughlin said that in the case of Boo.com, shoppers would
probably be safe. ``I'm almost sure there will be some unfulfilled
orders,'' he said, ``but I don't know the details. But their credit
cards would not be debited before the purchase shipped. Although
it's inconvenient, they shouldn't lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave online stores that are still operating but
about which you may have had a whiff of negative financial
information? The music site CDNow, for example, has been selling
CDs at bargain prices, but the company, which is short of cash, is
looking for a new partner or investor. Should you shop there?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going out of business, and it's safe to shop here,''
said Debbie Vondran, a CDNow spokeswoman. ``You can see that we
have been constantly growing the site, adding features and
functionalities, new promotions and new content. That's an
indication that we have a pretty solid business.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside for a moment the fact that Vondran is an
interested party, she does make a good point. When you visit an
unfamiliar online retailer, the first thing you should do is
scrutinize the site for robust, customer-friendly features. A
healthy site should prominently display a toll-free customer
service number, a clear return policy and an assurance that your
credit card will not be charged until after your items are shipped.
</P>
<P>
   And look for hints of trouble. For weeks before Boo.com
announced its difficulties, for instance, the retailer suddenly
started sending prospective customers coupons offering 30 percent
off merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Fashionmall.com acquired Boo.com. When I visited
again, the old Boo.com site was gone, replaced by an invitation to
join an e-mail list to learn about the reopening of Boo.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine some shoppers might have been leery, but I signed up.
If there is a Grand Opening sale, I will rush over to forage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
