<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-TINY-APARTMENTS-ART-N     06-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINY-APARTMENTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING THE BEST SQUARE FEET FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ELAINE LOUIE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the most ingenious small Manhattan apartments,
designers and their clients become illusionists. They make beds
disappear, tables double in height and televisions spin between two
rooms at once.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine David Copperfield channeling Billy Baldwin, the
space-conscious 1950s designer: now you see the furniture, now you
don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You missed it,'' Jordan Schaps, an editor for special projects
at New York magazine, said gleefully. A visitor to his railroad
flat had walked right by his invisible bed, which was hugging the
ceiling. Double-width, extra-long, it is raised and lowered by
pulley and counterweights to a space that is his desk by day.
</P>
<P>
   At night, with the panache of a 1917 Pullman-car porter, Schaps
transforms his 5-foot-by-8-foot home office into a sleeping
chamber. He takes the telephone off the wall, closes his desk top,
draws a curtain across the bulletin board and lets the bed platform
down, with pillows and comforter neatly folded in place. He uses a
cane to pull the curtain across. ``It's vaudevillian,'' he said,
``or is it Chaplinesque?''
</P>
<P>
   Schaps, who wears bow ties by day but bicycles around the
neighborhood with shirt unbuttoned at night, is decidedly the
playful type. His other design tricks: a television set that pivots
in place between the living room and the dining room, and a dining
table whose center section is glass covered and filled with sand
(dotted with mementos of his favorite beaches around the world). He
also created a cabinet in the shape of the United States whose
doors open where the time zones change. ``I'm very pro-America,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaps paid $22,000 for the 700-square-foot apartment in a West
Village tenement building in 1981, a momentous day in more ways
than one: It was also, he said, ``the day Prince Charles married
Princess Diana.'' At first, he put his bed in the front room,
facing Perry Street, which is paved with cobblestones. Picturesque,
yes, but vexing. The sound of mounted police trotting along the
street _ clickety-clack, clickety-clack _ and trucks rolling over
the uneven surface _ clunk-clunk, clunk-clunk _ led Schaps to
declare, ``Let's get rid of the bed.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet he is happy with his reduced (hide-the-bed)
circumstances. Although Schaps is considering buying a weekend
apartment in Miami, he has no plan to trade up to a larger home in
Manhattan. ``I'm in apartments all the time, producing stories,''
he said, referring to his special issues on home design and food.
``When I'm in a modern, cutting-edge apartment, I say, `This is is
how I want to live.' When I'm in a traditional apartment, I say,
`This is how I want to live.'''
</P>
<P>
   So he stays put, happily. ``I'm a nester,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The television twirls, too, at Emily Oberman's 750-square-foot
apartment on the Lower East Side. Oberman owns Number Seventeen, a
graphic design company, with Bonnie Siegler. The company creates
opening sequences for television shows, and did graphics for Andre
Balasz's Mercer Hotel in Manhattan and for his Chateau Marmont in
Los Angeles. ``I work in TV, and I love TV, and I wish I could take
my TV on a dolly wherever I went,'' said Oberman, 37.
</P>
<P>
   She paid $120,000 for the 750-square-foot apartment in 1990, and
barely unpacked until 1996, when she asked Marco Pasanella, a
Manhattan interior designer, to renovate it for under $20,000. His
mandate was to figure out a way that the television could follow
her, like a devoted puppy, and at the same time satisfy her
admitted narcissism. (``I'm really vain,'' Oberman said.)
</P>
<P>
   The designer, who just published his first design book, ``Living
in Style Without Losing Your Mind'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), succeeded
in one grand gesture. He cut a hole in the wall between the bedroom
and the living room and framed the television with a cherrywood
cube mirrored on the back. Then he put the cube on a Lazy Susan.
``If I'm not watching TV,'' Oberman said, laughing, ``I can watch
me!''
</P>
<P>
   Pasanella also designed a wall system made of doors of frosted
glass that camouflage the ugly barred windows. A soft muted light
comes in during the day, and at night, when lit from street lamps,
``the windows become light boxes,'' he said. He designed nearly
every panel in the room to do double duties.
</P>
<P>
   In the living room, a pair of wood-framed grates hide the
heating system on one side, and provide storage space on the other.
Between them, a wood panel lifts up and out to become a desk. A
round glass coffee table, 14 inches high, becomes a 28-inch-high
dining table when she stacks the large wood cubes that serve as its
base and adds others that are normally used for stools. Not that
Oberman needs a dining table: she takes all her meals out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
