<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-TINY-APARTMENT-LIFE-1     06-07 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINY-APARTMENT-LIFE-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 8,9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHEN MIHM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lot of New Yorkers live in small spaces, some
smaller than others. My own, for example, measures 250 square feet
as the crow walks. Over time, I've become obsessed with making the
most of it, getting up at odd hours to stack file cabinets and weed
my belongings, even removing doors from hinges. Today, within easy
reach, I also have a sofa, a desk, two chairs, three bureaus and an
18-pound cat named Gus, who takes up more than his fair share of
the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Suburbanites with tool sheds bigger than my apartment may have
good reason to wonder whether New Yorkers like me are a bit crazy.
But I'm not alone, as I found out when I went in search of other
small-apartment lovers in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   While financial concerns force many New Yorkers to cling to
small quarters, some actually savor living in the human equivalent
of a beehive. Those I met could have moved long ago into much more
spacious housing outside the city; the average single-family
American home, after all, provides 835 square feet of living space
a person, up from 477 square feet 30 years ago, according to the
U.S. Census.
</P>
<P>
   The city's housing code certainly doesn't coddle the
claustrophobic. Section D26-33.03, adopted in 1967, holds that
every apartment dweller is entitled to 80 square feet of so-called
livable space _ not much bigger than a king-size bed. Though
bathrooms aren't figured in, that's still less than the 94 square
feet allotted to well-behaved inmates at Attica.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Manhattan seems destined for compact living, and downsizing
here has become almost a trend. Costas Kondylis, a well-known
architect of residential buildings, said that in New York in the
1980s ``typically, one-bedrooms used to be 750 square feet.'' He
added, ``Now on average they are 640, even 625 square feet.'' (In
another sign of the times, Manhattan Mini Storage has added 12,000
storage units to its inventory of more than 20,000 units since
1990.)
</P>
<P>
   The first stop in my search was the 400-square-foot Greenwich
Village apartment of Zabel Meshejian. The sign in the elevator put
me in the right mood. ``Maximum Occupancy 6 people,'' it read,
surely a joke given that it measures less than 2 feet by 2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Meshejian works by day as a food stylist, staging photographs
for companies like Godiva, Red Lobster and Nabisco. At night, in a
galley kitchen, she cooks for herself, drawing from a
floor-to-ceiling collection of pots, pans and condiments. ``I have
spices for any kind of cuisine,'' Meshejian said, pointing to
wooden cabinets and boxes overflowing with herbs and bottles of
oils. ``Chinese, Indian, Mexican, Mediterranean. They're all
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But never mind the challenge of preparing dinner in a closet. It
turns out that Meshejian is also a frustrated gardener, and her
apartment seemingly houses more flowerpots than a professional
greenhouse. ``I started with one plant, and all of a sudden I had
hundreds,'' she said. Tiers of glass shelves mounted in three
southern-facing windows catch the afternoon sun, all filled with
her favorite miniature plants: euphorbias, haworthias and lithops,
kept small and root bound in tiny pots.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the apartment, shared with a 19-year-old cat named
Munchkin, doesn't seem crowded, just cozy. Antique bureaus, wooden
boxes and hundreds of cookbooks line the perimeter of the living
room, while odds and ends _ a parasol, some woven baskets, family
photographs _ take up the rest of the wall space. Everything has a
place, even Munchkin, who spends his days dozing in a basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this recurring dream that I go through my closet and
discover another room,'' Meshejian said. Not that she would ever
abandon her apartment of 22 years, which is perfectly positioned
across the street from a community green space, where she tends her
outdoor plants and a rock garden.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if there's anything besides economics that keeps people
chained to small apartments, it's location.
</P>
<P>
   For Doris Tobias, it all comes down to breezy views of the East
River and the United Nations. She lives in a one-bedroom apartment
of a little less than 700 square feet with a kitchen the size of a
bathtub, not all that unusual _ except that Tobias happens to be a
cookbook author. (``The Golden Lemon,'' published in 1979, is being
reissued by iUniverse, and Tobias is also the co-author, with
Jean-Paul Picot, of ``La Bonne Soupe Cookbook'' from Macmillan.)
She is researching her next book, a collection of recipes for
``salads that start the meal and salads that are the meal,'' as she
put it, in the same small space.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to have grandiose, grand-scale kitchens,'' she
said, wrinkling her nose. ``It's an act of one-upmanship. They're
not for use; they're showy.''
</P>
<P>
   The alcove that passes for her kitchen houses a standard
refrigerator; a diminutive four-burner stove; a Frigidaire
minidishwasher; a convection oven barely big enough for an
eight-pound turkey; and some wooden cabinets that spill into the
living room. A few choice pots and utensils hang at arm's length;
basil and rosemary sit in the windowsill, swaying in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to clean up as you go,'' Tobias added. She not only
washes as she cooks, but also prepares parts of the meal ahead of
time, running her kitchen like a miniature military barracks.
``Tidiness is space,'' she said. ``You have to work and clean, work
and clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Will she ever move, get a bigger kitchen? Not likely: she's too
attached to the neighborhood, where she has lived since 1979.
``Things have changed,'' she said wistfully. ``But the river is
still there, rolling along.''
</P>
<P>
   Living small isn't for everyone, of course, and it hasn't worked
so well for Richard Mason, a short cherubic man who moved into his
15-by-15-foot studio apartment in 1957, when he was 30. At first,
he said, the size of the place didn't matter. He and his friends
``had great parties,'' he continued, adding, ``We had 25 people
over at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he acquired a house on Long Island near Hofstra
University, where he taught theater, and he used the apartment only
on weekends. But when he retired, he moved back. Now, ``It's really
a challenge to live here,'' he said. ``There's not a square inch
that your eye will rest on that I actually haven't done something
to.'' He pointed to shelves that cling like barnacles to every
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such efforts, as he sees it, he needs professional
design help. ``For years now I've been trying to neaten this
place,'' he said, but it is always ``on the threshold of continuing
chaos.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Some savor the chaos. Surprisingly, I found that includes
families. My final stop was at the home of Ursula and Nilo Mitra,
who live on Pomander Walk, a 1920s gated community of miniature
Tudor row houses lining a blocklong pedestrians-only alley that
runs from 94th Street to 95th Street between Broadway and West End
Avenue. Their 600-square-foot apartment on a single floor has two
tiny bedrooms, with a home office in the parents' room and a
library lining their son's bedroom walls. There is a modest
dining/living room area and a kitchenette wedged into a walk-in
closet.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitras, who arrived from separate dwellings a few years ago,
are the first to raise a child on Pomander Walk in more than 20
years. Mitra works as bookbinder; her husband, who has a doctorate
in particle physics, works for Ericsson, which makes cell phones.
Their son, Amitav, is 2 and will be joined by a baby sister in
October. Two cats (Samantha and Nimbus), plus a sometime nanny,
round out the household.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinner is crazy around here,'' Mitra said.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy is practically nonexistent. ``There are no real borders
in this place, except maybe our bedroom,'' she said. And that
doubles as an office, with a hardwood partition the couple designed
themselves. The floor-to-ceiling unit contains a clothes closet, a
file cabinet, several bookshelves and drawers for linens. Another
storage unit, also of their own design, wraps around one of the
windows, providing space for china and a collection of vases.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitras store bulk purchases of diapers, toilet paper and
canned goods off-site in Mitra's studio in Hoboken. When they get
restless, there is always Central Park. ``We spend half of every
day out there,' Mitra said. ``Amitav loves the sandbox.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mitras can afford to move out, but they are attached to
their community And they are inured. Both grew up in small spaces:
Mitra in India, where extended families make privacy a luxury;
Mitra, in a small apartment in Germany with three siblings. ``My
father was the only one who had a private room,'' she said,
recalling his study.
</P>
<P>
   As she sees it, small is good for children _ and parents. In big
suburban homes, she said, ``the child is often in the farthest
corner of the house. Far too much responsibility is shifted away
from the parents and put elsewhere. Part of being responsible is
being there and seeing what's going on with your kid.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughed. ``That is not a problem in a place like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
