<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MINORITY-CONTRACTING-     06-07 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-CONTRACTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REPORT RECOMMENDS CHANGES IN MINORITY CONTRACTING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHUCK FINNIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A consultant's report recommends that the San
Francisco Human Rights Commission be stripped of its control over
the city's troubled minority contracting program to limit political
influence over the awarding of big public works contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Moving responsibility for the program, subject of a yearlong FBI
probe, to the controller's office would help restore public
confidence in the process by which disadvantaged minority- and
women-owned companies get a guaranteed share of such jobs as the
expansion at San Francisco International Airport, according to the
KPMG Consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The move also greatly would diminish political influence over
the program by Mayor Willie Brown, whose task force to investigate
the affirmative-action program sought the recommendations of KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   Under KPMG's proposal, responsibility for determining
eligibility for minority contracts and bid preferences would fall
to the largely autonomous controller's office.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Commission, or HRC, which has run the current
program since its inception in 1984, is overseen by a panel of
commissioners appointed by the mayor and is run by an executive
director chosen by and serving at the pleasure of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The controller, though also appointed by the mayor, enjoys far
greater independence. The post carries a 10-year term and its
occupant can be removed only for cause and with the concurrence of
two-thirds of the full Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Robert O'Neill, head of a team from KPMG Consulting that made
the proposal after six months of study, said the recommendation is
an attempt to bring professional standards to the minority
contracting program.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings, coupled with the HRC's perceived loss of
credibility made a compelling case for removing certification and
contract compliance and monitoring functions from the HRC,'' KPMG
said in an executive summary to the report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As contract dollar amounts rise substantially, independence
from potential political influence and strict adherence to
established procedures become increasingly important,'' the summary
said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed transfer of control over the program, which may
require voter approval of a city Charter amendment, is the most
sweeping of several recommendations by KPMG Consulting, which was
hired by the task force formed by Brown last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who said at the time that he was acting to ``ensure the
integrity'' of the minority contracting program, formed the task
force Aug. 30, five months after the San Francisco Examiner first
reported that the FBI was investigating the program and a week
after the newspaper reported that a company controlled by a large,
white-owned corporation landed $55 million in public works jobs set
aside by the city for disadvantaged minority businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a U.S. grand jury indicted four executives of the
company, Scott-Norman Mechanical Inc., and a top Human Rights
Commission official, Zula Jones, for allegedly participating in a
scheme to defraud the affirmative-action program.
</P>
<P>
   Under city law, economically disadvantaged, local companies that
are owned and controlled by minorities or women receive preferences
when bidding on city construction, professional services and supply
contracts. Contractors seeking major public works jobs must pledge
to set aside a portion of the work for these businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Commission first must certify that the
companies meet eligibility requirements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SURFER-SHACK-ART-NYT &LR;      06-07 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURFER-SHACK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANGRI-LA IN A SHACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 5,6,7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a well-known axiom that there is a correlation between the
size of a house and the number of headaches it causes. And in the
Hamptons, their severity increases exponentially as one proceeds
east along Route 27 to the windmill in East Hampton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Rowley, the fashion designer, and her husband, Bill
Keenan, a designer and sculptor, shucked the headaches involved in
owning a shingled four-bedroom stunner in the estate section of
East Hampton and moved instead to a surfer's shack in
less-prestigious nearby Montauk.
</P>
<P>
   Time, not money, was the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley's witty romantic garb and a company with $20 million in
sales last year have made her a lively presence and serious
contender on the fashion scene. And the couple already own homes in
TriBeCa in lower Manhattan and upstate New York. Their house in
Long Island was meant to be someplace relaxing, someplace to enjoy
with their baby daughter, Kit Clementine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be so busy at work,'' Rowley said of the summer five years
ago, a time when she was building an empire that now includes a
shop in East Hampton and six other stores around the world, in
addition to 27 in-store boutiques in Asia. Also, 1995 was the year
she and her husband set up their East Hampton house on Hedges Lane,
known for its rambling privet-cloaked getaways with a pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley recalled: ``I'd get out there on the weekend, and the
neighbors would call to say, `Hi! Your grass should be cut. It
really is getting a little too long.' And the pool would have some
problem. There'd be something else going wrong with the
air-conditioner. It was such a bad experience.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in addition to the weekend guests. ``Not that I'm not
social, but every weekend, so many people ... '' Rowley said,
trailing off at the memory of so many dirty towels and sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after buying the place for $925,000, they put it back
on the market (where it sold for $1.1 million) and started looking
for something smaller. ``Something that we could clean with a broom
in under five minutes,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   They headed east for Montauk, where turrets and swollen eyebrow
windows are in shorter supply than in the snootier Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a shack?'' Rowley asked a local Montauk realtor.
</P>
<P>
   Ada Stevens of Kathleen G. Beckmann Real Estate remembered the
visit. ``They came in a pickup truck, and she was wearing this
little cotton print dress,'' Stevens said. ``They were very
low-keyed, and I had no idea who she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowley, 40, doesn't indulge in the fashion diva act that her
mid-size clothing domain would entitle her to. Rather, she behaves
like the quintessential best girlfriend, the one who is a little
ditsy but ever at the ready to lend moral support _ and maybe a
great outfit. Keenan, 47, matches his wife in blithe, borderline
goofy spirit, although he appears to be a tad more on the ball when
it comes to things like taking an extra baby bottle to lunch and
monitoring their daughter's intake of French fries.
</P>
<P>
   They remembered the real estate agent's taking them to Ditch
Plains Road, where bland little houses, surfer's huts and Dew Drop
Inn-type motels vie for obscurity. A two-car-garage-size house,
only 200 yards from the beach, caught their eye.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Keenan said, it was love at first sight. The flat
roof, glass sliding barn door and deep overhang reminded him of
something by Richard Neutra, the California modernist. ``Yeah, if
you squint and drive by real fast,'' Rowley said. To her, it looked
``early gas station.''
</P>
<P>
   Its period modernity appealed to the couple's aesthetic interest
in everything resolutely 20th century, and especially anything with
a spark of midcentury optimism: for them, the World's Fair of 1964
and ``The Jetsons'' cartoons are watersheds in design savvy. And
this place was rife with diner details, like the built-in sofas, no
more than hinged platforms lowered by chain from the wall; Jacques
Cousteau porthole lighting; and combed plywood walls that fairly
screamed 1950s rec room.
</P>
<P>
   They bought the place on the spot, paying the asking price of
$189,000, Stevens said. ``If you tore it down and put in an
upside-down contemporary, you would more than likely get a view of
West Lake,'' she said, referring to the kind of top-heavy houses
straining to get a load of the sea that are so typical in other
parts of the Hamptons. So far, this neighborly street of skinny
plots doesn't have any of them.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple had no intention of making significant changes.
They especially didn't want to make the house larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``No fuss, no muss, no Calvin Klein $12 million shingled house
for us,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   For a guest house, there's an Airstream trailer parked in the
backyard, while the couple await approval to convert a
free-standing garage on the property into a guest house. Meanwhile,
the vintage 1969 trailer is ``the perfect self-contained
environment,'' Rowley said. ``It has everything.'' (She noted
brightly, however, that for weekend guests, ``you can't have people
who are too fancy.'')
</P>
<P>
   The house, basically a single room with a galley kitchen and a
corner partitioned off as a sleeping alcove, turned out to have
some serious structural problems. The roof had to be replaced in
the wake of a 15-year leak, and the couple took the opportunity to
open the place up a bit. ``It was so crowded you had to go outside
to turn around,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   They tore out eight built-in sofas that doubled as bunk beds.
The couple removed a closet in order to fit in a queen-size
mattress and a small bedside table. A sliding panel made of wavy
greenhouse plastic slides back and forth in front of the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``For privacy'' Keenan said. The baby, who just turned 1, sleeps
in a portable crib, for now.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture, too, was kept to a minimum. ``We knew we could only
have a few pieces, so we had to choose carefully,'' Rowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite shopping grounds are flea markets, garage sales and
street curbs. The '60s motel mood is up to the minute, from the
Greek flokati rug to the Ikea dresser that Keenan altered by
tacking on spindly legs and clunky drawer knobs. On the hearth
there is a vintage Bongo Board made quasi famous by Hugh Hefner's
``Playboy After Dark'' television show.
</P>
<P>
   The $350 Dux couch was ordered in the most diminutive size
available and then reupholstered in an expensive nubby green wool.
``You can't skimp on everything,'' said Rowley, who was wearing a
backless top made of two silk scarves that had been found at a flea
market and then sewn together along the bias.
</P>
<P>
   As with most of the furnishings, the tables in the house came in
at less than $10 and were picked up at garage sales. The larger,
metal one in the center of the room, which doubles as a dinner
table because there's no place else to eat, looks as if it were
designed by Richard Schultz, well known for his modern garden
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Future plans include adding a breezeway to the garage, which
Keenan uses as an art studio. He envisions it as a curved arc,
``like the Dulles wing,'' he said referring to the Washington
airport.
</P>
<P>
   But that could take a while. ``The whole idea is to come here
and not do much,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Rowley added: ``With so few walls and so little floor
space, I consider it done. We can't do anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
