<HEADER>
A7223 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     06-07 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEITHER NOTEBOOK NOR PALM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE HUTSKO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somehow the niche between a palm-size organizer and a notebook
has never been successfully colonized. Big companies are about to
withdraw their bigger handheld entries from the market. IBM
withdrew months ago, and Hewlett-Packard will stop production of
its larger handheld this month, although it will continue to
produce its tiny handheld with non-touch-type keyboard, which has
been selling well.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, Sharp, NEC and a few others still make so-called PC
companions, devices with keyboards that are bigger than an
organizer's but smaller than a notebook's. But they run on
Microsoft's Windows CE operating system, which draws its look and
feel from its big brother operating system, Windows 98. And
Microsoft is not saying whether it will allow the Windows CE system
to fade away while it concentrates its marketing muscle on its even
tinier Pocket PC software for palm-size computers.
</P>
<P>
   I hope that Windows CE and the bigger handhelds that run it do
not disappear, but if they do, there is a product from Britain by
Psion PLC waiting in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   The Psions, organizers with keyboards, have always been
competition for the palm-size computers and have been popular in
Europe, with some following here. The new Psion Series 7 is the
most powerful yet. It looks like a notebook computer, but does not
carry all the overhead like a hard drive or the ability to run the
same programs you use on the desktop. Instead it runs scaled-down
applications that offer the bare minimum of services required to
write, calculate, stay on schedule and in touch with contacts, send
and receive e-mail and connect to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   About the size of a large paperback book, the Series 7 weighs in
at just over 2.5 pounds. The black case is made of hard plastic
partially sheathed in bumpy black leather, giving the device a sort
of high-tech-meets-classic-Day Timer appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The $900 Series 7's color screen, which is 7.7 inches from
corner to corner, may seem awfully small when compared with
full-fledged notebook computers costing only a few hundred dollars
more, but if you compare it with a Palm or a Pocket PC handheld,
that is another matter. Like the larger Windows CE handhelds, which
have no hard disks and power on instantly without the lengthy boot
up times of regular computers, the Psion Series 7's attraction lies
not in its ability to be a notebook computer, but rather to offer
the essence of one.
</P>
<P>
   Psion estimates that unlike notebooks, whose batteries fizzle
out after a few hours, the Series 7's rechargeable battery will
last about eight and a half hours before you need to plug the power
adapter into the wall. The battery in the Series 7 I tested lasted
at least four hours with no signs of running out, although I did
not run it longer than that without its being plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   The included synchronization software works with Windows
computers, shuttling word processing, spreadsheet and personal
information manager (PIM) data back and forth. An included cable
plugs into the Psion's serial port on one end and the computer's on
the other.
</P>
<P>
   A double click of the synchronization icon shuttles personal
information between the Psion 7's Agenda, To-Do, e-mail and
Contacts information and any version of Microsoft Outlook running
on a Windows desktop computer. Unfortunately, Microsoft Outlook's
Post-It-like screen notes are not supported in the transfer, which
I find disappointing since I use them frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Where Windows CE manages to do the transfer and translation
between big computer and little computer automatically on all
application fronts, the Psion requires manual intervention to
shuttle documents; Word and Excel files must be dragged and dropped
into and out of the Psion 7's folders, and you have to activate the
file transfer utility to take documents with you or update on the
desktop. It would be nice if the Psion figured out that part by
itself, like Windows CE.
</P>
<P>
   The Series 7, however, does something Windows CE has never done:
it works with Macintoshes. Currently, optional software lets Mac
users back up data stored on the Series 7, and Psion says next
month it will offer beefed-up Mac software to enable
synchronization with several popular e-mail and organizer programs.
As for entering information by hand, the device's keyboard is
smaller than the standard desktop keyboard, but the difference is
not very noticeable when touch typing _ except for the awkwardly
placed question mark and slash key. Having to stretch the right
pinky to reach for the question mark key is maddening.
</P>
<P>
   The touch-sensitive screen flips back nicely and is complemented
on either side with 10 on-screen buttons for starting the built-in
programs. All of them, as well as icons and other objects or text
on the screen, respond to the fingernail or the included stylus,
which pops out of the side of the Series 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Four of the on-screen buttons may be customized to run secondary
programs _ included applications that are not linked to screen
buttons _ or ones you have installed yourself. Psion thoughtfully
dedicates two buttons to the ability to zoom in and out of the
screen's text in any application and have the system remember that
size for any other application. It is a wonder such a feature is
not easily available on desktop computers, because it eases
eyestrain when the text is enlarged while typing articles like this
and is equally useful for dropping the text size down a few notches
to make more of it fit on the screen when viewing Web pages. Text
views and font sizes can be changed in most Web browsers and word
processing programs, but with much less ease.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the Web, the Psion, which uses an operating
system called Symbian EPOC, is not as adept as competing products
that run Windows CE. Figuring out how to connect in the first place
is a bit tricky because of the machine's Eurocentric default
settings. But once the country and area code settings are typed in,
the Psion 7 is ready to make the connection by way of a PC Card
modem slipped into its available slot.
</P>
<P>
   Psion provided its own 56K version for this review, though
almost any PC Card modem should work. Once connected, Web pages
appear nicely in all their colorful glory, though certain sites
built with complicated or multicolumn layouts don't always look
they way they do on a desktop or notebook computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Besides connecting with a modem, the Psion has an infrared port
for beaming bits of information to other Psions or Palm OS handheld
computers. The infrared port can also be aimed at the infrared port
of GSM-equipped mobile phones for dialing into the Net. GSM (Global
System for Mobile Communications) is a digital cellular telephone
standard in use in more than 60 countries, including much of
Europe. Trial GSM systems have been set up in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A Compact Flash slot accepts memory cards to give the Psion more
room for storing documents and information, but the unit's 16
megabytes of RAM was more than big enough for storing my few
hundred contacts, birthday reminders and two novels. Since the
Psion's programs are built into the unit's ROM, they don't take up
storage space.
</P>
<P>
   Additional touches include a database program, a sketch program
and a notes program. All of the Psion Series 7's applications can
accept and display text scribbled with the stylus and pictures
imported from Web sites or the desktop computer. The extra feature
I am most grateful for is the voluminous spelling and thesaurus
program, which proves indispensable when searching for just the
right word while revising chapters of my next novel.
</P>
<P>
   But helpful as it is, the thesaurus is not reason enough for me
to replace the Hewlett-Packard Jornada 820 running Windows CE that
I rely on for my away-from-home computing. I have three reasons: 1)
It synchronizes all my personal data _ including Outlook Notes _
and documents without my ever having to think about it, whereas the
Psion is prickly in the same matters; 2) it runs AOL Instant
Messenger, which the Psion cannot; and 3) I prefer the Jornada's
notebook-style touchpad to the Psion's stylus-dependent
touchscreen.
</P>
<P>
   But if I did not already own the Jornada 820 _ whose days,
according to HP, are sadly numbered, with production of the device
ending this month _ the Psion Series 7 would probably be my first
choice as a companion to my desktop computer. Given time and a
little tweaking to improve its compatibility with Windows and Macs,
the Psion Series 7 could even unseat the few but significant larger
handhelds running Windows CE. Assuming, that is, that Microsoft
does not pull the plug on its own invention beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
