<P>
   MONASTERY-NUNS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTOVAL, Texas _ On a hot and gusty West Texas day, Sister
Marie hurries across the chalky construction site with her
traditional brown habit lapping at the top of her blue cowboy
boots. ``We all have cowboy boots,'' she says of the six cloistered
nuns who have made the new monastery their home. ``They warned us
there were a lot of snakes out here, but they said the snakes
wouldn't strike higher than six inches, and we would be safe as
long as we had our boots on.'' The new Carmelite Monastery of Our
Lady of Grace is rising, stone by stone, above the twisted mesquite
and live oak trees. It is a new Texas holy land on the rocky
pastures, a place of prayer and deep spirituality. Also a place of
goats and cattle and rattlesnakes. By ART CHAPMAN. (With excellent
art). Story will move in ``a'' general news category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
