<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7234 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     06-07 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV25-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 25, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: We have a large screened enclosure around and over our
swimming pool and there is a small tear in one vertical section.
The screen mesh is made of a plastic material that is fairly
flexible.
 &HT;    Hiring someone to replace all the screen mesh in that section
would be expensive, so I would like to simply patch that little
torn area myself.
 &HT;    What is the simplest way to do this?
 &HT;    A: If the tear is very small, you can often patch it by simply
dabbing over the hole with an all-purpose clear household cement.
 &HT;    For larger holes or longer tears you can cement on a square
patch of the same material.
 &HT;    Coat the patch and the area around the tear or hole with a light
coat of the cement, then press this patch firmly into place over
the defect while someone presses firmly on the other side of the
screening with a piece of plywood or stiff cardboard.
 &HT;    If you know the screen is actually fiberglass you may be able to
dispense with the cement and simply ``iron'' it into place with a
regular clothes iron set on medium high heat. Cover the patch with
a piece of cloth before pressing the iron on top.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Some oil was apparently spilled in my garage some years ago
and this oil has soaked into some of the wood framing and siding,
as well as into the concrete floor of the garage.
 &HT;    There is no surface oil left, so there is nothing to mop up on
the surface.
 &HT;    Is there any way I can remove these oil stains from both the
wood and the concrete?
 &HT;    A: Some absorbent materials such as powdered Portland cement or
kitty litter can be used to absorb and remove oil stains from wood
and concrete, if they can be spread on in a thick layer.
 &HT;    However, these are only effective when the stain is still fairly
new, so I don't think they will work on stains that are many years
old and already deeply absorbed.
 &HT;    On the concrete, you can try one of the liquid cleaners sold for
this purpose in most hardware stores, but even these would be
useless on the wood.
 &HT;    The only way to conceal these stains is to paint over them. You
will first have to apply one or two coats of a stain-killing sealer
such as BIN or Kilz.
 &HT;    After this dries the surface can be painted with any type of
latex paint.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My roof has moss on the shingles, especially on the sides
facing east and west where there is considerable shade.
 &HT;    Is there any way I can remove this moss without damaging the
roof?
 &HT;    A: Moss can usually be removed by washing with a solution of one
part laundry bleach mixed with four parts water.
 &HT;    Scrub this on with a soft brush and allow to dry on the surface,
then flush off with lots of water.
 &HT;    You can also use one of the commercial moss removers that are
sold in garden supply outlets.
 &HT;    In each case, protect plantings from the runoff by covering with
plastic sheets and by hosing them off thoroughly as work
progresses.
 &HT;    None of these solutions will harm the roofing.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I am building some cabinets out of a solid hardwood that
comes only in odd widths and I have to cut some boards into two or
three equally wide strips.
 &HT;    This means working with small, odd fractions that are hard to
measure accurately.
 &HT;    An old time carpenter once told me that this is easy to do with
an ordinary ruler. Have you heard of this?
 &HT;    A: Angle the ruler across the width of the board so that an even
inch mark on the ruler is at one edge (it doesn't matter which mark
you start with).
 &HT;    Hold this end in place and swing the ruler diagonally across the
width of the board until an even-numbered inch mark is at the
opposite edge, picking a number that will be easy to divide by the
number of widths you want. For example, if you want four equal
widths locate the opposite edge at exactly the 4- or 8-inch marks.
 &HT;    Now make a pencil mark at each of the intermediate inch marks to
divide the board into that number of equal widths you want.
 &HT;    Then use these marks to draw lines parallel to the edges to
indicate where to cut. (Don't forget to allow for the width of the
saw blade as it makes each cut.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Some years ago, solar window film was put on our windows.
This film is now wrinkled in several places, so we would like to
remove it completely.
 &HT;    How can we do this?
 &HT;    A. Most solar films can be removed by simply peeling them off
after you work one corner loose by sliding a razor blade under the
edge.
 &HT;    As you start to peel it off, keep wetting the film with a fine
spray of water while pulling gently with a steady pressure. Also
spray water onto the glass behind the film so it runs down behind
it.
 &HT;    Keep spraying and peeling and the sheet of film should come off
in one piece. Otherwise you may have to use a razor blade to scrape
it all off.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``PATCHING HOLE IN A SCREEN'' goes with
this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Torn plastic screen can be patched by using clear
household cement to hold the patch in place. Or, if the screen is
made of fiberglass, you can simply iron on the patch.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
