<HEADLINE>
THE INTERNET: INVALUABLE AND INESCAPABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet rules. It's not just boosterism anymore. People are
spending more and more time online _ for business and pleasure,
reshaping our attitudes and the corporate landscape, and
jeopardizing traditional pursuits such as watching TV, reading and
going to the library.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 years ago, when America Online first began running
TV ads, most people didn't know what the heck it was selling. Now
people are doing business entirely online, buying books and
groceries online, finding LOVE online. Dallas even has ``Dotcom
Guy,'' whose goal is to spend a whole year in his home doing
everything via the Internet. Few doubt that he can do it.
</P>
<P>
   How did this happen? Even most enthusiasts don't know how the
Internet managed to penetrate our lives quicker and deeper than any
other new technology or medium. Even if you don't have a PC, have
never surfed the Web and have no intention of entering a chat room,
you can't escape the effect the Net is having on society and pop
culture.
</P>
<P>
   So HOW did the Internet take over the world (or at least the
United States)? HOW did we become so dependent _ seemingly
overnight _ on double-clicking a mouse? When did computer viruses
start getting more headlines than the kind that send us to the
doctor?
</P>
<P>
   To answer such questions, we provide an Internet time line,
spotlighting milestones that have made the Net what it is today:
invaluable _ and virtually inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1950s-60s: Panicked by the Soviets beating us into space, the
U.S. Defense Department in 1957 forms the Advance Research Projects
Agency (ARPA), a technical team whose job is to beef up the
burgeoning federal computer system. This leads to the
establishment, a dozen years later, of ARPAnet, the first
decentralized computer network for sharing data. Research centers
and universities quickly begin to join ARPAnet.
</P>
<P>
   1969: Doug Englebart, a researcher at Stanford, comes up with
several ``far-out ideas,'' including the computer mouse and live,
interactive TV pictures. No one outside Englebart's family notices.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 1, 1969: The first e-mail message is sent by a team of
computer gurus at UCLA to another team at Stanford Research
Institute. The message is ``LOG IN.'' One letter is sent at a time
_ first ``L,'' then ``O,'' etc. The system crashes on ``G.''
</P>
<P>
   1975: Working out of their garages, twentysomethings Paul Allen
and Bill Gates form Microsoft in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Early to mid-1980s: The sniff of digital money is in the air,
even if it's very faint. The first Internet providers are launched,
including CompuServe, Genie and Quantum, which would be renamed
America Online and reacquaint us with the busy signal.
</P>
<P>
   1989: Tim Berners-Lee, who works at a Swiss particle physics
institute, comes up with the idea of the World Wide Web to share
physics research.
</P>
<P>
   Early to mid-1990s: The number of Internet users soars to 1
million. Building on Berners-Lee's World Wide Web program, the
first graphics-based Web browser, Mosaic, is unveiled, for the
first time giving the Net more than rudimentary visuals. With the
Internet freed from its text-based corset, sex-related sites soon
proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   1994: Netscape is co-founded by Marc Andreessen, the key figure
in the creation of Mosaic. Netscape Navigator quickly becomes the
dominant Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   1994-95: The White House goes online. Dorm-room Webcams help
spur the reality-programming rage that will lead to ``Who Wants To
Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' and ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   1995: Companies that are suddenly considered ``old media''
(read: newspapers and magazines, even TV networks) rush to get
online in a big way, and the marketing of the Net kicks into high
gear. Microsoft launches the Microsoft Network. Many insiders
predict that Gates' innovative MSN will crush AOL within a year. It
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   1996-98: Entertainment, retail and business-to-business
applications push the Internet's original purpose, research, into
the background. With the economy booming, individual investing
online becomes a phenomenon. Cyberhoaxes (Did you read the
``transcript'' of the Columbia astronauts on their ill-fated
launch?) proliferate. Computer games displace video games in
popularity. Michael Jackson and Paul McCartney simulcast Web-only
concerts; retail sites such as Amazon.com make buying CDs and books
on the Web easy. And, oh yes, did we mention sex? Although most
content sites operate at a deficit, online porn peddlers can't
count the money fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   1999-present: Online music community Napster, which allows
anyone with a computer to download and store music without paying
for it, is banned at several college campuses and sued by the band
Metallica, the Recording Industry of America and other
music-related organizations. The Commerce Department reports that
the Internet has contributed to 30 percent of U.S. economic growth
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   (Sources: ``Nerds 2.0 _ A Brief History of the Internet,'' by
Stephen Segaller, ``The Internet: The Rough Guide 2000,'' by Angus
J. Kennedy, and stuff on the Internet. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
