<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HERB-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE HERB, LINKED TO KIDNEY FAILURE, MAY ALSO CAUSE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a harsh example of the dangers of untested and unregulated
herbal products, doctors are reporting that a Chinese herb, already
linked to kidney failure, may cause cancer as well.
</P>
<P>
   The herb, Aristolochia fangchi, was given to patients at a
weight-loss clinic in Belgium from 1990 to 1992, according to a
report being published Thursday in the New England Journal of
Medicine. By 1993 more than 100 had kidney damage, and so far, more
than 70 have needed either transplants or dialysis. Now,
substantial numbers are also developing cancers of the urinary
tract.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of kidney failure from this herb have also been reported
in France, the United Kingdom, Spain, Japan and Taiwan. Dr.
Christine Lewis, director of the office of nutritional products,
labeling and dietary supplements at the Food and Drug
Administration, said there had been no reports of Americans being
harmed by Aristolochia. She also said the FDA did not know how much
of the herb might be on the market in this country.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, the FDA sent letters to doctors and to the
supplement industry, with a 6-page list of herbal remedies known or
suspected of containing Aristolochia. The agency urged
manufacturers to test their products for the presence of the herb.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks, importation of the herb, including every
item on the 6-page list, will be banned, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Cardellina, vice president for botanicals at the
Council for Responsible Nutrition, a trade group for the supplement
industry, said Aristolochia was found in some traditional Chinese
medicinal mixtures, but in few other products. Nonetheless, he
said, because Aristolochia is so extremely dangerous, the
supplement industry supports the FDA's decision to list every item
that might possibly contain the herb.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs, amino acids, vitamins and other ``supplements,'' a $15
billion industry, are largely unregulated. Unlike drugs, they do
not have to be proved safe and effective before they are marketed,
and no outside agency even checks to make sure that the products
actually contain the ingredients on the label. Regulation is
lacking because in 1994, Congress passed the 1994 Dietary
Supplement Health and Education Act, which cut back the authority
of the the Food and Drug Administration. Under that law, the FDA
does not have have the authority to take supplements off the market
until they are proved dangerous, in which case people may already
have been harmed.
</P>
<P>
   A report being published Thursday in the New England Journal of
Medicine describes 39 patients given transplants or dialysis at
Erasme Hospital in Brussels, by a team led by Dr. Joelle L.
Nortier. Eighteen of the 39 have also developed cancers of the
urinary system. Nineteen others have abnormal cells in the urinary
tract, possibly precancers.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial accompanying the article, Dr. David Kessler,
former head of the FDA and now dean of the Yale School of Medicine,
called the prevalence of tumors ``striking.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler also noted that Aristolochia could still be purchased in
the United States. He said he bought a bottle of Aristolochia
capsules, sold as ``Virginia Snakeroot,'' from an American supplier
via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In his editorial, Kessler urged Congress to change the law to
give the FDA more power over supplements.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, Aristolochia was given to patients by mistake;
doctors had prescribed another herb, but the product that patients
received was later found to contain Aristolochia, possibly because
of a manufacturing error. On average, patients took it for about a
year. Those who took highest amounts were most likely to develop
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Aristolochia contains compounds called aristolochic acids, which
are known to damage the kidneys and to cause cancer in lab rats.
The herb was traditionally used in Chinese medicine for a variety
of ailments, but about 25 years ago German researchers found it to
be highly toxic, according to Dr. Varro E. Tyler, an expert on
herbal medicine at Purdue University. Nonetheless, he said, some
manufacturers in China continue to use it.
</P>
<P>
   When a Belgian patient developed cancer, doctors there tested
the other kidney-failure patients for cancer. A high proportion, 18
of 39, had cancer in the kidney, bladder or ureter, the tube
connecting the kidney and bladder. Nineteen other patients had
abnormal cells, possibly precancers, in the urinary tract.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tissue from every patient had ``DNA adducts'' from
Aristolochia, meaning that molecules derived from the herb had
attached themselves to the patients' genetic material. Adducts can
interfere with DNA function, and are thought to increase the risk
of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said the high incidence of abnormal cells and adducts
even in the patients without tumors was worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   The warning letters and list of products that might contain
Aristolochia can be seen on the FDA Web site, www.fda.gov, by
clicking on ``What's New'' and then on ``dietary supplements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
