<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7242 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ECKERT-THEATER-$ADV11     06-07 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECKERT-THEATER-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MOBY-DICK BUT WHALE-ISH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Iowa, Conn., Wash., Calif.)   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
 By DON SHEWEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reviewers have often commented on Rinde Eckert's
remarkable stage presence. ``He's tall and bald and he looks a good
deal like an overgrown elf,'' a San Francisco critic once wrote.
``But when he opens his mouth to sing, it's as if there's an angel
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rockwell, writing in The New York Times in 1988, referred
to the persona that emerges from Eckert's texts as that of ``an
American loner-eccentric, with touches of Bertolt Brecht, Samuel
Beckett and Tom Waits.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckert is currently enacting the latest version of this persona
in ``And God Created Great Whales,'' which opens Sunday night in a
world premiere at Dance Theater Workshop's Bessie Schonberg
Theater, where it plays through June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Although inspired by a certain whaling epic by another American
loner-eccentric, Eckert said in a recent interview: ``I'm not
interested in doing `Moby-Dick.' Melville did that very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 80-minute music-theater piece, in which he sings,
speaks and plays the piano and ukulele, ``stands in a clear
relation to the epic but ramifies it in completely different
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   As the youngest of four children born to two music teachers
(Rinde _ pronounced RIN-dee _ is his mother's maiden name), Eckert
practically grew up on the stage. At the age of 8, he went
backstage at intermission to visit his father, who was performing
in ``La Boheme'' at the Amato Opera Company on the Bowery, and
found himself conscripted to play one of the children in the second
act. For him, nothing could have been more natural.
</P>
<P>
   When he went to college at the University of Iowa, his plan was
to study theater. Midway through, however, he found himself annoyed
by the lack of specificity in the training and switched to music,
``because they had a technique they were actually teaching you,''
Eckert recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were asking concrete questions about mechanics and
structure,'' he continued. ``Most of the theater departments I knew
were all over the place. They had no consistent philosophy. I
thought, how is it possible for an intelligent person to arrange
himself idiosyncratically in relation to this emotional chaos?''
</P>
<P>
   That existential question, framed early, could serve as a
unifying theme for the entire body of work the 48-year-old Eckert
has written, performed, directed, composed or recorded in the last
15 years. From the collaborations with the composer Paul Dresher
that began in 1985 with ``Slow Fire'' to Steven Mackey's 1998
two-act solo opera ``Ravenshead,'' Eckert has invented a series of
variations on the character of a smart, slightly cockeyed Everyman
who begins his journey with a pure sense of mission and descends
into the maelstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``And God Created Great Whales'' was conceived several years ago
during a conversation between Eckert and W. David Hancock, the
author of several wildly unconventional Off Off Broadway plays
(including ``The Convention of Cartography'' and ``The Race of the
Ark Tattoo''). Hancock had been in a workshop the performer taught
at the University of Iowa. Impressed with a show called ``The
Gardening of Thomas D.,'' Eckert's adaptation of Dante's ``Divine
Comedy,'' Hancock proposed that they tackle ``Moby-Dick'' together.
Although Hancock did not continue with the project, he did
introduce Eckert to his producer, Melanie Joseph, of the Foundry
Theater, who commissioned ``And God Created Great Whales.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically for Eckert, the work that resulted is several layers
removed from Herman Melville. ``As I did with Dante, I wanted to
find my own way in,'' he said. ``In this case, as I was thinking of
things quintessentially American, I started reading essays by the
leading proponents of 19th-century American pragmatism _ Charles
Sanders Peirce, William James. That led me to thinking about
manufacturing pragmatism and the development of the industrial
standard. Things we take for granted, like the size and shape of
the television screen, were actually decided by some guys sitting
around in a room.''
</P>
<P>
   Translating the notion of an industrial standard into musical
terms led Eckert to consider the development of the standard tuning
that allowed for the creation of a piano keyboard. The hero of the
piece became a piano tuner with a degenerative disease who
struggles to complete his life's work, an opera based on
``Moby-Dick,'' before he loses his memory completely. For this
character, whose name is Nathan, the great white whale is
represented at various times by the piano, by the blank page facing
the composer and by memory itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ends up disappearing into his own opera,'' Eckert
explained. ``As his mind goes down for the last time, he becomes
Ahab and goes down with the whale, never to be seen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckert is aware that tackling ``Moby-Dick'' may conjure
inevitable comparisons to Laurie Anderson, who last year presented
her own fractured take on Melville's classic, ``Songs and Stories
From Moby-Dick.'' Both are the type of multi-talented individuals
the term performance art was invented to describe, although
Anderson came to music from the visual arts while Eckert is steeped
in classical music traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performance art is a critical name for people who perform
their own work that doesn't fit into conventional categories,''
Dresher, the composer, said by telephone from his studio in
Berkeley, Calif. ``Most performance artists express their unique
artistry by combining elements of different disciplines, none of
which they master. The difference with Rinde is that he comes from
an extremely disciplined training as singer, musician and theater
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckert was born in Franklin Lakes, N.J., and received a master's
degree at Yale University, expecting to become an opera singer.
Although he spent four years after graduation studying with the
soprano Phyllis Curtin, he found that he was not spiritually
well-suited for the world of traditional opera. So he followed his
sister Thomasa to Seattle, where they formed the New Performance
Group. They created a piece with George Coates, a San
Francisco-based director, who coaxed Eckert to the Bay Area to help
create ``The Way of How,'' with Dresher, the tenor John Duykers and
the dancer-mime Leonard Pitt. The nonnarrative multimedia show was
a hit and put all of them on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Although Eckert admired Coates' spectacle-based kind of theater
(Robert Wilson and Philip Glass' ``Einstein on the Beach,'' he
said, ``changed my notion of what theater could be''), he soon
found that he preferred making chamber pieces. Over the course of
10 years, he and Dresher collaborated on 12 works that blurred the
lines between theater and dance, between rock and classical music.
Not all of these pieces have been critically well-received, and his
first attempt to direct a piece himself (``Odd Behavior'') was a
resounding failure. Yet his multiple skills and willingness to try
new things helped make Eckert a legendary figure in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my learning has taken place in public,'' said Eckert,
who moved to New York five years ago with his wife, the playwright
and actress Ellen McLaughlin, who portrayed the angel in the
original production of Tony Kushner's ``Angels in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the contract with myself: I'm interested in learning.
If you're interested in learning, you have to take your lumps. If
you don't want to take your lumps, then you don't want to learn. If
you don't want to learn, you're not going to grow. And if you're
not going to grow, you're going to be bored. And I don't want to be
bored.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
