<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-DADS-DAY-GIFTS0608-CO     06-07 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADS-DAY-GIFTS0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tools, gadgets always make good gifts for Father's Day
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Father's day rolls around June 18, a little more
than a week from now. If you want to buy a tool or gadget gift for
Dad or some other Dad-like person in your life, this weekend would
be a good time to shop.
</P>
<P>
   You can go with anything from a set of screwdrivers from the
nearest anything-for-a-dollar store to a $10,000 gas grill, so you
won't lack choices when looking for father-appropriate gear. But
all that variety may make selecting one thing tough.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion in this kind of situation is that you ask the
potential recipient what he might like.
</P>
<P>
   I personally don't care much for surprises and would find it
hard to work up much enthusiasm if someone spent $700 to buy me a
propane-powered mosquito catcher. Such a device turned up among the
press kits for products being promoted as Father's Day gifts this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few suggestions for gifts that cost less and would
probably be appreciated more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rotary tool: These handy little items for anyone who enjoys
detail work are like small power drills. The cylindrical body of
the tool fits comfortably in one hand, and it spins a variety of
drilling, cutting, grinding and polishing tools.
</P>
<P>
   A rotary tool fitted with an engraving bit can mark your name
and Social Security number onto expensive electronic equipment.
Insert a sanding bit, and a rotary tool can strip paint from old
furniture or smooth a wooden sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Variable-speed rotary tools of various brands are sold in kits
with a few starter bits for about $60 to $125. If your gift
recipient already has a rotary tool, hundreds of accessories are
available.
</P>
<P>
   For larger projects, the indispensable tool for the home
handyman is a variable-speed drill-driver. If you don't want to ask
the recipient which of the hundreds of models he would prefer, make
a list of jobs he has done or would like to do to and ask a
knowledgeable salesperson which drills best fit those duties.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lawn tools: The lawn tool that gets the most use is the mower,
but many homeowners could also use hedge trimmers, weed cutters,
edgers, snow throwers, leaf blowers, chipper/shredders and
cultivators.
</P>
<P>
   Assess what your lawn keeper might use before heading to the
lawn-equipment retailer. A cultivator suitable for a two-acre
vegetable garden wouldn't be much use to a guy who only turns soil
in a small flower bed once a year.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also need to make choices about power supplies. The
simplest way to power tools for a small yard is to plug them in
using an outdoor extension cord. Electricity from a nearby outlet
supplies all the power you'll need for most light-duty tools, and
it's relatively inexpensive and convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Rechargeable tools are an option if your property is so large
that stretching a cord to reach the weeds at the back fence would
be a problem. But remember that rechargeable tools are generally
heavier and more expensive, and they can go dead in the middle of a
job.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline-powered tools are also available, but they, too, tend
to be expensive and heavy. Gasoline motors on small lawn tools are
a major source of air and noise pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Closely related to lawn tools are compressor tools. Power
washers, for example, come in handy for cleaning driveways, washing
cars, washing windows and other jobs that require spraying large
quantities of water under pressure. Small electric models start at
about $150, and gas-powered models suitable for home use start
between $175 and $500 Compressors also come in handy for painting
and blowing up tires and volleyballs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Books: A good home-improvement book or two can increase your
handyman's handy-ness significantly. My favorite do-it-yourself
book publisher is Meredith Books, and it released a good one this
year: ``Ortho's Home Improvement Encyclopedia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ortho book covers subjects from making houses
handicapped-accessible to obtaining zoning permits. It offers more
than 800 color illustrations explaining how things work around the
house. The book seems to be geared more toward building and
remodeling and is light on routine maintenance topics such as
unstopping a sink or fixing a squeaking floor.
</P>
<P>
   For that kind of information, a good recent book is ``Better
Homes and Gardens New Complete Guide to Home Repair and
Improvement,'' also from Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Little gifts: Children and others on a tight budget still can
afford a tool gift for Father's Day. In fact, the hardware aisle of
any discount store is a great place to shop for small gifts for any
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things you might consider are work gloves, tape
measures, socket wrench sets, tool belts and aprons, work lights
and flashlights, vises and work benches, tool boxes, soldering
irons and glue guns, hammers and other hand tools.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb here is to buy something a step up from what
Dad uses now. If he's already got a 12-volt rechargeable drill, a
new 9-volt drill may not impress him.
</P>
<P>
   But if he's currently driving nails with a rock, the simplest
hammer in the store probably would be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
