<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FOOD-DIETICIAN0608-CO     06-07 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DIETICIAN0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Go ahead, eat your spinach
 &HT;    By Karen Collins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that people with osteoporosis should avoid
spinach?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not true at all. That idea probably started with someone who
heard that spinach contains oxalate, which binds up the calcium in
spinach making only about a quarter of it actually available to the
body. Getting enough calcium in a form that can be well-absorbed is
an important part of preventing or slowing the progression of
osteoporosis. Spinach does not contain enough oxalate to bind up
all the calcium you get from other foods, however, so there's no
reason to avoid it. Dark green leafy vegetables such as spinach and
kale ae excellent sources of beta carotene and other carotenoids,
folate (which may help prevent cancer and other health problems)
and minerals such as magnesium and potassium.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that olive oil should be stored in the
refrigerator?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Olive oil producers say that it should maintain its
quality for one year if stored in a tightly closed container in a
cool, dark place such as a pantry. In other words, a refrigerator
is not necessary, but don't store it in a cabinet right over your
stove. Some people find that it stays fresher if refrigerated
during hot months, but that is on the basis of personal preference,
not food safety. Refrigerated olive oil gets cloudy, but it clears
when brought to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the sweetener aspartame cause damage to nerves or
metabolism?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Aspartame (listed on many labels as NutraSweet) has been
tested many times, and no such effects show up. People with the
rare illness PKU cannot properly metabolize this sweetener, and
some people seem to react negatively to it for unknown reasons. But
that is no different than people who cannot tolerate tomatoes, MSG
or orange juice; it doesn't make those things less healthy for the
rest of us. Studies in recent years have looked for brain and
nervous system changes that might result from aspartame, and none
have been found. As with all foods, moderation is common sense. And
remember that just because foods sweetened with aspartame may be
low in calories, that doesn't make them ``health foods'' to load up
on at the expense of other healthy foods, such as the fruits and
vegetables that Americans chronically eat in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``Plant-based diets'' are said to be the healthiest, but
aren't they fattening with all those starchy foods?
</P>
<P>
   A: Plant-based diets _ diets centered on vegetables, fruits and
grains _ are the best advice for good health. Low-fat, balanced
eating combined with regular exercise and weight control could
prevent 30 percent to 40 percent of cancers. Fat and alcohol are
the most concentrated sources of calories, so as long as your
portions are appropriate and the plant foods you choose are not
soaked with fat (like deep-fried veggies or rich croissants), a
healthy, mostly plant-based diet should help, not hurt, weight
control. Remember how to balance food choices: A mostly plant-based
diet is not just high in bread, pasta and other grains; it also
includes lots of fruits and vegetables. Most vegetables contain
only 30 percent to 50 percent of the calories in an equal size
serving of a grain, so besides providing essential nutrients,
vegetables are an important part of weight control. A recent study
at Cornell University found that plant-based diets may cause
changes in metabolism that add up to preventing about 10 pounds of
weight gain per year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
