<HEADER>
A7245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLYMPIC-FLAME-1     06-07 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-FLAME-1,100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A TORCH AND A PEOPLE'S PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ Walk through the modest front door of
Nova Peris-Kneebone's Victorian home and you soon come face to
frame with a picture of Muhammad Ali standing on a stage next to
Peris-Kneebone's young daughter Jessica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melbourne 1998 just after the Commonwealth Games,''
Peris-Kneebone explains proudly. ``He was in a boxing ring here for
an appearance, and the people who brought him here, they introduced
us to Muhammad and brought Jessie up on stage, and you know he has
this affiliation with children. So he went straight up to Jessie
and held her hand and would not let it go. It was unbelievable, a
very special moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is more linking Ali and Peris-Kneebone than a small
child's grasp. In 1996, when the Summer Olympics were last held,
Ali was the last person to carry the torch. Trembling from disease,
he lit the Olympic flame during the Opening Ceremony in Atlanta,
sending goose bumps down Peris-Kneebone's and a lot of other
spines.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly four years later, it is her turn to play a leading
role, and on June 8 in Australia, when the flame arrives at the
sacred Aboriginal site of Uluru to begin a 100-day tour of the
sprawling continent before reaching Sydney, Peris-Kneebone will be
the first Australian to carry it when it is unloaded from the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   She will do so with the massive and magnificent red monolith _
dubbed Ayers Rock by the white European settlers but long called
Uluru by the Aboriginals _ looming telegenically in the background.
She will do so because Sydney Olympic organizers, eager to project
an inclusive and updated vision of Australia, found her
multifaceted, multicultural background irresistible even though
other Australian athletes have accomplished more. confident that
this moment, her moment, will have resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have an Aboriginal person carrying that flame is going to
make a hell of a lot of people very proud,'' Peris-Kneebone said
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to it than her rich brown skin; there is the
content of her character and of her resume. At 29, Peris-Kneebone
is a mother, an artist and a world-class sportswoman in the midst
of a career change. In 1996 in Atlanta, she became the first
athlete of Aboriginal descent (she also has Filipino and European
ancestors) to win an Olympic gold medal, as a member of the
Australian women's field hockey team. Several months later, she
retired from hockey and decided to train to become an elite
sprinter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was to show you my scrapbook as a kid, track and field
was my first love,'' she said. ''And that's what I'm going after
this year: my first childhood love.''
</P>
<P>
   After surprising the field and herself to win the gold medal in
the 200 meters at the 1998 Commonwealth Games, she is now focusing
her energies on the 200 and the 400 in the lead-up to the much more
competitive races in Sydney. Though her chances of an individual
gold medal are extremely slim _ her goal is to reach a final _ she
and an even more prominent Aboriginal runner, Cathy Freeman, could
win a medal together if Peris-Kneebone manages to qualify for the
4-by-400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she can do it,'' said Freeman, who won a silver medal
in the 400 in Atlanta and has won the last two world titles over
the distance. ``No matter what happens, I have a lot of respect for
Nova, because she's very courageous. She chases her dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The chase has sometimes resembled an obstacle course. Born in
1971, Peris- Kneebone and her younger sister were raised by their
mother, a single parent, in a two-bedroom house in Darwin in
Australia's Northern Territory. When Peris-Kneebone was 10, her
mother remarried and, according to Peris-Kneebone, the atmosphere
changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stepfather was a policeman, a very hard, strict man,'' she
said. ``I was really stubborn as a kid and him coming into our
lives at such a late stage, he was stubborn and I was stubborn and
he had to sort of chase me down to grab hold of me. There was none
of that sit in the corner and face the wall kind of thing. I was
always being chased across the road with a strap. But he was fair.
He hated lying, so as a kid, if you ever told a fib, you got the
belt. If you told the truth, it was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   At 13, largely because of a dearth of track and field programs
in Darwin, Peris-Kneebone focused her energies on field hockey, a
popular sport throughout Australia, and was soon one of the best
prospects in the country. But at 19, she gave birth to Jessica in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole 12 months after Jessie was born, I was just happy
being a mum,'' she said. ``It wasn't until 1991 that I thought,
`The dream is still there: if you want, you can go after it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The following year, she moved with Jessica to the western city
of Perth, where the national hockey team trains. She took a job
with the Australian telephone company and juggled day care,
practice and part-time employment while Jessica's father and
Peris-Kneebone's future husband, Sean Kneebone, remained in Darwin
attempting to build a career of his own in case her hockey career
foundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd put Jessie up in the stands with her coloring books or
dolls and a little lunch box and drinks,'' Peris-Kneebone said.
``There were times on Tuesday evenings, I'd have psychology
meetings and she'd come and sit underneath the table with a
coloring book and the other girls in the room wouldn't even know
she was there. She was just so quiet and did her own thing. She'll
be one of those people when she gets older who will love sport or
hate it, because she's seen the hard work that goes into me
achieving, seen all the highs and lows.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Kneebones divide their time between their rented
house full of photographs in Melbourne and their family and
spiritual base in Darwin. Aboriginal people represent approximately
2 percent of Australia's population of about 19 million but they
make up approximately 20 percent of the population in the Northern
Territory and own about one-fourth of the property because of the
Aboriginal Land Rights Act passed in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Aboriginal landowners are called ``traditional owners'' in
Australia, and Peris-Kneebone is a traditional owner in Kakadu
National Park, where she often fishes, camps and hunts with her
family. As a custodian of the land, Peris-Kneebone is in regular
contact with tribal elders, including her biological father, with
whom she had virtually no contact until he came to visit her after
Jessica's birth. Her father lives a traditional, seminomadic
aboriginal life style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, I spent 18 years apart from him and yet we are so
much alike in so many ways,'' she said. ``I never see him with a
watch on his wrist because time doesn't matter. He's lived out in
really harsh places on the Coburg Peninsula, living off the land
for eight months at a time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   It is on her people's land and with her father that
Peris-Kneebone has worked through her problems in the last two
years. First came her post-Commonwealth Games depression in late
1998, when she quickly grew weary of the interest in her private
life that accompanied her increased celebrity. It was all very
petty to Peris-Kneebone _ complaints that she wore too much gold
jewelry or that she had grown too arrogant for a society that
values egalitarianism. Irritated, she considered returning to the
more anonymous existence of a hockey team member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem getting criticized for my performances, but
when they start to get into my personal life, I have a problem,''
she said. ``I have a daughter who goes to school and has to face
the music and people saying, `Is this true about your mum?' And she
gets really upset about it, and I'd had a gut-full, an absolute
gut-full of the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was all ready to go back to hockey,'' Sean said. ``It was
all done and then about a week before it was announced, she was
watching video of the Commonwealth Games final and just turned
around and said, `I can't do this. I'd be quitting, leaving the
sport for the wrong reasons.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There have been calls from many Aboriginal leaders to use the
Games as a platform for increasing international awareness of the
intense discrimination Aboriginals faced after European settlement
in the 18th and 19th centuries. Aboriginals were only granted full
citizenship in 1967, and even now, their life spans are nearly 20
years lower on average than the rest of the Australian population,
while unemployment, child mortality and criminality rates are
significantly higher.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's attitudes and policies toward Aboriginals have
evolved considerably, but Peris-Kneebone knows there is more
progress to be made. Yet she often feels divided: eager to
capitalize on a unique opportunity and spread the word; worried
about spreading herself thin and missing out on her athletic goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some discussion of a boycott, but the grass
roots people tell us to run, tell us, `You're the one that inspires
our children and gives hope to our race.''' Peris-Kneebone said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there will certainly be Aboriginal protests of some
type at the Games in September, and there could also be some form
of protest at Uluru when Peris-Kneebone becomes the first of 10,000
Australians, including the golfer Greg Norman, to run with the
torch. Peris-Kneebone understands there is anger out there, but for
now she is more interested in carrying flames than fanning them.
And when she's asked what message she wants to convey to the world
100 days before the Olympics begin, she harkens back to a
conversation she and Sean had not long ago with one of the grizzled
elders from Kakadu known as Old Man Bill. The conversation started
out being about Peris-Kneebone's gold medals but it ended up being
about something more universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the sudden he sort of looked at Sean and said, `Do you
want to learn?''' Peris-Kneebone said. ``And Sean told him, `Yeah I
want to learn, and Old Man Bill told him, `No matter what color
skin you got, we all got the same color blood.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
