<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7247 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BONJOVI-SURVIVING-TEX     06-07 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONJOVI-SURVIVING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BON JOVI HAS KEPT THE PEDAL TO THE LITE-METAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, at the height of his first wave of commercial
success, singer Jon Bon Jovi would never be on the phone at 9 a.m.
talking to a reporter _ on a Monday, no less.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the singer and his band were busy indulging in the
typical rock-star, live-it-up lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every cliche you can think of associated with being a rock
star, we absolutely indulged in it,'' says Jon, calling from a pit
stop on Bon Jovi's current tour, the first in five years. ``Talk
about giving me the key to the candy store. I was 25 years old and
a multimillionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   The money remains, even if the memory is sometimes a bit
sketchy. The group's album sales in the '80s, most of which came
from the massively popular 1986 disc ``Slippery When Wet,'' made
his future secure. But the New Jersey-based rocker, and the band
that uses his last name as its moniker, are still around and proud
of their music. The band has considerably changed, the 38-year-old
singer says, and for the better. Everyone's older now, the partying
has stopped and Jon and his crew have something other than partying
on the mind _ namely, is Bon Jovi's forthcoming disc, ``Crush,''
gonna sell in a very non-metal-friendly musical atmosphere? That's
why Jon's talking to reporters at 9 in the morning, trying to hype
the disc and the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new world out there,'' Jon says.
</P>
<P>
   Bon Jovi seems well-prepared, though, because not only has the
band endured, it has matured. Other groups of its ilk have
disappeared or reduced themselves to playing the nostalgia circuit.
Bon Jovi has remained active, grown musically and, even more
important and impressive, remained popular _ with a wide-ranging
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're able to transcend time through their music,'' says
Island/Def Jam Music chairman Jim Caparro, who has worked with the
band for 12 years. ``And emotionally and creatively, they're in
step with what's going on in music today. They're not Korn or Kid
Rock or Limp Bizkit, but in the world of rock and roll, they remain
as credible as you get, if only because their music is honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stevens, program director for North Texas rock station
KEGL, says it's Jon's combination of musical prowess and smarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only talented, but he has a lot of business savvy,''
says Stevens, who has been in radio 21 years and interviewed Bon
Jovi in San Antonio on its first tour in 1982. ``He does have
personal charisma and he's smart enough to have exploited that, not
only in videos, but through his solo career and movies. He's
working it. He always has.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon would like to think it's the lyrics, the simple phrasings
and stories that chronicle the everyday lives of everyday people.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people relate to songs that have touched them in their
lives, they become memories,'' he says. ``Those memories are looked
back on, hopefully fondly. I'm not trying to rewrite ``Slippery''
for you now. I'm telling you who I am now. And hopefully, I'm
creating new memories, and hopefully that'll draw people back to me
10 more years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Jon Bongiovi in New Jersey, the singer was never much for
school; he ditched a lot, spending a good chunk of his time hanging
at a local recording studio, the Power Station, where he was
eventually hired as a janitor.
</P>
<P>
   There, he met several famous musicians, including members of
Bruce Springsteen's E-Street Band. Egged on by his new-found
musician pals, Jon started recording his own demos, including a
track called ``Runaway,'' which wound up in the hands of an
influential New Jersey radio station and, eventually, major labels.
</P>
<P>
   When the song took off, Jon formed a band to nourish the song; a
major-label bidding war ensued, with Mercury coming away the
winner. To downplay his ethnic background, Jon changed his last
name and the band's name to Bon Jovi.
</P>
<P>
   Success came fast: ``Runaway,'' the first single from the band's
self-titled debut, was just that, quickly becoming a Top 40 hit. A
year later, the group followed up with ``7800 Degrees Fahrenheit,''
which went gold. To strengthen their burgeoning fan base, the guys
toured and made several TV appearances, including one on disco show
``Solid Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Slippery When Wet,'' the band's 1986 third disc, ushered in a
whole new wave of popularity at the height of the metal-pop era.
Songs like ``You Give Love a Bad Name'' and ``Wanted Dead or
Alive'' became rock-radio staples, while the band tinkered with its
image. Soon the spandex and big hair were gone, replaced with jeans
and T-shirts. As a result, Jon's photogenic mug started popping up
everywhere, overshadowing, to some extent, the band's music. It's a
problem he has had to deal with ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when that was just heartbreaking,'' he says.
``We worked so hard to get where we were, and then the first time
we were on the cover of Rolling Stone, all anyone could talk about
was my haircut.''
</P>
<P>
   His good looks helped keep the music alive during the lean years
that followed, when grunge and then teen pop left the band
searching for an audience. When their records weren't in demand (he
also put out a solo CD that tanked in the mid-'90s), Jon made
movies, like this summer's ``U-571,'' which reminded people that he
was still very much around.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the movies were utter bombs, Jon says he
wouldn't change a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back on everything I've done and the band's done very
fondly,'' he says. ``I made a coupla minor stupid mistakes. I
should have zigged when I zagged. But there are no car crashes or
drug addicts in our story. Our ``Behind the Music'' has a happy
ending.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDUL/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
