<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-WOHLERS-NYT &LR;      06-07 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WOHLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER AND WOHLERS PASSING IN THE NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The baseball paths of John Rocker and Mark Wohlers first crossed
in May 1998. Wohlers, the Atlanta Braves' closer, went on the
disabled list, and Rocker was recalled from Richmond to replace him
on the roster. Three weeks later, Wohlers rejoined the Braves,
Rocker remained and the two briefly were teammates. Two years
later, they are opponents, pitching in the International League.
</P>
<P>
   What an unlikely development, not to mention coincidence, but
there they are, Wohlers relieving for the Louisville Riverbats, on
his way back to the major leagues, his control seemingly restored;
Rocker on his way to pitch for the Richmond Braves, demoted to the
minor leagues, having lost control of his pitches and his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   At least some, if not most, of the members of the Braves would
be happy if Rocker were never to rejoin them. On the other hand,
they are rooting for Wohlers to make it back, even if it is with
the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wohlers would be the consensus guy,'' a general manager of
another team said Tuesday, commenting on the feelings about each
reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers' former teammates, as well as other players, pull for
him because he has always been a good person, a good guy, and he
was the victim of a mystifying loss of control of his pitches. En
route to a brilliant career as a closer, Wohlers suddenly couldn't
throw strikes. A performance that produced 97 saves over three
seasons deteriorated into one that created 33 walks in 201/3 and
one-third innings in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A similar performance of 25 walks in 18 and one-third innings
created cover for the Braves to send Rocker to the minors, giving
him time for a refresher course on the strike zone and a more
important course on behavior in life. Had Wohlers not lost the
strike zone and forced the Braves to replace him, first with Kerry
Ligtenberg, then with Rocker, Rocker would not have been in a
position to take on New York's baiting fans last season, then the
world in a magazine interview last winter.
</P>
<P>
   But while Rocker's world is an unappetizing place to live, the
new world Wohlers has discovered is filled with fresh and
sweet-smelling air. Wohlers's agent, Seth Levinson, told Tuesday of
the delight with which his client related details of his
performance of the previous night. With a 2-1 count on the
Scranton-Wilkes Barre cleanup hitter, Wohlers threw a 96
mile-an-hour fastball on the black on one side of the plate, then
fired another 96 mile-an-hour fastball on the black on the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Wohlers, nearing the end of his rehabilitation
from so-called Tommy John elbow surgery 11 months ago, was making
his first appearance for Class AAA Louisville after three outings
for Class A Dayton. The Reds, who use relief pitchers like chain
smokers use cigarettes, eagerly await his arrival in Cincinnati.
Before they make the move, though, the Reds want to see Wohlers
relieve in consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be another 10 days, a week; they haven't put any
definite timetable on it,'' the pitcher told The Louisville
Courier-Journal. ``And it depends on how I do. There are a lot of
good hitters in this league. You can't just come down here, think
you're going to get your arm in shape and go straight up to the big
leagues. You have to prove yourself at each level you're at. I just
want to stay healthy and throw strikes, no matter where I'm at.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker would do well to heed Wohler's words. If he approaches
his appearances with Richmond with the angry attitude with which he
seemed to have departed from the Atlanta clubhouse Monday, he could
set back the nonexistent timetable the Braves have for his return
to their clubhouse. Now what a shame that would be.
</P>
<P>
   It is premature to talk about Wohlers's return to the majors; he
has suffered too many setbacks in his two-year effort to jump ahead
of his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing at speeds up to 97 mph in his appearance on Monday,
Wohlers threw strikes on 10 of his 18 pitches, struck out two
batters, walked one and gave up one hit. Dave Miley, the Louisville
manager, said Wohlers ``threw the heck out of the ball.'' The
pitcher's only concern, he said, was his inability to throw his
slider where he wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he said, ``I feel like it's a matter of getting
my slider going. I threw a couple good sliders for guys to swing
and miss, but not good for being in the strike zone. That's the one
pitch giving me a little bit of trouble right now. That's something
that will come with time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers is not prepared to talk in depth about his problems and
his comeback, his agent said. He has not proved anything yet. He
wants to know he's back before he talks about getting back. But how
delightful it would be to have Wohlers pitching in relief for the
Reds, saving games for the Reds. He has worked hard to make it
back.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's work has only begun. But then, he hasn't shown that he
wants to work at changing the attitude that created his problems. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1648EDT &QL; 
