<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CIGARETTES08-COX     06-07 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILLS AIM AT CURBING SALE OF 'GRAY MARKET' CIGARETTES
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Gray market'' tobacco has cost U.S. farmers and
wholesalers millions of dollars in the past four years, according
to members of Congress who introduced bills Wednesday that would
make its sale in the United States illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Gray market tobacco is tobacco that is sent abroad for sale in
foreign countries, but then is returned to the United States and is
sold here.
</P>
<P>
   Gray market cigarettes do not meet the required U.S. laws for
content and labeling, and are about $10 a carton cheaper than
cigarettes made to be sold domestically, said Rep. E. Clay Shaw
Jr., R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., said sales of gray market cigarettes in
the United States increased from 48 million in 1998 to 97 million
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said that these cigarettes cut into money that states will
receive from their settlement with the tobacco companies by
reducing sales of domestic cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to settlement payments, domestic tobacco sales have
recently decreased by 14.7 percent, and during the same period of
time gray market sales accounted for 16 percent of total tobacco
sales,'' Shaw said. ``The similarity of these percentages is
telling.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ron Lewis, R-Ky., said gray market cigarettes violate U.S.
trademark laws and also reduce payments for tobacco farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loophole in the law allows these cigarettes to get back on
the U.S. market,'' Lewis said. ``It has also reduced payments for
farmers in Kentucky by as much as 45 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill was introduced in the Senate by Sen. Kent Conrad,
D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will ensure that cheap cigarettes don't end
up in the hands of children, and that states receive the settlement
that they deserve,'' Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Wholesale Marketers Association applauded the
introduction of legislation to make gray market cigarettes illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray market cigarettes have eroded cigarette distributors'
profits,'' said David Strachan, president and chief executive
officer of the association. ``Distributors simply cannot match the
prices that gray market tobacco offers.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.awmanet.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is robo(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
