<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EDDIE-EAGLE-$ADV11-CO     06-07 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDDIE-EAGLE-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'EDDIE EAGLE' IN THE CROSSFIRE OF GUN SAFETY DEBATE
 &HT;    510&AMP;add. For release Sunday, June 11.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some call him a champion of gun safety. Others call
him ``Joe Camel with feathers.''
</P>
<P>
   His name is Eddie Eagle, and several million children have seen
him in coloring books, videos and posters as the cartoon star of
the National Rifle Association's gun safety program.
</P>
<P>
   The brown and white mascot, who flies around in high-top
sneakers, has one constant message for children who see a firearm:
Stop. Don't touch. Leave the area. Tell an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gun avoidance program,'' said Nancy Pretto,
spokesperson for the NRA. ``It makes no value judgements whether
guns are good or bad. It just promotes safe behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the NRA pledged $1 million dollars to pay for more
Eddie Eagle programs and challenged the public to match the
contribution. The announcement was the NRA's answer to the Million
Mom March, which brought hundreds of thousands of people to the
National Mall to push for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   But gun-control advocates say Eddie Eagle is no benign force.
</P>
<P>
   They say his main purpose is promotional, to market guns to
children much like the cartoon character Joe Camel entices children
to smoke cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have turned away from guns. ... They are watching video
games and doing other things,'' said Josh Sugarmann(cq), executive
director of the Violence Policy Center, a Washington-based group
that supports gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   If this trend continues, the NRA ``won't have foot soldiers for
gun-control battles that lie ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is why they need Eddie Eagle, he said: ``to perpetuate the
NRA and the firearms industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Pretto said the program does not promote gun use
among children, and that some people oppose the Eddie Eagle program
solely because of its association with the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Smokey the Bear taught children not to play with
matches, this program teaches young children, don't play with
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the program is not like other public safety
programs because it doesn't warn about the risks of guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie Eagle never says that guns can kill,'' said Sugarmann.
``It's like Smokey the Bear without the forest fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA says on its Web site that the program treats firearms
``simply as a fact of everyday life'' much like ``swimming pools,
electrical outlets, matchbooks and household poisons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With firearms found in about half of all American households,
it's a stance that makes sense,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   The Eddie Eagle program has reached 12 million children in every
state since 1988, according to the NRA, who says the program has
contributed to a drop in the rate of accidental shootings of
children under 14 over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   The program is mostly taught in schools and by law enforcement
agencies but has also been used by Boy Scout troops, civic groups,
and other community organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Pretto said NRA headquarters receives about 100 calls a day
requesting information about Eddie Eagle, and that the number
increases about 25 percent during the school year.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates will likely fight the proliferation of
Eddie Eagle, whose look has changed from early incarnations.
</P>
<P>
   In an early coloring book, Eddie had a harsher look, with
sharper features, a more pronounced beak and black claws on his
feet. Now, the character has soft, rounded eyebrows, wears a shirt
with his name on it and sports white high-tops.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the change is an effort to market to children and to
soften the public image of the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie Eagle is the warm, friendly face of the NRA,'' Sugarmann
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA doesn't deny that it changed Eddie Eagle to make the
safety program more appealing to children.
</P>
<P>
   At the NRA convention last month in Charlotte, N.C., Eddie Eagle
had a definite presence. Cloth bags with his image were handed out
to conventioneers and Eddie Eagle merchandise was for sale,
including stuffed toys.
</P>
<P>
   With his profile on the rise, Eddie Eagle has been the topic of
several recent debates.
</P>
<P>
   The New York General Assembly passed a law last year which would
have allowed school districts to develop Eddie Eagle-style
programs, but the measure was later vetoed by Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a New York City police officer angered
parents and gun-control advocates by showing an Eddie Eagle video
to fourth graders. The officer defended his actions and was not
reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   A day before the Million Mom March, Mayor Scott King of Gary,
Ind., summed up his attitude about the Eddie Eagle program, as he
stood before a memorial wall with the names of 4,000 victims of gun
violence, including that of his nephew, who was killed last year at
the age of 17.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing solutions to his city's gun violence, the NRA had
proposed bringing the gun safety program to Gary, Ind., schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about bone-headed,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.vpc.org, www.nra.org
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso can be reached by e-mail at
eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
