</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT-JUDGE08-COX     06-07 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUDGE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JACKSON: A SPHINX-LIKE JUDGE SHOWS HIS TOUGHNESS
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT and JUDGE-BIOBOX. Moving in (w) Washington (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Consider the various public faces of Thomas
Penfield Jackson, the burly U.S. District Court judge who on
Wednesday threw the book at Microsoft for having flouted the
nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   _ From the government's perspective, Jackson surprisingly proved
to be a nearly perfect draw. In filing their case in 1998, the
Justice Department and 19 states had scant basis to believe that
Jackson would issue sweeping rulings against the mighty software
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was named to bench by President Reagan in 1982 as a
conservative Republican who a decade earlier had defended the
Watergate-tainted Nixon re-election committee. Before the Microsoft
case came along, he had handed down a host of pro-business
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   _ As Microsoft's top brass see it, Jackson's stinging rulings,
neatly written out in blue ink, grasped neither the dynamic nature
of the ``new economy'' nor the company's specific role in setting
workable worldwide standards for most personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   As he drew the landmark trial to an abrupt halt, Jackson angered
chairman and co-founder Bill Gates with his refusal to let him and
other industry leaders testify against the government's ``extreme''
breakup plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ To journalists, who occupied most of the seats in the
Jackson's compact courtroom, the judge remains an enigmatic figure.
Once, in sharing a cab with reporters during a downpour, he said he
had tried hard to sit Sphinx-like on the bench so no one could
deduce anything from his expressions.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson turns down interview requests, although he let three
sketch artists work from an otherwise empty jury box. He has voiced
his contempt for the press, though he is a voracious newspaper
reader and one of his daughters is a Washington-based wire service
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Within this city's close-knit legal fraternity, the
white-haired Jackson is widely viewed as a good-natured and courtly
soul who cannot abide arrogance or evasiveness in his courtroom.
Nor is he known to be overly concerned about seeing his rulings
reversed, an arena where he has run up an above-average score.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls them as he sees them,'' said James Schaller, a former
law colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perspective of most antitrust observers before the
Microsoft case began is that the big monopolization case was a
swamp into which the plaintiff's theories went and never emerged
again. It was a place where the government's theories went to
die,'' noted William Kovacic, a scholar at George Washington
University Law School who followed the case closely.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping a tight scheduling grip on the trial and by sharply
limiting the number of witnesses, while still leaving time for a
vain quest for a settlement, Jackson managed to bring the most
watched business trial in decades to the appellate stage in just
over two years. This is an unprecedented feat in the long annals of
antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in most respects, Judge Jackson has done a masterful
job of structuring and managing the litigation,'' Kovacic said.
</P>
<P>
   During the 78-day trial, Jackson would sometimes go into a
Buddha-like trance, punctuated by occasional chomping on ice cubes.
But whenever he felt the situation demanded, the judge leaped into
the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when a Microsoft attorney protested the government's
serialized showings of Gates's videotaped deposition, Jackson
responded: ``I think the problem is with your witness, not with the
way in which his testimony is being presented. ... It's evident to
every spectator that, for whatever reasons, in many respects Mr.
Gates has not been particularly responsive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's used to seeing what lawyers do, and so I guess he would
be reasonably skeptical of what they do,'' said Jake Stein, a
veteran Washington lawyer who has known Jackson for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson remains rankled by a 1996 Washingtonian magazine article
that ranked him at the bottom among 15 local federal judges.
``Attorneys say he is mean, tyrannical and doesn't know the law,''
Kim Eisler, the magazine's national editor, wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The next issue ran a letter of protest, signed by 26 of his
former law clerks, labeling the piece ``blood sport'' and praising
Jackson as a fair-minded jurist.
</P>
<P>
   Even critics concede that Jackson knows his way about town. He
lives in a high-rise condominium on the edge of Georgetown. In good
weather, he often strolls five miles to the federal courthouse,
across Pennsylvania Avenue from the National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in suburban Maryland in 1937, the son of a
well-respected attorney, Thomas Searing Jackson, who co-founded a
firm, Jackson &AMP; Campbell, that still bears the family name.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson attended St. Albans School (where he sang in the choir
until his voice changed) and graduated from Dartmouth.
Subsequently, he served a three-year stint as a naval officer,
mainly aboard a destroyer in the Mediterranean. From Harvard Law
School, he joined his father's firm, where he specialized in
defending doctors accused of malpractice before moving to a
lifetime appointment on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.dcd.uscourts.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
