   ``He's used to seeing what lawyers do, and so I guess he would
be reasonably skeptical of what they do,'' said Jake Stein, a
veteran Washington lawyer who has known Jackson for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson remains rankled by a 1996 Washingtonian magazine article
that ranked him at the bottom among 15 local federal judges.
``Attorneys say he is mean, tyrannical and doesn't know the law,''
Kim Eisler, the magazine's national editor, wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The next issue ran a letter of protest, signed by 26 of his
former law clerks, labeling the piece ``blood sport'' and praising
Jackson as a fair-minded jurist.
</P>
<P>
   Even critics concede that Jackson knows his way about town. He
lives in a high-rise condominium on the edge of Georgetown. In good
weather, he often strolls five miles to the federal courthouse,
across Pennsylvania Avenue from the National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in suburban Maryland in 1937, the son of a
well-respected attorney, Thomas Searing Jackson, who co-founded a
firm, Jackson &AMP; Campbell, that still bears the family name.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson attended St. Albans School (where he sang in the choir
until his voice changed) and graduated from Dartmouth.
Subsequently, he served a three-year stint as a naval officer,
mainly aboard a destroyer in the Mediterranean. From Harvard Law
School, he joined his father's firm, where he specialized in
defending doctors accused of malpractice before moving to a
lifetime appointment on the federal bench.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.dcd.uscourts.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
