<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0608-COX     06-07 1580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Very close, getting even closer
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Lazio is even with Hillary Clinton in their Senate race,
just as Republican predecessor, Rudy Giuliani, was when he dropped
out of the contest last month, according to a poll released today.
Lazio and Clinton were each favored by 44 percent of voters in the
Quinnipiac University survey. That compares to a poll released May
16 with Clinton at 44 percent and Giuliani at 43 percent. ``It's
becoming obvious that the more people get to know Rick, the more
they like him,'' said Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan.
</P>
<P>
   `ELDERCARE' ON THE AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was promoting his ``eldercare'' initiative today in Palm
Springs, Calif., at the start of a three-day campaigning and
fund-raising sweep up the West Coast. His proposal is a $30
billion, 10-year program of tax credits, Medicaid coverage and
other aid to help families care for elderly relatives. At the core
are a $3,000-a-year tax credit for families providing long-term
care at home for an elderly or disabled relative, and a grant
program for communities to provide adult day care and respite care
to give stressed-out caregivers an occasional break.
</P>
<P>
   GORE AD BLITZ STARTING
</P>
<P>
   An ad featuring Al Gore discussing prescription drug coverage
and his efforts to get medicine to seniors will hit TV airwaves in
15 states Thursday in the Democratic National Committee's
multimillion-dollar campaign to boost its presidential candidate.
Meanwhile, the Republican National Committee was finalizing an ad
campaign of its own, but holding its fire for at least a few days,
hoping to pound home their contention that Gore broke a pledge not
to run this sort of ad.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING ALL WIRED UP
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party is trying to shake up the election process in
yet another way, planning to hold the first nationwide online
presidential primary. ABC News reports that the party has been in
talks with Seattle-based eBallot to administer the primary on the
Internet. Gerry Moan, the Reform Party's national vice chair, said
he expects the deal to be finalized soon. Officials at eBallot
declined to comment. As plans now stand, registered voters could
cast their ballots via computer or regular mail in advance of the
nominating convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   GOT THE MONEY? WHAT THE HECK
</P>
<P>
   Ex-investment banker Jon Corzine easily defeated former Gov. Jim
Florio for the New Jersey Democratic Senate nomination, and refused
to talk about the record-shattering $34 million he spent to win it
_ or how much more he'll spend through November. Instead, Corzine
wanted to talk about spending money on domestic programs. His
Republican opponent will be Rep. Bob Franks, who turned aside three
other candidates. Corzine won't have to scrimp on lunches any time
soon; he's still worth pretty close to $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   11 COMMANDMENT: BE SURE TO WIN
</P>
<P>
   Roy Moore, the Alabama county circuit judge who fought to keep
the Ten Commandments displayed in his courtroom, defeated three
opponents in the Republican primary for chief justice of the state
Supreme Court by enough of a margin to avoid a runoff. In November,
he'll face appeals court Judge Sharon Yates, who was unopposed in
the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARIES IN MONTANA . . .
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, State Auditor Mark O'Keefe won the Democratic
nomination for governor and will face Republican Lt. Gov. Judy
Martz in November. Farmer Brian Schweitzer, whose battle cry was
higher prescription drug prices on his side of the Canadian border,
won the Democratic nod for the Senate and will take on Republican
Conrad Burns, trying for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND IN IOWA . . .
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, lawyer Jay Marcus won GOP nomination to face Democratic
Rep. Leonard Boswell. Democrat Bob Simpson, an advocate for the
disabled who has worked for the Legislature, advanced to a November
challenge against 12-term Republican Rep. Jim Leach.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND IN NEW MEXICO AND SOUTH DAKOTA . . .
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, Bill Redmond, who had served briefly in Congress,
won a three-way GOP race for the Senate nomination to face
Democratic incumbent Jeff Bingaman. And in South Dakota, Democrat
Curt Hohn, manager of a water pipeline, won a three-way primary and
will take on two-term Republican Rep. John Thune, the state's lone
House member.
</P>
<P>
   BUT DON'T THEY MAKE EXCEPTIONS FOR A `10'?
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood actors who identify themselves as Republicans are
worried their party affiliation might affect their careers. Bo
Derek for one. ``Lurking behind Tinseltown's closed doors, paranoid
members of the GOP are bolting to the exits,'' afraid their
``liberal co-workers will wreck their dreams of stardom and
success,'' the New York Post quoted her as saying.``They are very
adamant and almost militant about their views. It's tough to have a
nice, open conversation of any kind. People get really angry, and
they treat me as though I'm some hateful monster.''
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS HURDLE CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   A Republican whose campaign against Sen. Ted Kennedy has been
plagued by trouble officially won a spot on the November ballot.
The Massachusetts secretary of state's office approved 10,139
nominating signatures for Jack E. Robinson, slightly more than the
10,000 he needed. The state's top Republicans withdrew their
support for Robinson, a black businessman who made a fortune in
telecommunications, after embarrassing details of his past were
revealed: a drunken driving arrest (he eventually was cleared), and
an ex-girlfriend taking out a restraining order against him.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING _ IN GENERAL TERMS
</P>
<P>
   In his first policy speech since he officially began his Senate
run in New York, Rick Lazio told a mayors' conference in Saratoga
Springs that he would continue to back federally supported housing
and community development programs, but offered no new proposals of
his own. He said his philosophy for housing and economic
development includes partnerships between the private sector and
the government to finance and manage programs. Lazio also vowed
support for federal programs that help first-time homebuyers and
the homeless move into permanent housing.
</P>
<P>
   ENCROACHING ON HILLARY STRONGHOLD
</P>
<P>
   Black voters traditionally favor Democrats, and Hillary Clinton
is predicted to win at least 90 percent of the black vote in her
Senate race against Rick Lazio. But New York's black voters are
still making up their minds, and a new Zogby poll finds that Lazio
is doing better than Rudy Giuliani had among the state's 1.2
million black voters. Lazio has increased his support among black
voters to 8 percent, according to the poll, four times what
Giuliani scored before bowing out last month.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUND OF `SCALIA-THOMAS'
</P>
<P>
   It's assumed that the next president will get to name one or two
justices to a Supreme Court that now decides controversial issues
by one vote. If George W. Bush wins, Democratic thinking goes,
chances are he'd appoint justices cut from the same cloth as its
two most visible conservatives, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
And so their names, uttered condescendingly in one breath, may well
become a campaign catch phrase, the latest Democratic rallying cry:
``Scalia-Thomas.''
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDLIER DISAGREEMENT
</P>
<P>
   The quadrennial wrangling over the Republican Party abortion
platform may not be as bitter this time. Wisconsin Gov. Tommy
Thompson, head of the platform committee, told party activists who
support abortion rights that GOP leaders plan no change in the
strong anti-abortion language and no public hearings on the issue.
Still, Susan Cullman, co-chair of the Republican Pro-choice
Coalition, said she was encouraged by the friendly tone of the
meeting, when Thompson promised them ample private opportunities to
air their views. Cullman: ``This is the beginning of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   THERE, THAT PROVES IT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says the U.S. Supreme Court decision throwing out
a Texas inmate's death sentence proves the system works. The high
court ordered a new sentencing hearing for convicted killer Victor
Hugo Saldano after prosecutors conceded his death sentence was
based in part on the fact that he is Hispanic. Bush: ``I think it's
an indication that there are safeguards in the system. ... As I
understand the facts, there is no question that the man did the
crime. It's the penalty phase that needs to be examined. I think
the system is working.''
</P>
<P>
   OPPONENT? AND WHO MIGHT THAT BE?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore might be understandably obsessed with George W. Bush,
given that the two are battling for the big prize. But these days,
Gore isn't even mentioning Bush's name. In fact, the name ``Bush''
has not passed Gore's lips since May 26, at least in public. During
an interview this week with WSEE-TV in Erie, Pa., Gore referred to
his opponent as ``the other side,'' and on WIFR-TV in Rockford,
Ill., Gore's reference was to ``the other fellow.'' Chris Lehane,
Gore's press secretary, says that for now Gore will appear to be in
this race all by himself _ ``to guarantee that the focus stays
where it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
