<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-REBEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DECADE ON, A PIONEER OF RUSSIAN CAPITALISM STILL HAS HIS DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOLOGDA, Russia _ When this newspaper last looked in on Viktor
Kuzmin, an aeon ago in 1990, Russia was still the Soviet Union. And
Kuzmin, 45, a brash, elfin rebel, was kicking hard at its tottering
legs.
</P>
<P>
   An unrepentant capitalist in a communist state, Kuzmin seemed
destined for greatness, or maybe prison. He was building his own
10,000-square-foot home, a shocking act for someone not even a
Communist Party member. He had subverted state curbs on ownership
by declaring himself a business. He ran his own construction
company and planned to start an investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   He also had gotten himself certified by a doctor as sane,
thwarting local apparatchiks who had summoned him for a psychiatric
examination _ a first step toward the mental hospitals then used to
silence troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old authorities consider me dangerous,'' he boasted, in an
article in The New York Times. ``And, of course, they are right.
Anyone independent is a threat to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Such nose-thumbing at communism's arthritic creed was news
enough back then to make The Times. Today it seems almost quaint.
It is no longer news that capitalism triumphed in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It would nevertheless have been nice to report that Capitalist
Kuzmin triumphed with it. But when the newspaper caught up with him
recently, intent on chewing nearly a decade of post-Soviet fat, his
first words made clear that the facts were otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just laughing today,'' he said, not laughing at all.
``All of us have two higher education degrees, degrees from two
institutions. But our country is such that we have to dig to make a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   In a still-unfinished dirt-floor room in his
still-mostly-roofless house, Kuzmin stood with two sweaty
colleagues. There was no tie on his frayed-at-the-collar shirt.
Instead of a cellular phone, he was grasping a shovel. He was
digging holes in the floor for his latest and considerably less
grandiose business venture, a one-saw sawmill.
</P>
<P>
   There is surely no shame in that. But even he allows that a
shovel is a far cry from what was wrested from his grasp just a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A quick diversion: Viktor Kuzmin is not your ordinary Ivan. He
has two pony-sized guard dogs, a fence plastered with warning
signs, a sawed-off shotgun under his desk and, for some reason, a
dump truck and a brand-new Volvo station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   The Kuzmin manse, on a glorious, sweeping bend of the Vologda
River, is equally eccentric. His first unfinished house, which he
began in 1987, stands next to the foundation of a second unfinished
house, under construction because House Number One was turned over
to the sawmill, an auto-repair shop and other speculative ventures.
</P>
<P>
   A short walk away, on a plot with the best river view, stands
House Number Three, a tiny wooden bungalow that serves as home
until Houses One and Two are, one hopes, finished.
</P>
<P>
   The place is a metaphor for Kuzmin, a man so tossed by
brainstorms that the latest great scheme is as likely as not to be
tossed by the roadside to accommodate the next. People think he is
strange, said an official of Vologda's regional government. They
are right.
</P>
<P>
   But he is neither crazy nor stupid. At 55, he is an accomplished
architect, an engineer, a self-taught lawyer and, albeit a bit
loquacious, an eloquent advocate for the new Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, you might be a bit strange too, if your story was like
his:
</P>
<P>
   In December 1990, Kuzmin quit a state construction company in
disgust after refusing a demand that he join the Communist Party.
It was a good move: soon, his own building firm had a payroll of 30
people. And by bartering his talents, he had acquired the loveliest
eight acres of a riverside collective farm, where he dug a pond and
began erecting his mansion. There would be arched windows, he said,
and a gymnasium, two greenhouses, workshops and a sheep-breeding
pen.
</P>
<P>
   For a man despised by the authorities, life was pretty good. And
when communism collapsed a year later, things seemed fated to get
better. Kuzmin had his defenders, mostly progressive city officials
who saw opportunity in democracy and the free market.
</P>
<P>
   When an ambitious plan emerged to restore 85 acres of riverfront
construction in this pleasant if slightly homely city of 300,000,
near the site of its founding in 1417, they asked him to execute
it.
</P>
<P>
   Kuzmin immersed himself. He spent a year in Moscow researching
architecture and history. He drafted a plan adorning the city's
squares with new and restored buildings and a rebuilt historic
cathedral. He worked out financing with a Soviet-U.S. venture, and
courted European bankers. He started a company to promote travel
across Russia's northwest, recruited foreign agencies to promote it
and built cabins for Vologda sightseers.
</P>
<P>
   The whole project took on the aroma of serious money. Which in
Russia, in the early 1990s, was a serious mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Kuzmin says his fairy tale lost its gossamer wings in 1992, when
local officials demanded that he build them five cottages in
exchange for their political support. He told them where to get
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `Where's the money?''' he recalled. ``And they said to
take it where you can; they didn't care. But I never compromised my
conscience. I'm stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Retribution was swift. Official support for the project began to
evaporate. When Kuzmin discovered a deputy had taken project money
to build himself a home, he angrily razed its foundation _ and got
arrested. The deputy went scot-free. Kuzmin was fined $30,000 and
given a three-year suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Korachev, then and now the region's director of historic
preservation, testified in Kuzmin's defense. Soon, his home was
firebombed. So was Kuzmin's downtown office, where he was directing
the restoration, his travel program and a yet another venture to
sell tourists Russian handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the city seized his 85-acre development, saying it had
failed to materialize. Without the restoration project, his tourism
venture collapsed. His handicrafts business had been firebombed.
His payroll shrank from 30 to two.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, several corrupt officials in the restoration project
did go to jail. The region's governor and a deputy were
investigated, though never prosecuted. It is all cold comfort to
Kuzmin, who has moved from international banking and real-estate to
turning out finished planks for other builders.
</P>
<P>
   He still hoards his plans and architectural drawings,
magnificent panels depicting riverfront architecture done up in a
canary yellow peculiar to Russian buildings, propped for a visitor
this week against the stray cables and broken bricks of Home Number
Two.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pride and my pain,'' he said. ``My great pain.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he is still a capitalist _ that he does not blame
capitalism, because capitalism really never made it to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in office now,'' he said, ``are the same people who
were in office when communism was here. They just moved chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuzmin walked a few yards to a bluff overlooking the broad
river. A mile away, the spires and onion domes of the
Spassapreluski Monastery, newly gilded 600 years after their
creation, rose from the plain, gleaming like some breathtaking
Russian Oz.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only spot in Vologda like this,'' he said, and
fingered the buds of a nearby scrawny bush. ``I planted these apple
trees. I dug that pond.'' The whirring of the gears between his
ears was almost audible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work on that pond,'' he said. ``We're going to put
expensive fish there, you know. It will be a great place for
fishermen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
