<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7274 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-GAMBLING060     06-07 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GAMBLING0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Erect high hurdles to online gambling
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no need to travel to Las Vegas or Atlantic City or any
of the newer casino resorts to scratch any itch you may have for
games of chance. That kind of action is all-too-available on the
Internet. An online gambler can access more than 250 casino sites,
64 lotteries, 20 bingo games and 139 sports books and run through a
week's wages with a few clicks of his mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed at the corrosive potential of this technological
temptation, the U.S. Senate made a show of outlawing Internet
gaming in a bill passed unanimously last November. However, the
Senate left loopholes in its ban that permit online wagers on horse
and dog races.
</P>
<P>
   That unfortunate precedent set House members to thinking: If
thoroughbreds and greyhounds could win exemptions, why not extend
the same favor for jai lai betting, American Indian casinos and
state lotteries?
</P>
<P>
   So what should have been an across-the-board prohibition could
evolve into a large-scale Internet gaming entitlement. In this
case, no bill is better than the version taking shape in the House.
Besides, since many of the cyber-gambling sites operate from
overseas, such a ban would not apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   A more effective line of attack is incorporated in a bill
co-sponsored by Reps. Jim Leach (R-Iowa) and John LaFalce (D-N.Y.),
the chairman and ranking member of the House Banking Committee.
Their measure would outlaw the use of credit or debit cards,
electronic fund transfers, checks, etc., to conduct any Internet
gambling, period.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber-gambling produces no discernible community benefit _ as in
the case of, say, casinos, which at least generate tourism. As for
its downside, individuals who get addicted to point-and-click
wagering often run up crushing credit-card debts, which all too
often have led to family breakups and occasionally suicides.
Moreover, law-enforcement authorities suspect criminal
organizations such as Colombian narcotraffickers use online gaming
transactions for money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   The issue before Congress could hardly be clearer. Its members
ought to enact the Leach-LaFalce approach and resist the urge to
load it down with exemptions for favored elements of the gambling
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
