<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7280 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-MARTINEZ-COLUMN-NYTSF     06-07 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMON BOLIVAR'S FINAL DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Wednesday, June 7, or thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by MARTINEZ-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, N.J. _ Certain words can lose their original
power and meaning with time and misuse. In some political circles,
words like liberty, justice, democracy, order and liberation have
become hollow, unreal, spoken only by those of the Middle Ages. And
the same thing seems to have happened to names. Lately, few names
have been so abused as that of the illustrious Simon Bolivar.
</P>
<P>
   Exalted and revered for 150 years, uncriticized and looked upon
as champion by both dictators and democratic thinkers alike,
Bolivar is still one of the few remaining symbols of Latin
America's greatness.
</P>
<P>
   He had _ besides a unique talent for military strategy _ a
fertile political imagination and a powerful gift for language that
to this day remains seductive.
</P>
<P>
   Those qualities allowed him to frame ideal constitutions for
ideal countries. But the nations of his day, sunk in anarchy or
burdened with oppressive strongmen, rejected those constitutions as
illusory.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of Bolivar's ideas _ such as his proposal for an
authoritarian senate and a democratically elected president who
would hold office for life _ wouldn't fly today. His utopian ideal
of a politically united Hispanic America, though, hasn't lost its
allure.
</P>
<P>
   In his document, the Letter of Jamaica, written in 1815, Bolivar
stressed the need for Colombia, Venezuela, Ecuador and Panama to
maintain unity by forming a confederation, with Maracaibo as its
capital. One of his profoundest disappointments was to witness,
before his death in 1830, a factious war that shattered that dream.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Bolivarian ideal of political unity has since
been revived several times on the continent, it has never seemed so
tenable as now. Leaders as divergent as Venezuelan President Hugo
Chavez and FARC's (Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia)
political leader Manuel ``Tirofijo'' Marulanda have claimed the
liberator's doctrines as the model by which their actions are
guided.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's new Constitution, promoted by Chavez, gives the
nation a new title: ``Bolivarian Republic.'' This designation also
encompasses the armed forces and every state enterprise. Even a
sector of the Ecuadorian army has claimed this title. And the same
can be said of the Colombian guerrilla forces that protect the so
called ``Zona de Distension,'' southwest of Bogota, and of the
incipient and irregular judicial system that currently rules in
that region. Added to this, the underground political movement with
which the FARC hopes to gain power, is called Bolivarian Movement
for the New Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Whether repeated use of this term is coincidental or part of a
conscious plan for ultimate political unity, it is a question
without an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already are a state within a state,'' declared Commander
Javier Calderon last month in Rio de la Plata, Argentina, alluding
to the territory ceded by Colombia's government to the FARC. ``We
are a state in fact, and will soon be so by law. We have taken up
arms to defend ourselves aginst the terrorist state which oppresses
us, and we have assumed the legacy of liberator Simon Bolivar. No
one is more Bolivarian than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   I heard similar words from Hugo Chavez last August in Caracas.
Chavez _ who has consolidated his mandate in a new election that
has extended his tenure by one more year _ was the leader of a
failed military attempt in 1982 to oust Venezuela's then President
Carlos Andres Perez. Even today, Chavez swears his revolt against
Perez was legitimate _ an oxymoron if I ever heard one _ in that it
was an attack against an ``oppressor and corrupt government'' that
was pillaging national institutions and looting the nation's
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows of the mediator's cloak Chavez has donned for the
Colombian guerrillas and his frequent contacts with their leaders.
When I asked him what was Colombian President Andres Pastrana's
reaction to those contacts, he said, pointing to the telephone on
his desk, that he immediately advises Pastrana of all discussions
with guerrilla representatives.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, Chavez has been accused _ without foundation _
of trying to establish links between his ``Bolivarian'' army and
the armed groups that, under the same name, fight in Colombia and
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington diplomatic source has suggested to me that part of
Venezuela's huge income earned from current rising oil prices is
being funneled to the FARC in the form of planes and military
equipment. Besides the fact there is no basis to this accusation,
it is quite malicious in that it attempts to portray Chavez as a
reckless adventurer.
</P>
<P>
   However, as in most rumors, there might just be a shred of truth
to be found. One point often noted is that nobody seems to know
where exactly Venezuelan oil revenues go.
</P>
<P>
   The difficult life ordinary Venezuelans have to endure hasn't
improved since Chavez was elected president more than 15 months
ago. And in some ways it has actually worsened, as the escalating
unemployment rate indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Another point to consider is the president's repeated
declarations, in public and private, of his desire to re-create the
Great Colombia that Bolivar dreamed of, and his sympathy for
anyone, whether they are irregular armed groups or opportunistic
politicians, who shares this ideal.
</P>
<P>
   It is unimaginable Bolivar would give his stamp of approval to
such a union today. To him, a perfect government was one that
``would produce the greatest happiness possible, the greatest
social security and the greatest political stability.'' Even though
``Bolivarian'' armies claim this, too, what they are in fact
creating is the exact opposite.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think of a country in the world that has been so
bloodied as present-day Colombia, torn by the concerted actions of
right wing paramilitary groups, drug cartels, the National
Liberation Army (ELN) and, of course, the FARC.
</P>
<P>
   This perverse use of Bolivar's name has sadly become vogue. A
paramilitary group operating in the Barrancabermeja area, near the
Magdalena River, is actively stealing peasant lands, either by
murder or terror. Yet it calls itself ``Bolivar's Squadron.''
</P>
<P>
   I've read, too, that land north of Bogota which the ELN has
claimed title to, will be called _ if the government finally gives
it to them _ ``Bolivarland.''
</P>
<P>
   A cocaine processing and distributing center in the mountains of
western Colombian, which was recently destroyed, was known as
``Pro-Bolivar.'' This abuse of the name may seem ridiculous, but in
reality it is horrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Few men in Latin America fought as fervently as Bolivar to build
a fairer, freer, happier and more civilized society. With this in
mind he wrote some 10,000 documents and fought scores of battles.
The heirs to his legacy, who today so extravagantly use his name
for such immoral activities, are debasing it.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 20 years ago, ``Bolivar'' called to mind
greatness and glory. Today, it is a name so commonly and shamefully
used and abased that soon it may have no significance at all.
</P>
<P>
   (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the author of ``The Peron Novel'' and
``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American studies
department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an editor
and journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
