<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATION-READING-Part4of8-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOOK LOVER'S GUIDE FOR THOSE LAZY, HAZY DAYS OF SUMMER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (New York Times Book Review's Summer Book Recommendations)   (This ``separate-buy'' eight-part compilation of recommended
lawn-chair reading is from the highly-regarded New York Times Book
Review section. Complete reviews of these books may be found at The
New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books.) 
 &HT;    
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR YOUR EASE, THIS EXTENSIVE ``BOOK LOOK'' HAS
BEEN MOVED TO YOU IN EIGHT EASY-TO-EDIT PARTS: PARTS 1 THROUGH 3,
FICTION &AMP; POETRY; PARTS 4 THROUGH 7, NONFICTION; AND PART 8,
MYSTERIES AND SCIENCE FICTION. ALL CAN BE FOUND UNDER THE SLUG
BC-VACATION-READING-PART()of8-NYTSF.) 
 &HT;    
 (To publish any, or all, of this tempting list, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480 or fax
her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267.) 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The New York Times Company  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT TOWN: The New Yorker and the World It Made. by Ben Yagoda.
(Scribner, $30.) A comprehensive history that salutes the sustained
brilliance of The New Yorker's editors and writers over many years
without losing sight of the movements and writers the magazine
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN DAUGHTER: Discovering My Mother. By Elizabeth Kendall.
(Random House, $23.95.) Kendall's examination of her own story and
her family's story is illuminated by reflection on her mother, who
left Vassar to bear and raise six children, a course now hard to
imagine.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN TRAGEDY: Kennedy, Johnson and the Origins of the
Vietnam War. By David Kaiser. (Belknap/Harvard University, $29.95.)
A detailed narrative tracing American military involvement in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   AS NATURE MADE HIM: The Boy Who Was Raised as a Girl. By John
Colapinto. (HarperCollins, $26.) A journalist recounts how a
hellish regimen designed to raise a mutilated boy as a girl failed
completely, though the victim survived to lead a fairly tolerable
life.
</P>
<P>
   BASIL STREET BLUES. By Michael Holroyd. (Norton, $24.95.) The
biographer of George Bernard Shaw turns obliquely to autobiography,
confessing that his literary life has been shaped by his efforts to
escape from involvement with a family of dreadful, compelling
eccentrics.
</P>
<P>
   THE BATTLE FOR GOD. By Karen Armstrong. (Knopf, $27.50.) A
scholar's disturbing account of the rise of fundamentalist sects in
the great voids left by the retreat of the world's monotheistic
religions.
</P>
<P>
   THE BATTLE OF NEW ORLEANS. By Robert V. Remini. (Viking,
$24.95.) The climactic battle of the War of 1812 was our country's
first great military victory and secured American independence, a
noted historian argues.
</P>
<P>
   BEN TILLMAN AND THE RECONSTRUCTION OF WHITE SUPREMACY. By
Stephen Kantrowitz. (University of North Carolina, cloth, $49.95;
paper, $19.95.) A thoughtful biography of one of the archracists
and pillars of Jim Crow in the post-Reconstruction South.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIOZ. Volume I: The Making of an Artist, 1803-1832. Volume
II: Servitude and Greatness, 1832-1869. By David Cairns.
(University of California, $40 each.) An outstanding biography,
written by the former chief music critic for The Sunday Times of
London, argues persuasively that Berlioz was ``the greatest French
composer between Rameau and Debussy.''
</P>
<P>
   BETWEEN FATHER AND SON: Family Letters. By V. S. Naipaul.
(Knopf, $26.) An entertaining correspondence that shows the young
author's vulnerability and mirrors themes of the South Asian
diaspora that will appear in his fiction; sagely edited by his
agent, Gillon Aitken.
</P>
<P>
   BOBOS IN PARADISE: The New Upper Class and How They Got There.
By David Brooks. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25.) Affection, ridicule and
plain ambivalence propel this work of ``comic sociology'' as it
examines the rise of the ``bourgeois bohemian,'' the social and
economic type that now controls and consumes everything.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOY WITH THE THORN IN HIS SIDE: A Memoir. By Keith Fleming.
(Morrow, $24.) The tale of a troubled straight teenager sent to
live with his uncle, Edmund White, one of the best-known,
best-liked gay men on earth, who turned out to be exactly the ideal
trustworthy parent.
</P>
<P>
   BROTHERHOOD IN RHYTHM: The Jazz Tap Dancing of the Nicholas
Brothers. By Constance Valis Hill. (Oxford University, $30.) A
choreographer gives an analysis of the celebrated brace of
tap-dancing brothers.
</P>
<P>
   BRUCE CHATWIN. By Nicholas Shakespeare. (Nan A.
Talese/Doubleday, $35.) This life of the author of ``The
Songlines,'' who died of AIDS in 1989, portrays a man beset with an
almost biological lust for loneliness, whose singular genius was
for passionate transitory connection.
</P>
<P>
   BURT LANCASTER: An American Life. By Kate Buford. (Knopf,
$27.50.) The magnetic, acrobatic, left-leaning, leonine,
Chiclet-toothed, womanizing actor emerges, by the end of this
comprehensive account, characterized by yet another adjective, one
less often applied to him: vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS NOTES: Posing as Politics and Other Thoughts. By Adolph
Reed, Jr. (New Press, $25.) A collection of essays by an acerbic
black social commentator who prefers class solidarity to identity
politics.
</P>
<P>
   THE COLLABORATOR: The Trial and Execution of Robert Brasillach.
By Alice Kaplan. (University of Chicago, $25.) In her incisive
account of the proceedings against Brasillach, who was probably the
most accomplished literary cheerleader for Nazism that occupied
France ever had, the author asks when words become crimes.
</P>
<P>
   CREATING COLETTE. Volume II: From Baroness to Woman of Letters,
1912-1954. By Claude Francis and Fernande Gontier. (Steerforth,
$27.) The concluding volume of a biography of the celebrated French
writer shows how she created her enduring persona and makes a
compelling and balanced argument that she was entitled to it.
</P>
<P>
   THE CULTURAL COLD WAR: The CIA and the World of Arts and
Letters. By Frances Stonor Saunders. (New Press, $29.95.) An
account of how the Central Intelligence Agency covertly financed
cultural activities as part of the Cold War. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (HERE'S AN EDITOR-FRIENDLY WORD COUNT BREAKDOWN OF THE
PACKAGE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 1 _ Fiction &AMP; Poetry: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 2 - Fiction &AMP; Poetry: 875 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 3 - Fiction &AMP; Poetry: 875 words
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 4 - Nonfiction: 800 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 5 - Nonfiction: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 6 - Nonfiction: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 7 - Nonfiction: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 8 - Mysteries/Science Fiction: 600 words.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOW GRAB YOUR BEACH TOWEL AND A BOOK!...) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish any or all of this eight-part list of recommended
summer reading from The New York Times Book Review section, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480 or fax
her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call us
at 800-444-0267.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: The complete reviews of these books may be found at The New
York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books.) &QL;
