<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: LITERARY TITANS FACE REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year has been, in a sense, an abounding one for great
American writing. It has brought us novels by three of America's
leading literary icons: the Nobel laureate Saul Bellow and two
potential Nobel Prize winners, Philip Roth and John Updike. Yet
notwithstanding generally strong reviews and tremendous coverage of
the daring literary conceits of the works, only one made The New
York Times' best-seller list, and that for but a week.
</P>
<P>
   Each author had everything going for him, and the publication of
each novel was treated as a cultural event by the newspapers,
magazines, national public radio stations and online magazines that
dote on them.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Updike's ``Gertrude and Claudius'' (Knopf), a sort
of prequel to ``Hamlet,'' did not approach best-seller numbers,
despite interesting word-of-mouth; Bellow's ``Ravelstein'' (Viking)
made the list for one week; Roth's ``Human Stain'' (Houghton
Mifflin) lingered a notch below the list before dropping, despite
exceptional publicity, including a long profile of the author in
The New Yorker by the magazine's editor, David Remnick.
</P>
<P>
   Why was there such a harrowing disconnect between the literary
chatter and the book-buying public? The easy answer is that a list
that includes three Harry Potter novels, one Dr. Seuss and several
ballyhooed by the Oprah Winfrey book club is indeed a tough one for
a literary novel to crack.
</P>
<P>
   But even in that quirky universe, literary fiction can make it.
Michael Ondaatje's ``Anil's Ghost'' (Knopf) will be No. 12 on June
18. Other recent literary best sellers included ``Horse Heaven''
(Knopf) by Jane Smiley and ``Plainsong'' (Knopf) by Kent Haruf.
(Toni Morrison's ``Bluest Eye'' (Knopf) and Isabel Allende's
``Daughters of Fortune'' (HarperCollins), both literary fiction,
were best sellers that were Oprah Winfrey book club selections.)
</P>
<P>
   That Bellows, Roth and Updike have come up so short has
stimulated some theories and stirred some speculation in book
publishing. It should be noted that no one in publishing is
questioning their viability as writers or their ability to hold
onto their fans or even gain new converts. But clearly something
has changed, besides the impact of book clubs and the fact that
chain stores are less apt to push literary fiction than are the
shrinking number of independent book stores.
</P>
<P>
   Many in publishing believe that a generation gap has grown
between the mass of book buyers and these three legends that even
bravura reviews cannot easily leap.
</P>
<P>
   James Silberman, an independent editor who works mostly with
Knopf and Harcourt Brace, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``In every generation the icons get eclipsed by the fashionable
and literary styles change, the tone of voice changes and certainly
commercial styles change, and the type of relationships they write
about are different.
</P>
<P>
   ``These three are in a sense realistic novelists, and to some
degree they write only about the world they know well,'' he said.
``Today there are the great explosion novels that are popular and
also the endless exquisite single relationship novels.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the relationships that Bellows, Roth and Updike write
about are in many ways almost murderous in the way they are torn
apart, but to many younger readers they may seem somewhat remote.
Murder today means murder.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Straus, president and chief executive of Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, linked the books' sales performance to ``the aging
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all getting old, and critics and the public look for
something really delicious, groundbreaking,'' he said. ``By the
34th novel, the fourth sequel, they say, `So what.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since these three great writers erupted on the
literary scene, the old issues of Jewish assimilation in American
society often at the core of Bellow's and Roth's novels have been
settled. Three different publishers mentioned that cultural change
that has robbed Bellow's and Roth's writing of urgency for the
current generation of book buyers. (Bellow and Updike did not
return calls for this column. Roth declined, through his
publisher.)
</P>
<P>
   So if their books are not selling in great numbers right now,
they are in libraries and on college syllabuses. Updike and Bellow
have been publishing novels for nearly half a century; Roth since
the 1960s. What makes them icons is that they have withstood the
flashes of the current literary moment, whenever that moment was,
continuing to write and sell books through several generations as
other writers were erased from memory and bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   Silberman noted: `` `Moby-Dick' was a commercial failure, after
Melville had written commercially successful books. His reputation
was in eclipse for a long time. He's certainly back now. When you
read him you know why.''
</P>
<P>
   While great commercial success may have eluded them this time,
there are a lot of doctorates in literature to be earned this
century on these latest novels and on the backlists of Bellow,
Updike and Roth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
