<HEADLINE>
A BOOK LOVER'S GUIDE FOR THOSE LAZY, HAZY DAYS OF SUMMER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (New York Times Book Review's Summer Book Recommendations)   (This ``separate-buy'' eight-part compilation of recommended
lawn-chair reading is from the highly-regarded New York Times Book
Review section. Complete reviews of these books may be found at The
New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books.) 
 &HT;    
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR YOUR EASE, THIS EXTENSIVE ``BOOK LOOK'' HAS
BEEN MOVED TO YOU IN EIGHT EASY-TO-EDIT PARTS: PARTS 1 THROUGH 3,
FICTION &AMP; POETRY; PARTS 4 THROUGH 7, NONFICTION; AND PART 8,
MYSTERIES AND SCIENCE FICTION. ALL CAN BE FOUND UNDER THE SLUG
BC-VACATION-READING-PART()of8-NYTSF.) 
 &HT;    
 (To publish any, or all, of this tempting list, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480 or fax
her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267.) 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The New York Times Company  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION _ CONTINUED &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   JAMES JOYCE. By Edna O'Brien. (Lipper/Viking, $19.95.) Not a
biography but a fan's notes, the fact-based musings of a fellow
novelist on the life and work of a personally insufferable man
without whom 20th-century fiction would be unreckonably
impoverished (though easier to read, maybe).
</P>
<P>
   JOAN OF ARC. By Mary Gordon. (Lipper/Viking, $19.95.) A
biographical meditation, one of the Penguin Lives series, that
construes Joan the maid and saint as the patroness of a commitment
that fears no defeat and counts no odds.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN RUSKIN: The Later Years. By Tim Hilton. (Yale University,
$35.) Opening when its subject is 40 and a rising authority on
aesthetics, Volume II of this vast biography charts Ruskin's
unraveling from passionate cataloger (rocks, plants, buildings,
paintings, clouds) to tragic obsessive (irrigation, drainage,
running water, little girls).
</P>
<P>
   KARL MARX: A Life. By Francis Wheen. (Norton, $27.95.) An
engaging reinterpretation of the prophet's life that defends his
ideas (not very persuasively) but emphasizes his Victorian male
egocentricity and bourgeois pretensions.
</P>
<P>
   THE KINDER, GENTLER MILITARY: Can Americas Gender-Neutral
Fighting Force Still Win Wars? By Stephanie Gutman. (Lisa
Drew/Scribner, $25.) An argument that making the armed forces more
amenable to women has compromised their ability to defend the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST MARLIN: The Story of a Family at Sea. By Fred Waitzkin.
(Viking, $23.95.) An ambitious, satisfying father-son memoir about
a family that fought a deadly civil war with several sides on
several fronts for several decades.
</P>
<P>
   LETTERS FROM THE EDITOR: The New Yorker's Harold Ross. Edited by
Thomas Kunkel. (Modern Library, $26.95.) Selections from Ross's
abundant correspondence by his biographer, calculated to dispel the
notion that The New Yorker's founding editor was a lucky bumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   MAILER: A Biography. By Mary V. Dearborn. (Houghton Mifflin,
$30.) Norman Mailer carefully examined from without (no interviews)
by a writer who appreciates the equal importance of his life and
his work in understanding America in the second half of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   MAO: A Life. By Philip Short. (John Macrae/Holt, $37.50.)
Written by an English foreign correspondent, this exhaustively
researched biography combines the best of journalism and
scholarship to portray the revolutionary who created modern China.
</P>
<P>
   MARIAN ANDERSON: A Singer's Journey. By Allan Keiler. (Lisa
Drew/ Scribner, $30.) A smart life of a distinguished artist whose
only real interest was her art, though she was repeatedly called
upon to serve as a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   THE MEASURE OF A MAN: A Spiritual Autobiography. By Sidney
Poitier. (HarperSanFrancisco, $26.) The pathbreaking black actor
reflects on his career and values.
</P>
<P>
   MORNING GLORY: A Biography of Mary Lou Williams. By Linda Dahl.
(Pantheon, $30.) An engrossing life of the great jazz arranger,
composer and pianist who chucked the wild life at 47 and strove for
sainthood until her death at 71.
</P>
<P>
   M: The Man Who Became Caravaggio. By Peter Robb. (John
Macrae/Holt, $30.) A biography of the great painter and
troublemaker who came to Rome in 1592 and disappeared 18 years
later, leaving behind his works and a lot of rumors.
</P>
<P>
   THE MYSTERIES WITHIN: A Surgeon Reflects on Medical Myths. By
Sherwin B. Nuland. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $24.) A surgeon and scholar
of medical history urbanely reviews the expansion of medical
knowledge since Hippocrates, Galen and Aristotle; his heroes are
the experimental scientists of the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   NAT KING COLE. By Daniel Mark Epstein. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$27.) A life of this American singer of tales follows its
perpetually seductive yet profoundly reserved subject from boyhood
(only gospel songs allowed) through 40's jazz prowess and 50's pop
stardom to his untimely death.
</P>
<P>
   THE NATURE OF ECONOMIES. By Jane Jacobs. (Modern Library,
$21.95.) The canonized social critic of ``The Death and Life of
Great American Cities'' (1961) contends that economies mimic
natural systems in the way they grow, and need to be ecologically
approached to be understood.
</P>
<P>
   NEWJACK: Guarding Sing Sing. By Ted Conover. (Random House,
$24.95.) A journalist's account of his year as a correction
officer, where his moral well-being was as much at risk as his
bodily safety.
</P>
<P>
   NONZERO: The Logic of Human Destiny. By Robert Wright.
(Pantheon, $27.50.) A journalist's argument, based on game theory
and evolutionary convergence, that humankind has a destiny and that
the globalization of trade and communication, here already, is the
next step onward and upward.
</P>
<P>
   ONCE UPON A TIME IN NEW YORK: Jimmy Walker, Franklin Roosevelt
and the Last Great Battle of the Jazz Age. By Herbert Mitgang.
(Free Press, $25.) How the Seabury Commission brought down the
freewheeling Mayor Jimmy Walker, told by a former writer for The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE REZ. By Ian Frazier. (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25.)
Close observation and a keen sense for piquant juxtapositions yield
an enlarged view of humanity in this report from a region that has
inspired acres of cliche and condescension in the past, the Pine
Ridge Reservation in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ORIGINAL STORY BY: A Memoir of Broadway and Hollywood. By Arthur
Laurents. (Knopf, $30.) Unsparing, strikingly candid reminiscences
from the Broadway playwright and Hollywood screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   OSBERT SITWELL. By Philip Ziegler. (Knopf, $30.) An elegant,
expertly written life of Sir Osbert Sitwell, an ineffable
aristocrat with a temporary literary reputation and a permanent
conviction that he, his sister Edith and his brother Sacheverell
were made of superior clay.
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER AMERICAN: The Life of Michael Harrington. By Maurice
Isserman. (PublicAffairs, $28.50.) An appealing biography of an
appealing man, a Socialist and a Democrat, whose 1963 book, ``The
Other America,'' recognized the obscured depth and dimensions of
poverty in this country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (HERE'S AN EDITOR-FRIENDLY WORD COUNT BREAKDOWN OF THE
PACKAGE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
