<HEADER>
A7298 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-MOVIES-$ADV11-2TAK     06-07 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOVIES-$ADV11-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE TELEVISION SPONSORS THE FILM INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: France, Britain, Germany, Denmark, Poland)   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
 By KRISTIN HOHENADEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Television may be the dirtiest four-syllable word in the
American cultural lexicon. But if we like to blame the medium for
dragging down our collective taste and IQ, in Europe, television is
still perceived as a cultural institution with a mission to inform
as well as amuse. It may be host to dubbed ``Dukes of Hazzard''
reruns, American-style celebrity magazines and inane game shows,
but turn on network television tonight in France and you're as
likely to see a documentary about poverty in India or a full-length
broadcast of ``Carmen.''
</P>
<P>
   You're also likely to see theatrical films that were not simply
bought by the networks but were also made by them. Yes, there is
made-for-TV drama in Europe, and it runs the gamut from
movie-of-the-week melodrama to educational projects like the
complete plays of Beckett on Channel 4 in Britain and the
forthcoming ``Les Miserables'' with Gerard Depardieu and John
Malkovich on TF1 in France. But there is also what you might call
made-for-movies TV: European television networks, whether public or
private, are the major players in financing feature films for
theatrical release.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believe that the dominance of television support
has left Europeans to make small, cheap, character-driven films
that can't compete in a world market. But a number of European
channels _ particularly in France, Germany and Britain _ are
devoting increasing financial resources in an attempt to compete
with Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by the European Audiovisual Observatory in
Strasbourg, France, television investment accounts for between 30
and 74 percent of the financing for the production of feature films
in Europe, depending upon the country. Much of that revenue is
generated by public funds derived from taxes on television
companies and by pre-sale agreements, in which television stations
support projects in exchange for the right to broadcast the films
two years after their theatrical release.
</P>
<P>
   The Audiovisual Observatory, which gathers data about broadcast
media in 34 countries, reported that almost 80 percent of the
feature films produced in Europe are made in Germany, France,
Spain, Italy and Britain. And in all those countries, filmmakers
receive some degree of financing from television.
</P>
<P>
   Television companies are the driving force in the business
development of filmmaking in Europe, with Canal-Plus in France,
Britain's Channel 4 and others acting as mini-film studios. In the
last few years, they have expanded their involvement with the
creation of Studio Canal-Plus and FilmFour Limited, stand-alone
entities that receive funds from the channels that own them but
produce movies for theatrical release.
</P>
<P>
   The films, of course, have second and third lives on free and
pay channels; but European television serves to support, not
compete with, national film industries. In France, for example,
pre-sale contributions from television networks are generally not
paid until the film is shown in theaters; this prevents the
possibility of straight-to-TV movies, but has created the need for
short-term bank loans to see filmmakers through development,
production and post-production. Film advertising is not allowed on
French television, to provide something of a level playing field
for rich production companies and more modest independent
producers.
</P>
<P>
   American network television's contribution to dramatic
filmmaking is the Movie of the Week, but in Europe even commercial
television isn't automatically dismissed as an ersatz vehicle for
interesting work. ``There's no stigma for actors, writers,
directors, because of the structure and depth of British television
and the history of the BBC,'' said Paul Webster, who heads
FilmFour. ``If Ian Holm does a TV production, it won't affect his
career like it would Gene Hackman's.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a British television performance that led to Ralph
Fiennes' Hollywood career-launching role in ``Schindler's List.''
Ingmar Bergman's ``Scenes From a Marriage'' (1973) is an edited
version of a six-part drama originally made for Swedish TV. Some of
Britain's most experimental directors _ Ken Loach, Mike Leigh and
Danny Boyle _ started in television. (In the case of Leigh, those
were BBC plays done without a script.) Recently, two noted French
directors made challenging films for the French-German channel Arte
_ Claire Denis' ``Beau Travail'' and Erick Zonca's ``Petit Voleur''
_ that were later released theatrically, further obscuring the
boundaries between films made for television and films destined for
the multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   Arte, which is broadcast free in France, Germany, Belgium,
Luxembourg and Switzerland is considered the most broad-minded and
erudite channel in Europe. Europeans grow up reading subtitles, and
Arte's programs are often seen in their original language with
local subtitles. Some 40 percent of Arte's content consists of
documentaries from around the world, many shown in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a European cultural channel, but we try to discover the
world through beautiful films from everywhere,'' said George
Goldenstern, general director of co-production for Arte.
Goldenstern's channel participated in the international
co-production of Lars von Trier's ``Breaking the Waves,'' ``The
Idiots'' and ``Dancer in the Dark,'' which just won the Palme d'Or
at the Cannes International Film Festival and was pre-sold to
several European television channels.
</P>
<P>
   There is continuing debate in Europe about whether it's healthy
for a handful of television executives to exert so much influence
on the taste of feature filmmaking, but Goldenstern insists that he
makes choices based on the strength of the script and if he
interferes at all, it's during the editing stage of a film.
</P>
<P>
   Vibeke Windelov, who produces von Trier's films for the
Denmark-based Zentropa Films, says: ``I've never had a comment from
Arte or Canal-Plus. They have no influence on what I'm doing and
never tried to.''
</P>
<P>
   Windelov estimated that about 25 percent of the funds for
``Dancer in the Dark'' came from television participation,
including contributions from Arte and COBO, a Dutch cultural
broadcasting fund whose revenue derives from reinvested foreign
cable rights fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lars wouldn't be able to make movies if it wasn't for people
like Arte and Canal-Plus who are willing to go in and give the real
money,'' Windelov said. Von Trier now makes his films in English,
like many European filmmakers. It's a way for them to reach a wider
audience and guarantee better distribution, but it also means that
they don't qualify for subsidies intended to promote national
language and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Gomez, the head of Lolafilms, Spain's largest film
distributor, emphasizes that television investment is crucial to
getting projects made in Spain: ``The average cost of a film in
Spain is $2 million; of that, one-third comes from national
subsidies that support Spanish-language films, another third from
television, and the last from theatrical, video and foreign sales.
Today all films end up on the small screen eventually, but European
producers depend on television money because the budgets are lower.
If the average cost of an American studio picture is $56 million,
television is not going to be a determining factor. But for us the
television money becomes crucial. Who's going to buy a $2 million
picture around the world in Spanish?''
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said that Spanish television executives favor films with a
wide appeal that can be shown in prime time. ``They don't support
sex, violence, auteur films,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   But the restrictions, he said, might be considered liberal by
American standards: uncut versions of ``Basic Instinct'' and ``Last
Tango in Paris'' were recently broadcast in Spanish prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to executives at Fox or Disney, he said, Spanish
executives are a piece of cake: ``They're not so pretentious and
aggressive. They don't get too much involved. They either like a
script or don't; but they won't keep you waiting for a year making
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The European Audiovisual Observatory reported that in newly
privatized countries such as Hungary and Poland, television has
sustained film production by taking up the slack left by weakened
public funding. In Poland, for example, 75 percent of film
production is now paid for by television. But some filmmakers feel
that support is geared toward commercial films that are an easy
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hungary, public television is not so open to the film
industry and was never so important for the film industry as in
western Europe,'' said the Hungarian director Istvan Szabo, who
made his best-known film, ``Mephisto'' (1981), in German. ``Here
there is a low-minded fight between television people and film
people, so there is never very good work between them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the almost 20 years since its founding, Channel 4, the backer
of ``Trainspotting'' and ``East Is East,'' has been widely credited
with pumping life back into the ailing British film industry.
</P>
<P>
   Loach, who has been making films in England for more than three
decades, sees the involvement of television as ``the most important
development in British and European cinema over the last 15
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He began his career at the BBC, directing police shows in the
1960s; his last film, ``Bread and Roses,'' was in competition at
Cannes and is scheduled to open in the United States later this
year. Its $5 million budget included funds from FilmFour and Arte.
``Throughout the 70s,'' he said, ``it was virtually impossible to
make cinema films _ certainly in our country _ that looked to
Europe or to Britain. Everything had to look across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Channel 4s policy of investing in a film that was basically
looking to Britain or Europe on a budget that was appropriate for
that audience, and withholding it on television for two years _
that really opened the doors for everyone. From the '80s up until
now, it made it possible for some of us to work in the cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that the world market is increasingly receptive to
British talent, there is talk in Britain about whether the hand
that has fed the film industry has also stunted its growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always difficult to quantify what makes TV versus
films,'' Webster said. ``But too often material that is better
suited to the small screen ends up on the big screen in the UK, and
that's potentially the downside. I don't think that the power of
television or the quality has held back the film industry in the UK
or Europe in general, in fact, but it may lead to more mistakes; TV
people don't know how difficult it is to get an audience. I think
the immaturity that exists in the industry happens much more often
at the level of sales and distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Making films that can capture worldwide audiences whose
moviegoing tastes have been shaped by the big American-style cinema
experience seems to be the main objective of many European
broadcasters, once content to satisfy their local markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point about movies is they ought to be seen, and quite a
lot of movies go into a black hole in this country,'' said Alan
Yentob, director of drama, entertainment and children's programming
at the BBC, which is in the early stages of stepping up its feature
filmmaking efforts. If nearly every film will end up on the network
anyway, they reason, why not aim to make a go of it at the box
office first?
</P>
<P>
   ``The BBC has always been involved in film,'' Yentob said, ``in
that we've given opportunities to a lot of key talent. We want to
use our leverage and clout now to make more ambitious films,
greater in scale that will get an audience around the world.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
