<HEADLINE>
A BOOK LOVER'S GUIDE FOR THOSE LAZY, HAZY DAYS OF SUMMER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (New York Times Book Review's Summer Book Recommendations)   (This ``separate-buy'' eight-part compilation of recommended
lawn-chair reading is from the highly-regarded New York Times Book
Review section. Complete reviews of these books may be found at The
New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books.) 
 &HT;    
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR YOUR EASE, THIS EXTENSIVE ``BOOK LOOK'' HAS
BEEN MOVED TO YOU IN EIGHT EASY-TO-EDIT PARTS: PARTS 1 THROUGH 3,
FICTION &AMP; POETRY; PARTS 4 THROUGH 7, NONFICTION; AND PART 8,
MYSTERIES AND SCIENCE FICTION. ALL CAN BE FOUND UNDER THE SLUG
BC-VACATION-READING-PART()of8-NYTSF.) 
 &HT;    
 (To publish any, or all, of this tempting list, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480 or fax
her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267.) 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The New York Times Company  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; MYSTERIES &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   BENEATH THE SKIN. By Nicci French. (Mysterious/Warner, $24.95.)
In this insinuating tale of sexual obsession, three London women
walk into the arms of the murderous sadist who is stalking them _
but not before sharing their panicked insights into the intimate
aspects of their characters that have made them perfect victims.
</P>
<P>
   DEATH FROM THE WOODS. By Brigitte Aubert. (Welcome Rain,
$24.95.) This strange, suspenseful thriller stirs suffocating
feelings of dread for its appealing young narrator, whose physical
disabilities make her a sitting duck for the fiend who is killing
children from her smug suburban neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   DEEP SOUTH. By Nevada Barr. (Putnam, $23.95.) The National Park
ranger Anna Pigeon finds herself smothering in the thick vegetation
_ and thicker intrigue _ of the Natchez Trace when she opens an
investigation into the macabre prom-night death of a high school
girl and soon finds herself tangled in the roots of old blood feuds
and race hatreds.
</P>
<P>
   THE EMPTY CHAIR. By Jeffery Deaver. (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25.) A
bug-obsessed teen-ager known as ``the Insect Boy'' drags two women
into the Great Dismal Swamp of North Carolina, setting off a
pulse-raising manhunt whose cunning twists confound even Lincoln
Rhyme, the quadriplegic criminalist who directs the chase from his
snazzy red wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   LOST GIRLS. By Andrew Pyper. (Delacorte, $23.95.) This elegant
debut novel follows a Toronto lawyer into the forbidding North
Country to defend a schoolteacher accused of killing two of his
students and takes a brilliant turn into psychological terror when
the ghostly girls appear to drive the cynical lawyer around the
bend.
</P>
<P>
   THE REMORSEFUL DAY. By Colin Dexter. (Crown, $24.) When it comes
time for a great detective like Inspector Morse to pack it in, he
deserves a splendid elegy with all the bells and whistles, and
that's what the irascible and erudite Oxford copper gets in this
cunningly plotted whodunit about the bondage slaying of a nurse _
the perfect finale to a grand career.
</P>
<P>
   WINTER OF THE WOLF MOON. By Steve Hamilton. (Thomas Dunne/St.
Martin's, $23.95.) Rugged men play brutal games in Michigan's
starkly scenic Upper Peninsula, where Alex McKnight, a former
police officer who knows all too well how the bitter cold and the
isolation can drive you nuts, tries to rescue an Indian woman from
bad guys who don't respect borders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE FICTION &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   INDIGO. By Graham Joyce. (Pocket Books, $23.95.) For the
disaffected protagonist of this skillfully plotted and engagingly
written novel, the search for the secret of invisibility leads to
painful but ultimately liberating self-knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   INVERSIONS. By Iain M. Banks. (Pocket Books, $23.95.) Nothing is
what it seems in this sly parable of love and war, set on a
nameless planet where nominally subordinate women find ways to get
their fingers, and more, on the levers of power.
</P>
<P>
   MEMORANDA. By Jeffrey Ford. (Avon/ Eos, paper, $12.) This sequel
to ``The Physiognomy'' continues the story of Cley, who battles his
one-time despotic master in a Kafkaesque landscape of mental
constructs. While the reality here is ``virtual,'' the author's
evocation of love, terror and pity touches the heart.
</P>
<P>
   MIDNIGHT ROBBER. By Nalo Hopkinson. (Warner/Aspect, paper,
$13.95.) Hopkinson's second novel confirms the promise of her
award-winning ``Brown Girl in the Ring'' (1998). In a vigorous
Caribbean-flavored ``patwa,'' she tells the tale of Tan-Tan, a
young girl too full of life to be broken by abuse on a prison
planet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (HERE'S AN EDITOR-FRIENDLY WORD COUNT BREAKDOWN OF THE
PACKAGE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 1 _ Fiction &AMP; Poetry: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 2 - Fiction &AMP; Poetry: 875 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 3 - Fiction &AMP; Poetry: 875 words
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 4 - Nonfiction: 800 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 5 - Nonfiction: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 6 - Nonfiction: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 7 - Nonfiction: 950 words;
</P>
<P>
   _ Part 8 - Mysteries/Science Fiction: 600 words.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOW GRAB YOUR BEACH TOWEL AND A BOOK!...) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
