<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV611-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICAL MERRY-GO-ROUND: ONE PARTY STEALING FROM THE OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For Release Sunday, June 11)   &HT;     (For use by NewYork Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If imitation is the sincerest form of flattery,
then Al Gore and the Democrats should be wallowing in adulation
provided by George W. Bush and the Republican high command.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his fellow GOP leaders have thus far demonstrated
remarkable political wisdom by copying and stealing issues that
Democrats have used successfully in past elections.
</P>
<P>
   To a ``yellow dog'' Democrat _ a staunch party loyalist who
would rather vote for a ``yellow dog'' than a Republican _ the term
``wise Republican'' is an oxymoron. But it is an accurate
description of Bush and the shrewd strategists who are running his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Name an issue that Democrats have shaped, fostered and converted
into a winning campaign theme and you will find that the new
Republican team has adopted that issue as its own. Bush and his
strategists appear to have learned from their defeats of the past
that wise politics dictates an invasion of Democratic territory.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Republicans lost the 1948 election to Harry
Truman when voters in major farm states such as Iowa, Illinois,
Minnesota and Wisconsin surprised the professional politicians and
the press by voting Democratic. They did so after Truman
barnstormed the Middle West accusing the Republican 80th Congress
of refusing to provide funds for ample grain storage in a year in
which a bumper corn crop was ready to be harvested.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to store their corn in bins approved by the government's
Commodity Credit Corporation, farmers could not qualify for federal
price supports. So many of them faced heavy losses in a year that
should have proved prosperous for them.
</P>
<P>
   At the national plowing contest in Dexter, Iowa, the president
hit the farm issue hard, recalling the desperate days of the Great
Depression when violence erupted in agricultural communities and,
Truman said, ``223,000 farmers'' lost their farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how many times you have to be hit on the head before
you find out who's hitting you?'' Truman asked the huge throng of
farmers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   He got his answer on Election Day when they cast a majority of
their votes for him and his fellow Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   That was long ago. But Republicans have good memories. The
current leaders do not want a repeat of that episode.
</P>
<P>
   So on May 25 the Republican-led Congress approved a $15.3
billion package of programs to aid farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Although George W. Bush was but a teenager in 1960, he no doubt
has learned from his father one of the reasons that the Democratic
presidential nominee that year, John F. Kennedy, won. Kennedy
capitalized on his claim that America had fallen behind the Soviet
Union in missile production and was the victim of a serious
``missile gap.''
</P>
<P>
   In his race against then-Vice President Richard Nixon, Kennedy
hammered relentlessly at the missile gap, attributing it to the
Dwight Eisenhower administration without mentioning the name of the
popular former five-star general.
</P>
<P>
   Since JFK defeated Nixon by a mere 13,673 popular votes out of
nearly 70 million cast for the two candidates, it would appear that
the missile gap argument played a key role in his victory.
</P>
<P>
   After his inauguration, however, Kennedy found that there never
was such a perilous national defense deficiency between the United
States and its No. 1 Cold War foe, the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   In the current debate, Bush has called for a substantially
larger missile defense system than the one proposed by President
Clinton and supported by Vice President Al Gore and has labled the
administration plan ``flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   To boost his argument, Bush unveiled his plan with two former
secretaries of state, Henry Kissinger and George Shultz, at his
side, along with his father's White House national security
adviser, Brent Scowcroft, and the former chairman of the joint
chiefs of staff, Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Bush contends that an adequate missile defense shield would
protect America and its allies from nuclear attacks by such rogue
states as North Korea, Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also taken up an issue that has been closely identified
with the Democrats _ Social Security, created by Franklin D.
Roosevelt and strongly supported by all subsequent Democratic
presidents and congresses. The vote of seniors who depend on Social
Security played an important part in Clinton's two presidential
victories.
</P>
<P>
   But who was first out of the gate this year with a proposal to
overhaul the program as a means of saving it? Why, George W., of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's various proposals for improving the federal government
raise a lot of questions. But even without much clarification, his
plans appear to have had a favorable impact on voters, according to
public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Democrats has been that when Bush acts, Gore
reacts.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, conservative critics in the GOP would have called
Bush and his colleagues ``me too'' Republicans. But so far the
critics have avoided that designation because Republicans are so
anxious to regain the White House after eight years of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If they were not involved in a political contest with few holds
barred, the Democrats might consider suing the Republicans for
invasion of their domain. It is a facetious idea, but one that
illustrates the dilemma of the Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
