<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTRESS OWNED AN ENTIRE TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ What town in Georgia does Kim Basinger own? _ G.B., via
the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Basinger was once an owner of Braselton, a town of 450
northeast of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The actress, a native of Athens, Ga., was part of an investment
group that paid $20 million in 1990 for 1,750 acres. The group
planned to develop a theme park, but the property was sold for $4.3
million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Basinger filed for bankruptcy protection after a Los
Angeles Superior Court ordered her to pay $8.9 million for
breaching a contract to appear in the film ``Boxing Helena.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans can write to her in care of Creative Artists Agency, 9830
Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Cape Canaveral was renamed Cape Kennedy after President
Kennedy's death. When was the name changed back? _ O.B., Fort
Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ In March 1973, the Florida Legislature passed a
resolution calling for a change back to Cape Canaveral. The Board
of Geographic Names, an agency of the U.S. Department of the
Interior, made it official five months later.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after Kennedy's assassination, President Johnson
persuaded the board to change the name, which he announced on
Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a number of Floridians were peeved about changing the
name of the cape, which had been called Canaveral for more than 400
years,'' ``Straight Dope'' columnist Cecil Adams writes.
</P>
<P>
   The cape, the main launching point for staffed space flights,
Earth satellites and long-range missiles since 1947, is the home of
the John F. Kennedy Manned Space Flight Center.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Where can I write to David Sedaris? _ S.R., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Write to Sedaris in care of Steven Barclay, 321
Pleasant St., Petaluma, CA 94952.
</P>
<P>
   Sedaris, 39, is an essayist who began contributing to National
Public Radio in 1992, describing his experiences as a Macy's elf.
His fourth book, ``Me Talk Pretty One Day,'' was atop the
``Publishers Weekly'' and ``Newsday'' nonfiction bestseller lists
in May.
</P>
<P>
   From Nov. 2 to 4, Sedaris is scheduled to do five readings from
``Me Talk Pretty'' at the McKinney Avenue Contemporary in Dallas.
Call (214) 953-1212 for more information.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
