<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS MICROSOFT SPLIT INTO TWO COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL BRICK   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled Wednesday that Microsoft (MSFT:Nasdaq)
should be split into two separate companies to remedy antitrust
violations and foster competition in the markets for computer
operating systems and software applications.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 17 state attorneys general devised
the plan, details of which the giant software company and
prosecutors have disputed in public court filings for the past two
weeks. The additional filings have delayed the ruling, which was
widely expected last week.
</P>
<P>
   The judged stayed the breakup portion of the ruling until
appeals are completed. The ruling gives Microsoft four months from
Wednesday to devise a plan to separate the operating system
business from the applications business.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the judgment, a series of restrictions on
Microsoft's business practices, takes effect in 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   In substance, the order closely resembles the original Justice
Department proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Redmond, Wash.-based company has repeatedly vowed to appeal
the three-part ruling note for note, including the judge's Nov. 5
finding that Microsoft sought to extend a monopoly on operating
systems to other markets, his April 3 ruling that such behavior
violated the Sherman Antitrust Act and the remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft shares closed up 7/8, or 1 percent, at 70 1/2. Adverse
developments in the trial, including the first two portions of
Jackson's ruling and the breakdown of private settlement
negotiations, have dragged the company's stock price down from a
52-week high of 119 15/16, reached in December during settlement
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-long antitrust trial has reverberated across most
sectors of this information and technology economy. For a full
decade, starting with a 1990 Federal Trade Commission
investigation, the government has pursued sanctions against the
25-year-old company.
</P>
<P>
   The widely expected ruling, which applies antitrust law to a
business sector revolving around rapidly changing technology, is
comparable in scope only to the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T's (T:NYSE)
telephone monopoly, the breakup of United Shoe in 1968 and the
historic dismantling of John D. Rockefeller's Standard Oil Trust in
1911. While comparable in scope, splitting Microsoft into separate
entities defined by the products they manufacture would be without
much precedent in method. The government's previous trust busting
has nearly always sought to stimulate competition in a single
product, be it footwear, oil or telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup, linchpin of the ruling, would place the ubiquitous
Windows operating system in one company and create a second
business for everything else, including software applications, the
Internet Explorer Web browser and the Microsoft Network Internet
service provider and network of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jackson's attempts to pick up the pace of the trial,
which he has said are partially motivated by a desire to allow
appeals to begin, the time required for those appeals is unknown.
Provisions specific to antitrust law give the U.S. solicitor
general, and not the Justice Department, 15 days to request that
the Supreme Court immediately review the company's appeal. That
would allow the government to leapfrog the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia, which reversed Jackson in an
earlier ruling adverse to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The behavioral remedies take effect within 90 days of a ruling.
These remedies include publishing the so-called source code used by
programmers to design software applications for Windows and placing
guidelines on Microsoft's relations with computer-makers and other
software companies.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
