<HEADER>
A7307 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     06-07 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in Scripture'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carol Meyers, general editor; Toni Craven and Ross S. Kraemer,
associate editors &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $40 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scripture is about humankind's attempts to get along with God,
and vice versa. It's easier to get along with people we understand.
And it's easier for modern Scripture readers to understand the
characters when their milieus are clear.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we're not trying to explain God here. But ``Women in
Scripture'' is an immense help in fathoming why the women in the
Bible _ and that includes the Hebrew Bible, the
Apocryphal/Deuterocanonical books and the New Testament _ did what
they did and elicited the reactions they did.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a regurgitation of unfounded myths, despite the
traditional Protestant Bible's sketchiness about even the most
important women. For example, much of what we've been told about
Mary Magdalene (reformed prostitute, etc.) is set aside here as
totally lacking evidence and is attributed to male fantasy and
jealousy. Few traditional Sunday schools give this Mary her due as
discloser of special revelations from Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Among the book's editors is Toni Craven, a professor of the
Hebrew Bible at Brite Divinity School in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women in Scripture'' is a valuable aid for anyone who wants to
understand the people through whom we have received our
Judeo-Christian legacy. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Betsy Friauf &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Signatures of Grace'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Thomas Grady and Paula Huston &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E.P. Dutton, $23.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This book of essays on the Roman Catholic sacraments attempts to
find a balance between the ``richly ambiguous'' nature of human
ritual and what Mary Gordon's chapter calls the ``church's desire
for legible symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it works, with enough personal epiphanies and
storytelling elements to offset the scholarly explorations of
theology, church history, doctrinal debate and contemporary
concerns. (The book doesn't candy-coat church shortcomings, but it
doesn't dwell on them, either.)
</P>
<P>
   What stick in the memory are the personal images, the
first-person voices and narratives about these rituals that ``cause
internal changes in the participants.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the voices are those of writers, such as Andre Dubus, a
father who sees ``holiness'' in everyday rituals like making
sandwiches in a cramped kitchen for his school-age daughters. Or
like Katherine Vaz, who writes lyrically about the water of
baptism.
</P>
<P>
   More minority voices would have given the collection a richer
feel. But considering the variety of approaches, it hangs together
reasonably well. It is a priest's voice, near the end, that draws
the threads together, describing the sacraments according to the
ways they help purify one's vision in order to ``see God in all
things.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Mary Bolduc &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1734EDT &QL; 
