<SLUG> BC-KINGLEAR-COMPARISON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH `LEAR' IS KING? YOU DECIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one of the great parts of the English-language stage _ and
cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Even as you read this, two new film versions of ``King Lear''
are headed for the multiplexes. One, with a screenplay by Ernst
Kaufmann, is scheduled to be released this year or in early 2001.
Another, Kristian Levring's ``The King Is Alive,'' recently
screened at the Cannes Film Festival. The modern-set film features
Jennifer Jason Leigh, Janet McTeer and Bruce Davison, it is set in
the desert. When a bus breaks down, its passengers decide to stage
``Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   We decided to take a look at some of the memorable film versions
of the Bard's famous tragedy. All are available on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Lear,'' 1997: This Mobil Masterpiece Theatre production
stars Ian Holm in the title role, and makes a 1996 stage production
TV-ready. What's interesting about this is that most of the
characters are cloaked in black, with Lear's daughters, Regan,
Goneril and Cordelia, outfitted in gray power suits. Much of the
opening action takes place in a crimson-red boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Thousand Acres,'' 1997: Jane Smiley's novel was inspired by
``King Lear.'' In the 1997 film, which critics generally panned,
Jennifer Jason Leigh (she must have a thing for ``Lear''), Jessica
Lange and Michelle Pfeiffer play the daughters of farmer Larry,
played by Jason Robards.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Lear,'' 1987: Perhaps the oddest version. After the
Chernobyl nuclear accident, many great works are lost, and it is up
to ``William Shakespeare Jr. the Fifth'' (Peter Sellers) to restore
the lost artworks. At a resort, he finds strange goings-on with mob
boss Don Learo (Burgess Meredith) and his daughter Cordelia (Molly
Ringwald). For some reason, he films it, and the footage is sent to
New York for Mr. Alien (Woody Allen) to edit. Jean-Luc Godard
directs.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Lear,'' 1984:You can't go wrong with Laurence Olivier and
Shakespeare, and you don't here. It's a well-acted version, but the
production, originally for stage, looks as if it were being taped
by a novice using a camcorder. Check out babe Diana Rigg as Regan.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Lear,'' 1982: This BBC version starring Michael Hordern
also has the shaky trappings of a slightly glorified filming of a
stage production. This one is a good introduction for those not
familiar with the play because of its simplicity and faithfulness
to the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Lear,'' 1971: Peter Brook directs this stylishly dark and
shadowy black-and-white version, starring Paul Scofield, who may be
to ``King Lear'' what Olivier is to ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
