<HEADER>
A7311 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-CONTROL-FREAK-SPI &LR;      06-07 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTROL-FREAK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPATHY BEST FOR CONTROLLING CONTROL FREAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pity the poor control freak.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he makes your life hell, he's quivering with hidden
anxiety. ``A jellyfish in armor'' is how one expert describes him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you understood what's driving him (or her), you'd
sympathize _ up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, maybe the jerk wouldn't get under your skin
so much, says psychologist Les Parrott III, who wrote the book on
control freaks and admits to some control tendencies himself.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to neutralize overcontrolling behavior, much of
which stems from a fear of being criticized or shamed for making an
error.
</P>
<P>
   But for now just start working on that empathy thing. Parrott
says that's the single best technique for dealing with overly
driven people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risky thing about empathy is it will change you,'' says
Parrott, co-director of the Center for Relationship Development at
Seattle Pacific University. ``It's threatening, because we don't
like to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says it's worth the effort:
</P>
<P>
   ``The research has shown that 90 percent of the problems we
encounter in relationships can be resolved, or at least improved,
by doing nothing other than seeing that issue from the other
person's perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrott delves deeper in his new book, ``The Control Freak:
Coping With Those Around You, Controlling the One Within'' (Tyndale
House, 193 pages, $19.99).
</P>
<P>
   Parrott, who writes prolifically on relationship issues, is a
familiar media figure, with past appearances on ``Oprah,'' ``NBC
Nightly News,'' ``CBS This Morning'' and other shows.
</P>
<P>
   His renown stems from his work with SPU's Center for
Relationship Development, which he and his wife, Leslie _ a
marriage and family therapist _ founded and direct. They also teach
the most popular class on the SPU campus, ``Relationships 101.''
</P>
<P>
   This month the Parrotts begin a year as
``marriage-scholars-in-residence'' in Oklahoma as part of the
state's $10 million campaign to reduce its spiraling divorce rate.
</P>
<P>
   So just what is a control freak?
</P>
<P>
   Parrott defines it as ``someone who cares more about something
than you do and becomes pushy to get their way.''
</P>
<P>
   He says their tactics are legion:
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be obnoxious, they can be persistent, they can be
invasive, they can be nit-picky and perfectionist.''
</P>
<P>
   And modern life is making it worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is feeding our control frenzy,'' Parrott maintains.
``People like to-do lists. These Palm Pilots and everything we use
now to get organized make us feel in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Control freaks victimize themselves as well as others. They risk
high blood pressure, heart disease and, at the very least, loss of
enjoyment in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically, there's this intense pressure that never
allows you to relax when you're a control freak,'' Parrott says.
``You're doing so much at the same time. You're putting on your
makeup while you're driving the car. There's no sense of peace or
centeredness.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrott has written about other difficult personality types,
from The Wet Blanket and The Critic to The Flirt. He described 15
such party-poopers in a 1997 book, ``High-Maintenance
Relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like the Avon Lady, the control freak pushes a lot of
buttons. After Parrott's ``High-Maintenance'' guide was published,
many readers sent letters asking him to expand on his chapter about
The Control Freak. So he wrote his new book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost anyone you talk to will say, `I know a control freak, I
am a control freak,' '' says Parrott, 38, a boyish-looking
professor with a shock of brown hair spilling over his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   He's dressed casually, in navy polo shirt, jeans and mocs
without socks. But he has the tightly coiled manner you'd expect in
a guy who says he has spent his entire married life harping on the
backhanded way his wife cuts carrots. To no avail, incidentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been married 16 years,'' he notes rhetorically, ``and
how do you think she cuts carrots?''
</P>
<P>
   His control-freak symptoms flared recently after a five-hour
wait at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport made him an hour
late for an appearance in Charlotte, N.C. Stressed and anxious, he
felt driven to control the entire event, from the scheduling to the
seating arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of saying, `What's your opinion?' I began to bark
orders,'' Parrott says.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the host told him, ``You need a vacation. You were
pretty uptight.''
</P>
<P>
   Nervous, high-strung people are more prone to controlling
behavior, but most of us go overboard once in a while. We may be
tired and stressed _ or reacting to a pet peeve like how to hang
the toilet-paper roll.
</P>
<P>
   Up to a point, a drive for control is healthy and even essential
for functioning, Parrott says. The ability to manage pain is one
example.
</P>
<P>
   Even hard-core controllers may have redeeming qualities _
competence and commitment, for example. As Parrott puts it, ``Would
you rather go to a surgeon who's happy-go-lucky or a control
freak?''
</P>
<P>
   Parrott says controlling behavior crosses the line ``when it
starts to interfere with your functioning, when you become an
irritant to the people around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core types turn every situation into a competition for
control. Most of them will do ``just about anything'' to get their
way, making victims feel not just annoyed but demeaned.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, empathy will get you only so far. If the control
freak is interfering with your ability to enjoy life or function
well, it's time to draw some boundaries. But try to remain tactful
and calm. Avoid ultimatums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Threatening a control freak is not the wisest of things,''
Parrott says, ``because that sends them more wildly out of
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, recognize it may not be in your power to fully remove
the thorn from your side.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person can change the dynamics of the relationship,''
Parrott says. ``But for the control freak to change, it really
comes down to awareness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
