<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-TRIALS08-COX     06-07 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-TRIALS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ORDERS MEDICARE TO COVER CLINICAL TRIALS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Paving the way for thousands of elderly patients to
receive potentially life-saving experimental medical treatment,
President Clinton ordered Medicare Wednesday to pay for routine
costs associated with clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's executive order expands on legislation which has
languished in Congress for four years that would have paid for
cancer-related clinical trial coverage. The president's action will
cover all approved medical trials.
</P>
<P>
   The order will not cover the actual costs of the trials, many of
which are paid by the drug company or medical equipment company
testing a new medicine or device. Instead, the order which takes
effect immediately means Medicare will now cover the cost of
hospitalization and related care which was not covered for most
patients participating in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has not projected how many of the 38 million
Medicare beneficiaries might participate in clinical trials and the
cost of such coverage has not been calculated. The president's
order will require Medicare to begin keeping such records.
</P>
<P>
   Patient groups and lawmakers involved with the stalled
legislation hailed the president's order as a major step toward
offering hope for many older Americans facing potentially
catastrophic illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of my friends who are senior citizens ... I think this
is a glorious day,'' said Ellen Stoval, executive director of the
National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., a cancer survivor and sponsor, along
with Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., of the cancer trial bill, said
``this is a very exciting moment for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that only about 2 or 3 percent of Medicare patients
participate in clinical trials because they cannot afford the
related hospital costs, Mack said the order should give many more
seniors ``the opportunity to participate in what, for them, could
be a life-saving medical procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller described prior Medicare rules barring coverage of
clinical trials as a ``blockage'' as deadly to some seniors as a
blocked artery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst possible scenario is when you have the best possible
care and you don't make them available ... because of some
blockage,'' Rockefeller said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., sponsor of a similar House bill,
said ``I believe firmly that thousands and thousand of our senior
citizens ... are going to have new hope ... longer lives, and some
of them cures,'' because of the order.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said he was concerned that Clinton's order may open the
door for trials that are not scientifically sound to receive
coverage, but Johnson said she was confident that the Health Care
Financing Administration's final rule would specify that only
medically approved trials would be covered.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly two-thirds of cancer patients are older than 65,
only about one-third of all cancer patients enrolled in clinical
trials are in that age group, according to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Among breast cancer patients, 44 percent are elderly, but fewer
than 2 percent are enrolled in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Cancer Society believes increased access to
clinical trials is a key element in the war on cancer,'' said Dr.
Gerald L. Woolam, the organization's president. ``Today's action
will remove one of the unnecessary roadblocks our seniors face in
their efforts to get state-of-the-art cancer treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent Institute of Medicine report listed the lack of
Medicare coverage of routine patient care as a primary reason why
more elderly do not participate in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   White House: www.whitehouse.gov/WH/New/
</P>
<P>
   National Coalition for Cancer Survivorship: www.cansearch.org/
</P>
<P>
   American Cancer Society: www.cancer.org
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
