<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7318 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT-GLANCE08-CO     06-07 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GLANCE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are sanctions ordered Wednesday by U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson in the antitrust case
against Microsoft Corp. Microsoft has 90 days to file an appeal of
these sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKUP OF THE COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   _ Within four months: Microsoft must submit a plan dividing
itself into two parts. One part would produce and sell the Windows
operating system, and the other would would produce and sell
applications such as Office and the Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   _ 60 days later: The government may submit objections to the
breakup plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ 30 days later: Microsoft may respond to the objections.
</P>
<P>
   RESTRICTIONS ON CONDUCT
</P>
<P>
   For three years after the breakup goes into effect, Microsoft
must operate under certain business practices, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ It cannot take or threaten action against any computer maker
that uses a competing product or service.
</P>
<P>
   _ It cannot restrict companies from displaying computer screens
or icons that direct users to competing products or services.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must provide the technical information needed to make other
software work with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   _ It cannot offer selected companies special discounts or other
incentives to license Windows.
</P>
<P>
   _ It cannot force companies to buy other Microsoft products in
order to get a license to sell Windows.
</P>
<P>
   _ It cannot take actions that make competing software work less
well with Windows unless it notifies the maker and offers to help
it avoid the problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must license future versions of Windows to current
customers at a fair price.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
