<HEADER>
A7319 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      06-07 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIEDAN HAS NOT MELLOWED 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I heard Betty Friedan yelling on the radio while I was driving
down the freeway and I started laughing. Good old Betty, giving a
radio interviewer hell, saying something like, ``That's it. I'm
leaving,'' because she didn't like his question.
</P>
<P>
   All the goll darn (but she didn't say goll darn) media ever
wants to talk about is a long-ago falling-out between her and some
other feminist leaders. Do they care that much when men wrangle?
No, she fairly hissed. They're just looking for a cat fight.
</P>
<P>
   She says in her new book, ``I've always been a bad-tempered
bitch.'' And aren't we glad? Had women not learned to be
disagreeable we'd still be crying into our soapsuds, smoldering in
silence. Thirty years of outspokenness has been good for women, and
as Betty Friedan points out, what's good for women is good for men,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The same week I heard her yelling on the radio I went to a book
signing for ``Life So Far,'' her first memoir following six books
that started with ``The Feminine Mystique,'' that basic primer of
discontent. She wore a brimmed hat and a turtleneck and sat in a
wicker chair, next to a brash bouquet of rhododendrons, a good
choice since her presence might have wilted a lesser flower.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan is nearing 80. She's prickly. When you're prickly,
people don't ignore you. It's a trait worth working on.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't open her book to read. She preferred to take
questions, peering at her audience with those lidded Buddha-like
eyes, daring us to say something intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   Someone wondered if feminism had made women happier? She frowned
over the word happy. There was always more to women's equality than
being happy. Happy is a bird in a gilded cage.
</P>
<P>
   What about this continuing crazy focus on body image? ``It's
really quite irritating,'' she agreed. ``We need more women defying
that sort of thing, saying this is a real body. Then we can start
applauding authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   How is it to be someone who smartened up a whole society, got
people thinking entirely different and encouraged half the
population to feel better about themselves? She seems pretty
humbled by it. ``I don't know who appointed me to lead women out of
the wilderness,'' she said, and then decides it was in the timing.
Women were itching to break free. She wrote about what was going on
in her life and it coincided with a moment in history. Her words
resonated and helped start a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   You might assume that a Betty Friedan is naturally bold and more
confident than others. But if you look inside her life story you
find a woman who was just as scared, guilt-ridden and insecure as
the rest of us. She was a housewife who guiltily squeezed her
writing time around her kids' school hours. Shy about her success,
she was embarrassed when people started referring to her husband as
``Betty's husband'' and then, as she says in the book, paid for it
at home. But the fear of being alone prevented her for a time from
leaving a troubled marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked at the book signing what the women's movement has
done for men and she said it's been good for them, to no longer
``require a subservient woman'' to feel good about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The male ego is starting to move to a firmer basis than
machismo,'' she said. ``Men have become strong enough to be
tender.''
</P>
<P>
   As for men's role in their families, she thinks our society is
still ``too mother-centered,'' with child-raising primarily a
mother's concern. As soon as fathers become just as involved in
raising their kids, ``we can pick up our skirts and declare
ourselves equal.''
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen will require ``a basic restructuring of
work,'' which allows ``both mother and fathers to effectively
combine work and family.'' The world of business, she says, still
operates on the dinosaur model ``that a working man has a wife at
home to take care of all the details of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's working woman surely doesn't have that at home, but
neither, she points out, does the working man. So business has to
change and feminists _ they being both women and men _ will have to
force it to change.
</P>
<P>
   Oh good. Another revolution.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
