<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Heat will reach record levels for early June in many spots from
the central Rockies to the northern and central Plains on Thursday.
Afternoon temperatures in the 90s to near 100 will be common in
those regions. Late Thursday, scattered potent thunderstorms will
erupt at the edge of the hot air mass from northern Montana to
northern Minnesota. Afternoon thundershowers will also develop over
many of the peaks of the central and southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front will move slowly east across the interior West, and
a band of clouds and showers will follow it from northern Nevada to
Idaho. The Pacific Northwest will be cool with variable clouds and
a few showers.
</P>
<P>
   A strong warming trend will blossom in much of the East. Showers
will precede the arrival of the warmth in northern New England.
Meanwhile, a tropical disturbance will send heavy showers toward
the Texas coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WET DAYS
</P>
<P>
   New York City, Boston and Albany, N.Y., all had their wettest
June 6 on record as a late spring storm brought 2-5 inches of rain
on parts of the Northeast. Within the last week, parts of Minnesota
and Texas also set daily records for rain. One of the most notable
climate trends in the United States during the past 100 years has
been a relatively steady increase in wetness. The added
precipitation has been the result of more days with extreme rain
that can produce flash flooding rather than a large increase in the
total number of days with precipitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
