<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7323 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-REVIEW-SPI &LR;      06-07 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``INVISIBLE MAN'' FILLS MINDLESS AIR TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holy ahi! Turns out you don't have to be a tuna to get mercury
poisoning. Just stop by your regional fish-and-game office and
they'll administer a quicksilver implant while you wait.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned: Side effects may include headache, bloodshot eyes,
violent tantrums and the urge to quote Nietzsche and Santayana. But
the upside is the ability to go missing at a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   In the newest televersion of ``The Invisible Man,'' petty thief
and inveterate con-man Darien Fawkes has chosen the implant, his
alternative being a lifetime in prison as a third-time offender.
This sci-fi experiment is standard TV stuff in that it goes
horribly awry _ you were expecting it to go horribly right? _ and
Fawkes has little choice but to remain in the employ of U.S. Fish
and Game, the government agency that was experimenting on him
because it had excess funding while the CIA and NSA were
underbudgeted. Besides, it controls the supply of counteragent he
needs to keep from becoming a real monster.
</P>
<P>
   His ability to become invisible makes Fawkes valuable in the
battle against crime, not to mention the battle of deciding what to
wear each morning. The biosynthetic quicksilver gland, developed by
Fawkes' brainy brother, is grafted to his cerebral cortex and looks
like a potsticker with tentacles. Its removal would cause
almost-certain death, for some pseudo-scientific reason that makes
no sense, so Fawkes continues showing up for work, unless it's to
his advantage not to show up, if you get my drift.
</P>
<P>
   This latest adaptation of the 1897 H.G. Wells novel is the fruit
of an idea that once had Kyle MacLachlan mentioned for the title
role and the series earmarked for Fox. MacLachlan and Fox
eventually disappeared, and the producer, Studios USA, is
simultaneously peddling the show to cable (Studios USA and Sci Fi
Channel are part of USA Networks) and to broadcast stations via
syndication. In the Seattle market, KONG/16 will carry episodes of
``The Invisible Man'' a couple of weeks after they run on Sci Fi,
beginning with the two-hour premiere at 9 p.m. June 18 (repeated at
10 p.m. June 25), and subsequent one-hour episodes on Sundays at 10
p.m., starting July 2.
</P>
<P>
   Syndication is an especially appropriate venue for ``The
Invisible Man,'' which has the passionless, assembly-line look of
so many other superficial shows intended not to challenge the actor
and the viewer but to provide an hour of mindless air time on a
weekend night.
</P>
<P>
   Sci Fi Channel describes the series as an action/comedy, and
Vincent Ventresca does play the tormented Fawkes with touches of
bemusement and bewilderment. But with so many folks dying in the
two-hour premiere, it's hard to take the comedy seriously. More
distressing is the disappearance of Fawkes' sometime girlfriend,
Casey (Rebecca Chambers), who promises at the end of tomorrow's
premiere to help him cope with the effects of his intracranial
dumpling. Casey happens to be a neuro-bio-something-or-other
physician, but in Episode 2 her place in the requisite eye-candy
category is usurped by the Keeper, a government doctor who tells
Fawkes to trust her whenever she sticks a needle in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Where Casey seemed to display a spark of real life, Shannon
Kenny's ``Keeper'' is the oh-so-hackneyed humorless scientist who
will no doubt let her hair down sometime this season and display a
warmer side when she discovers she likes Fawkes for more than his
slightly damaged mind.
</P>
<P>
   The cliches don't stop there. The agency partners Fawkes with a
wacky but disgruntled field agent named Hobbes (Paul Ben-Victor),
and his boss, known simply as ``the Official,'' is a rumpled civil
servant with a lot of miles on his weary countenance.
</P>
<P>
   On a gee-whiz level, ``The Invisible Man'' sticks to
slick-but-basic special effects reminiscent of those used on Robert
Patrick's now-you-see-him-now-you-don't melting man in ``Terminator
2: Judgment Day.'' For TV, they're very good, but they'll most
likely pale in comparison to the effects in the upcoming Kevin
Bacon film, ``The Hollow Man,'' which takes the invisible man
concept to the big screen July 28.
</P>
<P>
   Producers don't worry about such comparisons, as long as
interest in the movie _ unrelated though it may be _ generates
interest in the series. Should that happen, ``The Invisible Man''
will be a success in spite of its failure to go very deep into
Darien Fawkes' brain.
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's television critic. Call him at
206-448-8330 or send e-mail to tvguy &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
