<HEADER>
A7324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INDONESIA-INVEST-(TRI     06-07 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-INVEST-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S CENTRAL BANK CHIEF, ACCUSED OF CORRUPTION, REFUSES TO
QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Two days after Indonesia's central bank
governor was named as a suspect in a financial scandal, he and the
government squared off Wednesday in a bitter showdown that could
erode what little confidence investors have in this fragile
country.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Bank Indonesia, Syahril Sabirin, said he would
not step down despite repeated requests from Indonesia's president,
Abdurrahman Wahid. Sabirin denied any wrongdoing and said he was a
victim of a political witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have stolen any money,'' Sabirin said in an
interview on the CNBC Asia cable TV network. ``In fact, from my
childhood, I don't think I have stolen any money.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's chief law enforcement officer, however, said the
governor should be suspended. Attorney General Marzuki Darusman
said Sabirin could not serve as central bank governor while he was
the target of a criminal investigation. He also rejected a decision
by the speaker of Indonesia's parliament to allow Sabirin to keep
his job until his fate was decided in a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of interpretation or politics,'' Darusman
said in an interview Wednesday. ``He has to be suspended
temporarily. That's the law.''
</P>
<P>
   For Indonesians, who are steeped in scandals and political
intrigue, the power struggle is simply another chapter in the
stormy presidency of Wahid. But for foreign investors, who have
watched from the sidelines as Indonesia has struggled to recover
from the upheavals of 1998, it is a worrying sign that the country
is once again spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, fell 0.52 percent in trading
Wednesday, to 8,610 rupiah to the dollar. The rupiah has lost 19
percent of its value since the beginning of the year because of the
political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole way Wahid handles disputes has been baffling,'' said
Bill Kaye, the senior managing director of the Pacific Group, a
hedge fund in Hong Kong that has so far avoided Indonesia. ``He's
perceived as not only ineffectual, but also tainted by cronyism.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Wahid set off the rupiah's latest slide when he
dismissed two respected cabinet ministers and replaced them with
friends. In a twist typical of Indonesian politics, one of the
ousted ministers, Laksamana Sukardi, is now a candidate to replace
Sabirin at the central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid was also tainted when an official at the state logistics
agency said he had transferred $4.2 million to the president's
masseur. Much of the money has since been returned, and the scandal
seems destined to be a footnote in the annals of Indonesian
chicanery.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sabirin, however, was implicated in a more sensational scandal,
the Bank Bali affair. The governor approved a $63 million payment
from the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Authority to Bank Bali,
ostensibly to cover loans owed to it by other banks. Bank Bali then
funneled much of the money into a company linked to Indonesia's
former ruling party, Golkar.
</P>
<P>
   The money was to be used to finance the presidential campaign of
Wahid's predecessor, B.J. Habibie. Habibie withdrew from the
election when it was clear he would suffer a crushing defeat. The
public outrage over the Bank Bali affair was a major reason for his
downfall.
</P>
<P>
   An outside investigation of the scandal said Sabirin had
attended a meeting in which the use of the money was discussed. He
has denied attending the meeting, but other witnesses have
contradicted him. The attorney general said Sabirin should not have
approved the payment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sabirin, who was appointed by Indonesia's former president,
Suharto, was regarded as a competent and honest bureaucrat before
the scandal broke. A courtly, soft-spoken man, he has nevertheless
emerged as a stubborn foe of Wahid and his attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Darusman said Wednesday that Sabirin was a ``crucial element in
the whole case.'' He said the governor could provide evidence that
would allow it to pursue other senior officials in the Habibie
administration who had helped orchestrate the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the furor it is causing, some experts said the
government's pursuit of Sabirin was a welcome sign. ``This suggests
that the government is going to do something dramatic on the Bank
Bali case soon,'' said James W. Castle, an longtime consultant
here.
</P>
<P>
   For Darusman, who is also leading the government's investigation
of the disgraced former president, Suharto, the Bank Bali case is a
litmus test for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents the massive commercial fraud that took place in
this country for years,'' he said. ``If we are going to be serious
about tackling this problem, this case has got to be resolved. If
we don't resolve it, people will regard the government with
cynicism.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
