<HEADER>
A7325 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GENETIC-DISCRIMINATIO     06-07 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENETIC-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DNA EXPERT URGES CONGRESS TO TAKE STEPS AGAINST GENETIC BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A pioneer in the quest to complete the human
genetic map warned Congress Wednesday that the possibility of
genetic discrimination threatens to stall advances in
biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   J. Craig Venter, co-founder of Rockville, Md.-based Celera
Genomics Corp., said that as science unravels each individual's
genetic blueprint, insurance companies and employers could use the
DNA information to deny health coverage or jobs to people who are
genetically predisposed to certain diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural that an insurance company would be wary of
insuring someone who has a propensity to getting cancer at an early
age or who likely will be afflicted with Alzheimer's,'' he told the
Joint Economic Committee of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists also fear that genetic discrimination could creep
into other areas of life. For example, banks could refuse to give
loans to people susceptible to debilitating diseases, believing
they would not be able to repay the money.
</P>
<P>
   Venter, who expects individual genetic maps to be available in
the next 10 to 20 years, said that without legislation prohibiting
discrimination, people might be afraid to avail themselves of these
advances in health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``These maps will save lives and make our lives healthier and
better, but most people aren't going to risk their jobs and
insurance for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Venter, whose company is expected this month to report that it
has completed a draft of the human genetic code, said the issue of
confidentiality would be key to the future of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the assurance that this knowledge will not be used
against people, a field that will revolutionize medicine could slow
to crawl,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, comprises the genetic material
passed on from generation to generation that forms the building
blocks of nearly every living creature.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists estimate that every human has at least 100,000 genes,
each a vital bit of information that can explain everything from
which diseases each person may be at risk of developing, such as
cancer or Alzheimer's disease, to height or hair and eye color.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration earlier this year banned federal
agencies from using genetic testing to deny jobs or promotions to
their workers. In addition, the House and Senate are considering
legislation that would provide some protection against genetic
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., chairman of the Joint Economic
Committee, said during the hearing that he anticipates
congressional passage of genetic discrimination legislation this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe that biotechnology will be to the 21st
century what computers were to the second half of the 20th century,
and we need to ensure America is at the forefront of this
revolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once more is understood about genes, the hope is to use that
information to improve treatments or find cures for diseases. The
data also could be used to create individual genetic passports,
with information on potential diseases and how to prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   But Venter emphasized that humans should not forget that DNA is
not responsible for everything that happens in life _ the
environment and lifestyle matter. For example, smoking and obesity
can make people more susceptible to heart disease and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every disease has a hereditary component, but it
varies, and environment plays a role,'' Venter said, adding that
everyone has genetic flaws.
</P>
<P>
   So far 39 states prohibit, at least in part, discrimination in
health insurance based on genetic tests; 15 have some ban on
discrimination in employment. But many of the laws have loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   However, many employers continue to seek genetic information
about their workers. A 1999 survey by the American Management
Association, a New York City-based business association, found that
30 percent of large and midsize companies obtain such information
on employees. Seven percent use it in hiring and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
