<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KOONS-PUPPY-NYT &LR;      06-07 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOONS-PUPPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW DOG IN TOWN,   STEEL AND SPROUTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Spain, Australia, Italy)   By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it comes to public sculpture, Jeff Koons' giant
topiary-esque ``Puppy'' is a rarity, a guaranteed crowd-pleaser
with serious art credentials. A 1992 work, it has been seen in
Germany, Spain and Australia and is now stationed in front of 30
Rockefeller Center until Sept. 5. Irresistibly cute, 43 feet high
and quilted with flowers, it occupies the spot traditionally
reserved for New York's most famous Christmas tree and easily holds
down this patch of unusually fetishized turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puppy'' is identifiably a West Highland terrier sitting
attentively on its haunches. When you walk around this canine, you
almost expect to see a tail twitching quietly in anticipation of a
reward or the next command.
</P>
<P>
   Structurally speaking, ``Puppy'' is a hollow stainless-steel
sculpture covered with foam into which thousands of annuals have
been stuck, roots and all (marigolds, begonias and lobelias among
them). A little door near the tail and an interior ladder
facilitate watering. As the summer passes the work will become more
lush, and the plant life, guided by the sculpture's surface, will
look shaggier and shaggier, in a calico (noncat) sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   It seems safe to say that monumentality has never looked so
endearing or tender. The scale and simplicity of the form fend off
sentimentality, even as the zillions of flowers humanize the
towering scale. As soon as the scaffolding came down on Monday
afternoon, tourists started gathering on the eastern edge of the
skating rink (currently an open-air restaurant), cameras in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The dog plus flowers plus bigness is a particularly innocent,
joyful example of the transformation of familiar objects for which
Koons is best known. His strategy has a long history; it descends
from the Duchamp ready-made by way of Jasper Johns and Claes
Oldenburg, whose painted flags and giant vinyl hamburgers were in
essence remade ready-mades. Partly as a result of Koons' influence,
this strategy has been embraced by myriad artists since the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Koons' best remade ready-mades make the conversion to art
especially accessible by mating almost ubiquitous objects with
resonant materials. His goal doesn't seem to be to simply ``make it
new,'' in the words of Ezra Pound, but to make it new, beautiful
and oddly pure.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning he simply enhanced actual objects, emerging in
the early 1980s with a series tellingly titled ``The New'' that
consisted of shiny new vacuum cleaners placed in immaculate,
lighted vitrines, as if they were sacred relics.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has veered between innocence and jadedness. His
basketballs floating in fish aquariums took the notion of newness
to almost womblike extremes. Other works seemed deliberately
ironic, as when he translated objects of leisure into expensive
materials that also rendered them useless. In this vein he has cast
a Baccarat decanter in stainless steel and a diving lung and rubber
dinghy in bronze. Somewhere in between, he also used cast stainless
steel to breathe new life into both a kitschy bust of Louis XIV and
a dime-store inflatable bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Koons' goals have always been his own and have repeatedly
reflected a strong interest in communicating with a mass audience.
Thus he has made larger-than-life porcelain sculptures of Michael
Jackson with his pet monkey, and a polychrome wood piece, also
quite large, based on a postcard of a London bobby commiserating
with a bear.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 he seemed to feel that this communication required total
revelation, and innocence and jadedness met head-on. He exhibited
big high-gloss photo-based paintings of him having carefully staged
sex with his wife, the Italian porn star Ciccolina (they're now
divorced), in idealized settings. These images were widely
denounced at the time and probably helped ignite the current wave
of art-about-sex and personal revelation, but they possessed a
weird pre-Raphaelite pristineness.
</P>
<P>
   Even this series, titled ``Made in Heaven,'' included objects
that communicated a simpler, more obvious kind of love: floral
arrangements, a pair of putti and even a poodle, made (like the
bobby and bear) in polychrome carved wood by skilled craftsmen in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   These works in particular were part of a line that leads
directly to the puppy, which Koons has said he considers a
``spiritual work'' because it is intended to ``communicate
happiness,'' pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   It does. Koons, not known for his modesty, also once wrote,
``I've made what the Beatles would have made if they had made
sculpture.'' The Rockefeller Center ``Puppy'' gives this statement
the fullest credence it may ever have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JIM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-07 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JIM THE BOY': WISING UP, THOUGH HE AIN'T NO BIGGER THAN A POOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Accurate as it would be to call Tony Earley's first novel a
radiant, knowing, pitch-perfect parable of childhood, it seems
wrong to say things that would make his characters blush. Earley's
book is set during the Depression in the modest, folksy North
Carolina town of Aliceville, where ``Shoot!'' and ``Daggummit'' and
``You knothead'' are the cuss words in common parlance and a
ghostly story still resonates about the little girl for whom the
place was named. In this simple setting, which Earley renders with
a wonderful blend of nostalgia and sophistication, the verities
discovered by 10-year-old Jim have a way of seeming particularly
eternal.
</P>
<P>
   The expert and irony-free minimalism of ``Jim the Boy'' gives it
the plain, wholehearted sound of a book for young readers. But the
forthright and sweetly humorous way in which Jim's story unfolds is
anything but naive. This book's rural characters seem as carefully
chosen as figures in a Greek myth, like the widowed mother who
sounds as if she stepped out of a folk song (``Mama was tall and
pale and handsome; her neck was long and white'') to watch over her
son. The other deities in Jim's universe are the three uncles who
during the course of this quick and unexpectedly elegant fable
teach Jim everything he needs to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all know who I am,'' Jim insists on the morning of his 10th
birthday when Uncles Al, Coran and Zeno teasingly pretend not to
recognize him. ``Can't say that we do,'' Uncle Coran remarks, in a
book that, while not without seriousness, seldom sounds any less
good-natured than that.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the twins Al and Coran and their older brother
(``His age was considerable, up in the 40s somewhere,'' Jim thinks
about Zeno), mean to surprise Jim with a baseball glove and bat,
which they present with the characteristically wry understatement
that serves as local color.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never seen them before,'' says Uncle Coran, when the glove and
Louisville slugger turn up in the middle of the dining room table.
``What are they?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim's Mama urges the uncles to quit kidding. (``Oh, stop it.
Sometimes I could just strangle y'all.'')
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it is Zeno, the book's foremost source of wisdom,
who ends the birthday celebration on a suitably sweeping note. ``He
ain't no bigger than a poot,'' says Zeno, ``but I guess we'll keep
him.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't take many poots to tip a book this slender into the
realm of sugary down-home charm. But Earley, whose first book was a
collection of short stories, retains the economy and purposefulness
that that form demands, as he leads Jim through a series of
exploratory ventures beyond the loving shelter of his Aliceville
home. The book's landscape and cast of characters are so
selectively delineated that each of these forays has the mythic
quality of a major undertaking, even on the journey about which
``Uncle Al would say only that they were going to see a man about a
dog.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the trip on which Jim visits a town big enough to have a
courthouse, a place that affords a tempting sight. (``Jim could no
longer imagine sitting inside a soda shop than in the house of a
king, and did not ask Uncle Al to stop.''). It's the time he first
sets foot in another state. (``South Carolina,'' said Uncle Al.
``Not much to it, huh?'') And provides Jim with his first
experience of the Atlantic Ocean, where he steps into the water
(``A fish no bigger than a thought swam by his feet'') and tries to
imagine where else that water has been. The beauty of ``Jim the
Boy'' lies in its graceful way of describing a boy who is in every
way thus poised on the verge of discovery, thrilled and fearful to
find new wisdom flooding into his familiar world.
</P>
<P>
   The course of the book leads Jim to make peace with thoughts of
his father, who fell dead in a cotton field the week before Jim was
born. It leads him to understand his mother's loneliness,
especially when a genial traveling feed salesman named Whitey
Whiteside begins to court her. (Wondering about Whitey's presence
around his mother made other questions begin ``pulling into his
head like trains into a station.'')
</P>
<P>
   It brings Jim into friendly rivalry with a schoolmate named Penn
who fights with him about baseball and makes him see the contrast
between Penn's life on a nearby mountain and Jim's life in town. It
seems no coincidence that Penn's mother, glimpsed briefly at home,
is in a sky-blue dress and a white apron, as if this symbolic
setting were indeed part of the clouds. The whole book has the
sharp, clean, inviting hyperreality of a detail like that.
</P>
<P>
   The most daunting figure in Jim's world is the grandfather who
will have nothing to do with him and who can also be found
somewhere up the mountain. While it's true that Jim comes to know
about pride, competition, racial tension and disabling illness
during the course of the story, nothing looms larger for him than
the terrifying specter of that mean old man. It is some measure of
Earley's storytelling mettle that he uses Jim's grandfather to
generate the book's closing epiphany without remotely reaching for
the literary equivalent of a big grandfatherly hug.
</P>
<P>
   The novel's matter-of-fact-looking cover illustration ably
conveys the meaning of this last episode. Yet this picture, like
the story itself, has the stealth aspect of something intended for
young readers in an innocent, less cynical time. In fact, ``Jim the
Boy'' is anything but quaint. Earley may not have invented the
coming-of-age novel, but he streamlines and reawakens the genre
with this swift, lovely book.  &QL; 
PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL; 
`JIM THE BOY'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Tony Earley
</P>
<P>
   227 pages. Little, Brown. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
