<HEADER>
A7332 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP08-COX     06-07 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keep cool while making gooey treat
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dianna Thompson of Flowery Branch asked for Nine-Minute Fudge
made in the microwave. Mary Bishop sent this one by e-mail, along
with a note saying it is one of her family's favorites. It makes 3
pounds of fudge, but it's easy to halve the recipe. Just use half
the ingredients and cook for a shorter time.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great way to make candy in the summer, without heating up
the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Nine-Minute Microwave Fudge
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 pounds, 25 1 1/2-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 6 1/2 to 9 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: at least 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   2 (16-ounce) packages
</P>
<P>
   confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) butter or
</P>
<P>
   margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chopped nuts, divided (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   In large bowl, mix sugar and cocoa. Add, but do not stir, milk,
butter and 1 cup nuts (if using).
</P>
<P>
   Microwave 6 1/2 to 9 minutes, or until butter is melted. Add
remaining nuts (if using) and vanilla; stir until smooth. Spread
into well-greased 8-by-8-inch baking dish; chill until firm. Cut
into squares to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Note: For 1 1/2 pounds, follow same procedure using half the
amount of each ingredient. Microwave 3 to 4 1/2 minutes. Pour into
greased loaf pan.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: For Rocky Road Fudge, use coarsely chopped nuts and
stir in 1 cup miniature marshmallows with the vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without nuts or marshmallows): 223 calories, 1 gram
protein, 8 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 33), 39 grams
carbohydrates, 1 milligram cholesterol, 104 milligrams sodium, 1
gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   Carole C. asks by e-mail for pumpkin bread made with plain
yogurt and black walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember as a child in the '70s a fabulously, intense
chocolate dessert called Mississippi Mud Cake,'' writes Carole
Liebman of Marietta, Ga. ``It was almost the height of a thin
brownie and had thick, chocolate, fudgy icing drenched over it. It
was quite messy and incredible tasting. I have never forgotten it
or had anything quite as good. Can you help?''
</P>
<P>
   Contacting this column
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests to be published in this column should be
sent to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Fax:
404-526-5509. Include a daytime phone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
