<HEADER>
A7338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CHILD-INJURIES08-COX     06-07 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-INJURIES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report lauds safety laws protecting kids
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Community educational efforts to keep children safe from
accidental injuries aren't working well enough, and up to 37
children die each day as a result, according to a report being
released today.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by the California-based David and Lucile Packard
Foundation, concludes that laws mandating child-safety efforts _
including everything from seat belt use to swimming-pool fences _
make a greater difference in saving lives than educational
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, a nonprofit organization, examined unintentional
injuries, the major cause of death in childhood in the United
States. Each year, more than 13,000 children and teens die as a
result of car and bike crashes, fires, drownings and other
accidents; for each child that dies, the foundation said, 223
others are treated in emergency departments and released, and 18
are hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, a wide array of local and voluntary programs are
aimed at reducing risks to children, from car-seat giveaways to
driver's education to reminders to replace smoke-alarm batteries.
The foundation's 188-page study, prepared with the help of the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, doesn't call those
programs a waste of time or money, but concludes they are not as
effective as regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly, it is really laws and regulations that do more
to reduce deaths and injuries than teaching parents about safety or
giving away safety devices,'' said Lisa Deal, editor of the
foundation's journal, ``The Future of Children,'' which published
the report. ``Parents have so much to worry about. It is in many
ways up to policy-makers to take the lead in making kids safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Community efforts, such as encouraging pediatricians to discuss
safety with parents or giving away bike helmets to kids, do make
some difference, the foundation found. But the changes don't last:
According to the study, the more time that passes after a child
receives a bicycle helmet in a giveaway, the less likely it is that
kids will wear the helmets or parents will insist on their use.
</P>
<P>
   The report calls for laws that would mandate the use of some
safety strategies, such as car and booster seats at appropriate
ages, smoke alarms that run on a house's electrical supply rather
than batteries, and graduated ages for drivers' licenses. (Some of
those measures already exist in Georgia: For instance, the state
requires children younger than 3 years old to use car safety seats,
though it does not mandate booster seats for older children, as CDC
recommends.)
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of opposition to laws that restrict personal choice in
favor of public health, such as mandatory motorcycle helmets, the
foundation recommends studying potential legislation to be sure
benefits outweigh costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this would not be controversial,'' Deal said. ``We
feel like children don't have a voice in public debate, so it is up
to society to look at what is best for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
