<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-AWARDS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MTV serves Oscar with extra toppings
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight's ``MTV Movie Awards,'' taped Saturday at cavernous Sony
Pictures Studios in Los Angeles, is all about quantity.
</P>
<P>
   Like, how many different outfits host Sarah Jessica Parker can
stuff herself into? (We lost count at 14, including one bath
towel.) And, if you got a dollar for every ``Matrix'' mention,
clip, joke and Keanu Reeves sighting, it might top the budgets for
``The Matrix 2'' and ``3.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour show has two Greens _ Seth and Tom, the latter
making way too much ``Uma-Oprah'' commotion with his date, a coffee
machine. And three decidedly different musical performances _ the
shirtless D'Angelo singing ``Devil's Pie,'' the ubiquitous 'N Sync
gyrating to ``It's Gonna Be Me'' and hard-core Metallica putting in
one more soundtrack plug for ``Mission: Impossible 2'' by pounding
out ``I Disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this isn't the staid, wake-us-when-it's-over Oscars.
Old Hollywood thought it got down when it nominated ``Blame
Canada'' from the ``South Park'' movie for best song. Wrong cut,
clueless ones. MTV's ``Movie Awards'' is here not only to set the
record straight, but to relish that other ``South Park'' tune _
``Uncle $!&AMP;.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Collins, who won an Oscar for his ``Tarzan'' song, is
nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Who is here represents most every recent movie the
deep-pocketed, megaplex-going youth of America love. Like Freddie
Prinze Jr. (``She's All That''), Rebecca Romijn-Stamos (``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me''), Aaliyah (``Romeo Must Die'') and
Ryan Phillippe and Sarah Michelle Gellar (``Cruel Intentions'').
</P>
<P>
   A few hep cats are let in the door _ Samuel L. Jackson, of
course (appropriately sporting a white cap emblazoned with
``Shaft'' in capital letters), George Clooney (here to plug ``The
Perfect Storm'' with Mark Wahlberg; Parker squeezes both of their
butts), Mel Gibson (``The Patriot'' star in a neatly pressed tux;
what was he thinking?) and ``Star Wars'' uberlord George Lucas
(thoroughly stuffed in an ill-fitting suit and sporting silver hair
so highly coiffed they could have tossed a toga on him and he'd be
the perfect Roman senator to tout ``Gladiator'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies are just so swell,'' Parker enthuses in outfit No. 1, a
see-through black whiff more negligee than dress. She then sings as
clips behind her show vomiting, beheadings and general mayhem from
films like ``Sleepy Hollow'' and ``Fight Club.''
</P>
<P>
   The winners are already known, but winning at this show isn't
nearly as important as being seen or sputtering a joke as tasteless
as anything in ``American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   In pre-show taped skits, there's a humorous convergence of ``The
Matrix,'' with Parker's HBO comedy ``Sex and the City'' and a
witty-but-overlong ``Being Tom Cruise'' spoof with Tom Crooze (Ben
Stiller). The ``South Park'' kids take on ``Gladiator.'' Just guess
what happens to Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   Halle Berry bares her midriff and exposes her thong. Denise
Richards sports blow-out hair. Adam Sandler wears a yellow DCShoeCo
shirt and shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's dressed young, ``MTV's Movie Awards'' sometimes
feels just a little, well, old.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a summer 2000 event touting ``The Matrix,'' ``Austin
Powers,'' ``The Blair Witch Project,'' ``Fight Club,'' ``Big
Daddy,'' ``The Sixth Sense,'' ``Being John Malkovich.''
</P>
<P>
   All great films, but don't you feel like you saw them ages ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``MTV Movie Awards''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more on the awards:
www.mtv.com/sendme.tin?page &QC; /mtv/tubescan/ma2000
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
