<HEADER>
A7340 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE08-COX     06-07 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Marylin Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a friend who has the use of only one hand and arm. I'm
looking for a source for kitchen gadgets and other items to make
her life easier. I'm particularly looking for a fork that has a
knife as one edge. Can you help me find a source for such items?
</P>
<P>
   _ Beverly Cohen, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another question: I am a paraplegic who is new to Atlanta.
Do you know of a store or Web site that specializes in clothes and
items for disabled persons?
</P>
<P>
   _ Pete Gray, Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We have several suggestions on saving you time and energy.
One handy book, ``The Best 25 Catalog Resources for Making Life
Easier,'' by Shelley Peterman Schwarz ($8.95 plus shipping) tells
you who might benefit from the products being offered (people with
mobility problems, people with hearing problems, etc.). She lists
the catalogs _ and some of their key products _ with phone numbers
and Web sites. To order, write: Shelley Peterman Schwarz, 9042
Aspen Grove Lane, Madison, WI 53717-2700.
</P>
<P>
   (608-824-0402).
</P>
<P>
   One of the catalogs in Schwarz's book, Easy Street Co., offers a
three-in-one stainless steel utensil from Duro-Med Industries. It
can be used as a spoon, fork and knife and is designed for those
with limited strength and hand control. The utensil is $7.50 plus
$4.50 shipping. Order: 1-800-959-3279.
</P>
<P>
   A handy Web site for clothing and accessories is
www.kansas.net/(tilde)cbaslock/clothint.html. It includes 65
manufacturers, phones numbers and/or Web addresses. Items, for men,
women and children, are designed especially for disabled
individuals and wheelchair users.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For several years, I've used Eliminate Shower, Tub and Tile
Cleaner that I bought at Home Depot. But they no longer carry the
product. Any help you can give in locating it will be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   _ James N. Parkman, Cumming, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We looked around a bit and found Eliminate at Home Depot,
2450 Cumberland Parkway (770-432-9930). A 32-ounce bottle is $4.87.
A spokesman said Eliminate should be at most Home Depot stores. The
manufacturer, Unelko Corporation, says its cherry-scented,
biodegradable product ``removes calcium, hard water spots, soap
scum and body oils without offensive odors or the need for
aggressive scrubbing.'' Use it on glass, porcelain, ceramics,
chrome, stainless steel, marble and brass.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Don Imus, the morning talk show host on Sports-talk 790/the
Zone, has a business with his brother Fred. One of the items they
sell is a Southwestern salsa available in grocery stores in New
York and Florida. Is it sold anywhere in the Atlanta area? Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   _ Todd Zinke, Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Bring on the chips. We found Fred Imus Southwest Salsa,
medium or hot, at Kroger, 910 Athens Highway, Loganville
(770-554-1100). A 16-oz. jar is $1.67. Most Krogers are just now
getting in a supply. You can also order it at
www.autobodyexpress.com. Then click on gift accessories. This thick
and chunky salsa is from all natural ingredients, including
tomatoes, onions, green chilies, red jalapeno peppers, red and
green bell peppers and various spices. Good news: No sugar,
additives or preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago during a choir tour to Germany, I was
introduced to Grether's Pastilles, a very comforting throat
lozenge. These little glycerin drops are small miracles for a sore
throat. I find it in drug stores in Germany and Switzerland, but
have been unsuccessful in Atlanta. My throat needs a miracle. Can
you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ron Cook, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Soon you will be in fine singing voice. We tracked down
Grether's Pastilles, which are made in Switzerland, at
Caswell-Massey in Phipps Plaza (404-261-9415) where a tin is $6 and
at Wender &AMP; Roberts Drugs, 1262 W. Paces Ferry Road NW
(404-237-7551), where a tin is $6.95. Both stores stock black
currant and red currant flavors. The slogan on the tin reads: ``For
a soothing, deliciously different experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find a hand-cranked ice cream maker for my
Momma, one like we used to have in the country. I can find the
electric ones, but they don't work as well. The ice cream isn't as
firm as with a hand-cranked freezer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pierson Burke, Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We can just taste that yummy ice cream and you will be able
to enjoy it for a July Fourth celebration. Here's the scoop: We
found White Mountain's Hand-cranked Ice Cream Freezer at Handy Ace
Hardware, 4351 Hugh Howell Road, Tucker (770-939-6842). A 4-quart
freezer (shown) is $169.99. Other sizes include an 8-quarter
freezer ($249.99) and a 2-quart size ($98.99). The stainless steel
cream can is surrounded by a natural wood finished tub. And the
cast-iron dasher won't give out as the cream hardens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
