r e BC-VIDEO-GIRL08-COX     06-07 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GIRL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Girl, Interrupted' offers fine performances
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two fine actresses, two fine performances. Based on Susanna
Kaysen's memoir about the two years she spent at an upscale mental
hospital in the late 1960s, this movie, eschewing the potential
touchy-feely pitfalls of the material, goes for a rip-roaring tone
reminiscent of ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   As Susanna, Winona Ryder steadies the film and gives it its
emotional center, but Oscar winner Angelina Jolie provides the
fireworks in a fiercely showy turn as a charismatic sociopath.
</P>
<P>
   `Girl, Interrupted'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For an Angelina Jolie fan site:
www.geocities.com/Wellesley/Garden/1284
</P>
<P>
   /angelina.html
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mr. Death: The Rise and Fall of Fred A. Leuchtre, Jr.''
(PG-13) _ This documentary from Errol Morris (``The Thin Blue
Line'') follows the fascinating, peculiar career of Leuchtre, an
engineer who gained fame finessing the mechanisms of execution
(gas, electric chair, gallows) in order to keep a death sentence
from being ``capital torture.'' Then, in the 1980s, he agreed to
investigate the grounds of Auschwitz-Birkenau to support the claims
of a revisionist historian, on trial in Canada for claiming that
the Holocaust never happened. His dubiously achieved results
pitched Leuchtre into an ethical and media firestorm that brought
him unexpected infamy. Though Morris' arty touches (close-ups and
slo-mo) can be distracting, his film presents a fascinating
portrait of an elusive man who seems to be many things at once: an
earnest dweeb, a dupe, a publicity monger and a smiling
anti-Semite. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Next Friday'' (R) _ It's back to business as usual at the
movies, with the return of this typical dumb comedy starring Ice
Cube and former Atlantan Mike Epps. The best that can be said for
this sequel to the 1995 comedy ``Friday'' is that, unlike in the
first flick, the characters don't spend most of the movie sitting
on the front steps and yakking while they get stoned. No, they go
elsewhere to get stoned. Lamely written, it's a reminder that,
while more complex, mature but still funny African-American
comedies are getting made (``The Wood,'' say, or ``The Best Man''),
there's always a market for flatulence and dog poop jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Eel'' (unrated) _ This Cannes Film Festival award winner
tells the story of a prison parolee (Koji Yakusho) trying to
rebuild his life after a bloody crime. It's an engaging but uneven
mixture of comedy and melodrama. In Japanese with subtitles. Grade:
B-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
