A7342 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL08-COX     06-07 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A quick ride through the best of cars on film
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The automobile industry and the movie industry grew up together.
No wonder they work so smoothly together on film, whether it's a
cute little Love Bug named Herbie or a glamorous Thunderbird
convertible carrying Thelma and Louise to their destiny. ``American
Graffiti's'' cars are as much the stars of the picture as the kids
who drive them. And in ``Le Mans,'' the cars probably had more
screen time than the stars inside them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' which opens Friday, looks at the largest
carjacking ever. We'll look at a few less larcenous examples of
auto-mania at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Christine'' (1983): From the pen of Stephen King comes this
1958 Plymouth Fury with a murderous mind of her own and a radio
that only plays '50s rock 'n' roll. Keith Gordon (later to direct
such distinguished films as ``A Midnight Clear'') is the nerdy high
schooler who finds himself becoming possessed by his own jealous
vehicle. The moral? Woman hath no hell like a Plymouth Fury
scorned. Chop shop note: Seventeen identical Christines were used
in the picture; only two survived in mint condition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' (1988): This could just as
easily be called ``Coppola: The Man and His Dream.'' Out of the
true story of Preston Tucker, a 1940s visionary whose dream of a
better, safer and cheaper car suffered a head-on collision with
Detroit, Francis Ford Coppola has fashioned a fable of American
can-do-ism. Jeff Bridges is brashly charming as the
huckster-inventor who wanted to do things his way, not the company
way (read, Francis vs. the Hollywood studios). This project had
obsessed the director for years. At one point he asked Frank Capra
to produce, but the elder statesman of cinematic optimism turned
him down after reading the script. ``I don't think we can make
this,'' Capra said. ``Because, in the end, Tucker didn't get his
dream. Are you saying in America you can't make your dream come
true?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ronin'' (1998): The title _ something to do with
dispossessed samurai _ makes about as much sense as the plot, which
has something to do with modern ronin (Cold Warriors without a war)
hired to snatch a mysterious suitcase. The gang includes Robert De
Niro and Jean Reno, which right away suggests something out of the
ordinary. Bt the film's true stars are a pair of high-speed car
chases _ one through the narrow, twisting roads in and around Nice,
France, the other through the heart of Paris. Longtime director
John Frankenheimer knows a great ride is a great ride. And that's
what he delivers. Twice. The script, written by David Mamet under a
pseudonym, is a canny match for Frankenheimer's bold, self-assured
style. You're probably thinking, What about the car chases in
``Bullitt'' and ``The French Connection''? Yeah, I know. Check out
``Ronin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Great Race'' (1965): This period slapstick farce was, at
the time, the most expensive comedy ever produced (it cost $12
million). Built around a transcontinental car race at the turn of
the century, the movie is director Blake Edwards' tribute to silent
comedies (sometimes, I must say, an overblown tribute, including
the largest pie fight ever staged). The vintage cars are exquisite
to look at, as are stars Tony Curtis and Natalie Wood. He's the
hero in white competing with a comically villainous Jack Lemmon
(who even has a mustache to twirl); she's an intrepid, Nellie
Blye-ish reporter. Unfortunately, the stars didn't get along so
hansdomely off-screen. Reportedly, when asked whether there would
be a wrap party, Edwards said: ``Natalie and Tony are going to set
each other on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For a lineup of car-racing movies:
www.sandlotshrink.com/movieauto.htm
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
