<SLUG> BC-TV-MTV-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV MOVIE AWARDS: AND THE WINNER FOR SHORTEST AWARDS SHOW IS ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If nothing else, the ``MTV Movie Awards'' proves to be terrific
public relations for Tom Cruise (as if he needs any). Playing
himself, in a sly spoof of ``behind the scenes'' documentaries, he
is the foil for Tom Crooze, his overeager stunt double, whom Ben
Stiller portrays astutely, with grasping self-importance.
</P>
<P>
   Crooze is a familiar Hollywood type: the underling who mistakes
his association with stars for actual stardom. Dressed in classic
Cruise-wear (black T-shirt, black jeans, black sunglasses), the
Stiller character says haughtily to the fight director for
``M:I-2'': ``I've done 14 films with Tom. I have a pretty good idea
of what Tom wants.'' Of course, what Tom wants _ and gets _ is for
Crooze to step in when it's time for a fist to make contact with
Cruise's face. But he's also sympathetic to his double's plight.
Flashing his best movie star smile, Cruise says of Crooze, ``He's
harmless.'' The spoof works so well that Cruise's magnanimity feels
authentic, not scripted.
</P>
<P>
   The awards show also offers an amusing animated satire. As
punishment for misbehaving at school, the characters from ``South
Park'' face Maximus, the hero of the hit ``Gladiator.'' Just as
Maximus prepares to impale them on his sword, John Travolta drops
in from outer space with a crew of Scientologists, a nod to
``Battlefield Earth,'' the new Travolta movie based on the L. Ron
Hubbard novel.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest, at least it's brief _ 90 minutes, compared with
the numbing four-hour Oscar presentation _ which is the advantage
of a taped, edited program versus live television. In that vein,
give the best presenter award to Nicolas Cage for admirable
succinctness. Striding briskly onstage and apologizing for the
laryngitis that attractively thickens his voice, Cage yells out his
line: ``They've all been kissed, chased, stalked and
double-crossed, and for their hard work they've all been nominated
for best female performance!'' Cut to the clips.
</P>
<P>
   The show began eight years ago as a frisky alternative to the
Oscars, with awards categories like best kiss and best fight. The
prize remains a bucket of gilded popcorn, reflecting the populist
leanings of the awards. Nominees are distinctly not high-minded.
``American Beauty,'' which swept the Oscars, is a blip at the MTV
proceedings, a failed contender for best movie, nothing more.
Perhaps honoring the show's desire to be unconventional, MTV
viewers _ who decide the winners _ give the best kiss award to two
women, Sarah Michelle Gellar and Selma Blair, for their vigorous
bussing in ``Cruel Intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   But except for a more casual, sometimes ostentatiously sloppy
dress code, the MTV awards conform to many Hollywood standards.
Lists are pulled from pockets so the appropriate parties can be
thanked, including agents, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wahlberg offers the only political note. Presenting the
best villain award with George Clooney, he says, ``Let's give it to
Charlton Heston for being the head of the NRA.'' Instead, the prize
goes to Mike Myers for ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Sarah Jessica Parker seems rightfully uncomfortable with
her role as spokesmodel. Mocking the Oscar obsession with dresses,
she changes outfits 12 times, appearing onstage in a bizarre
collection of revealing concoctions. But they aren't as silly as
the most outrageous Oscar get-ups, so the joke fizzles.
</P>
<P>
   Though many of these costumes are extremely revealing, none are
as embarrassing as the decision to have Parker flirt awkwardly with
Clooney, rocking back and forth in one of her many gowns like a
giggling teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   She is far more at ease playing a more familiar role, in an
opening sequence that manages to combine ``Sex and the City'' with
``The Matrix.'' While no Billy Crystal, she also is charming as she
performs a singing homage to last year's films. ``They filled us
with joy and laughter and hope for a better tomorrow,'' she says
with mock sincerity, before singing the wistful ``Imagination''
from ``Willy Wonka and the Chocolate Factory'' to a backdrop of
gory and grotesque film clips.
</P>
<P>
   More frequently, however, vulgarity is substituted for
irreverence and foul language mistaken for wit. If a smart joke
replaced every obscenity, the show would be hilarious. Instead, it
is often merely crude.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `2000 MTV MOVIE AWARDS'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Thursday on MTV
</P>
<P>
   Joel Gallen of Tenth Planet Productions, producer; Salli
Frattini, executive producer; Bruce Gowers, director; Sarah Jessica
Parker, host.
</P>
</TEXT>
