<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-L.A.-SCHOOLS-ROMER-(T     06-07 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-SCHOOLS-ROMER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW L.A. SCHOOLS CHIEF: AN UNLIKELY CHOICE FOR AN INTIMIDATING
JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES &UR;  &LR; _ Roy Romer is no stranger to politics. As governor
of Colorado for 12 years, and then general chairman of the
Democratic National Committee for two years, he has seen his share
of infighting, bureaucracy and blood feuds.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps nothing could prepare Romer, 71, for his latest
assignment, as superintendent of the sprawling Los Angeles Unified
School District, the nation's second largest, with 711,000
students, a budget nearly two-thirds the size of Colorado's, and a
list of problems that would stretch from here to Denver: lagging
test scores, severe overcrowding, dilapidated buildings and a
burgeoning population of new immigrant children who speak every
language but English.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the toughest jobs a guy could find,'' said
Romer, virtually the only candidate to seek a job that few wanted,
after his appointment was hastily announced on Tuesday. Though his
appointment was unanimous, at least two of the seven members of the
school board said they had voted for him with some reluctance,
after a search conducted largely in private, and after several
other candidates, including the school board's favorite, former
U.S. Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros, either turned down the job
or expressed little interest.
</P>
<P>
   Romer had the support of influential business leaders, including
Eli Broad, the billionaire executive and philanthropist, who
suggested he apply. He has a longstanding interest in education
policy and was active in national efforts to improve public
education by imposing rigorous standards and goals.
</P>
<P>
   But he has never lived in Los Angeles or run a school system,
and is little known among the city's diverse communities, including
Hispanics, who make up 70 percent of the district's student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bad Fit for the LAUSD,'' is how The Los Angeles Times
greeted Romer's appointment in its lead editorial Wednesday
morning, saying it was ``like choosing a spouse based on which
suitor is most eager; it doesn't make the strongest basis for a
long-term relationship.'' The board was rushing to meet the
self-imposed July 1 deadline for the departure of its interim
superintendent, Ramon C. Cortines, who took on the job last fall
after the ouster of the former superintendent, Ruben Zacarias.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the tragedy is that he was deprived of any opportunity
through the selection process to learn more about Los Angeles and
for Los Angeles to learn more about him,'' Thomas A. Saenz,
regional counsel of the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Educational Fund, which has filed various lawsuits alleging
inadequacies in the California public schools, said of Romer.
``It's not his fault; it's something they've done to him, and we're
obviously hopeful that he will be a person who seeks to reach out
to the community and incorporate its ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a brief telephone interview Wednesday as he headed to
Sacramento to testify before the state Board of Education, Romer
insisted his first priority would be to introduce himself. He said
he had been looking for ways to start a national policy discussion
on education and decided there was no better approach than to
practice what he has been preaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, it was a crisis of conscience,'' he said. ``I
said, `Romer, do you want to start a think tank or do you want to
go on the street and walk your talk.' This is the last job I intend
to take, so I am very free. I don't have any agenda that I'm
working on. I can come into this job and really call it as I see
it. I recognize it's a tougher job than I had as governor, and will
take more time and energy, but I thought this was the most
important thing I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Romer's first tasks will be to help Cortines select
superintendents for 11 new semi-autonomous subdistricts, which the
board agreed to create in an effort to head off demands for
breaking up the district altogether. The reorganization is to take
effect on July 1, the same week Romer takes over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has worked with unions, he is very fluent in educational
issues,'' said Day Higuchi, president of the United Teachers of Los
Angeles union, which is in the midst of contract talks. ``I think
maybe the time is right to try going out of the box a little. L.A.
Unified has more students than the smallest 29 states put together.
So having a governorship may not be bad qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer, an intense, energetic man, was forced out of office as
Colorado's governor by term limits in 1998, and friends say he
seemed a bit bored being out of harness.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton named him to head the Democratic National
Committee in 1997, when the party organization was tangled in
fund-raising controversies from the 1996 campaign. In 1998, Romer
saw his reputation tarnished by his acknowledgment of a 16-year
``very affectionate relationship'' with a former female aide, and
he stepped down from the party chairmanship last year to
concentrate on planning its national convention in Los Angeles this
summer, which is how he first got interested in the schools job.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Romer led the development of early-childhood
education programs, created a centralized child-care referral
system and intervened to halt a teachers strike in Denver in 1991.
In the early 1990s, he was co-chairman of the National Council on
Educational Standards and Testing, an advisory group that
recommended national curriculum standards.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Caprice Young, one of the school board members, ``the
real challenge and the real test is whether he can take us from
policy through implementation, and that is not easy in a school
district the size and complexity of L.A.Unified.'' She added, `I
think on balance, the board believes that he can get there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cisneros, who is now president of Univision, the
Spanish-language television network, turned down the
superintendent's job for family reasons, but urged Romer to pursue
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredibly diverse school district and city, and
requires a great deal of understanding of the different roles that
parents play in different cultures and about how education works,''
Cisneros said. ``Governor Romer has some experience in Colorado but
generally that's a much more homogenous state. It is a challenge
which he is up to, he's a wonderfully wise man. But I think
there'll have to be some real tilt toward understanding on those
issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
