A7363 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PIANO-COST-TEX     06-07 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANO-COST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT CHEAP, BUT IT PAYS OFF
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: ONE of two sidebars with PIANO-LESSONS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE PIANO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expect to spend $3,000 for a decent, new acoustic spinet piano
that will take a young student through a decade of lessons; if
you're willing and able to spend more, a very good Steinway upright
is a reasonable choice (actually better than comparably priced baby
grands) at about $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to start on the cheap, a digital electronic
instrument, at about $1,000, will get a beginner through the first
year or two. Beyond that beginner period, the student will need an
acoustic instrument, however. It's a matter of paying more now or
paying more later.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a used piano is about like buying a used car. Unless you
really know what you're doing, it's a risk. If you think you have a
good deal going for a beautiful 1929 Steinway, find a piano
technician in the Yellow Pages and pay $50-$100 to have him or her
to look it over before you buy.
</P>
<P>
   Getting your acoustic piano tuned is no more optional than
changing the oil in your car. That means $50-$100 twice a year; get
a referral from the store where you buy the piano. Please, don't
expose your piano to direct sun or a cold north wall, or place it
in within 10 feet of a lighted fireplace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE LESSONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expect to spend $50-$100 a month for weekly half-hour lessons
for a beginner. In return, expect the teacher to be well-educated,
with a bachelor's degree in music or music education.
</P>
<P>
   Most teachers charge monthly. Don't expect a refund for days off
for the flu, baseball games or the reasonable vacation the teacher
takes at Christmas and the end of summer: The teacher still has to
make the mortgage payments, keep the air conditioner running and
eat.
</P>
<P>
   Again, don't stint. Pay extra for a teacher you trust who has a
good reputation, and don't complain about paying for music, or
festival and contest entry fees, which can run $10-$30 a month.
Having access to plenty of good printed music (the teacher will
either pick it up at the music store for you or let you know where
to buy it) is as necessary as having up-to-date textbooks in
school. And playing in festivals and contests is part of the
experience of connecting with the larger community of pianists.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, it's your job to provide time and kind, gentle
encouragement for daily _ that's right, daily _ practice at home.
Gimmicks and rewards don't work nearly as well as simply making the
piano part of the routine of home life. Taking lessons yourself, to
get a little extra benefit of your own out of the weekly trek to
the piano studio, is a superb example for your child.
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour a day of practice is ideal for the student of
average intelligence and ability at the early stages, although that
should expand at more advanced levels; fifteen minutes six days a
week beats two hours once a week anytime.
</P>
<P>
   To find a music teacher, start with recommendations from
professional musicians or friends who have a student in the family.
</P>
<P>
   Or call a professional association. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
