<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7364 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PIANO-LESSONS-TEX     06-07 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANO-LESSONS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Has two sidebars, PIANO-COST and PIANO-WHENTOSTART 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My editor summoned me into his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've noticed you leave the office early every Friday
afternoon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gulp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because you're taking your son to his piano lesson, I
understand,'' he continued. ``Would you write a column about why
you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Aaaah.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason _ a good one _ that I leave deadlines
dangling, phone calls unanswered and expense accounts unfiled every
Friday afternoon. It goes back to long before I was born, to rural
Oklahoma in the midst of the greatest economic disaster in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand Ol' Opry'' on the radio provided most of the music for
Depression-era folks who lived on the mostly rented dirt farms
north of Lindsay, Okla., where my mother grew up. That and a little
fiddling at square dances, a few hymns at church.
</P>
<P>
   But my grandfather, whose skills (after his third-grade
education) included raising crops and livestock, rolling cigarettes
while driving a pickup and talking bankers into loaning him money
to buy land, for some reason wanted his daughter _ my mother _ to
play the piano.
</P>
<P>
   About 1935, he bought a converted player piano from a movie
theater and moved it out to the farm. He drove my mother into town
for lessons some weeks. Other times, he talked the local
schoolmaster, who had a daughter the same age who also took
lessons, into driving the two girls into town together.
</P>
<P>
   Many years afterward _ and many mules, tractors, cattle, trucks
and acres later _ he happened to be within earshot of my mother as
she played the piano. He was overheard to say, ``Those piano
lessons were the best money we ever spent.''
</P>
<P>
   The legacy continued. My mother gave me my first piano lessons
on the same converted player piano. My playtime as a preschooler
was accompanied by waltzes of Chopin, sonatas of Scarlatti,
impromptus of Schubert.
</P>
<P>
   When I had my own son, I knew what to do. Although I never gave
him lessons myself, I drove him to his lessons whenever I could and
sat through festivals and contests. Along with his mother, I
indoctrinated him with the idea that being able to play the piano
is right up there with being able to read.
</P>
<P>
   It's an expense, but it's also an investment _ not necessarily
one that pays off in financial returns, but one that pays off in
human enrichment. A decent, budget-conscious instrument will cost
$3,000 to $10,000. That's about half the cost of a budget-sized
car, which will wear out in five years; a piano will last about 50
years, and will provide infinitely more pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   If you can play the piano, you can ``own'' a prelude of Chopin
or a sonata of Mozart. That, friends, is as good as owning a sketch
by Rembrandt or Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Commune with Bach or Beethoven or Joplin. Play a fugue of
Shostakovich, and understand, on a spiritual level, what it was to
live in Stalin's Russia _ and know, beyond doubt, that even in the
most degraded level of human existence, the intellect and the
spirit transcend.
</P>
<P>
   Play an intermezzo or waltz of Brahms, and understand that
passion and intellect can be organized and combined. Wake your
brain every morning with an interactive conversation with Haydn;
exercise your coordination, clean out your mind, keep your memory
working.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime near the end of the 21st century, when I am long gone
and my son is old, he will sit down at a piano and play a bit of
Debussy or Shostakovich or Bach.
</P>
<P>
   It was something my grandfather, who never knew my son, and who
never heard of Debussy or Shostakovich or Bach, wanted him to have.
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music for the Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
