Florida-based Jim Walter Homes and its financing arm, Mid-State
Homes, alleging that the companies violated Georgia law when they
tacked on attorneys fees to mortages that had gone into default.
There are two plaintiffs from Athens named in the suit and their
lawyers are trying to get a class action declaration from the
judge. Jim Walter's registered agent is in Cobb. The company builds
homes in 22 states. Lawyers for the plaintiffs say that the fees
were added to the principal and the plaintiffs were never told
about them. GA law requires the companies to tell people what they
are doing. Lawyers estimate that between 1,000 and 5,000 people in
Georgia could be affected. (Rodriguez, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-TRIAL _ ATLANTA _ The post-Super Bowl murder trial resumes
without NFL All-Pro linebacker Ray Lewis. The media attention has
waned, and the defense begins its cases. (Torpy/Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA _ The billionaire philanthropist Bill Gates is
mounting a major effort to combat the seemingly inexorable spread
of AIDS in Africa with the help and advice of one of the world's
foremost experts on public health _ longtime Atlanta resident Dr.
William Foege. So far, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation has
committed about $70 million to fight AIDS in Africa, but that is
just the beginning, Foege said in an interview this week. The
figure could grow even within the next few weeks, he said. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 31. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL _ JERUSALEM _ While negotiators try clear the way for a
peace summit, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's political opponents
Wednesday tied to take his
</P>
<P>
   Israeli government to the brink. Israel's parliament voted 61-48
for preliminary passage of a bill calling for new elections.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
