<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PEPPERS0608-COX     06-07 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPPERS0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Heat Goes On
 &HT;    By Diana Blowers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you have a vegetable garden, you probably have
peppers. If you don't have a vegetable garden, you may have peppers
tucked among the ornamental plants.
</P>
<P>
   Few vegetables, except tomatoes, can beat peppers in the garden
popularity contest. The bell pepper is a longstanding tradition,
but hot peppers are quickly gaining in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The bell pepper is often mistakenly referred to as a mango, but
a mango is an unrelated tropical fruit. Neither are sweet and hot
peppers related to the ground black pepper usually coupled with
salt.
</P>
<P>
   Often bell peppers are referred to as ``green peppers,'' but
they are only green because we pick them before they ripen. When
allowed to ripen, they turn red, orange, yellow, purple or even a
chocolate color, depending on the cultivar.
</P>
<P>
   A bell pepper takes two to three weeks to turn color after it
has reached its mature size. This delay often leads the impatient
gardener to pick peppers before they have a chance to change color,
Richard Funderburg, owner of Funderburg Greenhouses, said.
</P>
<P>
   A popular bell pepper this year is the `Blushing Beauty,' chosen
as a 2000 All-American Selection by the nonprofit All-American
Selections organization that for 67 years has tested and introduced
improved flowers and vegetables. `Blushing Beauty' begins with a
pale green or ivory color and then takes on a pastel pink blush
before turning a deep rosy red at maturity.
</P>
<P>
   All bell peppers have a similar taste, according to Dave Scott,
general manager of Knollwood Garden Center, but the different
colors add to their visual appeal in cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new hybrids, probably the most requested bell pepper
is still the `California Wonder.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an old-time pepper. It's open pollinated, not
hybridized, so it's not crossed with anything else,'' said
Funderburg, who raises a variety of heirloom plants. A newer
cultivar that is becoming quite popular is the `Lady Belle,' he
said, because it continues to produce during extreme heat, when
many peppers' blooms fall off.
</P>
<P>
   Hot peppers are becoming hot gardening items, Scott said.
Although they often come with hotness ratings, the heat in the
peppers will be affected by growing conditions and maturity.
</P>
<P>
   People often make the mistake of planting a very hot pepper next
to a mild, sweet pepper, Funderburg said, but because of
cross-pollination, the sweet pepper may ``become quite hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Chile peppers have been one of the biggest sellers in the past
three or four years, especially for use in salsa, Funderburg said,
pointing to `Anaheim' and `Garden Salsa' as two of the more
popular. Among the popular hot peppers are jalapeno, super cayenne,
super chile, and the habanero. One habanero, `Red Savina,' is
``probably one of the hottest peppers in the world,'' Funderburg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Peppers are sometimes selected not just for their hotness but
also for their beauty, said John Evers, owner of Evers' Country
Gardens in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some use them for decoration,'' he said. ``Like the Thai hot
pepper _ it's pretty. It's a little bitty pepper, but it is very
decorative.''
</P>
<P>
   Evers, a third-generation grower of peppers, has more than 20
varieties and marvels at how ``they just keep on getting better and
better,'' becoming not only more productive but also more disease
resistant.
</P>
<P>
   He has a couple of tips for gardeners:
</P>
<P>
   _ Peppers like hot days and warm nights. People who plant them
early, say in April, ``are pretty much wasting their time,'' Evers
said, because ``they really don't grow until it gets hot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I highly recommend a slow-release fertilizer, like Osmecote
. . .,'' he said. ``This stuff is so good that one application will
last the entire growing season.''
</P>
<P>
   TYPES OF PEPPERS
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Peppers:
</P>
<P>
   _ `Blushing Beauty': All-American Winner. Bell pepper, matures
to red.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Peppourri': Bell pepper that starts out with a bit of a
lavender color and matures to purple.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Gypsy': This tapered or wedge-shaped yellow pepper is one of
the earliest peppers to mature.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sweet banana: Long, yellow pepper that matures to red.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Parks Whopper': Very large bell pepper, good for stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   _ `California Wonder': An old standby bell pepper that turns red
at maturity.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Lady Belle': Continues to produce even in extreme heat. Turns
red at maturity.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Jingle Bells': One of the first to fruit, it is a compact
plant good for container gardening.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Bell Boy': A large bell pepper good for stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Peppers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Anaheim: Dagger-shaped fruit. Matures from green and mild to
red and hot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Poblano: Moderately hot, heart-shaped fruit, used widely in
Mexican cooking and called ancho when dried.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thai hot: Very small plants with small, cone-shaped green
fruit that matures to one of the hottest red peppers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jalapeno: Deep green fruit that matures to red. One of the
hottest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hungarian yellow wax: Yellow fruit that turns red at maturity.
Moderately hot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Habanero: One of the hottest. Turns from light green to
orange.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red chile: Green fruit matures to red. Very hot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Red cayenne: Yellow fruit turns flaming red at maturity. Very
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
