A7379 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-TERRORISM-B     06-07 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TERRORISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS AND COUNTERTERRORISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the bombings of the World Trade Center, the federal
building in Oklahoma City, the El Khobar dormitory of US soldiers
in Saudi Arabia, and, most recently, two US embassies in Africa,
there should be no doubt about America's need to have the best
possible strategies for identifying terrorists and preventing their
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued this week by the 10-member National Commission
on Terrorism recommends several policies. Some of them have
properly stirred debate, however, because they either impinge
unnecessarily on civil liberties or would institute ineffective
measures.
</P>
<P>
   The foreword to the report acknowledges a need to strike ``the
appropriate balance'' between effective counterterrorism policies
and America's ``democratic traditions.'' But the commission's call
for monitoring the courses of study of foreign students in this
country signifies not only a violation of America's democratic
traditions, but also a pointless surveillance of the wrong suspect
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign students here have had hardly any role in terrorist
attacks against Americans. Instead of trying to monitor every
visiting student who changes his or her major from history to
physics, the federal government should be making an honest effort
to determine the true identity of Ramzi Yousef, the mastermind of
the World Trade Center bombing who arrived in New York with one
Iraqi passport and left with someone else's Pakistani passport.
</P>
<P>
   If Yousef was working with Iraqi intelligence, then perhaps
counterterrorism policy should be weighted more toward prevention
of state-sponsored terrorism rather than the ``loose networks'' of
religious fanatics who have become prime suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is correct, however, to suggest that Washington
be less tolerant of Pakistan and Afghanistan as states that sponsor
or protect terrorists. Most terrorism still has an address _ a
government that can be held responsible for backing or sheltering
the vile cowards who kill civilians to terrorize an entire society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
