<HEADER>
A7382 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      06-07 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, June 8 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Ledeall: A federal judge
ordered the breakup of Microsoft Corp. on Wedsnesay, saying the
severe remedy was necessary because Microsoft ``has proved
untrustworthy in the past'' and did not appear to be taking
seriously his previous rulings against the company. ``There is
credible evidence in the record to suggest that Microsoft,
convinced of its innocence, continues to do business as it has in
the past and may yet do to other markets what it has already done''
in the markets discussed during the long antitrust trial, Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson said in his ruling. The judge accepted the
government's remedy proposal in its entirety, without alteration,
utterly rejecting Microsoft's repeated assertions that the breakup
plan was ``extreme,'' ``unwarranted'' and ``bad for consumers, the
high tech industry and our economy.'' Microsoft said it would
appeal the ruling immediately. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT12.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: For complete list of related stories, see
MICROSOFT-ADVISORY-NYT.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ASSESS (Undated) _ With his final order Wednesday in
the Microsoft antitrust case, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said
``yes'' to the government one more time. He has agreed with the
government, almost without qualification, on the facts of the case,
on the law and now on the harsh remedy of splitting the company in
two. In Jackson's court, the result has been not just a defeat for
Microsoft but a rout, not a closely fought legal contest but a
judicial ratification of the government's case. Yet the
two-year-old case is far from over. And with a year or two of
appeals ahead, the chances of Microsoft ever being broken up are
uncertain. Microsoft will try to reverse every element in Jackson's
ruling that the big software maker is a monopoly that has
repeatedly violated the nation's antitrust laws, stifling
competition and innovation. A news analysis by Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   NON-EDUCATOR-SUPERINDENDENTS (San Diego, Calif.) _ The
superintendent of San Diego schools, Alan Bersin, is a former U.S.
attorney for southern California, and one of the first of a new
breed of high-profile outsiders taking over big-city school
districts. On Tuesday, the Los Angeles board of education named Roy
Romer, the former Colorado governor, as its new superintendent.
Last month, Harold O. Levy, a corporate lawyer, was chosen to lead
the New York City school system, the nation's largest. They are the
first non-educators ever chosen for those jobs. Other urban
districts, too, have turned to law, business government and the
military for new leadership and an outside perspective. By Tamar
Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-THRILLER (Wheaton, Ill.) _ The latest thriller in a
hugely popular Christian fundamentalist series about the Apocalypse
will enter The New York Times fiction bestseller list at No. 1 this
Sunday, an unprecedented achievement for a Christian novel. The
book, ``The Indwelling,'' by Tim LaHaye, an evangelical minister,
and Jerry Jenkins is the seventh installment in the ``Left Behind''
series, which in five years has sold 17 million copies, only three
million less than the Harry Potter series, with nothing else close.
By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's government was thrown into tumult Wednesday when
parliament, by a 61-48 vote, approved a preliminary bill to
disperse and head toward new elections. The bill requires three
more hearings to become law and it could become derailed by
political maneuvering. But it seemed inevitable that it would break
up the governing coalition and create a chaotic interlude as the
peace process tries to proceed. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-RATES (Washington) _ Folo on the AT&AMP;T plan to raise some
charges at the same time it was announcing with the FCC that it was
passing on to customers savings from a government-ordered reduction
in the fees that long-distance companies pay to local phone
companies. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONVENTION (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush and his
strategists consider plans for the Republican convention in
Philadelphia. By Frank Bruni and Alison Mitchell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
