<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MICROSOFT-SOFTWARE060     06-07 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SOFTWARE0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft will likely continue to dominate software market
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At almost every software store in the United
States, vast aisles crammed with computer games, word processors
and educational tools written for Windows engulf the tiny, barely
visible shelves bearing Macintosh or Linux programs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Wednesday's ruling, that's not likely to change in the
near future. Spinning off Microsoft Corp.'s Windows system into a
separate, smaller company can't make that dominance disappear _ and
as a result, programmers scripting new software are still likely to
build it around the world's most widely used operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, this will give smaller developers an edge,'' said
S.P. Rana, co-founder of Austin software company Exterprise Inc.
``Before, many weren't interested in doing anything with Windows
because they figured, sooner or later, Microsoft would do it. But
separating Windows from Microsoft's software unit will let others
write with more freedom, and feel empowered to do more for what is
still the dominant operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the split will likely feel like a price pinch.
Microsoft will no longer be bundling Windows with its popular
Office software like Word and Excel, meaning shoppers must pick up
those pieces separately and likely at higher cost, according to
analyst Rob Enderle of California-based Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a lengthy stretch of legal appeals on the way,
shoppers may have more imminent problems with things like
customer-service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people depend on Microsoft support, and the company has
trouble holding employees during the turmoil, then that support
will degrade,'' Enderle said. ``Over the next 18 months (of a
probable appeals process), dealing with Microsoft will be more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   That period of lingering legal turmoil is a boon for Microsoft
competitors. Having reaped benefits from the Microsoft backlash,
companies like Oracle Corp. and Sun Microsystems Inc. may face
hefty pressure to truly prove themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of excitement created by people like Oracle,
but most of it was based on anti-Microsoft feeling as opposed to
what they're doing and what's good about them,'' Rana said. ``Once
that bogey disappears, they have to rethink their strategy and find
a positive way to sell what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Microsoft, the new software company could turn
competition to its advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Free of its filial ties to Windows, it could start scripting
programs for systems that were once Microsoft's nemeses _
specifically, the reborn Apple Computer Corp. Macintosh system and
the upstart Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would immediately begin writing for Linux and anything
else they could think of,'' said Roger Kay, an analyst with
International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. ``Why shouldn't they
write Office for Linux? They write Word for the Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Allcorn, a member of the Central Texas Linux Users
Group, said even that strategy might not entice all Linux users to
abandon the up-and-coming system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see Office 2000 available for Linux, but if it's
going to win with many fans it has to be all the programs and not
just Word,'' said Allcorn, a computer consultant. ``But there's a
whole other side of Linux users who are tired of Microsoft products
and won't touch anything with that name on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The split is expected to make pieces of much-guarded Microsoft
programming code more widely available to software developers,
which could make it simpler for people to create programs
compatible with Windows-based computers.
</P>
<P>
   That flurry of activity, plus severed filial ties with the
software-creation arm of Microsoft, should put healthy pressure on
the Windows company to make its operating system friendly to
developers, and more reliable for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say the Windows unit would be smart to dabble
in other operating systems _ specifically, by making its own
version of Linux, becoming less a Windoes-centric entity and more
of a general operating-systems company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at automobiles _ Ford did a heck of a job building a
better Jaguar than Jaguar itself could make,'' Enderle said. ``When
it comes to controlling the market, Microsoft could be closer to an
Intel. Handling another OS wouldn't be a bad thing if Microsoft
could do it differently and even better than anyone else has done
it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
