<P>
   MEXICO-VOTEBUY-0611 _ SAN PEDRO EL ALTO, Mexico _ Maria del
Carmen Peralta has little more than corn and beans to feed five
children. Her family has no bathroom and they sleep in a hut that's
a virtual ice box at night in this cold mountain region of Mexico
state. Peralta's life has been so harsh she wants to finally vote
for an opposition candidate in Mexico's July 2 presidential
election. But she's frightened that her vote might cost her the $45
a month supplement she receives from Progresa, a federal welfare
program here. Although it is illegal, Peralta's welfare coordinator
</P>
<P>
   confirms that she has been under pressure to instruct Progresa
recipients to vote for Mexico's ruling party on July 2 _ or suffer
the consequences. Other impoverished Mazahua Indians in this rugged
rural area have similar
</P>
<P>
   stories. All over Mexico, allegations of vote-buying and
pressure tactics are mounting as election day approaches. (Ferriss)
With photos of dissident Mazahua Indians. Moving Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   COKE _ BRUSSELS _ Last year's disaster with contamination in
Belgium has prompted Coca-Cola to completely change the way it does
business in Europe. The company has decentralized power from
Atlanta, placing much more control in the hands of its new European
divisions, which were aligned to reflect more ``natural markets.''
The company's European managers want to bring in Europeans to run
the business and become more sensitive to the continent's cultures.
For example, the company has abandoned hopes of trying to persuade
the French to abandon wine in favor of Coke and is instead trying
to find a way to ensure that its products have a place in French
consuming culture. Also, things seem to be normal in Belgium.
(Roughton). 1200 words. With photos and charts available from the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. To move late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With COKE-FRENETTE-Q&AMP;A _ Charlie Frenette, the new European
chief for Coke, talks about the changes. (Roughton)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TENSIONS-$ADV11 _ MITROVICA, Kosovo _ One year after the
NATO bombing campaign, an uneasy peace reigns in Kosovo. Serbs and
Kosovar Albanians are not living together happily, and, in fact,
clashes occur as a normal part of life in large towns like
Mitrovica. Evidence shows that the KLA _ the armed separatist group
many give at least partial credit for causing the Serb crackdown _
is still hoarding weapons for possible future attacks, while
Belgrade-backed forces are supporting violence by Serb
paramilitaries in the region. An overview of both groups' political
and military aims, and reaction from international diplomats on the
success of their peace deal. (Coker).
</P>
<P>
   With KOSOVO-CIVIL-$ADV11 _ MITROVICA, Kosovo _ A look at how
regular features of life _ schools, hospitals, courts, police,
utilities _ are working again, and what's still not working. Who is
the driving force behind getting life back to normal _ the United
Nations, local authorities or nongovernmental organizations? The
U.N. has been rather vocal about its disappointment with the
so-called donor countries who all pledged billions of dollars in
military and civilian aid to return some form of stability and
peace to this province. (Coker).
</P>
<P>
   With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TOURISM-$ADV11 _ LONDON _ Finally, a surging U.S. economy
is translating into some extra dollars for overseas tourists.
