<P>
   JOURNAL-CUBA-0615 _ HAVANA, Cuba _ Jesus Perez toiled for
decades on a collective farm in Cuba's tobacco fields, frustrated
that the once-fertile plot he tended near Pinar del Rio west of
Havana produced such meager crops. Then came the early 1990s and
Cuba's ``Special Period'' _ the economic crisis brought on by the
end of Soviet subsidies. Desperate to raise hard currency,
government officials saw world-famous Cuban tobacco as a valuable
resource. Hoping to spur production, they turned over some fields
tended by collective workers to individuals like Perez. In eight
years, Perez has boosted his field's production from about seven
100-pound bales of tobacco a year to 35 to 40 bales annually. Along
the way, he's also boosted his own earnings from 1,000 pesos per
year to 7,000 per year. He also has great pride in his leaves,
which are used to make some of Cuba's finest and most expensive
cigars. (Williams).
</P>
