<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7398 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-PENTAGON-FRAUD08-COX     06-07 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-FRAUD08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PENTAGON CONTRACTORS MAKE REPEAT APPEARANCES ON FRAUD LIST
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Top Pentagon contractors, including Lockheed Martin
Corp., Raytheon Co. and Rockwell International Corp., paid fines
totalling $434 for defective pricing, inflated costs, kickbacks and
defective products, according to a list released by Congress on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The procurement fraud list, put together by the U.S. General
Accounting Office (GAO), covers January 1995 through September 1999
and includes several companies which also appeared on a comparable
GAO list for the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there is a continuing pattern of fraud and
abuse at some of our nation's largest military contractors,'' said
Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who had asked the GAO, the investigative
arm of Congress, to make the new report.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin noted that none of the companies on the list had been
debarred from future federal contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has cracked down on individual criminals who commit
multiple crimes,'' he said. ``It's time to consider a 'three
strikes and you're out' law for repeat criminal Pentagon
contractors as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO list included eight companies that have pled guilty and
paid fines totaling $66 million in criminal fraud in procurement.
In 95 civil cases, companies have paid $369 million. Those numbers
are considerably lower than during the previous five years, when
defense spending was increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Glen Flood said that he had no information
about the contracting fraud list. However, he said that debarring
contractors in such cases ``is not an automatic thing.'' Banning a
company from doing government work generally requires the Justice
Department to take legal action, Flood said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the criminal cases, the largest involved Lockheed
Aeronautical Systems, a division of Lockheed Martin, the Bethesda,
Md., based defense giant. The company pled guilty in 1995 to making
payments to a member of the Egyptian Parliament and paid $24.8
million in fines and restitution. Some individuals involved were
debarred from government contracting for three years, but the
company was not.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed, which has a major aerospace plant in Marietta, Ga.,
and is the chief contractor for the new F-22 aircraft, also paid
more than $8 million to settle civil cases involving allegations of
defective pricing, labor overcharges and contractor kickbacks. And
Martin Marietta, which has now merged with Lockheed, paid more than
$3 million in awards to settle procurement fraud and defective
pricing cases.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed spokesman Jim Fetig on Wednesday said that in response
to past ``business concerns,'' the company has since instituted
``an award-winning business ethics programs that is one of the very
best in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't tolerate waste fraud and abuse, and we act promptly
when it's discovered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the GAO list:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hughes Aircraft Company, which merged with Raytheon in 1997,
paid $6.66 million in civil settlements in various cases involving
accusations of altered tests, failure to do tests on fighter
aircraft, missiles and tanks as well as charges of substandard
parts for torpedoes. Hughes was named in procurement fraud cases in
the 1988-95 list.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rockwell International, based in Seal Beach, Calif., paid
nearly $24 million in 1995 to settle allegations that it hid
reductions in B1-B bomber costs. The company also paid $5.5 million
in criminal fines in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   _ Philips Components and Philips Electronics, divisions of the
Dutch company Royal Philips Electronics, paid the government $55.6
million in 1996 after charges that employees had falsified test
records in weapons testing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pratt &AMP; Whitney, the aircraft division of United Technologies
Corp., which has a factory in Jupiter, Fla., agreed to pay $14.8
million in 1997 after allegations that employees had funneled $10
million in U.S. aid to retired Israeli military officers. The
company denied having knowledge of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
