<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7399 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-INVESTORS06     06-07 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-INVESTORS0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft shareholders will likely reap rewards of company's
splitBy Amy Schatz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If previous breakups are any guide, a split of
Microsoft Corp. would likely be a boon to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been few breakups of a company the size of
Microsoft, federally-enforced divorces generally yield impressive
returns to stockholders, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Most point to AT&AMP;T Corp.'s split into the current company and
the seven regional telephone companies in 1984 and the breakup of
Standard Oil into 33 companies in 1911. Both splits yielded
impressive returns to investors _ something that IBM Corp. was
unable to deliver after it successfully appealed its antitrust
breakup in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``The split-up of AT&AMP;T clearly led to innovation _ new pricing
plans, wireless technology. The old AT&AMP;T had horrendous rates that
had no connection with the actual costs of calls,'' said Sandeep
Dahiya, an assistant professor at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T shareholder in 1984 who held on to his shares (of AT&AMP;T
and each of the seven regional Baby Bells) would have seen the
value of his holdings increase more than 1,000 percent by the end
of 1999, according to Dahiya's research. That works out as a
compounded annual return of 16.4 percent. ``If all you did was hold
onto your shares you would have beaten the S&AMP;P 500 handily,''
Dahiya said.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, IBM has returned an average of about 11 percent
since 1984, the year it successfully won its antitrust battle.
During that time period, the S&AMP;P 500 returned average gains of
about 14.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people would argue that IBM shareholders would have
done better if the company had broken up,'' said Michael Murphy, an
analyst with the California Technology Stock Letter, an industry
newsletter. ``Historically, breakups have always been good news.
IBM went into a decline for about 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is an important one to most investors _ even
those who don't know that they're invested in the company.
Microsoft is one of the most widely-held stocks in the country and
a favorite of pension funds and institutional investors. For
example, Microsoft makes up the largest equity position in the
Teacher Retirement System. The $86 billion fund currently holds
about 16 million shares of Microsoft with a market value of about
$1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the country's largest mutual funds _ Fidelity's Magellan
fund and Vanguard's Index 500 _ both have more than 4 percent of
their assets tied up in Microsoft stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an investor, (the breakup) is probably going to be a
non-event,'' said Louis Kokernak, senior equities strategist at
Martin Capital Advisors, a portfolio manager and investment
advisory firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has had plenty of time to prepare for this. If I'm
a shareholder of Microsoft, I'd hold if not accumulate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue for shareholders is not what will happen if the
company is ultimately broken up, but how the stock will perform
during the long appeals process. ``Markets don't like uncertainly.
You'll probably see Microsoft take some whacks from time to time,''
said Kokernak.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
