<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MICROSOFT-HARDWARE060     06-07 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-HARDWARE0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer manufacturers and consumers to benefit from Microsoft
ruling
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The biggest winners in a Microsoft Corp. breakup may
be the computer makers and customers who have been dependent on the
software giant that dominates about 90 percent of the world's
desktops PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers such as Dell Computer Corp. should get more
leverage in dealing with Microsoft, and customers could have
greater choice in selecting individual products for the computers
they buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you were really tied down because Microsoft made you
buy their applications,'' said Amir Ahari, an industry analyst at
U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray. ``You'll see tools that are leaner and
a bit more bug-free because they don't have the Windows (operating
system) to hide behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition will be more pervasive,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's decision Wednesday to
break the company in two, the case, of course, isn't over.
Microsoft plans to appeal, which would delay Jackson's ruling even
if it's upheld.
</P>
<P>
   But many in the PC industry say that much of the impact of
Wednesday's ruling has already been felt. Since the antitrust case
began two years ago, computer makers have managed to weaken
Microsoft's near stranglehold on the PC industry. Manufacturers
such as Dell and Compaq Computer Corp., the two biggest PC makers
in the world, are still reliant on Windows. But already they've
started to embrace the Linux operating system. Dell officials
regularly note in conference calls with analysts the growing
popularity of Linux among Internet companies who buy its servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Linux is alive at all is a product of this
(case),'' said Roger Kay, an analyst with International Data Corp.,
a research firm based in Framingham, Mass. ``(Microsoft has) been
able to totally stifle other competitors in the past that were a
threat to their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers politely sidestep the issue of whether they've got
more bargaining power. Compaq _ which emerged as one of the most
staunch, full-throated defenders of Microsoft by the end of the
case _ argues the breakup will be bad for the computer business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' said Compaq spokesman Alan
Hodel. ``(But) we would continue to partner with the companies that
would result and do what we have to do. Obviously, it's easier to
deal with one company than with multiple companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell officials said that company will deal with Microsoft in
whatever forms the company takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has got lot of products people want,'' said Dell
spokesman T.R. Reid. ``Whether it comes from one company, two
companies or three companies, that's less significant. Provided
customers still want those products, we will provide those products
to them, regardless of the source.''
</P>
<P>
   For computer makers, the relationship with Microsoft has been an
uneasy one. But because Windows emerged several years ago as the
top choice by customers, they've been linked by necessity to the
products coming out of Microsoft's Redmond, Wash. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship has been strained in recent recent years as
computer prices have dropped about 25 percent a year, Microsoft's
software prices have remained fairly constant.
</P>
<P>
   But a major reason for the emergence of Linux, aside from being
cheap or even free, is that it's a lean system that's easily
customized. Windows is viewed by many as increasingly bulky and
rigid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linux is good for Microsoft in that a post-split company would
be a lot more focused and dedicated to being more innovative and
responsive to market instead of being Big Brother,'' Ahari said.
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt, however, that Microsoft will remain the
industry's 800-pound gorilla for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be sort of the beginning of the sunset years for the
Windows monopoly, but it's only the beginning,'' Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In corporate (accounts), they've got five years before they
can totally disentangle from Windows, given replacement cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
