<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7402 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TRASHY-NOVELS-1600(2n     06-07 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRASHY-NOVELS-1600(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S TRASH IS ANOTHER MAN'S ...WELL, YOU KNOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED:a lot more.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A bad girl meets a bad end, but not before the reader gets a
lot of voyeuristic pleasure out of the journey,'' wrote voluptuous
``Star-Telegram'' food maven Beverly Bundy of ``Forever Amber,''
the novel by Kathleen Winsor. ``I read it in college, and I still
thought it was dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   From a blond bombshell business writer came ``Flame and the
Flower,'' by Kathleen Woodiwiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it when I was 13, the perfect age for trashy romance
novels,'' she offered. ``I'd have to refresh my memory, but I
believe if followed the classic romance outline: ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that the synopsis made me blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best soft-core porn I've ever encountered,'' dark, dashing
classical music critic Wayne Lee Gay raved about ``Valley of the
Dolls'' by Jacqueline Susann.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't beat the descriptions,'' another business vixen
wrote of ``Scruples'' by Judith Krantz.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after an hour or so of the deluge, I had to put a stop
to it. In a bit of a panic, I composed a second message, zapped
into computers across the editorial department.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK folks. Let's all calm down and get our little collective
minds out of the gutter,'' I scolded, before going on to clarify
just what I meant by trashy novel. ``Not that the gratuitous sex
that appeals only to the prurient in us isn't included here, but
not exclusively. ... So calm down, for crying out loud. Cyberspace
was literally searing with all your responses, all those e-mails
about this book or that book which taught you about the birds and
the bees in junior high, or, in Beverly Bundy's case, college.
Reconsider. Ponder.''
</P>
<P>
   Most staffers only scoffed. All my clarification served to
accomplish was to reveal myself as a prude who would have been
right at home in the age of Queen Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``You set yourself up, big guy,'' Texas travel writer and
worldly sophisticate June Naylor Rodriguez responded to my second
message. ``In the age of Jerry Springer, trash means one thing to
people.''
</P>
<P>
   A villainous Northeast Star-Telegram reporter was less
charitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You spent too much time in the frozen North,'' he sneered.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, my second message was not completely fruitless. Mickey
Spillane and Agatha Christie finally surfaced in the responses. As
did John Grisham and Scott Turow, Michael Crichton and Stephen
Coonts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can participate under the new rules,'' Arlington
editor Matthew Brady wrote, reassuringly. ``My favorite pulp
fiction writer is Dick Francis, the British ex-jockey who writes
mystery stories that revolve around the world of racing. Great
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but what do you expect from a goody-two-shoes who used to
cover religion? And this relatively tasteful response
notwithstanding, I am not consoled. I still feel virtually alone in
my definition of trash. Trashy novels, it seems, have gone the way
of ... well, trash. Somewhere, Travis McGee, my knight-errant hero,
takes a sip of gin, sits on his houseboat, watching the brilliant
orange sun disappear on the horizon, and sadly shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7403 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TRASHY-NOVELS-1600(2T     06-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRASHY-NOVELS-1600(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S TRASH IS ANOTHER MAN'S ...WELL, YOU KNOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First let us ponder the meaning of the term ``trashy novel.'' I
have recently come to discover that my definition of trash and that
of most of the rest of the English-speaking world are hopelessly at
odds.
</P>
<P>
   First, mine.
</P>
<P>
   To me, labeling a novel trash is not a pejorative thing.
``Trash'' is merely a book that falls short, sometimes just short,
of literature. In my simple mind, a book is either one thing or the
other. Literature typically calls our attention to the human
condition. Trash allows us to escape it. Literature typically
requires a quiet room and concentration. Trash can be consumed
while simultaneously watching ``The Practice.'' Great literature
inspires deep thought and profound emotions. Trash, generally
speaking, does not.
</P>
<P>
   My trash is populated by private detectives, spies, cops, a
sultry blonde here and there, romantic subplots, moderate body
counts and generous sprinklings of sex, although graphic
descriptions of the same are not necessary or even preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Examples: My favorite trash of all time is the Travis McGee
series by author John B. MacDonald. McGee is a lifelong cynic and
loping hunk of a private detective, who reluctantly leaves his
Florida houseboat to confront various bad guys in yarns with
color-themed titles, (''Bright Orange for the Shroud, The Empty
Copper Sea, Free Fall in Crimson.'') The adventures are punctuated
by McGee's pithy observations on contemporary life, and by his love
interests. He sips Boodles gin after a hard day. He refuses to grow
up, to conform. I still remember the sad day 13 years ago when I
picked up the newspaper to learn that MacDonald had died, taking
Travis to the grave with him.
</P>
<P>
   Today I'm still in mourning, and determined to seek out McGee
titles I haven't read. But one must move on. So I also currently
await the latest from espionage legend John LeCarre, though his
elegant way with the language, penetrating insights into the darker
side of humanity and his character development probably qualify his
books as literature. But that's another argument.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, I have recently discovered the 87th Precinct novels
of Ed McBain, mesmerizing stories that flirt with the status of
literature, too, but are too entertaining to quite get there.
Daniel Silva's three recent novels (''The Unlikely Spy; The Mark of
the Assassin; The Marching Season'') more safely fit into the
category of trash. They are slick, well-written thrillers full of
international intrigue that is convincingly rendered. The latter
two Silva titles feature a studly hero, CIA agent Michael Osbourne,
a rather cynical fellow who only reluctantly takes on the bad guys.
McGee-esque, you might say.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe you get the idea. That's what trash means to me. I
thought the term conjured up pretty much the same image for most
people. Boy, was I wrong.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The voice of ``Texas Monthly'' senior editor Skip Hollandsworth
positively purred when he returned my call. A few minutes earlier,
I'd left a message on his voice-mail, inquiring about his favorite
trashy novel of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wedding scene of `The Godfather', Page 66,'' Hollandsworth
replied without even saying, ``Hi.''
</P>
<P>
   That page of Mario Puzo's Mafia tale was dog-eared by
Hollandsworth and his fellow junior high school boys in Wichita
Falls a few decades ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was passed around my homeroom and I read the sex scene at
the wedding. Somebody got married and the bride and Sonny had sex
up in a room,'' Hollandsworth said, his words quickening at the
memory. ``I can remember this feeling of blood coursing through my
veins, and I went, `This is the power of literature.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Actually, it was Pages 27 and 28. And it was the coupling of
the bridesmaid and Sonny Corleone, not Sonny and the bride. I found
the book and read the pages closely, just for accuracy's sake.)
</P>
<P>
   And so it went. That same day, my newsroom-wide e-mail similarly
soliciting nominations for great trash was greeted by that same
panting. Lots of panting. That afternoon, newspaper cyberspace
sizzled. Judging from the newsroom reaction, somewhere between
puberty and college, the average ``Star-Telegram'' staffer learned
of carnality from books their parents didn't know they were
reading. Naughty books. Not a spy or detective tale in the bunch.
``Bodice-ripping'' was the operative term. I grew up in a fairly
repressed slice of rural Minnesota. So thus, on that recent
afternoon, I was appalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohhh ... There's so many,'' gushed a sultry brunette from
online services. `` `Peyton Place' and `Return to Peyton Place' by
Grace Metalious. A New England town and its gossip. Better book
than movie. Or rather, the book got away with a lot more.'' MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
