<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT08-COX     06-07 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE ORDERS MICROSOFT TO BE SPLIT IN TWO
 &HT;    740&AMP;add. With MICROSOFT-REACT, MICROSOFT-JUDGE, JUDGE-BIOBOX and
MICROSOFT-GLANCE. Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge issued a historic antitrust ruling
Wednesday that orders Microsoft Corp. to be split in two in order
to halt the company's unlawful behavior and restore competition in
the computer software industry.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ordered the part of
Microsoft that makes the Windows operating system to separate from
a new applications and Internet-based company. The two new firms
would have to compete on an arms-length basis for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also ordered broad restrictions on Microsoft's business
practices toward other firms in the computer industry, as well as
controls on many of Microsoft's internal activities.
</P>
<P>
   If sustained on appeal, the order would break up a giant
enterprise that in its 25-year lifetime has done much to define the
personal computer era.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft dominates the worldwide market in operating systems
for small computers, earning annual revenues of more than $20
billion a year and holding a current market worth of some $371
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The next phase of one of the biggest battles in the annals of
antitrust law will be a series of appeals that could consume
several more years and will likely eventually be decided by the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said they would seek a direct
expedited review by the high court under a rarely invoked 1970s law
that provides for short-circuiting the normal appeals process in
antitrust cases of vital national importance.
</P>
<P>
   All or part of Jackson's formula might be set aside pending the
outcome of the legal skirmishes, and the judicial order provides
that the breakup cannot occur until all appeals are exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, assuming it stands up to legal scrutiny, Jackson's
order is the most drastic antitrust action taken by the courts in
nearly 90 years. As one of the most successful engines of the
high-tech economy, Microsoft could find itself joining the ranks of
the former Standard Oil and American Tobacco trusts, which were
both broken up in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing why the world's biggest software firm needed to be
dismantled under the 1890 Sherman Antitrust Act, Jackson wrote that
``Microsoft, as it is presently organized and led, is unwilling to
accept the notion that it broke the law or accede to an order
amending its conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge found Microsoft to be an ``untrustworthy'' defendant
whose ``purported compliance'' with an earlier 1995 court antitrust
injunction while it was being appealed was ``illusory.''
</P>
<P>
   In an 1,500-word memorandum that accompanied his sweeping order,
Jackson wrote: ``Microsoft has shown no disposition to voluntarily
alter its business protocol in any significant respect. Indeed, it
has announced its intention to appeal even the imposition of the
modest conduct remedies it has itself proposed as an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing 78 days of testimony from the bench and reviewing
scores of post-trial briefs, Jackson essentially upheld the
government's original contention that Microsoft had illegally
leveraged its Windows monopoly to try to crush its rivals and bully
its clients.
</P>
<P>
   His 5,800-word judicial order faithfully tracked a plan devised
by the Justice Department and 17 state attorneys general after
intensive settlement talks had broken down.
</P>
<P>
   That April 27 filing triggered a series of back-and-forth briefs
from the company and the government. While serving to delay a
ruling that had been widely expected late last month, the exchanges
scarcely altered its final content.
</P>
<P>
   Said Attorney General Janet Reno: ``Today's ruling will have a
profound impact not only by promoting competition in the software
industry but also by reaffirming the importance of antitrust law
enforcement in the 21 century and the importance of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing her words, Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein, who as
head of the Justice Department's antitrust division had brought the
landmark case in May 1998, said: ``The court's order is the right
remedy for Microsoft's serious and repeated violations of the
antitrust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   But across the continent, at Microsoft's Redmond, Wash.
headquarters, a defiant Bill Gates confidently predicted the
company he had co-founded would be vindicated on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe very strongly today is first day of the rest of this
case,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In a decisive preliminary ruling on April 3, Jackson sealed
Microsoft's fate in the trial court by finding company had flouted
the nation's antitrust laws in placing ``an oppressive thumb on the
scale of competitive fortune'' _ targeting rival firms that
threatened its powerful Windows software monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   In finding that Microsoft had used illegal means to dominate one
most dynamic sectors of the U.S. economy, the judge laid the
eventual groundwork for Wednesday's order to break up the world's
most valued software company.
</P>
<P>
   The remedial order and the earlier 43-page ruling flowed in turn
from Jackson's blistering ``findings of fact,'' issued last
November, in which he branded Microsoft as an abusive monopolist
that for years had run roughshod over competitors, strong-armed
clients, harmed consumers and throttled technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Even at this late stage of the judicial process, the litigants
could decide to try once more to settle the case, this time
probably through direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the case is still under appeal next year, a new
administration in place at the White House and the Justice
Department could also possibly move to reignite the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But barring any such an out-of-court settlement, or an unlikely
decision by a new administration to halt prosecution, the Supreme
Court will likely serve as the final arbiter.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup order, immediately available on the Internet, was
timed for release at 4:30 p.m. EDT, 30 minutes after the closing of
the major financial markets Prior to after-hours trading, Microsoft
stock had risen a modest 88 cents for the day, closing at $70.50 on
volume of 38,193,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   The company's uncertain future has dragged the company's stock
price down from a 52-week high of $119.94, reached in December
while failed settlement talks were showing some signs of progress.
</P>
<P>
   In his final memo, Jackson noted ruefully that ``the final
judgment proposed by plaintiffs is perhaps more radical than might
have resulted had mediation been successful and terminated in a
consent decree.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jackson has his way, so-called conduct-based remedies would
go into place well before the final structural breakup of the
25-year-old company comes to pass.
</P>
<P>
   They call upon Microsoft to stop pricing Windows in ways that
favor cooperative personal computer makers, to stop tying its
products to Windows in its sales contracts, to set aside all
exclusionary contracts and to stop driving sales up by raising the
price of older versions of Windows whenever a new version comes
out.
</P>
<P>
   Although what has now happened to Microsoft has been widely
compared with the breakup of AT&AMP;T in 1982, sharp differences can be
found between the two cases. AT&AMP;T was a regulated monopoly for
eight decades before it was broken up in a negotiated deal that
split off seven regional operating companies _ the so-called Baby
Bells _ while allowing the core firm to concentrate on
long-distance service and enter the computer market.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, on the other hand, deals largely in intellectual
property _ the tens of millions of lines of computer code that go
into such products as the Windows operating system or the
applications suite known as Office.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: usvms.gpo.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7410 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT08-COX     06-07 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
