<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7412 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD     06-07 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-900(2TAKES)-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK GOVERNMENT THREATENED AFTER PARLIAMENT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update and restructure; inserts new 2nd graf;   rewrites
grafs 3,4 to clarify (bgng: `The bill requires...'; deletes grafs
4,5 from original text (bgng `We are on...') to move material
elsewhere in story; recasts 5th graf; adds new grafs 7,8; recasts
graf before 1st optional trim to clarify; adds new graf to end of
optional trim material to add Sharansky quote; deletes grafs 2-4
after optional trim and inserts new grafs 2-6 (bgng `He could
negotiate...; in 2nd take, adds new grafs 2,3 with comment from
Palestinians) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government was
thrown into tumult Wednesday when parliament, by a substantial
majority, approved a preliminary bill to disperse and head toward
new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the six parties in Barak's broad coalition voted
against him, including the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, which has
been the prime minister's most temperamental ally and on Wednesday
ensured his defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires three more hearings to become law, and it
could end up being derailed by political maneuvering or the basic
desire of members of parliament to cling to their jobs and
perquisites. But Wednesday's vote, even if it does not provoke new
elections, could break up the governing coalition and create a
chaotic interlude at a diplomatically inopportune moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Palestinian final peace talks were supposed to
consume Barak's energies this summer. Instead, he may be forced to
devote considerable time to domestic negotiations _ ``What's next?
'' said his Cabinet secretary, Yitzhak Herzog. ``Poker.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak kept silent immediately after the vote, which was 61-48
with 11 of the 120 members absent. But Wednesday evening, he
addressed the nation with a completely unruffled manner. Saying
that the Cabinet would meet on Sunday and figure out how to
proceed, his advised all Israelis to relax, enjoy the holiday of
Shavuout, which begins Thursday evening, and trust him to restore
calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dust will settle,'' he said confidently. ``There aren't
going to be any elections.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, busloads of settlers were gathering outside his
residence to shout: ``Barak, go home! You have no mandate!''
Carrying babies and banners, they looked exultant, and dozens of
yeshiva students performed a joyful line dance.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Nahum Barnea, the dean of Israeli newspaper
columnists, shook his head as he surveyed the frenzied politicking
in the bustling halls of the flat-roofed parliament building. ``We
are on the threshold of a new era, and from here it looks like it
will be a mess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A former general who was elected by an overwhelming majority in
May of last year, Barak went to great effort to cobble together a
broad coalition of left and right, religious and secular parties in
what he portrayed as an effort to heal the diverse rifts in Israeli
society. He also believed that he needed a broad government to back
his peacemaking plans.
</P>
<P>
   But from the time Barak took office in July, the coalition was
fractious.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday three of the six parties in the government
voted against him: the National Religious Party, which was on its
way to quitting anyway; the Russian immigrant party, Yisrael
B'Aliyah, led by the interior minister, Natan Sharansky; and Shas,
the ultra-Orthodox movement that is the third-largest political
party in Israel, after the Liberal/One Israel and the Likud
parties.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   All three parties voting against Barak served in the right-wing
Cabinet of the former prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu. A former
chief of staff of Netanyahu's, Avigdor Lieberman, who heads a
second Russian immigrant party, introduced the bill. Shas members
encouraged him to do so, and when the vote passed, they surrounded
Lieberman for an extended group hug.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, several feet away, Ophir Pines-Paz, the
chairman of Barak's faction, sat alone, looking shocked and
crestfallen.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, which with 17 members of parliament represents Jews of
North African and Middle Eastern origin, has been the balkiest
party in the coalition, fighting for money and respect from the
first day. The other two parties more specifically opposed Barak's
peace moves, and long felt out of place in a center-left
government, frequently siding with the right-wing opposition that
was weakened without them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his party would do, Sharansky, who has complained
bitterly about Barak's failure to consult his Cabinet ministers,
said: ``It takes two to get a divorce. But definitely this virtual
coalition can't continue.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Barak faces several options in the immediate future, as this
bill wends its way through parliament.
</P>
<P>
   He could negotiate with Sharansky and with Shas to try to save
his original coalition. That seemed unlikely because Barak said
Wednesday night that, ``Those ministers who voted today for early
elections fired themselves.'' But leaving the door open, he also
suggested that ``a coalition of similar composition to the current
one'' could work if it acted more cohesively.
</P>
<P>
   Barak could also bypass parliament and ask outgoing Israeli
President Ezer Weizman to give him permission to resign. Also an
unlikely scenario, that would force new elections in 90 days from
the time the request was granted. That would be much quicker than
if the elections came about as a result of Wednesday's bill, and it
would allow Barak to seize the momentum and profit from his surge
in popularity after the Israeli troop withdrawal from Lebanon last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in the most likely option, he could reshape the coalition as
a narrow, minority government that depends on Arab parties for
majority votes on peacemaking issues. To do that, Barak would
likely enlist a six-member secularist party, called Shinui, a
two-member workers right's party, and a two-member, left-wing
Russian party. That would give him a 52-member government, with 10
votes from the Arab parties as a cushion.
</P>
<P>
   It would also give him a political framework similar to that of
his mentor, the late Yitzhak Rabin. Barak had aspired not to copy
Rabin's governmental model because he felt it exacerbated the
left-right, secular-religious divide in Israeli society. And it
engendered a strong opposition to peace efforts, which could be
recreated now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Further, it would allow the right wing to bait him as it did
Rabin about relying on the Arab parties because he couldn't get a
Jewish majority.
</P>
<P>
   Several ministers of the government wrung their hands Wednesday
and claimed that the politicians who voted to shake things up were
tone-deaf to the public mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote has nothing to do with what people want,'' said Haim
Ramon, a minister charged with Jerusalem affairs. ``Your desire,''
he told the lawmakers, ``is disconnected from reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Melchior, a dovish rabbi in Barak's Cabinet, said the
vote revealed the ``sectorialism'' of parliament and predicted that
it would infuriate the public. ``What? They want a period of
uncertainty?'' he said. ``No one will want this. Everyone outside
this building will hate us.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said they feared that the country's diplomatic efforts
would suffer most. ``This is not just a government crisis,'' said
Naomi Chazan, a leftist lawmaker. ``It's the future of the peace
process, and everyone who voted for this is exercising maximum
irresponsibility.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the right-wing Likud Party did not waste time in
proclaiming Barak's days to be numbered. ``I'm running around
trying to form a new coalition right now,'' said Silvan Shalom, a
young lawmaker who aspires to take over the Likud.
</P>
<P>
   Shalom acknowledged that the peace effort, which is not his
priority, might be hurt. `Obviously the other side will understand
that they are negotiating with a lame duck, and they won't want to
make decisions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Ramallah, the West Bank, Saeb Erekat, a senior
Palestinian negotiator, said the vote was ``an internal Israeli
matter'' but one that made the Palestinians nervous. ``I hope this
situation will not be used as an excuse to introduce more
settlements or more obstacles to peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the Israeli government will not use what is happening
as a pretext not to implement the third phase of redeployment or to
release more prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shas party, whose power base is built on a social service
network that includes a large religious school system, has been
battling for money to cover its schools' debts. Shas' leader, Eli
Yishai, has butted heads with the leftist education minister, Yossi
Sarid, on funding, educational reform and power issues. And Shas'
spiritual leader, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, is under police investigation
for inciting violence against Sarid in his sermons.
</P>
<P>
   Shas' vote Wednesday was the culmination of its threats against
the government, which followed Barak's suspension of negotiations
over the problems of its school system earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided on Monday morning to vote in favor of Avigdor
Lieberman's bill,'' said Yitzhak Suderi, the spokesman for Shas.
``When we gave him our word, he decided to introduce his bill. We
warned the prime minister a few weeks ago that Lieberman was
preparing the bill and that we might support it if we were to
continue to be persecuted by Meretz,'' which is Sarid's party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for the prime minister to make a decision,''
Suderi continued. ``Does he want a narrow coalition that will
endure only two or three weeks, or does he want to try to maintain
his broad coalition. He can either show leadership, as we know he
is capable of, given the experience with the withdrawal from
Lebanon, or he can do Yossi Sarid's bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   The liberal, secular members of the Israeli public who voted
Barak into office are hoping that he will finally turn his back on
Shas. Several ministers said they imagined he would.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ramon, long a political ally of Shas, sounded fed up
Wednesday. ``One thing's for sure,'' he said. ``The mess is over.
And the next coalition will be organized so that whoever votes
against us is out the same day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
