<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TELEFONICA-1STLD-WRIT     06-07 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEFONICA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEFONICA CHAIRMAN TRIES TO REVIVE MERGER TALKS WITH KPN,
EXECUTIVES SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs lede to include time element.) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Juan Villalonga, the chairman of Telefonica, the
Spanish telecommunications company, has been trying to rally
support among board members to revive merger talks with the Dutch
telephone operator Royal KPN, executives close to Telefonica said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga was embarrassed last month when his board succumbed
to political pressure from the Spanish government and Spanish banks
and rejected a $58 billion merger with KPN that Villalonga had
sought. Opponents argued against the deal in part because the Dutch
government would be the biggest shareholder in a merged company.
</P>
<P>
   The failed merger was viewed by telecommunications industry
analysts as a major setback for Telefonica, once a state-owned
monopoly. With KPN, Villalonga had hoped to create a pan-European
network of fixed-line, data and wireless services with the size to
compete against the likes of Vodafone Airtouch PLC and France
Telecom, which recently agreed to buy Orange PLC of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to Telefonica, Villalonga has been
making private overtures to several of the nine board members who
voted against the merger, asking them to reconsider. The executives
cautioned that Villalonga was far from winning the support he
needed to restart talks with KPN, and might decide to abandon the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of Telefonica's 20 board members officially voted for the
deal, nowhere near the unanimous approval regarded as necessary for
such an important change in the company. Some opponents had
privately voted a day earlier in favor of the merger, the
executives said. Villalonga hopes to persuade them to create enough
support to at least return to negotiations with KPN.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, KPN remains somewhat interested in combining with
Telefonica, but only if Telefonica's board fully supports the deal,
executives close to KPN said.
</P>
<P>
   After the merger talks fell apart, KPN's chairman, Paul Smits,
accused the Spanish government and the banks of interfering. ``We
have no interest in an internal political process,'' he said.
``It's not about a merger of emotions, it's about a merger of
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   KPN believed that without the complete support of both
management boards, no deal was possible, Smits said. ``You have to
have a merger with passion con amor and with total commitment for
it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits apparently remains interested in a merger with Telefonica,
perhaps even more so now because of its relationship with Lycos,
the Internet company based in the United States, the executives
said. They stopped short of saying he would necessarily endorse
resuming negotiations with Telefonica, however, because of the
messy ending to their last merger attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Terra Networks, the Internet unit of
Telefonica, acquired Lycos for $12.5 billion. If KPN and Telefonica
merged, the combined group would be one of the largest Internet
companies in Europe with a strong foothold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   KPN and Qwest, which is based in Denver, are working together in
Europe to create a high-speed network. KPN's mobile arm, KPN
Mobile, also recently entered into an alliance with the Japanese
mobile communications giant NTT DoCoMo, an added attraction for
Villalonga.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Telefonica declined to comment on whether
Villalonga was working to restart talks with KPN. A spokesman for
KPN could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Telefonica stressed that it was too early to
tell whether the company's board was committed enough to reaching a
deal with KPN to justify new talks. One executive said he expected
that a decision on whether Telefonica would try to restart talks
would be made within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts questioned whether Villalonga could revive enough
interest among the board members to try to negotiate a deal with
KPN and whether a deal could in fact be consummated. Nonetheless,
analysts said the deal would be beneficial to both companies,
pointing out that shares of both fell significantly after the
original talks collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be a marriage made in heaven,'' said John Tysoe, a
telecommunications analyst at West LB Panmure in London. ``But some
marriages of convenience end up working out well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
