<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SUDAN-SLAVERY-BOS &LR;      06-07 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-SLAVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBESMAN RELATES EXPERIENCES AS SLAVE IN SUDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A full house, matrons all in white, a pulsing, powerful
gospel choir _ all were usual for Communion Sunday services at
Southern Baptist Church. But the very tall, very thin, very black
man standing before Pastor Gerald Bell at the altar was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bless God's name for the days this man did not eat,'' Bell
cried, locking eyes with the visitor. ``Bless God's name for the
days he slept with the pigs, the days he slopped the camels, the
day he saw sisters shot. I don't know what good will come out of
this, but we believe!''
</P>
<P>
   Francis Piol Bol Bok, 21, Dinka tribesman, fugitive slave,
Christian, stood stock still, eyes riveted on the minister,
thoughts wandering across the decade that ended with his escape
from bondage in Sudan four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bok was in this church Sunday morning, is in Washington
Thursday, and will be at Faneuil Hall Friday evening to bear
witness to unimaginable cruelty and suffering. His is a featured
story in a two-week national campaign against slavery in Sudan that
culminates Friday with rallies and vigils in 25 cities.
</P>
<P>
   Telling old people and young about slavery today, and making the
link with slavery yesterday, are key ingredients in an effort to
give the problems of Africa more prominence in US foreign policy,
where it has become common wisdom that African nations get little
attention because they do not make anything the US needs, they do
not pose a threat, and they are not a high priority among African
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope that by presenting real people like Bok to the
public, support can be rallied against some of the most grotesque
and preventable sources of African suffering _ such as slavery in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need everyone to come out of their seats and press close!''
Bell said. ``Touch him. Form a hedge around him. Lift up this
brother! Support him! Give him strength!''
</P>
<P>
   The congregation moved forward as a single body, encompassing
the thin man, reaching out and laying on their hands until only
Bok's head and round-cut Afro poked above the massed humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people you need to hear this,'' Bell called out to the
congregants, almost all of them African American. ``It was once
this way with us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' scattered voices responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were slaves and no one wanted to believe us,'' he called;
``Yes Lord!'' the response gained strength.
</P>
<P>
   Bok was 7 years old, a farm boy living in the southwest Sudanese
town of Gorian, on the day he walked to the regional market in
Nyamlall to sell his family's eggs and beans.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the area was surrounded by Sudanese Muslim militiamen.
Hardly anyone in the vast market escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Adults and adolescent boys were slain on the spot. Children who
were not killed were tied on donkeys for their journey into
bondage; those too small to straddle an animal were tied into
baskets bound to the beasts.
</P>
<P>
   Bok cannot forget the sight of a 12 year old who had just seen
her parents killed. ``She would not stop crying,'' he said. ``They
took her out of the basket and shot her, and then her sister, who
was about 10, would not stop crying, and they took her out of the
basket and cut off her hand with the sword.''
</P>
<P>
   The children were taken to a slave market in Kirio, where
hundreds of captives were bound and sold; Bok was given to a
brother of the militia leader, and his indoctrination began.
</P>
<P>
   ``That man took me to his home and told all his family to take
sticks, and beat me, and call me `slave, slave,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of abuse and malnourishment, during which he
was compelled to sleep outdoors with his master's animals, Bok made
his first escape attempt _ a mission impossible in the militarized
and ethnically divided Sudan, where a young boy with no sure sense
of geography and the tribal scars of the Dinka on his forehead was
easily identifiable as a runaway slave. He was caught quickly,
returned to his master, and beaten severely.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, he tried again. In consequence, he suffered
tortures from which he still bears scars on his ankles, chest, and
hands _ scars he incongruously, unselfconsciously, displayed during
a breakfast interview at a deli, where he also saw his first
waffle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me if I tried to escape again they would kill me,''
he said, ``so I stayed'' for a while. ``But I knew I would have to
escape again, because when you get to be 16 or 17, they think
you're some kind of threat to them, and they kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   On market day soon after he turned 17, Bok dressed like an Arab
and escaped. He sought help from police, ``but they are Arab too
and they didn't want slave to go out _ so they slave me too.''
After two months, he escaped at a market in a larger town, where a
trucker gave him a ride out of the region.
</P>
<P>
   He reached Khartoum, but then was arrested, beaten, and tortured
by government security men who thought he had been telling
foreigners there was slavery in Sudan _ a fact the government still
denies. Released after seven months, he escaped to Egypt. He took
his story to United Nations officials there, and in September 1999
was granted refugee status.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Where you want to go?' and I said, `I don't care,
I want to be free,' '' Bok said. In August, he flew from Cairo to
New York to Chicago _ to Fargo, N.D., where he was the only
Sudanese. One New Year's Day he moved to Ames, Iowa, where there
was a family of southern Sudanese, and in May he came to Boston to
become a staff member of the Boston-based American Anti-Slavery
Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Such rapid and extreme changes would befuddle many people, and
Bok cannot imagine how it will all turn out. For now, ``there are
many, many things I'd like to do,'' he said. ``First I want to go
to school. Second, I want to find my family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
