<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories and graphics on
the judge's ruling in the Microsoft antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Ledeall: A federal judge
ordered the breakup of the Microsoft Corp. on Wedsnesay, saying the
severe remedy was necessary because Microsoft ``has proved
untrustworthy in the past'' and did not appear to be taking
seriously his previous rulings against the company. ``There is
credible evidence in the record to suggest that Microsoft,
convinced of its innocence, continues to do business as it has in
the past and may yet do to other markets what it has already done''
in the markets discussed during the long antitrust trial, Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson said in his ruling. The judge accepted the
government's remedy proposal in its entirety, without alteration,
utterly rejecting Microsoft's repeated assertions that the breakup
plan was ``extreme,'' ``unwarranted'' and ``bad for consumers, the
high tech industry and our economy.'' By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT12.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ASSESS (Undated) _ With his final order Wednesday in
the Microsoft antitrust case, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said
``yes'' to the government one more time. He has agreed with the
government, almost without qualification, on the facts of the case,
on the law and now on the harsh remedy of splitting the company in
two. In Jackson's court, the result has been not just a defeat for
Microsoft but a rout, not a closely fought legal contest but a
judicial ratification of the government's case. Yet the
two-year-old case is far from over. And with a year or two of
appeals ahead, the chances of Microsoft ever being broken up are
uncertain. Microsoft will try to reverse every element in Jackson's
ruling that the big software maker is a monopoly that has
repeatedly violated the nation's antitrust laws, stifling
competition and innovation. A news analysis by Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LAW (Washington) _ ``Possession of unchallenged
economic power deadens initiative, discourages thrift and depresses
energy.'' ``Immunity from competition is a narcotic, and rivalry a
stimulant, to industrial progress.'' Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
in June, 2000 ordering the breakup of Microsoft? No, Judge Learned
Hand declaring in 1945 that the Aluminum Company of America had
illegally monopolized the market for a type of aluminum ingot. A
lot has changed since 1945, the exact midpoint between the passage
of the Sherman Antitrust Act in 1890 and the Microsoft ruling on
Wednesday. An economy based on heavy industry and capital
investment has transformed itself into one based more and more on
human capital and information technology. Nonetheless, as
Wednesday's ruling demonstrates dramatically, the old factories may
be obsolete, but the legal principles that led to the breakup of
the Standard Oil trust in 1911 and the American Telephone &AMP;
Telegraph Co. in 1984 are not. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REACT (Washington) _ Looking at the reaction from the
plaintiffs as well as political fallout. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REDMOND (Redmond, Wash.) _ The reaction from Microsoft
headquarters. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Looking at Microsoft's stock,
its past performance and its prospects. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REMEDY (Washington) _ A summation of the government's
remedy proposal: The centerpiece of the government's cure for the
predatory, monopolistic, take-no-prisoners behavior that Microsoft
was found to have embraced is to chop the company in two. One new
company would make the Windows operating system, the other would
make the applications that are run by the operating system, as well
as Microsoft's Internet and computer hardware businesses. The
government called the companies ``Ops Co.'' and ``Apps Co.'' in
court papers. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-NEXT (Undated) _ What happens next in the legal
process. (A short)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ Looking at the potential impact
on consumers. By Peter H. Lewis and Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, the text of the government's breakup plan and other
documents issued previously in the Microsoft case may be found at
The New York Times on the Web:www.nytimes.com
</P>
