<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7436 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JIMWALTER-SUIT0608-CO     06-07 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIMWALTER-SUIT0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Homebuilder hit with suit
 &HT;    By Yolanda Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the country's largest homebuilders and its
financing arm are being accused of illegally tacking on attorneys
fees to home mortgages that have gone into default in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit against Jim Walter Homes and Mid-State Homes was
filed by two Athens residents who discovered the fees had been
added to their mortgage principals when they received printouts of
their payments during bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the plaintiffs, Joann Davis and Tommy C. Roach, will
try to convince a judge that the companies have charged similar
fees to other unsuspecting consumers and that the suit should be
given class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed May 26 in the Superior Court of Cobb County,
where the company has its registered agent.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company, Walter Industries, received a copy of the
lawsuit this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe our practices are in full compliance with Georgia
law,'' said David Townsend, a spokesman for Walter Industries,
which is based in Tampa. ``We'll contest the lawsuit accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael O. Crain, the lead plaintiffs' lawyer, estimated that
between 1,000 and 5,000 consumers in Georgia could be in similar
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   According to its Web site, _ www.jimwalterhomes.com _ Jim Walter
Homes has built 330,000 single-family houses since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   It has offices in 22 states, mostly in the South. Mid-State
Homes holds 63,000 mortgages in its market.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lee Morgan, co-counsel for the plaintiffs, Davis
and Roach were never informed in writing that their mortgages had
gone into default and that they could pay the past due amounts
within 10 days without incurring attorneys fees. Georgia requires
the notification.
</P>
<P>
   Then the company added the fees, which totaled $475 for Davis
and $730 for Roach, to the principal balance without telling them,
also in violation of the law, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly mortgage payments were never increased, so the
plaintiffs did not suspect that they were paying a higher
principal, Crain said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Roach went into Chapter 13 bankruptcy _ a repayment
plan in which a debtor makes payments to a trustee, who in turn
pays off the debt. That's when they discovered the fees, Crain
said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Industries is listed on the New York Stock Exchange under
the stock symbol WLT. The company was founded in 1946, by Jim
Walter, who created a niche in the affordable housing market. It
does not build homes on speculation, it constructs them on
already-owned lots.
</P>
<P>
   According to its web site (jimwalterhomes.com), Jim Walter Homes
has built 330,000 single-family houses since its inception. It has
offices in 22 states, mostly in the South. Mid-State Homes holds
63,000 mortgages in its market.
</P>
