<P>
   DEFICIT-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ It has become one of the most
familiar refrains in economic circles. Every time the trade deficit
reaches yet another record, as it did again this March, economists
generally assure us that there is little, perhaps nothing, to worry
about. Why are we so complacent? One reason is that a couple of
misleading half-truths have become conventional wisdom. By Jeff
Madrick.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Paced by technology issues, stock prices
resumed their climb as the belief spread that the Federal Reserve
can soon stop raising interest rates to keep inflation in check. By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
