<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SPIDERCAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIDERCAM COMING TO THE WORLD WIDE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHEL MARRIOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before television became a friendly flicker in American
households and laptop computers started popping up in trendy coffee
bars, there were comic books. Crammed with colorful graphics and
plain-talking super heroes speaking in bursts of text, comic books
looked like Web sites in search of a Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now executives and artists at Marvel Comics are turning to
digital technology to give birth to an entirely new kind of comic
book to be launched on the Internet this summer _ free.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jemas, president of publishing, new media and consumer
products at Marvel, calls the new approach ``SpiderCam'' because it
stars Marvel's most popular character, Spider-Man, and is produced
with cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Everything except Spider-Man himself, is being shot in New York
with high-resolution digital cameras using models, actors and
landmark locations that even the occasional tourist would easily
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Little, if anything, will be drawn by hand. Details and visual
effects, like the suggestion of motion, are more likely to be
accomplished with computers using Photoshop software, say artists
working on the SpiderCam episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting as much as we can in camera,'' said Henry
Tenney, director of the first SpiderCam episode called ``Pretty
Ugly.'' He said artists using Photoshop will give the comic a
consistent look.
</P>
<P>
   Spider-Man, the arachid-powered super hero, will also be
computer-generated and inserted into the photo-realistic action
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``Because no human can do what your imagination wants
Spider-Man to be,'' Jemas said. When these still scenes download
and appear on computer screens, he said, they will _ using Flash
technology _ splash, slide and glide into view, quickly assembling
in varying shapes for dramatic effect into something resembling a
traditional comic book page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our readers want to see the cutting edge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By early next year, Jemas said, the scenes will be accompanied
by voice-over narration in a style much like a recorded book. When
the first SpiderCams appear online at www.Marvel.com the only
sounds will be sound effects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other comic books online, often referred to as
cybercomics, to recapture young, male reader who may have migrated
to electronic entertainments like video games, many of which
feature comic book characters or their computer-animated
knock-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Jemas said he hoped that the new form will induce writers and
artists to invest their talents in the medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission here is to invite the best and the brightest from
other media to come into the comic book world,'' he said. Jemas
said he would like to say to screenwriters unable to get their
projects on movie screens, ``Here's a budget and go shoot your
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But producing a photo comic book is not as simple as it may
sound, said Philip Goetz, vice president of new media programming
for Marvel.
</P>
<P>
   Like an action film, each SpiderCam script is worked out on a
story board with scene-by-scene sketches. Actors and models are
cast and put in costumes. Location shooting, usually with a crew of
no more than a few people, takes about 10 days, Goetz said.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is shot with two Sony high-resolution digital, still
cameras, one automatic and the other manually operated. Hundreds of
pictures are taken, he said, but only about 150 will make it to the
finished episode.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest difficulties, Goetz said, is shooting still
scenes that give the reader a sense of action. In a traditional
comic book, action is often suggested by drawing characters frozen
in motion, or placing the reader at distorting vantage points, like
beneath a falling bad guy or in the direct path of a spray of
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   When similar techniques are used with flesh and blood models and
actors, the effect can be stilted, said Goetz and Tenney.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you shoot the actors in motion with a still camera you
get a lot of half-closed eyes and blurred limbs,'' Tenney said.
``What we do is try to set them up and make it as kinetic as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing he wants to see, Tenney said, is ``a lot of
people standing around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
