<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REACT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WILL MICROSOFT RULING HURT OR HELP CONSUMERS? EXPERTS DISAGREE
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge's decision to split Microsoft Corp.
into two parts left industry experts divided as well, with some
insisting that consumers will see lower software prices, and others
predicting fewer innovations and higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think prices will come down over time because Microsoft
will face more competition,'' said a jubilant Mark Cooper, director
of research for the Consumer Federation of America, a non-profit
group.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was guilty of ``plain old dirty business practices''
that will stop now, resulting in more and cheaper choices for
consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillard Sterling, an antitrust lawyer with a Chicago firm
that specializes in information technology cases, said U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ruling Wednesday would not
help consumers because Microsoft did nothing to harm them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts and law simply do not support such an extreme
judicial remedy,'' Sterling said. ``There is no evidence that a
breakup will lead to lower prices or more products.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve DelBianco, a spokesman for the Association for Competitive
Technology, a software trade group that includes Microsoft, said
the judge's ruling would actually hurt consumers. Computer shoppers
will see ``increased complexity, less innovation and higher
prices'' when software developers no longer can count on having
Microsoft's standardized operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions were divided, too, over what kind of changes might be
coming for Microsoft workers in light of the decision to break
their company into an operating systems business and an
applications business.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Bick, a Seattle resident and former Microsoft employee who
wrote the book ``All I Really Need to Know in Business I Learned at
Microsoft,'' said most employees are still assuming that the
breakup decision will be overturned by the U.S. Court of Appeals or
the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying, 'This is as bad as it's going to get,' ``
she said. ``They've known this ruling was coming, so now they feel,
'let's move to the next part of it' in the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than desert the company during this unsettled period,
Bick predicted Microsoft workers would remain loyal to Chairman
Bill Gates. ``I don't think anyone is going to leave now,'' she
said. ``This is just another step in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, immediately after the ruling, Gates issued a statement
announcing his company's intention to appeal, and declaring that
Wednesday's ruling was merely ``the beginning of a new chapter in
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   But while many Microsoft workers may like Gates's tough
attitude, at least one company analyst was dismayed. Carl D. Howe,
a Microsoft expert with Forrester Research in Boston, said it was
``time to ditch the appeal'' and start dividing the company.
</P>
<P>
   Howe said Gates is frittering away time and resources on
fighting the government, rather than helping workers, investors,
customers and consumers move on. When adversity comes to a
business, ``leaders stand up and get over it'' rather than wallow
in self-pity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the case drags out much longer, management's attention will
continue to be distracted, allowing other companies to get ahead of
Microsoft, he said. With a long appeal, ``even if you win, you
lose,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sterling said the judge's decision was so inappropriate that
Gates has a good chance of winning on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is making a reasonable judgement that this court
decision is vulnerable,'' he said. ``It's a sound strategy to fight
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
