<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7451 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-OBESE-KIDS-1STLD-WRIT     06-07 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBESE-KIDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOVERNMENT, GROUPS TEAM UP TO ATTACK CHILDHOOD OBESITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: ADDS the word ``by'' after eating habits in second
sentence, 7th graf)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If U.S. officials and major health organizations
have their way, french fries, pizza and colas will be banished from
school lunchrooms. Instead, students will be served more fruits,
vegetables, low-fat meats and low-sodium foods.
</P>
<P>
   With obesity rates of U.S. children at an all-time high, the
government and five health groups launched a program Wednesday to
stamp out most fast food, at least in schools.
</P>
<P>
   The groups and the Agriculture Department also urged an often a
slothful generation immobilized by the Internet, video games and
television to get more exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is imperative we do something to turn this situation around
for our children,'' said Shirley Watkins, under secretary of
agriculture for food and nutrition, at a news conference announcing
the food and exercise effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``School children are flunking healthy eating 101,'' said Dr.
Javette Orgain, president of the National Medical Association,
which represents African-American physicians. ``There is a national
epidemic of childhood obesity.''
</P>
<P>
   Orgain added that blacks have the highest obesity rates in the
country and that some inner city schools serve mainly
fast-food-type meals. In these schools, vegetables and fruits ``are
a rare sighting,'' Orgain said.
</P>
<P>
   The program to reverse the trend will start in many school
lunchrooms this summer. It seeks to promote healthy eating habits
by ensuring that school lunchrooms serve meals that include
selections from several of the five major food groups _ fruits,
vegetables, milk products, proteins (such as meat, fish or beans)
and the group that includes bread, rice, pasta and cereal.
</P>
<P>
   The program will encourage students, parents and school
administrators to push for dietary changes in the lunchrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Bagley, president of the American Academy of
Physicians, said obesity in school-age children has stark
ramifications for the future because many obese children will
develop heart disease, diabetes and other life-threatening ailments
later in life.
</P>
<P>
   The health organizations joining the Agriculture Department in
the obesity effort are the American Academy of Physicians, the
American Dietetic Association, the National Medical Association,
the National Hispanic Medical Association and the American Academy
of Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1970, about 6 percent of children aged 6 to 17 were
considered overweight. Now, nearly 15 percent of children 6 to 11
are overweight, and so are 12 percent of children 12 to 17.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 84 percent of high school students eat too much fat
and more than 91 percent eat too much saturated fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only one in five high-school students eats the recommended
five daily servings of fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   _ About half of students in grades K through 12 eat less than
one serving a day of fruit, and 29 percent eat less than one
serving a day of vegetables that are not fried.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Surgeon General's office, American
youngsters are increasingly sedentary. Nearly half of those aged 12
to 21 are not physically active on a regular basis. Only 19 percent
of high school students are physically active, and daily enrollment
in high school physical education classes has dropped from 42
percent in 1991 to 25 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Obesity is a severe problem in adults. The government estimates
that 300,000 deaths a year are directly attributable to poor diet
and physical inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
