<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-AIDS-AFRICA-0608-COX     06-07 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-AFRICA-0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Visionary' optimistic for AIDS war in Africa
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Billionaire philanthropist Bill Gates is mounting a
major effort to combat the seemingly inexorable spread of AIDS in
Africa with the help and advice of one of the world's foremost
experts on public health _ Dr. William Foege, a longtime Atlanta
resident.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation has committed $70
million to fight AIDS in Africa, but that is just the beginning,
Foege said in an interview this week. The figure could grow within
the next few weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the new figure will not reflect the foundation's full
commitment, Foege said. Some of the new grants may be for
preliminary studies, awarded with the presumption that greater sums
will follow once the planning has been done.
</P>
<P>
   The spread of aids in Africa has been, by any measure, a
catastrophe. Of the 33.6 million people around the world living
with HIV or AIDS, 23.3 million of them _ almost 70 percent of the
total _ live in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of the residents of Zimbabwe are
HIV-positive. In Mozambique, AIDS is expected by the year 2030 to
kill half of all those who are now 15 years old. In some countries,
HIV patients occupy up to 80 percent of the hospital beds in urban
areas, crowding out patients suffering from other diseases and
using up scarce health care resources.
</P>
<P>
   The disease has decimated the productive sector of the
population on a continent that can ill-afford any drag on economic
development. And it has left between 9 million and 12 million
African children orphaned.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Foege, who played an important role in the global
eradication of smallpox, is optimistic. One source of his optimism
is the experience in Uganda, a small East African country that has
managed over the last several years to reduce the incidence of HIV
infection in virtually all population groups, from military
recruits to secondary school students to expectant mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is light at the end of the tunnel,'' Foege said. ``The
continent does not necessarily have to wait for a vaccine before it
can do something. And I think this example has to give great hope
to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Foege, 64, (whose name is pronounced FAY-gy) has long experience
in public health issues. After working to eradicate smallpox, he
served from 1977 to 1984 as director of the Centers for Disease
Control. In 1984, he helped form the Task Force for Child Survival,
a group that worked _ with the World Health Organization, UNICEF,
the World Bank, the United Nations Development Program and the
Rockefeller Foundation _ to immunize children.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, he became executive director of the Carter Center.
Since 1997, he has taught international health at the Rollins
School of Public Health at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   And last fall, Foege was named the Gates Foundation's senior
global health adviser. He still works half-time at the Rollins
School, while spending the rest of his time advising the
Seattle-based foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, which was started by the
Microsoft founder and his wife, has assets of approximately $21.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Curran, dean of the Rollins School _ and also a former
acting director of the CDC's Division of HIV/AIDS Prevention and a
former assistant U.S. surgeon general _ said the Gates Foundation
could hardly have done better than Foege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has been, in my view, perhaps, if not the most
influential, certainly one of the most influential figures in
international public health of the last half-century.'' Curran
said. ``I think it's a credit to them that they looked around and
found him and convinced him to work on this.''
</P>
<P>
   That view is shared by Dr. John Hardman, who succeeded Foege as
executive director of the Carter Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is such a visionary,'' Hardman said, ``and I think that
he brings that vision to the Gates foundation.'' By focusing on the
goals, Hardman said, Foege convinces diverse groups to drop their
separate agendas and work together.
</P>
<P>
   Foege said the foundation's effort to fight AIDS in Africa
probably will have six components:
</P>
<P>
   An effort to use the facilities and resources already in Africa
to provide comprehensive treatment. That would include _ ``in a
single package,'' Foege said _ testing, counseling, prevention,
treatment of secondary infections, treatment of sexually
transmitted diseases, treatment of tuberculosis, the interruption
of transmission between mother and child, and the use of anti-viral
medications.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to determine how to replicate the experience of Uganda
in reducing the rate of HIV infection. Uganda, Foege said, had the
fortunate combination of a head of state, President Yoweri
Museveni, who took a
</P>
<P>
   Yoweri Museveni, who took a direct interest in fighting AIDS,
and many governmental and non-governmental organizations that stood
ready to help. The CDC is already working on a project to replicate
the Ugandan experience in 14 other African countries. The Gates
Foundation is examining the possibility of working with the CDC in
those countries, and of working with other organizations _ such as
UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS organization _ in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   A concentration on prevention, perhaps learning from the example
of Senegal, which Foege said is often used as an example of ``a
country that has made the right moves to keep transmission rates
low.''
</P>
<P>
   An effort to reduce transmission from mothers to children during
childbirth, perhaps through the administration of inexpensive drugs
at the end of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   A look at what tools could be given to women to help them reduce
their risk of contracting HIV. This would include, Foege said, the
use of ``microbicidal agents.''
</P>
<P>
   A program to help the continent's AIDS orphans, whose number
Foege put at 12 million.
</P>
<P>
   So far, initial funding has been approved for two of those six
components _ the comprehensive treatment program and the effort to
reduce transmission of AIDS from mothers to their children. But
other grant requests may be approved soon, Foege said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the successful campaign to eradicate smallpox,
Foege has been involved in efforts to eradicate polio and Guinea
worm. He realizes that combating the spread of AIDS in Africa is a
daunting task. Turning the corner was not easy in Uganda, and it
will be difficult, too, in the rest of Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about concentrated, labor-intensive work,'' he
said. But the work can be accomplished, he said. The goal is not
beyond reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``UNAIDS has estimated it might take as much as $3 billion a
year for the rest of Africa,'' he said. ``And while that sounds
like an impossible figure, I keep reminding people that that's what
we spend on health in this country every day. So you have to have
that perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
