<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7454 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-07 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TOO MUCH IN TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Greta Garbo, playing the depressed ballerina
Grusinskaya in the 1932 movie ``Grand Hotel,'' discovered a jewel
thief in her room and delivered what became her signature line: ``I
vant to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm with Garbo. What with cell phones and palm pilots and
satellite-controlled pagers and messagers, the world is too much
with us. In our lust to be in constant hand-held communication, we
fritter away our long-held value of personal freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, if you are lost on a rainy night, a car phone is a
blessing. If you are trying to file copy from remote Chechnya, a
link in hand via satellite offers an escape hatch for truth. And if
you are stuck in traffic and late for a family party or a crucial
meeting, the wireless gizmos enable you to signal, as did General
Sherman atop Kenesaw Mountain: ``Hold the fort! I am coming!''
</P>
<P>
   But use in emergencies does not account for the cellumania that
has fastened itself to our ears and belts. Something more troubling
is at its root. Too many of us are gripped by the fear of being
alone. If we are not in demand round the clock, goes this worry, we
don't count.
</P>
<P>
   That mass separation anxiety is driven by a curious culture that
demands we all form a circle and hold hands. If you are out of
pocket, you are considered to be somewhat out to lunch. If you are
off the scope, society thinks you must be off your rocker.
Detachment is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The individual's normal desire to stay in touch has, with a
shove from technology, led to society's relentless pressure never
to be out of touch. As a result, the world is too much with us; we
lay waste our power to be by ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Is the tintinnabulation of bells at restaurants and in theaters
suddenly turning me into some kind of hermit? No; three decades ago
I rejected the earliest electronic pager. At a Moscow summit
meeting, President Nixon's aides were issued this invention by
which the chief executive could reach his entire staff at all times
and in all places.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of staff, H.R. Haldeman, demanded to know why I was
the only one to refuse to wear the new pager. I replied that I did
not want to feel like a dog on a leash. He shook his head, but made
a beckoning motion with his fingers, as if to say: Couldn't I come
up with a better reason than privacy?
</P>
<P>
   So I lied. The sound and vibration of the pager on my belt, I
offered, would give me an urgent desire to urinate. He nodded and
took back the pager: ``You have a medical excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that wirelessness is next to godliness, what excuses can we
come up with to slip today's electronic leashes?
</P>
<P>
   Forget courtesy, civility, concern for others around you; those
old-fashioned reasons are blown away by the new info-age necessity
for constant contact. See that couple in a restaurant, each talking
on a cell phone to someone else? For us to insist they talk only to
each other would take the steam out of their self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, consider the cell phone's destruction of the wall
between work and leisure. Used to be, when you went to work, you
worked; when you commuted, you thought about working or planned
about playing; and when you got home, you could forget work and
make whoopee.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even when you are cultivating your garden, you are on call
and on edge; and when you are whispering into your hand at work,
your boss wonders if you may be playing. As differentiation frays,
stress builds; life becomes a blur, and where there is no real
recreation, there is little creation.
</P>
<P>
   When a friend is late for an appointment, what do cellumaniacs
do? They call to see what's the delay, or scroll furiously through
their palm organizers to fill the unforgiving minutes. Not me; I
stare at the wall, see beautiful shapes in memory, have a
conversation with myself, maybe dream up a column. Ten unexpected
minutes for contemplation is not an insult; it can be a gift.
</P>
<P>
   When Garbo said, ``I vant to be alone,'' the jewel thief, played
by John Barrymore, replied, ``Let me stay just for a little
while.'' Garbo murmured, ``Just for a minute, then,'' and was
seduced.
</P>
<P>
   Savor occasional solitude. Don't give in to cellumania. Not for
a minute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
