<HEADLINE>
FAST-TRACK COULD SPEED APPEALS PROCESS FOR MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The appeals process for the Microsoft case could be wrapped up
by Christmas or drag on until the summer of 2002 _ depending
entirely on whether the Supreme Court agrees to hear the case on a
fast-track basis, legal specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the US Justice Department indicated Wednesday that
they will seek to put the case directly before the Supreme Court,
invoking a fast-track statute first passed by Congress in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   The nine Supreme Court justices will then entertain arguments
from both sides as to why they should hear the case without it
first going to the US Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia. The justices could agree to hear the case because it is
of such enormous public importance, or they could insist that it
get more thorough lower-court review first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Supreme Court takes the case they would hear it in the
fall, and they could resolve this by Christmas,'' said Lawrence
Lessig professor at Harvard University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   If the case gets kicked back to the appeals court, Lessig said,
a ruling wouldn't be likely there until early 2001. That would mean
it would be fall of 2001 before the case went back before the
Supreme Court, and the summer of 2002 before a Supreme Court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of whether to hear the case now, ``the court is
going to be pulled in two directions,'' said Larry Kramer,
professor at New York University Law School. ``The economy turns on
this case in some ways. You have the 800-pound gorilla in the
emerging industry where most of America's economic growth lies.
There is pressure to eliminate the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, the issues are complicated, and the Supreme
Court always likes to have as many lower court opinions as they
can. They are usually not in a hurry,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyers have complained that the rapid pace of
industry change and increased competition in the marketplace have
rendered the government's case irrelevant. But now that US District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson has issued his ruling, the company's
new strategy is likely to call for more deliberation and no quick
action.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Microsoft would vastly prefer that the D.C.
appeals court hear the case before it goes to the Supreme Court,
legal experts say. Company lawyers would hope that appellate judges
would overturn Jackson's ruling, giving the case a different spin
by the time it arrived back at the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyers will probably argue that the lower court
should get a shot at the case before the Supreme Court justices
take on such hugely complicated issues, specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Microsoft violated antitrust standards in
linking its Windows operating system and other software such as
Microsoft Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   There is no precedent to help predict the fate of the Microsoft
case at this stage in the process. The breakup of Standard Oil
occurred before the Supreme Court had the option to decline to hear
such cases. The AT&AMP;T breakup case did bypass the appellate court
and go directly to the Supreme Court, but only technical issues
were in dispute at that point.
</P>
<P>
   The juncture that the Microsoft case has reached ``is very
rare,'' said Thane D. Scott, head of the antitrust group at the
Boston law firm of Palmer &AMP; Dodge. ``You really can't read the tea
leaves from the AT&AMP;T case.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time major issues involving antitrust law have
been sent via the expediting law to the Supreme Court, since the
justices got the option in the early '70s to decline to hear
fast-tracked cases, Scott said. The court sought that option in an
effort to clear its docket.
</P>
<P>
   The next round of legal arguments in the case will center on
these issues of process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arguments for hearing the case right away are: The case is
going to end up there anyway, it's of significant public importance
and it's time-sensitive,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arguments against accepting are that the Supreme Court is
the last stop, and it's very important that a correct result be
achieved. The best way for that to happen is to let the D.C.
circuit court process the facts and the legal issues, and give the
Supreme Court something sophisticated to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft itself will also be torn, some experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a purely legal question, delay is a good thing for
Microsoft,'' said Scott. ``From the perspective of their
shareholders and employees, delay may not be a good thing,'' and it
may be more important just to get the matter resolved, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
