<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-LAW-ART-NYT     06-07 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-LAW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLYING LONG-ESTABLISHED LEGAL PRINCIPLES TO A NEW WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST)  
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Possession of unchallenged economic power deadens
initiative, discourages thrift and depresses energy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Immunity from competition is a narcotic, and rivalry a
stimulant, to industrial progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson in June 2000 ordering the breakup
of Microsoft? No, Judge Learned Hand declaring in 1945 that the
Aluminum Company of America had illegally monopolized the market
for a type of aluminum ingot.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has changed since 1945, the exact midpoint between the
passage of the Sherman Antitrust Act in 1890 and the Microsoft
ruling Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   An economy based on heavy industry and capital investment has
transformed itself into one based more and more on human capital
and information technology where ``it's pretty hard to figure out
what the markets are and what really competes with what,'' as
Thomas E. Kauper, a former government antitrust chief who now
teaches antitrust law at the University of Michigan, noted
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as Wednesday's ruling demonstrates dramatically,
the old factories may be obsolete, but the legal principles that
led to the breakup of the Standard Oil trust in 1911 and the
American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. in 1984 are not.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions and priorities have changed, naturally enough. When
oil and tobacco trusts loomed over the economic landscape, the
perceived enemy was price fixing, while in the government's theory
of the Microsoft case, adopted by Jackson, the enemy is the ability
of a predatory monopolist to strangle innovation.
</P>
<P>
   But from a broader perspective, these are simply different ways
to measure a monopolist's threat to consumer welfare, the
protection of which was the ultimate goal of antitrust enforcement
in the old economy and remains so in the new. There is no reason
why the old rules should not apply in the software-driven new
economy, Joel I. Klein, the assistant attorney general for
antitrust, has insisted throughout the case.
</P>
<P>
   Simply attaining monopoly status in a given market, by being
quicker out of the starting gate, or more creative or diligent than
the competition, does not itself violate antitrust law. As Hand
said in the Alcoa case 55 years ago, ``The successful competitor,
having been urged to compete, must not be turned upon when he
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, portraying itself as a victim of antitrust policy run
amok, has long argued that the government was turning on it in
exactly that way. Jackson disagreed. Microsoft's offense, he held,
lay not in the fact that its Windows operating system runs 90
percent of the world's personal computers, but in the methods the
company used to maintain and try to extend its monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Jackson found that Microsoft mounted a campaign of dirty
tricks, and the dirty tricks are old tricks,'' said Robert E.
Litan, director of economic studies at the Brookings Institution,
who served in the Justice Department's antitrust division earlier
in the Clinton Administration. In an interview, he continued:
``John D. Rockefeller used them all: exclusive contracting,
throwing your weight around, scaring off the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust cases have two dimensions: liability and, if liability
is found, a remedy. While on the liability side, there is a
straight line leading from the earliest antitrust cases to
Wednesday's ruling, Jackson's approved remedy _ breaking Microsoft
in two _ arguably moves the case toward uncharted territory.
</P>
<P>
   Monopolies have been broken up before, of course, either by
court order, as in the old Standard Oil case, or by negotiated
settlement, as in the AT&AMP;T case. But the earlier breakups or
divestitures were along fairly obvious lines.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's own corporate structure reflected the division between
long distance service, which it kept in the breakup, and local
telephone service, which was spun off. Microsoft's chairman, Bill
Gates, repeated Wednesday, as he has in the past, that there was no
precedent for breaking up a ``unitary'' company such as his.
``We're unique,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To assess the wisdom of the remedy in the Microsoft case, which
the government sought and which Microsoft strenuously resisted,
requires a set of subtle judgments and just plain guesses about the
environment for Internet-based information and a technology market
that even during the two years of the Microsoft trial has evolved
with surprising speed away from the desktop and toward wireless,
hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   It also involves, to a degree that no other antitrust case has,
questions about maintaining the country's leadership in the global
economy. Of all the earlier antitrust cases, only the AT&AMP;T case
came close to having such global implications. ``If we had left
AT&AMP;T where it was, we'd have a stodgy, non-dynamic
telecommunications world today, and we'd never even know what we
were missing,'' said Harvey J. Goldschmid, an antitrust professor
at Columbia Law School, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years further into the information revolution, the
global implications of gambling wrong on the Microsoft remedy are
even greater, given the dominance that Microsoft's success has
meant for the United States. While the government's economic
experts have dismissed the warnings of Gates that efficiency and
synergy will be lost by cleaving the Windows operating system from
the software applications, the fact is that nobody knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Charles D. Weller, an antitrust specialist at the Cleveland law
firm of Baker &AMP; Hostetler, commented Wednesday that under the
Supreme Court's current skeptical view of expert testimony _ a view
the justices have applied in negligence cases but not yet directly
to antitrust cases _ the economists who testified on both sides
should have been disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up Microsoft ``is not like breaking up two factories,''
Goldschmid said. ``A breakup may well be the appropriate remedy,''
he added, ``but the tough part is that there is a heavy investment
in human capital, and breaking up Microsoft means changing things
for a lot of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
