<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7460 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-EAR-BUDS-ART-(2TA     06-07 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EAR-BUDS-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW TOY: THE PHONE YOU CAN'T SEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 3,4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was Thursday at rush hour on the street in front
of Grand Central Terminal, and it was a cell phone circus.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it was predictable. People walking with phones to their
cheeks, others leaning against buildings, plugging their ears
against the sounds of trucks, buses and sirens, shouting above the
din.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing unusual, except for one young man, carrying his portable
CD player, no cell phone in sight, who seemed to be having an
animated conversation with himself. It was another common city
sight, except that his words were completely comprehensible, as if
he were talking to a real person, not some imaginary adversary. In
fact, he was discussing the virtues of ESPN Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Meet a new breed of cell phone user: a small but growing number
of mobile talkers who have decided to put down their phones and
plug in to accessories that enable them to go hands free. Tiny ear
pieces and microphones are now spotted dangling next to cheeks.
Many drivers are adopting slightly bulkier headsets or using a
barely visible microphone and speaker mounted in the car.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, people in large cities, in particular, will soon
face another round of weird social behavior stemming from cell
phone use. Just a few years ago, handheld cell phones elicited
stares and whispers, especially in public areas like airports and
coffee shops.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just as we have grown accustomed to the sight of people
standing on street corners screaming into pieces of plastic and as
we struggle to develop cell phone etiquette, wearable phones have
arrived to complicate matters. ``Cell phones have started to become
socially accepted,'' said Phil Hester, chief technology officer at
IBM's personal systems group. ``These ear buds are pushing it to
the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man with the CD player was Davis Macias, a college
student, who had his phone attached to his belt, a microphone
clipped to his shirt and an earphone in his left ear. He was
talking to a friend on 67th street who was walking to work wearing
the same kind of contraption.
</P>
<P>
   So far, of course, most people do not wear their phones. The
proportion of Americans buying headsets is under 5 percent. But
that number has been rising for two years, according to recent
survey results from the International Data Corp. And if users in
countries with more cell phones can be a guide, the number of
people getting around with wearable phones will continue to go up.
</P>
<P>
   In London, ``you can walk around the city and see people using
them everywhere,'' said Jim Moore, a consultant for McKinsey &AMP; Co.
who recently lived in Europe and who would not even think about
using a handheld cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Moore adopted a headset to avoid the ache of holding up the
phone. Others, interviewed on the streets of Manhattan, said they
had heard that holding cell phones to the head causes brain tumors
(So far, the Food and Drug Administration has said that such risks
cannot be confirmed nor ruled out.) And most simply liked being
able to use both hands while chatting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so convenient,'' said Wilson Ortega, who wore a
headset as he stood in line at a midtown Starbucks last week. When
a cell phone rang inside the pocket of his baggy jeans, he took a
peek at the phone, slid it back into his pocket and said a soft
hello into a microphone hanging by his face.
</P>
<P>
   How the new technology will fit into the current cell phone
confusion is not clear. People already complain about the rude
intrusions of ringing cell phones in movie theaters and the
annoyance of hearing one side of someone's extended phone
conversation while sitting on the bus heading home. And that is
when they are prepared by the sight of the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Social scientists say much of the consternation is caused by the
blurring of the lines between public and private spaces _ lines
that will become even fuzzier as phones are not only taken
everywhere, but are also worn everywhere, for easy access at any
time. The Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association says
that more than 92 million people now have mobile phone service in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of work and home is already largely gone,'' said
Philip E. Agre, a professor of information studies at the
University of California at Los Angeles. The same principle, Agre
said in an interview via his cell phone (though not a wearable
one), can be extended to spaces like cars and sidewalks. As he
stood in a Los Angeles taco bar, he managed to order a burrito and
talk on the phone at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling self-conscious about those blurring lines, people using
cell phones are trying to find ways to achieve privacy in public,
often while still holding conversations a decibel above the norm. A
woman on 6th Avenue and 43rd Street last Thursday, for example,
held a phone to her face using one hand and held a crumpled tissue
in the other. She had turned her tear-stained face to the wall of
the building. Nearby, a man stepped into an alley just before
screaming obscenities into his cell phone, words that could still
be heard with remarkable clarity many steps away.
</P>
<P>
   Wearers of headsets and ear pieces may need to create social
cues of a different sort. They need signals that let others know
when they are talking to people who are nowhere to be seen and when
they have come down to earth to interact with the people around
them.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Barnwell, who works at the Starbucks at 44th Street and
Lexington Avenue, said she was once trying to make sense of a
customer's confusing order when he stopped in midsentence and said,
``Hold on, I'm in Starbucks.'' Then he made a comprehensible
request for a drink and shifted back into his former conversation,
without any external sign that he was on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
