<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-NOTPACIFIC0608-COX     06-07 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTPACIFIC0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Political storms haunt South Pacific
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The tropical nations of Fiji and the Solomon Islands
evoke images of of warm nights, swaying palms and sandy beaches
bordered by Pacific waters.
</P>
<P>
   The official Fiji Web site boasts about an ``ideal South Sea
tropical climate'' and calls the country ``a perfect holiday
destination.''
</P>
<P>
   The official Web site of the Solomon Islands touts the country's
``pristine sandy beaches, butterflies as big as birds, rare
orchids,'' not to mention ``some of the friendliest people in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But the political waters in these two South Pacific nations have
been anything but pacific lately.
</P>
<P>
   In Fiji, rebels have been holding the prime minister and about
three dozen other people hostage for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And in the Solomon Islands on Tuesday, some of the friendliest
people in the world strafed a plane carrying two British mediators
who were fleeing the country, as fighting between rival groups
intensified and truckloads of armed teenagers cruised streets. On a
positive note, rebels released that country's prime minister
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries, both of which lie northeast of Australia, are
tiny. Their combined population is about 1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But they are home nonetheless to ethnically diverse populations
_ and those ethnic differences have led to the current unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Fiji, which is 2,250 miles northeast of Sydney,
Australia, erupted May 19. A bankrupt, part-Fijian businessman
named George Speight, proclaiming that he was acting in the name of
all indigenous Fijians, stormed the parliamentary compound in Suva
with a small group of armed followers and took three dozen people
captive, including Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, the first
ethnic Indian to hold that post in Fiji's history.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Indians make up about 44 percent of the country's
population. Speight and his followers want them banned from holding
office.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crisis began, the military, led by army Commodore
Frank Bainimarama, has taken power, revoked the constitution and
tried to negotiate with Speight. But the hostages are still being
held.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Speight warned the military to expect serious
reprisals if soldiers shoot at his gunmen. His threat came after a
burst of automatic gunfire around Fiji's parliament complex, where
the hostages are being held.
</P>
<P>
   But the unrest posed few problems for a mission group of about a
dozen people from the Campus View Church of Christ in Athens, Ga.,
said Owen Tingle, 21, a rising senior at the University of Georgia
who made the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Some buidings in Suva had been burned in riots, some shops were
boarded up and a curfew prevented the group from conducting evening
Bible study sessions, Tingle said. But the group, which spent two
weeks in Fiji and returned May 31, never felt in danger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people down there seemed real cheerful and happy,'' he
said. ``Their main thing down there is tourism, and they were real
worried about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Solomon Islands, 1,600 miles northeast of Sydney, the
tension is between natives of different islands.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis eased Wednesday as rebels from Malaita island
released Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu from house arrest and
dropped demands that he resign, but violence on Guadalcanal grew.
</P>
<P>
   The indigenous Istabu have been fighting to force the Malaitans
off Guadalcanal, the largest of the Solomon Islands, and the place
where U.S. Marines in 1942-43 began the long fight back against
Japan after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known which group _ the rebel Malaita Eagle Force or
the Istabu Freedom Movement _ fired on the plane carrying British
politicians Glenys Kinnock and John Corrie, members of the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnock, the wife of European Union official Neil Kinnock, said
the situation ``became completely lawless'' after Monday's coup
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police just seemed to concede to the gunmen of the Malaita
Eagle Force under Andrew Nori. There were armed men roaming around
with home-made weapons, and the streets were blocked and the
airport closed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels fought around the capital Wednesday, and stranded
foreigners reported seeing truckloads of armed teenagers cruising
Honiara's streets.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Malaitan spokesman, Nori, said his forces
fired from a stolen police gunboat on a rival rebel group on a
beach, killing 100. Nori said his comrades on the ground watched
from about 60 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   While the coup, in which the Malaita Eagle Force seized the
prime minister, took place Monday, the two groups have been
fighting over Guadalcanal for months.
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 people have been killed or left missing in recent
fighting, and 20,000 have been forced to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
