<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7462 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-EAR-BUDS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-07 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EAR-BUDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the phone.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think people may have a strong reaction to people wearing
these things all over the place,'' said Susan Squires, an
anthropologist who is studying variations in cell-phone behavior
for GVO, a product-research company in Palo Alto, Calif. Society
will have to learn that wearers of ear pieces are not people who,
as Squires delicately put it, ``are having auditory
hallucinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ear bud and microphone users sometimes try to signal to others
that they are on the phone, putting the handset on a restaurant
table in full view, for example, or holding the microphone wire as
they walk, no longer, strictly speaking, hands-free. Jon Geist, a
guitar teacher who was recently spotted walking around wearing his
phone, said he thinks people are getting used to the sight of him
involved in conversation. ``I usually just smile as if to say, look
I'm not a lunatic, I'm on the telephone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other earbud users retain some of the unconscious,
privacy-seeking behavior that they learned from using a regular
cell phone: At Grand Central Terminal a few weeks ago, a management
consultant from Boulder, Colo., named Sandy Keziah had turned away
from the crowds to use his hands-free system. He leaned his
shoulder against a marble wall as he began to speak, his face so
close to the cool surface he could have kissed it.
</P>
<P>
   Wearable phones will also have to pass the trendiness test
before they gain popularity in the United States. Which is more of
a status symbol: wearing tiny ear buds and a gadget on your waist
or carrying a phone that all can see? In New York, among the
hundreds of stylish and toned 20-somethings who gathered at an
outdoor cafe in Union Square on a recent Thursday evening, not one
could be seen wearing a headset or ear piece. Almost all had a cell
phone in hand, thumb often poised to hit the Talk button to take a
call.
</P>
<P>
   Among younger crowds, however, Squires sees some hints that
hands-free cell phones may catch on. Her research among American
teen-agers has shown that many of them are not happy with the idea
of constantly carrying a cell phone, because it reminds them of
their lack of time spent talking face to face with Mom and Dad, who
are often on their phones while transporting their children. ``They
see the cell phone as business-oriented and cutting into their
ability to interact with their parents,'' Squires said. So if the
phone were ``disguised'' or designed as something to be worn, she
said, it might be more palatable to the future cell phone set.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, she said, if a day arrives when earphones for music
are meshed with ear buds for cell phones, teen-agers will probably
adopt them in droves. Since cell phones are already being sold with
Web access, and MP3 music files are shared on the Web, that
combination may not be far away.
</P>
<P>
   For Macias, the college student strolling around Grand Central
last week, it could not come soon enough. While the ear bud for his
cell phone was in his left ear, his right ear was occupied as well.
It held an earphone that connected him to the silver CD player in
his hands. ``I'm listening to Eminem's new album, but I can still
be on the phone,'' he said, grinning. Then he turned and headed up
Lexington Avenue, his head full of hip-hop rhymes, remote
conversations and maybe the faint rhythm of the city rumbling by.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
