<P>
   SUDAN-SLAVERY (Boston) _ Former Sudanese slave is enlisting
people into a movement to stop the age-old practice, still
occurring in parts of Africa. By Charles A. Radin. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PROZAC-SUICIDE (Undated) _ Opening a new front in the battle
over Prozac and suicide, the family of a man who killed his wife
then himself while taking the antidepressant accuses Eli Lilly and
Co. of fraud for allegedly concealing damaging details about Prozac
contained in a patent for a new form of the drug. By Mitchell
Zuckoff. 1000 words. (a and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-DECISION (Undated) _ Federal judge issues antitrust
remedies that would split Microsoft into two companies: one making
the Windows operating system for personal computers and the second
making applications and running other multi-platform Internet
businesses. Microsoft is expected to appeal. By Peter Howe. 1500
words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MISCROSOFT-ANALYSIS (Undated) _ Judge's formal decision to break
up Microsoft will have a far-reaching impact on the company and the
technology industry. By Hiawatha Bray. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-APPEAL (Undated) _ The appeals process for the
Microsoft case could be wrapped up by Christmas or drag on until
the summer of 2002 -- depending entirely on whether the Supreme
Court agrees to hear the case on a fast-track basis. By Anthony
Flint. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REACT (San Jose, Calif.) _ Microsoft's enemies in
Silicon Valley, including the companies that championed the Justice
Department's case against Microsoft, react to the decision to split
the company. By Alex Pham. 700 words.
</P>
