<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: WHAT MICROSOFT CAN DO TO GET THE PUBLIC ON ITS SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Microsoft Corp. assesses the implications of the breakup
ordered Wednesday by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, the advice from
professional communicators on how the company ought to handle the
consequences is being offered almost as quickly as the ``I Love
You'' computer worm infested e-mail in-boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft ``should turn it into a political issue and go right
over the heads of the politicians and appeal to their bosses: the
taxpayers, the voters,'' said Richard Laermer, chief executive at
RLM Public Relations in New York, which represents several
technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it could be the `Isn't that what America is all about?'
angle, free enterprise, the melting pot, opportunity,'' he added,
``and it becomes emotional. Pull the heartstrings, and keep
positioning Microsoft as the underdog against the mean guys.
Everyone roots for the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   But could Microsoft be successfully spun as an underdog?
</P>
<P>
   ``In an environment where everyone is so cynical about
Microsoft,'' the public perceives the company's leaders ``as
insincere, even though I don't believe they are,'' said Trish
Adams, account director at Wieden &AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore. She
worked on the Microsoft account when Wieden &AMP; Kennedy was a
principal Microsoft agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than use Microsoft's top managers to respond to the
ruling, Adams said, ``I'd be much more likely to put more `real
people' on the air: the people who are the workhorses, the people
who really believe in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having worked with them, I know those people still see
themselves as working for a small, scrappy company,'' she added,
``and believe what they do is best for consumers. The other
approach would do more damage than good.''
</P>
<P>
   Some executives, however, said they thought no amount of spin
control could overcome Microsoft's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's a bit late,'' said Chris Wall, executive
creative director on the IBM account at the New York office of
Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, part of the WPP Group. ``You can't undo
years of neglect with a couple of ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives ``have tried in fits and starts to humanize
their image,'' Wall said _ referring to steps like having Bill
Gates, the company's chairman, appear on television programs and in
commercials _ ``but they have not been terribly evangelical'' in
disseminating their point of view, and ``a `take no prisoners'
attitude is coming back to bite them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall, who was creative director on the Microsoft account at
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, said he admired the company because when ``it got
powerful, it didn't get fat but kept focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Microsoft has not made a compelling public case for what
is the truth,'' he asserted, ``that it works in an industry fueled
by change and innovation and in a way it is under threat now more
than ever, from Unix and Linux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple Computer has shown that you can be very focused on
margins and at the same time project a benevolent image,'' Wall
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Microsoft should talk to Steve Jobs,'' he added,
referring to the Apple co-founder and chief executive. That would
not be too difficult to arrange; Microsoft owns a small stake in
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens, Bill Gates should become a student of
Richard Nixon,'' said Ed Gyurko, president at Smart P.R. in New
York, an agency specializing in technology clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon was pilloried,'' Gyurko said, recalling the resignation
in the face of impeachment over Watergate, ``but then he redeemed
himself and carved out a new role as a pundit and statesman.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates ``could become a guru for business,'' Gyurko suggested,
``taking what he does best and reversing the bad karma.''
</P>
<P>
   What might Microsoft actually do in the wake of the antitrust
ruling? Its current agency, McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L, which replaced
Wieden &AMP; Kennedy on the account, is mum for now.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Alter, a spokesman in New York for McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L,
declined to comment on what plans were being formulated. The agency
is part of the McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising unit of the
McCann-Erickson World Group; McCann-Erickson is owned by the
Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   The trade publication Advertising Age reported this week that
Microsoft executives were considering ``at least half a dozen
advertising possibilities to react immediately'' to the ruling. The
options include television commercials, according to the report,
that would feature Microsoft senior managers or customers offering
testimonials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
