<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-HIRES0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After dramatic layoffs, Coke is making hires
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After months of letting thousands of employees go,
Coca-Cola is hiring again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a moratorium on hiring through the realignment process,
which concluded at the end of April,'' Coca-Cola spokesman Ben
Deutsch said Wednesday. ``We've begun some hiring, primarily
filling positions held by people who voluntarily left the company
or retired, as well as new positions created as a result of our
reorganization.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch would not comment on the number of positions that are
being filled, but it is believed to be in the hundreds. He also
would not comment on the types of positions.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Bernstein analyst Bill Pecoriello said the company is
likely to be beefing up its hiring of employees who will be fueling
future growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is picking up the pace of innovation and Internet
marketing,'' Pecoriello said. ``They're probably bringing in some
new, young talent with new, young thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pecoriello also expects Coca-Cola to hire employees to work on
boosting sales of the company's noncarbonated beverages _ including
water, teas, juice drinks and sports drinks _ in the wake of the
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 26, the company announced a major reorganization to
result in the loss of 6,000 jobs around the world, including 2,500
in Atlanta. Then in April, it reduced the worldwide number to
5,200.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts have been accomplished through layoffs, attrition,
early retirements and outsourcing of work to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Former human resources manager Larry Jones said he believes the
company is trying to fill ``several hundred vacancies'' right now.
Jones, who was laid off in February, and about a dozen other people
protested Wednesday outside Coke's headquarters in support of a
boycott aimed at pressuring the company into settling a racial
discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
