<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APTITUDE SEEN AS SMART PICK AT BELMONT STAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No Fusaichi Pegasus. No Red Bullet. Where's the
glamor in Saturday's 132d running of the Belmont Stakes? Well, take
a look at Aptitude.
</P>
<P>
   Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus may have been knocked out with an
injured hoof and Preakness winner Red Bullet may have been held out
by cautious connections, but Aptitude, established Wednesday as the
8-5 morning-line favorite, is very talented and should make it a
Belmont worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude, a son of 1992 Belmont winner and Horse of the Year
A.P. Indy, is royally bred for the 1 1/2-mile Test of the Champion.
In addition to his sire's accomplishments, his dam, Dokki, who is
by Northern Dancer, is related to both Coastal, who won the '79
Belmont, and Slew O'Gold, who ran second to Caveat in '83.
</P>
<P>
   Having captured only a maiden race, it may seem surprising that
Aptitude is so highly regarded. However, he stamped himself as
legitimate when he ran a strong second in the Kentucky Derby under
Alex Solis in only the sixth start of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Frankel, who trains Aptitude for Juddmonte Farms, then
held the dark bay out of the Preakness. He believes he'll turn a
tiger loose Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missing the Preakness gives him a big edge,'' said Frankel.
``My horse needed the break. He ran really hard in the Derby. I
knew before the race that if he didn't win the Derby, we'd wait for
the Belmont. All along, if you look at his pedigree, I thought my
best chance was to win the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude, who is 1-3-1 in six races, made his first two starts
on the turf as a 2-year-old because he didn't train well. Aptitude
went well over the lawn, but did not win, running sixth (beaten by
just 2 lengths) and second. On Jan. 1, he started on the dirt, came
from seventh to tally, and was on his way. Prior to the Derby,
Frankel shipped him to Aqueduct, where he finished second in the
Gotham, behind Red Bullet, and third in the Wood Memorial, behind
Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was slow coming around,'' said Frankel. ``I didn't know he
was a Triple Crown horse untill we raced him on the dirt and he
began to improve. He never seems to get tired at the end. He's
always trying right to the finish. We stayed out of the Preakness
because we didn't want to train him back in two weeks with nothing
to gain. Why bury the horse to win two out of three? Now, if you
could win all three, that would be a different thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My horse is not a big, strong horse. He's a good doer, but I
didn't want to jeopardize his chance in the Belmont by running in
the Preakness. I'm sure there'll be an honest pace up front, but my
horse is not a plodder. He's got a quick turn of foot. If it's a
slow pace, he'll drop back. Otherwise, he'll be right up there.
We'll just let him run his race.''
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude worked 6 furlongs Sunday in 1:15 1/5 at Hollywood Park
with Solis aboard. Frankel reported he finished strong after a
leisurely start. The horse was shipped to Belmont Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he'll win the Belmont,'' said Frankel. ``Then we'll
give him some time off and look toward the Haskell (Aug. 6 at
Monmouth) and the Travers (Aug. 26 at Saratoga). Then comes the
Breeders' Cup (at Churchill Downs Nov. 4).''
</P>
<P>
   Those are ambitious plans for a horse who has won just one race.
But don't be surprised if Aptitude fits the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
