A7469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WWII-JEWISH-CHILDREN-     06-07 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-JEWISH-CHILDREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANDLE OF HEROISM IN FRANCE'S DARK NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ With France gradually and painfully reassessing its
record during Germany's wartime occupation, Resistance myths have
given way to deep discomfiture over the collaborationist Vichy
regime's role in sending 76,000 Jews to Nazi death camps. And yet
the very process of investigating a dark past has uncovered points
of light, stories that are not only morally uplifting but also help
to explain why at least 250,000 Jews survived World War II in
France.
</P>
<P>
   One such point of light was a chateau in the village of
Chabannes in the Creuse region of central France, where from 1939
to 1943 some 400 Jewish children found a safe haven. Their
protectors were local teachers and villagers as well as Communist
and Jewish activists, all working under the leadership of a portly
former journalist, Felix Chevrier, who in his own way believed he
was defending French honor.
</P>
<P>
   The moving story of this unlikely community has now been rescued
in a documentary, ``The Children of Chabannes,'' which is to open
on Friday at the Quad Cinema in Greenwich Village and will be shown
several times this month on the HBO Signature channel, beginning on
Sunday night at 7:30. As with many other newly revealed instances
of French valor in face of Nazi terror, it is principally those
saved who are doing the remembering. Chevrier himself died an
unsung hero in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Gossels, a New Yorker who produced, directed and edited
this film with Dean Wetherall, did not have to look far for the
story: her father, Peter, and her uncle, Werner, both born in
Berlin and sent to the presumed safety of France in July 1939, were
children of Chabannes until 1941, when, at ages 11 and 8 they were
sent by Quakers to the United States. Their mother died at
Auschwitz. ``My father does not consider himself a survivor because
he was not in a camp, but he survived the war thanks to the
French,'' Gossels said in a telephone interview from New York. ``It
is not something he talked about a lot. It was not part of our
daily existence. Yet in a sense the story gave a certain purpose to
my life. In the 1980s I even met two sisters, Reine and Renee
Paillassou, who had taught at Chabannes, and I thought they'd make
a wonderful film.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a planned reunion at Chabannes in May 1996, however, that
served as the catalyst for this documentary. ``The idea of honoring
these people who risked their lives for the children was central to
the project,'' Gossels said. ``I also thought that the occasion
would probably not happen again. At first I found people reticent
to speak. It was traumatic for many to go back into their memories.
But we came in with love and trust, and this opened things up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a story built around two points of view, two sets of
memories: those of the children, now in their 60s and 70s, people
like Gossels as well as Ruth Keller, Norbert Bikales and Jerry
Gerard, who also ended up in the United States; and those of
surviving protectors, now in their 80s and even 90s, among them the
Paillassou sisters, Georges Loinger (who later helped more than
1,000 Jewish children escape into Switzerland) and Rachel
Pludermacher, herself Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us never saw our parents again, and these educators
were our parents and they guided us to a better life,'' Bikales
said of his Chabannes companions, many of whom came from Poland and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the need to avoid too many talking heads, Gossels
said, she filmed the farms and hamlets around Chabannes as a way of
conveying the region's quiet isolation before the hunt for Jews
stepped up in the area in 1942. But her greatest stroke of fortune
was to discover a 170-page journal of essays, reflections,
photographs and drawings prepared by staff and children at the
chateau in 1942. It was among papers donated by Chevrier to the
Center for Contemporary Jewish Documentation in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The journal, which provided additional illustration for the
film, also had the effect of jogging memories. For instance,
Gossels was able to persuade the Paillassou sisters to read aloud
before a camera reflections they had written more than a
half-century earlier. Frederic Pottecher, a former journalist, read
from Chevrier's letters.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, the children _ many already orphans in 1942 and
1943, though perhaps not yet aware of their parents' deaths _
remembered Chevrier as a jovial fatherly figure who ran something
resembling a summer camp. (Many photographs show happy children.)
Those who worked with him, however, spoke more of his courage and
determination to shield his wards.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrier's motivation seemed to be political. ``He wanted to
remain a true French republican,'' recalled Pottecher, who knew
Chevrier well, ``and republican meant a little bit on the left but
not too much. Not socialist, but a little. But in reality he was
very socialist. But you couldn't say that because it was political,
so he was republican. It was very French. It was in the great
French tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end Chevrier could not save all his children from
deportation. In August 1942, 12 children and 2 teachers were taken
away on a bus by French police. Chevrier eventually managed to
obtain the freedom of six children and two teachers, but six people
from the chateau were deported and, of these, only two, Wolfie
Blumenreich and Gerard, managed to survive slave labor in a
succession of camps.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment things grew steadily more difficult at
Chabannes. After Germany took over the so-called unoccupied zone
run by Vichy in November 1942, Chevrier began dispersing the
children, smuggling some into Spain and Switzerland and placing
others in homes. A few teen-agers joined the Resistance. Finally,
after a French gendarme tipped him off that the remaining children
were about to be seized, they were taken from the chateau and never
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the children who had taken Chevrier for granted have
now come to understand everything he did for them,'' Gossels said.
``Chevrier is also to be honored as a righteous Gentile at the Yad
Vashem memorial in Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   But France, too, has taken note. The primary school in Chabannes
now carries Chevrier's name and, after the prefet, or governor, of
the Creuse region saw the film, he nominated the Paillassou sisters
for the Legion of Honor. The ceremony is to take place in
September.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
