<HEADER>
A7473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COX-EXCITEHOME0608-CO     06-07 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-EXCITEHOME0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox to test TV e-mail, Net service in San Diego
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Cox Communications is making Southern
California its national testing ground for offering new toys to TV
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The company says in the fall it will begin a six-month trial
allowing 2,000 of its San Diego cable TV customers to get e-mail
and surf the Web on their TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   Cox officials say they expect to spread the service to other
markets next year. The company serves 6 million households
nationwide, mostly with cable TV service, though in several markets
it also offers phone service and Internet connections to computers.
</P>
<P>
   Internet TV isn't the only push Cox is making in San Diego. The
company is starting there for the national launch of its service
allowing residential TV viewers to rent and watch videos without
having to drive to their local Blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   The service, called video-on-demand, will be rolled out to 2,000
cable customers in August. Cox will expand the offering to other
parts of San Diego and other markets next year, company spokeswoman
Amy Cohn said.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and telephone companies are scrambling to expand beyond
their traditional turfs, adding expensive upgrades to their systems
with the hope it will allow them to sell more services and make
more money.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, Charter Communications and Comcast Corp. _ all companies
with large cable holdings _ have or are planning to offer
interactive TV. Business Week magazine reported that America Online
is launching its own Internet TV service this month, using digital
set-top boxes that can work with TVs regardless of whether the
signal comes by cable, satellite or regular broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, dominant cable provider MediaOne plans to offer
video-on-demand later this year but has no plans for Internet TV.
</P>
<P>
   Charges for Cox's Internet TV service haven't been finalized,
but Cohn said it will be less than Cox's average $29.95 monthly
charge for regular Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is controlled by Cox Enterprises, which is
the owner of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
