u i BC-TURKEY-GREECE-520&AMP;ADD     06-07 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-GREECE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TURKISH-GREEK RELATIONS WARM, THOUGHTS TURN TO   AEGEAN
DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ For decades the Aegean Sea has been not just
a vacation spot but also a zone of military confrontation. Now
Turkey is debating a step that could considerably reduce tension
there.
</P>
<P>
   A retired admiral who is an adviser to Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit has recommended that Turkey disband its 100,000-man Aegean
army. The army is deployed along the Aegean coast and confronts
Greek units based on islands that lie in some cases only a few
miles offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit has not commented on the four-page ``action plan''
presented by the adviser, Adm. Guven Erkaya. The general staff said
the question of dissolving the Aegean force was not on their
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the plan was written by such a high-ranking
figure, and that its contents were so prominently reported in the
Turkish press, has opened a national debate over this question for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The debate comes after nearly a year of steadily improving
relations between Greece and Turkey. Having now resolved many of
their minor disputes, they must now decide whether to move ahead to
the two big ones: Cyprus and the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
   With Cyprus perhaps the more complex problem, Turkish leaders
are apparently reflecting on how they can make progress in the
Aegean. There Greece and Turkey are locked in a tangle of
sovereignty disputes over sea lanes, air rights and barren islets.
A confrontation over one islet led the two countries to the brink
of war in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the course of the European Union accession process Turkey
must solve its problems with Greece by 2004,'' Erkaya wrote,
referring to the application for membership in the union. ``By
doing away with the Aegean army, Turkey can take the first step
and, in return, put the Aegean airspace and Aegean islands disputes
on the negotiating table.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aegean army was deployed in 1975 amid the tension that
followed the landing of Turkish troops on Cyprus. Its first two
commanders became Turkish presidents, the second, Gen. Kenan Evren,
after leading a military coup in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Some want the force to remain in place. Defense Minister
Sabahattin Cakmakoglu, a member of the far-right Nationalist Action
Party, said it was ``too early to consider suggestions that the
Aegean army be disbanded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot decide there is no longer a threat simply by looking
at some short-term solutions or signs of friendship,'' Cakmakoglu
told a television interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several months, private groups of Greeks and Turks
have been meeting to discuss the problems that separate their
countries. Erkaya has been in several of those meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As both parties get to know each other and believe in each
other's sincerity, an atmosphere of confidence is born,'' wrote
Mehmet Ali Birand, a newspaper and television commentator who has
also taken part. ``That someone such as Erkaya, whose life has been
dominated by Turkish-Greek and Aegean problems, who has been
burdened with great responsibilities and known for being a
conservative with rigid attitudes, has made such a proposal has
impressed a lot of people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Greece and Turkey are members of NATO, and for years their
rivalry was one of the alliance's gravest internal weaknesses. But
they began to cooperate after earthquakes in both countries last
year, which led to outpourings of compassion and mutual support.
Relations between them are now warmer than at any time since before
the 1974 landing in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for the first time in more than a generation, Turkish
soldiers took part in maneuvers on Greek soil. More than 150
Turkish commandos staged a mock landing on a Greek beach, and 10
Turkish warplanes flew over Greek territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
