<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7479 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-HNS &LR;      06-07 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH SAYS HE HAS NARROWED LIST FOR RUNNING MATE  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Republican George W. Bush said Wednesday he is
narrowing his list of prospective vice presidential running mates
on the GOP ticket, with an eye on candidates who would be loyal and
capable of serving as president.
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive Republican presidential nominee told editors and
executives of the Hearst Newspapers that he expects to reach a
decision in coming weeks but will most likely delay his
announcement until closer to the Republican convention in
Philadelphia that begins on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Bush interrupted his 75-minute interview with the Hearst editors
in a reception room at the governor's mansion to take a telephone
call from Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary and one-time
White House chief of staff, who is screening prospective running
mates for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who said he speaks with Cheney roughly every four days,
said the call focused on ``a particular person that he has talked
to that has indicated an interest that they would like to be
considered.'' Bush declined to name the prospective running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made up my mind yet,'' the two-term Texas governor
said. ``The list is a little fluid these days. ... It just means
people are being added and sometimes dropping off at their own
whim, their own desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush reiterated that both Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and retired
Gen. Colin Powell, the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, have insisted repeatedly that they not be considered as
possible running mates. ``Those are two good men who unfortunately
aren't on the list of the vice presidential selection process,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it would be up to Cheney to vet the candidates to make
sure that there were no embarrassing or politically damaging
episodes in their background. Bush said he would meet with the
candidates privately without an unseemly ``parade of stars'' in
which prospective candidates would traipse to Austin for personal
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was looking for ``somebody I can trust,
obviously,'' as well as someone who would be capable of serving as
president, if circumstances required.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in a vice president with whom I can seek
counsel and know that the counsel I seek won't be on the front page
of the Hearst newspapers the next day,'' Bush said. ``There's a
certain sense of loyalty that's necessary to make an administration
work. There are a lot of political factors that go into it. But the
two biggest factors are who can be president and will the person be
loyal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in response to a question, said that he had narrowed his
list of prospects ``some _ a little bit.'' He did not elaborate.
``Not everybody wants to be considered for vice president. It may
come as a complete shock to you but it's very simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had a short list, Bush replied: ``It's getting
shorter.''
</P>
<P>
   Various political figures have been mentioned as possible
running mates, including Govs. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania; Christine
Todd Whitman of New Jersey; George Pataki of New York; Rep. John
Kasich, R-Ohio; Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., and Sen. Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said initially he had more than a dozen candidates on the
list.
</P>
<P>
   The governor touched upon a variety of issues during the
interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Republican National Committee will hit the
nation's airwaves in coming weeks with campaign ads financed with
so-called soft money to respond to the Democrats' $25 million blitz
in 15 states scheduled to begin Thursday. Bush said he expected the
first ad to focus on his plans to bolster the finances of the
Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Al Gore would love me to be the (campaign finance)
reformer in the middle of the campaign and give him an advantage''
by not responding to the Democrats' ad blitz, Bush said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be outspent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he couldn't say whether Gore was a ``good man'' or not
because he doesn't know him well enough to form an opinion. In the
heat of the Republican primary campaign earlier this year, Bush
said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., his main opponent, was ``a good
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that if elected president he will not breach
hydro-electrical power dams in the Northwest to spare salmon.
``This administration wants to breach those dams to save salmon,''
Bush said. ``I don't want to breach the dams and if I'm president
the dams won't be breached.''
</P>
<P>
   He underscored his continued support for the death penalty
despite granting a 30-day stay of execution last week for a
condemned murderer so that DNA evidence can be reviewed. Bush said
the final decision on whether the execution takes place will be up
to the state's board of pardons and parole that he has named. ``I
support the death penalty because I believe it prevents people from
killing people. I know that's open for contention and argument.''
Bush said, however, that he has asked state officials to look into
revising Texas laws if necessary to make sure that the state uses
DNA evidence to determine guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our state probably needs to change some laws to that effect
and I'm having people look at it to make sure that (DNA) is used,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who has presided over the executions of 131
condemned prisoners since taking office in 1995, said he believes
that ``everybody put to death has been guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined comment on the federal judge's decision Wednesday
in Washington, D.C., to break up Microsoft to end monopolistic
practices prosecuted by the Justice Department. Bush said that he
favors ``innovation as opposed to litigation'' but he declined
substantive comment. ``On this issue or any other issue (people)
should not hope that a Bush administration is going to behave one
way or another,'' he said. ``I hear all the time, `We'll just hold
out and wait for the Bush administration to come. People need to
make their decisions based upon right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush announced that he plans no foreign travel before the
November election. Karl Rove, Bush's political strategist, said
that it would take too many days off the campaign trail for Bush to
prepare for and carry out a hopscotch foray to foreign capitals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
