<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE     06-07 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: LITTLE PANIC OVER MICROSOFT RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST)  
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft is more than a company that dominates a rapidly
growing industry. To investors it has been a stock whose owners
believed in it with almost religious conviction. Its declines were
usually mild and always brief.
</P>
<P>
   But that faith has been shaken in the last couple of months, and
now investors face the question of how well Microsoft can perform
after its conduct has been ruled to be illegal and a breakup of the
company ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as investors awaited Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's
decision, Microsoft's stock rose 87.5 cents, to $70.25. In
after-hours trading, as the actual court document was digested, the
shares traded as high as $73, ending at $71.875.
</P>
<P>
   That gain, which may reflect some hope that the judge's strident
tone would make a reversal more likely, still left the stock far
below its peak of $119.9375 in December. Microsoft lost almost half
its value as it sank to $60.375 late last month. ``Investors think
the ruling will be materially changed'' on appeal, commented
Richard G. Sherlund, a Goldman, Sachs analyst.
</P>
<P>
   If the breakup begins to appear likely, investor opinions of the
future of the two Microsoft companies _ known informally as Opsco,
for operating system company, and Appsco, for the company that is
to produce applications ranging from Microsoft Word to Internet
Explorer _ will come to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   There is some worry that even though the operating company would
retain an effective monopoly it would be so hamstrung by government
oversight that its profit margins would inevitably erode. And there
is concern that the applications company would be a less formidable
competitor when deprived of its close relationship with the company
that designs the operating system and thereby sets the rules for
competition for other software companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the longer term, the real issue may be whether investors
lose their faith in Microsoft as a money machine whose rapid growth
will end up justifying the purchase of its stock at any price. For
years, Wall Street analysts routinely ignored cautions from
Microsoft's management about the company's valuation, and were
vindicated as the price continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1990s, as Microsoft's profits and share price
grew rapidly, one measure of investor confidence did not soar. The
price-earnings ratio stayed in the 20s and 30s. Those were
good-sized numbers, reflecting anticipations of substantial growth,
but they were modest compared with what was to come. The
price-earnings ratio topped 40 in 1996, and by the end of last year
it was up to 78. That figure may be overstated a bit, given that
Microsoft's accounting is extremely conservative, but even after
discounting for that, the price clearly assumed many years of rapid
profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   Such growth is not easy for any company to produce, but it is
even harder for one already as large as Microsoft. That the company
could sell at such a high valuation in part reflected a general
expansion of multiples in the bull market, but it also reflected
investors' convictions that Microsoft had become a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's aura of invincibility held even after the Justice
Department set its sights on the company. Microsoft stock fell
almost 4 percent on the day Justice filed suit against the company
in 1998, but within two months it had not only recovered that loss
but was up 30 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial progressed, there was plenty of bad news for
Microsoft. But the stock price seldom fell for more than a few
days, and at the peak in December it was four times as high as it
had been in late 1997, shortly after Jackson ruled against
Microsoft in an earlier antitrust case _ a ruling that was
overturned on appeal. Even now, the stock is 58 percent above where
it was when the latest suit was filed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of Microsoft's stock price began in late March, just as
many Internet stocks were beginning to crumble. It is impossible to
calculate how much of the Microsoft plunge since then has
represented specific fears about the ruling, and how much has been
a reassessment of the extraordinary growth that the market had
previously seemed to accept for virtually all technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's stock price of $70.50 before the ruling was
released, Microsoft was trading at 42 times the profits it reported
over the last 12 months. That was a higher multiple than it enjoyed
through the first half of the 1990s, hardly a time of investor
pessimism regarding the company.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, in other words, still expects great things
from Microsoft, even if the expectations are not as high as they
were late last year. There is room for severe disappointment if
Microsoft loses on appeal _ or if it simply cannot keep growing at
the extraordinary high rates of the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
