<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-PRIMARIES-RDP-1STLD-W     06-07 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THE NOMINEES CHOSEN, THE REAL RACES BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs 11th graf, Both Skeen ..., to fix Rep. Udall's first
name to Thomas, not Mark.) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Montana Gov. Marc Racicot barred by law from seeking a
third consecutive term, his lieutenant governor, Judy Martz, and
state Auditor Mark O'Keefe had little trouble winning their
gubernatorial primaries on Tuesday to face each other in the
November general election.
</P>
<P>
   Martz, a Republican who has served with Racicot since 1996, had
57 percent of the vote to 43 percent for Rob Natelson, a law
professor who fared better this time than four years ago, when he
won only 24 percent in a primary challenge to Racicot. In the
Democratic primary, O'Keefe won 48 percent of the vote to defeat
two other high-ranking state officials, Attorney General Joe
Mazurek, with 36 percent, and Secretary of State Mike Cooney, with
16 percent. The voting reflected totals from all but two of
Montana's 867 voting precincts.
</P>
<P>
   Montana was also one of several states that held congressional
primaries on Tuesday. In winning the Democratic U.S. Senate
primary, Brian Schweitzer, a farmer who made the high cost of
prescription drugs a campaign focus, easily defeated John Driscoll,
a former state public service commissioner who entered the campaign
late. Schweitzer, who won 66 percent of the vote to 34 percent for
Driscoll, will face the two-term Republican incumbent, Sen. Conrad
Burns, who had no primary opponent.
</P>
<P>
   While their approaches are certain to be different, Martz and
O'Keefe both said they would make statewide economic development a
high priority. Montana currently ranks lowest among the states in
average wages, 47th in per capita income and, as O'Keefe contended,
first in the number of families in which the chief wage earner
holds at least two jobs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keefe said those rankings reflect how poorly the Racicot
administration had performed, but Martz said the situation was far
worse when Racicot took office in 1993, when the state was $200
million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We re-did workmen's compensation, we reformed welfare, and
after the last legislative session, we enacted $116 million in tax
cuts,'' she said in an interview Wednesday, boasting of
administration successes.
</P>
<P>
   But they do not obscure the obvious, O'Keefe said, adding,
``We're having our first debate on Friday. One of things I'm sure
we'll talk about is the lieutenant governor's administration.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, Democrats held primaries in all three
congressional districts and one produced a close finish. Seeking to
oppose Rep. Joe Skeen, a 10-term Republican from the 2nd District,
state Treasurer Michael Montoya narrowly defeated Mike Runnels, a
district attorney, despite a recent investigation by New Mexico
State Police into accusations that Montoya's brother, Orlando
Montoya, diverted money from his construction business into the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Montoya won 52 percent of the vote to 48 percent for
Runnels, a margin that Montoya said might have been helped by a
sympathetic backlash against the police investigation, which, so
far, has produced no charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1st District primary, former U.S. Attorney John J. Kelly
won 43 percent of the vote in a three-way race to face Rep. Heather
A. Wilson, a first-term Republican who is viewed by Democrats as
one of the most vulnerable members of the House majority. Kelly
defeated Sam Bregman, a former Albuquerque city councilman, who won
33 percent of the vote, and John V. Wertheim, the party's nominee
four years ago, who had 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both Skeen and Wilson ran unopposed, but not so New Mexico's
other incumbent, Rep. Thomas Udall, a freshman Democrat who soundly
defeated Francesca Lobato, a tax lawyer from Santa Fe, with 83
percent of the balloting. Udall will face Lisa Lutz, a state
lawmaker, who ran unopposed to win the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican U.S. Senate primary, Bill Redmond, a former
congressman, breezed in a three-way race, with 60 percent of the
vote, to oppose Jeff Bingaman, a Democrat seeking his fourth term.
Two state lawmakers trailed, Steve Pearce with 22 percent and
William F. Davis, 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In South Dakota, Curt Hohn, general manager of the state's Water
Development Association, beat two other Democrats to oppose Rep.
John Thune, a two-term Republican who was expected to win in
November no matter who prevailed among the Democrats. With the
turnout extremely light, Hohn won 56 percent of the vote to 36
percent for Steve Sandven, a lawyer, and 7 percent for Raymond
Osloond, a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Each party had two primaries in Iowa. In the 1st District,
Democrats elected Bob Simpson over Gregory Guy, by a margin of
almost 2-to-1, although Simpson is given only a slim chance against
Rep. Jim Leach, the 12-term Republican incumbent. In the 3rd, Jay
Marcus narrowly defeated Phil Ferren to oppose Iowa's only
Democratic House member, Leonard Boswell, who is seeking a third
term.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties held primaries in the 5th District. Mike Palecek
defeated Conrad Lawlor for the Democratic nomination, and Rep. Tom
Latham, who is seeking a fourth term, easily turned back Thomas
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In the lone Alabama contest, Rep. Earl Hilliard, a four-term
Democrat from a solidly Democratic district, the 7th, won 58
percent of the vote to defeat two challengers, Arthur Davis and
Wayne Sowell. Ed Martin won the 7th District Republican nomination,
defeating Milton Bethune in a primary than drew less than a tenth
of the voters who cast ballots for Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
