<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-FILE     06-07 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    FILE 2 of 2
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What's the status of El Toro Marine Corps Aviation Station in
California, where I served in 1947? Is it true, as I've heard, that
it has closed?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. It was one of several Navy and Marine air facilities in
California, Virginia and Florida shut down as part of a
restructuring due to federal budget cuts. The Defense Base Closure
and Realignment Commission announced the closure in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, a move has been under way to concert El Toro into
a civilian airport. But that has generated considerable opposition
because Orange County already has a civilian airport (John Wayne).
</P>
<P>
   In late March, attorneys for Orange County said they would ask a
Los Angeles County Superior Court judge to freeze voter-approved
limits on spending for the proposed El Toro airport until the
validity of a March 7 county ballot measure was decided.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Charlton Heston ever serve in the military?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Current Biography Yearbook (1986) reports that after
Heston had completed two years at Northwestern University, he left
school to enlist in the 11th Army Air Forces. He spent most of his
three-year tour stationed in Alaska's Aleutian Islands. The
yearbook says he was a radio gunner on B-52s, but that doesn't seem
possible since B-52s didn't go into production until 1954. The
movie star and president of the National Rifle Association was
discharged in early 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An item about unassisted triple plays mentioned that of the
11 in Major League history, two were carried out by a first
baseman. Can you explain the circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both of those unassisted triple plays were similar. The first
occurred on Sept. 14, 1923, in a game between the Boston Red Sox
and Cleveland Indians, when Red Sox first baseman George Burns
caught a line drive hit by first baseman Frank Brower. Burns tagged
out Rube Lutzke and ran to second base for the third out before
Riggs Stephenson could get back.
</P>
<P>
   The second was on May 31, 1927, in a game between the Detroit
Tigers and Cleveland Indians, when Tigers first baseman Johnny Neun
nabbed right fielder Homer Summa's line drive and tagged Charlie
Jamieson off first. Then, ignoring his shortstop's shouts to throw
the ball, he dashed toward second base and tagged the bag before
Glenn Myatt could get back. Neun's play happened in the ninth
inning to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   As dramatic as that game-ender was, a more-famous unassisted
triple play occurred during a World Series. In the fifth game of
the 1920 Series, Cleveland Indians second baseman Bill Wambsganss
caught a line drive hit by the Brooklyn Dodgers' Clarence Mitchell,
touched second to retire Pete Kilduff, then tagged Otto Miller
running from first base.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was told that Nelson Mandela gave the commencement address
at Blair Academy in New Jersey. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although Mandela was invited to speak, he didn't do so, said
Chandler Hardwick, Blair's headmaster. Mandela's grandson, Zinhle
Dlamini, received his diploma at Blair on May 27, so it would have
been appropriate for Mandela to deliver the commencement address,
Hardwick explained. A death in the family, however, prevented the
visit of both Mandela and Zinhle Dlamini's grandmother, Winnie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The newspaper printed an excerpt of the poem ``For the
Fallen,'' inscribed on the Vietnam War Monument at the Atlanta
History Center. I've also seen it at Virginia Military Institute.
Can you print the full text?
</P>
<P>
   A: Laurence Binyon's ``For the Fallen'' (Sept. 21, 1914):
</P>
<P>
   With proud thanksgiving, a mother for her children,/ England
mourns for her dead across the sea./ Flesh of her flesh they were,
spirit of her spirit,/ Fallen in the cause of the free.
</P>
<P>
   Solemn the drums thrill: Death august and royal/ Sings sorrow up
into immortal spheres./ There is a music in the midst of
desolation/ And a glory that shines upon our tears.
</P>
<P>
   They went with songs to the battle, they were young,/ Straight
of limb, true of eye, steady and aglow./ They were staunch to the
end against odds uncountered:/ They fell with their faces to the
foe.
</P>
<P>
   They shall grow not old, as we that are left grow old:/ Age
shall not weary them, nor the years condemn./ At the going down of
the sun and in the morning/ We will remember them.
</P>
<P>
   They mingle not with their laughing comrades again;/ They sit no
more at familiar tables at home;/ They have no lot in our labour of
the day-time;/ They sleep beyond England's foam.
</P>
<P>
   But where our desires are and our hopes profound,/ Felt as a
well-spring that is hidden from sight,/ To the innermost heart of
their own land they are known/ As the stars are known to the Night;
</P>
<P>
   As the stars that shall be bright when we are dust,/ Moving in
marches upon the heavenly plain;/ As the stars are starry in the
time of our darkness,/ To the end, to the end they remain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On my newest maps of Canada, I see an area labeled Nunavut.
Is this a new province?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It's a new territory, split off from Northwest
Territories as of April 1, 1999. The name means ``our land'' in
Inuktitut, the language of Inuit. The designated capital is
Iqaluit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About 10 years ago, a cable channel called The Tuxxedo
Network was shut down after a district attorney in Mississippi
filed criminal charges against the owners for transmitting X-rated
movies into the state by satellite. Whatever happened with that
case?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was Alabama, not Mississippi. The company, Home Dish Only
Satellite Network, operated American Exxxstasy Channel and Tuxxedo
Channel. The New York company pleaded guilty in 1990 to obscenity
charges in Alabama state court, becoming the nation's first
satellite TV company to be indicted outside its home state for
beaming adult films into another state. The indictment stemmed from
an obscenity law enacted in Alabama in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Home Dish was fined $5,000 and paid $75,000 each to two
children's homes as part of the penalty. The company went out of
business after satellite owners refused to transmit its movies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a new American flag. How do I dispose of the old one,
which is too faded to give to anyone?
</P>
<P>
   A: When a flag is no longer fit for display, it should be
destroyed in some dignified way, preferably by burning.
</P>
<P>
   Call an American Legion or VFW post (locations and phone numbers
are listed in the telephone directory) to see if it will accept
donated flags for disposal. Also, many Boy Scout and Girl Scout
troops will accept them for flag-retirement ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If burning is the preferred disposal method for American
flags that have passed their useful life, how would the proposed
constitutional amendment against flag burning affect this practice?
</P>
<P>
   A: The proposed amendment would make it a federal crime to
desecrate the American flag. Disposing of an old, worn-out flag in
a respectful ceremony conducted by veterans' organizations or a
Scout troop wouldn't be considered desecration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Navy's next class of aircraft carriers is designated
CVNX. What can you tell us about these carriers, and CVNX 1 in
particular?
</P>
<P>
   A: CVN is the Navy's designation for a nuclear-powered,
multipurpose aircraft carrier. The X refers to the next generation
carrier fleet. Adm. Jay Johnson, chief of naval operations, put it
this way: ``CVNX will form the core of the Navy that will prevail
today, tomorrow, and for decades to come _ anytime, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy says the large-deck nuclear-powered ships will evolve
``at an evolutionary pace'' beginning with CVN 77, which will
replace USS Kitty Hawk in 2008. Construction on that vessel will
begin in 2001. Construction is scheduled to begin in 2006 on CVNX
1, which will replace USS Enterprise in 2013.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Navy, the nuclear propulsion plants on the new
class of carriers will provide ``immediate and future warfighting
enhancements and life cycle cost reductions.'' Subsequent carriers
will feature such new technologies as an electromagnetic aircraft
launching system. They will have ``stealthier features'' than
current carriers, but won't have a completely stealth design.
</P>
<P>
   More information online:
www.hq.navy.mil/airwarfare/N885/CVNX%20Program.htm.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
