<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-FILE     06-07 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    FILE 1 of 2
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: The obituary for 93-year-old John Coolidge, son of President
Calvin Coolidge, didn't mention Coolidge's other son, who died
after playing tennis at the White House in the 1920s. Could you
refresh my memory?
</P>
<P>
   A: Calvin Coolidge Jr., who was born in 1908 _ two years after
John Coolidge _ died in 1924. He had developed a blister from
playing tennis and developed a staphylococcus infection which
proved to be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked Americans mourned his death, and even the famously
taciturn president broke down. As John Coolidge told Life magazine
in 1992: ``Though father was tenderhearted, he rarely showed his
feelings. But when they were taking my brother's casket from the
White House after the services, my father broke down and wept
momentarily. Calvin was my father's favorite. It hurt him terribly.
It hurt us all.''
</P>
<P>
   President Coolidge and his wife, Grace, had no other children.
John Coolidge died May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A report about the National Spelling Bee stated that the top
three finishers were home schooled. How many other contestants were
home schooled? Are similar statistics available for contestants in
the National Geographic Bee?
</P>
<P>
   A: Of the spellers participating in the Scripps Howard National
Spelling Bee in Washington, D.C., May 31-June 1, 27 were home
schooled, including the winner, George Thampy of Maryland Heights,
Mo. The remainder: public schools, 178; private, 24; parochial, 19.
</P>
<P>
   Of the contestants in the National Geographic Bee finals May
23-24, also in Washington, six were home schooled. The remainder:
public schools, 36; private, 5; parochial, 6.
</P>
<P>
   The spelling bee winner, 13-year-old Thampy, came in second at
the National Geographic Bee, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens to donations made to political candidates when,
for whatever reason, they end up not running for office?
Specifically, what will happen to the donations New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani received before he withdrew from his Senate
campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   A: Presidential and congressional candidates can return the
money to contributors, save it for a future campaign of their own,
donate it to another political party organization, or conceivably
donate it to a charity. Before 1993 it would have been possible for
them to convert the money for their own personal use, but the law
was changed that year, said Pete Sepp of the National Taxpayers
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who raised $20 million for the race, spent $13.8
million before he bowed out. Of the remainder, he has said he will
return $2.8 million to the donors and ask them to send their money
to Rep. Rick Lazio, who jumped into the race in his place. Election
laws require that Giuliani give donors back the money they
earmarked for the general election rather than the primary; that's
$2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about technology mentioned something called
``carbon nanotubes.'' What are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're man-made carbon tubes 10,000 times thinner than a
human hair. It's part of what scientists and researchers call
``nanotechnology,'' a broad term given to the ability to control
atoms.
</P>
<P>
   Nanotechnology scientists work on the incredibly small
``nanometer'' scale. The prefix ``nano'' refers to one billionth of
one meter; one nanometer is the length of about five carbon atoms
strung together.
</P>
<P>
   Information on Georgia Tech's nanotube research can be found
online at www.gatech.edu. Click on the search button and type in
the word nanotube to access the information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I can remember as a child using the phrase ``oly, oly, oxen
free,'' but I can't remember what game it went with. Can you tell
me the origin and what it meant?
</P>
<P>
   A: The chant was common in hide-and-seek to call in any players
who were holdouts at the end of the game. The Morris Dictionary of
Word and Phrase Origins speculates that it might have been a
childish corruption of ``all in free.''
</P>
<P>
   The book ``The Lore and Language of Children'' reports that
``ollyoxalls'' and ``olly-olly-ee'' were common ``truce terms''
among children in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We're going to Cuba, and understand that U.S. credit cards
and travelers' checks cannot be used there. Is it possible for a
U.S. citizen to get a credit card in Canada for use in Cuba?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're correct in saying that credit cards and travelers'
checks from U.S. banks aren't accepted as payment in Cuba. The
accepted mode of payment is U.S. dollars. In fact you must travel
with cash, according to Cubatravel, a Tijuana, Mexico, company that
arranges tourist visits in Cuba. Cuban pesos are necessary only in
rural areas rarely traveled by tourists, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   One possible option is travelers' checks from foreign banks,
such as Thomas Cook or Barclays, which may be used to pay for some
services. But Cubatravel says you can save yourself some worry by
prepaying for such expenses as hotel accommodations, rental cars
and airport-hotel transfers.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. citizen cannot get a credit card issued by a Canadian
financial institution, said Laurel DeWolf of the Canadian Consulate
in Atlanta. In order to qualify for a Canadian credit card, an
applicant must have a social insurance number _ the equivalent in
Canada to a U.S. Social Security number _ and must have established
a residence in Canada for at least one year. Without meeting both
conditions, an application for a credit card would be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   As you're aware, the U.S. government restricts the spending of
money in Cuba. Americans traveling there without a Treasury
Department license must enter via a third country, such as Canada,
Mexico and the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When and where in Vietnam did Al Gore serve? Was he in fact
an Army journalist? Why was he there only five months, when most
Vietnam tours were one year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Gore was an Army journalist, Military Occupation Specialty
71Q20, with the rank of Specialist 5, the equivalent of a buck
sergeant. He was assigned to the 20th Engineering Brigade,
headquartered at the Bien Hoa military base about 40 miles north of
Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived there Dec. 26, 1970, and stayed five months. He had
received orders for Vietnam five months before he was actually
shipped out. While Gore himself offers no explanation for the
delay, there has been considerable speculation that it was the work
of the Nixon White House.
</P>
<P>
   According to this speculation, Nixon's political strategists
worried that if anything happened to Gore, there could be a
sympathy vote for his father, Sen. Albert Gore Sr. (D-Tenn.). The
elder Gore was in a heated re-election campaign that fall with Rep.
Bill Brock (R-Tenn.), who was using the senator's opposition to the
Vietnam War as a campaign issue. Gore Jr. was shipped off to
Vietnam after the election, which Brock won.
</P>
<P>
   Two books _ ``Inventing Al Gore,'' by Bill Turque; and ``Gore: A
Political Life,'' by Bob Zelnick _ mention this subject in more
detail.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was growing up, the Pledge of Allegiance didn't
include the words ``under God.'' When was that added, and was it
done by Congress?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Under God'' was added by an act of Congress in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article mentioned that part of the skull of Adolf
Hitler was put on public display in Moscow. I had read previously
that none of Hitler's remains were ever found. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not entirely clear, but the story goes that after Hitler
shot himself in his Berlin bunker on April 30, 1945, his body was
taken outside by his staff, doused with gasoline, and set ablaze,
along with the remains of Eva Braun. When Soviet troops captured
the bunker afterward, they seized the remains.
</P>
<P>
   What happened after that is shrouded in mystery and speculation.
Secret communications between Soviet counterintelligence units in
Germany and the government in Moscow told of repeated burials and
exhumations of the remains, and of their final destruction by fire
in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   According to Soviet officials, however, a piece of Hitler's
skull and jaw weren't destroyed. What they claim is a fragment of
his skull _ a four-inch section with a hole where a bullet
reportedly exited through the left temple _ went on display at
Russia's Federal Archives Service in April. Photos of the jaw also
went on display, but the jaw itself, with the dental work that
presumably allowed the Soviets to identify Hitler's body, is still
in secret archives.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia announced in 1993 that it had the skull fragment,
some Western experts were skeptical. But Sergio Mironenko, head of
Russia's state archives, insisted it's authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw where a water sports amusement park had built a
``zero-depth'' pool for toddlers. If a pool has some water, how can
it be ``zero'' depth?
</P>
<P>
   A: The pool can be a place for toddlers to get wet, but without
a measureable water depth. ``Zero depth'' pools have fountains,
squirt guns and other features, but for safety reasons no standing
water for the tots to ingest.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
