<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MCCOYS0608-COX     06-07 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOYS0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mountain reunion recalls fierce feud
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than a century after ending their bloody feud in
remote Appalachia, the Hatfields and McCoys are gathering this
weekend vowing to fight myths, not each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no feuding anymore,'' Waycross, Ga., minister Bo
McCoy said Wednesday from Pikeville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Georgia descendant of family patriarch Randolph
McCoy of Kentucky is helping organize the three-day reunion of as
many as 2,000 members from both families.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Friday, the reunion will culminate a year of planning
by Bo McCoy and his cousin, Ron McCoy, a music engineer in Durham,
N.C. They credit the Web page they created in 1998 for attracting
the interest of kinfolk who plan to attend from as far away as
South Korea and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a glorified reunion, a remembrance festival,'' Bo McCoy
said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1892, 12 years of feuding along the Tug Fork had claimed 12
lives. Six were Hatfields, six were McCoys.
</P>
<P>
   From the isolated river valley separating Kentucky and West
Virginia rose one of America's most enduring, and unflattering,
portrayals of Southerners as barefoot hillbillies shooting at each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The first dispute was over whether a Hatfield or a McCoy owned a
particular hog. But historians say their shooting war evolved into
a clash over ownership of timber, a battle foreshadowing the deadly
coal mine wars in one of America's most impoverished regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is part of our heritage to let people know we were not as
notorious, as bad as some people think,'' said Cecil Hatfield, 63,
a retired school teacher in Williamson, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody asked me today,'' Hatfield said, ``who won the feud.
Nobody, I told them. It's just an unfortunate thing that happened,
something that my father and others from his generation did not
talk much about.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid this weekend's Hatfield vs. McCoy softball game and tug of
war, bluegrass and gospel music and appearances by Kentucky and
West Virginia, the families will share stories passed down for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering in Pikeville and Matewan, W. Va., they also hope
lectures will help correct the historical record and set to mood
for a collaboration among relatives to preserve historical sites,
such as cemeteries and spots where killing occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives gathered Wednesday in Blackberry Creek, Ky., for the
dedication of one of the bloodiest sites with a new marker.
</P>
<P>
   At this spot in August 1882, three McCoy boys stabbed Ellison
Hatfield with knives and shot him in the back. Hatfield's relatives
chased down the three McCoys and held them captive for three days,
until Hatfield died.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's kin then tied the three McCoys to a paw paw tree
and shot them, execution-style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very peaceful little spot down there by the river,''
Ron McCoy said Wednesday, ``especially for a place of such
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
