<HEADLINE>
SHARES RALLY ON HOPE THAT FED WILL HOLD STEADY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paced by technology issues, stock prices resumed
their climb Wednesday as the belief spread that the Federal Reserve
could soon stop raising interest rates to keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   After a lackluster start, the Nasdaq composite index pushed
solidly higher and finished just shy of its best level, with an
advance of 82.89 points, or 2.2 percent, to 3,839.26.
</P>
<P>
   Optimistic comments about IBM by a Goldman, Sachs analyst helped
send the company's shares up 8|, to 121, and rippled throughout the
market, accounting for about 60 percent of the Dow Jones industrial
average's rise of 77.29 points, or 0.7 percent, to 10,812.86.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's action left the Nasdaq with a smaller decline so far
this year than the Dow _ 5.65 percent compared with 5.95 percent _
despite suffering a 34 percent skid between March 10 and April 14.
</P>
<P>
   And the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index nosed back into
positive territory for the year. It climbed 13.52 points, or 0.9
percent, to 1,471.36 Wednesday. The index is now ahead for the year
by 0.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically in a bullish trend because there's much less
fear that they'll increase rates past June,'' said Mayer Offman,
chief trading strategist at the Carlin Equities Group, referring to
Federal Reserve policy-makers whose next scheduled meeting is June
27 and 28. He also called it a very good sign that recent sinking
spells had attracted bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
   As trading began, Alfred E. Goldman, chief strategist at A.G.
Edwards in St. Louis, made a sweepingly upbeat declaration. ``We
are ringing the bell to announce that the three-month `bearable'
correction is over and a summer rally has begun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman cited slackening economic growth and the market's
reaction to this news last week when the Nasdaq surged a record 19
percent. He also predicted the Fed would forgo a June rate
increase.
</P>
<P>
   With 38.2 million shares changing hands, Microsoft was the most
heavily traded stock Wednesday as the market awaited the decision
by U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who ordered
the company to be broken in two. The shares moved as low as 67[,
but were up ~, to 70{ at 4 p.m., and they climbed to 71} in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's gains were highly concentrated in technology,
with declining shares slightly outnumbering advancing ones, 244 to
238, in the S&AMP;P and by 16 to 14 in the blue-chip Dow industrials.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest Nasdaq technology winners Wednesday were
Qualcomm, up 5 13/16, to 74 11/16; Veritas Software up 9|, to 134{;
Yahoo up 9 7/16, to 144{; i2 Technologies up 11\, to 138\; and
MicroStrategy up 9|, to 37|. Immunex, which won approval for
expanded use of an arthritis drug, jumped 4 13/64, to 36 5/16.
Applied Micro Circuits skidded 9 15/16, to 96~, after warning of
lower sales to its biggest customer.
</P>
</TEXT>
