<HEADER>
A7491 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-DECISION-BO     06-07 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-DECISION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: JUDGE SAYS MICROSOFT MUST BECOME TWO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge has ordered Microsoft Corp. split in half as
punishment for stifling competition in the computer software
industry, in a ruling that seethed with exasperation at the
``untrustworthy'' and defiant leadership of Microsoft chairman Bill
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   US District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ruling
Wednesday would impose the first corporate antitrust breakup since
telephone monopoly AT&AMP;T was forced to spin off the seven Baby Bells
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft vowed to seek a months- or years-long appeal, and a
stay of the judge's order, to keep the company intact. But top
Justice Department antitrust prosecutor Joel I. Klein said the
government will seek to have the case leapfrog an intermediate
appeals court and be heard directly by the US Supreme Court to
speed a resolution of the 2 1/2-year-old case.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson essentially accepted outright the demands by federal
antitrust prosecutors and 17 state attorneys general that Microsoft
be divided into two companies.
</P>
<P>
   One would sell basic operating systems for computers. The second
would sell word-processing, electronic mail and Web-surfing
programs that ride on those systems, and control Microsoft's
Hotmail e-mail service and MSN Web portal, with restrictions aimed
at preventing the two units from colluding.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier rulings, Jackson found that Microsoft has used its
domination of the operating system market _ its Windows software
runs an estimated 90 percent of the world's personal computers _ to
preserve that monopoly and try to kill off emerging software
rivals, including Web browser maker Netscape Communications, now
part of America OnLine.
</P>
<P>
   In just three terse and often angry-sounding pages, Jackson said
it has become clear that Microsoft under Gates' leadership refuses
to accept the authority of the century-old federal antitrust laws
that were used to break up AT&AMP;T and the Standard Oil trust and
thwart monopolization efforts by US Steel and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``A structural remedy has become imperative: Microsoft as it is
presently organized and led is unwilling to accept the notion that
it broke the law or accede to an order amending its conduct,''
Jackson wrote. He added that ``Microsoft has proved untrustworthy
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the certainty of lengthy appeals, likely to the
Supreme Court, Jackson said effectively: Let's get on with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft officials have recently been quoted publicly to the
effect that the company has `done nothing wrong' and that it will
be vindicated on appeal,'' Jackson wrote. ``The Court is well aware
that there is a substantial body of public opinion, some of it
rational, that holds to a similar view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to put that assertion to the test,'' Jackson
declared.
</P>
<P>
   In a late-afternoon press conference at Microsoft's Redmond,
Wash., headquarters, Gates refused to back down from his repeated
assertions that Microsoft has done nothing wrong and will prevail
over Jackson in higher courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe very strongly that today is the first day of the
rest of this case,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling says to creators of intellectual property that the
government can take away your property if it proves to be too
popular,'' Gates added. He vowed to press ahead with efforts to
develop new software, including systems that respond to spoken
commands and those hand-written on an electronic tablet.
</P>
<P>
   Gates also complained that Jackson was ordering a radical
bifurcation of the company ``without a single day of testimony'' on
how to proceed. ``There has never been anything like this in
judicial history,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson said Microsoft's ``profession of surprise'' at the
order ``is not credible.'' The judge contended that ``yet another
round of discovery, to be followed by a second trial'' on how to
atone for Microsoft's violations of law gives no assurance of
reaching ``an optimum remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's order gives Microsoft four months to devise a plan for
breaking up the company, as sought by federal prosecutors, with the
breakup itself phased in to enable the parties to return to court
several times to fix problems that emerge.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged the split-up ``is perhaps more radical than
might have resulted had mediation been successful,'' but said it
will ``take force in stages, so that the effects can be guaged
while the appeal progresses'' and amended if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's top lawyer, William Neukom, said the company
will within days seek a stay of Jackson's order. ``We're in the
middle innings of the judicial proceedings,'' Neukom said. ``I
anticipate that the appellate phase of this will go on for a number
of months, if not a year or possibly longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have speculated Microsoft is eager to drag out
the case, in the hope that Texas Gov. George W. Bush _ who seems
inclined to avoid a breakup _ is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, every month Microsoft avoids a breakup is another
month it can plow its $600 million monthly profits and $20
billion-plus cash hoard into new ventures, such as wireless Net
access products and services, that could help it to survive losing
its Windows operating system monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said, ``I am pleased that the court
has ordered a strong, effective remedy to address the serious
antitrust violations that Microsoft has committed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's ruling will have a profound impact, not only by
promoting competition in the software industry, but also by
reaffirming the importance of antitrust law enforcement in the 21st
Century and the importance of competition,'' Reno added.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said, ``Microsoft itself is responsible for where things
stand today... Decisions made at the highest level of the company
reflect defiance of, not respect for, the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Microsoft leaders decried the ruling, however, Wall
Street seemed unfazed. Microsoft shares rose 87.5 cents to $70.50 a
share during the regular Nasdaq trading session, later rising to
$72 in after-hours trading following a brief trading halt in the
minutes after Jackson's ruling came out.
</P>
<P>
   If the appeals go straight to the Supreme Court, it appears
unlikely the justices will take them up before their next session
begins in October, leaving Microsoft and much of the US technology
industry in limbo all summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court could well send the case back down to the
Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia, which has
been a far friendlier venue for Microsoft in the past than
Jackson's court.
</P>
<P>
   However, in one part of his ruling, Jackson ordered several
steps that, unless frozen by a stay, could have more immediate
impacts on the sale and development of computer software.
</P>
<P>
   Within 90 days, Jackson ruled, Microsoft must stop controlling
which program icons are displayed on a computer screen when a user
buys a computer loaded by a manufacturer with Microsoft software.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment makers such as Compaq and Dell would be able to
arrange the desktop as they want, even if the machine ran on
Windows software _ removing a major hurdle for Microsoft rivals
trying to make their products more easily available to users.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson would also force Microsoft to reveal some now-secret
aspects of the so-called application programming interfaces in
Windows to make it easier for non-Microsoft programmers to write
products like document and business-manageemnt software that would
run on Windows.
</P>
<P>
   And the order requires Microsoft to charge the 20 biggest
computer makers the same price for Windows, except for volume
discounts, to curb its leverage over computer makers to promote
Microsoft products. Jackson also forbade Microsoft from raising
prices of older versions of software once a new version is
launched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is to a large extent in limbo,'' said David Smith, a
software analyst at the Gartner Group. ``Their products are well
established in the market and I don't think customers will abandon
them, but the new initiatives that are dependent on innovation will
suffer from the uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, to prevent Microsoft from snarling an ultimate breakup,
Jackson ordered the company to preserve its current structure and
continue to maintain all its current offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Baby Bills,'' as some industry analysts have dubbed
them, would be organized as follows:
</P>
<P>
   --An operating systems business producing all Windows operating
systems. Those include Windows 95, 98, NT, 2000, the Pocket PC
system for mobile devices, and soon-to-be-released systems
including Windows Millennium Edition and a product called Whistler
that combines consumer and business uses.
</P>
<P>
   --An applications business that essentially collects everything
else: all applications such as Office, Exchange, Internet Explorer
and the Outlook Express e-mail system, the Media Player for
listening to music over the Web, videoconferencing systems, the
MSNBC television network, the MSN Web portal, Slate magazine, the
Hotmail free e-mail service, and the Expedia Net travel service.
</P>
<P>
   Under Jackson's ruling, Gates, the Microsoft chairman and chief
software architect, and chief executive officer Steve Ballmer would
be made to choose one company to join and own stock in.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department sued Microsoft in October 1997, saying it
had violated a 1995 settlement by forcing computer makers to
install its Internet Explorer Web browser if they wanted to use
Windows 95. Nineteen states later joined the case, 17 of which
urged a Microsoft breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-six sometimes grueling days of testimony, in which Gates
was repeatedly found professing ignorance about e-mails he had sent
urging executives to crush rivals, ended last June.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Jackson issued harsh ``findings of fact''
portraying Microsoft as a monopolistic bully. These findings, which
preceded a lengthy but failed effort to negotiate a settlement,
largely anticipated Jackson's later rulings finding the company
guilty of antitrust violations and ordering a corporate breakup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
