r l BC-WWII-GRATITUDE-3200(3     06-07 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-GRATITUDE-3200(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TOOK SO LONG TO THANK WWII VETERANS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By any measure but his own, perhaps, Ralph Spina was a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   As a combat medic with the 101st Airborne Division _ which
fought its way across France, Holland and Germany in World War II _
Spina went onto the front lines, unarmed, to tend the wounded. He
was wounded on the battlefield, a fact he downplays when he comes
to my office to talk about the grand opening Tuesday of the
long-awaited National D-Day Museum in New Orleans, which he is
attending, one of the 10,000 veterans expected for four days of
celebration and recognition.
</P>
<P>
   I had wanted to hear, from a decorated veteran, how it feels to
have the nation finally recognize his generation's heroics; to hear
the unvarnished story of the war's worst battles from someone who
lived them. But Spina would rather talk about his buddies from
South Philly who served with him than about his work ferrying the
wounded from the beaches of Normandy after D-Day. He'd rather tell
a funny story about the Christmas Eve when he and some fellow
soldiers tried to cook a stolen chicken in a German helmet than
relive the 26 grueling days his company spent in the thick of
fighting at the Battle of the Bulge.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as he's heading down the hall after the brief
interview, he tosses a comment over his shoulder, just to make sure
I got the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, sweetheart, don't get too mushy with this thing,'' he
says. ``OK? Don't make it sound like I think I'm some kind of
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   The war, I think, was fought by millions of men like Ralph
Spina, who went most of a lifetime hardly mentioning the horrors
they saw and the bravery they demonstrated. No wonder it's taken 56
years to finally get around to honoring them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the 56th anniversary of the Allied invasion of
Normandy, a high-tech, multimedia National D-Day Museum was
christened in New Orleans with a splashy ceremony moderated by Tom
Brokaw. Luminaries such as Steven Spielberg and Tom Hanks, as well
as at least 10,000 World War II vets, were in attendance. The
museum traces not just the battles at Normandy but the events
leading up to and following them; next year, it will open a gallery
devoted to the D-Day battles in the Pacific, such as Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years in the making, the museum was founded by noted
historian Stephen Ambrose, who has collected thousands of oral
histories from veterans for books such as ``D-Day,'' one of
Spielberg's inspirations in making ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Ambrose
originally wanted just to create a home for the many artifacts he'd
been given by veterans; he also wanted to honor New Orleans
boatmaker Andrew Higgins, whose factory made the thousands of
Higgins landing vessels used in D-Day and nearly every other
amphibious assault during the war.
</P>
<P>
   But the project kept growing. Now it will mix genuine artifacts
_ a British Spitfire military plane, a reconstructed Higgins boat,
helmets, tattered Bibles and penknives _ with oral histories, short
films and re-created scenes, such as the war room where Gen. Dwight
Eisenhower and other top strategists made the decision to proceed
with the D-Day landing, and a panorama showing the vast scope of
the beach assaults.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is the first in a troika of elaborate, high-profile
tributes to the World War II era scheduled to open in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   On or around Veteran's Day this fall, ground will be broken on
the National WWII Memorial in Washington, D.C., a $100 million
monument to everyone who contributed to the war effort. And on June
4, 2001, the 57th anniversary of D-Day, the National D-Day Memorial
will be unveiled in Bedford, Va. Bedford lost 21 of its sons at
Normandy, the largest per-capita loss of any city in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But the timing seems cruel. The remaining World War II veterans
are mostly in their mid-70s or older. An estimated 1,000 die every
day. Why didn't we do something earlier, when more of the honorees
would have been around to hear the thanks personally?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question that veterans ask themselves. Douglas Owens, a
Fort Worth veteran who was one of the first soldiers ashore at
Normandy, appreciates the attention, but is a bit puzzled by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't understand is, what's the deal now? I've done
forgot about it,'' says Owens, who doesn't plan to attend the
museum opening and has only vague interest in seeing it. ``For 40
years, nobody paid any attention .... Why is everybody interested
in it now?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is a melange of factors, the simplest being the vast
scope of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are museums that honor Americans at air bases in
England, at Normandy, but nothing in the USA, partly because the
war wasn't fought here in the sense of battles taking place here,
and partly because everyone was involved,'' says Ambrose, the
historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were either in the armed forces or working in defense
plants or growing food. And how on earth do you build a monument to
everybody?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, World War II was the most massive war effort in
U.S. history, taking a huge toll between 1941 and 1945. More than
16 million served in the armed forces; 400,000 died. Virtually
everyone else in the nation contributed to the effort, by working
in one of the defense factories, by serving in the civilian support
workforce, by growing victory gardens or collecting scrap rubber,
or by simply doing without. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7493 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-3D-LEMMINGS-NYT &LR;      06-07 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-3D-LEMMINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEMMINGS ARE BACK, AND FALLING FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER OLAFSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have bushy green hair, a wardrobe borrowed from Alvin the
Chipmunk, no will (except to walk) and no instinct whatsoever for
self-preservation. When they reach a ledge, they fall. When the
fall is long and ends on a hard surface, they splat.
</P>
<P>
   The lemmings, who strolled onto the computer game scene in 1991,
have returned in their first new game in almost four years.
Lemmings Revolution, which blends conventional lemming-saving with
a modest taste of 3-D, serves as a reminder of both the pleasures
of a proven concept and the lost art of playing the good Samaritan.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny, suicidal creatures that populate this puzzle game
remain as cute as the proverbial button, and none the wiser for the
passage of time. Real-world lemmings were once said to drown
themselves during mass migrations, although now we know that they
don't really seek death _ their straight-ahead style of migration
sometimes gets them into trouble when what's ahead is a big lake or
an ocean. Their virtual cousins apparently have not heard about the
latest research and still trek inexorably, in single file, from the
entry trapdoor to their doom.
</P>
<P>
   The lemmings drown in water, cook in lava, dissolve in acid.
They are dismantled by traps or sent flying by equally tiny weasels
(the reason the lemmings are in this fix to begin with) equipped
with tiny red boxing gloves. Each still meets its demise by
squeaking, ``Oh, no!'' It sounds as if it had accidentally left its
ATM card at home.
</P>
<P>
   In each of 100 levels, you must intercede to rescue a
predetermined number of lemmings by shepherding them to hot-air
balloons before a clock runs out. They are nothing if not
adaptable. You click on icons at the side of the screen and then on
the relevant lemming to imbue it with one or more skills. Many of
the 16 included in the game (no more than 8 of them in a given
level) will be familiar from Lemmings games past.
</P>
<P>
   A ``blocker'' obstructs the path of its fellow lemmings and
sends them walking back in the opposite direction. When falling, a
``floater'' will pop open a tiny umbrella to slow its descent. A
``builder'' assembles a wooden staircase of finite length. A
``basher'' claws its way horizontally through the appropriate
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   New additions to the Lemmings canon include trampoline and
antigravity skills, which can turn a level's treacherous platforms
and pitfalls upside down. Complicating the picture are lemming
species that are impervious to certain hazards. In the course of
solving a level, you may have to attend to the needs of more than
one breed and find yourself struggling to adopt different
strategies for their different paths.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution's tone is very like the tone of early Lemmings games.
There is something delightful about watching a critter no bigger
than a hangnail scale a wall or build a bridge, plank by plank.
(It's a bit like watching an ant farm.) Moreover, the levels
preserve their airy atmosphere right up to the moment when they
turn wicked.
</P>
<P>
   These cleverly constructed challenges range from simple
explorations of a given skill to exercises in careful placement or
timing to seemingly impossible challenges that require the player
to look ahead and see beyond the obvious uses of skills. For
instance, a ``builder'' lemming's staircase isn't always a path to
higher ground. Built in the right place, it might break a lemming's
fall.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect the appeal is also related to the player's point of
view, a retreat from the unconventional perspectives of 3D
Lemmings, from 1995, and Lemmings Paintball, from 1996. In
Revolution, each level is wrapped around the exterior of a giant
spindle, which you can rotate at will with the mouse. (Hence the
title.) That gives the game the trappings of modernity without its
burdens. It is 3-D that feels almost like 2-D, and that, as a
result, comes across like the games of the early and mid-'90s:
Lemmings, Lemmings 2: Tribes and the Lemmings Chronicles.
</P>
<P>
   The resemblance is not simply physical. Revolution's creator _
Psygnosis, of Leeds, England, which published earlier Lemmings
games _ has tapped into the same wellspring of good feeling that
comes from being the savior of small, helpless creatures. In many
current games, clearing a path means killing anything that moves.
Here, it means removing anything that kills, and Revolution
distinguishes itself with this essential generosity of spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year hiatus may have been a good thing. When the
Lemmings line was in its heyday, it generated a cottage industry of
similar games: Humans, Diggers, Troddlers. Little creatures seemed
to be in jeopardy everywhere. These days, with Revolution standing
more or less alone, it's easy to develop a renewed appreciation for
its sweet style.
</P>
<P>
   Booting up the game was rather like stepping into a time
machine. It took me back to a simpler era, when such innocent
pursuits constituted a larger share of the game market, when we
were outside games more than we were in them and when most games
fit on a single disk. It's a small world after all.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution feels economical, even though the typical
installation will take up roughly 450 megabytes on your hard disk
and the minimum requirement of a 266-megahertz Pentium II is
relatively hefty for a game. It loads speedily and can be learned
easily and played quickly (though mastery is another matter). Even
at its most challenging, it is comparatively weightless.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, death remains part of the bargain here (albeit cute,
squeaky death). But it is bloodless and, at worst, an act of
omission on the player's part. The only lemmings you are likely to
have to kill outright _ using the ``nuke'' command, which
obliterates all lemmings remaining in a level _ are the
``blockers'' you have left behind because they remain fixed in
place even after they have run out of lemmings to redirect. Think
of it as a lesson not so much in death as in altruism.
</P>
<P>
   Lemming Revolution, published by Take 2 Interactive for Windows
95 and 98; $19.95; for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
