<HEADER>
A7495 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WWII-GRATITUDE-3200(3     06-07 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-GRATITUDE-3200(3rdTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TOOK SO LONG TO THANK WWII VETERANS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED: they went through. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I did what I was supposed to,'' Douglas Owens says. ``I didn't
do anything more than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those boys was brave, but they were all just
doing their job,'' Ralph Spina says. ``You know where the heroes
are? They're in the cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time I hear a veteran say something like that, I think of
my father, who served in England during the war. How many times, I
think, have I heard him say the same thing?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dad was a child of the Depression, born in 1917 and leaving
school at 16 to go to work. When the war broke out, he was 24; he
volunteered within months, ending up in England, supervising
maintenance crews that worked on bombers. Everybody he knew was
involved, somehow, in the war; to him, it was the biggest event of
his lifetime _ and nothing out of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   I am a child of the baby boom, born in 1962 and supported by my
parents through college. My peers were too young to serve in
Vietnam; I knew only a few people who served in the military. War
to me meant John Wayne movies and old men wearing military gimme
caps at the American Legion hall.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't talk about it much as I grew up. He didn't volunteer
anything beyond the occasional story about the terrible food or the
kinds of planes he used to work on. I was too self-absorbed to ask
him many questions, and when I did, he didn't really answer them. I
But five years ago, we went together to a reunion of his bomber
group at the base weher they'd been stationed in Seething, England.
He wasn't sure he wanted to go at first; he had always said he
didn't care if he ever saw Europe again. Once we got there, he
seemed to enjoy driving through the countryside and walking through
the towns he'd visited, drinking a pint at a pub he remembered. He
even told a few war stories _ about the bombers carrying his
friends who disappeared, about clustering in bunkers during the
rare nighttime airstrike, about working on planes more than 24
hours straight during the D-Day invasion, everyone knowing what was
at stake.
</P>
<P>
   What I remember most, though, was his genuine surprise when
hundreds of English citizens attended the reunion, many of them
stopping to personally thank the veterans. Many of his buddies wore
the same look of puzzled, embarrassed appreciation. I honestly
don't think they had ever really realized just what they had
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   I was so proud of Dad that day _ not just for his unselfish,
uncomplaining service, but because he was so unaware that he'd made
a sacrifice. And now, the more I hear about World War II in the
news, the more grateful I feel not just to him, but to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have a feeling I'm not the only child or grandchild who feels
that way. A rising tide of gratitude and patriotism has helped make
the books and movies about World War II more popular, which in turn
has helped raise the profile of the various memorial projects. We
baby boomers may have been selfish _ we honored our own generation
with the Vietnam memorial first _ but now, we want to rectify our
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw, born in 1940, began developing an obsession with the war
in 1984, when he covered the 40th anniversary of D-Day in Normandy.
Over the following years, he found himself bringing up the topic
with friends and dining companions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time, they would all become very quiet. They would stop
and realize how much different our lives were from those of our
parents, in terms of material wealth, opportunity, security,'' he
says. ``The current generation goes white-water rafting on the
weekend, and if somebody goes overboard, they think, oh, what an
adventure. Then they realize that when their father was 19, he was
landing in Iwo Jima or fighting in the Battle of the Bulge, or
their mother was going to work in a factory not knowing where her
husband or boyfriend or brother was. ... It just kind of all came
into focus at a time when we have no other distractions, no Vietnam
War, no civil rights movement, no social upheaval.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, all this recognition might never have happened if
celebrities hadn't gotten involved.
</P>
<P>
   Take the national memorial soon to be constructed in Washington,
D.C. The quest for a memorial was first brought up in Congress in
1987, sparked by a WWII veteran who asked his congresswoman why
there was nothing commemorating the vets. In '93, the project was
finally signed into law, and two years later, President Clinton
dedicated a site on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The project got its first big boost in 1997, when former Sen.
Bob Dole, a wounded and decorated World War II vet, signed on as
national chairman. But fund-raising was still difficult. In 1998,
the toll-free contribution line received just 5,000 calls, memorial
spokeswoman Betsy Glick says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, after ``Saving Private Ryan'' won five Oscars and Hanks
did a series of public-service announcements for the memorial, the
line received 230,000 calls, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the National D-Day Memorial Foundation was established
in Virginia in 1989, but it languished in obscurity until the 50th
anniversary ceremonies in Normandy in 1994, says foundation
President Richard Burrow. It, too, has been adopted by influential
patrons. Cartoonist Charles Schulz served as national chairman for
several years, until his death from cancer. And Spielberg recently
donated the money to build a theater in the memorial's education
center.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg, known not only for ``Saving Private Ryan'' but for
the Holocaust drama ``Schindler's List,'' has also supported the
National D-Day Museum in New Orleans, partly because of his
friendship with museum founder Ambrose, and partly because of his
movies. But his involvement is apparently more than just the
typical Hollywood publicity machine _ and it is a microcosm of how
the nation has finally reached the point of saying thank you.
</P>
<P>
   The theater that Spielberg is paying for at the Virginia
memorial will be named not for Steven Spielberg but for his father,
Arnold, who was a radio operator on a bomber during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
