<HEADER>
A7496 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WWII-GRATITUDE-3200(2     06-07 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-GRATITUDE-3200(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TOOK SO LONG TO THANK WWII VETERANS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED: simply doing without.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the war ended and the soldiers came home, America showed
its gratitude with things like the GI Bill, through which millions
of ex-soldiers went to college and received job training. As for
more-lasting tributes, they mostly consisted of things such as
little memorials at the county courthouse, or small sections in
other military museums. Meanwhile, we dedicated the Vietnam
Veterans Memorial in 1982 and the Korean War Veterans Memorial in
1995. For the men and women of World War II, there was nothing
comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose, other historians and veterans all concede that the
reasons for that omission are complicated, bound up in everything
from the psyche of a generation brought up stoically during the
Great Depression and the nation's ill-fated involvement in Vietnam
to nostalgia and a later generation's search for heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The commemorative efforts follow, not coincidentally, a raft of
news media attention, starting with coverage of the 50th
anniversary of D-Day in 1994. After that, books such as Ambrose's
``D-Day'' and Brokaw's ``The Greatest Generation,'' the personal
stories of mostly nonfamous survivors of World War II, hit the
bestseller lists. And most famously, there was ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' the '98 Spielberg/Hanks film that graphically depicted the
battles of Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, the spate of recognition follows the natural cycle of
things: Anniversaries provide a natural looking-back point; Ambrose
points out that Civil War veterans received a similar outpouring of
gratitude 50 years later. And part of the reason is that the nation
is ready to hear these stories.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s were too early; veterans were busy building careers,
raising families. And the '60s and '70s, when many veterans were in
their prime, were too late; by then, the nation had become involved
in the divisive Vietnam conflict, which soured many on the idea of
honoring anything to do with war.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the '80s and '90s, and growing national
disenchantment with corporate greed, political infighting and
senseless violent crimes, that the World War II era would be looked
at with admiration, with respect, as a time when America was
unquestionably in the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the century, when we looked back, it was hard to
in any way diminish the importance of World War II,'' says Brokaw,
the NBC news anchor whose bestselling 1998 book, ``The Greatest
Generation,'' has been credited with fueling the new respect for
the era.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stop and think about what the world would be like if we
had not prevailed, and it's a pretty unsettling thought. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, that unsavory business with (Monica) Lewinsky and
(Ken) Starr and the president left everybody with a great craving
to hear about something uplifting and heroic and good.''
</P>
<P>
   World War II stories fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're honoring in the D-Day Museum, and all these other
memorials, and in `Saving Private Ryan,' is a whole generation, and
a world view. We're honoring a time when life seemed simple and
people seemed nobler and we knew the difference between right and
wrong,'' says Steve Gillon, a history professor at the University
of Oklahoma who hosts a weekly talk show on the History Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a D-Day today, every person who came within 100
yards of the beach would have a press agent and would be out
selling their story to Fox News. These men, they just came home and
went back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, that's exactly why the stories were slow to be told.
Toughened by the Depression, raised to accept their lot
uncomplainingly and to support their country unquestioningly, those
who lived through the war didn't think it was their place to talk
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only struck me in the last year or two, but they're almost
embarrassed when they're treated like heroes,'' says Nick Mueller,
a history professor at the University of New Orleans who was
drinking sherry with Ambrose in his back yard when Ambrose first
mentioned the idea of a museum. He is now the chairman of the
museum's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're pleased in a way, but deep down, they feel
that the real heroes were the guys who didn't make it. ... I think
they feel that to allow themselves to be treated as heroes demeans
the sacrifice of the friends who they lost, who didn't come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose, who has interviewed thousands of veterans while
researching such popular books as ``Band of Brothers'' and
``D-Day,'' concurs. Almost to a man, World War II veterans insist
that they didn't do anything special, that everybody sacrificed.
And most of them didn't really care to relive what they went
through. MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
