<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLING A ROCKY ROLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are certain types of women that Anne Archer finds very
attractive. Artsy. Opinionated. A little wild, perhaps. Definitely
eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   Women a lot like Rockie Rogers, the impulsive, mentally unstable
character Archer plays in Robert Glaudini's drama ``The Poison
Tree,'' which opens a six-week run tonight at the Mark Taper Forum.
</P>
<P>
   In her younger and more vulnerable days, in the 1970s, Rockie
was the toast of the La Jolla intelligentsia. Sexy and
cosmopolitan, she hobnobbed with renowned, worldly figures like the
philosopher Herbert Marcuse. Once, Rockie was asked to pose by the
German surrealist painter Max Ernst _ or so she says, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But after 15 years of a financially secure, emotionally humdrum
marriage to a conservative Superior Court judge, the twice-divorced
Rockie is feeling stifled and confused. She's also grieving the
recent loss of her beloved son due to a drug overdose.
</P>
<P>
   With a personality as bumpy as her name, Rockie is a woman on
the verge.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lives in the past, when her life was more on the edge,
even though it was probably hell,'' Archer says during a recent
pre-rehearsal break.
</P>
<P>
   ``She misses living that dream, that crazy, wild dream, where
she was the center of things and was sexy and beautiful, and
everybody was interested in her.''
</P>
<P>
   As Glaudini's play quickly establishes, life can be harsh to
women like Rockie who've outlived their glamorous years and are
losing their grip on reality.
</P>
<P>
   But characters like Rockie also make life rewarding for female
actors of a certain age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting because, well, you know what roles are like for
women in film,'' says Archer, who's probably best-known for blowing
a hole through a knife-wielding Glenn Close in Adrian Lyne's
``Fatal Attraction'' (1987).
</P>
<P>
   ``There just aren't great roles for women, especially if you're
not in your 20s,'' continues Archer, whose aversion to revealing
her own age in print would be hard to overstate. (For the record,
she could pass for a dozen years younger than her recorded age.)
``So this (role), it's a gift, really, it's a beautiful gift to be
able to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Taper audiences conditioned by Archer's Hollywood image may be
in for a surprise this summer. As Beth Gallagher in ``Fatal
Attraction'' and Dr. Cathy Ryan opposite Harrison Ford in ``Patriot
Games'' and ``Clear and Present Danger,'' she comes across as a
wholesome, warmly sensual presence, an intelligent, middle-class
woman who probably went to good schools and drinks chardonnay at
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Rockie, spiky and paranoid, exists at a very different point on
the post-'70s, post-feminist spectrum. Adding to her life's other
complications, her husband (played by Bob Gunton) is presiding over
a harrowing court case involving a young woman who apparently has
castrated three male surfers. And Rockie is struggling with her own
strange attraction to a young poet (Christian Camargo) bearing an
eerie resemblance to her dead son.
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Glaudini says he had admired Archer's film work for
some time, but also suspected there were hidden depths to her
previous screen characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the kick I get is that, `Well, maybe some of those
women that she played had another whole big story, you know what I
mean?''' Glaudini says. ``And maybe Rockie can express part of
that, that never makes it into the films where the man's the hero
and the lead, and she's the support. So I just was gambling that
underneath the lid of that is a lot of stuff waiting to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer says she's never had to work so hard at a role, or
explore so much psychological backstory, as she has had to do with
Rockie. Beth Gallagher, comparatively, was a piece of cake,
although ``if I was playing Glenn's role, I would've needed the
backstory for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of her more emotionally complicated film roles haven't been
seen by that many people, Archer says, mentioning one upcoming part
as an alcoholic whose daughters were sexually abused by her former
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's last stage appearance was about eight years ago. She
has appeared at the prestigious Williamstown Theatre Festival in
``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' and co-starred in both the
off-Broadway and Los Angeles productions of ``A Coupla' White
Chicks Sitting Around Talking.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the extremity of their situations, several characters in
``The Poison Tree'' strike personal chords with Archer, who was
born and raised in Los Angeles and is the daughter of screen actors
John Archer and Marjorie Lord. She is married to producer-director
Terry Jastrow and has two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the characters in the play I've had actually in my life,''
she says, ``so there's a lot of rich stuff that I can feed on.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Rockie, it's her taste for great art and interesting
people, her appetite for life rather than her taste for
self-destruction, that makes her a woman after Archer's own heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the richest parts of the play for me: that
you'll die if you don't have art in your life. You'll die. I feel
that way. That's one of the reasons I did this play: To have a
chance to do this keeps me alive.''
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
What: ``The Poison Tree.'' &QL; 
Where: Mark Taper Forum, Performing Arts Center of Los Angeles
County, 135 N. Grand Ave., downtown. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Tuesdays through Fridays, 2:30 and 8 p.m. Saturdays,
2:30 and 7:30 p.m. Sundays; thorugh July 16. &QL; 
Tickets: $29 to $42. Call (213) 628-2772.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
