<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-KIDS-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      06-07 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN MOHAMMED CAN'T GET TO THE MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALICE KEIM   
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was lucky enough to grow up in New York City, just a few
blocks from Museum Mile. My art history classes included weekly
visits to the Metropolitan Museum of Art; I learned about dinosaurs
at the American Museum of Natural History. But, while nothing can
replace the experience of seeing a masterpiece up close, the Web
means that museum education is no longer geographically restricted.
Some of the world's most remarkable institutions have Web sites
specifically designed for children and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Art Safari (http://artsafari.moma.org/), a site by the Museum of
Modern Art in New York is by far the most impressive art education
site for children that I have seen. (For adults, the MOMA site also
has online projects and collaborations with various artists, and
helpful commentary and information on the museum's exhibitions and
collections.)
</P>
<P>
   The online activities provide a virtual experience similar to
what a child might have at a weekend museum workshop. Students
focus on a selected sculpture or painting from the museum's
collection as they answer a series of questions about each piece.
The activity encourages close observation and active imagination.
At the end of the sequence of questions, children are asked to
create their own masterpiece using the online art tools.
</P>
<P>
   I picked Picasso's ``She-Goat'' and answered five on-screen
questions about the sculpture. Afterward, my answers appeared on
screen in story form. The site also suggested ways to create my own
sculpture using everyday found objects as Picasso did, or using the
site's online art program. Using the online tools, I struggled to
manipulate the pictures of a bowling pin, baseball, a spoon,
eyeglasses, a hammer and a bowl to form the shape of a cat. The
recommended non-virtual, live project might have been more fun. I
also did the exercises for works by Frida Kahlo, Henri Rousseau,
and Diego Rivera. Each has its own online questions and art tools,
all of which were easier to use than the Picasso project.
</P>
<P>
   On the home page of the Natural History Museum in London
(www.nhm.ac.uk), I clicked on Interactive and brought up a page
with links to eight different interactive activities. I visited
AntCast and after patiently waiting for the live video stream
watched two ants slowly make their way around what looked like a
piece of wood. I was not all that interested in watching an English
ant go about its daily routine, but my third graders who study ants
would have been delighted.
</P>
<P>
   The Earthlab Datasite, which contains information on fossils,
rocks and minerals in the United Kingdom, is an extensive and a
wonderful resource for a middle school or high school science
student.
</P>
<P>
   Science Casebook has sections on meteorites and speculates on
the possibility of a real Jurassic Park. There is also a
fascinating account of the Beast of Bodmin Moor, a legendary
catlike animal in Cornwall, England.
</P>
<P>
   Dinosaur-crazed students will find the Dinosaur Data Files and
the Quest II to be the gems of this extensive site. Educators
should find the Dinosaur Data files, fact sheets on 28 different
types of dinosaurs, extremely useful. Each file contains the name,
proper pronunciation, origin, size, feeding preferences and other
facts about each dinosaur. While the information is designed for
the classroom, many of the suggested activities could be used at
home.
</P>
<P>
   In the Quest II section students can become museum scientists.
Online tools and data allow students to examine and draw
conclusions about a dozen objects. For example, I investigated the
physical and historical traits of a butterfly using a virtual
magnifying glass and scale. (When finished I could have submitted
my notes to be posted on the Web.) After completing my research I
clicked on the book icon to learn the full details of my specimen.
The language and tools are appropriate for children as young as 8.
Quest is available in five languages.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Franklin Institute Science Museum
(http://www.fi.edu/), has a fantastic exploration of the human
heart, including a tour of valves and arteries using actual
photographs and some medical terms that may require a dictionary.
Younger users can skip some of the denser biology sections and use
the table of contents to go directly to an area of interest. The
site also has excellent pages on weather, earth forces like
volcanoes and earthquakes, a program about early aviation and a
large area on Benjamin Franklin. Some sections are a bit text heavy
for a child to use independently but are worth a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the museums with extensive online activities or
tours for children or adults.
</P>
<P>
   THE SAN DIEGO NATURAL HISTORY MUSEUM:
www.sdnhm.org/kids/index.html
</P>
<P>
   THE EXPLORATORIUM: www.exploratorium.edu
</P>
<P>
   THE METROPOLITAN MUSEUM OF ART: www.metmuseum.org
</P>
<P>
   THE NATIONAL GALLERY OF ART: www.nga.gov/home.htm
</P>
<P>
   THE LOUVRE: www.louvre.fr/louvrea.htm
</P>
<P>
   THE GUGGENHEIM MUSEUM: www.guggenheim.org
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
