<SLUG> BC-MATCHBOX-20-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCHBOX TARGETS NEW FANS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year around this time, the Orlando, Fla., pop-rock outfit
Matchbox Twenty was in danger of slipping into the ``Where Are They
Now?'' file.
</P>
<P>
   The quintet's 1996 mega-selling debut, ``Yourself or Someone
Like You,'' had dropped off the charts and hit singles including
``Push'' and ``3am'' were turning into golden oldies.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Carlos Santana's sensual salsa-tinged single, ``Smooth,''
featuring Matchbox Twenty's Rob Thomas on vocals, stormed the
charts, transforming Thomas into an instant superstar. Suddenly,
everyone remembered his band, which was in the studio taking its
time with the next album, the recently released ``Mad Season.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday at the intimate Wilshire-Ebell Theatre, the restorative
powers of ``Smooth'' could be felt. Clumps of females stood at
their seats dancing and singing along with every song as the
triple-Grammy-winning Thomas and company gave fans a taste of the
new album, which entered the charts last week at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Matchbox's strength is in radio ballads, sweetly tuneful
classic-rock sing-alongs like the current Top 20 hit ``Bent'' or
the title track of the new disc, universal numbers that benefit
from whisper-to-a-scream dynamics and chiming hooks delivered by
dual guitarists Kyle Cook and Adam Gaynor.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most affecting moments came with turbulent songs
like ``Angry'' and ``You Won't Be Mine,'' both off ``Mad Season.''
Readings of earlier hits, including ``Real World,'' ``Push'' and
``3am,'' drew fans to their feet while the sound of female voices
sometimes threatened to drown out the singer on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is a refreshing figure, a seemingly regular guy with a
convincing vocal delivery who did something few rock stars do on
stage anymore _ he talked to the audience, asking if they were
having a good time, thanking them for their reaction and offering
comments on the venue, which hadn't hosted a rock concert in nearly
a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sanctioned _ and kosher,'' Thomas said gleefully.
</P>
<P>
   And then some. The recently married Thomas' every dramatic
inflection met with screams from the packed audience.
</P>
<P>
   In concert, Matchbox Twenty, augmented Tuesday by a keyboardist
and horn section on some numbers, concentrates on tight,
well-played music, which sometimes recalls Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish
with its melodic, radio-ready appeal. The smoldering Thomas and his
musicians were mostly static, and the singer rarely strayed from
the microphone center-stage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the music's occasional lack of personality, the band
clearly gave it all they had. The only question is whether Matchbox
Twenty can keep coming up with hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
