   MICROSOFT-RULING (Undated) _ In a blistering attack on the
Microsoft Corp., U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson orders
the company split in two. Undaunted by the judge's declaration that
Microsoft has ``proved untrustworthy in the past,'' Chairman Bill
Gates vows to appeal. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN and GREG HASSELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OBESE-KIDS (Washington) _ If U.S. officials and major health
organizations have their way, french fries, pizza and colas will be
seen less in school lunchrooms. Students will get more fruits,
vegetables and low-fat meats. With obesity rates of U.S. children
at an all-time high, the government and five health organizations
launch a program to stamp out fast food for kids, at least in
schools. The officials also urge more exercise for a slothful
generation of children. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GENETIC-DISCRIMINATION (Washington) _ J. Craig Venter, a leading
pioneer in the quest to map the body's total genetic blueprint
tells Congress that the possibility of genetic discrimination
threatens to stall advances in biotechnology. He says employers and
insurers could use the DNA information to refuse to hire or provide
health coverage for people genetically disposed to the early
onslaught of disease. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-EXPERIMENT (Undated) _ An Arizona couple thwarted in
their bid to have their son's cancer treated by controversial
Houston doctor Stanislaw Burzynski have taken the boy to Mexico for
the same alternative therapy tried by basketball player Kim Perrot
a year ago. The boy, Thomas Navarro, is receiving insulin-induced
coma treatment, an experimental therapy that is showing promise in
advanced cancer patients but had not previously been studied in
humans or animals. By TODD ACKERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BIBLES-SCHOOL (Willis, Texas) _ School officials in this town
northwest of Houston respond to some pupils' recent accusations
that a teacher threw their Bibles into the trash and another
teacher made a boy remove his Ten Commandments book cover. By
HARVEY RICE.
</P>
