<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RANGER FANS TAKE NOTICE: DEVILS EXIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Memo to all you Ranger fans and all the
others, judging by the Neilsen ratings, who are pretending that the
Devils don't exist: admit that this is the hockey team you wish was
yours.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers were only one victory away from winning the
Stanley Cup in 1994, you acted as if they had invented ice, that
the National Hockey League had never existed until Mark Messier put
on a Ranger sweater. But if the Devils dethrone the Dallas Stars in
Thursday night's fifth game of the Stanley Cup finals, they will
have won the cup twice in the last six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers won the cup in 1994, they had won it twice in
55 seasons. At that rate, it will be 2048 before the Rangers win it
again. All you Ranger fans should live so long.
</P>
<P>
   But your attitude toward the Devils is typical. When the
Islanders won four consecutive Stanley Cup championships from 1980
to 1983, all you Ranger fans pretended that the Islanders didn't
exist.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the Islanders do hardly exist, even with new owners,
but stop pretending that the Devils don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   If the Devils win the cup again, they will have already
accomplished what the Knicks have done in more than half a century
and what the Mets have done in nearly 40 years: win two
championships. They will have as many Stanley Cup titles as the
Giants have Super Bowl trophies, and one more championship than the
Jets have had in 40 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   You and too many others don't seem to realize that the Devils
should be easy to appreciate because they possess what so few
franchises in any of the four major sports possess anymore _
throwback class and charm.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, John McMullen, is not a corporate honcho fronting for
the stockholders. He put up his own money to purchase the Colorado
Rockies nearly two decades ago and move the franchise to where he
lives, New Jersey. And he seldom blows up or sputters.
</P>
<P>
   The 82-year-old McMullen has said he now has remorse over having
sold the club to the YankeeNets organization for delivery in July,
but if the Devils win the cup, his name will be engraved on it
again, not the name of George Steinbrenner or Lewis Katz.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen has been a rarity, a club owner his players not only
respect but also cherish. Lou Lamoriello is a rarity, too, a
general manager the players respect and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the players both cherish and fear the coach even
though Larry Robinson's defining moment occurred when he yelled
loudly at them after they fell behind the Philadelphia Flyers, 3-1,
in the Eastern Conference finals. Even before they rallied with
three straight victories, the players agreed that they deserved to
be chewed out.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, hockey players are like that. As a group, they are
the most honest and the most humble of professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the calmly conscientious Canadian culture that
surrounded the upbringing of many NHL players, but the
multimillion-dollar contracts haven't spoiled them. Or changed
them. With too many players in too many other sports, more money
often means more nonsense. But as a group, hockey players are
pretty solid citizens.
</P>
<P>
   If Scott Stevens and Martin Brodeur, the rocks upon which the
Devils have been built, were on the Rangers, there would be statues
of both outside Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   If Ken Daneyko, the bearded and burly defenseman who has played
in every playoff game in Devils' history, were on the Rangers, he
would be a folk hero in the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patrik Elias-Jason Arnott-Petr Sykora line was on the
Rangers, it would already be compared to the Rod Gilbert-Jean
Ratelle-Vic Hadfield line of three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers need is what the Devils have: the warriors
Bobby Holik, Randy McKay, Claude Lemieux, Scott Neidermayer and Jay
Pandolfo; the Russian artistes Sergei Brylin, Alexander Mogilny,
Vladimir Malakhov and Sergei Nemchinov (the only ex-Ranger); and
the mature rookies: John Madden, Scott Gomez, Brian Rafalski and
Colin White.
</P>
<P>
   Put them all together and the Devils are within a winning goal
of another Stanley Cup celebration.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Devils skate around the ice with the Stanley Cup
Thursday night (or Saturday night or Monday night), all you Ranger
fans should break down and applaud. You can just say the Devils
made you do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
