<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT IDLES, THEN STALLS OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movie promoters, especially in the
fun-at-the-cost-of-any-brain-cells summer season, like to tell you
that their picture is ``a ride.'' It's their favorite description,
one they hope will attract thrill-seekers of all ages and cognitive
limitations. After all, who doesn't like a roller coaster,
especially one with minimal chance of causing nausea or damaged
vertebrae?
</P>
<P>
   While anything heralded as such a ride is rarely a cause for
critical celebration, there are, obviously, certain movies that
should be nothing but.
</P>
<P>
   Movies like ``Gone in 60 Seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   So how come this potential Lamborghini of ride movies stalls at
every turn?
</P>
<P>
   Astonishingly, the, um, brain trust behind this slick, expensive
remake of H.B. Halicki's down-and-dirty, 1974 redneck romp decided
that stealing cool cars and spectacularly wrecking them wasn't what
this movie should really be about. They figured it should be about
the characters and relationships of guys who steal cars. Bad idea
going in, even worse in execution when you consider that characters
and relationships are pretty much the last options anyone goes to
movies produced by Jerry Bruckheimer and scripted by Scott
Rosenberg (``Armageddon,'' ``Con Air'') for.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, motives and connections here are dramatically
rudimentary at best. But we're still forced to spend extensive time
idling over the drivel before the movie finally gets down to its
big, 50-car heist climax _ which, by the stretch, powers too little
excitement, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Cage is legendary auto thief Memphis Raines, now happily
retired from the mean streets of Long Beach and running a kiddie
go-kart track. But Raines' dopey little brother, Kip (Giovanni
Ribisi), wants to follow in his notorious sibling's tire tracks.
Kip's Porsche theft for a ruthless English crime boss (Christopher
Eccleston) brings down the heat (Delroy Lindo is quite good as an
ever-frustrated, tough-but-decent detective). The upshot: either
Memphis comes out of retirement and delivers 50 luxury models in
one night, or the bad Brit sends Kip to the steel compactor.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good deal of time spent convincing the equally
straight members of Memphis' old gang to re-up for the cause.
Grandfatherly mentor Otto (Robert Duvall) is happy with his legit
customizing business. Mem's ex-squeeze Sway (Angelina Jolie, given
little more to do than strut around in waistlength platinum
dreadlocks) has a two-track career _ mechanic and dive bartender _
she does not wish to jeopardize. The Sphinx (English soccer star
Vinnie Jones, who made a great screen debut in last year's ``Lock,
Stock and Two Smoking Barrels''), still doesn't speak.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't take long for these old pros and several more to
team up with Kip's younger, rasher crew. There are half a dozen of
these kids, too, which should give you some indication of just how
superficially they're all defined. There simply is not enough time
to give so many characters their due, even in a film that's so
inexplicably more talk than action.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Dominic Sena. He made his name doing music
videos in the early '90s, has made his living with award-winning
commercials since, and directed one interesting, noirish road
thriller with Brad Pitt and David Duchovny, ``Kalifornia,'' some
years ago. Sena knows how to make well-painted rolled steel look
its best (not hard), throws in some clever if not breathtaking
stunt driving (required some wit) and stages the big chase decently
enough (but where's William Friedkin the few times these days when
you actually need him?).
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, though, Sena lets his actors walk around too much. What
about the title ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' was so hard to understand? &QL; 
--- &QL; 
- The film: ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' (PG-13; violence, sex,
language) &QL; 
- The stars: Nicolas Cage, Giovanni Ribisi, Angelina Jolie, Robert
Duvall, Will Patton, Delroy Lindo, Christopher Eccleston, Scott
Caan, Vinnie Jones. &QL; 
- Behind the scenes: Directed by Dominic Sena. Written by Scott
Rosenberg. Produced by Jerry Bruckheimer and Mike Stenson. Released
by Touchstone Pictures. &QL; 
- Running time: One hour, 58 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
