<SLUG> BC-ALA-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA JUDGE WHO CHAMPIONS TEN COMMANDMENTS WINS GOP PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  ATLANTA _ Despite being vastly outspent, Judge Roy S. Moore, the
Alabama jurist made famous for his defense of the Ten Commandments,
won a convincing victory in Tuesday's Republican primary for chief
justice of the Alabama Supreme Court.
  ``Of course we give our first recognition to God,'' Moore said in
an interview Wednesday. ``He has providence over us and his will is
something that can't be thwarted.''
  Moore, who sits on the Etowah County Circuit Court in Gadsden,
Ala., ran against three Republican opponents, all well-respected
judges. One, Associate Justice Harold See of the state Supreme
Court, was the consensus favorite of Alabama's business leaders and
raised more than $1.1 million for the race, four times as much as
Moore did.
  Yet Moore won 55 percent of the vote, surprising many political
analysts by easily avoiding a runoff. See finished second, with 30
percent, followed by Judge Pam Baschab of the state Court of
Criminal Appeals, with 8 percent, and Judge Wayne Thorn of the
Jefferson County Circuit Court in Birmingham, Ala., with 7 percent.
  Moore, 53, will now face Judge Sharon Yates, a Democrat who sits
on the state Court of Civil Appeals, in the general election in
November. Yates had no opposition in her party's primary.
  Polls taken only days before Tuesday's primary suggested that
Moore and See were in a tight race and would probably find
themselves in a runoff. But with little interest by voters in other
races on the ballot, including two meaningless presidential
primaries, turnout was low across the state. The poor turnout
apparently benefited Moore, whose Christian conservative supporters
showed their commitment by getting to the polls.
  It was the second significant victory for the religious right in
Alabama in less than a year. In October, Christian conservatives
mobilized to defeat a referendum that would have permitted a state
lottery in Alabama.
  Moore received national attention three years ago when he defied
another judge's order that he remove a handmade wooden tablet of
the Ten Commandments that he had hung behind his bench. He also
continued to invite Alabama pastors to begin court sessions with a
prayer, again despite a judge's order to stop. The rulings came in
response to a lawsuit against Moore filed by the American Civil
Liberties Union.
  Ever since then, Moore has been an icon of the Christian
conservative movement, praised at rallies across Alabama and
invited to speak around the country. He makes it clear in his talks
that he believes that God's law, as revealed in the Bible, is the
source of man's law and that Christian principles form the
foundation of American government and jurisprudence. He said
Wednesday that if he wins he will take his Ten Commandments plaque
with him to the Supreme Court, though he does not know whether he
will hang it in his chambers or behind the court's bench.
  Moore's victory places Alabama's traditionally Republican business
leaders in a bind. They are likely to find Yates difficult to
embrace, but may also fear that Alabama will again be portrayed as
a backwater should Moore become the chief justice. In the 1998
gubernatorial election, many business leaders opposed the incumbent
Republican, Fob James Jr., because he had emphasized conservative
stands on social issues, particularly school prayer, to the
detriment of the state's industrial recruitment efforts. James won
the primary but lost the general election.
  Bill O'Connor, president of the Business Council of Alabama, said
his members would have to re-evaluate the race in light of See's
defeat. ``Our concern is simply that we help to elect judges who
follow the law and don't make the law from the bench,'' he said.
  Wayne Flynt, a historian at Auburn University in Auburn, Ala.,
predicted that the general election would be a tight race, and that
the primary showed that Yates would have to be tread carefully in
challenging Moore. ``She can't make fun of him,'' he said. ``She
has to talk about her respect for the Ten Commandments and how she
can understand why people might want to have them on courtroom
walls, but that there are other issues. If she makes him a martyr,
he'll win by a landslide.''
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
