<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JamCam 3.0 and Jam-It For Pictures and Sound
</P>
<P>
   As every parent finds out, children will abandon even the most
elaborate and expensive toys to play with one of the following: an
old camera, a tape recorder and the box the elaborate and expensive
toy came in.
</P>
<P>
   KB Gear Interactive has heeded the tastes of children with this
year's crop of Jam products. JamCam 3.0 is the new version of the
company's down-market digital camera. The original JamCam, released
in 1998, was a popular alternative for people who did not want to
spend a lot of money. It also appealed to those users (children and
artists) who did not mind its low-tech feel and uneven results.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution on the new $99 JamCam 3.0 is the same as previous
models, 640-by-480 pixels, but the company says software
enhancements have helped picture quality. The new version also has
a built-in flash, a self-timer and a slot for up to 64 megabytes of
expandable memory.
</P>
<P>
   What the JamCam is to pictures, the Jam-It, billed as an
inexpensive ``digital sound studio,'' is to sound. The Jam-It ($49)
can record up to four minutes of sounds or voices. Once the Jam-It
is attached to a PC through the microphone jack, the sounds can be
downloaded in Jam-It software, manipulated and converted into sound
files that can be sent as attachments to e-mail messages,
incorporated into digital images, speeded up, slowed down or
synchronized with one of 15 preloaded rhythm tracks. KB Gear has
also introduced a new MP3 player that is called the JamP3 and sells
for less than $100. It has 16 megabytes of onboard memory but an
expandable memory slot that can hold a 64MB card. Like the new
JamCam, the Jam-It comes in metallic blue or silver. All three will
be available in August.
</P>
<P>
   HOLD THE PHONE _ A new survey suggests that e-mail users tend to
make fewer long-distance phone calls, but that doesn't mean that
they are ready to abandon the telephone altogether. The study,
published in the journal Communication Research, found that almost
half of the 309 Columbus, Ohio, residents surveyed had used
long-distance less after they began using personal e-mail, although
they were not asked how much less. But the respondents still rated
the telephone very high for socializing and as a way to express
emotion, while e-mail was favored when there was a scheduling
conflict or when a phone call would otherwise have to be made to a
different time zone.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallery of Glimpses Of the Martian Surface
</P>
<P>
   Mars spacecraft have gotten a lot of bad press in the last year
or so, but the Mars Global Surveyor has been a good Boy Scout since
it was launched in 1996 (and like a good Boy Scout, it even helped
in the search for one of the spacecraft that was lost).
</P>
<P>
   Part of Global Surveyor's job is to obtain images of the Martian
surface using a special camera operated by Malin Space Science
Systems under contract to NASA. A gallery of images _ more than
27,000 of them _ is available at the contractor's site,
www.msss.com/moc(underscore)gallery/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   The images include high-resolution shots of specific surface
elements, regional views of larger-scale features and wide-angle
strips covering thousands of miles that show weather patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The high-resolution images tend to be the most interesting, and
potentially the most useful to Internet millionaires planning their
next real estate purchase _ a ranchette, perhaps, in the foothills
of Olympus Mons.
</P>
<P>
   Human Touch Still Important in College Search, Poll Finds
</P>
<P>
   Most college-bound students have access to the Internet and use
it voraciously to help them decide what schools to apply to, but
they still consider human contact most important in the process,
according to a survey that will be released next week.
</P>
<P>
   The survey by Art &AMP; Science Group polled 500 high school seniors
who intended to apply to four-year colleges and found that 94
percent of the students had Web access, a leap from 30 percent
among students polled four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that the use of computers and the Web for
the college application process did not differ greatly between
white students and minority students, although the study did not
differentiate between blacks, Asian-Americans or other ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single respondent said he did not have access to a
computer anytime he wanted one, whether at home or school, said
Richard A. Hesel, publisher of Art &AMP; Science, which is sponsored by
Embark.com, an online applications company. When students were
asked how they gathered information, 48 percent said from guidance
counselors and 37 percent said from Web sites, while others
mentioned friends, books or parents. When asked what was most
influential in deciding where to enroll, campus visits was first,
followed by parents and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Find Old Books on the Web, Then Prepare to Pay the Price
</P>
<P>
   The Web has made it easier to track down used books, but not
without a price, according to a study by two Ohio University
professors.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 189 booksellers who listed their products with the
Advanced Book Exchange found that 34 percent charged higher prices
to customers arriving on the Web instead of through the front door.
``Everyone assumes when you go online, the prices will be
cheaper,'' said one of the researchers, Phyllis Bernt, a professor
of communication systems management. ``But by having access to a
world of buyers, the used-book seller is in a much better pricing
position for items that are unique.'' She did the study with her
husband, Joseph, an associate professor of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Prices vary according to the type of book, the study found.
Low-end books, like recent mass market romance paperbacks, are all
but unavailable on the Web because postage costs generally exceed
their value, Phyllis Bernt said. The prices of books that are
desirable but commonly available have either remained stable or
fallen because of Web sales, the Bernts found. But there has been a
big impact on books that are hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   A small minority of respondents, 1.7 percent, said they believed
that the Web had raised prices for used books by as much as 200
percent. ``I suspect it will become increasingly difficult to find
books at what we now regard as reasonable prices,'' Joseph Bernt
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
