<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS `PIMPS' SELLING?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything you didn't want to know about the world's oldest
management position is on display in the regrettable documentary
``American Pimp.''
</P>
<P>
   The talented twin filmmakers Allen and Albert Hughes (``Menace
II Society,'' ``Dead Presidents'') spent two years gathering
bad-looking video interviews with masters of that mysterious trade.
They clearly wanted to examine the myth of the black urban pimp on
its practitioners' own terms, evidently hoping that the resulting
work would expose the racist and class hypocrisy that's
automatically levelled against what are, after all, some of the
most aggressive capitalists the American system has produced.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hughes' brothers made the fatal mistake of giving these
yahoos way too much rope. Amusing and charismatic as many of them
are (no doubt crucial job skills), the pimps, to a man, ooze such
virulent, unadulterated contempt for the women they exploit that
any arguments for their behavior are buried in raging slime.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not offended by the fact that these guys sell sex for
a living, you are because they're so selfish and disdainful of
everybody who's not like them. And that's a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Hugheses somehow admire their subjects or not is
open to question. Obviously, they've tried to make a serious
inquiry here, though they do have fun with juxtaposing real
players' insights against the romanticized macks '70s
blaxploitation films lionized.
</P>
<P>
   But by not really presenting counter-opinions in the movie _ a
couple of working girls discuss their managers in broad terms, and
the rapper Too Short, well, rhapsodizes about the life he makes his
living memorializing in song _ the Hugheses appear to endorse their
loquacious entrepreneurs' self-serving views.
</P>
<P>
   Disheartening as the overall atmosphere of ``American Pimp'' may
be, it also, quite expectedly, offers much to laugh at _ if you can
stay in the mood to do so. Vulgarity in Cadillacs and eyewear has
never been presented in so concentrated a form. One retired
businessman takes us to his proud mother's apartment, where photos
of himself with such diverse luminaries as Marion Barry, Al Green
and Donald Trump are displayed. They hold conventions and give one
another trophies. And there's a lot of tasteful jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of these guys, who go by names such as Rosebudd, Charm
and Payroll, has at least one interesting anecdote to share. We
also learn that pimps have their sensitive sides, since most of
them agree that they feel bad whenever a girl of theirs gets
murdered. Sterling insights are of the `That Hugh Hefner? He's just
a pimp, too' variety.
</P>
<P>
   Funny stuff. Except for all the barely contained, unexamined
hatred, that is. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
- The film: ``American Pimp'' (Not rated; language, nudity) &QL; 
- Behind the scenes: Directed by Allen and Albert Hughes. Produced
by the Hughes Brothers and Kevin Messick. Released by Seventh Art
Releasing. &QL; 
- Running time: One hour, 28 minutes &QL; 
- Playing: Nuart, West L.A. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
