<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT `CUCKOO'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two obvious reasons to watch ``Girl, Interrupted'' _
Angelina Jolie and Winona Ryder. While Jolie had the splashier role
in this story based on writer Susanna Kaysen's account of her
two-year stay at a mental hospital in the late 1960s, Ryder's
performance as Susanna simmers.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to dismiss this film _ as some have _ as just a
variation on ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' but ``Girl,''
which is new to video, isn't about who's really insane _ the
inmates or the keepers or the whole system. What seems to be
overlooked in the rush to make ``Cuckoo's Nest'' comparisons is
that the film is called ``Girl, Interrupted.'' It is not so much a
condemnation of our mental institutions (actually, the hospital
staff in the film is portrayed as being fairly sensitive) as it is
about the confining social and psychological states that have been
placed on women for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Susanna isn't crazy. She's an upper-middle-class white girl from
New England who just graduated from high school and doesn't know
what she wants to do with her life.
</P>
<P>
   One night, Susanna consumes a bottle of aspirin and a bottle of
vodka. ``My hands have no bones,'' she observes. Her family panics
and sends her to a psychiatrist who diagnoses her as having a
borderline personality disorder. They then convince her to commit
herself to Claymoore, an upscale psychiatric institution.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget that well into the 1900s there were some
states in which a wife could be institutionalized simply on her
husband's say-so. Even in 1967, when this film begins, women's
liberation was just beginning to take hold in many parts of
America. Would Susanna's parents have been so quick to stick her in
an institution had she been a boy?
</P>
<P>
   The girls that Susanna encounters at Claymoore are, as expected,
worse off. There's Polly (Elisabeth Moss), who's been scarred by
self-inflicted burns; Daisy (Brittany Murphy), with a weird eating
disorder; Georgina (Clea Duvall), a pathological liar who adores Oz
books; and Lisa (Jolie), an engaging sociopath whose cool exterior
masks her traumas.
</P>
<P>
   There's a scene where the girls break into a doctor's office
late at night and read their psychological profiles, which doesn't
tell them anything they don't already know. And once we get to know
the girls and their situations, the film doesn't really show us
anything we haven't guessed.
</P>
<P>
   We know that Susanna _ with the help of a nurse played by Whoopi
Goldberg (``You are a lazy, self-indulgent little girl who is
driving yourself crazy'') _ will make it out, but the story is
ultimately more melodramatic than insightful. It's not that
director James Mangold has made a bad film. He has made a decent
one and should be commended for avoiding too much sentimentality,
but in the end it was perhaps too polite.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ryder's performance as Susanna is first-rate as
she moves from her confused state to one of self-awareness, and
that is what will keep you watching.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder also starred in the 1994 film ``Little Women,'' which was
recently released as a special-edition DVD. Louisa May Alcott's
19th-century novel, as told by director Gillian Armstrong and
writer Robin Swicord, also looks at the plight of women. It's the
story of the four March sisters, who, along with their mother
(Susan Sarandon), must cope with the absence of their father, who
is off fighting in the Civil war. Ryder plays Jo, the literary
sister, with the most outspoken views. Armstrong (``My Brilliant
Career,'' ``Oscar and Lucinda'') has found a way to make the story
relevant for today while keeping all of its charms. Once again,
Ryder is luminous. It is Jo, with her strengths and doubts, who is
at the heart of this excellent film. &QL; 
--- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, Interrupted'' (Sony) is priced for rental at $106.99 on
VHS. The DVD is $24.95 and includes commentary by director Mangold,
a making-of documentary and deleted scenes with Mangold's
commentary. The ``Little Women _ Collector's Edition'' (Sony) DVD
is $27.95 and includes commentary by director Armstrong, Ryder and
producer Denise DiNovi, a making-of documentary and deleted scenes
with Armstrong's commentary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
