u k BC-OPED-CORZINE-SEVERIN-     06-07 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CORZINE-SEVERIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY WELL SPENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for use Thursday, June 8, and thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By JAY SEVERIN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In politics, as in life, money talks, and that makes Jon Corzine
positively eloquent. To acquire New Jersey's Democratic nomination
for the Senate, the former Wall Street whiz spent a record $32
million, give or take, but who's counting?
</P>
<P>
   Many have lamented this spending; a seat in Congress, they say,
should not be bought. But was Corzine wrong to spend his millions?
No, and here's why.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's be honest about what kind of candidate he
represents: the vanity candidate, a man or woman for whom prominent
political office is the next world to conquer. Such candidates
require two ingredients: a belief in their ability to tackle any
challenge, a quality that is never in short supply, and cash. Table
stakes in a big state are already $25 million; by next election
cycle this might well double.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not willing to spend that money, you are wasting not
only your time, but your supporters' time. There have been wealthy
candidates who romantically believed that good ideas, good
intentions and good will would elect them. But a
multimillion-dollar ad campaign does the job a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   I've worked for wealthy candidates like Bernadette Castro, who
was the Republican nominee for Senate in New York in 1994. If she
had spent her own money freely, as she had originally suggested,
then she could have actually posed a challenge to Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who was a three-term incumbent in an anti-incumbent kind
of year. As it was, Castro spent meagerly and won 42 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Having the nerve to spend a personal fortune is not unfair to
other candidates. Yes, Jon Corzine is a political neophyte, while
his opponent, Jim Florio, was a former governor. But Corzine was
right when he pointed out that Florio, in public life for 20 years,
had cumulatively spent the equivalent of $35 million in boosting
his image, and that had helped him as a Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, who was 30 points ahead of Corzine a few months ago, was
the one who started the race with the advantage of name
recognition. Florio's problem was not that New Jerseyans did not
know him, but that they knew him too well. Corzine spent his money,
letting voters know they had a choice. What's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's wealth probably did drive other possible primary
opponents out. But that's a function of today's Darwinian politics.
Never before has celebrity mattered more than issues and party
loyalty. (See Hillary Rodham Clinton, New York.)
</P>
<P>
   An unknown without money has a real uphill, indeed nearly
implausible, battle in both raising funds and gaining name
recognition. An unknown with money can buy a certain celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, money is no guarantee that you'll win anything. In
1994, Michael Huffington, a Republican, spent $28 million to try to
win a California Senate seat, only to lose to Dianne Feinstein. In
1998, Al Checchi spent $38 million in a race for the Democratic
nomination for governor of California and lost to a career
politician, Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   And for every candidate who has lost a seat and a small fortune,
there are examples of candidates who spent a lot of money and went
on to serve honorably. In 1982, Frank Lautenberg, a wealthy
businessman with no political experience, spent millions of dollars
of his own money to win the New Jersey Senate seat Corzine is now
seeking. Although his politics are not my cup of tea, he has served
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   As people pay more attention to the general election, we don't
know how Corzine will do. But one thing is for sure: He must
continue to spend his own money, despite his statements that he
would spend less.
</P>
<P>
   So long as he is prepared to spend, Jon Corzine has a chance at
a Senate seat. And at this point, he has a duty to his party to
spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Severin is a Republican political consultant.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
