<HEADLINE>
ONLY WITH THEIR WITS, PART II 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for use Thursday, June 8, and thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By DAVID MARTIN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ With the success of CBS' new series, ``Survivor,'' we
can expect the other networks to play catch-up with copycat
versions like these:
</P>
<P>
   BIG APPLE SURVIVOR (Fox)
</P>
<P>
   Two eight-member teams of Midwestern tourists are dropped off in
Bensonhurst with nothing but the clothes on their backs. Over the
next 39 days, relying on their wits, they compete to see which
player will be first to reach Midtown and claim the million-dollar
prize. Every three nights, the teams are pitted in competitions
like ticket scalping and taxi hailing in hopes of winning precious
prizes like subway tokens. The losing team must vote to remove a
member, who is left in the new Times Square to wander alone.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON VALLEY SURVIVOR (ABC)
</P>
<P>
   Ten technophobes, deposited in Silicon Valley, use their
rudimentary skills to see who will be first to contact family and
be taken home. Watch as they tackle coinless pay phones, cashless
supermarkets and Palm Pilot banking. Each week, the survivors are
given a new device, like an e-mail pager or Global Positioning
System receiver, with just an instruction manual to guide them.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE HOUSE SURVIVOR (NBC)
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen males and one female are split into teams, the Democrats
and the Republicans. Using only their natural gifts to raise soft
money, each team slowly narrows itself down to one presidential
candidate. The two finalists compete in a late fall 900-number
telephone contest for a four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   E.U. SURVIVOR (CNN)
</P>
<P>
   Each week, representatives of the 15 states of the European
Union compete to see which will emerge as the economic ruler of
Europe. Contestants can artificially inflate or deflate their
currencies to undermine the euro. Smaller countries can band
together to reinstate tariff barriers. The show will end when
Germany wins.
</P>
<P>
   SOLAR SYSTEM SURVIVOR (PBS)
</P>
<P>
   Nine planets, nine orbits. Watch as each planet tries to avoid
the effects of climatic change, deteriorating orbits and random
asteroids. See who survives into the next millennium and who ends
up as a sunspot.
</P>
<P>
   (David Martin is a lawyer.)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
