<SLUG> BC-KLM-BRITISH-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLM AND BRITISH AIRWAYS BEGIN MERGER TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The game of musical chairs sweeping the global airline industry
expanded to yet more players Wednesday, but it appears that it will
be some time before the music stops.
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Airways PLC, Europe's largest airline, and
the Netherlands-based carrier, KLM Royal Dutch NV, acknowledged
they had entered into merger negotiations. Across the Atlantic, AMR
Corp., the parent of American Airlines, and Delta Air Lines held
preliminary merger discussions earlier this week, according to two
people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The talks between AMR and Delta followed an overture by AMR to
Northwest Airlines. Those discussions in turn were sparked by the
acquisition of US Airways by UAL Corp., the parent of United
Airlines, for $4.3 billion, a deal that would create by far the
world's largest airline. That poses a direct threat to American and
Delta, the second and third-largest carriers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are increasingly keen to merge in order to expand their
networks and pare costs. UAL has said that buying US Airways, the
largest carrier on the East Cost, will fill a large hole in its
route network, making it more attractive to corporate customers and
to its airline partners in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sent the shares of all four airlines in the latest
reported pairings up Wednesday. KLM shares surged 8.5 percent to
30.1 euros or $28.29, and have risen 45 percent since rumors that
it might be purchased began to swirl weeks ago. British Airways
shares rose 1.3 percent to 390 pence or about $5.85. Delta shares
rose 3.2 percent or $1.625 to $52.50 on the New York Stock
Exchange, and AMR shares rose 12.5 cents to $28.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the reaction to the talks in the stock market, it is
notoriously difficult to combine airlines smoothly. British Airways
and KLM tried once before, in 1992, but the deal foundered over
price. Yet even if the two managements can agree on price and
management control, the powerful role played by labor unions often
make mergers more trouble than they are worth. In addition, there
is a real chance that regulators would block such large deals.
</P>
<P>
   Both British Airways and KLM dominate their respective home
markets and have little room to expand. They have also been hurt by
competition that has eroded their profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   A British Airways-KLM would create the world's fourth largest
airline with $19.5 billion in sales. It would have hubs outside of
London serving trans-Atlantic and long haul flights to Asia as well
as a hub outside Amsterdam that could serve connecting flights and
intra-Europe routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a necessity for consolidation to take place,'' said
Andrew Light, an aviation analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in
London. He said a deal is especially important for KLM, which broke
off its alliance with Alitalia of Italy in April. ``It gives them a
lifeline,'' he said. ``They are desperately in a need of a
partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Both British Airways and KLM cautioned that the talks were ``at
a preliminary stage.'' Executives close to the negotiations who
spoke on condition of anonymity said that it would take
considerable time to negotiate any deal. The executives said price
has not been significantly discussed yet. But on the assumption
that a deal would be structured as a British Airways purchase of
KLM, analysts estimate KLM's price could exceed $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   KLM has a strong alliance with Northwest Airlines in which the
two carriers have merged their trans-Atlantic operations. British
Airways has an alliance with AMR. Those were among the reasons many
analysts believe an AMR merger with Northwest makes the most sense.
</P>
<P>
   But people close to the initial talks between the two carriers
said Northwest sought a premium price, which gave AMR pause. The
talks between AMR and Delta, which took place in New York on Monday
and were reported by The Wall Street Journal, were also described
as very preliminary. Present at the meeting were Edward West and
Tom Horton, the chief financial officers of AMR and Delta, along
with lawyers and investment bankers from Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
representing Delta, and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter representing
AMR.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people walked away from it with the conclusion: Here
are some things we need to think about,'' said one person close to
the discussions. It was not clear when the two sides would meet
again.
</P>
<P>
   A merger would bring together Delta's strong European and East
Coast routes with American's dominance of Latin America and its
access to London's Heathrow airport. But the two carriers together
would control nearly 40 percent of the domestic market, and they
overlap heavily in the South and Soutwest. In addition, neither has
a strong network in Asia, which is a jewel in Northwest's crown.
</P>
<P>
   That is why most analysts believe AMR and Northwest make a
better fit, while Delta and Continental Airlines are considered
more suitable partners.
</P>
<P>
   But as all the recent activity proves, nothing is ruled out.
Some analysts and airline executives believe that the talks
involving AMR were publicized at such an early stage to try to
scuttle the UAL-US Airways deal by alarming antitrust regulators in
Washington. They may also have been intended to send a message to
Northwest that it may be passed over if it does not lower its
asking price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
