<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESERVED JOY IN SILICON VALLEY OVER THE DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ While few in Silicon Valley were disappointed
with Microsoft Corp.'s comeuppance Wednesday, no one was popping
champagne bottles to celebrate a post-Microsoft world either.
</P>
<P>
   That's because no one expects Microsoft to go away in the wake
of the federal court order to split the company in two, an order
that Microsoft will vigorously appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In the technology capital of Silicon Valley, the company's vast
influence on broad technology sectors makes for a complicated
relationship. Many companies here have business agreements with
Microsoft, but their executives privately grouse about the
company's heavy-handed approach.
</P>
<P>
   The quandary was best summed up by an executive at a large
company in the Valley who declined to be named: ``There are areas
where we compete with Microsoft, and there are areas where we
cooperate with them, so it's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Intel Corp., the Santa Clara chipmaker seen as a close ally
of Microsoft, tried to project a neutral stance Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judgment issued could potentially represent structural
changes at Microsoft, and that in turn could result in a
significant change for the industry,'' said Chuck Mulloy, an Intel
spokesman. ``We're confident that if it does, the industry will
find a way to adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who don't have ties with Microsoft are conflicted
by the prospects of government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their business practice is clearly one of intimidation,
especially in light of how they treated smaller companies,'' said
Walter G. Kortschak, managing general partner of Summit Partners, a
venture capital firm in Palo Alto, Calif. ``On the other hand, I
just wish there could have been another remedy that would be less
intrusive. Having the government come in and altering the
structural landscape of the industry is a little scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Komisar, an advisor to startups in the Valley and a
veteran entrepreneur, explains it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Silicon Valley think this is the last bastion of
libertarianism, where the myth of the cowboy in his Stetson hat
still exists. They're saying `We don't need no stinkin'
government.' At the same time, we know Microsoft has done bad
things. (Government prosecutor) Joe Klein got the right verdict.
The problem is coming up with the right remedy, and I'm not
convinced that breaking up the company will make much of a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Komisar had his own suggestion: ``Send Gates to live in St.
Helena, where they exiled Napoleon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideology aside, self-interest also factors into the Valley's
ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people here think something needs to be done to curb
Microsoft's power over the computer industry,'' said Linley
Gwennap, analyst with the Linley Group in Mountain View, Calif.
``On the other hand, there are companies here with very large
market shares who are worried they might be next in line'' to bear
the antitrust scrutiny of the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in Silicon Valley is ambiguous about the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good!'' said Pamela Samuelson, a professor at the University
of California at Berkeley law school. ``The pattern of
anti-competitive behavior at Microsoft is so much part of their
culture that I am convinced a structural remedy is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good when the bad guys get caught and justice
prevails, and that's what happened here,'' said Mitchell Kertzman,
chief executive of Liberate Technologies in San Carlos. ``It's not
going to make life easy for us to compete with them. We'll still
have to execute, as will they. But this will help level the playing
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lockyear, attorney general of California, a state that is
party to the Department of Justice lawsuit against Microsoft,
Wednesday said the company's anti-government comments in response
to the breakup ruling were ``disingenous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that the Microsoft leadership still doesn't get it,''
Lockyear said in a press conference. ``You can't abuse that
monopoloy position by injuring consumers and competitors in the way
Microsoft did.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, most here in Silicon Valley expect
Microsoft to remain a force in the industry, for better or for
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the dust settles,'' said Scott Kriens, chief executive of
Juniper Networks, a Mountain View maker of Internet routers,
``Microsoft will still be a great company _ or companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
