<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATAFISH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH OF A GOOD THING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say this for ``Catfish in Black Bean Sauce'': In telling the
story of an African-American couple and their adopted Vietnamese
children, the movie puts the spotlight on two minority groups that
rarely get their due in movies. And writer-director-star Chi Muoi
Lo must believe that this could be his only chance to speak his
mind. He packs so much plot into this wildly uneven film that he
could well have made three movies for all storylines he has crammed
into this single entry.
</P>
<P>
   Would that he had told just one. ``Catfish'' is best when
concentrating on Harold and Dolores Williams (Paul Winfield and
Mary Alice, both excellent) and how their lives are affected when
their adopted children, Mai (Lauren Tom) and Dwayne
(writer-director Lo) are reunited with their birth mother, Thanh
(Kieu Chinh). But there are a lot of added (and unnecessary)
subplots mixed in with this cross-cultural stew, resulting in a
jumbled movie that sabotages its own good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Mai has always had issues with her adopted mother, Dolores, so
when Thanh re-enters her life, she's initially overjoyed. Dwayne,
however, is apathetic, having embraced the African-American ways of
his new parents, right down to his language, which is straight out
of Compton. The insecure Dwayne is engaged to a beautiful young
African American, Nina (Sanaa Lathan), but constantly undermines
their relationship because he feels she's going to dump him
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne's new mother, Thanh, isn't thrilled about her Vietnamese
son dating an African-American woman. Nor is she sure what to make
of Dwayne's roommate, Michael (Tyler Christopher), and his
relationship with a transvestite. Dwayne's uncertain about
Michael's relationship, too, as is the audience, since it seems to
belong in an entirely different movie.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the main problem with ``Catfish.'' Lo undercuts his
story at every turn with broad slapstick about transvestites,
talking cats and elderly men protesting ATM fees. The movie has its
share of warm, with funny and touching moments, but it's also
frequently screeching, ridiculous and heavy-handed. Lo isn't
exactly a master of subtlety, either, as an actor or a filmmaker.
His movie will certainly resonate at times with its cinematically
underrepresented audiences, but for others, ``Catfish'' will be a
less-than-satisfying offering. &QL; 
- The film: `` Catfish in Black Bean Sauce'' (PG-13; adult
situations, themes). &QL; 
- The stars: Paul Winfield, Mary Alice, Lauren Tom, Chi Muoi Lo. &QL; 
- Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Chi Muoi Lo. Released
by Iron Hill Pictures. &QL; 
- Running time: One hour, 51 minutes. &QL; 
- Playing: AMC Media Center 8 in Burbank; Regent Theater, Los
Feliz; Landmark's NuWilshire in Santa Monica; Magic Johnson
Theaters, Baldwin Hills. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-GONEIN60SECONDS-     06-07 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GONEIN60SECONDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS A CAR WRECK OF A MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Film critic Gene Siskel had a frequent complaint about remakes:
Why do filmmakers always redo good films, rather than bad or
mediocre ones? If action-movie producer Jerry Bruckheimer were the
type of guy who listened to critics, Siskel's lament could have
been the inspiration for ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' a remake of an
obscure 1974 B-movie that has achieved cult status because it
smashes more than 90 cars and concludes with a 40-minute chase.
</P>
<P>
   These are elements that could send the mayhem-mad Bruckheimer _
the man responsible for ``Con Air'' and ``Armageddon'' _ into
ecstatic convulsions. You can almost imagine him saying, drool
barely in check, ``You mean there's a movie we could remake and
improve and still get to break stuff?'' And yes, it's true: The
original ``Gone,'' which looks like it was made for less money than
the change on Bruckheimer's dresser top, has a plot so
unintelligible that even Bruckheimer, along with his stable of
lowest-common-denominator screenwriters and excess-obsessed,
music-video-trained directors, couldn't help but do a better job.
</P>
<P>
   And they do, sorta. First of all, there's a plot _ kinda _ which
pretty much goes like this: Legendary car thief comes out of
retirement when his kid brother gets into trouble; legendary car
thief has to steal 50 boss cars in four days to save his kid
brother's life. For some reason, the bad guys let the kid brother
go, and nobody simply high-tails it out of town. But, of course, if
you're looking for logic in a Bruckheimer movie, you've come to the
wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   What you should be looking for is loud action and
testosterone-laced humor mixed with moments of sensitivity _ call
it the heavy-metal-concert school of filmmaking, as exemplified
this time by Dominic Sena, director of the much-reviled
``Kalifornia'' and about a million commercials and videos (OK, not
a million, but if they can get excessive, so can I). On a certain
level, Sena delivers, with editing so fast that it's a wonder the
title wasn't changed to ``Gone in 15 Seconds.'' But darn it, he's
too slow to, as they say, cut to the chase. Either he or writer
Scott Rosenberg actually thought some exposition was necessary, and
that keeps the movie in second gear for too long.
</P>
<P>
   Few things are more irritating than a dumb movie that isn't dumb
enough, and ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' isn't dumb enough. It would be
easiest to enjoy it if your brain power was gone in 60 seconds, but
unlike the original, it has some expensive actors in it, and it has
to do something with them. So it wastes time setting a plot into
motion as a mysterious person contacts Nicolas Cage, kinda like a
mysterious person contacted Tom Cruise in ``M:I-2.'' And Cage has
to round up a crew of specialists ... kinda like Tom Cruise did in
``M:I-2.'' Come to think of it, Cage spends a lot of time wearing
shades and has interesting hair, kinda like ... well, you get the
idea. Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people Cage rounds up are Angelina Jolie, who plays
the requisite ex who still carries a torch for the, um, hero, and
Robert Duvall, who plays the requisite older-but-wiser buddy (yes,
they have character names, but that hardly matters). The movie's
publicity material makes much of having three Academy Award winners
in its cast, but except for Cage _ who shifts from neutral
(sincerity) to overdrive (fast-talking con man) _ they have little
to do. Jolie, whose lines consist mainly of ``C'mon, c'mon!'' and
``Go, go, go!,'' is particularly wasted, although she gives her
character enough winks and lip-smacks to make her at least a little
intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth's'' Christopher Eccleston plays the suavely oily bad
guy, and Delroy Lindo and Timothy Olyphant play a pair of
persistent, bantering cops. Throw in the motley crew of supporting
actors in Cage's posse, and you have so many characters that
Rosenberg struggles to give them all something to say, and his
screenplay turns more into a series of car-theft sketches than a
script.
</P>
<P>
   The actors aren't the stars here, anyway. Nor are the beautiful,
expensive cars that make up the thieves' prey. No, it's the film
editors and sound-effects specialists who rev up the car chases and
put all the bangs and vrooms and screeches into the right places.
The movie pays tribute to the original with ``Eleanor,'' a 1967
Mustang GT that is a sort of Holy Grail for Cage's character (in
the original, ``Eleanor'' received top billing). Eleanor figures
into the climactic chase, and in a rare moment of restraint from
the Bruckheimer gang, it doesn't go on as long as the chase in the
original ``Gone.'' It does go on for a while, though, and it's
followed by an even more climactic fistfight. Kind of like in
``M:I-2.'' Um, which movie were they remaking?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' is rated PG-13 for crashes, smashes,
bangs, clangs, screeches, rrrrrrs, strong language uttered by
humans, and nudity and sexual situations. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Film: ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' &QL; 
Director: Dominic Sena &QL; 
Stars: Nicolas Cage, Angelina Jolie, a buncha cars &QL; 
Length: 119 minutes &QL; 
Score: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
