<SLUG> BC-POP-ME-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROAD LESS TAKEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know the state of father-son films has become pretty
desperate when a ludicrous serial killer drama like ``Frequency''
can bring tears to grown men's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the engaging documentary ``Pop &AMP; Me'' feels like a
breath a fresh air. The winner of the Audience Award at the 1999
Los Angeles Independent Film Festival, ``Pop &AMP; Me'' celebrates the
ties that bind fathers and sons together, and it manages to earn
its tears and smiles without resorting to any cheap gimmicks. It's
a beautiful film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop &AMP; Me'' was borne from mid-life crisis. Richard Roe, a
hard-charging former stockbroker, lost his job, his marriage and
his parents in the span of a couple of years. He hit on the idea of
a six-month trip around the world with his son, Chris, an aspiring
filmmaker who would capture their travels with his camera. Chris
had his reservations _ he liked the idea of spending time with his
father, but wondered whether the length of the trip and the fact
that Richard was funding it would cause friction between them.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out it did, which gives ``Pop &AMP; Me'' a ``Real World''
kind of intrigue that takes on a ``Survivor'' tone as the trip
wears on. Chris longs for his father's respect and wonders why
Richard listens to his other two sons (who are seen at different
points in the journey), but never seems to pay attention to him.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Pop &AMP; Me'' is much more than a family soap opera.
Throughout their travels, the Roes interview various father-and-son
duos, sometimes resulting in feelings being shared for the first
time. These aren't Oprah-style confessionals, though, just honest
emotions being expressed by men who aren't accustomed to such
sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights: A South African father who gave up
drinking, winning his son's admiration in the process, and a
Vietnamese son who speaks of the value of having his frail,
78-year-old father live with him. The Roes also bump into Julian
Lennon, who candidly admits that he doesn't have much respect for
his famous father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave more love to the world than he did to me,'' Lennon
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Roes never do achieve any kind of closure themselves, which
is perfect given that reality is rarely tied up into a neat
Hollywood kind of package. But they certainly valued the time they
spent together, and you will, too. And you needn't wait until
Father's Day to see it, either. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
- The film: ``Pop &AMP; Me'' (Film has not yet been rated). &QL; 
- Behind the scenes: Directed by Chris Roe. &QL; 
- Running time: One hour, 31 minutes. &QL; 
- Playing: Laemmle's Music Hall, Beverly Hills. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
