<HEADER>
A7541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ESCAPE0608-COX     06-07 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCAPE0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Escape plan gone awry halts plan for new life
 &HT;    By Jill Taylor and Pat Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. _ All they had to do was get to Okeechobee's Budget
Inn. Waiting there were hair color, barbering tools, fresh clothes
and two train tickets from Jacksonville to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   They planned to start a new life together and blend into the Big
Apple, far from the double rows of razor wire encircling the Martin
Treatment Center.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Whitsett and Clifford Burkhart, captured Tuesday
after a bold attempt to flee the center the day before in a tiny
helicopter, needed a lot of things to go right to see their scheme
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Their luck ran out shortly after Burkhart, a novice helicopter
pilot, picked up his longtime friend in the fenced yard of the
center 10 miles north of Indiantown Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to fly a few miles to a remote area near some
railroad tracks where a Chevrolet van sat waiting. Then they would
speed west on a rural highway to spend the night in the Okeechobee
motel.
</P>
<P>
   But Burkhart and Whitsett, a sex offender detained at the center
under the Jimmy Ryce Act, barely made it outside the fence before
the helicopter crashed Monday, prompting a massive manhunt that
ended with their dramatic capture at gunpoint 25 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once (the helicopter) went down, their plan was kind of shot
and they had to improvise,'' said Florida Department of Law
Enforcement Agent Richard Piccininni.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsett, 28, was charged with escape and Burkhart, 23, was
charged with aiding an escape. Both were being held at the Martin
County jail without bail Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of their capture on the banks of the C-23 Canal east
of Interstate 95, both men carried loaded 9mm handguns and had
carried extra clips of ammunition _ although Whitsett lost his
spare magazine in the woods during the chase.
</P>
<P>
   Martin County sheriff's Lt. Ron Cucchiara jumped from a hovering
helicopter to confront the armed men as they waded in the canal
Tuesday afternoon. He fired two warning shots into the water about
a foot to the side of each man when they refused to get out of the
water and drop their guns.
</P>
<P>
   They finally obeyed Cucchiara's commands, and later told
Piccininni they never intended to shoot it out with deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they didn't want to hurt anybody,'' Piccininni said.
``(Burkhart) said the guns were for if they failed (in the escape)
they would shoot themselves. . . . But I don't know about that. You
don't need extra magazines (of ammunition) to shoot yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators initially wondered if the two had help in carrying
out the escape plan. They theorized Burkhart could not park the van
he rented by the side of the road in Martin and get back to his
home in Hollywood without help.
</P>
<P>
   But Burkhart told them he drove the van north, put a sign in the
window saying it was broken down and tried to get a taxi to take
him home. When no cab company would drive out to the remote spot to
pick him up, he called friends until he found one who would do him
the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they do not believe the friend knew anything
about the escape plot.
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart, who works as a waiter and reportedly has a computer
business on the side, told investigators he maxed out his credit
cards to pay for the helicopter and van rentals, the train tickets
and the other escape preparations.
</P>
<P>
   He had the Okeechobee hotel key in his pocket and $10,098 in
cash, which he and Whitsett planned to use for starting their new
life.
</P>
<P>
   During their first court appearances Wednesday, Martin County
Judge David Harper did not set any bail and the two men made no
comments.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State Attorney Robert Belanger said he intends to
prosecute both men on enhanced first-degree felony charges,
punishable by up to 30 years in prison, because firearms were used
during the escape.
</P>
<P>
   The judge appointed the public defender's office to represent
Burkhart. Whitsett signed paperwork refusing a public defense
attorney ``at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Public Defender John Hetherington said he questions
whether the escape and aiding escape charges will withstand legal
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to punish them as criminals under a civil
statute,'' Hetherington said, referring to the Jimmy Ryce Act,
which keeps sex offenders incarcerated in a treatment facility once
their prison sentences expire if experts determine they are likely
to commit additional crimes if released into society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be trying to say they are entitled to equal protection
as anyone else charged under civil laws such as Baker Act (for
psychological commitments) or Marchman Act (for substance abuse
commitments),'' Hetherington said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone held under (those acts) who walks away from a
treatment center cannot be charged with escape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hetherington said appeals courts will likely be sorting out the
issues in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all brand new,'' he said of the escape charges called for
in the Jimmy Ryce Act that was enacted in Jan. 1, 1999. ``Not to my
knowledge has this happened in any other state that has these
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger said legislators who passed the law specifically stated
that anyone escaping from a Jimmy Ryce treatment center could be
prosecuted on a criminal escape charge.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Olds,the attorney representing Whitsett in his challenge
to the Jimmy Ryce commitment, called his client's escape a
``setback'' in his effort to get Whitsett freed.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsett completed 4 1/2 years of an eight-year prison sentence
in September stemming from a sexual assault on a 15-year-old boy at
a psychiatric treatment center in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legislators intended this law to keep the `worst of the worst'
from society. . . . When we look at (Whitsett's) case, he never
harmed a soul and he did all his prison time.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart has no criminal history. He has been close to Whitsett
for about eight years, according to Whitsett's sister, Carenann,
32, who attended her brother's first court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   She lifted her sunglasses for a moment when her brother appeared
on the closed circuit television screen dressed in the orange
high-risk inmate jail uniform, and wondered aloud about the bandage
on his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Piccininni later said the injury was a minor scrape suffered in
the helicopter crash, and that other than being thirsty, tired and
hungry, the fugitives were in pretty good shape when caught.
</P>
<P>
   Carenann Whitsett said she has attended many of her brother's
court hearings and while she does not approve of his homosexuality,
she loves and supports him.
</P>
<P>
   She lashed out at some of the media coverage in which Burkhart's
mother seemed to blame the escape plan primarily on her brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother did not go out and get a helicopter. He did not go
out and get guns. He did not go out and get money. . . . They are
both responsible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
