<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7543 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-GONE-FEATURE-LADN &LR;      06-07 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUT TO THE CHASE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Fri., June 9, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients.) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got the remake rights to a low-class, non-classic of the
'70s _ which, run through the calculus of modern Hollywood's summer
movie formula, equals a potential blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   But then some fool went and hired two Oscar-winning actors (and,
by the time of the remake's release, a third one) to star in what
was supposed to be a nice, brain-dead entertainment in which stolen
cars, driven irresponsibly, were supposed to be the whole show.
</P>
<P>
   How to work this? That was the dilemma that faced superproducer
Jerry Bruckheimer (``Armageddon,'' the upcoming ``Pearl Harbor'')
and director Dominic Sena when Disney handed them the assignment to
modify and turbocharge ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' for a generation of
moviegoers raised on adrenaline-fueled, technically perfect movie
mayhem. It turned out to be a very different project from junkyard
owner H.B. Halicki's self-starring, independently produced, 1974
original, which was basically a primer on auto theft climaxed by a
40-minute demolition derby of a chase.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruckheimer and his favorite screenwriter, Scott Rosenberg,
designed the remake for their ``Con Air'' star Nicolas Cage, who,
despite having re-invented himself as an action hero in the
mid-1990s, maintains the serious commitment to actual acting that
earned him an Oscar for ``Leaving Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Duvall, an even more widely respected Oscar-winner who
occasionally does big bucks slumming in popcorn pictures like
Bruckheimer's ``Days of Thunder,'' was also a first choice.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was sizzling hot Angelina Jolie, who won a supporting
actress statuette in March. The ever-newsworthy, alarmingly
unpredictable young star made ``Gone'' before that happened, but
brought every bit of her serious actor's attitude to the project
(trust us; tattoos and white blonde dreadlocks were not what studio
suits wanted to see on what was basically a testosterone fantasy's
girlfriend role).
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations, obviously, needed to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a lot of story to [Halicki's] movie,'' says Sena,
an award-winning commercials and music video director who actually
worked a bit for the late, thrill-crazed Halicki when he first came
to Hollywood. ``If you look at it, they had 90 cars they could
afford to wreck, and the story of the movie ends when they wrecked
the 90th car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured that's not going to fly today. What's the point of
having Nic Cage attached to the project if we're going to go with
wall-to-wall sheet metal? There needed to be a story, we wanted to
get a good cast, and the film wound up being about these two
brothers, coming back and doing the last thing you want to do
because you have to to save your brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The scenario that Rosenberg and some additional writers finally
hammered out had Cage as Memphis Raines, a retired Long Beach car-
boosting legend who must get back into the illegal game when his
little brother Kip (Valley-bred actor Giovanni Ribisi) blows a
major luxury vehicle delivery for a ruthless English gangster.
Memphis' impossible mission is to steal 50 costly models in one
night or lose his kin.
</P>
<P>
   Jolie and Duvall play ex-members of Memphis' gang, whom he must
press back into service for this night of all nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a car freak, and that did have a lot to do with my
decision to make the movie,'' admits Cage, who claims to have
recently pared his classics collection down to 10 (the favorite is
a '55 Jaguar D-Type). ``But, having said that, I still wanted to
know that there was something I could act. Knowing Jerry, I was
pretty confident that he would put a terrific cast together _ as he
has _ but I still wanted to know that there would be scenes where
there was some kind of dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``From those conversations, they built up the backstory of the
two brothers, and his needing to go back into a life of crime to,
ultimately, do good. That, to me, was interesting, because that's
not your standard, politically correct action hero. I thought the
idea of having people root for a car thief would be unique.''
</P>
<P>
   And easier said than done. Due to Cage's busy work schedule,
``Gone'' had to begin production last spring before a satisfactory
final script draft was completed. This led to almost daily
rewrites, which at times felt scarier than a 360 spinout at 130
mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be terrifying, and it can be exhilarating,'' admits
Cage, who cooked up some of his own Memphis dialogue. ``I mean, I'm
not joking; sometimes, I would have the writer and the director in
my trailer with me, going over script revisions five minutes before
I started shooting _ and I didn't know what I was going to say.
Sometimes, you felt like you were out there doing a tap dance,
trying to make it work. With that kind of high wire, you can either
find something really fresh and spontaneous that is compelling, or
you can fall on your face and look like a complete fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Other cast members rolled more casually with the hairpin
rewrites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'know, this script wasn't that thick to begin with,'' notes a
laughing Jolie, her jet black hair now shoulder-length and a dragon
tattoo bearing the name of her newlywed husband, Billy Bob
Thornton, on her upper left arm. ``We changed a line or two here
and there, but it's not like we were rewriting big monologues.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for all the talk about character and drama, ``Gone'' is
mainly a stripped-down drama about planning and executing the
ultimate rolling heist. For the picture, actors were taught
state-of-the-art car-stealing techniques, some by an expert Cage
and Bruckheimer had met at Folsom Prison while preparing ``Con
Air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous for me to admit to, isn't it?'' Jolie chuckles.
``It's like, cars are missing, they'll go, 'Oh, her.' But yeah,
though I might want to check my notes, I think I could steal a car
now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 60 seconds I could teach you how to steal cars. Then we
could go out and be gone in, literally, 10 seconds,'' adds Ribisi,
who actually built a '69 Camaro with a 502 crate engine as part of
his research. ``Anybody can do it; it's actually quite simple. You
can get into cars with a screwdriver. Technology has probably made
it a little more difficult, but apparently there's not really a car
out there that can't be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``My little joke that I've been telling everybody, which
probably isn't funny anymore, is that the best sort of security
system to have on a car is just an insurance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   A nice message for a major motion picture to impart _ especially
one that often relied on the kindness of luxury car manufactures
and classics collectors for its key props.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each situation was different,'' Sena recalls. ``Porsche would
let us use their car in the opening scene only if we didn't show
them breaking in. I don't think we stole any BMWs either because
they gave them to us, but we crashed one. Other ones, we'd lease
from dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the collectors ... there was a scene where we were in a
Ferrari warehouse, where individual cars were worth millions of
dollars. I walked over to one and leaned over for an angle with my
viewfinder, and suddenly these guys were on me, going, `Sir, watch
it! If you scratch that paint job it's $27,500.00 to repaint.'''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, all that machinery looks great in the film. But
Sena is quick to caution those expecting sheer motorized fetishism
that they should expect more from his remake.
</P>
<P>
   Or less that's more, something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rewatched the original, just to remind myself of what I'd
forgotten,'' Sena says. ``And you know what? A 40-minute car chase
is just too long. I was going out into the kitchen, getting some
chips. I'd come back and turn on the news, turn back to it and the
chase is still going on. It's pretty slow, y'know?
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a whole bunch of car chases in this movie. One's
enough, and at 13 minutes, that's plenty, I think. The hope we had
was that you stay with the story long enough to get to the car
chase. It's not filled with action.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
