<HEADER>
A7547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0608-COX     06-07 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jurors shown photos of victims
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Attendance at the murder trial dropped off Wednesday,
now that celebrity defendant-turned witness Ray Lewis has come and
gone from the Fulton County courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard used the day to bring the focus
back on the two men who were stabbed to death Jan. 31 on a Buckhead
street.
</P>
<P>
   Howard introduced slide after slide of grisly autopsy photos
displaying the knife wounds that killed Jacinth Baker, 21, and
Richard Lollar, 24. Howard wanted to show ``the wounds were
purposeful with intent to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   When some of the photos were displayed, sobbing relatives of the
deceased bolted out of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   John Parker, a Fulton County medical examiner, testified Baker
suffered a severe incision where the knife was twisted when it hit
the liver. Lollar lived only 45 to 90 seconds more after a gaping
stab wound punctured his heart, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   But attorneys for the two remaining murder defendants, Reginald
Oakley, 31, of Baltimore and Joseph Sweeting, 34, of Miami, used
cross-examination to help defuse the state's witness, as they have
done repeatedly during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley's attorney, Bruce Harvey, got Parker to admit that the
type of knife recovered at the scene was most likely not involved
in killing Baker.
</P>
<P>
   A small folding knife, with no blood on it, was found at the
scene. Prosecutors are expected to contend Oakley killed Baker with
a knife identical to the one Sweeting bought the day before the
Super Bowl at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker said that was unlikely. ``In the examination of the
body, I saw nothing to say this knife caused it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey also pointed out that Baker had a .07 blood alcohol level
and was carrying a plastic bag with marijuana that included smaller
baggies of the drug apparently for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The state's last witness, who will conclude her testimony this
morning, documented with DNA analysis a trail of blood from the
crime scene to Ray Lewis' hotel room at the Georgian Terrace. Dawn
Pierce, a GBI forensics analyst, identified bloodstains belonging
to Baker inside Lewis' stretch limo, inside the Holiday Inn where
the limo stopped to change a tire flattened by gunfire and inside
Room 804 at the Georgian Terrace.
</P>
<P>
   One bloodstain taken from inside the limo was a mixture of the
blood of both Oakley and Baker, the analyst testified. The three
defendants' attorneys had presented a united front against
prosecutors until last weekend, when Lewis' team cut a deal for
their client to become a witness against his two friends.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey and Sweeting attorney Steve Sadow had a spat Wednesday in
the courtroom after Sadow asked several questions about bruises on
Baker's face. Harvey, angered that Sadow was reinforcing testimony
against Oakley, cut into Sadow's cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Sadow bent across the table to talk to Harvey, who said, ``Well,
don't get excited when I do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But during his cross-examination, Harvey never mentioned Lollar,
the man Sweeting allegedly killed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
