u f BC-PHONE-RATES-2TAKES-NY     06-07 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-RATES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T, UNDER PRESSURE, AGREES TO PUT OFF RATE INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ AT&AMP;T gave into pressure from embarrassed federal
regulators and outraged consumer groups on Wednesday and said that
it would put off a planned rate increase that would have raised
telephone bills for tens of millions of customers.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after a flurry of calls between senior
AT&AMP;T executives and the chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, William E. Kennard, who said that the nation's largest
long-distance company had broken a promise to reduce overall phone
charges under an agreement reached last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard and AT&AMP;T had promoted that agreement, under which the
FCC reduced the fees paid by long-distance carriers to local phone
companies, as a ``historic'' rate cut. But at the same time, AT&AMP;T
filed documents with the commission that said the company would
actually be raising most of the per-minute charges on the basic
accounts of millions of customers who make few calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T promised to pass on savings to all consumers,'' Kennard
said in a statement issued after his conversations with AT&AMP;T
executives, including its chairman, C. Michael Armstrong. ``Their
new rate plan does not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in our order and I am going to enforce it,'' he said.
``AT&AMP;T promised to tell their consumers which plan would be most
cost effective for them. This was not done. I will also hold AT&AMP;T
to this commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Tristani, another FCC commissioner, issued a blistering
six-word statement. ``I was totally misled by AT&AMP;T,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Their statements were curious in light of comments on Tuesday
from other officials at the commission who said that they knew all
along that AT&AMP;T had intended to raise certain rates and that they
were not particularly troubled by it.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which handles 60 percent of the nation's residential
long-distance calls, said it had decided to defer the rate
increases in light of the FCC's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the reaction on the part of some, we want to go back and
make sure we're delivering the benefits we thought we were,'' said
James Cicconi, AT&AMP;T's general counsel. ``We expect to move as
quickly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the FCC complaints to AT&AMP;T were prompted by a
report on Wednesday in The New York Times about the rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of an announcement last Wednesday by the FCC and
AT&AMP;T of an agreement that they said would cut phone costs for
millions of customers, the company filed documents wit the agency
describing plans for major rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
   The new basic plan would have eliminated a $3 monthly minimum
for long-distance service but would have increased per-minute
charges every day except Sunday, the only day when rates would come
down. The biggest increase would have taken place on Saturday, when
rates would have jumped by 163 percent, from 11 cents a minute to
29 cents.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's announcement came after officials at the FCC threatened
on Wednesday to take steps to reject the rate hikes. Ordinarily,
the agency has limited authority to force telephone companies to
reduce their rates. But under the agreement announced last week
between the agency and most of the major phone companies, including
AT&AMP;T, the FCC may impose ``fines, forfeitures or the rejection of
any non-conforming rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither AT&AMP;T nor the FCC publicized the rate hikes last week
when they said that millions of telephone customers would see lower
bills as the company passed on savings from a government-ordered
reduction in the fees that long-distance companies pay to local
phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   In their announcement last week, the agency and AT&AMP;T also said
that subscribers to the basic service would benefit by the
elimination of a minimum monthly $3 fee. But the announcement never
mentioned that the flat per-minute rates would be increased Monday
through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2103EDT &QL; 
