<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7550 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SUNSHINE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-07 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNSHINE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUNSHINE' OVERSHADOWED BY FLAWS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A century of harrowing Hungarian history is given soap opera
treatment in ``Sunshine.'' The nearly three-hour long,
sensationally superficial family saga was made in English by the
Academy Award-winning Hungarian director Istvan Szabo
(``Mephisto''), who co-wrote its unwieldy yet somehow also
claustrophobic script with the respected American playwright Israel
Horovitz. The film is not without merit, but watching it is a
chore.
</P>
<P>
   And that is a shame, since a morelucid, honestly felt epic on
this work's grand themes would have been fascinating. Pretty much
employing the whole 20th century as a canvas, Szabo addresses the
persistent nature of political oppression, the soul-risking
struggle to assimilate in an intransigently anti-Semitic society
and the heartbreaking tendency of sons to repeat their fathers'
worst mistakes. Rich material, to be sure, but not when presented
as a collection of position speeches, great events that are
referred to more often than shown and melodramatic sexual
encounters with the most inappropriate partners.
</P>
<P>
   What we're looking at is a Jewish family saga, beginning at the
point when great-great granddad Sonnenschein blew himself up along
with the shtetl still that brewed the herbal tonic which came to
bear the family name. Great grandpa Emmanuel headed to the capital
with the recipe, and by the time his own children were born, the
Taste of Sunshine bottling enterprise had become big in Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   By the turn of the century, Emmanuel's sons Ignatz (Ralph
Fiennes) and Gustave (James Frain) had grown into, respectively,
one of the Austro-Hungarian Empire's most promising jurists and a
doctor with anarchist leanings. And both young men had fallen in
love with their beautiful life-force of a cousin, Valerie (recent
Tony-winner Jennifer Ehle), whom they were raised with like a
sister.
</P>
<P>
   Ignatz changes his name to the more gentile-sounding Sors in
order to advance his career and, scandalously, marries Valerie.
Gustave gets miffed. In service to his beloved Emperor _ a pretty
liberal guy for a Hapsburg, after all _ Ignatz signs up for a
little war with Serbia. Four years later, everything's been shot to
hell.
</P>
<P>
   But, as we all know, it gets a lot worse. Succeeding generations
of Ralph Fienneses and an amazingly durable Valerie (played for the
next 50-some years by Ehle's real-life mother, Rosemary Harris),
suffer under succeeding socialist, military, fascist, Stalinist and
late Communist regimes, losing almost everyone and everything to
awful historical forces ... Yet, somehow, still managing to bed
everybody that they shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The tedious, poorly spoken film (sample dialogue: ``I want to
grow like a wildflower, where it belongs!'') has its best moments
when Ralph (Num)2, known as Adam, leads the Hungarian fencing team
to victory at the '36 Berlin Olympics (where he's actually
applauded by the Nazis whose Magyar partners will murder him in
less than a decade); and when Ralph (Num)3, this one called Ivan,
bonds with a cagey but doomed Communist functionary (William Hurt
in the film's best performance) over wreaking vengeance on war
criminals and, later, in appalled disbelief at the murderous
paranoia of their Moscow-puppeted associates.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting stuff, but not enough so to make this a rewarding
sit for any but the most devoted Ralph-watchers (and, needless to
say, if you're not a fan of the Englishman's twitchy mannerisms,
the sleding is even tougher). ``Sunshine'' feels like nothing so
much as a great opportunity missed, it's grand intentions
overshadowed by pedestrian execution. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
- The film: ``Sunshine'' (R; violence, sex, nudity, language). &QL; 
- The stars: Ralph Fiennes, Rosemary Harris, Rachel Weisz, Jennifer
Ehle, William Hurt. &QL; 
- Behind the scenes: Directed by Istvan Szabo. Written by Szabo and
Israel Horovitz. Produced by Robert Lantos and Andras Hamori.
Released by Paramount Classics. &QL; 
- Running time: Two hours, 50 minutes. &QL; 
- Playing: Town Center 5, Encino; Rialto, South Pasadena; Cecchi
Gori Fine Arts, Beverly Hills; Monica, Santa Monica. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-PARTNERS060     06-07 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-PARTNERS0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Competitors of all sizes hopeful
 &HT;    By Caroline Hubbard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal judge's decision Wednesday to split
Microsoft into two parts is good news for Atlanta companies big and
small that compete with the world's largest software company.
</P>
<P>
   Giants like Scientific-Atlanta, as well as start-up companies
like Weema Technologies and SideTalk, believe they'll profit from
the split.
</P>
<P>
   But some local companies, especially those that partner with
Microsoft, may suffer.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that Microsoft has already said it would appeal,
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled that a two-way
split of the world's largest software firm is the best way to make
sure there is competition in the software market.
</P>
<P>
   According to the plan, one company would be formed to oversee
the Windows operating system and the other would be responsible for
all other Microsoft software, such as its word processing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Two Atlanta companies _ publicly traded Scientific-Atlanta and
tiny start-up SideTalk _ hope the breakup delays Microsoft's
development of new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta produces three levels of software for cable
set-top boxes _ operating system, middleware (programs that serve
as the glue to connect two separate programs) and applications.
Microsoft is developing technology to compete in all three
categories, though it hasn't commercially released any products
yet. The technology allows for interactive television, such as
video-on-demand and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reasonable to predict that the breakup would be fairly
disruptive,'' said Steve Necessary, chief executive of PowerTV, a
subsidiary of Scientific-Atlanta that focuses on the set-top box
software. ``It is also reasonable to predict it would not
accelerate (development).''
</P>
<P>
   Because Microsoft would be split into an operating systems
company and an applications company, Young hopes its set-top box
division would also split along those lines. That way, Microsoft
would not be able to offer a comprehensive set-top box product the
way that Scientific Atlanta does.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great, inherent appeal in providing a single,
integrated solution,'' Necessary said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta's stock closed Wednesday at $65.50, up 3.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   SideTalk, which has technology that allows two or more people to
surf the Web together on a co-browser, hopes the breakup will
hinder Microsoft's development of a similar product. ``My guess is
that this would slow them down,'' said Chief Executive Officer
Andrew Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   Another company that hopes to benefit is Weema, a streaming
technology company that competes with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will affect us positively,'' said Marty Young, chief
executive officer. ``I think it will affect a lot of companies
positively.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the benefits go directly into Weema's cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   When Young started looking for venture capital funding last year
to get Weema off the ground, Microsoft hung over every negotiation
like a dark cloud. ``Microsoft has always been an issue,'' Young
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Taetle, a partner at Atlanta venture capital firm
Noro-Moseley Partners, told Young he was impressed with the
technology but concerned about a start-up's chances against a giant
like Microsoft. Though Weema managed to raise $2 million, the
Microsoft breakup likely will make it easier for Weema to get
another round of funding, according to both Young and Taetle.
</P>
<P>
   Weema built its streaming media technology _ used to display
real-time audio and video _ to run on Microsoft's Windows platform.
But Young contends that Microsoft strong-arms customers into buying
both the Windows operating systems and its applications, such as
streaming media.
</P>
<P>
   When and if Microsoft splits in two, ``at least other people can
write software on top of (Windows) without feeling threatened by
the vendor,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Atlanta companies that may benefit don't even realize it
yet, supporters of the breakup contend, saying existing companies
will expand and new companies will sprout due to the marketplace
changes.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is cheering. The breakup could hurt local
companies that partner with Microsoft, including consulting company
IntelliNet.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants at IntelliNet primarily use Microsoft products to
build solutions for clients. IntelliNet expects revenue between $16
million and $18 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Frank Bell said the breakup of Microsoft could
hurt IntelliNet's bottom line. ``There will be more overhead in
maintaining relationships with two companies,'' he said. ``That
will mean higher prices for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who said the breakup doesn't make sense in the Internet
age, calls himself ``a believer in Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to executives who are happy and those who are angry,
there are plenty of Atlanta executives who say they just don't
care. Leaders at two companies that received strategic funding from
Microsoft _ Radiant Systems and Interland _ say they don't expect
to feel much impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our communication and interaction with Microsoft thus far has
been a continuous stream,'' said Ken Gavranovic, chief executive
officer at Web hosting company Interland, ``and we fully expect
that the ruling would not do anything to change this.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Heyman, president of Radiant Systems, said, ``In general,
we are not concerned that (a breakup) will have any material
negative effect on our relationship with Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Radiant Systems' stock closed at $17 Wednesday, up $1.25.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Morettini, a partner at Deloitte &AMP; Touche in Atlanta, said
he doubts Atlanta's technology community overall will feel much
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Microsoft breaks up, they will still have tremendous
resources,'' he said. ``This is a non-event.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
