u p BC-REPUBS-CONVENTION-925     06-07 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CONVENTION-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMPAIGN IS PLANNING A LESS COMBATIVE, MORE POSITIVE
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANK BRUNI and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hoping to preserve and perpetuate an upbeat tone
that has served them well over the last several months, advisers to
Gov. George W. Bush say they are fashioning a party convention that
will emphasize policy over partisan vitriol and perhaps abandon the
frequent practice of devoting one night to an attack on the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   They say they want the second of the four nights, which has
often been reserved for such sniping, to adhere to a mostly
positive, sustained focus on exalting Gov. George W. Bush rather
than eviscerating Vice President Al Gore. They want every night to
underline a different set or area of Bush's substantive proposals.
</P>
<P>
   And, on a less atmospheric note, they want Gen. Colin Powell and
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., front and center, in prominent speaking
roles on different nights, so that each of them serves as a
separate lure for the fickle and finite attentions of the major
television networks.
</P>
<P>
   These sorts of issues will be a primary focus at a retreat Bush
and his aides are taking starting Sunday at his parents' compound
in Kennebunkport, Maine, as the campaign increasingly turns its
attention to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   And what is most striking about their plans, at least as they
were described in interviews with several of Bush's advisers over
the last few days, is the campaign's stated desire to avoid harsh
attacks and to try to make the intrinsically partisan proceedings
seem less so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to be a somewhat different convention,'' Karen P.
Hughes, the Bush campaigns director of communications, said in an
interview here Tuesday. ``There will not be the traditional Tuesday
night attack at this convention. Each night will have a positive
discussion of Governor Bush's proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, tone is relative, and often in the ear of the
beholder, and Hughes and other advisers were careful to say that
the convention would still have a place for critical evaluations of
Gore's record and proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser said the convention shares the same goal that
the campaign has pursued ever since Bush effectively sealed the
Republican nomination in mid-March: namely, to convince voters that
the Texas governor is ``a different kind of Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   One clear way to do that is to change the tone, the adviser
said. Republicans toyed with that in 1996, scheduling the comments
of the party's most polarizing figure, then-House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, during the portion of the second night before prime-time
television coverage, and putting more women into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But even during the peak of the second night, when Rep. Susan
Molinari of New York delivered the keynote address, there was ample
venom for President Clinton. Molinari characterized him as utterly
untrustworthy and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas attacked
Clinton and his ``Social-Security-taxing, health-care-socializing,
drug-coddling, power-grabbing, business-busing'' administration.
She also bluntly ridiculed first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Gillespie, an adviser to the Bush campaign who is helping to
organize the convention, said that this time around, ``We're going
to continue to emphasize what Governor Bush is for, and I don't
know that there's time left over for the kinds of bitter attacks
that we've seen from both parties' conventions in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are differences between the two candidates,''
Gillespie said, referring to Bush and Gore. ``And you can't
necessarily point out what they are without talking about the vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention, in other words, will walk a fine oratorical
line, several advisers said. It will take equal care, they said, in
the way it presents former President George Bush, whose position as
the last Republican to reside in the White House makes him a
compelling figure but whose presence could also remind voters of
the advantages that helped get his son to this point.
</P>
<P>
   One adviser said that the former president would probably be
introduced and included primarily in the context of other recent
Republican presidents, like Gerald Ford, who would also attend the
convention. Ronald Reagan, who suffers from Alzheimer's disease,
might be represented by video footage or by his wife, Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, one adviser said, the convention may include some
featured speakers who are not politicians but rather people who are
grappling, in their professional or personal lives, with the very
issues that Bush has discussed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is making its plans for this year's event with
the belief that both parties' conventions may matter more than in
previous years, for the simple if seemingly unrelated fact that the
Summer Olympics will occur so much later than usual.
</P>
<P>
   In most recent presidential election cycles, the Olympics were
over by the time of the conventions, and both the Republicans and
Democrats could count on relatively sustained network television
coverage of their candidates in September, the month after the
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the case for this cycle. The Republican
convention, in Philadelphia, runs from July 31 to August 3. The
Democratic convention, in Los Angeles, is from August 14 to 17. The
Olympics, in Sydney, Australia, take up the last two weeks of
September.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the television networks may pay little heed to
politics for much of September, and the impressions that Bush and
Gore create at their respective conventions may linger longer,
unchallenged by new information, in voters' minds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Various officials with the Bush campaign have been plotting
convention strategy for months, but Hughes said that the gathering
of senior advisers in Kennebunkport will be the first time the
campaign's senior decision makers have paid such close, vigorous
attention to the coming event. Bush will head to Kennebunkport late
Friday so that he can visit his parents and join his relatives in
celebrating the 75th birthday of his mother, former first lady
Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Those present at the gathering, in addition to Hughes and Bush,
will include Karl Rove, the campaign's chief strategist, Josh
Bolten, the campaign's policy director, and Michael Gerson, the
chief speechwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will see the first full draft of a proposed convention
speech that Gerson has spent much of the last month preparing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said that they were trying to plan the
convention less as a four-day event than as a 12- or 16-day one,
with a preceding schedule of appearances and announcements for Bush
that would build to the actual proceedings in Philadelphia. They
said they had not yet decided when they will announce the
candidate's vice presidential selection, and that he was not close
to making that decision.
</P>
<P>
   One aide said that each night of the convention might come under
a different ``umbrella theme,'' like education or Social Security
or America's role and stature in the world, which would allow for a
summary of various proposals Bush has made.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Powell and McCain, Elizabeth Dole is being
considered for a prominent speaking role. But aides stressed that
changes to their current intentions could occur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
