u f BC-MICROSOFT-REDMOND-NYT     06-07 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REDMOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT LOOKS AHEAD TO THE APPEALS PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ From the perspective of the Microsoft Corp.,
the nation's largest software company, its legal battle with the
federal government is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman and chief software architect,
said Wednesday that he was looking forward to the next round of the
epic antitrust trial that will soon move to a higher court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reminded of the old saying that today is the first day of
the rest of your life,'' Gates said during a press conference here
on his company's sprawling campus. ``I believe very strongly that
today is the first day of the rest of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates appeared calm Wednesday, briefly stumbling over his words
at the outset of his prepared remarks but then warming to his theme
that during the appeals process Microsoft would continue to do what
he believed the company does best: design software.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated his belief that Microsoft had done nothing wrong.
And when asked during the press conference if he felt he might have
done anything differently, he responded that his only regret was in
not articulating Microsoft's story earlier and more clearly to the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft and the whole story of the PC was missed here,'' he
said. ``I should have taken the opportunity to go and talk about
this industry and what it has meant in terms of empowering
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates argued that the company's principal contribution was in
transforming what was once a low volume and high cost computer
industry into a fast-paced, mass market business, in which
Microsoft's Windows operating system allowed consumers to
continually receive the benefits of new features that enhance the
power of desktop computing.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in front of seven of his top executives _ including
Robert Herbold, Microsoft's chief operating officer; William
Neukom, its chief lawyer; Jeff Raikes, a veteran marketing
executive; and Mich Matthews, the current marketing chief _ Gates
said that his most important challenge Wednesday is to pursue new
technologies like speech recognition and computing on tablets.
</P>
<P>
   He also sought to define the substance of the antitrust case
narrowly, saying that at its heart the case was about nothing more
than whether his company had the right to add Internet browsing
capabilities to its operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core of the case is whether it was appropriate for
Microsoft to put Internet support into Windows,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's press conference, Gates answered questions for
several minutes before turning the meeting over to his legal
counsel, Neukom, who proceeded to give a preview of the company's
strategy on appeal, which he said would be filed in a matter of
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both the substance of the case and the lack of any
process during the remedy phases make a compelling case for our
appeal,'' Neukom said.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom, who led the company's defense before Jackson during the
long antitrust trial, also pointedly attacked the many state
attorneys general _ without mentioning them by name _ for foiling
the company's attempts to reach a negotiated settlement with the
Justice Department during a mediation attempt by federal appeals
court Justice Richard Posner several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all of the parties were willing to engage in a serious
good faith effort towards a mediation,'' Neukom said.
</P>
<P>
   The feelings Gates expressed Wednesday about how his company has
been treated unfairly by government prosecutors were echoed widely
among Microsoft's 34,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   On the Redmond campus, there has been a palpable sense in recent
months of the closing of ranks, according to a number of Microsoft
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The view here, almost universally held, is that Microsoft, while
seen by many outsiders as a huge and highly successful predator, is
actually the victim of a small Silicon Valley cabal. This group of
industry chieftains were fairly vanquished on the market
battlefield, Microsoft employees often say, but decided to carry on
their war in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is a sense in Redmond that the situation has
become exacerbated by what many here view as the media circus that
now surrounds the antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become the designated whipping boy for corporate
misbehavior,'' said one of the company's top executives. ``It
leaves other companies free to merge and engage in all kinds of
behaviors without being noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other employees said that there were no surprises for them in
Wednesday's ruling, even as they insisted that Jackson's decision
to endorse the government's proposed breakup was clearly
wrongheaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all the media coverage of this, I'm not surprised,''
said George Bullock, a programmer who works for the company's MSDN
group that creates tools for software developers. ``But I
whole-heartedly disagree with the government's case.''
</P>
<P>
   But while there was widespread disappointment over the outcome
so far in the case, many employees took issue with Microsoft's
contention in its last court filing in the case on Tuesday that a
break-up could lead to mass defections among the company's highly
technical workforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe in Microsoft, and I still like what I do
here,'' said Franc Camara, a program manager in the company's
Windows Division. ``As long as I'm doing something interesting, I
don't care if it is broken into two, or three, or four companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates clearly remains a revered figure in the Seattle area. The
case has been closely watched by many of the region's residents.
</P>
<P>
   At the Seattle airport Wednesday, Gates had many fans on his
side. ``I think that if the company is split up it will harm
consumers and raise costs,'' said an employee at a rental car
counter. ``Tell Bill Gates that Jenny at Avis said hi and is
supporting him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny noted that she owned a small amount of Microsoft stock.
When asked about its recent performance, she frowned slightly and
turned her thumb down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
