<SLUG> BC-ROCKER0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Rocker's day to quit or play
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Rocker is a lot of things to a lot of people, but
a quitter?
</P>
<P>
   The controversial Braves closer threatened to do just that on a
radio show, two days after being optioned to the Braves' Class AAA
team. The Braves said the move was made so he could work on his
control on the mound, although it came the day after Rocker's
outburst at Sports Illustrated writer Jeff Pearlman.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker has until today to report to Toledo where the Richmond
Braves are playing. If he doesn't, he can be fined or suspended
without pay.
</P>
<P>
   If Rocker goes to Richmond _ and the Braves still expect him to
_ he's not going to go quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't even decided if I'm going down or not,'' Rocker said
on 96 Rock's morning show, on which he has regularly appeared in
the past year. ``I'm still pretty chafed about the whole situation.
I'm just not wanting to play anymore, just shut it down . . . for
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves players and general manager John Schuerholz agreed
Wednesday that Rocker was just upset, like any player is when he's
sent down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a position where he's ticked off and not thinking,''
pitcher Tom Glavine said. ``Come on. Where else is he going to make
the kind of money he can in this game? He has a talent to play the
game. . . It's up to him. Plain and simple. That's the biggest
thing he has to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
