<SLUG> BC-LEAH-SFCHRON-PERSONALS </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: British Still Holding a Grudge? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
In ``The Patriot,'' which opens in the United States late this
month,  &UR; Mel &LR;   &UR; Gibson &LR;  plays an American farmer,  &UR; Benjamin Martin &LR; ,
a historic figure who fought against England in the Revolutionary
War. British newspapers aren't taking this well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is far from an accurate account of (Martin's)
participation,'' says the Sunday Times of London, in a passage
quoted by MSNBC. ``Instead, in the hands of an Australian actor
working with a German director and funded by Hollywood money, his
story has been transformed into a 160-minute polemic against the
British.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Mail agreed. ``I don't know what Mel Gibson has
against the English, but he gives them absolute hell in `The
Patriot,' '' said that newspaper. As did the Belfast Telegraph:
``New York-born, Australia-raised Mel Gibson loves bashing the
Brits in his movies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's next?'' asked the Mirror. ``A film about a young boy
from Wisconsin named Winston Churchill who saves the world from the
evils of Nazism?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; STATE LEGISLATURES TAKING ACTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Libertarian Party, which naturally wrinkles its nose at this
sort of thing, is the source for a list of recently passed state
laws and recommendations, cited on  &LR; prorev.com &LR; . Legislators have
OKd:
</P>
<P>
   _ The creation of a secretary of barbecue in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   _ The banning of clothing made out of dogs or cats in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   _ The scolding of  &UR; Craig Kilborn  &LR; for calling Kentucky
``Kensucky'' on late night television. Also in Kentucky, the
prohibition of any mention of non-Christian religions when teaching
Colonial history.
</P>
<P>
   _ The prohibition, in Utah, of auto dealers from selling cars or
trucks on consecutive Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Kevin Ryan  &LR; forwards a Sacramento Bee clipping describing
a paper sign on the men's room wall in the state Capitol's
Legislative Office Building: ``Please wash your hands before
touching legislation.'' Next to it, someone has posted another
sign: ``Please wash your hands after touching legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; A WOMAN'S WORK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The next-to-last page of the latest issue of the smart woman's
magazine Bitch carries an editor's notice saying it was supposed to
be a full page ad for a record. The image was of two sexy women on
a heart-shaped bed, a picture editor &UR; Lisa &LR; 
 &UR; Miya-Jervis &LR;  described as ``familiar faux-lesbian porno iconography
to make its sales pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the editors realized the photo could be taken as a
``gross usage of women's bods'' or ``an example of empowered women
manipulating their own image,'' when they realized that magazines
such as Maxim were running it, ``We knew our instincts were right.
Satire or not, an ad that uses the body language of porn to speak
to the Maxim reader is not getting its powerful, women-in-charge
subtext across. . . . Obviously, it's hard to judge without
actually seeing the ad, but we're not about to give these folks for
free the exposure we wouldn't let them pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MSNBC says that  &UR; Camilla Parker Bowles &LR;  wants  &UR; Donatella &LR; 
 &UR; Versace &LR;  _ creator of  &UR; Jennifer Lopez &LR; ' famous Grammy dress _ to
give her a makeover. This seems a sure way for Parker Bowles to
ingratiate herself with with her boyfriend's mother.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR;  writes in Marie Claire magazine that she's
``obsessed with manicures,'' has flown from San Francisco to Los
Angeles for fingernail ministrations and has flown her manicurist
up to San Francisco for a house call.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``There are two things I can play: an intellectual, because I &LR; 
 &UR; look like one, and a lowlife, because I am one. I've played an &LR; 
 &UR; ant and I've played a sperm. The low end of the spectrum comes &LR; 
 &UR; easy to me.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Woody Allen &LR;  in US weekly magazine.
</P>
