<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-ONWHEELS-YEA-1600(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING WHILE CELLING: SHOULD IT BE A CRIME?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Has a sidebar, CELL-ONWHEELS-NAY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
UNDATED: motor vehicle accident. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We caution,'' wrote authors Donald A. Redelmeier, M.D., and
Robert J. Tibshirani, Ph.D., ``against interpreting our data as
showing that cellular telephones are harmful and that their use
should be restricted. Even if a causal relation were established,
drivers are vulnerable to other distractions that could offset the
potential reductions in risk due to restricting the use of cellular
phones.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors also wrote that they found no safety advantage in
using hands-free units. What this could mean, they said, is that
motor vehicle collisions result from a driver's limitations with
regard to attention rather than dexterity.
</P>
<P>
   What this could mean, I extrapolated, is that it wasn't juggling
the phone that was the problem in cellphone-related accidents.
</P>
<P>
   It was that the drivers involved were AQ-challenged. The
cellphone was their distraction of choice. But it could have been a
cigarette. A Big Gulp. Or the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Nicholas Trott had to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A grave problem that developed has all the motor-vehicle
commissioners of the Eastern states in a wax. It's whether (they)
should be allowed in cars. Some states don't want to permit them at
all _ say they distract the driver and disturb the peace. The
manufacturers claim that the sound ... is less disturbing than
backseat conversation.... The whole problem is getting very
complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Trott wrote this in 1930, and he was talking about the radio
(this letter was published in the ``Farmer's Almanac'' in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   But the debate sounds familiar. New technology has a habit of
frightening people.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years later, we've learned that the radio is the tool,
not the terror.
</P>
<P>
   In compiling my defense of the car phone, I decided to take
another ride, this time on the Internet, where statistics abound.
Here's the best of what I found regarding car phone safety:
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 National Highway Traffic Safety Administration study
showed that distraction by a cellphone can increase the risk of
crashing, but also pointed out that anything that distracts the
driver of a vehicle _ from fiddling with the radio (!) to talking
with passengers _ increases that chance.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 California Highway Patrol survey concluded that ``none of
the researchers were able to make the statement that cellular
telephone use causes traffic collisions.''
</P>
<P>
   A current article on Drivers.com points out that drivers often
talk with other passengers, eat, smoke cigarettes and much more.
``Some drivers do this better than others, and this is an area
where appropriate research is lacking.'' As the author notes, there
is no such driver's test for attention-dividing skills (aha! my
sister's AQ test concept!).
</P>
<P>
   According to a Canadian Wireless Telecommunications Association
1986 study published in the ``New York Journal of Medicine,''
smokers had 50 percent more traffic accidents than nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine if a smoker had a Big Gulp, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   On the way home from the office, having digested all this
cellphone information, I dialed up my sister again. She had some
more to say about cellphones _ how they make you more productive
(''Look, you're working now!'' she pointed out). They make things
easy. They improve the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   And if they were such a true problem, why the heck hadn't the
hordes of statistics-loving actuaries jumped at the chance to hike
up cellphone users' car insurance rates?
</P>
<P>
   While Laura and I were mulling this, I made a mental note that
the woman ahead of me failed to use her signal indicator and then
moved across four lanes of traffic so she could get to the exit.
</P>
<P>
   Was she on the phone? It doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   You see, we've got laws against reckless driving.
</P>
<P>
   And clearly this woman was at fault, not whatever was
temporarily driving her to distraction.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
