</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL-ONWHEELS-YEA-1600(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING WHILE CELLING: SHOULD IT BE A CRIME?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Has a sidebar, CELL-ONWHEELS-NAY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first week I had a car phone, I backed out of my space in
the supermarket parking lot, gleefully dialing as I drove _ right
into the side of a white Subaru station wagon. No one was hurt, the
driver was abnormally kind as I confessed that it was all my fault,
and it was the beginning of a beautiful four-year friendship.
Between me and my cellphone.
</P>
<P>
   I am not alone in my infatuation with the wireless wonder.
Joining me are 92,367,059 Americans, many of whom, like me, take
the phones with us to the places we love (and hate) most. Grocery
stores. Medical appointments. Vacations. The car.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the car. It is its status as car accouterment that has
gotten the cellphone into a lot of trouble lately. Critics say the
phone is a menace, a distraction that impairs a driver's ability to
tend to the task at hand. Drivers with cellphones cause accidents,
they say, and they wave copies of a 1997 ``New England Journal of
Medicine'' study on cellphone safety under the noses of legislators
as proof-positive that Driving While Celling is as much of a danger
as Driving While Intoxicated. Wireless phones should be banned from
our autos, they say, noting that at least 35 states have considered
measures banning cellphone use in the car since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   I knew these anti-phone fanatics were wrong. And to prove it, I
decided to make a few phone calls. I started on the way home from
work.
</P>
<P>
   The first call was to my sister in New York. Laura is not an
expert on cellphone safety, but she has a lot of opinions and
offers them with the ring of authority. She tells me she thinks the
nay-sayers are probably people who can't multitask, people like
men.
</P>
<P>
   She says that if she weren't on the cellphone when she drives,
she'd be listening to books on tape, jotting down work-related
notes, carrying on a conversation with her husband and assuaging
the carsick puppy who is invariably in the way-back.
</P>
<P>
   Potential drivers, Laura proposed, should have to take an AQ _
attention quotient _ test to get on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all got distractions,'' she summed up. ``And tell me
drinking a Big Gulp in the car is any safer than using the cell.''
</P>
<P>
   These seemed like personal examples, but apparently my sister
had a point. The next phone call involved a librarian at the
National Safety Council in Chicago. She told me she'd fax me a copy
of the council's fact sheet on cellphone safety _ which clearly
said that there is no research that demonstrates that car phone use
while driving increases crash risk _ as well as a 1998 Traffic
Safety Facts sheet on crash data. This data looked at related
factors for drivers involved in fatal crashes and showed that
Inattention was a factor in 7.2 percent of the crashes that year.
Conversations on the cellphone would fall into that category, she
said, but so would eating. Unrestrained pets. Smoking. And,
presumably, Big Gulps.
</P>
<P>
   She also said she'd fax a copy of the ``New England Journal of
Medicine'' article.
</P>
<P>
   I thanked her, and immediately dialed up the baby sitter.
Traffic was a little heavy, and I was going to be late getting back
to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take your time,'' the sitter said, sensing my panic. ``We're
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   I slowed down, flipped through my CD holder and popped in
Santana to soothe my nerves. In the car ahead of me, the driver was
shaving.
</P>
<P>
   The report from the ``New England Journal of Medicine,'' on my
desk by 9 a.m., showed me how numbers can be crunched to suit
various purposes. I had read in at least one newspaper that the
report said driving while talking on the car phone was as dangerous
as driving drunk. But that wasn't exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   What it really said was that the study, involving 699 drivers,
showed an association but not necessarily a ``causal'' relation
between the use of cellular phones while driving and a subsequent
motor vehicle accident. &QL; 
MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
