<SLUG> BC-CELL-ONWHEELS-NAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S RANT AGAINST RECKLESS TALKERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Has a sidebar, CELL-ONWHEELS-YEA) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUGLAS PERRY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever been driving along, minding your own business,
when suddenly some car appears beside you, and the lunatic driving
it is screaming obscenities at you and shaking a threatening fist?
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you should do when that happens: Hang up the dang
phone!
</P>
<P>
   It's time we face up to it. Americans' obsession with the
cellphone has gotten out of control. A ``New England Journal of
Medicine'' study suggests that talking on the phone while driving
is about as mind-muddling as being drunk. To be sure, studies and
stats can be twisted to suggest just about anything, but there's no
way around the fact that the worldwide car chaos has become severe
enough that a dozen countries prohibit the use of cellphones by
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, of course, is not one of those countries _
and that doesn't seem likely to change. (When a city councilman
from The Colony in Denton County, Texas, recently suggested a ban
after a fatal car crash that may have involved a cellphone, the
public clamor against the idea was immediate.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, please understand, I'm no by-the-book driver's ed hard
case. Preoccupied drivers, one could argue, provide some spice to
life. For example: I once watched a young blonde woman, cruising
along in a lime-green VW Bug, skillfully shed her business suit
and, shifting gears in the altogether, replace it with a bikini.
Not once did her car drop below 40 mph. (This was, needless to say,
Southern California.)
</P>
<P>
   Even besides such eye-opening Left Coast moments, I can
acknowledge legitimate excuses for letting your focus occasionally
wander from the road. For one thing, we're not robots. And for
another, danger is an integral component of the driving experience
_ especially in Texas, where driving is a test of our martial
spirit. With no foreign wars to fight, we must take our combat
where we can find it _ and that's on the road. The car has become
our chariot, the horn (or middle finger) our sword.
</P>
<P>
   So, the reason no one should be allowed to use a cellphone while
driving isn't simply that it's dangerous. Putting on makeup and
brushing your hair while driving are dangerous, too, but we all
have our personal grooming standards to uphold. No, the clincher is
that it's also extremely inconsiderate.
</P>
<P>
   Ever been on Interstate 30 when it's as wide open as the West
Texas horizon and you find yourself stuck behind a car going 35 in
the left lane? Nine times out of 10 it's some idiot chatting away
on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Before you nod in agreement, though, you should take a moment to
be grateful for the ones who simply go slow. It's better than the
folks so caught up in their phone conversations that they
mindlessly pull out into traffic or drive the wrong way on a
one-way street (I've witnessed both more than once). More typical
than the cell users who seem to be having an out-of-body experience
_ although often just as troublesome _ are the chatty drivers who
are aware of their surroundings only in fits. For no particular
reason, they slow down, speed up, slow down again, then begin to
drift sloppily into the next lane before suddenly jerking back into
place.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to say that such arguments are purely anecdotal
or that the accident stats are suspect. But anyone who drives knows
_ even if only deep, deep down in their subconscious _ that this is
the simple truth: No matter who you are or how long it's been since
you've gotten a moving violation, you cannot drive competently
while cupping a phone to your ear. You will get in an accident,
cause an accident, or, at the very least, get a lot of people's
blood boiling.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we've established that talking on the phone while driving
is needlessly dangerous and inconsiderate. That said, in all
fairness, there are a few situations when it's all right. When you
are stuck in bumper-to-bumper traffic and barely moving, there's
nothing wrong with calling the baby sitter to say you're going to
be late. Using a cellphone is similarly acceptable when you're lost
(I realize that's a big loophole for some people). And if, heaven
forbid, you're being menaced by another driver, a phone can be the
most valuable purchase you've ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, the best idea is always to pull off the road
and stop the car when you need to make a call. Unless, of course,
you're dialing 4-1-1 for the listing of the naked blonde whose VW
you're trying to keep up with. .MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
