</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROUST-FILM-$ADV11-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING PROUST'S WORLD ON FILM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Chile, Belgium)   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
 By LESLIE CAMHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In his 3,000-page monument to lost time, Marcel Proust
barely mentions the cinema. Writing in the decades immediately
following film's invention, he appears to have been largely
uninterested by the medium in which so many memories of the 20th
century would be stored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he saw very few films,'' said Jean-Yves Tadie, a
professor at the Sorbonne, over tea recently at his home here in a
graceful fin-de-siecle apartment building. The English translation
of Tadie's biography, ``Marcel Proust: A Life,'' will be released
by Viking in August. ``Perhaps a few newsreels, or some light
Gaumont comedies. He went out very little toward the end of his
life, fearing attacks of asthma. He died before Abel Gance's
`Napoleon,' and probably never knew the films of Chaplin. And so he
must not have understood that film was an art.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in ``Remembrance of Things Past,'' the narrator's
memories of childhood in the village of Combray _ with its
black-steepled church and all its inhabitants _ which unfold like a
Chinese paper flower from the cup of tea in which he's dunked a
madeleine, seem an apt metaphor for film's remarkable power to
revive the past and make the dead live again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Film is a very Proustian medium,'' said Raul Ruiz, the
director of ``Time Regained,'' during an interview after the film's
premiere at the Cannes International Film Festival last year. This
remarkable adaptation of the final volume of ``Remembrance of
Things Past'' opens in New York on Friday. ``At any given moment,
you can be kidnapped by the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Remembrance of Things Past'' does not lend itself easily
to film adaptation. Filmmakers must cope with the novel's
extraordinary length, and its strangely porous nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most novels, you have action, dialogue and commentary,''
Tadie said. ``But in Proust, the commentary takes up so much space.
A few lines of dialogue are followed by five pages of the
narrator's observations. And if you reduce things to action, there
just isn't much of it. He's no Sir Walter Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of finding a cinematic equivalent for
those interminable sentences, which seem to explore every shading
of erotic ambivalence or gilt Sevres porcelain, and in which one
can almost hear the asthmatic author gasping for breath.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the problem common to all literary
adaptations, but extreme in Proust's case, of reconciling cinematic
time with the experience of reading. Film's gratifications are
relatively speedy and immediate, while Proust's novel preaches the
infinite pleasures of deferral. Months or even years may separate
the reading of the first volume from the seventh and last. How can
all those intimate, solitary hours of enchantment be translated
into a marketable 120 minutes on screen ?
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz explained his working method. ``For a long while, Einstein
thought that, if time were a dimension, it should be visible,'' he
said. ``In making this film, I wondered how I might play with that
idea. I approached it in the most naive manner possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Using flashbacks, repetitions and visual refrains, he created a
film as intricately structured as a symphony, where each part
refers back to another in an infinite play of mirrors. He cast a
mother and daughter (Catherine Deneuve and Chiara Mastroianni) as
Odette and Albertine, figures who are unrelated in the novel but
whose roles as loved women echo each other across generations.
Within the continuous flow of his film's two-and-one-half hours,
time seems to expand exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   Early on in Proust's novel, the narrator describes the long
afternoons he spent in his room at Combray, amusing himself with a
magic lantern, a pre-cinematic device something like a slide
projector, whose glass negatives could be changed to create the
illusion of motion. The luminous images swallowed whole the forms
of the doorknobs and curtains onto which they were projected, and
took on extraordinary life for him. So every director who has
adapted Proust's work for film finds his own vision of cinema
reflected in that impossible project.
</P>
<P>
   Late in life, Luchino Visconti, the poet of smoldering,
suppressed passion among Italian aristocracy, planned a screen
version of Proust's middle volume, ``Sodom and Gommorah,'' but the
work was never realized. Near the end of his career, Joseph Losey
commissioned a screenplay called ``Proust Scenario,'' based on the
novel and written by the playwright Harold Pinter, but no film
emerged from it.
</P>
<P>
   Percy Adlon's ``Celeste'' (1981) was inspired by the memoirs of
Celeste Albaret, who worked as Proust's maid during the last eight
years of the author's life. Proust, a notoriously big tipper in
restaurants, was also known for his extravagant kindness toward
servants. Adlon's film, a strange combination of reticence and
caricature, follows a woman living in the antechamber of greatness,
rising at 3 p.m. each day to bring Monsieur his ``morning'' coffee,
and remaining on call for most of the night _ a portrait of the
intimate bond between the invalid artist and his servant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one had to wait until 1984 before a filmmaker tackled the
novel directly. For ``Swann in Love,'' Volker Schlondorff cast
Jeremy Irons as the cultivated Jewish art collector Charles Swann
and a remarkably fluffy Ornella Muti as Odette, the courtesan he
eventually marries. There's lots of lingerie, with heavy emphasis
on a pulchritudinous orchid tucked into Odette's swelling breast.
But by eliminating the crucial position of narrator, Schlondorff
sacrificed the novel's philosophical dimension, which transforms
Proust's account of aristocratic decadence and erotic despair into
a highly evolved work of art.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Chantal Akerman's ``Captive'' had its premiere in
the Director's Fortnight at Cannes. Akerman's Proust draws upon
passages from ``La Prisonniere,'' the novel's darkly minimalist
fifth volume, which describe the relation between the narrator and
his lover, Albertine _ a complex and ever-changing equation whose
key elements are jealousy, domination, sequestration and flight. To
render this bond, Akerman returned to the claustrophobic style of
``Jeanne Dielmann, 23 Quai de Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles,'' the
monumental film she made in 1975 when she was just 24 years old,
about three days in the life of a Belgian housewife, mother and
prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``For `La Captive,' I worked a lot in interior spaces,'' Akerman
said in a cafe on the Place des Vosges. ``The town houses, the
cars. Through them, the viewer is projected into a mental universe.
At the same time, you escape all psychological explanation. You're
just caught in a machine that moves forward.'' Akerman's signature
style is the long traveling shot. In ``La Captive,'' it tracks the
movements through Paris of a young woman in a floral print dress,
and evokes the narrator's libidinal fixations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Proust's iconic stature in French culture may explain why to
date there have been no French film interpretations. Adlon and
Schlondorff are German; Akerman is Belgian, though she has lived in
France for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of some 60 films, Ruiz (a Chilean who moved to
Paris in the 1970s) has cultivated a surrealist sensibility far
removed from the conventions of period drama and the salons of the
Belle Epoque. But ``Time Regained'' is a summation of themes that
have preoccupied him throughout his career, from the theoretical
rigors of ``Hypothesis of a Stolen Painting'' (1978) to more recent
thrillers like ``Genealogies of a Crime'' (1996): a fascination
with doubles and the uncanny, memory and childhood, the visual arts
and philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   His Proust is imbued with a narrative self-consciousness that
owes much to the author Jorge Luis Borges. But Ruiz also is able to
train an almost ethnographic eye on Parisian habits and manners.
Among his reference points for ``Time Regained'' were Edward
Curtis' sepia-toned, early-20th-century portraits of Native
Americans, in which grandeur combines with the threat of
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to explore what it's like to be a member of a
tribe,'' he explained. ``These French aristocrats, with their
boredom and their rituals. I tried to describe the behavior of that
tiny part of society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Regained'' opens in 1922 as Proust (played by Marcello
Mazzarella, an Italian actor who bears a striking resemblance to
the writer) lies on his deathbed, attended by the faithful Celeste.
He regards a series of photographs of figures in his life through a
magnifying glass.
</P>
<P>
   Subtly, the furniture in his room starts moving, and we are
carried back in time to Parisian soirees during World War I, where,
far from the front lines where men were dying, the upper classes
drank Champagne and listened to Beethoven. The infidelities of
Robert de Saint-Loup (Pascal Greggory), who betrays his wife
Gilberte (Emmanuelle Beart) with both the actress Rachel (Elsa
Zylberstein) and the arriviste violinist Morel (Vincent Perez); the
ghosts of the narrator's childhood love for Gilberte and his adult
passion for Albertine; the social ambitions and artistic
pretensions of Mme. Verdurin (Marie-France Pisier); the lingering
vanity of Odette; the strange sexual proclivities of the Baron de
Charlus (John Malkovich); and the stench of death which hangs
equally over soldiers on leave from the trenches and le tout Paris
arrayed for an elegant matinee concert; all these memories swarm
around the narrator. The effect is like a piece of music, a gradual
building of a sense of loss and time's passing, combined with a
fanatical devotion to detail and a gently ironic regard for human
frailty.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz reflected upon the author's perennial fascination. ``There
are Proustians who have nothing to do with the world of Proust,''
Ruiz said. ``Myself, for example. But also, Taiwanese dentists,
African economists, rock stars, and others. One of the characters
in Jack Kerouac's `On the Road,' either Sal Paradise or Dean
Moriarty, is continually reading Proust while he's working in a
parking lot. You can apply a Proustian vision to almost any
context. My explanation is that Proust teaches you a way to look at
your own life, and that the life of any human being is incredibly
rich.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
