right, in East Brunswick, N.J., Tuesday night. Propelled from
obscurity by his record-shattering $33 million campaign, retired
investment banker Corzine captured New Jersey's Democratic Senate
nomination. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   TRAD
</P>
<P>
   Clockwise from top left, John Danzer cooks for 12 in 518 square
feet; William Cohane's screens hide clutter;
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Schaps in his levitating bed; Marco Pasanella's design
gave Emily Oberman's television a whirl. Rowley, holding one-year
old daughter, and her husband, Keenan,. CYNT Cynthia Rowley, in a
leather jacket from her own line, with her 1-year-old daughter.
(Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times; stylist, Carlos Mota)
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Rowley, the fashion designer, and her husband, Bill
Keenan, a designer and sculptor, shucked the headaches involved in
owning a shingled four-bedroom stunner in the estate section of
East Hampton and moved instead to a surfer's shack in Montauk. The
1946 surfer shack, left, impressed Rowley, holding one-year old
daughter, and her husband, Keenan, with its midcentury- modern
look. Above, the living space was furnished with garage sale finds.
(Outside, a 1965 Galaxy.) Top right, the bed goes behind a sliding
screen. Bottom, the ``cheese grater'' partition sealed the deal.
TINY WATERING HOLE Doris Tobias crams hundreds of plants into 700
square feet.
