<HEADLINE>
OSUNA STRUGGLES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Dodgers needed Antonio Osuna on Wednesday
afternoon. But his head was still in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, who got the loss Sunday against the Angels, took over for
Darren Dreifort to begin the eighth inning. The Dodgers held on to
win 11-6, but Osuna again didn't pitch well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked four in the Angels game and I was still thinking
about that,'' said Osuna, who faced just four batters on Wednesday,
retired only one and allowed two runs. ``I felt good, but I
couldn't make the pitches. I tried too hard not to mess up and I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   With closer Jeff Shaw just coming back from shoulder trouble and
Mike Fetters still unable to pitch on back-to-back days, the
Dodgers were hoping Osuna could close out the game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson had to pull him almost
immediately. Johnson wound up using Shaw in the ninth in a non-save
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hadn't pitched in a while so I figured he'd be strong,''
Johnson said of Osuna. ``But he didn't have any pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, once projected as the team's closer, returned from the
disabled list May 5 after missing most of the past two years with
elbow problems. With six other relievers, Osuna has been in a
position to ease his way back. But with Shaw struggling, Wednesday
was critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the problem today was more mental than anything,'' Osuna
said. ``I have to stop worrying about the walks and just throw.''
</P>
<P>
   CORA STAYS HOT: Dodgers rookie shortstop Alex Cora had two more
hits Wednesday and scored three times. He was 4 for 9 in the last
two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Opening-day shortstop Kevin Elster could be back by the weekend
from a tender groin. Adrian Beltre is eligible to return from a
strained hamstring on Monday but could be out a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   Elster probably will move to third and Cora will stay at short.
But what happens to Cora when Beltre returns?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a day-to-day situation,'' Johnson said. ``Cora is playing
great. We don't have to make a decision right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre remained in Los Angeles during the Texas trip and began
light running. But he still hasn't taken batting practice and
Johnson said it's unlikely he'll be ready Monday.
</P>
<P>
   SUSPENSION HEARING DATES: Paul Beeston, chief operating officer
for major-league baseball, will hear arguments June 20-22 in
Houston from the 16 Dodgers players and three coaches suspended for
the May 16 fight at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 89 games in suspensions and $77,000 in fines were
handed down by Frank Robinson, baseball's vice president of
on-field operations. But Beeston is expected to reduce and in some
cases wipe out the penalties imposed on the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS: Left-hander Trever Miller, who was designated for
assignment after posting a 23.14 ERA in two games with the Dodgers,
has cleared waivers and was outrighted to Triple-A Albuquerque. ...
Rangers starter Rick Helling, who appeared to regain the form that
led to 20 victories in 1998, was battered by the Dodgers. Entering
the game fourth in the AL with a 3.45 ERA, Helling allowed seven
runs and a career-high 11 hits in five-plus innings. ... Texas
catcher Ivan Rodriguez might be the AL MVP but he also leads the
league grounding into 15 double plays. He had two more Wednesday
and also had his second passed ball of the year. Rodriguez had one
all last season. ... Gabe Kapler, the Taft High product who was
part of the Juan Gonzalez trade with Detroit, wound up a brief
rehab assignment (partial tear right quad) Wednesday night. He went
6 for 8 in the first two games, with two homers. The Rangers
already have made plans to bring him back, sending out pitcher
Jonathan Johnson, who pitched three innings Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
