<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-PRESIDENTIAL-POLLS-HN     06-07 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIAL-POLLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS WARN ABOUT READING TOO MUCH INTO POLLS AT THIS STAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Politicians are fond of saying the only poll that
counts is on election day.
</P>
<P>
   But five months before the presidential election, the public is
being swamped with surveys telling them exactly what they think
about Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Media pundits and political campaigns often seize upon such
polls to validate their perceptions about whether candidates are
gaining momentum or backsliding.
</P>
<P>
   A raft of May polls showing Gore slipping behind Bush were cited
as evidence that the vice president's campaign had lost its footing
and that the Texas governor had recovered from a rough primary.
</P>
<P>
   However, a crop of new polls finding the race a statistical dead
heat has prompted some analysts to opine that Gore may have halted
the hemorrhaging and Bush may have peaked.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to spin poll results their way, Bush campaign aides
briefed reporters in Austin this week to stress that the Texas
governor has led in the vast majority of surveys since the Super
Tuesday primary in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this give us confidence that we've been right in
executing the plan in the way we have? Does it give us confidence
that if we continue to execute it the way that we have that we have
a good shot at it (the election)? You bet,'' said a high level
strategist to Bush, a candidate who regularly proclaims on the
stump that he would not govern by the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, which like the Bush campaign has professional
pollsters on the payroll, has not brandished poll results in media
briefings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane accused the Bush campaign of being
``obsessed'' with polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls go up. Polls go down. They are merely a moving
picture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And experts warn about reading too much into polls at this early
stage, when much of the public is spending more time pondering
summer vacations than presidential options.
</P>
<P>
   They say that voters will tune into the presidential race during
the national political conventions in late July and August and
begin to firm up their voting intentions around Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientists argue that other factors, particularly
public satisfaction with the economy, have historically been more
indicative of whether voters will reward the candidate whose party
currently controls the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polls today just don't tell you a lot about what is going
to happen in November,'' said Christopher Wlezien, a political
scientist at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Wlezien, along with Columbia University Professor Robert S.
Erikson, has developed a forecasting model that uses economic data
and presidential approval rates to determine who will win the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the the booming economy and President Clinton's high
approval rating at the beginning of this year, Wlezien's model has
predicted that Gore will win with 56.1 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes toward Bush are less relevant than how voters feel
about the performance of the current administration, Wlezien said,
because the election is largely a referendum on the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We either stay the course or we change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Wlezien was only slightly off in his prediction that,
excluding Reform Party candidate Ross Perot, Clinton would beat Bob
Dole with with 54.5 percent of the vote. In the two-way match-up
Clinton actually took 54.6 percent of the vote _ though in total
votes Clinton fell below 50 percent both times he was elected. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But some pollsters scoff at the notion that presidential
elections are determined by historical trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we only relied on history to make predictions, then nothing
new would happen,'' said Andy Kohut, the director of the Pew
Research Center Poll, whose May results had Gore trailing Bush by a
statistically insignificant one percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Kohut said his polls show that while respondents are giving
Clinton credit for the good economy, they do not transfer that good
will to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the polls are bouncing around right now because
many voters still are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   However, Frank Newport of the Gallup Poll says that despite
slight variations in polls, the basic dynamics of the race have not
changed. He said Bush was ahead of Gore last year and has remained
so through the spring, although by a smaller margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup Poll taken at the end of May had Bush leading Gore 49
percent to 42 percent
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters agree that just looking at horse race numbers is not
enough. They say that response to the question of whether voters
believe the country is headed in the right or wrong direction is
helpful in gauging the depth of support for the incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   For example, even though June 1992 polls showed President Bush
ahead of Clinton, only about 14 percent of those surveyed by Gallup
said they were satisfied with the way things were going.
</P>
<P>
   Bush eventually lost the election, which political observers
attributed largely to voters' unhappiness with the sour economy.
The most recent Gallup poll found that 55 percent were satisfied
with the direction of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters also point to the favorable-unfavorable ratings of
candidates as a gauge of how the public is responding to more
intangible aspects of a candidate, such as his character and
likability
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Gallup Poll, Bush scored slightly better than Gore
on this measure, with 61 percent of voters giving him favorable
marks and 33 percent unfavorable. Gore had 53 percent favorable and
38 percent unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   Newport said that polls at this stage are not intended to be
predictive but rather ``here's where this race stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the vast majority of the presidential elections since
1936, the contender who was ahead in the June or late spring Gallup
Polls went on to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   However, these polls were an accurate predictor in only one of
the three elections involving sitting vice presidents, who often
have trouble emerging from the shadow of the president until the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960 John F. Kennedy was slightly ahead of Vice President
Richard Nixon in the June polls and went on to win in a cliffhanger
election.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later Vice President Hubert Humphrey was ahead of
Nixon in the early polls but lost in the close 1968 contest. And in
1988 Vice President Bush trailed Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
in June but later beat him by a healthy margin.
</P>
<P>
   Experts note that it is important to look not just at national
surveys but at state polls, particularly in traditional
battleground states, since the presidential outcome actually is
determined on a state-by-state basis under the Electoral College
system.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates are close in a number of swing states that
Clinton won in 1996 including Michigan, Illinois, New Jersey and
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   A tally of state polls _ some of them several months old _ by
The Hotline, an on-line political newsletter, found that Bush led
in 26 states with 282 electoral voters while Gore led in 13 states
with 178 electoral votes. To win, a candidates must get 270
electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Independent polls also provide insight into the behavior of
campaigns, which track their progress through their own private
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   The internal polling often ``drives what candidates are doing,''
said pollster John Zogby.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when polls showed Bush losing support among
independents after his primary battle with John McCain, the Texas
governor quickly tried to move back to the middle by proposing a
number of of initiatives aimed at moderate voters.
</P>
<P>
   And after recent polls detected Gore's support among women
waning after his harsh attacks on Bush, the vice president toned
down his rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the year Zogby's polls have bounced from
double digit leads for Bush to a one-point advantage in a survey
released late last week. The New York-based pollster said he now
believes Bush may have peaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard for me to see Gore losing this race,'' he
said. But he added, considering the strong economy, the vice
president should be doing better in the polls. ``He really ought to
be clobbering the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
