<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7595 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-PHONE-RATES-2NDTAKE-N     06-07 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-RATES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: through Saturday.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the plan announced last week would reduce bills by as much
as 50 percent for a consumer who made no long distance calls, it
would increase rates for those on the basic plan who made more than
12 minutes of calls and followed the national pattern for calls,
according to an analysis by the Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   A customer who, for instance, decided one month to make 45
minutes worth of long-distance calls on Saturdays under the old
plan would pay $4.95 plus taxes and special fees. Under the plan
filed last week, that same customer would pay $13.05 plus taxes and
fees. And under another current plan the company will be promoting
that charges 19 cents a minute, the customer would pay $8.55.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups and Wall Street analysts said on Wednesday that
they did not blame AT&AMP;T for what some said was, in effect, a
pricing shell game of reducing rates in some areas and increasing
them in others. But they criticized the FCC for both being
misleading and for failing to prevent rates from increasing.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, Scott Cleland of Legg Mason Precursor Group, who
had praised the FCC for putting forward a rate plan that eliminated
some hidden subsidies from bills, on Wednesday compared officials
there to a scene in the Peanuts comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like Lucy and the football,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Kimmelman, the co-director of the Washington office of
Consumers Union, said the day's developments had demonstrated that
the FCC had failed to negotiate a rate plan that it could properly
monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FCC has put out a plan which has no effective monitoring
or compliance mechanisms,'' he said. ``The decision announced by
AT&AMP;T today is not a bad deal. It is fine for today, but what about
tomorrow, next week and next month when you don't have the outrage
that was clearly felt today by the company.''
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom and Sprint, the nation's second- and third-largest
long-distance companies, will also benefit from last week's
agreement cutting the fees they pay to local phone companies to
connect customers' calls.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike AT&AMP;T, neither has filed a rate increase for basic
service in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T executives said that Wednesday's announcement would not
affect its plan to increase charges on some One Rate plans, in
which customers pay a flat fee on top of a set per-minute charge.
The flat fee on those plans will increase by 66 percent, to $5 a
month from $3.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that they had proposed the new basic rates
presuming that many customers would shift making long-distance
calls to Sunday to save money. The proposed plan would have reduced
Sunday calling rates on the basic plan to 7 cents a minute from 11
cents.
</P>
<P>
   But only about 20 percent of all residential calls are placed on
Sunday, and the filing last week with the FCC raised rates for the
other six days.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old basic plan, customers paid 11 cents a minute for
Saturday long-distance calls. For calls made on Monday to Friday
during the peak hours of 7 a.m. to 7 p.m., the basic rate charged
26 cents a minute. For off-peak hours, long-distance calls cost 16
cents a minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
