<HEADER>
A7596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-07 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Judge Orders Breakup of Microsoft Into 2 Units
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered the breakup of Microsoft, saying the
severe remedy was necessary because Microsoft ``has proved
untrustworthy in the past'' and did not appear to accept his ruling
that it had broadly violated the nation's antitrust laws. Under his
order, Microsoft would be broken into separate companies, one for
its Windows operating system and one for its other businesses.
Microsoft would also be forced to comply with restrictions on its
conduct. The order stays the breakup plan, but not the other
measures, pending an appeal. As Microsoft assesses the implications
of the breakup order, the advice from professional communicators on
how the company ought to handle the consequences is being offered
almost as quickly as the ``I Love You'' computer worm infested
e-mail in-boxes.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Puts Off Its Rate Increase
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T gave into pressure from embarrassed federal regulators and
outraged consumer groups and said that it would put off a planned
rate increase that would have raised telephone bills for tens of
millions of customers. The announcement came after a flurry of
calls between senior AT&AMP;T executives and the chairman of the
Federal Communications Commission, William Kennard.
</P>
<P>
   A Bitter Showdown in Indonesia
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Indonesia's central bank governor was named as a
suspect in a financial scandal, he and the government squared off
in a bitter showdown that could erode what little confidence
investors have in this fragile country. The governor of Bank
Indonesia, Syahril Sabirin, left, said he would not step down
despite repeated requests from Indonesia's president, Abdurrahman
Wahid. Sabirin denied any wrongdoing and said he was a victim of a
political witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Issues Bolster Stocks
</P>
<P>
   Paced by technology issues, stock prices resumed their climb. A
jump in IBM after a positive analyst report accounted for about 60
percent of the Dow Jones industrial average's rise of 77.29 points,
or 0.7 percent, to 10,812.86. The Nasdaq composite index advanced
82.89 points, or 2.2 percent, to 3,839.26. And the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index climbed 13.52 points, or 0.9 percent, to
1,471.36.
</P>
<P>
   Big Board in Talks on Global Link
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange is discussing the creation of a
single global stock market that would electronically connect the
trading systems of a half-dozen major exchanges from Tokyo to
Toronto. Such a market could provide investors worldwide with
one-stop access to exchanges that list companies with a total
market value of $20 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors Agree to Portfolio Review
</P>
<P>
   In response to an inquiry into possible breaches in the
independence of corporate auditors, the Big Five accounting firms
have agreed to open up the investment portfolios of their partners
and top managers to the Securities and Exchange Commission in
exchange for immunity from enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com Dismisses 13 Employees
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com, one of the highest-profile Web magazines, dismissed
13 employees in an effort to make up an anticipated $7 million
shortfall in its $35 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Credit Up 7.8 Percent in April
</P>
<P>
   Americans increased their borrowing at a less feverish pace in
April, ringing up the smallest rise in consumer credit in six
months, the Federal Reserve said. Total consumer credit rose a
seasonally adjusted $9.3 billion in April for an annual growth rate
of 7.8 percent. That was the smallest gain since October, when
borrowing rose by $5.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Complacency on the Trade Deficit
</P>
<P>
   Every time the trade deficit reaches another record, as it did
in March, economists generally say there is little, perhaps
nothing, to worry about. But the rising level of debt is not
sustainable indefinitely. Why are we so complacent?
</P>
</TEXT>
