<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-HERB-CANCER-1STLD     06-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HERB-CANCER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE HERB, LINKED TO KIDNEY FAILURE, MAY ALSO CAUSE CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for additional details and some reorganization; story grows
by about 150 words)  
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an example of the dangers of untested and unregulated herbal
products, doctors are reporting that a Chinese herb, already linked
to kidney failure, may cause cancer as well.
</P>
<P>
   The herb, Aristolochia fangchi, was given to patients at a
weight-loss clinic in Belgium from 1990 to 1992, according to a
report being published Thursday in The New England Journal of
Medicine. By 1993 more than 100 of the patients had kidney damage,
and so far more than 70 of them have suffered kidney failure,
requiring transplants or dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a some of these patients are also developing cancers of the
urinary tract. The report gave no indication how many patients
might have taken the herb at the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of kidney failure from the herb have also been reported in
France, Britain, Spain, Japan and Taiwan. Dr. Christine Lewis,
director of the office of nutritional products, labeling and
dietary supplements at the Food and Drug Administration, said there
had been no reports of Americans being harmed by Aristolochia.
Lewis also said the FDA did not know how much of the herb might be
on the market in this country.
</P>
<P>
   In a check of 14 stores in New York City on Wednesday,
Aristolochia was available at two. At one it was being sold under
the name of Aristolochia Sertentaria for $13.95 an ounce. Another
said that it had Aristolochia available under the name Senega and
that it was used to heal snake bites. A third store said it had
discontinued the herb because it was not selling well.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the FDA sent letters to doctors and to the supplement
industry, with a six-page list of herbal remedies known or
suspected of containing Aristolochia. The agency urged
manufacturers to test their products for the presence of the herb.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is also preparing to issue an ``import alert'' within a
few weeks that will, in effect, ban importation of the herb,
including every item on the six-page list, Dr. Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Cardellina, vice president for botanicals at the
Council for Responsible Nutrition, a trade group for the supplement
industry, said Aristolochia had been found in some Chinese
medicinal mixtures, but in few other products. Nonetheless,
Cardellina said, because Aristolochia is so dangerous, the
supplement industry supports the FDA's decision to list every item
that might possibly contain the herb.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs, amino acids, vitamins and other so-called dietary
supplements are now a $15 billion industry, which is largely
unregulated. Unlike drugs, supplements do not have to be proved
safe and effective before they are marketed, and no outside agency
even checks to make sure that the products actually contain the
ingredients on the label. Regulation is lacking because in 1994,
Congress passed the 1994 Dietary Supplement Health and Education
Act, which cut back the FDA's authority.
</P>
<P>
   Under that law, the FDA does not have have the authority to take
supplements off the market until they are proved dangerous, in
which case people may already have been harmed.
</P>
<P>
   The report published Thursday in The New England Journal of
Medicine tells of 39 patients who took the herb and had kidney
transplants or dialysis at Erasme Hospital in Brussels, by a team
led by Dr. Joelle L. Nortier. Eighteen of the 39 have also
developed cancers of the urinary system. Nineteen others have
abnormal cells in the urinary tract, possibly precancers.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial accompanying the article, Dr. David Kessler,
former head of the FDA and now dean of the Yale School of Medicine,
urged Congress to change the law to give the FDA more power over
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said he had bought a bottle of Aristolochia capsules,
sold as ``Virginia Snakeroot,'' from an American supplier via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At the Belgian weight-loss clinic, Aristolochia was given to
patients by mistake; doctors had prescribed another herb, but the
product that the patients were given was later found to contain
Aristolochia, possibly because of a manufacturing error. On
average, the patients took it for about a year. Those who took the
highest amounts were most likely to develop cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Aristolochia contains compounds called aristolochic acids, which
are known to damage the kidneys and to cause cancer in rats in the
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The herb has been used historically in Chinese medicine for a
variety of ailments, but about 25 years ago German researchers
found it to be highly toxic, according to Dr. Varro E. Tyler, an
expert on herbal medicine at Purdue University. Nonetheless, he
said, some manufacturers in China continue to use it.
</P>
<P>
   When a patient who had taken the herb in the Belgian weigh-loss
program developed cancer, doctors tested other patients in the
program. A high proportion, 18 of 39, had cancer in the kidney,
bladder or ureter, the tube connecting the kidney and bladder, the
report said. Nineteen other patients had abnormal cells, possibly
precancers, in the urinary tract.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, tissue from all 39 patients had molecules derived
from the herb attached themselves to the patient's genetic
material, known as DNA adducts. Adducts can interfere with DNA
function and is thought to increase the risk of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler said the high incidence of abnormal cells and adducts
even in the patients without tumors was worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA warning letter and a list of products that might contain
Aristolochia can be seen on the agency's Web site, www.fda.gov, by
clicking on ``what's new'' and then on ``dietary supplements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-ROCKER-TEAM-REACT0608     06-07 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-TEAM-REACT0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Closer's radio rant shrugged off by team
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves have learned to expect the unexpected as
far as their _ for now _ demoted closer John Rocker is concerned.
But on Wednesday afternoon, they had to chuckle when they heard he
had gone on 96 Rock and said he might quit baseball rather than
report to the minor leagues, and offered this alternative:
</P>
<P>
   ``Stockbroker?'' Chipper Jones asked, eyes widening as he read a
copy of Rocker's morning comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of things I can do besides deal with the
headaches of this garbage every single day,'' is what Rocker said
on the air. ``I'd be a stockbroker probably. There's something to
be said for having a job that's not just a complete headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox got word on Wednesday afternoon that Rocker had come
by the Braves clubhouse to collect his belongings and Cox fully
expected he would soon be on his way to Toledo to join the Class
AAA Richmond Braves on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker didn't report there on Wednesday night but few of the
Braves were actually convinced Rocker wouldn't show up in Toledo by
his deadline today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody who's ever been sent down to the minor leagues is ever
happy about it, especially one who established himself as one of
the top closers in the game,'' Jones said. ``It was a shock to him
and a shock to everybody else. He's probably venting a little bit.
You can't just quit, just stop playing the game and not want to
play anymore. I think he'll go down. He won't like it, but he'll do
it. Hopefully it'll be a wake-up call for him. I'd like to see him
get down to business and work on some things. It's still not beyond
the realm of comprehension that he can come back and be the closer
for the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker has to be in the minors for a minimum of 10 days from
when he was optioned (Monday) before he can be recalled to Atlanta.
The longer he takes to report the less likely he'd be back when
those 10 days are up. Some players are estimating privately he's
got a 50-50 shot of making it back to the majors with the Braves
period - mentally and physically. Others weren't so generous.
</P>
<P>
   The way Tom Glavine figures, Rocker is doing himself a
disservice by spending time on the radio instead of the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they say they want you to go down and work on some things
and get back as quickly as possible, normally that's a crock,''
Glavine said. ``He's in a rare position. In this case it's true.
And he's already wasted two days. It's another decision you say to
yourself `What are you thinking?' The smartest thing he could have
done was to get down there as soon as you can and see where you are
for 10 days. He's doing nothing but prolonging his absence from
this team. And that's nobody's fault but his own.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rocker refuses the assignment, the Braves can fine or suspend
him. They wouldn't likely grant him release to make him eligible to
other clubs. So it's either the Richmond club or nothing, for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a pretty raw deal of raw deals this time,'' Rocker had
said.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine is not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later he's got to look in the mirror and take
responsibility for his actions,'' Glavine said. ``Everything that's
happened has been a direct result of something he's said or done.
Nobody else said anything to the photographer in San Diego, nobody
else did that to (Jeff) Pearlman.''
</P>
<P>
   No Brave is willing to say the team is better off without
Rocker, although they're beginning to prepare themselves for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say he wouldn't be missed, somebody is lying to
themselves,'' Jones said. ``The fact of the matter is life goes on
whether John Rocker is here or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it get to the point all the shenanigans overrides that
and it causes you more problems that it helps you?'' Glavine said.
``Possibly. But I don't think it's going to happen with us. We have
too many guys who are professional and won't let one guy bring us
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
