u f BC-MICROSOFT-REACT-NYT &LR;      06-07 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTED REACTION TO BREAKUP RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST)  
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Vice President Al
Gore, the presumptive presidential nominees, declined to comment
Wednesday on the court order to break Microsoft into two companies,
but congressional Republicans condemned the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for Bush, who in February had
expressed concerns that a breakup would threaten economic growth,
said Wednesday night: ``Governor Bush has said all along that it
would not be appropriate for him to discuss the specifics of the
case while it is still before the courts, and Microsoft has
indicated that they intend to appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore, said that ``since it's an
ongoing legal matter, it would be inappropriate to comment.''
Hattaway declined to explain why silence was indicated in this case
when Gore freely commented last month on the case involving
political asylum for Elian Gonzalez, as has Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Their reluctance to comment reflected a sense among political
professionals that the decision was unlikely to have much impact on
the presidential election, except perhaps in Microsoft's home
state, Washington, where it could hurt Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, both supporters and foes of Microsoft have contributed
heavily to all sorts of candidates this year. As one Washington
lobbyist put it, ``It's obvious why no one is getting too far out
front _ there's too much money to be raised from both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   But that did not stop Republicans on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the assistant majority leader,
said the decision marked ``a sad day for the American consumer.''
Nickles said the Clinton administration apparently wanted a
``federal department of software regulation,'' but said Congress
should decide ``whether we need federal bureaucrats and federal
judges writing our computer software and deciding how we surf the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader, denounced
the decision even before it was issued. In a statement released at
3:56 p.m., 34 minutes before the ruling was made public, Armey
said: ``Judge Jackson's ruling will divert innovative companies
from creating better products. Worse, it will send the message to
innovators around the world that in America we punish success.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were more hesitant in their comments. Sen. Patrick
Leahy of Vermont, the senior Democrat on the Judiciary Committee,
said the implications of the ruling ``are anything but clear right
now.'' Leahy urged the government and Microsoft to ``invest new
urgency'' in trying to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said the penalty was too severe.
``Obviously,'' Schumer said, ``if Microsoft broke the law, they
should be punished, But not all legal roads lead to a breakup,''
which he said should be used only as a ``last resort.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from Washington state were vehement in their
complaints, regardless of party. Sen. Patty Murray, a Democrat,
called the decision disappointing, saying it would ``hobble
Microsoft at a critical time in the development of our
information-based economy'' and ``cripple a major technology
innovator.''
</P>
<P>
   That was mild compared with the comments of Sen. Slade Gorton, a
Republican running for re-election. Calling the result a sham,
Gorton said: ``Wednesday is truly a sad day in our nation's
history. Never before has our government so viciously pursued a
company that has done so much good for not only Americans, but for
people worldwide. Microsoft, the driving force behind the booming
U.S. economy, has revolutionized how we communicate, how we educate
our children and how we live.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of any immediate denunciation of Microsoft, even
from members of Congress who have been critical of its activities,
reflected not only a desire to study the decision by Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson and weigh the politics of attacking a generally
popular company, but perhaps also represented a bow to the
corporation's increasing role as a campaign contributor.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Center for Responsive Politics showed that while
Microsoft, and individuals and political action committees
connected to it, gave candidates and parties about $1.8 million
from 1993 to 1998, in just the first 17 months of the current
election cycle they gave $2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   And while almost three-fifths of the earlier giving went to
Republicans, the donations between Jan. 1, 1999, and June 1 of this
year were divided with almost surgically exactness. Democrats
received 50.2 percent, or $1,118,014; Republicans took in 49.8
percent, or $1,083,723.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates, has made strenuous efforts to
cater to Democrats as well as Republicans. During his visit to
Capitol Hill on Tuesday, he met at length with the all-Democratic
Congressional Black Caucus and the heavily Democratic Hispanic
Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Microsoft officials are known to hope that if Bush
is elected, his administration might be willing to settle the case
on terms more generous to the company than would the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's spokesman, McClellan, avoided that issue, saying, ``As
president, Governor Bush will fully enforce our antitrust laws to
foster competition and innovation and protect consumers,'' but he
declined to say whether that meant Bush would have supported
government action against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the case seems to have little national
political impact. Last month, an NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll
did find the public opposed to a breakup, by 52 percent to 35
percent. And many polls have found the company and Gates popular
with the public.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no indication either in those surveys or elsewhere
that the subject was one that could change votes. Charles Cook,
editor of a highly regarded political survey, The Cook Political
Report, said he had seen no impact anywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
