<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MEETING OF TRIBAL LEADERS, GORE TAPS A NEW FONT OF CASH 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ Vice President Al Gore, ever on the prowl
for money, has found a new source: American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning a three-day West Coast campaign swing, Gore raised
nearly $1 million at three events Wednesday, including $400,000
from a group of Indians at a luncheon at the Hilton Hotel in Palm
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Edward G. Rendell, general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, which organized the events, said that although many
Indians had attended fund-raisers for the party in the past, these
were the first events held exclusively with Indians.
Representatives of 16 tribes from the region _ there are more than
400 tribes across the country _ were in Palm Springs attending a
tribal council meeting, and about 40 of them ate lunch with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell, who noted the emerging economic power among Indians
through casinos and shopping malls, said that at least 80 percent
of those Indians who voted traditionally voted Democratic, and
there seemed to be considerable support for the vice president
among this group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has made a commitment to who we are as a people,''
Mary Ann Martin Andreas, chairwoman of the Morongo Band of Mission
Indians from Banning, said in introducing the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Gonzales Lyons of the Agua Caliente Band of Cahulla
Indians, and vice chairwoman of the council, said, ``Vice President
Al Gore has taken the time to meet and speak with us and candidate
Bush has not,'' referring to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, Gore's
Republican rival.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said Indians looked more favorably on Gore than
on Bush because Bush had suggested that states be allowed to
determine whether gambling could take place on Indian reservations.
Without directly endorsing gambling, Chris Lehane, Gore's
spokesman, said of the Indians, ``We support their right to do what
they want to do on their land.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief and solemn speech, Gore said he recognized that the
tribes' agenda _ including better health care and more economic
opportunities _ had received too little attention. ``I don't wear
rose-colored glasses,'' he said, ``but I think that it's important
to take stock of the fact that we have made success in the
direction of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited his support for tribal sovereignty, tribal hunting and
fishing rights and economic empowerment zones, but said more needed
to be done to attract investments and jobs to Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know _ I say that I know, but I don't know in the same way
that you know _ the burden of history on Indian people,'' Gore
said. He said he understood how ``travails as well as opportunities
can cascade down through the generations, parents to children to
grandchildren and on and on, to the seventh generation and then
beyond.'' Indians traditionally refer to the seventh generation as
a symbol of the future. But, he said, ``we have the ability to
interrupt the cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore was collecting money from this group, he lamented
doing so. ``I accept that there's a great irony in this process,''
he said, adding that he was determined to overhaul the campaign
finance system. ``We need sweeping reforms to end the money
chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then flew to a fund-raising reception at the Santa Monica
home of Brad Krevoy, chief executive officer of the Motion Picture
Corporation of America, where 100 people gave $1,000 each to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   He then had a date at the Conga Room in Los Angeles, where 65
people were paying $5,000 each to have dinner with him and where he
expected to raise $325,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
