<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDY-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES OF ETIQUETTE FOR THE BREAKUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct verb tenses in the 11th and last graf; adds
sentence to graf 26, which begins ``Microsoft cannot link ...'';
grafs 27 and 28 are new.)   (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The centerpiece of the government's cure for the
predatory, monopolistic, take-no-prisoners behavior that Microsoft
was found to have embraced is to chop the company in two.
</P>
<P>
   One new company would make the Windows operating system, the
other would make the applications that are run by the operating
system, as well as Microsoft's Internet and computer hardware
businesses. The government called the companies ``Ops Co.'' and
``Apps Co.'' in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   If Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's decree is sustained on
appeal, Microsoft would not be able to keep the vow made in court
by its lawyer, John L. Warden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not acquiesce in our own commercial demise,'' Warden
declared.
</P>
<P>
   If not acquiescing, Microsoft would at least have to cooperate
in radical surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Microsoft is granted a stay pending appeal, it must give
Jackson and the Justice Department's antitrust division a
reorganization plan by early October.
</P>
<P>
   So Microsoft, which consisted of three people and had sales of
$16,000 in its first year, 1975, and now has 36,000 employees and
annual sales of $20 billion, would cease to exist in its present
form.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's decree spelled out how the present Microsoft must
behave toward other companies and how the new companies that would
arise from it, must behave toward each other and toward other
companies, some of which have been bitter competitors or even
adversaries in court.
</P>
<P>
   Once Microsoft submits its proposed plan, the Justice Department
and the states that joined in the lawsuit would have 60 days to
file objections. Microsoft would then have 30 days to respond.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge reviews the new paperwork and issues a final
reorganization plan, and assuming the government wins on appeal,
reorganization would take place within a year.
</P>
<P>
   The two entities are to have separate employees, assets and
intellectual properties. There would be separate stock, so that
principals in ``Ops Co.'' could not own stock in ``Apps Co.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge described the fire wall against anything that
resembled cross-ownership or excessive coziness between the new
companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ No board member of one can acquire securities or assets of the
other. No one who is an officer, director or employee of one
business shall be an officer, director or employee of the other.
</P>
<P>
   _ The operating system business and the applications business
are barred from merging, recombining or entering into joint
ventures for 10 years. The new companies are barred, for the most
part, from entering into any agreement under which one develops,
sells, licenses or distributes products or services developed,
sold, licensed or distributed by the other.
</P>
<P>
   _ One company cannot provide the other with any technical
information that is not ``made readily available'' to other makers
of computer products. Nor can the two companies license, sell or
make available to each other ``any product or service'' on better
terms than are offered to outside companies.
</P>
<P>
   The new companies are allowed to license technologies (other
than middleware, like e-mail programs or browsers) to each other,
provided the technologies have not been separately sold, licensed
or offered as a product.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Microsoft is ordered to do its best to run both
the operating systems end of its business and the applications
branch at a profit, and to support research and development for
both.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft must do nothing ``that undermines, frustrates,
interferes with, or makes more difficult'' the reorganization.
Again, unless it is granted a stay, Microsoft must file a report no
later than 90 days from now on steps it is taking to comply with
this portion of the decree.
</P>
<P>
   Until the reorganization takes effect, the present Microsoft is
not to punish or threaten any computer maker for using,
distributing, promoting, licensing, producing or selling any
product or service that competes with Microsoft. (This and other
restrictions on conduct would remain in effect for three years if
the breakup takes place, 10 years if the breakup is rejected on
appeal.)
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft must license its Windows operating system products to
computer makers under uniform royalty terms, with exceptions
granted for different language versions and ``reasonable'' volume
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft may not stop a computer maker that uses the Windows
system from modifying its start-up sequence and desktop so that
Microsoft icons, start-menu entries and other features are removed
_ as long as users can get them back, if they want. Nor can
Microsoft restrict a computer maker from offering its own
Internet-access provider.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft cannot terminate a computer maker's license to use
Windows without providing a written notice and allowing the
computer maker at least 30 days to correct its supposed
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that Microsoft shares technical information with all
hardware, software and computer makers that are entitled to it,
Microsoft must create ``a secure facility'' where representatives
of those companies can study it.
</P>
<P>
   With limited exceptions, Microsoft cannot interfere with the
performance of any non-Microsoft middleware that operates with any
Windows operating system product.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is not to give or withhold any consideration, or take
or threaten any action, based on a hardware or software maker's use
of a Microsoft product or service, or its choice of non-Microsoft
products or services. And it must not enter into arrangements in
which third parties agree or are offered considerations to favor
certain Microsoft products to the exclusion of non-Microsoft
products.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft cannot link the licensing of a Windows operating
system to a customer's agreement to use other Microsoft products.
Strict limits are placed on Microsoft's binding middleware products
to operating-system products.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Microsoft is barred from penalizing computer makers
who install Windows but choose not to use Microsoft middleware.
</P>
<P>
   The new companies cannot retaliate against ``any person or
entity'' for providing evidence in the lawsuit against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   And when Microsoft releases a new version of Windows, it must
continue selling the previous version without raising the price and
must continue to offer service and support for it.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a stay, Microsoft has 90 days to set up a compliance
committee on its board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   That committee is to hire a chief compliance officer, who would
be given broad powers to see that Microsoft obeys the ruling. Among
other things, the compliance officer would obtain written
statements from senior corporate officers certifying that they have
read the court's ruling, that they understand it and that they will
abide by it.
</P>
<P>
   The compliance officer is to report immediately to the court and
government any violations of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail messages of high-ranking Microsoft executives engaged
in software development are to be saved for at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   The court reserves the right to act on its own to issue orders
ensuring compliance with the ruling, and to punish violations.
</P>
<P>
   The court's final judgment will expire in 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
