u w BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-560&AMP;AD     06-07 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAY FORGO HEARINGS ON EGYPTAIR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More certain than ever that a pilot deliberately
caused the crash of Egyptair 990 as it left New York on Oct. 31,
American investigators are wrapping up their investigation and may
approve their conclusions without a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   This unusual approach is meant to avoid further damage to
relations with Egypt, which have been strained by the inquiry,
government officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But the Egyptian government, which has resisted the theory that
the crash was caused by a suicidal pilot, has developed a competing
theory, that the plane, a Boeing 767, developed a mechanical
problem in its tail, a problem that has been seen on 767s operated
by AeroMexico and other airlines. None of those planes have
crashed. All 217 people aboard Egyptair 990 died when it plunged
into the Atlantic off Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian theory has been informally rejected by experts at
the National Transportation Safety Board, which investigates
crashes, but Egypt is pressing its case. On Tuesday, the Egyptian
Civil Aviation Authority asked the Federal Aviation Administration,
which is in charge of safety regulation, to begin an investigation
of the suspect part, and to order all airlines to conduct daily
inspections of the tail to screen for the kind of failure the
Egyptian agency says may have brought down Flight 990. The FAA has
not made a decision on the request.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian theory was developed with help from a phalanx of
U.S. aviation experts who are retired from the NTSB or the FAA. It
involves the controls on the two elevator panels, the movable
surfaces on the horizontal tail that point the plane's nose up or
down.
</P>
<P>
   Each panel is controlled by three actuators, for a total of six.
Salvagers have recovered four acuators from the ocean bottom. One
of those acuators bears marks that the Egyptians argue show that it
malfunctioned. In a presentation to the Safety Board in April, they
argued that if a second actuator on the same elevator had also
failed, the plane's nose would have suddenly been forced down. The
flight data recorder from Flight 990, recovered after the crash,
showed that the plane was proceeding in level flight until it
dived.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. investigators say the marks are not a sign of
malfunction and could have been caused by the plane's impact on the
water. They say that even if two actuators failed and forced the
elevator down, engineering studies performed at Boeing's simulator
in Seattle showed that the crew could have recovered from the
resulting nose dive.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investigators say they suspect suicide because the flight
data recorder, an advanced model, does not give evidence of
mechanical malfunction. Nor does the cockpit voice recorder. It
does record the first officer uttering what the Americans, but not
the Egyptians, regard as a final prayer. Then it records the
captain, who investigators think had left the cabin, returning and
forcefully asking his first officer what was going on. During the
dive, someone turned off the engines, an action not called for by
emergency procedures, the Americans say.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the flight data recorder shows that after a long dive,
the elevators pointed in opposite directions, a sign that the two
men were working their controls in opposite directions, U.S.
investigators say.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the Egyptians have argued that a pilot who intended to crash
his plane would not have put it into a dive, from which another
crew member might have rescued it. More likely, they have said,
such a pilot would try to roll the plane upside down. And they have
argued to the NTSB that although engineers in a simulator could
recover from the dive, a crew startled by a sudden malfunction
while flying over the ocean at night might not be so skilled.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member NTSB tries jealously to maintain a monopoly on
public statements about investigations in progress, and, as a
result, people involved in the investigation were not willing to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   But some U.S. investigators are frustrated that the inquiry,
which the Egyptian government delegated to the United States, has
not been completed. As one said, in investigations of domestic
crashes, each party has a ``constituency,'' because each represents
the airline, or the plane manufacturer, but, he said, ``usually you
want to solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, said the investigator, the Egyptians ``don't care
about solving it; they want to cover themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptians, on the other side, have complained about what
they call a ``rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines often hire retired government investigators to help
with safety problems, but Egyptair has assembled a particularly
distinguished crew: Carl W. Vogt, a former chairman of the Safety
Board; a retired deputy chief of aviation safety; a retired top
metallurgist from the NTSB; and a former FAA chief accident
investigator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
