<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7623 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e       06-07 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACLEAN-JESUSSON-FILM-$ADV11-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLING TO TAKE A WALK IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Ariz., New Zealand, Australia)   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
 (Editors: Subs to correct slug.)  
 By HOWARD FEINSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The films that I want to do are perceived as a
little bit risky and dark,'' the director Alison Maclean says. Now
that is an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Maclean languished in director hell after her debut feature, the
defiantly noirish psychological thriller ``Crush,'' which she shot
in New Zealand in 1992, piqued the interest of a number of American
critics and producers. ``I moved to New York right after `Crush'
and have spent most of the last eight years writing three feature
scripts,'' she says. ``Two seemed like they were almost fully
financed, then fell apart. It's definitely been a frustrating time.
Then this came at me from left field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This'' is ``Jesus' Son,'' an adaptation of Denis Johnson's
collection of interwoven short stories about alienation, ennui and
drugs in the American heartland in the 70s, which Maclean shot
early last year in New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Arizona. It has
proved to be a godsend, pardon the expression. Not only did it
offer her the chance to get back behind the camera for a feature
film, it successfully transcended its $2.5 million budget. It has
received excellent reviews at the Venice and Toronto Film Festivals
and at the recent New Directors/New Films series at the Museum of
Modern Art. (Lions Gate will open the film on Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   Maclean, a tall, lean, slightly androgynous woman who looks a
lot younger than her 41 years, is sitting in the living room of her
unpretentious West Village apartment, which is ultraminimalist save
for a bit of furniture and several sculptures she made as an art
student in New Zealand. She says she was approached by the
co-producers and screenwriters of ``Jesus' Son,'' Elizabeth
Cuthrell and David Urrutia, who had just optioned the book. They
had seen ``Crush'' and Maclean's 1989 short, ``Kitchen Sink,'' and
considered her a perfect match for the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted someone who could create a strong sense of tension
that could link Denis' fragmented stories,'' Cuthrell says. ``We
called Alison. She called back in 10 minutes and said: `You don't
understand. This is a book I dearly love.' We met the next day, and
that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   The finished film is fragmented, though accessibly so. Its
structure mimics the mind-set of its protagonist (Billy Crudup), a
heroin user/drinker/petty thief/voyeur/layabout with an unprintable
nickname _ its initials are F.H. _ while he makes his way across
the United States trying to find himself. Essentially an innocent,
F.H. is also a spiritual seeker. (The film's title comes from Lou
Reed's lyrics to the Velvet Underground song ``Heroin.'') He
encounters a motley assortment of wacky, amoral guys, like Georgie
(Jack Black), a hilariously incompetent emergency room orderly with
whom F.H. works as they pop uppers and downers simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   F.H. falls in love with Michelle (Samantha Morton), a tragic
young woman who also shoots up regularly and is the character
closest to those in Maclean's own scripts. F.H. hallucinates all
sorts of things, often objects with religious associations. His
fantasies are not surreal or heavily exaggerated in the style of
Terry Gilliam's ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas'' or the
psychedelic films of the '60s. They are more akin to what Maclean
calls ``a slightly heightened reality, part of the fabric of daily
life.'' On a snowy night, F.H. walks through a drive-in movie
theater dotted with car-speaker stands and experiences it as a
cemetery with gravestone crosses. In the film's central scene, he
imagines a sacred heart emerging from the chest of a thin, scruffy
man whom he's followed from the Chicago El into a laundromat.
</P>
<P>
   Maclean says that the religious iconography of the book and the
script was one of the project's main attractions. She is interested
in Buddhism. Her mother, Mary Forrest, a potter, lives the
spiritual life in a New Age sort of way, to the point where,
according to one of Maclean's old friends, she dangles crystals
over her food before eating. (Maclean's parents divorced when she
was a teen-ager.) Her maternal grandfather, on the other hand, was
a Christadelphian, a strict fundamentalist who taught his family to
deny themselves pleasure (including movies) and placed
Christ-affirming banners on his front lawn. Those probably would
have caught F.H.'s eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing I liked about the project is that there is a lot
of comedy in it, and a lot of optimism as well,'' says Maclean,
who, for someone with such a somber oeuvre and reserved demeanor,
has a deep, endearing laugh. The humor in ``Jesus' Son'' is very
black, but the film is far less disturbing than her earlier work
(in addition to ``Crush'' and ``Kitchen Sink,'' she wrote and
directed four shorts in New Zealand), and those screenplays over
which she has been tenaciously laboring in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She is willing to go for lighter fare _ she directed the first
two episodes of ``Sex and the City'' for HBO _ but her own
sensibilities lead her on precarious journeys into the unconscious.
``I do choose the difficult path,'' she concurs. ``I'm not sure
why.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some clues are provided by Bridget Ikin, a New Zealander who
lives in Sydney, Australia, and a close friend; she produced
``Crush'' and three of Maclean's shorts. ``For me, the journey that
Alison's taken to New York, living as a single woman, hacking it
out for eight years now, has been beyond,'' Ikin says. ``We could
have happily continued to make films together, but Alison always
goes for the hard option. I don't think it's any coincidence that
one of the projects that took her to the States was a film from her
own script of `Moby-Dick.''' (Maclean's version, which she herself
says she ``hijacked,'' has a female Ishmael.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Alison is a troubled person, embattled with demons that she's
dealing with,'' Ikin adds. Like several other longtime associates
of Maclean, Ikin feels that she suffers for her art. ``What
interested me about the work I produced for her was her use of
personal material,'' she says. ``The scripting for `Crush' was a
completely torturous process.
</P>
<P>
   ```Crush' was about an anxious moment in her relationship with
New Zealand, about her sense of alienation from that culture, about
female sexuality and desire, about shifting sexuality and about
shifting power relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Maclean says: ``There's something ominous in me somewhere. I
love the warts-and-all people.'' The two main characters in
``Crush,'' both women, are a New Zealand journalist, Christina
(Donogh Rees), and an American opportunist, Lane (Marcia Gay
Harden), who just might be lovers. Lane is responsible for
Christina's becoming paralyzed in a car accident; she then abandons
Christina and assumes her identity to gain access to _ and
ultimately have a love affair with _ a noted author, Colin (William
Zappa), who lives with his teen-age daughter, Angela (Caitlin
Bossley). Angela becomes lovingly obsessed with Lane, then does a
flip and begins to intensely hate her. At film's end, the severely
damaged Christina musters the energy to climb out of her wheelchair
and, just when you think she's going to hug and forgive Lane, she
shoves her off a cliff, an incident witnessed by the horrified
Angela.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ikin: ``Alison is the young girl, Angela, desiring
the powerful American woman. America is this metaphor of power and
desire, the longing to be in the other, more exotic, unreachable
place. In fact, Alison's never felt at home in any country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus' Son'' reflects its director's outsider status. ``I
think the film has a European sensibility,'' says Maclean, who
lived in Canada, New Zealand and Australia before moving to New
York. ``It's in the framing, in the way there is a certain distance
or detachment, a certain remove, which is really my temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   On the commercial front, her feelings of estrangement have
resulted in collisions with some powerful people. She came to the
United States at the behest of Disney's Touchstone Pictures, with
the idea of developing projects. The one that most appealed to her
was ``Up Close and Personal'' (eventually directed by Jon Avnet,
starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Robert Redford). ``I read Alanna
Nash's `Golden Girl,''' Maclean says. ``It was about the TV
anchorwoman Jessica Savitch, who had a bad cocaine habit and died
young in this freak car accident with her boyfriend. It was dark
and tragic. I was interested in the real story. But Joan Didion and
John Gregory Dunne, who at that point had written a few drafts of
the screenplay, were interested in `The Star Is Born' element for
the film. They turned Savitch into an ingenue.'' (Dunne's 1997 book
``Monster'' lays at least some of the blame on Touchstone
executives.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Touchstone and I agreed that we disagreed,'' she continues.
``It was a perfectly amicable parting of the ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so with ``Bedlam.'' Maclean was hired by the producer Ruth
Charney to rewrite a John Sayles script based on an atmospheric
1946 thriller produced by the legendary Val Lewton, and then direct
the film. ``Bedlam'' was to be a vehicle for the actress Illeana
Douglas, then the girlfriend of Martin Scorsese, who was the
executive producer. Set in the 18th century, it is the tale of a
Quaker who tries to expose the conditions inside an insane asylum
and who himself becomes an inmate. Douglas was to play his love
interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alison was attracted to all aspects of it,'' Charney says.
``It had a lot of morality lessons.'' After much tinkering, Maclean
finally gave up trying to tailor the screenplay to suit Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alison didn't see Illeana in the role, and that is where it
all broke down,'' Charney says. ``Alison is a very moral person, so
she told Marty herself. She was willing to risk her career to do
that. She's incredibly pure that way.'' According to several people
who were involved, Scorsese hit the roof. (Both he and Maclean have
declined to elaborate.)
</P>
<P>
   Now that the reception for ``Jesus' Son'' has changed her luck,
Maclean has been able to begin her next project, ``Iris,'' the
third of the scripts gathering dust at home. To be financed by New
York's Good Machine and Britain's FilmFour, and produced by Good
Machine's Ted Hope, the film could go into production as early as
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iris'' is a contemporary, supernatural, psychological tale
``about a woman who starts remembering things from her childhood
that didn't happen,'' Maclean says. ``One of the things it deals
with is sexual abuse of a child as a metaphor. The deep dark secret
of the family turns out to be that there is not a dark secret.''
But the film is dark nonetheless, and that sounds like Alison
Maclean at her most deliciously unadulterated.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
