<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORE PLANS `PROSPERITY TOUR'
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore will embark on a ``prosperity tour'' next
week. In contrast to President Clinton's ``poverty tour'' last year
highlighting failing communities that had been left behind
economically, the vice president plans to highlight the economic
successes of the last eight years _ and by extension hopes to
become associated with those successes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers say the flights to several cities across the
country are part of a larger strategy to emphasize the positive and
optimistic aspects of Gore's candidacy and will coincide with the
start this week of a $10 million advertising campaign that is also
intended to redefine the vice president's image. In that same
political vein, as part of the ``family agenda'' he has been
promoting over the last two weeks, Gore called Wednesday for a $30
billion package of tax credits and other assistance to help
children care for their elderly parents in the coming decade. ``I'm
proposing an initiative that's partly based on the experience that
Tipper and I have had,'' he told a group of nursing home residents
and their families in Palm Springs, Calif. ``Tipper's mother lives
with us, and we help provide her health care.''
</P>
<P>
   But since at least 2 million families are not fortunate enough
to have the resources to handle such expenses comfortably, he said
that what was needed was a $3,000-a-year tax credit to help others.
</P>
<P>
   CHALLENGE IN MASSACHUSETTS
</P>
<P>
   Jack E. Robinson, the Republican challenger for Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy's seat, says reports of the demise of his campaign have
been greatly exaggerated. It looked unlikely for a while that
Robinson would succeed in gathering the 10,000 signatures of voters
he needed by Tuesday to qualify for the race. But the Massachusetts
secretary of state's office credited him with 10,139 signatures
before the deadline passed, so Robinson, an entrepreneur, is still
in the running. But he still faces another major obstacle _
overcoming the embarrassing disclosures about his personal life,
from bad relations with women to traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
   A TEXAS TIFF
</P>
<P>
   The way that Molly Beth Malcolm, leader of the Texas Democratic
Party, sees it, Gov. George W. Bush is the kind of person who women
want at their parties but do not want to marry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of when I was in college,'' she told The Dallas
Morning News the other day. `There were lots of guys who were lots
of fun to go out with, and you wanted them at your party. But when
it came time to settle down, he wasn't the one you're looking
for.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Texas Republican Party, Susan Weddington,
found that a ``real offensive'' observation and countered in Bush's
defense: ``We're choosing the leader of the free world, not a prom
date.''
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Knoxville, Tenn., and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Palm Springs, Long Beach and Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
