u i BC-MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT-NYT     06-07 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ALBRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TELLS SYRIANS AN ACCORD FOR PALESTINIANS IS FIRST GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told Syrian and
Egyptian officials Wednesday that the Clinton administration was
willing to push once more for peace talks between Damascus and
Israel, but that its main goal in its remaining months in office
was a settlement between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no higher foreign policy priority for the Clinton
administration than an Israeli-Palestinian peace,'' Albright said
between meetings with President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and Foreign
Minister Farouk Shara of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Capping a hastily scheduled three-day swing through the Middle
East, Albright appeared to be trying to clear the rubble off both
tracks of the peace effort. Arriving Wednesday morning from Israel,
where she secured an agreement to resume talks with the
Palestinians next week in Washington, Albright reiterated President
Clinton's hopes for conclusive negotiations there this summer with
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and the president of the
Palestinian Authority, Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the troubles of Barak's coalition might disrupt
the plans, Albright said Washington was sticking to ``its own
timetable'' for a peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rare opportunity to reach an accord, and we cannot
let it slip away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong meeting with Shara, she stressed that ``the door
is still open'' to a renewal of American-sponsored talks between
Syria and Israel, a senior American official said. This was the
first high-level Syrian-American encounter since Clinton's meeting
with President Hafez al-Assad in Geneva in March, when the Syrians
effectively ended the talks by insisting that Israel would have to
surrender not just the entire Golan Heights, but also the
northeastern shore of the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beyond Geneva,'' a senior American official said after
the meeting. ``We are looking forward. We are not looking
backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright made it clear that the administration was aiming for a
comprehensive pact between Israel and the Palestinians, not Syria.
She said she believed that Israel and the Palestinian Authority
could negotiate compromises on core issues like refugees and the
status of Jerusalem before Sept. 13, the date that Arafat has
pledged to move toward the establishment of an independent state
with or without an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes deadlines focus the mind,'' Albright said. ``I would
just like to announce, for those who care, we are not having a
summer vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington is also keeping a wary eye on the still volatile
situation in southern Lebanon. Albright said she expected the
United Nations to certify soon that Israel has fully withdrawn,
following the terms of U.N. resolutions adopted after Israel
occupied the zone 22 years ago. But Lebanon and Israel continue to
wrangle over fragments of territory along the hilly border line,
which has never been definitively negotiated or even surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Israel pulled back Wednesday from two small outposts north of a
provisional boundary newly demarcated by U.N. cartographers. But
the U.N. mission that is supervising the pullout contends that
Israel continues to violate withdrawal requirements in another
pocket, of pastures, near a border kibbutz. The disagreement,
though minor, may further delay official certification of the
withdrawal, which is required before U.N. forces can be deployed in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's discussions with Shara dealt as much with the Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon as with prospects for new bilateral talks,
U.S. officials said. American and Israeli officials have voiced
concern that violence in southern Lebanon could disrupt talks with
the Palestinians, because of its political effects in Israel and
the fear that it could spark outbreaks by dissidents in the West
Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has more than 30,000 troops in Lebanon and maintains
effective political and economic control over the country. Albright
urged Beirut and Damascus to do more to pacify the frontier zone
that Hezbollah guerrillas now largely govern.
</P>
<P>
   In her talks with Shara, Albright did not reiterate the demand
for a Syrian withdrawal, concentrating on Syrian acceptance of the
U.N. verification of Israel's withdrawal, U.S. officials said.
Damascus and Washington are now ``pretty much in agreement'' about
the certification terms, an American official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
