<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7633 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-HAMILTON0608-COX     06-07 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAMILTON0608-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UM's Hamilton considering Washington Wizards offer
 &HT;    By Jorge Milian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORAL GABLES, Fla. _ An emotionally-torn Leonard Hamilton
expects to decide soon whether he will accept Michael Jordan's
offer to coach the NBA's Washington Wizards or remain at the
University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who signed a seven-year extension to stay at UM in
April, has reached an agreement in principle with the Wizards on a
four-year contract that would pay him an average of $2 million per
season, according to the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton makes approximately $750,000 under his new UM contract.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left is for Hamilton to decide whether he wants to
accept the Wizards' job, then negotiate a buyout clause in his UM
contract that is believed to be worth at least $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an easy decision,'' said Hamilton on Wednesday.
``I just need time to sort this out and come to a conclusion that I
feel comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love what I do. I love working with the kids here at the
University of Miami...(but) like most of us, I'm ambitious. So when
opportunities are made available, I think it's only the right thing
to do to give them strong consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked when he would decide, Hamilton said, ``As soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   UM Athletic Director Paul Dee said he hoped to convince Hamilton
to stay, but added the university had no plans to sweeten the
coach's contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Leonard Hamilton to stay at the University of Miami,''
Dee said. ``We've been through good times and thin times...I'm also
a realist. I understand this opportunity is magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, Washington's president of basketball operations, and
Hamilton began talking about the Wizards' vacant coaching job in
May. The two men have known each other for ``a long time'',
according to Hamilton. Talks began to heat up after St. John's
coach Mike Jarvis turned down the Wizards' job just over two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 51, has never coached in the NBA. That doesn't seem to
bother Jordan who told the Associated Press on Wednesday that
Hamilton ``is certainly our leading candidate right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could make the transition from college to the NBA,
Hamilton said, ``If you're asking me if I think I'm capable of
coaching (in the NBA), I think time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton held a team meeting at his home with some of his
players on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   UM senior center Dwayne Wimberly, who was ``in shock'' when he
first heard the news concerning Hamilton, said the coach was very
emotional during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us he wanted our support,'' Wimberly said. ``He cares
about us. You can tell it's a hard decision for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has coached at UM for 10 seasons. Last season, he led
the Hurricanes to their first Big East Conference regular season
championship and the school's first Sweet Sixteen berth. It was
UM's third consecutive NCAA Tournament appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Those accomplishments and the pursuit of several universities
looking for a coach earned Hamilton a contract extension and an
annual raise of approximately $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 144-147 at Miami, said Wednesday he was concerned that
he might be viewed as disloyal to UM if he accepts the Wizards'
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just uncomfortable because I don't want to be perceived as
a person that doesn't live up to his obligations,'' Hamilton said.
``I hope people don't automatically feel like I've lost my
integrity. I hope people understand that this is an opportunity
that I need to give strong consideration to.''
</P>
<P>
   A stumbling block to Hamilton accepting the job could be his
buyout. Sources have placed the fee anywhere from $1 million to $2
million. Dee declined to give specifics accept to say that on-going
discussions would ``lead to some resolution one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very difficult for us to lose (Hamilton), to
replace somebody like that,'' Dee said.
</P>
<P>
   If Hamilton leaves, UM's new coach might have to worry about
keeping a recruiting class that has been consensusly ranked among
the nation's top 10. Those players, which include McDonald's
All-America forward Darius Rice, have already signed letters of
intent and are obligated to UM for one season. Rice's father said
Wednesday night that the family would have no comment until ``Coach
Hamilton makes his final decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Dee said UM would be unlikely to give players their release if
Hamilton left. Dee cited a situation in 1989 when Jimmy Johnson
left as UM's football coach and was replaced by Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Krein, an incoming freshman, requested but lost an appeal
to be released from his scholarship. Krein went on to become an
All-Big East defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
