<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-REMEDIES-ANALYSIS-SFC     06-07 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMEDIES-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: CONSUMERS SHOULDN'T EXPECT IMMEDIATE CHANGES  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Whatever real changes in the technology
landscape Wednesday's decision in the Microsoft antitrust case
ultimately produces, consumers won't see them any time soon. And
when they do come, they're likely to take a gradual and subtle
form, rather than revolutionary upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's not-so-final judgment itself
notes that the most dramatic provision _ the splitting of Microsoft
into two companies, one selling Windows operating systems, the
other offering Office, Internet Explorer and all the other current
company's products _ won't go into effect until appeals are
complete.
</P>
<P>
   And to no one's surprise, Microsoft lawyers confirmed within
minutes after the ruling's release that they will file an appeal in
the next few days. Experts expect the appeal process to take a year
or more.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, there will still be only one Microsoft.
Windows will still come preinstalled on virtually every new
consumer PC, although starting sometime this summer, it will be a
new version called Windows Millennium Edition, which will look and
feel pretty much like the familiar Windows 95 and 98. In the
business market, the company will continue to promote Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Explorer Web browser will still be built into both
versions of the system. And Microsoft will still be issuing press
releases about its plans to integrate Windows and the Internet more
tightly in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the prices for new PCs, operating-system upgrades or
applications and games likely to change appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Some Action Could Happen Soon
</P>
<P>
   The ruling does, however, impose a long list of restrictions on
Microsoft's business practices that are scheduled to go into effect
in 90 days _ the week after Labor Day. Microsoft will undoubtedly
seek to get these provisions, like the breakup plan, suspended
pending the outcome of the appeal, but there's no guarantee higher
courts will grant the company's request.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Unlike the breakup plan, these restrictions, or ``conduct
remedies,'' address evidence of Microsoft misdeeds presented during
the 78-day trial. Microsoft will be hard put to prove that the
remedies would do it harm, so there is a good chance they will go
into effect this fall, as the case winds its way through the
appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   If imposed, the conduct remedies could give users _ at least
those buying new PCs _ noticeably more choice about how their
systems look and work. The judge's order, for example, gives PC
manufacturers more freedom to customize the desktop by adding their
own first screen, browser favorites and setup ``wizards.'' They'll
also have the option of removing icons Microsoft has traditionally
locked onto the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The order even allows PC makers to provide alternatives to the
conventional Windows user interface, as long as they also include a
button that would take the user back to the standard Windows
desktop. Some PC makers could take advantage of this clause to
appeal to the 50 percent or so of U.S. households that don't yet
have a PC by offering products with simpler interfaces, perhaps
tailored to specific market segments like young children, teens or
seniors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
New Options for PC Makers
</P>
<P>
   And because the order bars Microsoft from forcing PC makers to
include its other software products or to limit bundling of
third-party software, more PCs could come with competitors'
products: Netscape Navigator in addition to Internet Explorer, for
example; Corel's WordPerfect Office or Sun's StarOffice instead of
Microsoft Office; Real Networks' RealPlayer or Apple's QuickTime in
addition to Microsoft's Windows Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft adds new features to Windows, such as multimedia
viewers, PC makers could choose not to include them. As a result,
Microsoft would have to reduce its price for the operating system
proportionately, and the savings could be passed on to customers in
the form of lower prices for PCs without all the bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   If the breakup plan ultimately takes effect and Microsoft is
split, the likely results are harder to predict. The Justice
Department contends that its plan will restore competition to the
software marketplace, but it would do so only in indirect ways.
Instead of a single monopoly there would be two, at least at the
beginning of the post-split period. One would market the dominant
operating system and the other the dominant office productivity
suite and Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   The case that this will produce new competition rests on several
unproved assumptions about the behavior of the new companies. Part
of the argument is that the proposed applications and browser
company will have strong incentives to offer its products in other
operating systems, such as Linux, and thereby make these
alternatives more credible competitors to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department argument, now accepted by the judge, also
assumes that both new companies will be motivated to develop
additional ``cross-platform products'' _ software and Internet
services that will be available on any computing platform, not just
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   It even foresees the possibility that each could begin competing
with the other. The applications company, in theory, could
eventually produce its own operating system to compete with
Windows, while the operating-systems company could develop its own
alternative to Office.
</P>
<P>
   sh1 More Competition Possible
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, even though both new companies would be
powerhouses in their own right, neither could match the wealth,
clout and talent Microsoft has amassed, and Bill Gates could direct
only one of them. That presumably reduces the chances that either
could acquire the grip Microsoft has today on such emerging markets
as Web services, hand-held computers, Web-capable cell phones and
``set-top boxes'' that integrate digital services with television _
markets that are expected to set the technology pace in the coming
decade.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
