<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP-SFC     06-07 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 JUDGE ORDERS MICROSOFT SPLIT IN TWO  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The federal judge who found that Microsoft
crushed rivals and stifled innovation Wednesday ordered the
software titan to be sliced into two, ending a major chapter in the
acrimonious two-year antitrust battle and setting the stage for a
lengthy appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ruling hewed
closely to the remedy proffered by the Justice Department and
attorneys general from 17 states, including California.
</P>
<P>
   If it survives the appeals process, the plan is expected to have
wide-ranging effects on the high-tech industry and on consumers,
though opinions differ on whether competition will flourish and
consumers will pay less for software _ goals that have motivated
the government's crusade against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the judge said that Microsoft can't be trusted to compete
fairly, therefore necessitating the first breakup of a U.S. company
since AT&AMP;T was carved up into ``Baby Bells'' 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A structural remedy has become imperative,'' the judge wrote.
``Microsoft as it is presently organized and led is unwilling to
accept the notion that it broke the law or accede to an order
amending its conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's plan entails breaking the company into two distinct
firms:
</P>
<P>
   -- One would develop and sell the Windows operating systems for
corporations and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   -- The other would control the company's applications _
including the popular Office suite of word processing and
spreadsheet programs _ and Internet operations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft must submit a plan to split itself up in four months.
The two companies could not unite for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Jackon's order, widely expected last week but delayed by one
last round of briefs from both sides, also includes a range of
curbs on Microsoft's legendarily aggressive business tactics. They
include prohibiting the company from discriminatory pricing for
hardware makers and making public portions of the closely guarded
Windows source code.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the so-called conduct remedies could go into
effect within 90 days. However the company said it is seeking an
injunction preventing the measure from going into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said the ruling will have a profound
impact ``not only by promoting competition in the software industry
but by reaffirming the importance of antitrust laws in the software
era.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which has called the plan ``draconian'' and
``unjustified,'' vowed again to appeal both the legal findings and
the remedies and believes it will succeed in overturning those
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling ... is unreasonable in its call to break up
Microsoft and regulate software design; and it contradicts the
reality that consumers see every day,'' said the company's
chairman, Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly the most massive attempt at government
regulation of the technology industry ever, and it was conceived by
the government and imposed by this ruling without a single day of
testimony or scrutiny,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   From Jackson's courtroom, the case is likely to move to the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington, D.C., although government
attorneys are seeking an expedited review by the U.S. Supreme
Court. The appeals court had sided with Microsoft in a similar
case.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's remedy is aimed at spurring additional product
offerings from smaller companies now squeezed out of the
marketplace and precluding the software behemoth from future
antitrust violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is credible evidence in the record to suggest that
Microsoft, convinced of its innocence, continues to do business as
it has in the past, and may yet do to other markets what it already
has done in the PC operating system and browser markets,'' the
judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption is that Microsoft competitors, armed with the
Windows code, will develop word-processing programs, Web browsers
and other products that will compete with Microsoft's popular
stable of applications. The ``apps'' company will develop programs
for alternative operating systems, such as Linux, thereby lessening
Windows' dominance. Eventually, the two entities may compete with
each other.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is little consensus on the long-term
ramifications of the ruling for the software industry, hardware
makers and consumers, in part because the high-tech landscape is a
fluid, ever-changing place.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, handheld devices like cell phones and digital
personal organizers _ an arena where Microsoft has proven weak _
are expected to shift computing beyond Microsoft's traditional
bastion, the PC. Some say that evolution makes the decision moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has been operating under a competitive paradigm
that has become almost obsolete,'' said Hillard Sterling, a Chicago
antitrust attorney. ``Every day brings new products and mrkets
that provide increasing access to consumers and that have nothing
to do with Microsoft's browser and the operating systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's opponents _ which the company has accused of
pressuring Washington to pursue the case _ hailed the decision as a
first step toward creating real alternatives in the software
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Microsoft can stifle Apple and Netscape, they can do it to
thousands of people who can't get their ideas off the ground,''
said Mike Pettit, executive director of an anti-Microsoft trade
group. ``Splitting up the company will unleash a robust new round
of innovation ... and I think that will be the greatest benefit
when we look back at the judge's ruling 20 years hence.''
</P>
<P>
   Some immediate winners may be the big dogs like networking giant
Cisco and the Finnish cell phone maker Nokia.
</P>
<P>
   While the antitrust shadow lingers over Microsoft, ``companies
are going to be shifting from buying PCs and operating systems to
building out their networks and wireless systems,'' said Rob
Enderle, analyst at Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   However, Enderle is concerned that dismantling the world's
largest software company will create chaos in the consumer market,
which has come to rely on the ubiquity of Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're an MSN user, you touch Microsoft a lot,'' he said.
``This next phase is going to make it very difficult for consumers
to depend on the people within Microsoft who might answer their
service questions, because many of them will be departing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though much remains murky, a few things are certain. The legal
salvos will continue, and a breakup probably won't occur for at
least a year or more, if it happens at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has a real shot at reversing Jackson outright,''
Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sterling, the government never proved that
Microsoft locked competitors out of the marketplace; and he
believes the breakup order goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he questioned the speed at which Jackson concluded
the last phase of the trial. In one of its last filings, Microsoft
requested an additional six months to hold essentially a mini-trial
on the remedies. Jackson denied the motion.
</P>
<P>
   And yesterday's ruling came just about 24 hours after Microsoft
filed its last response to the government's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackson's lightning-quick decision raises inferences for these
appellate judge that something is wrong here,'' Sterling said.
``These appellate judges must be wondering why judge Jackson didn't
take more time to craft a remedy carefully and deliberately.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the details of its fate are more clear, many wonder
whether Microsoft's zenith has come and gone _ along with its stock
price. Since late December, the company's shares have fallen 42
percent, erasing tens of billions in market value.
</P>
<P>
   Investors fear a dismembered company will not be worth the sum
of its parts. Others wonder how the company will function in the
interim.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, Microsoft is scheduled to hold a splashy confab
for media and analysts on its ``Next Generation Windows Services''
project. The multibillion-dollar initiative is aimed at making
Microsoft's mainly PC-dependent software available on a host of
devices, from cell phones to personal digital assistants. Gates has
said the effort is ``doomed'' if the company is carved up.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe the company will be in dire straits well before
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to start losing people. Companies aren't going
to trust them, because Microsoft's future is going to be so
uncertain and Next Generation Windows Services will essentially be
stillborn,'' Enderle said. ``They're going to be severely crippled
until the appeals process is over.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
