<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7764 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-REACT-BAYAREA-SFCHRON     06-07 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REACT-BAYAREA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 microsoft's bay area staff reacts to judge's decisaHEADLINE HERE  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF and CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Employees on Microsoft's Mountain View, Calif.,
campus rarely watch television together except to talk about how to
make it more Internet compatible.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, about a dozen of them in Building No. 5 made an
exception for a few minutes to confirm what they already assumed:
their company would be divided in two.
</P>
<P>
   They watched silently, some leaning against the wall, some
standing on scooters, some petting a colleague's dog, as
Microsoft's fate was reported on CNBC, the cable news channel.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing enough, they eagerly explained that the decision
will not be a distraction and, in fact, many had meetings to go to
in a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of work to do,'' said Alex Crovetto, a software
testing manager, while standing on a skateboard and finishing off a
protein milk shake. ``None of this impacts what we're doing. I'm
just glad to see a decision finally made.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, employees unanimously agreed that the decision to
break up Microsoft is wrong. A few snickered when a television
journalist reported that Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who oversaw
the trial, wrote in his opinion that the company was
``untrustworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you determine that an entire company is
untrustworthy?'' asked Mo Harkness, a test engineer, who said that
the breakup left her feeling ``pretty bummed.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkness is one of many employees who said she did not know
where she would fit in a Microsoft divided into separate operating
systems and software companies. The problem, she and others said,
is that employees often work in both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like breaking up McDonalds into separate hamburger and
french fry companies,'' said Dick Craddock, a group manager. ``How
can you make a Happy Meal?''
</P>
<P>
   Craddock added that Wednesday's ruling should not affect
employee retention, even though the company's lawyers claimed
during the trial that a break_up might lead employees to leave.
Despite the uncertainty caused by the trial, he said, only one
worker has left his group in the past two years and that was for
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 people work at Microsoft's Mountain View campus on
projects like Internet Explorer for Apple computers, Powerpoint
software and Web TV, which enable people to use the Internet in
conjunction with television. The company's headquarters is in
Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that the ruling did not seem to destroy was the
employees' appetite for amusement. Not long after getting the news,
about a dozen workers were standing around a ping pong table to
watch a match.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the microsoftSF store in San Francisco was an art
exhibit that provided a series of mini-metaphors of Microsoft's
plight. To raise money for charity, artists and local celebrities
had crafted dioramas around the Microsoft computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   One called ``Tidy Bowl Dreams'' had a disemboweled Microsoft
mouse immersed in a jar of clear liquid, while the ``X-Actosaurus''
was a mouse decked out like a porcupine, bristling with dozens of
razor-sharp X-Acto blades _ similar to the way Microsoft's rivals
view it.
</P>
<P>
   Another display said it all. Called ``End of Game/Richest Player
Wins,'' it was a hamster cage filled with shredded Monopoly money,
with a Microsoft mouse perched strategically on the exercise wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers at microsoftSF, the only store in the world dedicated
to the software giant, were tepid about the prospect of splitting
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Casebolt, who works at business-systems maker EDS in Denver
and whose brother is a project manager at Microsoft, said he thinks
Gates may be ruthless, but ``the nature of business is
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ilona Nagy, a buyer at Macy's in Manhattan, was worried about
how a break-up might affect her work life. ``We use all their
software. Will everything we've done have to go through a huge
conversion process?'' she wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monopoly is a bad word, but it's not necessarily a bad
thing,'' said Bruce Hunter of Sausalito. ``It lets them create
things on a bigger scale and make things work together.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone dissenter was Isaac Silverman, who just finished his
junior year of high school in Meadow Vista, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea'' to break up Microsoft, he said.
``The Windows OS seems to have squashed all the competition, even
though the Macintosh is a superior machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door at the Moscone Center, the JavaOne conference was in
full swing, drawing 20,000 Java programmers. Sherry Wang, a
quality-assurance engineer from Mountain View, supported the
break-up. ``I want to be able to choose what applications I use
with my OS and not have it chosen for me,'' she said. ``I don't
want to boot up my machine and have IE (Internet Explorer) staring
me in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Orville Pike, a programmer from Annapolis, Md., said he thinks
market forces ultimately will decide Microsoft's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No company has stayed the leader from one generation to the
next. No matter what the judge did, their time has come. Look at
the new Net companies _ it's their turn now.''
</P>
<P>
   His colleague Nick Bhadanga agreed. ``Microsoft has had its 15
minutes _ okay, 20 years _ of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR;  and Carolyn Said
at  &LR; csaid(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
