<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-EINSTEIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: AOL PICTURES SEEN BUT NOT SENT  &HT;     BY DAVID EINSTEIN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Q: I connect to the Internet via America Online.
When I save pictures off the Web, I can view them just fine. But if
I e-mail pictures to other people, sometimes they can't open them
up. What's the problem and, more important, what's the solution?
</P>
<P>
   A: The problem is that AOL saves some images in its own
proprietary format, using the extension .art. Unfortunately, few
other programs can open .art files. The newest version of
Microsoft's Internet Explorer has an installation option that lets
you view them, but that's not going to solve your problem, because
you can't be sure that the person to whom you send pictures has IE
with the .art viewer installed.
</P>
<P>
   There is a solution, however. After saving your image as an .art
file, open it up in AOL by using the Open function in the File
menu. Then re-save the image _ only this time you should have the
option of saving it in .jpg format. That's the most popular format
for storing Internet images, and all your friends should be able to
view it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whacked-Out Printer
</P>
<P>
   Q: I use Internet Explorer for Web surfing. Somehow, something
got switched and my printer now prints in landscape instead of
portrait mode _ in other words, sideways on the paper instead of
top to bottom. I have tried everything I can think of to fix this.
I've gone to File, then Print and changed the properties, which
works until I log off. But the next time I get online, it's back to
landscape. So I have to go in every time and change it before I
print. Help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It sounds like you've somehow changed your printer's global
default setting from portrait to landscape. That would affect the
printing orientation of most, if not all, Windows programs. And
changing the properties from inside a program won't change the
default _ as you've discovered.
</P>
<P>
   What you need to do is switch the properties for the printer
itself _ rather than for the individual print job. Click the
Windows Start button, point to settings and choose Printers.
Right-click the icon for your printer and choose Properties. Now
find the settings for paper orientation and choose Portrait (the
dialog box for this may be different for different printers).
Finally, click OK and close the Properties window. That should do
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Skinny on Screen Burn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: What is the truth about ``screen burn''? How long must an image
remain on the screen before it burns in and ruins the monitor? Some
of my screen savers have partially static images that I would think
are just as dangerous as any other image such as a home page or
desktop wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Relax. Today's PC monitors are practically impervious to screen
burn. In fact, you don't even need a screen saver. I had a computer
at work that I never turned off, and it would sit there all night
displaying the Windows desktop. After two years, there was no
burn-in, and the display was as sharp and clear as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than worry about screen savers, why don't you configure
your PC to turn the monitor off after 15 or 20 minutes if nobody's
using it. That way, you'll put your mind to rest, and at the same
time you'll score points with the conservationists by saving
electricity. Right-click any empty area of your desktop and choose
Properties, then tab over to Screen Saver. If your monitor supports
energy-saving features, you'll see a special section for that at
the bottom of the window. Click Settings, and the rest of the
procedure should be easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Banishing Unwanted Icons
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: How can I get rid of the icons in the bottom right corner of the
Windows Desktop? I have a Dell computer and it preloads a bunch of
stuff I don't need. I have 12 icons down there, not counting the
clock and the Internet connection icon. I know I can right-click on
them and close them temporarily, but how can I get rid of them
permanently?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: First thing to do is check your c:Windows/Start Menu/Programs/
StartUp folder. You should find files there that are responsible
for loading some of the unwanted icons. Feel free to delete those
files.
</P>
<P>
   Not all programs are loaded via the StartUp folder, however. If
your computer is loaded with Windows 98, you can track down the
programs by following these steps: Click the Windows Start button,
choose Run, type in MSConfig and click OK. This will open the
System Configuration Utility. Tab over to Startup and you'll see
checked boxes for programs that load during startup. If you find
one you don't want, uncheck the box. But be careful. Some of these
programs may be required by your system. So only dump the ones
you're sure about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Use the History feature on your browser to see links for every Web
site you've visited in the past few days. The links are live, so
you can use them to revisit the sites. In both Netscape Navigator
and Microsoft Internet Explorer, press the letter H while holding
down the Ctrl key to open the history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Einstein is a columnist for Forbes Digital Tool. Got a
question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
