<HEADER>
A7771 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-DODGERS-RANGERS-L     06-07 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-RANGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT WILL TAKE `W' FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Darren Dreifort wanted to pitch better. But
it was more important just to get a win.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort hadn't done that in three weeks and had been pretty
awful since throwing a two-hit shutout last month in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But in the postgame clubhouse Wednesday afternoon, Dreifort
looked over at teammate Kevin Brown, who was brilliant in losing
two nights earlier, and made no apologies for his part in an 11-6
victory over the Texas Rangers at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take this any time,'' said Dreifort, who allowed nine
hits and four runs in seven innings. ``You look at what happened to
Brownie the other night and it doesn't make sense. You just have to
go with what you've got. Winning is all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, that means some occasional
anxiety. Dreifort was counted on to be one of the club's top
starters in his final year before free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said recently that the key to his team making a move in
the National League West will be the consistency of his starting
pitching. He has to look no further than division-leading Arizona,
which has dropped five straight since Randy Johnson skipped a start
with a tired shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, Brown is Brown. Tuesday, rookie Eric Gagne
finally won his first game on his eighth try. Chan Ho Park pitches
tonight against Houston at Dodger Stadium having won his last two
starts.
</P>
<P>
   They still are concerned about erratic left-hander Carlos Perez,
who has won four games but has a 5.61 ERA. Perez, who starts Friday
against the Oakland A's, has agreed to be sent to the minors if he
doesn't pitch well.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was pounded for 13 runs in seven innings during his
last two appearances. And Wednesday, after his team took a 4-0 lead
in the second against Rick Helling (7-4), Dreifort quickly gave up
two runs.
</P>
<P>
   But after Rusty Greer doubled home a third run in the bottom of
the third, Dreifort found his composure, retiring eight of the next
nine batters.
</P>
<P>
   He was nicked for another run in the fifth on an RBI double by
Rafael Palmeiro, but when Dave Hansen's two-run double capped a
four-run Dodger sixth, this was a game Dreifort wouldn't give back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see him get in a rhythm,'' Johnson said. ``He
found himself later in the game and I thought he pitched pretty
well. We needed that.''
</P>
<P>
   With just four regulars in the lineup because of injuries to
catcher Todd Hundley, shortstop Kevin Elster, center fielder Devon
White and third baseman Adrian Beltre, the Dodgers also needed a
big game from their bench.
</P>
<P>
   F.P. Santangelo went 3 for 6 and scored twice. Since taking over
for Todd Hollandsworth in center last weekend, Santangelo has gone
7 for 16, including an RBI double in the Dodgers four-run sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The hot streak only raised his average to .187, which says
something about how poorly he hit the first two months of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to find a way to start the season in June,'' he said.
``Every year is like this for me. Always a slow start and
aggravating. It's tough to stay sharp when you don't play a lot,
but that is the job description. When you get a chance to play
every day like I've been doing lately, it feels great.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Hanson, the club's top left-handed pinch hitter
who played all three games against Texas, including two as a DH.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Hansen had a two-run single. Wednesday, he went 3 for
4, raising his average to .348.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be prepared when you get your chances,''
Hansen said. ``It's a hard job when you don't play a lot. You have
to take advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort had a chance not only to right his season, but to give
the bullpen a day off.
</P>
<P>
   With closer Jeff Shaw needing to work his way back from rotator
cuff trouble, Johnson was hoping to get some innings from Antonio
Osuna on Wednesday. But after replacing Dreifort to start the
eighth, Osuna lasted just four batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers couldn't use Mike Fetters, who has closer experience
but who Johnson said won't pitch on back-to-back days until after
the All-Star break. Shaw wound up on the mound in the ninth inning,
but he was preserving a five-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go nine every time,'' Dreifort said. ``But like I
said, it's more important to win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
