<SLUG> BC-NJ-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW JERSEY, U.S. SENATE CANDIDATES QUICKLY STAKE THEIR GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Robert D. Franks was not halfway through his
victory speech early Wednesday morning when he began ripping into
Jon S. Corzine, his opponent in the U.S. Senate race in New Jersey,
as a dangerously out-of-touch spendthrift.
</P>
<P>
   The race to control the wide middle of New Jersey politics began
even before all the votes were counted in Tuesday's primary, which
left Franks as the apparent Republican nominee. And Franks' swift
attack raised a question that he clearly hoped would define the
race: Can he succeed in turning the liberal proposals and
record-setting spending that won Corzine the Democratic nomination
into liabilities big enough to keep Corzine from winning the
general election?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's dangerous about Jon Corzine isn't the fact that he has
spent tens of millions of his own money,'' Franks said. ``What's
really dangerous is the prospect of Jon Corzine sitting in the
United States Senate, where he will have the power to spend your
money.''
</P>
<P>
   In giving his own acceptance speech, Corzine, emotional and
exhausted after his overwhelming but hard-won victory over former
Gov. Jim Florio, seemed to be thinking more about how soon he would
be able to take a vacation than about his next opponent. But his
advisers suggested Wednesday that Corzine, the former co-chairman
of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., would soon begin pointing to his Wall
Street background as evidence that, for all his expansive ideas, he
would understand as well as any lawmaker the importance of fiscal
moderation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon Corzine is a can-do, pro-jobs Democrat who understands the
new economy,'' said Steven Goldstein, a top official in the Corzine
campaign. ``He's running against a lifelong politician who's never
had any real-world experience. And New Jersey, whether it's Frank
Lautenberg or Bill Bradley, likes real-world experience in its
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, aides to Corzine outlined a plan to depict Franks, who
was elected to the House in 1992, as an ideological soul mate of
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, a strategy used most
successfully by President Clinton in his 1996 campaign against Sen.
Bob Dole, and by Sen. Robert G. Torricelli of New Jersey in his
race the same year against Rep. Richard A. Zimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Franks-Gingrich agenda is hopelessly out of touch with New
Jersey,'' Goldstein said. ``Bob Franks can't possibly be moderate
when he voted for the Contract With America.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Smith, an aide to Franks, made it clear that he would
not be intimidated by Corzine's stated willingness to spend
whatever it takes to win the Senate race, which he demonstrated by
spending close to $35 million in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we'll have the financial wherewithal to compete,
with a message that's much more in tune with New Jersey's voters
than Jon Corzine is with his immense wealth,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that $10 million was an acceptable rule-of-thumb
estimate for what an effective fall campaign would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Republican officials in Washington, whose help Franks
will sorely need, expressed glee Wednesday at the prospect of
helping him take on Corzine, whose advocacy for ambitious
government programs, against the death penalty, and for affirmative
action, gun control and gay rights made his campaign as
left-leaning as any successful Senate primary bid in memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Franks is an accomplished legislator and an
outstanding candidate, while all Corzine has is rich liberal
guilt,'' said Steven Law, executive director of the National
Republican Senatorial Committee. ``We believe in this race because
Bob Franks has New Jersey common-sense values, while on the other
hand, if Corzine goes any more to the left, he'll be in
Pennsylvania.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much more Corzine will spend in the fall campaign was
the subject of much speculation Wednesday. His advisers have said
they long believed that a primary campaign against Florio would be
much more difficult and costly than a general election. And after
an unprecedented 12-week saturation of the New York and
Philadelphia television stations with Corzine's image in gauzy
commercials, he enters the race with Franks, who is little known
outside his congressional district except among Republican
stalwarts, holding an incumbent's name-recognition advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But Franks' decision to focus on Corzine's spending was striking
not only because he picked right up where Florio left off, vowing
to make campaign finance reform a central issue, but because
Florio's efforts in that regard had won him newspaper endorsements
but had failed to sway most Democratic voters. Goldstein also said
Franks was vulnerable to attack for his own acceptance of
special-interest contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
