<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR SET TO EXORCISE GHOST OF MATTEAU PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Perhaps one of these seasons Martin
Brodeur will step onto the ice at Madison Square Garden and not
hear Stephane Matteau catcalls.
</P>
<P>
   Matteau's goal, of course, will forever live in Ranger fans'
memories. His shot eluded Brodeur at 4 minutes 24 seconds of double
overtime of Game 7 of the Eastern Conference finals in 1994, and
propelled the Rangers to their first Stanley Cup in 54 years. After
one of his poor performances against the Philadelphia Flyers,
Brodeur was asked if one of the soft goals he allowed was as
devastating as the one to Matteau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go to Madison Square Garden I hear someone
mention the guy's name,'' Brodeur said of Matteau, now a member of
the San Jose Sharks. ``I don't even know where the guy's playing
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur recovered from Matteau's goal to lead the Devils to the
Stanley Cup a year later. On Thursday night, Brodeur and the Devils
have a chance to win another cup with a victory over the Dallas
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur has been terrific in the series with a 1.75 goals
against average. One of his numerous strengths is what the golfer
Chi Chi Rodriguez calls ``instant amnesia'' after a bad shot. If he
has a bad game, he forgets about it and looks ahead to the next
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with him for seven years,'' Jacques Caron, the
goaltending coach of the Devils, said Wednesday, ``and I've learned
that his mental strength is unbelievable. He recovers well from a
bad game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur has had a handful of stressful moments against the
Stars. In Game 3, with the Devils holding a 2-1 lead, he was
assessed a delay-of-game penalty with 4:15 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty didn't think my hair was gray enough,'' Coach Larry
Robinson said. Brodeur redeemed himself with 50 seconds left in the
game, however, when he denied Brett Hull on a blistering 20-foot
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him with the puck, I said, `Anybody but him,'''
Brodeur said about Hull, who scored the winning goal in Game 2. ``I
didn't want to have to face him like that because I know the kind
of shot he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at practice the Devils were looking to close out the
championship series. Standing on a small platform, Sergei Brylin
reminded listeners what the Devils accomplished after facing
elimination three times against the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas can do what we did in the last series,'' Brylin said.
``I know it's difficult to concentrate on the game and not think
about the Stanley Cup, but we know what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux said, ``You focus on what you have to do to get
it, rather than what to do after you get it.'' Lemieux speaks from
experience. He won the Stanley Cup with the Devils in 1995 and
again a year later with the Colorado Avalanche. He won his first
cup with the Montreal Canadiens as a rookie in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the dressing room knows they'll have to play
their best game of the series,'' Brodeur said. ``I feel pretty good
about the way I'm playing personally, but it's the team that
counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Caron said: ``Marty wants to be the best, but that's not his
focus right now. What he wants more than anything now is to win the
next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Including the regular season and the playoffs, Brodeur has 58
victories this season, which ties Mike Richter's mark with the
Rangers in 1994. Brodeur needs to win one more game to tie the
league record for victories in a season with 59, accomplished by
Bernie Parent of the Flyers in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   With these credentials, perhaps Brodeur will finally get some
respect from the hockey fans in the metropolitan area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
