<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL PLANS TO DO HIS TALKING ON THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Things are so desperate for the Dallas Stars right now
that even Brett Hull is talking.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who leads all playoff scorers this season with 11 goals
and 23 points, sat in front of his locker stall here Wednesday
morning at the Stars' practice facility, reflecting on the reasons
why his team was one loss away from relinquishing the Stanley Cup
to the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas trails the series by three games to one, and since the
finals went to a four-of-seven game format in 1939, the 1942
Toronto Maple Leafs are the only team to rally from a similar
deficit and win the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Hull was asked he had previously avoided the news media during
the finals, allowing interviews only after he had scored two goals
in the Stars' victory in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   He replied, ``I don't have anything to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to the questions,'' said Hull, who called them, at
best, ``all rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll believe anything I say,'' he said. ``It's more time
consuming than anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all propaganda. No one wants to say anything too
controversial. It will only end up being put on the other team's
bulletin board. All you do is get chastised for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to hear it, but then they call you a baby for
speaking out. And more than three quarters of the players never
back you up on it, even though privately they agree with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old right wing has long been known not only for his
deadly release and pinpoint accuracy on the ice, but for his
penchant for verbosity most of the time off it. His teammate and
good friend, Mike Keane, had a hat made that says, ``Shut Up,
Hull!''
</P>
<P>
   ``All year, he talks 24 hours a day about everything _ sticks,
crossword puzzles,'' Keane said. ``It just saves me from having to
tell him.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least in his dealings with the news media, Hull has taken
Keane's hat to heart. Teammates like Derian Hatcher, Mike Modano,
Guy Carbonneau and Keane have done the talking for him _ unless he
scores a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the team we have and the people we have on it,
we have enough people to speak,'' Hull said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hull has been one of the few athletes willing to speak his mind
on any subject imaginable. But since coming to Dallas, he has had
to trade in his candor to fit into Coach Ken Hitchcock's faceless
system of 12 interchangeable forwards and six interchangeable
defensemen, full-court pressing, checking and trapping for 60
minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off has had its benefits. Last season, Hull won his
first Stanley Cup _ and scored the controversial cup-winning goal,
to boot.
</P>
<P>
   But it is obvious that he is not altogether comfortable in his
low-key role, consecutive appearances in the finals or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that have been around the team for this season have
seen a frustrated athlete,'' said Hitchcock, alluding to the
career-low 24 goals Hull scored in the regular season. ``During the
playoffs, he has made a determined effort to focus on his play and
not on what he's said. He's done this to get away from the
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's cagey. He knows that if he talks too much, the other team
is going to point at him. So he doesn't bring attention to himself
on the ice. He's almost like a sandbagger in golf. The regular
season was embarrassing to Hully. He's trying to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a lot different,'' Hitchcock said of Hull in the
playoffs. ``He's been a lot more sincere, a lot less sarcastic. He
still comes up with his one-liners every 30 seconds, but they've
been different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's the bitterness there was in the regular
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is there the outspokenness that the old Hull used to
possess before he came the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no old Brett Hull, so I'm not saying anything,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Do you miss him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes I do,'' he said, almost wistfully. ``Very much. He was a
lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
