<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: SENTENCE VOIDED
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has overturned a guilty verdict and prison
sentence against Kosovo's most prominent human rights activist, Dr.
Flora Brovina, her lawyer said. The court sent the case back to a
lower court for review, which is likely to mean a new trial or,
possibly, the dropping of charges. The court also urged that
Brovina be released on bail, her lawyer said. Brovina, an ethnic
Albanian, was convicted of terrorism on Dec. 9 and sentenced to 12
years in prison, prompting an international outcry.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: HOPE FOR POPE
</P>
<P>
   Talks on a reconciliation between the Roman Catholic and Russian
Orthodox churches may resume this fall, officials said, raising
hopes Pope John Paul II might still make the first papal visit to
Russia. The two churches have been at odds since the schism of
1054. Relations were further strained in 1999 after NATO's attack
on Yugoslavia, an ally of Russia. Prime Minister Vladimir Putin,
while on a visit to Italy this week, raised the prospect of a papal
visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: CHURCH CALLS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   A week after branding the prime minister a dictator, the Greek
Orthodox Church has called on its followers to take to the streets
and protest the government's decision to abolish religious
affiliation from state identity cards. Archbishop Christodolous and
a council of 79 prelates agreed to the move after Prime Minister
Costas Simitis turned down their request for a meeting. The
church-led protests will start in Salonika next Wednesday and end
in Athens a week later.
</P>
<P>
   SLOVENIA: NEW GOVERNMENT
</P>
<P>
   After two months without a government, Slovenia got a
center-right cabinet headed by Andrej Bajuk, a conservative prime
minister. The tiny nation, which broke away from Yugoslavia in
1991, is the wealthiest, per capita, in eastern Europe and among
the first nations in line for membership in the European Union. All
sides were worried that the government crisis would hurt Slovenia's
reputation abroad.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: COMMUNIST GRAVE DEFACED
</P>
<P>
   The grave of Erich Mielke, the former chief of Stasi, East
Germany's secret police, was vandalized just hours after his burial
on Tuesday. Flowers and wreaths were ripped up at the unmarked
headstone in the Berlin Friedrichsfelde cemetery. Mielke's grave
was placed outside the memorial section where Communist heroes like
Karl Liebknecht and Rosa Luxemburg, co-founders of the German
Communist Party, were buried.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATIN AMERICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: LANDMARK RULING
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark case, a prominent Amazon landowner has been
sentenced to 19 years in prison for ordering the 1991 assassination
of a leader of the local farmworkers' union. ``This is a historic
moment,'' said Luiz Eduardo Greenhalgh, a lawyer for the union.
``It is the first time in Brazil that the mastermind of a crime
against a rural worker has been found guilty.'' After the killing
Jeronimo Alves de Amorim fled to Mexico, where he was seized last
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: PEACE MOVES
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to advance peace talks with the two main left-wing
guerrilla groups, President Andres Pastrana has ordered a six-month
extension of a demilitarization pact with the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia, permitting the group to keep control of a
Switzerland-size area. He also granted formal negotiating status to
the Army of National Liberation, saying it ``has demonstrated a
will to negotiate the armed conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BURUNDI: PEACE CONCESSION
</P>
<P>
   In a concession toward peace, President Pierre Buyoya, agreed to
close down dozens of camps where a third of a million Hutu farmers
have been forced to live for the last nine months. Buyoya made the
agreement after meetings in Johannesburg with former South African
President Nelson Mandela, who is mediating talks to end Burundi's
civil war. Buyoya's Tutsi-led government has said the camps were
necessary to calm violence around the capital.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO: FIGHTING KILLS 50
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 civilians have been killed since fighting broke out
again between Rwandan and Ugandan soldiers in Kisangani, the United
Nations and relief groups reported. Soldiers from the two nations,
once allies, have clashed since last summer in Kisangani, where
they have troops stationed to aid rebels fighting to overthrow
Congo's government. Both have agreed to leave to make way for a
U.N. force, but neither has done so.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET ARREST
</P>
<P>
   Police have arrested the operator of an Internet site whose
postings included material about dissident activities, the 1989
crackdown in Tiananmen Square and other delicate topics, according
to rights groups. Huang Qi is being charged with subversion, which
can carry a long prison sentence. The Web site's name,
www.6-4tianwang, is a clear reference to June 4, 1989, when the
Chinese army dispersed the Tiananmen protesters, killing hundreds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
