u p BC-NJ-FRANKS-NYT &LR;      06-07 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FRANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLE-CLASS, MIDDLE-OF-ROAD FRANKS IS HAPPY AS CORZINE'S RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, N.J. _ If a moment can have a message, Bob Franks
was sending one by beginning his race as the Republican nominee for
the U.S. Senate at the Lido Diner here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lido Diner, that's as middle-class New Jersey as you can
get,'' Raymond Bateman, an experienced Republican leader in the
state, said with a laugh. ``That's Bob Franks.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the spring, Franks, who is in his fourth term in
Congress, and the other three Republican candidates for governor
were eclipsed by the civil war within the Democratic party between
Jon Corzine and Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Franks is the presumed Republican nominee, he will step
out into the limelight alone to face Corzine in the general
election. The face he is most likely to present is of a typical New
Jerseyan, a successful suburban lawyer with a wife and a little
daughter, stepping out of the Lido Diner after breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   With 99 percent of the vote counted, Franks had 95,801 votes,
35.4 percent, and state Sen. William L. Gormley had 92,454, 34.2
percent. But with absentee ballots uncounted, Gormley refused to
concede Wednesday morning, saying in a statement that the vote had
to be certified first.
</P>
<P>
   The image Franks presented at the Lido is one he evidently
expects New Jerseyans to be comfortable with, and one he hopes to
contrast with Corzine's self-financed $35 million scorched-earth
campaign against Florio. Franks has said that Corzine is out of
touch with average New Jerseyans, and in his victory speech early
Wednesday morning he challenged Corzine to meet him at the Lido for
the first debate.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Corzine was up just as early, thanking voters at
Journal Square in Jersey City. So Franks stood alone in front of
the diner and took a poke at his rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon is going to have to answer the voters' questions,'' Franks
declared in the early light of a sparkling day. ``He can no longer
hide behind the multimillion-dollar ad campaigns and the focus
groups. He is going to have to come out here to these diners and
answer the tough questions.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the sharpest contrasts between Franks and Corzine is
political experience. Corzine has never held public office, and
Franks, 48, has spent much of his life in politics, including 14
years in the state Assembly and eight as a congressman. He has
never lost an election, although he has come close.
</P>
<P>
   Franks borrowed a campaign slogan from Florio on Tuesday night
when he introduced a theme he is sure to repeat in the next five
months: that he is a man ``with experience you can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   He began in Republican politics in 1954, when he was a
13-year-old with a tab collar and a skinny tie going door to door
in suburban Chicago, where he lived, for Charles H. Percy's
unsuccessful campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   After he got his law degree from Southern Methodist University
in Dallas, Franks joined the staff of Tom Kean's successful
campaign for governor in 1981. The next year he directed James
Courter's Senate campaign, and then the 1984 House race of Dean
Gallo. He went on to two separate stints as chairman of the state
Republican Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Corzine's sudden dash from nowhere for the Senate
nomination, Franks spent years cultivating political friendships.
Instead of searching for a promising congressional seat, he
patiently waited for his friend, Matthew Rinaldo, to retire from
the 7th District in 1992 before running. He has held the seat ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched all of the politicians in both parties, and the
one who has developed the best is Bob Franks,'' said Bateman, who
can name every presidential candidate who carried New Jersey back
to Dewey in 1948. ``Before, he was not that good on his feet, now
he's terrific. He's good with people and he's good on the issues
and he's going to be tough for Corzine to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophically, Franks is as middle of the road as diner
coffee. In 1998, the National Taxpayers Union, an antitax group,
rated him at 50 percent. The Concord Coalition, which aims to
eliminate the federal deficit, rated him at 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was the absence of ideological rigor in Franks that prompted
Kean to make Franks his Assembly floor leader. Even Bateman, an
early admirer, once said he thought Franks was more comfortable
managing party business than legislating, with its tough up-or-down
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Franks earned Gormley's scorn in 1990, when he twice abstained
on a law that Florio had championed that would ban certain kinds of
semiautomatic firearms, and which Gormley supported.
</P>
<P>
   Franks' preference for compromise was also evident in 1998, when
he long resisted committing himself on the Republican House
leadership drive to impeach President Clinton. While other members
of the state delegation declared for impeachment, Franks remained
neutral, hoping that a vote would be averted, until finally voting
to impeach on three of the four counts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of this reputation, Franks has been called
bland. On the cover of the May issue of the New Jersey Reporter, a
public affairs magazine, Gormley was drawn holding cards and poker
chips, symbols of his support for Atlantic City's gambling
industry. Franks was drawn holding a pint of vanilla ice cream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
