<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-DORISMOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI TRIED TO SEE FAMILY OF DORISMOND
</HEADLINE>
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Wednesday that he had
tried to meet twice in recent days to express sympathy belatedly to
the family of Patrick M. Dorismond, the unarmed black man shot dead
earlier this year by the police. But the mayor said he backed away
from the meetings because the family members wanted their lawyer,
Johnnie Cochran, to be present.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor was looking for a heart-to-heart, not a
deposition-like meeting with a lawyer,'' said Giuliani's
spokeswoman, Sunny Mindel.
</P>
<P>
   But an intermediary for the Dorismond family, the Rev. Brian
Jordan, said Wednesday that the presence of Cochran was not
necessarily a problem and that the mayor and the Dorismonds were
still negotiating ``mutual terms'' for a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's refusal to express sympathy to the Dorismond family
at the time of the shooting in March and his attempt to discredit
the victim, which shocked even fellow Republicans, has been called
the harshest example of the mayor's aggressive style.
</P>
<P>
   But when Giuliani withdrew from his U.S. Senate race against
Hillary Rodham Clinton because of his prostate cancer, the mayor
promised to be a better person who would reach out to the
minorities he had alienated. Blacks in the city, who are hopeful
but skeptical about the mayor's ability to change, are now watching
for clues.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs Wednesday of some thawing on both sides.
Kadiatou Diallo, the mother of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed black man
who was shot dead by the police last year, said she would meet with
Giuliani if he was willing to reach out to her.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough president
and a longtime critic of the mayor, met privately with him for an
hour at City Hall to discuss the need for community policing,
Ferrer said, as well as policy on schools, housing and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough president, who is
black, announced Wednesday that she and the mayor were to meet
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings with Ferrer and Fields were both initiated by
Giuliani. Normally such meetings between a mayor and his borough
presidents would hardly be news, but Giuliani has regularly warred
with both officials during his years in office. The meeting with
Fields would be their third. Ferrer said Wednesday that he could
not recall the last time he met with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrer pronounced himself ``very pleased'' with the meeting, but
said he now wanted to see results. ``And that's always where the
rubber meets the road,'' Ferrer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, one of the mayor's angriest critics, said
Wednesday that he was unimpressed with the mayor's efforts. ``The
mayor is being very selective in how he plays `the new Rudy,'''
Sharpton said. ``Clearly, he has not met anyone he has not met with
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mrs. Diallo and Marie Dorismond, the mother of
Dorismond, met in Albany with Gov. George Pataki, who expressed his
sympathy and hugged members of the Dorismond family. Mrs. Diallo
and Mrs. Dorismond were there with other relatives of victims of
shootings and injuries by New York City police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
