<HEADER>
A7790 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-HULL-TEX     06-07 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL HAS LITTLE TO SAY, BUT HIS SCORING TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Brett Hull has spent this playoff season saying
little and carrying a big stick with a nasty curve in the blade,
which is as at least halfway out of character. His fervent hope is
to remain equally unobtrusive _ off the ice _ for three more games
this playoff season.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he'll get that chance depends entirely on whether the
Stars, down 3-1 to New Jersey in the Stanley Cup Finals, can win
tonight at Continental Airlines Arena] in East Rutherford, N.J.,
and bring the series back to Dallas for a Game 6 on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hull has dodged the limelight throughout the playoffs, a
difficult tightrope to walk when you are your team's leading
playoff scorer with 11 goals and a dozen assists, not to mention
its most controversial figure.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, when Ed Belfour's enjoying a night on the
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to say,'' Hull said with a shrug after
yesterday's practice at Dr Pepper StarCenter. ``Nobody wants to say
anything too controversial to put on the other team's bulletin
board. If you say something stupid, that's where it winds up.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Hull might have shrugged even that minor
problem away and let rip with a hot sports opinion or three. Now,
he's simply beaten down by it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you do is get chastised for it,'' Hull said. ``Everybody
\R in the media\S wants to hear it, then they call you a baby, so
it's not worth the effort because nobody gives you any credit for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of the controversial Hull holding court on the Stars'
dire situation heading into Game 5 tonight, he merely assessed the
situation in a straightforward, here's-what-we-have-to-do fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like a real leader might do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing needs to be said,'' he said before the Stars boarded
their flight to New Jersey. ``You'd hope it wouldn't need to be
said anyway. It's all up to the individuals. You either want to
come back and win or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling of urgency coach Ken Hitchcock has been pleading
for throughout this series? It's there now, Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can call it panic, but obviously there's
desperation,'' he said. ``You have to be desperate and you have to
play with everything you have if you haven't already, because you
cannot lose. You have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The players must depend on each other, Hull said. They must
believe in and commit to the system and stick with it for 60
minutes. There can be no peeking beyond tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game can't get out of control,'' Hull said. ``Our system
is control and we're going to stick to that. We just have to be
better within the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is go out and do the best you can and hope the
guy next to you is doing the best he can and that everybody's doing
what they're doing within the system. If you put in that effort and
pull on the same rope as everyone else is, more times than not you
are going to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, Hitchcock said, can't win this game by himself. Nor
can Mike Modano or anyone else. They fell into that trap in the
third period of Game 4 and watched a 1-0 lead turn into a 3-1
Devils victory in less than four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need Brett Hull to score for us to win,''
Hitchcock said. ``What we need from Brett Hull and guys like him is
to stay on the page for 60 minutes and not try to hit the home run,
be patient. Don't get too far ahead of the play or get impatient
with his positioning, with or without the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting to hear what the old Brett Hull might
say about this game, but he apparently doesn't exist any more. Or
if he does, he's being kept in a cellar somewhere, blindfolded and
handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hull admits he misses the devil-may-care nature of that
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do, very much,'' he said. ``He was a lot of fun.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
