<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS KNOW HISTORY NOT ON THEIR SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ While coaching juniors, Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock twice had his teams rally from 3-1 deficits to win
seven-game series. It can be done, but can the Stars do it?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars face an elimination game tonight in New Jersey. It is
the first time they have faced elimination in Game 5 since the
Western Conference Finals in 1998, when they finally lost to the
Detroit Red Wings in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we have come back and won,'' Hitchcock said. ``But I
think the difference being is that there was a goaltender \Rin
juniors\S that was saving the bacon for the other team. In other
words, he was making 40, 50 saves. This is different. We are going
to have to be at our best to win the next game. We felt like in
those games, it was just a matter of time before we got the
goaltender to crack. That is not the case here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars never have rallied from a 3-1 deficit to win a
postseason series.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the Stars players ever have been on a team _ NHL, juniors
or otherwise _ that has overcome such long odds.
</P>
<P>
   Winger Jamie Langenbrunner's 1995 Kalamazoo team was down 3-0
and forced Game 7 before losing. Winger Jon Sim's juniors team,
too, took a 3-1 series to Game 7 before losing. Defenseman Derian
Hatcher once was on a team that was up 3-1 only to lose three
consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at it as a series right now,'' Stars winger
Kirk Muller said. ``I think you've got to look at it like we're
going into Jersey to play a game. Don't even think of Game 6. Don't
even think of Game 7. We're going into Jersey, and we have a game
to win. That's it. We can't look behind us. We can't look ahead. We
can't think about winning three in a row. We just have to win
one.''
</P>
<P>
   That few of the Stars have ever been on a team that has come
back from a 3-1 deficit proves how difficult it is.
</P>
<P>
   It has been accomplished only once in Stanley Cup history. The
1942 Toronto Maple Leafs won the Cup after falling behind the Red
Wings, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars know history is against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the odds right now, it's only been done once,''
Stars defenseman Sylvain Cote said. ``But I don't think we want to
even think and look at it that way. We just want to go game by
game. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars need inspiration, they need only to look across the
ice. The Devils trailed the Philadelphia Flyers, 3-1, in the
Eastern Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what it's like,'' Hatcher said. ``They came back
\Rwhen they were\S down 3-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars need a three-game winning streak to keep the Cup. Six
times during the regular season they won at least three games in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident in what we can do,'' Stars winger Brenden
Morrow said. ``This game here is going to be the biggest game to
win. It's anyone's ballgame after that. We're coming back home to
our fans. If we can get this game, this is a big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though, most of the Stars have never seen it done, they
still believe it can be done. Even if no one else does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to believe it can be done or else it's
going to be futile even trying,'' Stars winger Blake Sloan said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
