<HEADLINE>
STARS BATTLING INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Neither Stars center Guy Carbonneau nor forward Jamie
Langenbrunner participated in yesterday's practice. They might not
be ready for tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said both players were bothered by
sore knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them would be question marks for \RGame 5\S,''
Hitchcock said. ``We'll see how they are \Rtoday\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner has played in only one game, Game 4, since
injuring his right knee in Game 5 of the Western Conference Finals.
Hitchcock said Carbonneau injured his knee yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on both players' availability will be made at the
morning skate.  &QL; 
A rare practice
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brenden Morrow said yesterday's practice was their
best in months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our only practice in months,'' Ken Hitchcock said. ``It
was our third hockey practice in five and half weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars spent the hour working on a lot of game-type
situations. Hitchcock said it was just to remind the players what
they were expected to do in certain situations.  &QL; 
Scoring contributions
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock realizes a lot has been made of the scoring bite
of the Devils' No. 1 line of Petr Sykora, Jason Arnott and Patrik
Elias. But in his mind the difference makers in the series have
been the unexpected contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have gotten scoring from theirs. The Stars haven't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Game 4, which looks like it has been the
pivotal game right now, we do a great job of shutting down their
key offensive people and they get goals from \RJohn\S Madden,
\RBrian\S Rafalski and \RSergei\S Brylin,'' Hitchcock said. ``Those
are our \RMike\S Keanes and \RGuy Carbonneau\S Carbos and Blake
Sloans and Brenden Morrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, I think you have to have those guys
scoring if you are going to win.''  &QL; 
Modano hits 30
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't it seem like yesterday that Mike Modano, with his spiky
short hair and his baby face, was being selected by the Minnesota
North Stars in the draft?
</P>
<P>
   Well don't look now but Modano turned 30 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of weird. It doesn't feel any different, but it's
kind of scary when you hit 30,'' Modano said. ``One year closer to
retirement, that's the way I'm looking at it.''  &QL; 
History against them
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars are looking for history to help them out in their
attempt to rally from a 3-1 Stanley Cup Finals deficit, they may
want to look at other sports.
</P>
<P>
   Only once has a team rallied from 3-1 down to win the Finals.
That was the 1942 Toronto Maple Leafs, who trailed Detroit, 3-0,
before winning the final four games to win the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Do any of the Stars find solace in this?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible,'' Stars defenseman Sylvain Cote said. ``But, we
don't look at as, `Oh, it's been done.' It's been such a long
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
