<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS JOKE UNDER PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A number of pseudo doctors, disguised as
reporters, descended on Stars practice yesterday in search of a
pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Their patient looked alert. The Stars were, after all, skating.
</P>
<P>
   Their vital signs were also encouraging. Nobody seemed to have
quit after Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   A strong pulse proved harder to discern until just that moment
when Stars winger Mike Keane slammed a pie into Mike Modano's face
to honor his turning 30. Players suddenly were laughing and
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   No need for further examination. The Stars may be one loss away
from having to hand the Stanley Cup over to the New Jersey Devils,
but there are definite signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Keane said. ``We're still here. We're not dead yet.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the Cup, the Devils have to beat them once, their first
chance coming in Game 5 of the Stanley Cup Finals at 7 tonight at
Continental Airlines Arena in East Rutherford, N.J.. The Stars need
to win the remaining three games, including two in New Jersey, to
retain it. Did they mention the only other team to come back from a
3-1 deficit in the Finals was Toronto? In 1942. Not easy.
</P>
<P>
   For a team presumed to be dead, though, the Stars looked
strikingly confident and composed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what's up ahead, what's at stake and how tough it
is going to be,'' Stars winger Kirk Muller said. ``We're not
looking at Game 6 or Game 7. We're just looking at what we have to
do to walk into New Jersey and win one hockey game.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Stars have to do is be better at what they do best.
They have to play patient hockey. As Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said, players can't be looking for a ``home run.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is hard not to do when you're on the verge of elimination
and a home run seems to be exactly what you need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can call it panic, but obviously, there is
desperation,'' Stars winger Brett Hull said. ``And you have to be
desperate, you have to play with everything you have if you haven't
already because you can not lose. You have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperation gone awry is what coaches and players feel
contributed to them losing Games 3 and 4 at Reunion. The Stars
weren't scoring, generating four goals in the last three games. But
instead of patiently sticking with their system, their scorers like
Hull and Modano tried to win the game with one shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to them about that,'' Hitchcock said. ``That line
has so much responsibility on their shoulders because of we haven't
had that undercurrent scoring. When it doesn't come early, you get
impatient and try to stretch out your offense, in other words, try
to find holes that aren't there instead of stay with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The message has been received loud and clear. Modano and Hull
were preaching the virtues of staying with it and the necessity of
playing 60 minutes yesterday. They say this is what is going to get
them out of the hole they're in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look further than your nose,'' Stars defenseman
Darryl Sydor said. ``That's for sure. That's where it starts,
yourself and what you bring to the team, what you got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hull: ``It's all up to the individuals. You either want to
come back and win or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what 40-year-old center Guy Carbonneau asked
his teammates on Tuesday: Do we really want to go deep and try to
come back?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes and heck yes are a sampling of player responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something where we don't get this chance very often,''
Keane said. ``I think we take it for granted. We know we have a
good team; that's our goal every year, but, if you look around, a
lot of good teams don't get back. So we shouldn't take these
chances for granted. We're three wins away. Everyone is confident
we can win three games.''
</P>
<P>
   They said, sometime last night, they'd probably get together and
talk about where they are and where they want to be. They didn't
want the coaches around. They had some things to talk about,
leaders like Carbonneau, Keane, Hatcher, Modano, Nieuwendyk, et
al., reminding exactly what needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have exceptional performances from your leaders or
it doesn't work,'' Hitchcock said. ``There is no point in grabbing
control and go out and talk about it and not do it. They've been
excellent at it for two or three years now. Now, they need
exceptional performances. Good performances _ we've had a lot of
good performances _ isn't enough for us to beat this team.''
</P>
<P>
   And for anybody still wondering about that pulse, just listen:
</P>
<P>
   ``Strawberry something,'' Modano said. ``It was good, too.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
