<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAHKODA HILLS' TRAINER AIMS AT JACKPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Belmont Stakes' loss could be Ralph Ziadie's gain. A $1
million gain.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and Preakness Stakes
winner Red Bullet are not running in the Belmont. It's the first
time in 30 years that the Belmont will be conducted without either
the winner of the Derby or the Preakness being there.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it makes for a dull race. Not unless you're Ziadie.
</P>
<P>
   Ziadie trains Lone Star Derby winner Tahkodha Hills, and the
colt will earn its owners an extra $1 million if he can win the
Belmont. Ziadie admits he isn't sure he would have tried this if
Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet \Rwould have\S showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the two big horses were running in there, I would say
not,'' Ziadie said this week by telephone from his barn in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ziadie is in an enviable position, although his horse
is a 30-1 long shot to win the Belmont even after the withdrawal of
Fusaichi Pegasus and Red Bullet. When Tahkodha Hills won the Lone
Star Derby on April 22 at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie, he
became eligible for a $1 million bonus if he would win any of the
Triple Crown events.
</P>
<P>
   No one else has a chance at that sort of money in the Belmont.
The owner of Unshaded has to pay a late entry fee of $100,000 to
get into the Belmont because he missed the regular nominating
payments when the horse was trying to overcome injuries earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded did overcome his foot injury, and he won the $325,000
Lexington Stakes in Kentucky on the same day the $300,000 Lone Star
Derby was conducted. Unshaded is 5-1 on the Belmont morning line.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no bonus tied between the Lexington and any Triple
Crown event. First-place money in the Belmont is $600,000, and
Unshaded has to finish at least third to cover the entry fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unshaded ran for $25,000 more \Rin purse money in the
Lexington\S on the same day they were offering a $1 million bonus
at Lone Star,'' Lone Star leading trainer Steve Asmussen said.
``Now with the Derby winner and the Preakness winner missing the
Belmont, doesn't the Lone Star Derby look like a better prep than
the Lexington? Doesn't it look like Unshaded would have a big shot
at that million?''
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star contracted with Chubb Custom Market of Los Angeles to
underwrite the bonus. Lone Star isn't liable for the $1 million.
Chubb would pay that _ $750,000 to Tahkodha Hills owner Vernon
Heath and $250,000 to Ziadie _ if the colt wins the Belmont. Lone
Star general manager Steve Sexton said the track paid a premium of
$60,000 for the insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it to get better horses to run in our Derby, and I'd
say we did get a little better field,'' Sexton said. ``We'd
probably go ahead and do it again next year, as long as the policy
doesn't shoot up in price.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Racing Association offered a bonus of $250,000 for
victories in the Wood Memorial Stakes and the Kentucky Derby. That
one was collected when Fusaichi Pegasus won the Wood and followed
it with the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   But Neil Drysdale, trainer of Fusaichi Pegasus, said the bonus
had no part in his decision to race in the Wood. He was looking for
a racing surface where he felt comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said he's not comfortable with the idea of bonuses
because it appears some horses may race for a bonus even if they're
not 100 percent sound. He cited the year when Derby winner Sea Hero
and Preakness winner Prairie Bayou raced against each other in the
1993 Belmont. The horse with the best finish was given a $1 million
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Hero got the bonus despite finishing seventh. Prairie Bayou
was unable to finish the race because he suffered a broken leg and
had to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was bad advertising for our sport,'' Drysdale
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ziadie said the bonus isn't driving him to run Tahkodha Hills in
the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be 100 percent to go into this race,'' Ziadie
said. ``Before I ran in the Texas race, my ultimate goal was to run
in the Belmont. The bonus is nice, but it's not important to me.
I'd probably give most to the church anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering his Belmont odds of 30-1, it may take something
miraculous for Tahkodha Hills to win. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
