A7795 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX     06-07 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL AND T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eye on Martinez
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Add Dave Martinez of the Chicago Cubs to the list of
outfielders being considered by the Rangers as a way to replace
injured center fielder Ruben Mateo. The Cubs acquired Martinez from
the Tampa Bay Devil Rays last month but aren't happy with the way
he has played.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is hitting .185 with the Cubs but was hitting .260 with
the Devil Rays before the trade. He's also a left-handed hitter,
which would allow him to platoon with Chad Curtis in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis has taken over in right field with Gabe Kapler expected
to start in center when he comes off the disabled list in the next
week. But Curtis is 5-for-45 with 11 strikeouts in his past 13
games after going 0-for-4 yesterday. He is hitting .228 against
right-handed pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have considered trading for an impact player like
the Astros' Moises Alou but aren't sure they can afford to give up
the talent it would take to make that trade. Someone like Martinez,
Darren Bragg of the Colorado Rockies or Jon Nunnally of the New
York Mets could be available for minor- league prospects.  &QL; 
Clayton rests
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton, who is hitting .143 during his past 15
games, received the afternoon off yesterday. Clayton's slump,
though, had nothing to do with manager Johnny Oates' decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing unbelievable defense, and I just want to keep him
fresh,'' Oates said. ``It's very conceivable that this will be his
last day off until the All-Star break.''  &QL; 
Arm yes, bat no
</P>
<P>
   Back spasms prevented closer John Wetteland from taking batting
practice with Rangers pitchers in preparation for interleague games
at National League ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't concern Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to depend on his bat to win a game,'' Oates said,
``I'm in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The spasms haven't prevented Wetteland from being effective on
the mound. Wetteland has recorded a save during each of his past 13
appearances.  &QL; 
Rochester honors Oates
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates will be inducted into the Rochester Red Wings Hall
of Fame during a ceremony before a June 19 game at Frontier Field
in Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Oates played for the Red Wings during 1970 and '71 and managed
the Baltimore Orioles' Triple A affiliate to the International
League championship in 1988. Oates was recognized that season as
the league's manager of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Oates will become the 50th member inducted to the Red Wings'
Hall of Fame, which recognizes individuals for unique contributions
to the history of professional baseball in Rochester.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo (fracture in right leg) attended yesterday's game
after being released from Harris Methodist Fort Worth earlier in
the morning. Mateo suffered his season-ending injury Friday and
requires the use of crutches.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers probably won't face right-hander Mike Mussina during
their three-game series with the Baltimore Orioles, which begins
Tuesday in Baltimore. Mussina is scheduled to pitch Sunday against
the Philadelphia Phillies. Mussina is 1-1 with a 1.59 earned-run
average in two starts this season against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed Baylor right-hander Chad Hawkins and assigned
him to Class-A Savannah of the South Atlantic League. Hawkins,
selected 39th overall during Major League Baseball's 2000
First-Year Player Draft, received a $625,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed left-hander J.J. Pearsall to a minor-league
contract and assigned him to Double-A Tulsa. Pearsall, a 15th-round
selection of the Los Angeles Dodgers from the 1995 draft, went 4-1
with one save and a 6.27 ERA at Double-A Chattanooga this season in
the Reds' minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   Infielders Derek Baker and Travis Hafner and outfielder Kevin
Mench of Class-A Charlotte were selected to play in the Florida
State League All-Star Game, scheduled July 11.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
