<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' OFFENSE UNABLE TO KEEP PACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers hitters tried to be relentless
yesterday. Trailing from the beginning, they did almost everything
they could to bring the team all the way back.
</P>
<P>
   Their pitchers just couldn't let them finish the job. On a
long-and-weary afternoon at The Ballpark in Arlington, the Rangers'
inability to hold the Dodgers scoreless for more than a couple of
innings in a row proved agonizing for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, after trailing 4-0 in the second inning, rallied to
make it 5-4 in the fifth. But the Dodgers struck back with four
runs in the sixth against Rangers starter Rick Helling and reliever
Tim Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty much the decisive moment of the game,'' Crabtree
said. ``If I do my job, it's a totally different game.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, after giving up five runs in the first three innings,
held the Dodgers scoreless in the fourth and fifth while the
Rangers mounted their comeback. But Alex Cora started the sixth
with a fly ball down the left-field line, and Rusty Greer just
missed making a diving catch on what turned into a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the daytime here it's very difficult to see,'' Greer said.
``More so for the infielders than the outfielders. But in the
outfield you have to wait a split-second longer to see the ball and
that can cost you making a play. But we've also played a lot of day
games here and won a lot of them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   F.P. Santangelo followed with a long drive to right-center, and
Chad Curtis, running out of room near the Rangers' bullpen, didn't
get far back enough. The ball landed just beyond him on the warning
track for a double that scored Cora and made it 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said that his outfielders were having
trouble with the cloudless sky, but Curtis refused to use that as
an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a rough day at work today,'' Curtis said. ``Bad
decisions and poor execution. I don't have any excuses. I just
didn't get it done. There are things I should have done that I
didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   The next play was on his list. After Crabtree replaced Helling,
Mike Grudzielanek fought off a fastball and flared a single to
right. Curtis tried to throw out Santangelo at home, missed the
cutoff man and allowed Grudzielanek to reach second. Crabtree
walked Gary Sheffield, then struck out Shawn Green and Eric Karros.
He got ahead of Dave Hansen 1-and-2, but Hansen worked the count
full and fouled off two pitches before lining a fastball down the
left-field line for a two-run double that made it an 11-6 game
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great at-bat,'' Crabtree said. ``I felt I was in a
groove after getting Green and Karros and had a chance to get out
of the inning. I had to go with a fastball down and away and all he
could do was stick his bat out there.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
