<HEADLINE>
BEST TOO LATE FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ At approximately 4:30 p.m. yesterday, the
Rangers got a 1-2-3 inning from a member of their pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Rangers, right-hander Rick Helling
delivered the afternoon's first pitch at 2:05 p.m. Furthermore,
that 1-2-3 inning belonged to right-hander Jonathan Johnson, whom
the Rangers plan to option to Triple-A Oklahoma before tomorrow's
game in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The end result was an ugly 11-6 loss to the Los Angeles Dodgers
at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Helling surrendered seven runs and a career-high 11 hits before
being removed during the sixth inning with the Rangers trailing,
6-4. Right-hander Tim Crabtree relieved and allowed an inherited
runner to cross the plate and two of his own before the Rangers
returned to their first-base dugout staring at a five-run deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of bad pitches,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Johnson, who allowed only two hits and two unearned
runs during his three-inning appearance. The Rangers recalled
Johnson from the RedHawks on Tuesday after optioning right-hander
Ryan Glynn to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me to get an opportunity to throw,'' said
Johnson, the Rangers' first-round selection in the 1995 draft. ``I
was really hoping I wouldn't come up and just sit around for two
days. That would have been heartbreaking for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson only pitched, however, because those preceding him
endured a rough afternoon. Helling (7-4) lost for the third time in
as many starts, although he pitched better during his previous
losses to the Minnesota Twins and Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all command,'' Oates said. ``He was up all day. There
were a few balls that fell in, but he was up in the zone. He just
hasn't been as sharp with his command. Today was not Rick. He
struggled getting anything down in the zone. It wasn't from a lack
of effort, but he just couldn't get the ball where he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still felt like I made enough good pitches where it could
have been a better outcome,'' Helling said. ``There were probably
four or five balls that weren't hit hard that fell in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not play well in the field, Oates said,
referring to ``plays that could have been made.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored in each of the first three innings, with
seven hits and two walks in that span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to do a better job of getting out of the gate,''
Helling said. ``I seem to settle down, but it's hard when you put
the offense behind the 8-ball early, especially against a good
pitcher like \RDarren\S Dreifort.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (4-3) allowed three runs through three innings and
another in the fifth before pitching two scoreless frames.
Right-handers Antonio Osuna, Matt Herges and Jeff Shaw preserved
the lead, although the Rangers mounted a threat in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored twice and eventually loaded the bases with
one out, but line drives off the bats of pinch hitter Frank
Catalanotto and left fielder Rusty Greer found the glove of Dodgers
second baseman Mark Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't over 'til it's over,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``There was nothing that I liked about that game.''
nn
</P>
