<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS MIGHT BRING SERIES HOME, BUT AFTER THAT...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Don't even talk to me about Game 6; it's
not relevant.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering how in the world the Stars are going to win
three games in a row to keep the Cup in Dallas, get thee behind me;
that's not the issue at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Stars fan and you're focusing on anything but the
here-and-now of tonight's Game 5 showdown with the New Jersey
Devils at Continental Airlines Arena, then you're no real fan at
all.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Stars are at: Their noses are pressed against
a sheer wall of rock and ice as they try to climb Mount Everest.
One misstep, one slip, one break in concentration, and they're
yesterday's news.
</P>
<P>
   It is simple now. Win tonight or go home as second best. Give up
the Cup and let the Devils play with it. Settle in as last year's
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Win and play another day.
</P>
<P>
   The fashionable ploy in this age of shock-jock journalism would
be to step out and say the Stars are still going to win this series
with the Devils, that they'll somehow erase a 3-1 deficit, capture
three games in a row and repeat as NHL champions.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. I may look stupid but occasional periods of soberness
prevail. Predicting that the Stars will beat the Devils three
straight, after what we've seen in the first four games of this
series, wouldn't be shocking, it would be moronic.
</P>
<P>
   But I will say this: The series is coming back to Dallas. It
won't end tonight in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Please, not that toxic wasteland in east Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at three games, it's really daunting,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock conceded yesterday after working his team out
at the Dr Pepper StarCenter before boarding a flight to New Jersey.
``Our whole focus is to bring it back to Dallas and see where this
thing goes.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to be optimistic at this point. The Devils have
outplayed the Stars in three of the four games. Ironically, they
lost one of the three (Game 2) when they were the better team and
won Game 4 when the Stars dominated two of the three periods.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have done what no other team has done to Dallas in
two years: broken their system down. They have imposed ``their''
will on the Stars, instead of the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have run into a team willing to be more patient than
they are. The Devils have taken the blueprint that won the Stars a
Stanley Cup a year ago (and maybe it was the same blueprint that
won the Devils the Cup in '95) and taken it a step further.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have done Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   They have been incredibly fast on the counterattack, constantly
turning the puck back up the ice and into the neutral zone for
odd-man rushes that even Eddie Belfour can't always stop with
spectacular plays.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Stars aren't trying. Maybe they've been trying
too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not always about effort,'' Brett Hull said. ``Sometimes
it's about Xs and Os. You can work as hard as you want, but if
you're not doing the right things it kind of counteracts the
effort. Just as important is following your game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the finals because of our Xs and Os. Stick with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have been giving himself a pep talk because there's no
question that Hitchcock has fingered the Mike Modano-Hull-Jere
Lehtinen line for being partially responsible for that four-minute
breakdown in the third period of Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Devils scored three quick goals to wipe out a
1-0 Stars lead. Modano and company were pressing to pick up another
insurance goal and in doing so, caused a breakdown in the Stars'
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been impatient,'' Hitchcock said. ``We've gotten
frustrated by our inability to score and we've talked to \RModano
and Hull\S about that. That line has so much responsibility on its
shoulders because we haven't had that \Rsecondary\S scoring and
they've stretched it out too early trying to create an offensive
odd-man rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like their attitude that they want that responsibility,
but what we want to see tomorrow is for them to stay with it and
not try to hit the long ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the attitude is good, even loose. Ask Modano. He celebrated
his 30th birthday yesterday with a strawberry cake. Lots of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Keane skated over as the team gathered near the sideboards
for an apparent meeting near the end of practice and mashed the
cake into Modano's face as his teammates howled with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, as much as anyone, understands the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take it shift by shift, period by period,'' he
said. ``We can't take any time, any period, off, or they'll be
coming at us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now talk is real cheap. It's what you put on the ice and
who comes ready to play. Guys will be measured by how they move on
from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they will. Lose and it's suddenly summer. Win and play
another game.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that?
</P>
<P>
   Don't even go there.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
