<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRODEUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRODEUR PLAYS QUIET, SUCCESSFUL ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ If the New Jersey Devils raise the
Stanley Cup tonight, rock-solid defenseman Scott Stevens is the
favored thoroughbred to win the Conn Smythe Trophy race as playoff
MVP.
</P>
<P>
   If not Stevens, then Jason Arnott. Or Petr Sykora. Or Patrik
Elias.
</P>
<P>
   Practically lost amid a Devils machine cranking on all cylinders
is the man behind the mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting recognized is getting recognized,'' Devils goaltender
Martin Brodeur said with a who-cares shrug of the shoulders. ``I am
real happy I have accomplished what I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur ranks among the top five playoff averages of all time
with his microscopic 1.76 goals-against average going into
tonight's Game 5. Yet, he's practically forgotten among the Devils'
high-scoring top line, their dominating defense and a stellar
rookie foursome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the whole key with our team,'' said John Madden, one of
those rookies. ``You can go through our lineup and there's six or
seven guys you can point to that in every series or every game they
made a difference. Marty, obviously, is right up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Where would the Devils be without the wizardry of Brodeur?
Likely not looking at a series-clinching Game 5 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to early in the second period of Game 1. The Devils
held a 2-1 lead when Stars center Mike Modano fired a shot from the
left circle. Brodeur made the save, but the rebound popped left to
a wide-open Brett Hull at the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Hull tried to whip the puck in, but, outstretched sideways on
the ice, Brodeur snatched it in his glove. Minutes later, the
Devils made it 3-1 and the rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could have been a turnaround,'' Devils winger Claude
Lemieux said. ``He's made many great saves to keep us in the game.
He's been tremendous. You can only win if you have a contribution
from your goaltender like he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur provided the Stars another head-spinning, what-if
scenario in a scoreless second period of Game 4. Brodeur came way
out of the crease to challenge a one-on-one attack from Modano.
Brodeur disrupted Modano's progress and sent him flying head-first
behind the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty comes sliding out and makes a great save,'' Devils coach
Larry Robinson said. ``There are always little turning points.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are huge turning points in a Stanley Cup Finals in which
the past three games have been decided by four goals.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur took the heat when he allowed 11 goals in Games 2, 3 and
4 against Philadelphia as the team fell behind 3-1 in the series.
He responded with three consecutive one-goal games to propel the
Devils into the Finals. Against the Stars, he has limited his
mistakes, kept rebounds to a minimum and has allowed four goals in
the past nine periods, two coming on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   He's outplaying his counterpart, Stars goalie Ed Belfour, who
was the Stars' unanimous Conn Smythe candidate entering the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who ranks among the all-time best with a career playoff
goals-against average of 1.91, puts little stock in individual
awards. He's concentrating solely on a second Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``They \Rthe Stars\S will be fighting and they will be playing
well,'' Brodeur said. ``We need myself and the players that play in
front of me to be on top of our games.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
