<HEADLINE>
MOON MADNESS AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Eddie Gossage does not believe in astrology.
But when it comes to night racing at the Texas Motor Speedway, he
sometimes wonders whether the moon and the stars really affect the
little world of TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Through the three years of night (though twilight is a more
appropriate description) races at TMS, some scheduled and others
not, some strange things have happened. From one former
Indianapolis 500 winner slapping another in Victory Lane to a pace
car hitting an Indy Racing League car last year, night racing at
the 1.5-mile quadoval has produced some interesting moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange things come out at night and strange things happen in
the night race here,'' Gossage said. ``I guess you need to go back
and look at the solunar tables and see whether those were full-moon
nights ... full-moon Saturday nights. Police and emergency room
personnel will tell you, it's no myth.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual June night-racing weekend begins today with
qualifying for the Pronto Auto Parts 400k NASCAR Craftsman Truck
race and the Casino Magic 500 Indy Racing Northern Light Series
event. The 167-lap Truck race is scheduled for tomorrow, and the
208-lap IRL event on Saturday. Though billed as night races, it
won't be dark when the 400k begins at 6:30 and the Casino race
starts at 7. But strange nighttime things happen.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hot June night during the 1997 IRL race that made an
indelible mark on the track. During the victory celebration for
apparent winner Billy Boat, Arie Luyendyk interrupted, saying that
he had won the inaugural 500-kilometer Indy-car race at the track.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt, who owned Boat's car, slapped Luyendyk as he exited
the victory celebration, a scene that made highlight reels across
the country. It turned out Luyendyk was right; a malfunction in the
U.S. Auto Club scoring equipment showed Luyendyk had won.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt has the trophy to this day, but Luyendyk is listed as the
official winner of the first night Indy-car race at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as a team we were very upset, and it showed,''
Luyendyk said three years ago. ``The telemetry doesn't lie, and we
were convinced that we had won. I do have to respect USAC for
stepping up to the plate and auditing the results.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat vindicated himself one year later by beating Plano resident
Greg Ray to the finish line, in a race where Ray tried to pass Boat
on the grass in the dogleg.
</P>
<P>
   Then last year, another strange incident made people wonder what
it is about racing under the lights at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   With a little more than 20 laps remaining in the last year's
June IRL race, pace-car driver Johnny Rutherford, a three-time Indy
500 winner, was trying to catch the leaders when he collided with
competitor Donnie Beechler on the bottom of the second turn.
</P>
<P>
   The Oldsmobile Aurora sustained some damage, which deployed the
driver's side air bag. Rutherford and Beechler were not hurt, but
it was another strange scene on the high banks at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like that before,'' Rutherford said.
``I think there's lessons to be learned from everything, and I
think chasing the leaders is something we won't do again.''
</P>
<P>
   Other oddities under the lights included Jack Sprague taking a
wild slide in the dogleg two years ago and returning to finish
sixth. In last year's June truck race, Dennis Setzer winning a race
that was extended more than 10 laps because of the rule the race
must end under green.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun goes down and the lights go on at TMS, something
out of the ordinary is likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars look faster, there is a different feel and it
certainly is special,'' Gossage said. ``When I was playing sports,
I felt like I could run faster and jump higher do whatever in a
night game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
