<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-NYT &LR;      06-07 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STERN JUSTICE FOR MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 8:
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's order to split Microsoft into
two independent companies _ one selling Windows, the other selling
applications like Word and Excel _ is the proper remedy for
repeated violations of the antitrust laws. A less drastic remedy
would prove ineffectual or horribly intrusive. Jackson chose
breakup because the two companies would then compete and innovate
without having government officials overseeing every move. Breakup
is the best way to create a market where Microsoft can no longer
smother software that would be good for consumers but bad for
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of deliberation, Jackson ruled in April that
Microsoft had abused its monopoly over Windows, the operating
system that runs nearly all personal computers, to crush
competition. It adopted business practices that would have been
unprofitable but for their role in blocking rivals from getting
fair access to customers. Specifically, for example, it used
illegal tactics to prevent Netscape from freely selling its
browser.
</P>
<P>
   That is important because the Netscape browser could have served
as the platform from which customers could run word processors and
other application programs, thereby diminishing the importance of
the Windows operating system. Using a monopoly to block entry into
a market by potential competitors is a blatant violation of the
antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The judge could have turned to a less drastic remedy, imposing
rules that would prohibit Microsoft from engaging in illegal
practices. Indeed, the judge did impose such rules for the next
several years. But relying on rules permanently would be
unworkable. In a fast-moving industry, rules become irrelevant
quickly. Besides, an army of government officials would be needed
to second-guess every contract that Microsoft would enter into and
every product design it would offer to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson decided instead to create two companies, each having
incentive to do business with independent software enterprises and
even encroach on the other's territory. The Windows company might,
for example, develop applications and the applications company
might develop a substitute for Windows. That should give consumers
the benefit of vigorous innovation.
</P>
<P>
   The government, with the judge's blessing, will try to take
Microsoft's appeal directly to the Supreme Court as the law allows
for important antitrust cases. That would bypass the normal
practice of having an appeals court first analyze the complicated
technological and legal issues raised by this case so as to provide
a fuller record before the Supreme Court is asked to render a final
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a case where an expedited appeal to the Supreme
Court, explicitly allowed under a 1974 revision to the antitrust
laws, is justified. The uncertainty over Microsoft's future is sure
to complicate business judgments in the fast-changing world of
high-tech industry, the company's monopolistic practices have been
egregious, and the nation deserves a speedy resolution of this
struggle by the highest court in the land. There is no need to drag
it out with an intervening appellate review.
</P>
<P>
   Though the content of Jackson's ruling was unsurprising, the
tone was startlingly stern. Microsoft, he says, has been ``not
credible,'' ``untrustworthy,'' ``disingenuous.'' And he added,
``There is credible evidence in the record to suggest that
Microsoft, convinced of its innocence, continues to do business as
it has in the past and may yet do to other markets what it has
already done.'' Jackson sided completely with the government in
part because he mistrusts the company. Wednesday, Microsoft reaped
the well-deserved consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT &LR;      06-07 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: POLITICAL TURMOIL IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 8:
</P>
<P>
   A cabinet crisis was the last thing Israel's prime minister,
Ehud Barak, needed days ahead of a potentially decisive new round
of peace talks with the Palestinians. But that is exactly what he
got Wednesday when three member parties of his governing coalition
joined the opposition in a preliminary vote for new elections.
Three more votes must be held before the bill becomes law.
Regrettably, Barak must now divert attention from peacemaking to
repairing his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging defection came from the Sephardic religious
party, Shas. Without the party's 17 votes, the coalition would lose
its majority. Shas' argument with Barak is not over peacemaking but
over its demand for additional government money for its private
school system. Shas wants to be able to offer all-day classes,
easing the child care burdens of its working-class constituents.
The government wants to rein in the budget.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long-running quarrel in which both sides have shown some
willingness to compromise. Shas was wrong to press the issue to the
point of calling for new elections. But some further concession by
Barak toward Shas' demands is now probably necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Barak rightly decided when he formed his government last year
that he needed support from the broadest possible cross-section of
Israelis to sustain the compromises necessary for peace. That
assessment remains just as true today. The other two defecting
parties, the National Religious Party and the Russian immigrant
party led by Natan Sharansky, are two of the most hawkish in the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Winning back these two relatively small parties would be
desirable. But retaining Shas is virtually essential. Barak's only
alternative would be to form an extremely narrow coalition of the
center-left that would have trouble selling any peace agreements it
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Early next week, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are
scheduled to begin talks near Washington meant to prepare for a
possible Camp-David-style retreat later this summer. That meeting
would bring Barak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and President
Clinton together in an effort to reach a final peace agreement.
Those talks should proceed as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, meanwhile, should be asked, as the price of any further
concessions, to pledge that from now on it will subordinate its
pursuit of parochial causes to the wider Israeli interest in
negotiating peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
