<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEMIEUX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEMIEUX LIKE ROLES TO `STIR THINGS UP'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Claude Lemieux doesn't try to get around it. No
sugar-coating, no ``no comment'' answers, no avoiding the question
about what his role on the ice often is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to deny that I cause \Rtrouble\S out there,''
Lemieux said. ``There are guys that get paid to do that, get paid
to bring life into the game and stir things up when you are down. I
can't try to change my game now. When I'm too quiet out there, I'm
not myself and I'm not helping the team as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a lot of pride in being a guy they rely on for the
dirty work. Somebody's got to do it, and that's just the way I
play.''
</P>
<P>
   In most arenas, Lemieux, a winger for New Jersey, is the most
hated Devil. He's the master of the hidden shoves, elbows and
slashes that frustrate the opponent as much as they pain them. It's
a part of the game every successful team needs. Not coincidentally,
every team for which Lemieux has played has been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Lemieux is about much more than a slash across the back of
the knee. He's about more than his 517 career playoff penalty
minutes, which is third all time. He's about much more than his
most vicious check ever, which sent Detroit's Kris Draper
face-first into the boards in the 1996 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, first and foremost, is about winning. Just check his
records.
</P>
<P>
   In his 15th NHL season, Lemieux is playing in his 15th
postseason. This is his fifth trip to the Stanley Cup Finals, and
if New Jersey can close out the series tonight with a Game 5
victory, he'll be one of four active players (including Paul
Coffey, Mark Messier and Larry Murphy) to have won four Cups.
</P>
<P>
   When Claude Lemieux walks in a locker room, any team suddenly
seems to become a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's something to it,'' teammate Ken Daneyko
said. ``He's like that gum on your shoe you can't get off. He's
just stuck to your sole. Every team he goes to, guys suddenly learn
what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux won his first Cup in 1986 as a rookie with Montreal.
That season he scored 10 goals and had a career playoff-high 68
penalty minutes. He and the Canadiens lost to Calgary in the 1989
Finals, but he had his name engraved on the Cup again in 1995 with
New Jersey. That year, he won the Conn Smythe Trophy as playoff MVP
with a league-leading 13 goals, including three game winners.
</P>
<P>
   He joked then about a name like his being on the Conn Smythe,
but there was no joking about his impact when he left New Jersey
for Colorado the next season and the Avalanche won the Cup. While
he was gone, the Devils were eliminated in the first round three
times and the second round once.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back, and New Jersey is one victory from its second Cup
in six seasons. And it's not a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought something back we needed,'' Devils defenseman Scott
Stevens said. ``He's a strong, physical guy playing up front who
knows how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And he knows how to score. The list for game-winning playoff
goals, expectedly, starts with Wayne Gretzky, who had 24. This
season, Brett Hull of the Stars has moved into second with 21.
Third on the list? You guessed it _ Lemieux, with 19. Many wouldn't
put Lemieux's name near the other two, but he does belong.
</P>
<P>
   He's also eighth all time in playoff goals scored with 80,
trailing Gretzky, Messier, Jari Kurri, Glenn Anderson, Hull, Mike
Bossy and Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard. And, he's an impressive
plus-43 for his playoff career.
</P>
<P>
   He scores. He wins. And he has a wife who makes friends wherever
they go, even if he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was here with friends for two games,'' Lemieux said.
``The fans were so good to her. They said to her `we hate your
husband, but we're glad to have you with us.'''
</P>
<P>
   And luckily, like Lemieux, his wife has accepted the nature of
his job and the feelings it creates.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's comfortable with it,'' he said. ``She's been around me
long enough now she's fine with it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
