<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRAGUE READY TO BITE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jack Sprague's voice sort of changes when he
begins to talk about the Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series champion has had some
adventures in the four races at the 1.5-mile quadoval. There was
1997 when he qualified with what at that time was the fastest lap
in a NASCAR race truck, only to start from the rear of the field
because of a nonapproved cylinder head.
</P>
<P>
   He did not finish the race.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1998, he almost flipped on the front stretch but
nonetheless ended up sixth. And last year, he said he just did not
run well], finishing fifth in June and a disappointing 11th in
October after he crashed his primary truck in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Most would like to have such finishes at a track such as TMS,
where the series races in front of some of its largest crowds. But
not Sprague, who was once called the ``Master of the
Superspeedway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to win this race because this place has bit me,''
Sprague said. ``We have won poles, but we just have not won a race
there. We are going there this time to win this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague enters this week's Pronto Auto Parts 400K at TMS leading
the points and fresh off a victory at Evergreen Speedway in Monroe,
Wash.  &QL; 
Twilight events
</P>
<P>
   It's billed as ``Racing Under the Lights at Texas Motor
Speedway,'' but the past two years, it has resembled racing in the
twilight. Early start times to both the NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series and the Indy Racing Northern Light Series events have had
some competitors finishing before the sun is completely down.
</P>
<P>
   But television dictates the times for races. The Pronto Auto
Parts 400K Truck race is scheduled to start at 6:30 p.m. tomorrow
and Saturday's Indy Racing Series Casino Magic 500 is slated for 7
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very frustrated by it, and it is a TV thing,'' TMS
general manager and executive vice president Eddie Gossage said.
``NASCAR does not want it at 6:30 p.m. ... But TV has the right to
dictate some of this stuff to us.''  &QL; 
New trophy
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Saturday's Casino Magic 500 Indy Racing Northern
Light Series event at TMS will be awarded the Foyt-Rutherford
Trophy. The name for the 20-inch-tall crystal trophy was decided in
a contest conducted on the track's Web site, and will be awarded to
the winner of the June Indy Racing] winner each year.  &QL; 
Renfrow rebounds
</P>
<P>
   Randy Renfrow's season started similar to a lot of drivers with
a poor finish in the inaugural NASCAR Truck race at Daytona.
Renfrow, a Wilson, N.C., native who drives for Fort Worth-based TKO
Motorsports, has rebounded from a 31st at Daytona to finish with
four top-10s in the past nine races.
</P>
<P>
   His best finish in the Farris Concrete Dodge Ram was a fifth at
Mesa Marin Raceway near Bakersfield, Calif. Renfrow also has had an
eighth-place run at Phoenix, was seventh at Pikes Peak and 10th at
Madison, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   He was 11th at Monroe, Wash., last week and is 14th in the
series standings. He has won $102,225 this season, more than he has
won in the two previous seasons combined.  &QL; 
Texas drivers
</P>
<P>
   B.A. Wilson won't be the only native Texan attempting to qualify
tonight for tomorrow's race, with four other drivers from Texas on
the entry list for this event.
</P>
<P>
   David Starr, who drove in both races last year for Joey Sonntag,
will drive for John Conely this year. Also on the list is Jay
Stewart of Lubbock, Patrick Lawler of Colleyville and Joel White of
Royse City.
</P>
<P>
   Lawler, who has experience in the NASCAR Featherlite Southwest
Tour and drives a Legends car, will drive a Truck owned by former
Rangers pitcher Jeff Russell.  &QL; 
Autograph session
</P>
<P>
   Drivers from the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series will conduct an
autograph session from 6 to 7 tonight in the main concourse. The
session will be before the final Truck practice of the evening,
which is scheduled to begin at 7:15 on the 1.5-mile quadoval.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
