<HEADER>
A7807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NJ-SENATE-NYT &LR;      06-07 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NJ-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW JERSEY'S EXCESSIVE SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, June 8:
</P>
<P>
   At his victory celebration after Tuesday's election, Jon
Corzine, New Jersey's new Democratic nominee for the U.S. Senate,
made a promise that could be taken two ways. ``I want to invest in
America,'' he told supporters. ``That's what this campaign is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   What the former Wall Street financier meant was that he wanted
to spend for better health care and schools, instead of cutting
taxes. But Corzine had also just invested a stratospheric $35
million to win a primary, more than any other Senate candidate in
American history.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag for this victory now stands as a distressing
symbol of a political system so driven by money that a candidate
must be either extremely wealthy or extremely beholden to
contributors in order to win. Corzine and Rep. Bob Franks, his
Republican competitor for the general election, should now commit
themselves to correcting the way money skews the nation's politics.
</P>
<P>
   Both these candidates talk about favoring campaign finance
reform, but Corzine has a special obligation to push for remedies
to the very imbalance that helped him win. Campaigns for federal
office need a combination of public financing and free television
time.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey spectacle also offers only the latest important
signal to the Supreme Court of how its unfortunate 1976 decision
treating political money as free speech has given an unfair
advantage to wealthy candidates. When Congress finally begins
dealing with this issue as part of a desperately needed campaign
finance reform package, it should enact a mandatory limit on the
use of personal wealth in campaigns as a way of forcing the court
to correct its earlier decision.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, a former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., is not
the first wealthy novice to try his hand at politics. A fellow New
Jersey resident, Steve Forbes, unloaded $70 million in two
unsuccessful tries for the presidency. Ron Lauder, Al Checchi and
Michael Huffington tried to buy victory, but lost. Corzine's
success at this stage appears to result not simply from $1 million
a week spent on television ads, but also from his heavy spending on
voter turnout and his lavish contributions to the state's
Democratic Party organizations. It was this generosity that party
regulars more than reciprocated when they trotted out the loyal
vote on this rain-soaked Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   What also fueled Corzine's victory was a deep anger at his
worthy but unpopular opponent, former Gov. Jim Florio, who raised
taxes in 1990 to help schools in poorer areas. For the general
election, Corzine's opposition will not be so instantly unloved.
Franks has almost no sharp edges as a timid but moderate
Republican. Corzine ought to be able to gain traction from Franks'
tendency to slip away from hard votes or even from giving his views
as a candidate on how he would have voted on the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty. But Corzine also hid from the most important candidate
debate in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates should now readily accept offers to debate,
especially in the larger forums offered by such groups as the
League of Women Voters. New Jersey's residents deserve to see these
two candidates not in their soft and expensive television ads but
in debates that are not choreographed to shield them from tough
policy tests. Without such promises to debate linked to a solid
oath to reform campaign financing, the New Jersey race could
degenerate into an auction.
</P>
<P>
   But neither a Democrat's deep pockets nor Republican campaign
committees' habitual dependence on special-interest money should
determine the outcome of a race for the U.S. Senate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
