<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD NOT WORRIED ABOUT L.A. FASTBREAK THIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last time Larry Bird saw the Lakers in the Finals,
the one thing he had to guard against was the fastbreak. This time
around, the one thing he's not worrying about is their fastbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, where have you gone? Very far away, according to Bird.
</P>
<P>
   The dreaded Lakers fastbreak Bird had to concern himself as a
player with the Celtics in the '80s has been replaced by another as
the Pacers coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is very important for us to really not worry about
fastbreak points,'' Bird said. ``What we have to do is have all the
guys around the basket so we can pick up some rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're dominating on the boards. We'd like to have five guys
standing around there picking up as many as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   In the previous 17 playoff games, the Lakers outrebounded their
opponents by a combined 749-690; Indiana was outrebounded in its 17
playoff games 702-685.
</P>
<P>
   TIMELY ARRIVAL: Most of the Pacers barely got to Staples Center
in time to dress and warm up before tipoff on Wednesday. The second
Indiana bus, with eight Pacers and Bird, had this little problem
navigating the Los Angeles freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson, Jalen Rose, Travis Best and Co. didn't arrive in
their locker room until 5:05 p.m. PDT for the 6 p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying a sneak attack,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the team didn't try to offer the driver any tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, man, he was a Lakers fan,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers were coming from their hotel in Santa Monica, a
direct commute up Interstate 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the 10, the 15 and the 20,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bird was just used to his Celtics-Lakers days in the
Finals over at the old joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the Forum,'' Bird said. ``We were sitting over there
waiting for the game to start.''
</P>
<P>
   THOSE WEREN'T THE BLAZERS: Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal never
had as difficult a time getting his game going as he did against
Portland in the Western Conference finals, but the Pacers said
there isn't much they can take from the Blazers' approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blazers have a different type team than we do,'' Bird
said. ``They've got long arms, they're lanky, they've got
quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the quickness they have. We don't have the arm
span they have. They're a good defensive basketball team. We're not
a great defensive basketball team. Obviously, Shaq is going to
cause us a lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird said this before O'Neal went 7 of 8 from the field in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   WE FIGURED: Bird said he was proud to be coaching his first team
in the Finals, but all things considered: ``I'd rather be playing,
to tell you the truth. It's completely different.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
