<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7812 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-L     06-07 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TRY TO FOCUS ON PLAYING, NOT HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Banners draped over every Staples Center railing
screamed ``NBA FINALS 2000,'' but the Lakers' first objective
Wednesday was to ignore their enhanced surroundings and concentrate
on the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're really just stuck on basketball right now,''
fourth-year guard Derek Fisher said before tipoff. ``I think
because all season long we've just been focused on winning, that we
still don't really recognize that this is the Finals because we
haven't won it yet. So until maybe Game 4 or Game 5, when we get
close to actually winning it, then maybe some jitters and some
anxiety will start to come up because we know we're getting that
close to what we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, as many Lakers playing in his first Finals, admitted to
some excitement, ``but I'm not overflowing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson's message to his team was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us to recognize the situation but definitely live in
the moment and not allow, whether it's family members or friends
that are bugging you for tickets and calling about coming to town,
or whether it's the thousands of media personnel that seem to be
here,'' Fisher said. ``He allows us to soak in things but at the
same time, be in control and if you can't use it to your advantage,
don't use it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson: ``This is great, but you have to narrow your
focus, you have to remember what we're here for, playing ball. ...
Try and stay to your routine, so you stay in touch with your game
and in touch with the kind of mental process you go through to get
ready for a game.''
</P>
<P>
   FLASHBACK: Jackson said there was no comparing this Finals (the
Lakers' first since 1991) to his first as Chicago Bulls coach
(coincidentally, the 1991 Finals, when the Bulls beat the Lakers).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing similar or anything like the first Finals,''
he said, ``That Bulls team I think had only lost one game going
into the Finals and lost one (game) in the Finals at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. obviously was in the Finals, and that's a long time ago
for L.A. and we're happy to be back here again,'' Jackson said.
``Sam Perkins (then a Laker, now a Pacer) hit a key shot in that
first game, a very big shot at the end of that ballgame to give
them a (93-91) win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lost the next four games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   FLASHBACK 2: The last time Jackson saw the Pacers in the
playoffs was in the 1998 Eastern Conference finals, won by the
Bulls in seven games. Jackson recalled the Pacers struggling at
Chicago in that series but said they have improved since _ they won
the East last week with a win at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've learned to win playoff games on the road in
this (postseason). I think they've improved as a basketball team on
the road during the playoffs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   STAPLES UPDATE: Staples Center will be open to the public to
show Games 3 and 4 from Indianapolis on Sunday and Wednesday,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Free tickets will be available today beginning at 10 a.m. PDT at
the Staples Center box office and at TicketMaster outlets at
participating Warehouse Music, Tower Records, Robinsons-May and
Ritmo Latino stores.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, not available by phone, are limited to four per person,
per game.
</P>
<P>
   OUCH REPORT: Rookie swingman Devean George _ out since Game 3 of
the Western Conference finals _ is on the mend from his sprained
left ankle, and Jackson expects him to rejoin the rotation soon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
