<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CLARK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BLAIR CLARK, 82, CBS EXECUTIVE, McCARTHY'S '68 CAMPAIGN MANAGER  
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blair Clark, an influential executive at CBS News, a former
editor of the Nation and the campaign manager for Sen. Eugene J.
McCarthy in his unsuccessful bid for the 1968 Democratic
presidential nomination, died June 6 in Princeton, N.J. He was 82
and lived in Princeton and Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pulmonary complications after colon surgery, said
his wife, Joanna.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was something of a mandarin, playing key roles in the
careers of men who became much better known to the general public
than he, including managing the unsuccessful McCarthy campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, of Minnesota, was challenging President Lyndon B.
Johnson's stance on Vietnam and did well in the New Hampshire
primary, which helped persuade Johnson not to run for another term.
</P>
<P>
   From 1961 to 1964 Clark was general manager and vice president
of CBS News, after being a CBS correspondent based in Paris. He was
known for broadening the radio and television coverage of CBS News
by hiring additional correspondents in the United States and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Cronkite recalled Wednesday ``I've always assumed that,
as the general manager of CBS News, he was instrumental in
assigning me to the anchor role on `CBS Evening News,' beginning in
1962.'' The actual decision was made by Clark's superior, Richard
Salant, who was president of CBS News at that time.
</P>
<P>
   And Dan Rather recalled that Clark and another CBS executive,
Ernie Leiser, had hired him in 1961 because his hurricane coverage
in Texas had been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair was a pioneer of television news as a distinguished
correspondent based in Paris and later as an executive,'' Rather
added. ``As a correspondent he helped to build on and maintain the
CBS News reputation that had been built primarily during the World
War II years, and then as an executive he laid the foundation for
the modern television era at CBS News.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark was born in East Hampton, N.Y., into the Clark family of
Coats &AMP; Clark's Thread.
</P>
<P>
   He was educated at a New England boarding school, St. Marks, and
received a bachelor's degree in 1940 from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   He was a reporter for The St. Louis Post-Dispatch before serving
in the Army from 1941 to 1946. Then he held other journalistic
posts before joining CBS News in 1953 in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   After he left CBS in 1964, he was associate publisher of The New
York Post, editor of The Nation magazine, where he found expression
for his liberal views, and a fellow of the New York Institute for
Humanities at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   His 1942 marriage to Jessie Holladay Philbin ended in divorce in
1960.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, the former Joanna Rostropowicz, whom he
married in 1971, he is survived by a son from his first marriage,
Timothy, of Bethesda, Md.; a son from his second marriage, Ian, of
Manhattan; a stepson, Tomasz Malinowski of Washington; a sister,
Anne Martindell of Princeton; and a brother, William, of
Stockbridge, Mass., and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
