<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEDDING-ROBBERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY COUPLE TRIED TO ROB A BANK FOR WEDDING CASH
</HEADLINE>
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dorrell Mainer and Kevin Rainey were eager to
celebrate their wedding this Saturday in Brooklyn. They expected
150 friends and relatives, including Rainey's elderly mother from
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But the police said that when a financial setback threatened the
nuptials, the couple so worried about disappointing their relatives
that they devised a moneymaking plan not found in any bridal
planner: bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, after a botched bank robbery attempt on Coney Island,
their wedding plans were in even greater disarray, the police said.
The couple were arraigned in Brooklyn Criminal Court on one count
each of first-degree robbery.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to rob the Chase Manhattan Bank branch in Brighton
Beach shortly after noon on Tuesday, the police said. Mainer, 38,
who wore a brown floppy hat and sunglasses, walked up to a teller
and passed a note, while Rainey, 41, was a lookout by the door, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The note demanded money and said a bomb linked to the bank's
telephone system would detonate if the teller called the police,
according to a police supervisor familiar with its contents. It
also referred to a sick child who needed care and said the couple
``had nothing to lose in robbing the bank,'' the supervisor said.
</P>
<P>
   But the teller stalled Mainer, the police said, forcing the
couple to flee without taking any cash. They were arrested minutes
later, after stopping at a doughnut shop to use the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   After their arrests, Mainer and Rainey admitted that they did
not have a sick child, according to investigators. Instead, they
said, Mainer told a different tale of woe: a tax refund that was to
be used to pay for the wedding had been taken back by the
government because the Internal Revenue Service had overpaid her.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to rob the bank, the police supervisor said, because
``they didn't want to disappoint their family members.'' The police
also said Mainer was a suspect in two bank robberies in Queens. But
Mainer's lawyer, Paula Notari, said she was a ``stellar member of
the community'' with no criminal record, who supported her three
children, ages 11, 14 and 21, and had a bachelor's degree from John
Jay College.
</P>
<P>
   At the arraignment, Rainey's lawyer, Julie Clark, said he had
known nothing of the robbery and thought that his fiancee had
stopped by the bank to make a wire transfer.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Wednesday whether the wedding, which has been set
for 11 a.m. on Saturday at the First A.M.E. Zion Church in
Bedford-Stuyvesant, would go forward. Neither Rainey nor Mainer
immediately posted bail. And the church clerk, Hazel Harvey, said
she was astounded to hear about the arrests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000607.0460 </DOCNO>
