<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-07 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-MURDERS-KAN &LR;      06-07 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-MURDERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH TOLL COULD RISE WITH AS MANY AS EIGHT WOMEN, BABY LINKED TO
MURDER SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA and TONY RIZZO  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As many as eight women and a baby linked to
John Edward Robinson Sr. could be dead, authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, the suspect in the deaths of five women whose bodies
were recently found in barrels, is connected to three women and a
baby girl reported missing from Overland Park, Kan., in the 1980s,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those cases that continues to unfold every day,
and I think it's impossible for anyone to speculate where it will
end,'' Johnson County, Kan., District Attorney Paul Morrison said
at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Robinson was connected to the 1984
disappearance of Paula Godfrey, 19, of Overland Park, Kan. About
four months later, police suspected he had a hand in the
disappearance of Lisa Stasi, 19, and her 5-month-old daughter,
Tiffany. Authorities also have linked him to Katherine Clampet, 27,
of Overland Park, who was reported missing in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison and police officials from Overland Park and Lenexa,
Kan., also said that Izabela K. Lewicka, a Polish immigrant with
known connections to Robinson, could not be found. Lewicka, 22, had
been living in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators asked anyone who has information about the missing
women or Robinson to call the task force at (913) 477-7633.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   - Authorities confirmed that one of two bodies found in barrels
on property Robinson owns in Linn County, Kan., was that of Suzette
Marie Trouten, 28, of Monroe County, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   - Authorities were finishing draining a pond on the Linn County
property. They wouldn't discuss any evidence they found there, but
said a pickup that was pulled from the pond earlier did not appear
significant to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 56, is suspected of recently meeting some victims
through sadomasochistic connections made on the Internet,
authorities said. But in the 1980s, he was presenting himself as a
businessman and philanthropist who wanted to help unwed mothers and
other women who needed a hand, according to Overland Park Police
Capt. Jeffery Dysart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears as if all these women were just getting started in
their lives,'' Dysart said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said police do not believe the bodies in the barrels
are those of the missing women from the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a guy here who has lived in a lot of
different places and has had a lot of contacts,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said detectives worked the earlier cases as far as they
could in the 1980s, but never learned what happened to the women or
gathered enough information to charge anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Police reopened those cases in March, when Trouten was reported
missing. Trouten met Robinson on the Internet and told relatives
she was going to Lenexa to see about a job, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the two bodies found Saturday in Linn County,
officers on Monday discovered barrels containing three bodies in a
storage locker Robinson had rented in Raymore, Mo. All five women
had sustained blows to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have been hampered in their efforts to identify
the bodies by not knowing where the women came from or even how
long they have been dead. For now, investigators are taking dental
and DNA samples. Also, police and relatives of missing persons from
around the country have been calling the task force in Lenexa to
see whether their cases may be related to Robinson's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said authorities suspect that one of the bodies could
be that of Lewicka, who had been living around Westport in Kansas
City before she moved to an Overland Park apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators think Lewicka dated Robinson and worked with him,
although they would not say what Robinson did for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Lewicka may have known Robinson since 1997, according to a
marriage license application filed then in Johnson County District
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The application lists the name Isabella Katyzma Lewicki of
Kansas City as the prospective bride and John Anthony Robinson of
Olathe, Kan., as the prospective groom.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's real middle name is Edward, and he has been married
to the same woman for more than 20 years, but the marriage
application lists his correct date of birth.
</P>
<P>
   Although marriage applicants state under oath that information
they are providing is correct, no proof of identity is required
when requesting the application.
</P>
<P>
   After the application was requested, no further action was taken
and no marriage license was issued, according to the records.
</P>
<P>
   Murder charges have not yet been filed against Robinson,
although Morrison and Chris Koster, the Cass County, Mo.,
prosecuting attorney, have said that capital murder charges are
likely.
</P>
<P>
   He is being held on a $5 million bond on charges of sexually
assaulting two women he met on the Internet who were interested in
sadomasochistic sexual activity. Because of the high bond,
prosecutors say, murder charges can wait.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County Jail officials said Robinson was being held in
protective custody because of concerns that he might harm himself
or be harmed by other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's attorney, District Defender Byron Cerrillo, filed
notice Tuesday that Robinson was invoking his constitutional rights
and did not want to give any statement to police.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they have talked to Robinson's relatives and do not
believe they are involved in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
